<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Basketball-NBA Finals Notebook,0710 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jazz will remember Bulls finish
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NANCY ARMOUR &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CHICAGO (AP) _ It wasn't just the score that bothered Utah coach
Jerry Sloan, it was how the game ended.
	   ``They were shooting 3-pointers there at the end to see if they
could bury you,'' Sloan said. ``That should make it easy to play
the next game.''
	   The Chicago Bulls humiliated the Utah Jazz 96-54 Sunday. It was
the fewest points ever scored in an NBA game, playoff or regular
season, since the inception of the shot clock.
	   The Bulls made four 3-pointers over the final 7:47 of the game,
and Jud Buechler missed another attempt from long range. Chicago's
bench also was rooting for Bill Wennington to make a basket in the
closing seconds so every Bull on the roster would score. Wennington
hit a jumper with five seconds left for the final margin.
	   Chicago wasn't trying to run up the score, coach Phil Jackson
insisted.
	   ``Michael didn't play the fourth quarter, Scottie kind of guided
that crew, we had four guys off the bench playing,'' Jackson said.
``That wasn't the case and I'm sure Jerry didn't mention that.''
	   As if the high score wasn't bad enough, the Bulls also were
goofing off on the bench for everyone to see. Michael Jordan and
Ron Harper were giggling at the fan limbo contest on the giant
scoreboard screen, with Jordan even joining in at one point.
	   Jordan also threw a towel in NBC commentator Ahmad Rashad's
face.
	   ``No one in this business feels sorry for you, but you watch a
game and endings of games like this, and you should be ready to
play the next game,'' Utah forward Karl Malone said. ``We're not
going to be talking about running the scores up and all that, but
like I said, it's just one of those things.
	   ``If you're not ready to play after the things that went on out
there, you shouldn't be in this profession.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; AIR BALLS: Utah's 26 turnovers matched the NBA's all-time
playoff high. ... Only five players scored in double figures in
Game 3, tying the NBA Finals record for fewest players over 10
points. ... Scottie Pippen moved into third place on the NBA
Final's career steals list. Pippen had two Sunday, giving him a
total of 61.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; WORM WATCH: The Chicago Bulls are back home for the playoffs,
and that can only mean one thing: Dennis Rodman is going to be
late.
	   Rodman continued his own little playoff ritual, strolling into
the United Center about an hour before the tipoff for Game 3.
Players are supposed to be in the locker room 90 minutes before the
game, but Rodman has been showing up late since the Eastern
Conference finals began.
	   He's also been ducking back into the locker room when the game
starts, a move that's been criticized as disruptive to the team.
Rodman goes back to ride a bicycle to keep his muscles loose, but
he's never on the bench when Phil Jackson wants him, forcing the
coach to send a trainer to fetch him.
	   Jackson said before the game that he and Rodman have discussed
the Worm's antics, and everything is fine. Rodman went back to the
locker room Sunday, but he was on the bench when Jackson looked for
him.
	   ``He's 37, playing in a career which he's played a lot of
minutes and to get stiff, sometimes you don't loosen up for a
couple of minutes and that can be a critical couple of minutes. So,
I can understand that,'' Jackson said of Rodman's warmup habits.
	   Besides, it's not like Rodman is the only player who does this.
When Luc Longley picked up his fifth foul in Game 2, Jackson sent
him back to the locker room to stay loose.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; HABLA ESPANOL? The NBA is going south of the U.S. border.
	   The Los Angeles Clippers and San Antonio Spurs will play Dec. 12
in Mexico City as part of the NBA's effort to expand its
international market. The Houston Rockets and Dallas Mavericks
played at Mexico City's Palacio de los Deportes last year before a
crowd of 20,635 _ the largest crowd to ever see a basketball game
in that country.
	   The NBA has also played regular season games in Japan, and has
had exhibition games in Mexico, Italy, France, Germany, Spain and
the United Kingdom. The Miami Heat will play an exhibition game on
Oct. 12 in Israel.
</TEXT>
