<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Policy Differences </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mahathir's party backs his critique of money policy
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ New voices within Malaysia's
ruling party appear to be joining the prime minister's attack on
high interest rates, which his deputy argues are needed to
stabilize the economy.
	   ``We urge the government to take quick measures to reduce the
current high interest rate,'' a leader of the youth wing of Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad's United Malays National Organization was
quoted as saying by New Straits Times Monday.
	   The tight monetary policy was ``leaving behind an array of
problems,'' Abdul Rahim Mohamed Ghouse said.
	   More than 25,000 small industries were in dire straits because
high rates were choking cash flows and preventing them from running
businesses profitably, he said at a party meeting.
	   While Mahathir's deputy and finance minister, Anwar Ibrahim has
backed the central bank-prescribed rates, saying these were needed
to prevent a run on reserves and spiraling inflation, Mahathir has
repeatedly differed.
	   The issue reportedly divided officials at a recent Cabinet
meeting, with some people criticizing Anwar's solutions.
	   On Friday, Mahathir, who returned from Tokyo after a series of
speeches criticizing high interest rates, denied there was a rift
between him and Anwar on economic policy.
	   But he also refused to budge from his position.
	   ``I do not necessarily endorse Bank Negara's tight monetary
policy,'' he said. Bank Negara is the central bank.
	   Mahathir has routinely chided the International Monetary Fund
for recommending high interest rates as a panacea for economic
ills. IMF prescriptions often bring more pain to struggling
economies, he has said, citing Indonesia.
	   Malaysia should not follow IMF policies too closely, Mahathir
said in an interview in the June 8 issue of Time magazine.
	   ``Someone accused us of following the IMF prescription too
closely. Why do we raise interest rates? Why do we squeeze credit?
I replied: because we are frightened,'' he told Time.
	   ``If we were to follow the IMF any closer, we would bankrupt all
our companies.''
	   Malaysia's economy is battered by the same crisis that sent
Thailand, South Korea and Indonesia into recession and is now
threatening Hong Kong.
	   The government this month announced that gross domestic product
in the first quarter of 1998 had shrunk by 1.8 percent. Two
subsequent quarters of contraction usually mean recession. 	   
</TEXT>
