w2342 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-Disasters     06-08 0229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Disasters </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China bracing for floods, other disasters
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Alarmed by a series of floods, earthquakes and
other disasters that have killed hundreds of people this year, the
government has stepped up preparations for relief work, the
state-run newspaper China Daily said Monday.
	   More than 300 people were killed in floods that have struck 10
provinces, including usually arid Ningxia in the northwest and
Hunan, the worst-hit region, where some 648,000 homes have been
destroyed, the report said.
	   Floods triggered by torrential summer rains are an annual
scourge for much of southern China. But this year, unusually heavy
rainfall means that floods that usually peak in July and August are
expected to hit earlier and harder.
	   In eastern Jiangsu province, near Shanghai, the rainfall has
been 2.5 times heavier than normal, the report noted.
	   The Civil Affairs Ministry has allocated 850 million yuan (dlrs
102.9 million) to disaster relief, but even more was needed, the
report cited ministry official Zhou Ming as saying.
	   ``We need to put in more effort considering the frequency of
natural disasters this year,'' Zhou said.
	   But Zhou also said that those affected by calamities so far had
been provided with sufficient food, clothing and shelter and that
no major epidemics had broken out in disaster stricken areas. 	   
</TEXT>
