<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Nursing Cutback </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Malaysia bans more foreign nurses in state hospitals
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ The government has banned
recruitment of nurses from overseas in state-run hospitals in an
attempt to halt the outflow of foreign exchange amid an economic
crisis, a newspaper reported Monday.
	   The shortage of nursing staff in government-run hospitals would
be made good by increasing domestic recruitment, Star newspaper
reported, quoting Health Minister Chua Jui Meng.
	   More than 3,000 nurses being trained in Malaysia would be
recruited, he said.
	   Many foreign workers repatriate their savings to their home
countries after converting them into dollars, thus depleting the
nation's foreign exchange reserves.
	   About 300 nurses from India, Bangladesh, Myanmar and Indonesia
who are currently working in government hospitals could be asked to
leave soon, the minister said on Sunday. An exception would be made
for highly specialized nurses.
	   Since Malaysia's economic crisis deepened this year, the country
has deported 30,000 Indonesians found working without valid papers,
the home ministry said. Most workers deported have been from the
construction industry. 	   
</TEXT>
