<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-NKorea-Nuclear </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan ready to provide dlrs 1 billion for North Korean energy
</HEADLINE>
project &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan is ready to provide dlrs 1 billion, or nearly
one-fourth of the expected cost, for an international project to
construct nuclear reactors in North Korea, Foreign Minister Keizo
Obuchi said Monday.
	   Speaking in Parliament, Obuchi thus became the first official to
express Japan's intention to extend the funds for the project, a
Foreign Ministry official said.
	   In 1994, North Korea agreed to freeze and eventually dismantle
its nuclear weapons program in exchange for two light-water nuclear
power plants and 500,000-ton annual fuel shipments until the
facilities are completed.
	   That agreement, reached after intensive negotiations between the
United States and North Korea, was aimed at controlling nuclear
proliferation and preventing the reclusive state's ability to
produce nuclear weapons-grade material.
	   ``Efforts are under way in Japan to cooperate with dlrs 1
billion, although the nation's fiscal situation remains severe,''
Kyodo News quoted Obuchi as telling a parliamentary committee.
	   Officials from the Korean Peninsula Energy Development
Organization, or KEDO, held talks in New York earlier this month.
They agreed to meet again in Brussels on June 29-30 to try to
resolve differences over sharing the cost of supplying the two
reactors.
	   South Korea wants to reduce its share of the construction costs,
much of which has been calculated in the South Korean currency,
because of a sharp devaluation in the won due to the Asian
financial crisis.
	   The project is eventually expected to total somewhere between
dlrs 4 billion and dlrs 5 billion, down slightly from an original
forecast of dlrs 5.2 billion, said the ministry official, who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
	   The project has taken on new urgency since India and Pakistan
conducted nuclear test explosions last month, raising international
worries that the international non-nuclear proliferation system
might be jeopardized.
	   But Obuchi said there has been ``no clear sign'' at present of
North Korea's nuclear development progressing with alleged
technology cooperation from Pakistan, Kyodo reported.
	   KEDO comprises the United States, Japan, South Korea and the
European Union.
 &UR; (km)
</TEXT>
