<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Chiapas-Bishop,0492 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bishop who played central role retires from Chiapas peace efforts
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ALEJANDRO RUIZ GUZMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) _ Blaming the government
for stalled peace talks with armed rebels, Bishop Samuel Ruiz
stepped down as the central figure in efforts to resolve the
conflict in southern Mexico.
	   ``It is clear to me that a chapter in the peace process has
ended,'' the Roman Catholic bishop said in his Sunday homily. ``I
am grateful to all who have accompanied me in my mediation tasks.''
	   Ruiz's resignation as president of the church mediation team
formed after the Zapatista rebel uprising 4 1/2 years ago
underscores growing pessimism about peace efforts in the southern
state of Chiapas.
	   Several hours later, the church mediation commission announced
its dissolution, also blaming the government for ``dismantling the
necessary conditions for dialogue and negotiation.''
	   It cited growing militarization and violence by the government
and its agents in the region. Forty-five unarmed residents of a
pro-rebel village, many of them children, were killed in December
by gunmen linked to Mexico's governing party.
	   Mediation commission members also cited recent criticism of
their group by government leaders, including President Ernesto
Zedillo.
	   The bishop has been the central figure in peace efforts since
the Zapatista National Liberation Army staged a brief uprising in
January 1994, demanding greater rights for the region's
impoverished Indian farmers.
	   In March of that year, Ruiz invited the rebel's top military
leader Subcomandante Marcos and government peace envoy Manuel
Camacho Solis to the first series of talks, televised nationally
from this mountain community's centuries-old cathdral.
	   After talks broke down, Ruiz continued to urge both sides back
to negotiations. But the bishop said that unless the government
changes, more talks are impossible.
	   ``There will have to be constructed another chapter in which the
conditions for peace can be created,'' Ruiz said.
	   The government's backing off on a signed treaty to grant Indian
autonomy has resulted in ``a heavy, final silence'' from the
Zapatistas, said the bishop. He said that the government, in turn,
has read the rebels' silence as a rejection of dialogue.
	   Chiapas state and Mexico's federal governments have become
increasingly frustrated with the stalemate. For several years,
their primary strategy has been to surround them in one region with
thousands of troops.
	   Recent attempts to further marginalize the Zapatistas have
included expelling foreigners accused of rebel sympathies, and the
breaking up of pro-rebel parallel governments in Chiapas
municipalities.
	   Some 1,000 police officers and soldiers swarmed into a small
town early Wednesday, firing tear gas, breaking down doors and
arresting 167 rebel sympathizers.
</TEXT>
