<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore stock market and currency down on yen's fall, bad news
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Singapore's stocks and currency were both down
sharply Monday morning as regional and local developments depressed
the markets.
	   The benchmark Straits Times Industrial Index was down 2.6
percent at noon (0400 GMT), about 30 points off its 1168.46
opening. It dropped to a low of 1127.33 in late morning trading
before recovering slightly.
	   The Singapore dollar was also sharply lower, breaking the
psychologically important 1.70 level against the U.S. currency. In
late morning trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 1.7125 against
the greenback, up from 1.6945 late Friday in Asia.
	   The markets were reacting to the continued weakness of the
Japanese yen and other regional currencies, along with news over
the weekend that a local property company defaulted on a payment
deadline for a development plot.
	   The U.S. dollar broke above the psychologically important 140
yen level as the market opened in Tokyo, and the Singapore dollar
slumped Monday morning in sympathy.
	   News that a Singapore-Hong Kong joint venture missed a deadline
for a 68.6 million Singapore dollar (dlrs 40 million) payment on a
plot of land to develop condominiums also dampened sentiment.
	   The company, a joint venture between Singapore's Eltech
Electronics and Hong Kong's Lai Sun Development, missed the last
deadline Friday to pay the remaining 75 percent of the bid it made
last July.
	   Mounting fears that Singapore could head into a recession this
year are also depressing the stock market, according to dealers.
	   The chairman of United Overseas Bank, Wee Cho Yaw, has warned
that the Singapore economy may slip into a recession next year if
the government does not take immediate steps.
	   Dealers said they were awaiting comments by Deputy Prime
Minister Lee Hsien Loong, who is also the chairman of Singapore's
de facto central bank, on the banking sector at a speech expected
after the markets close. 	   
</TEXT>
