<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Queensland Election </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Poll: Hanson's One Nation Party saps governing conservatives
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Australia-Hanson

<TEXT>
	   BRISBANE, Australia (AP) _ With Queensland's election looming
Saturday, Pauline Hanson's One Nation Party continues to drain
support from Australia's governing conservatives, lifting the
opposition Labor Party to victory, a new poll says.
	   The Bulletin-Morgan Poll released Monday is the third major
survey in a week to predict the split in conservative ranks will
turn the government over from Premier Rob Borbidge's conservative
coalition to the Labor Party.
	   If the conservatives lose Queensland, partly because Hanson's
ultra-rightist party has cut into their appeal, it is a bad omen
for Australian Prime Minister John Howard.
	   He has to call an election by March and faces the same problem
on a national scale.
	   The 89-seat Queensland Parliament is split 44-44 between
Borbidge's conservatives and the Labor Party; Borbidge has retained
government only with the support of one independent legislator.
	   But that looks set to end Saturday, with support for the
conservatives down 19 percent with its voters flocking to Hanson's
One Nation, according to the new Bulletin-Morgan Poll.
	   Labor is poised to win, the poll found, with 54 percent support,
up 7.3 percent since the 1995 election. The conservative coalition
vote was down 7.3 percent to 46 percent, the poll results said.
	   The poll, to be published in Wednesday's Bulletin magazine, has
the National/Liberal conservative coalition on 30 percent of the
primary vote, down from 49 percent since 1995.
	   One Nation is continuing to climb at 18.5 percent, the
Bulletin-Morgan Poll said.
	   When asked who they expected to win on Saturday, 52 percent of
those polled said Labor, 30 percent said the conservative coalition
and 18 percent were undecided.
	   Asked why One Nation supporters preferred Pauline Hanson to
Premier Rob Borbidge or Labor's Peter Beattie, nearly half said she
was ``better, more trustworthy, more honest than other politicians
and knows what Australians want.''
	   Fourteen percent chose One Nation because of their anti-Asian
immigration policies, 10 percent on Aboriginal issues and 5 percent
for gun control.
	   A significant 17 percent voted for One Nation on the basis of
other issues, like being against foreign aid and protecting
Australian jobs.
	   The Bulletin-Morgan Poll was conducted by telephone to 1,255
electors throughout the state on June 6 and 7, one week before the
state election. The margin of error was not provided. 	   
</TEXT>
