<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Suharto-Birthday, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Suharto turns 77, lonely and upset over allegations
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS possible news conference, graf 7; Suharto happy to be a
private citizen, graf 15

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesia's former president had his
77th birthday Monday, reportedly lonely and upset over allegations
that he and his family amassed billions of dollars illegally.
	   The Jakarta Post quoted a Suharto aide as saying few of his old
friends and associates have visited him at his home in central
Jakarta since he quit office last month.
	   Military personnel guard the house but no longer salute him,
said the aide who has worked for Suharto since the 1970s.
	   Only a pet parrot, long ago trained to say ``Good Morning Bapak
(Mister) President,'' still calls him by his former title, the Post
said.
	   On the rare occasions that he leaves his house, his car must
stop at red lights, whereas before his presidential limousine sped
through the streets of Jakarta under police escort.
	   The Post said he planned to hold a news conference Tuesday to
counter growing allegations against him. However, officials later
said nothing had been scheduled.
	   Forced to quit after mobs went on a rampage and angry protesters
demanded he be tried for corruption, Suharto has said nothing
publicly since his May 21 resignation.
	   Critics say he and his family amassed between dlrs 20 to 40
billion in assets during his 32 years in power.
	   Many want the state to seize the money and use it to help
Indonesia overcome its worst economic crisis in decades.
	   Inflation and unemployment have soared, making life miserable
for many of the nation's 202 million people.
	   New President B.J. Habibie has said that an inquiry will be held
into corruption under Suharto's rule. However, he has called on
Indonesians not to seek unlawful retribution.
	   Habibie, a longtime friend and formerly the loyal deputy of
Suharto, has rolled back many of his old boss's draconian ways. He
has released some political prisoners, promised elections in 1999,
ended a ban on free labor unions and dropped restrictions on media
freedom.
	   He has also said that he hasn't talked to the aging former
autocrat since he was sworn in as the new head of state.
	   The Post said Suharto spends most of his time at home reading
newspapers, which daily run accusations of corruption and nepotism
during his time in office. He also watches television and spends
time with his grandchildren.
	   The aide said Suharto was happy to be a private citizen again.
	   Presidential security guards still stand watch over his home.
But their numbers are gradually being reduced.
	   ``As he is no longer president, they do not give him a military
salute,'' the Post quoted an unidentified aide as saying.
	   Few people still come to see Suharto because ties to the former
president are now seen as a liability in post-Suharto Indonesia,
the aide was quoted as saying. 	   
</TEXT>
