r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-Elections     06-08 0280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Elections </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodian leader visits king amid election dispute
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Cambodian strongman Hun Sen headed
Monday for the northwestern province of Siem Reap early Monday for
a surprise audience with King Norodom Sihanouk amid a dispute that
could hurt the credibility of upcoming elections.
	   A Hun Sen adviser, Prak Sokhon, said he didn't know the purpose
of the talks. However, the topic was expected to be the deadlock in
Cambodia's highest legal appeals body, the Constitutional Council,
charged with resolving election problems.
	   The inaugural meeting of the nine-member council was stalled for
the second time last week when the king's three appointees did not
show. They appear to be protesting that the other six members of
the supposedly neutral panel are strong Hun Sen supporters.
	   In a faxed weekend statement, the king strongly denied ``any
ill-intentioned allegations'' that he was behind their boycott.
	   Hun Sen ousted the king's son, Prince Norodom Ranariddh, as his
co-prime minister in a bloody coup 11 months ago. He has sought new
elections to win back aid and legitimacy lost after the takeover.
	   The council, charged with determining the constitutionality of
all laws, would be called on to resolve disputes arising from
controversial electoral and political party regulations.
	   The former chairman of the Supreme Court, Chan Sok, who also
sits on the body, has warned that further deadlock could call into
question the credibility of elections, scheduled July 26.
	   Sihanouk, the country's constitutional monarch, resides at a
palace in Siem Reap, near the ancient Angkor temple complex. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
