r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Thailand-Markets     06-08 0168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai currency plumbs new lows; stocks down
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ The Thai currency hit a 13-week low
Monday as investors dumped regional currencies after the U.S.
dollar surged to a seven-year high against the Japanese yen.
	   Thai share prices were also down in line with other Asian
bourses. The Stock Exchange of Thailand index lost 1.33 points at
the open to 316.83.
	   At mid-morning, the dollar had strengthened to 43.80 baht, up
from 43.25 at the close of trading Friday. It was the baht's
weakest level since March 10.
	   Dealers blamed the stock market and baht decline to a regional
currency sell-off as the dollar rose above 140 Japanese yen for the
first time since June 1991.
	   The weakness of the Japanese currency, dealers said, spells
trouble for crisis-hit Southeast Asian economies that have been
increasingly dependent on Japan as an export market.
	   Fears are rising that the Asian economic crisis could enter a
new, more devastating phase. 	   
</TEXT>
