w2382 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AsianMarkets     06-08 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asian Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian stock markets mostly lower as currencies plunge on weak yen
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Most Asian markets extended last week's losses
early Monday on fears that further depreciation in the yen, which
fell to a seven-year low, could spark another round of currency
devaluations in Asia.
	   Many regional currencies also plunged through important support
levels early Monday as investors shifted their money into more
robust markets in the United States and Europe.
	   Dealers in the region said institutional investors, spooked by
the weakening regional currencies and persistent pessimism over
Japan's economy, continued to dump shares.
	   Though regional bourses were mostly lower, there were no steep
falls. The largest was in Singapore, where the benchmark Straits
Times Industrial Index was down 33.47 points, or 2.9 percent, at
1,134.99 at midday.
	   The U.S. dollar broke through the 140-yen level for the first
time in seven years in New York on Sunday, and showed no signs of
slowing in morning trading Monday in Tokyo.
	   In Tokyo, the dollar bought 140.69 yen at midday, up 1.27 yen
from late Friday in Tokyo and its highest point since June 20,
1991. In New York, the dollar settled at 139.75 yen on Friday.
	   ``Further depreciation of the yen is sparking another round of
currency devaluation in Asia,'' said Joseph Yam, chief executive of
the Hong Kong Monetary Association, Hong Kong's de facto central
bank, on the sidelines of a conference in Switzerland.
	   The weaker yen also raises ``concern in fixed exchange rates
like the Hong Kong dollar and the (Chinese) yuan ,'' he added.
``That actually isn't very helpful to everybody.''
	   Officials in China and Hong Kong have vowed repeatedly to defend
the fixed exchange rates. Devaluation of the two currencies would
likely reverberate through the region's troubled economies.
	   The dollar's strength against the yen sprang from fresh evidence
of a robust U.S. economy after the Labor Department reported on
Friday that the nation's unemployment rate held to a 28-year-low of
4.3 percent in May.
	   Also supporting the U.S. currency was the diminishing likelihood
the Group of Seven industrialized nations will make a strong
statement criticizing the current dollar level at their meeting
Tuesday, traders said.
	   Elsewhere, the yen's weakness drove the Singapore dollar past
the key support level of 1.7000 to the U.S. dollar, and the
Malaysian ringgit past 4.000 to the dollar.
	   The Thai baht was at a 13-week low at midday, and Indonesia's
thinly-traded rupiah lost 2 percent in value against the U.S.
dollar.
	   The Australian dollar dropped to its lowest level against the
dollar since July 1986, hitting a low of 59.75 U.S. cents by
afternoon.
	   New Zealand's dollar was also lower, down to 50.88 U.S. cents.
	   In Taipei, the dollar also opened at an 11-year-high against the
New Taiwan dollar, but fell later amid talk of intervention by
Taiwan's central bank.
	   On other stock markets, in Tokyo, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock
Average edged down 26.03 points, or 0.17 percent, to 15,297.40 at
midday. On Friday, it had lost 103.04 points.
	   Shares in Hong Kong closed mixed at midday, with the blue-chip
Hang Seng Index rising 11.84 points to 8,581.31.
	   Meanwhile, shares in Kuala Lumpur, Bangkok and Manila were
moderately lower, but the key index in Jakarta rose slightly on
gains of telecommunications shares.
	   In Seoul, despite the weakening won, shares opened sharply
higher on optimism that President Kim Dae-jung, currently in the
U.S., will succeed in drawing more foreign investment, analysts
said.
	   The key Korea Composite Stock Price Index opened up 11.43
points, or 3.3 percent, to 352.96. 	   
</TEXT>
