w2385 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-Alternati     06-08 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Alternative Centennial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine leftists to stage separate centennial celebration
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Left-wing groups said Monday they
will hold a protest parade in Manila to celebrate their version of
the 100th anniversary of the Philippines' declaration of
independence from 333 years of Spanish colonial rule.
	   The protest coincides with, and could disrupt, a
government-organized centennial parade also scheduled on Friday in
Manila.
	   Leaders of the New Nationalist Alliance said they will celebrate
the demise of Spain's colonial reign in 1898 but also highlight the
United States' subsequent takeover of the Philippines.
	   ``We would like to stress that there is an unfinished
revolution,'' said Lutgardo Jurcales of the alliance. ``This is the
fight against the vestiges of U.S. colonialism.''
	   The Philippines was a Spanish possession from 1565 to 1898.
	   Gen. Emilio Aguinaldo, a former mayor who became the republic's
first president, declared independence from Spain on June 12, 1898,
at a house in Kawit in Cavite province, south of Manila.
	   Before the Philippines could gain its independence, however, the
United States acquired it after defeating Spain in the 1898
Spanish-American War.
	   The country gained its formal independence from the United
States on July 4, 1946, but American influence remained strong
thereafter.
	   Jurcales said students, activists and workers will join a march
from a statue of Philippine revolutionary hero Andres Bonifacio in
downtown Manila to the U.S. Embassy along Roxas Boulevard, where
the main government parade also will pass.
	   Police have said they plan to tightly guard the government
parade and other centennial activities, which are expected to draw
large crowds of people.
	   Jurcales said they have no plans of disrupting the main
centennial parade, which left-wing groups describe as ``elitist and
highly commercialized.''
	   The Philippine government, helped by private companies, is
spending at least 3.5 billion pesos (dlrs 92 million) on the
centennial celebrations, which are to be highlighted by a trade and
historical exposition at the Clark Special Economic Zone, a former
U.S. air base in northern Pampanga province.
	   A third of the money is going to the renovation of 16 historic
shrines and the construction of historical markers and monuments
along the ``freedom trail,'' areas where Filipinos put up
resistance against Spain. 	   
</TEXT>
