<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-New Zealand-Wildlife Smuggling </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Zealand major staging post for smugglers of wildlife
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) _ The world's most endangered birds
and animals are stopping over in New Zealand before being sold to
rich Americans as part of a large wildlife smuggling trade,
officials said Monday.
	   New Zealand Wildlife Enforcement Group investigator Peter
Younger said the international trade in endangered species ranked
behind drugs and guns as the highest illegal money earner.
	   Interpol has valued the illegal wildlife trade internationally
at U.S. dlrs 3 billion and identified New Zealand as a major
staging post for smuggled wildlife from Australia and other Pacific
countries to other parts of the world.
	   Following a request from American authorities, the enforcement
group _ made up of representatives from the Department of
Conservation, Customs Service and the Ministry of Agriculture _
helped to uncover a gecko-smuggling ring estimated to be worth
around U.S. dlrs 270,000.
	   The lizards _ which fetch up to U.S. dlrs 4,750 on the U.S.
market _ were being smuggled from New Caledonia in baggage that was
left in transit in New Zealand before carrying on to America,
Younger said.
	   The native tree geckos were placed in cloth bags inside
cardboard boxes.
	   An American who had regularly stopped over in New Zealand during
trips to New Caledonia was arrested in Los Angeles after he was
found with 57 of the lizards in his baggage.
	   ``We assisted the U.S. authorities with descriptions, search of
baggage and advised them of his onward travel,'' Younger said.
	   The group had earlier been contacted by the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service as part of Operation Jungle Trade, a three-year
undercover investigation which resulted in the arrest in America of
40 people and the seizure of 660 endangered birds and other
animals.
	   The protected birds and animals were being smuggled across the
United States-Mexico border and being sold in nine U.S. states,
Puerto Rico and 10 other countries.
	   The seizure was estimated to be worth more than U.S. dlrs
500,000.
	   Earlier this year a New Zealand bird breeder, Roy Nichols, 40,
was sent to jail for 18 months after being found guilty on
smuggling charges involving exotic bird eggs, tortoises and
chameleons.
	   The trial in the High Court at Auckland was the first under the
Biosecurity Act to involve exotic birds. 	   
</TEXT>
