<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Flood Warning </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
After drought, Malaysia braces for floods
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Still reeling from the effects of
its worst drought in decades, Malaysia is bracing for floods, the
national news agency reported Monday.
	   Local officials had been directed to dig pools and channels that
would drain flooded rivers and prevent farmlands from being
inundated, Deputy Agriculture Minister Mahmud Mansor was quoted as
saying by Bernama news agency.
	   Some weather experts say that the El Nino system, blamed for
causing the drought in Southeast Asia, is weakening. But it could
be replaced by the so-called La Nina, which could reverse some of
the effects and bring excessive rain. Its strength or timing is not
entirely predictable.
	   ``We have to brace ourselves for La Nina,'' Mahmud told
reporters Sunday in the northeastern city of Kuala Terengganu.
	   Agencies like the Drainage and Irrigation Department have been
put on alert in anticipation of the destructive power of the La
Nina, he said.
	   The minister said the government had allotted 400 million
ringgit (dlrs 100 million) for measures to combat floods.
	   The drought has not only caused a severe water shortage in Kuala
Lumpur, with rain-fed reservoirs drying up, but also left huge
tracts of farmland parched in the north and south.
	   The price of home-grown rice has risen by 20 percent and the
government last week said it would have to import more rice to meet
the shortfall caused by crop failures. 	   
</TEXT>
