<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Labor Protest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thousands of strikers rally, clash with police in Indonesia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ As many as 10,000 striking workers
scuffled with and threw rocks at anti-riot police when they staged
a 10-kilometer (6-mile) march through the streets of Indonesia's
second city of Surabaya on Monday.
	   Police and witnesses said violence broke out when a line of
police blocked the path of the marchers as they approached the East
Java's provincial parliament building.
	   At least five police and three protesters were hospitalized.
Some were bleeding after being beaten with sticks or being hit with
rocks.
	   The protest was the biggest since Indonesia's new President B.J.
Habibie last week relaxed tight restrictions on labor unions and
signed an International Labor Organization convention on respect
for workers' rights.
	   Habibie, who has delivered a list of liberalizing reforms, was
sworn in May 21 after ex-President Suharto resigned following a
wave of protests and riots against his 32-year authoritarian grip
on power.
	   Police later let the crowd pass and stage a noisy rally outside
the legislature in Surabaya, about 650 kilometers (400 miles) east
of Jakarta.
	   Witnesses said the strikers damaged at least five automobiles.
Police denied one report that two police motorcycles were set
afire.
	   Police spokesman Lt. Col. Sutrisno said about 10 people were
being questioned.
	   Shops were closed but were not attacked, said witness Ludi
Lumanto.
	   The workers, employees of a household appliance manufacturer,
went on strike last Tuesday demanding higher salaries and better
conditions as the effects of Indonesia's worst economic crisis in
30 years begins to bite.
	   Among their demands was the right to observe Islamic prayers
during their working time. About 90 percent of Indonesia's 202
million people are Muslim.
	   Indonesia is now suffering runaway inflation and mass
unemployment as the economic situation worsens.
	   Meanwhile in Jakarta several smaller and peaceful
anti-government rallies were held.
	   At one demonstration about 100 protesters called for Habibie to
speed up the promised release of as many as 200 political
prisoners. So far four political prisoners have been freed. 	   
</TEXT>
