<HEADLINE>
Report: Body of Indonesian shooting victim exhumed, bullet removed
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Officials investigating the deaths of
four student protesters, allegedly shot by security personnel last
month, have exhumed the body of one the victims and removed a
bullet from it, the Jakarta Post newspaper reported Monday.
	   It said the body of Heri Hartanto was taken from its grave in a
Jakarta cemetery on Saturday and brought to a hospital where a
bullet was taken from the man's chest.
	   The military has charged 18 police officers in the fatal
shootings. Court martial proceedings against two started on
Saturday.
	   Government critics claim that military personnel might have also
been involved in the deaths, which have been solely blamed on the
police.
	   Prosecutors say police should have only used rubber bullets.
	   Mum'im Idries, a physician who examined all four victims before
burial, said they died of wounds from real bullets.
	   He said he removed one bullet from the body of another victim
before it was buried. Bullets that hit two others had passed
through their bodies.
	   The protesters died when shots were fired at Jakarta's Trisakti
University as an anti-government rally took place.
	   The deaths caused an uproar in the capital, Jakarta, and were
followed by a wave of rioting.
	   Almost 1,200 people died in the violence, which helped force
ex-President Suharto to resign after 32 years in power. 	   
