<SLUG> BC-China-Housing </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China's commercial banks increase loans for housing
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Mortgage loans by China's commercial banks rose
only by a sliver in the first quarter of 1998, despite the
government's announcement of a program encouraging private
apartment purchases, the China Securities News reported Monday.
	   Housing loans by the four state-owned commercial banks rose 0.3
percent or 834 million yuan (dlrs 100.97 million) to 264.3 billion
(dlrs 32 billion) in the first three months over the same period
last year, the report said.
	   Of the total, loans to individuals amounted to 33.7 billion
(dlrs 4.08 billion), it said.
	   China's four state-owned commercial banks _ the Industrial &AMP;
Commercial Bank of China, the Agricultural Bank of China, the Bank
of China and the China Construction Bank _ are intended to be at
the vanguard of reforms intended to build a commercially sound
banking system.
	   To boost flagging economic activity and fend off the economic
doldrums that have stricken much of Asia, the government has
declared the housing industry a key area of growth.
	   Earlier this year, the People's Bank of China, the central bank,
said banks can allocate up to 15 percent of their loan portfolios
to mortgages. The central bank has also raised ceilings for housing
debt so banks could accommodate more mortgage lending. 	   
</TEXT>
