<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Political Prisoners </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian human rights watchdog group wants more dissidents freed
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesia's National Human Rights
Commission called Monday on new President B.J. Habibie to make good
a promise to release more political prisoners put behind bars by
his authoritarian predecessor, Suharto.
	   Commission member Marzuki Darusman told reporters after meeting
with Habibie the commission would hold talks with the Justice
Ministry with the aim of speeding up the release of inmates.
	   The commission was appointed by Suharto in 1993, but has a
proven track record for investigating human rights abuses.
	   Suharto ended 32 years in office on May 21 when he quit and was
replaced by Habibie.
	   Within days the new leader ordered the release of four high
profile dissidents who had been jailed for criticizing Suharto's
regime. Habibie said more would be released in the future, but gave
no timetable.
	   Private human rights groups say at least 200 political prisoners
are still locked up.
	   Darusman declined to tell reporters how many prisoners might be
freed but said the commission wanted more releases as soon as
possible.
	   Also on Monday about 100 protesters staged a peaceful rally
outside the Justice Ministry demanding the prisoners' immediate
release.
	   Some carried a banner that read: ``Hey government! What about
your promise to release more political prisoners?''
	   ``It seems that the government isn't really serious about
granting amnesties to more political prisoners,'' said Bonar Tigor
Naipospos, a former jailed dissident who now heads the Indonesian
Society for Humanity. 	   
</TEXT>
