w2425 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-AirlineSt     06-08 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Airline Strike </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine labor officials call meeting to resolve pilots' strike
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos Planned
 &UR; By JIM GOMEZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Labor officials called an emergency
meeting Monday to try to resolve a strike by more than 600 pilots
at Philippine Airlines which has plunged the financially troubled
flag-carrier into crisis.
	   PAL fired all the striking pilots on Sunday, calling their
action illegal, except for a few who had complied with an airline
order to return to work to avoid dismissal.
	   Labor Secretary Cresenciano Trajano said the Philippine
government is intervening in the dispute because it affects the
national interest. Representatives of PAL's management and the
620-strong Airline Pilots Association of the Philippines were
summoned to the meeting.
	   Trajano said he ordered the strikers to return to work and the
airline to accept them back. He also urged both sides to refrain
from further hostile actions.
	   The union is protesting a new management policy of firing pilots
who have reached 20 years of service or flown 20,000 hours,
regardless of age. The policy puts about 200 pilots in danger of
forced retirement, the union said.
	   The financially beleaguered airline has said it must cut
expenses by as much as 40 percent, slash flights, and sharply
reduce its work force in order to survive. The airline hasn't
disclosed an estimate for its manpower reduction, but employees
fear it could be as much as 30 percent.
	   The strike began Friday, forcing cancellations of more than 200
international and domestic flights and affecting thousands of
passengers.
	   PAL fired all 29 officers of the union on Saturday and warned
remaining members would also be dismissed if they didn't return to
work by noon Sunday. The 620 striking pilots represent the
airlines' total pilot force.
	   Virtually all of the pilots, however, defied the order and PAL
announced Sunday it was firing all the strikers, plunging the
airline into one of its most serious crises. PAL said it has
started to process job applications of new pilots.
	   PAL called the strike illegal because the Department of Labor
had earlier assumed jurisdiction over the dispute and barred both
sides from committing any hostile actions.
	   The airline said the strike was embarrassing the country, citing
pilots who abandoned a PAL plane in Bangkok at the start of the
strike.
	   PAL scheduled one flight each to Hong Kong and Tokyo on Monday
but indefinitely canceled all flights to the United States, Europe
and Australia. One return flight each from Hong Kong and Singapore
also was scheduled, along with 14 domestic flights.
	   Most of the flights were being flown by management pilots, who
are senior pilots who train other pilots.
	   Over the past four years, the airline has incurred annual losses
ranging from 451.4 million pesos (dlrs 11.3 million) to 2.5 billion
pesos (dlrs 62.5 million), in part because of large debts, an aging
fleet and Asia's currency crisis.
	   Angel Sambo, a PAL spokesman, denied union allegations that the
dismissals could be a way of achieving a reduction of PAL's
workforce.
	   ``Why would PAL go into that? We have no pilots to fly our
planes now,'' he said.
	   PAL is controlled by Chinese Filipino tycoon Lucio Tan. It had
been completely owned by the Philippine government from 1941 until
it was partly sold in 1992. 	   
</TEXT>
