<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Indonesia-Investment </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Investors postpone Singapore-Indonesian resort development
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Stung by the economic crisis gripping Southeast
Asia, major investors have postponed further development of a
resort complex on the nearby Indonesian island of Bintan, a
newspaper reported Monday.
	   Started seven years ago, Singapore and Indonesian investors
planned to turn 23,000 hectares (57,000 acres) into the Bintan
Beach International Resort, with hotels, golf clubs, and housing
units.
	   But investment groups have shelved their plans indefinitely,
putting on hold developments worth more than one billion Singapore
dollars (dlrs 585 million), according to The Business Times.
	   About 2 billion Singapore dollars (dlrs 1.17 billion) have
already been committed to the project, according to the newspaper.
	   The first phase covering 6,000 hectares (14,800 acres) has been
launched, and about 240 million Singapore dollars (dlrs 140
million) has already been spent on island infrastructure.
	   Four major investor groups _ including Singapore
government-linked companies like Sembawang Corp. and the Wah Chang
group _ have completed sizable projects, the daily said.
	   Bintan Beach International Resort is owned by Bintan Resort
Corp., whose shareholders include Indonesia's Salim Group and a
Singapore consortium which includes government-linked conglomerate
Singapore Technologies Industrial Corp. and four major banks.
</TEXT>
