<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Editor Shot, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Newspaper editor loyal to Cambodian leader Hun Sen shot
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS 3 grafs at bottom with statement from president of
journalist association &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ The publisher-editor of the
country's most widely-read newspaper _ which supports Cambodian
strongman Hun Sen _ was shot by an unidentified gunman Monday.
	   At least two of six bullets fired struck Thong Uy Pang, 55, in
the shoulder while he was standing outside a pagoda, his wife and
police said. His bodyguards returned fire. One was hit and so was
the gunman, who fled, witnesses said.
	   Thong Uy Phang was undergoing surgery at the capital's Calmette
Hospital. Yet Razaque, a deputy municipal police commissioner, said
the shooting was being investigated. There was no immediate known
motive.
	   Thong Uy Phang's hard-hitting Koh Santepheap (Island of Peace)
backs Hun Sen, who has often been accused of orchestrating attacks
on journalists supporting his opponents.
	   Last October, two men on a motorcycle hurled grenades inside
Thong Uy Phang's residential compound. No one was hurt, but damage
was extensive. That attack was apparently prompted by articles
about internal problems within Hun Sen's Cambodian People's Party.
	   The journalist's wife, Yim Phanny, said she was standing next to
him Monday before the shooting. He was talking on a mobile phone to
an angry reader about an article criticizing the electricity
company for allegedly inflating prices.
	   Thong Uy Phang shouted, ``I'm hit!'' when the first bullet
struck him and tried to pull his own gun, but was unable to return
fire, his wife said.
	   Yim Phanny said that she thought there was a plot to assassinate
her husband but had no idea who was behind it.
	   Hun Sen is engaged in an election campaign seeking to restore
international legitimacy and aid lost since his bloody coup last
year against his co-prime minister, Prince Norodom Ranariddh.
	   The opposition has complained of being denied access to the
broadcast media, controlled entirely by Hun Sen, and of violence
and intimidation of opposition supporters.
	   Chum Kanal, president of the League of Cambodian Journalists, a
media association sympathetic to Hun Sen, condemned the attack,
said he thought opposition politicians might be resorting to
violence to obstruct the electoral campaign.
	   ``This is a barbarous act which is unacceptable,'' said Chum
Kanal. ``I consider this to be politically motivated terrorism, and
I ask the authorities to find the culprit.''
	   He said that in recent months attacks against journalists have
calmed, but that with the return of opposition politicians _ who
fled the country in fear following last year's coup d'etat _ he now
sees a return to ``terrorist tactics.''
</TEXT>
