<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Japan-Communists </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japanese and Chinese Communists seek rapprochement in Beijing talks
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ The Japanese and Chinese Communist parties are
seeking to end more than 30 years of estrangement in talks that
began Monday in Beijing.
	   The head of the Japanese Communist Party's international
department, Hikaru Nishiguchi, met with his Chinese counterpart,
Dai Binggou, to discuss ways to revive ties severed in 1967, a
party official said on condition of anonymity.
	   During the 1966-1976 ultraleftist Cultural Revolution, China
declared the Japanese Communist Party an enemy because it refused
to ascribe to the utopian dogma ordered by then-leader Mao
Tse-tung.
	   An attempt to reach rapprochement failed in 1985 during talks in
Europe.
	   Early this year, the two groups resumed efforts to settle their
differences. The Japanese Communist Party group now in Beijing is
the first such delegation to visit China since 1966.
	   The talks are to prepare for a visit to China later this summer
by Japanese Communist Party Chairman Tetsuzo Fuwa for the
announcement of a joint statement on normalizing ties between the
two parties, the official said.
	   The newspaper of the Japanese Communist Party, the Akahata (Red
Flag), reopened its bureau in Beijing this year for the first time
since 1967.
	   Increasingly isolated in Japanese politics, the Japanese
Communist Party is seeking to develop relations with kindred
communist parties elsewhere.
</TEXT>
