<HEADLINE>
57 students in southeast China poisoned by pesticides
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Pesticide residues sickened 57 students in two
cases of food poisoning this month in southeastern China's Fujian
province, a Chinese newspaper reported Monday.
	   Twenty-four primary school students in the city of Changle
suffered headaches and vomiting on June 3 after eating
pesticide-tainted yangmei, or red bayberry, the China Youth Daily
reported.
	   A day earlier, 33 students in Xiamen fell ill after eating
pesticide-contaminated watercress, the report said. Students in
both cities were hospitalized, it said.
	   Agricultural officials say there are many cases of improper use
of farm chemicals on China's small family farms.
