r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Koreas-Electricity     06-08 0284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Koreas-Electricity </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Seoul official offers to provide surplus electricity to North Korea
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ A top South Korean government energy
official offered in an interview published Monday to provide
surplus electricity to energy-starved North Korea.
	   ``In promoting economic cooperation, electricity can be as
important as food,'' Chang Young-shik, head of the state-run Korea
Electric Power Corp., was quoted as saying by the Moonhwa Ilbo
newspaper.
	   ``Technically, the process is very simple and the work can be
done within a year, if the two governments reach such a deal,'' he
said.
	   Chang, a former economics professor at New York State
University, has stressed the importance of cooperation with North
Korea since being named to head the state-run utility in April.
	   South Korea, with a total generating capacity of 43 million
kilowatts, can produce 20 percent more electricity than it needs
daily.
	   ``A small fraction of the surplus electricity can help North
Korea in a big way,'' Chang said in the interview.
	   South Korean officials say most of North Korea's aging power
plants are fossil-fired and only produce about 1.5 million
kilowatts daily, about one-fifth of their total capacity, because
of fuel shortages.
	   ``Except for about 100 hours in the summer when electricity
demands reach their peak, we have enough surplus to provide them
almost throughout the year,'' Chang said.
	   About 200 North Koreans have defected to South Korea in the past
three years and all complained of acute food and fuel shortages in
their communist country.
	   Foreign tourists have reported frequent power outages, even in
Pyongyang, the capital.
</TEXT>
