<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sri Lanka-Summit,0406 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indian, Pakistani leaders may meet at July 9-11 South Asian summit
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) _ Sri Lankan officials said Monday they
have proposed July 9-11 for a South Asian summit at which the
leaders of rivals India and Pakistan counld sit down together for
the first time since their nuclear tests.
	   Tension in the region has been high since India's tests May 11
and 13, followed two weeks later by retaliatory tests from
Pakistan. The two countries have fought three wars since their
independence from Britain in 1947, and fears their rivalry could
escalate to nuclear war have prompted the U.N. Security Council to
call on them to talk about their differences, particularly their
disputing claims to the border region of Kashmir.
	   Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee and his Pakistani
counterpart Nawaz Sharif have said they want talks, but no dates
have been set. Both are, though, expected to attend next month's
summit of the seven-nation South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation in the Sri Lankan capital of Colombo.
	   Although SAARC meetings focus on multilateral trade and policy
matters, leaders can hold informal bilateral talks if they desire.
Members are Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan
and Sri Lanka.
	   At last year's summit, Sharif and Inder Kumar Gujral, then prime
minister of India, agreed to open negotiations on a number of
disputes. Those negotiations never got much beyond the stage of
bureaucrats wrangling over the agenda. The centrist Gujral was
replaced two months ago by Vajpayee who, though considered a
moderate, leads the right-wing Bharatiya Janata Party known for
Pakistan-bashing.
	   Speaking Sunday on condition of anonymity in Bangladesh, a
senior aide to Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina said Hasina will try to
bring India and Pakistan closer together during the summit.
	   The date for the summit is arranged by mutual consent of the
leaders of the seven member states.
	   Hasina has already agreed to the dates suggested by Sri Lankan
President Chandrika Kumaratunga, the Sri Lankan foreign ministry
said Monday in a press release.
	   Sri Lankan Foreign Minister Lakshman Kadirgamar will next visit
India and Nepal to formally propose the dates, and later this month
Maldives and Pakistan.
	   Sri Lanka's Deputy Foreign Minister Lakshman Kiriella will
deliver the invitation to Bhutan next week.
</TEXT>
