<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Heart Drug </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Roche withdraws heart drug Posicor
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BASEL, Switzerland (AP) _ Swiss pharmaceutical giant Roche
announced Monday it is withdrawing the drug Posicor, prescribed for
high blood pressure and chronic angina pain.
	   The voluntary withdrawal is ``based on evolving information
concerning the potential for drug interactions, some of them
serious, which may occur when Posicor is taken together with some
other medications,'' Roche said in a statement.
	   It advised patients to consult their doctors about ``appropriate
alternative therapy'' and not to simply discontinue treatment with
the drug. Roche also warned patients against adding any new
medication to their present treatment without advice.
	   The decision followed analysis of the preliminary results of a
three-year study of the drug in congestive heart failure, the
company said.
	   In December, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration warned
doctors not to prescribe the drug for patients with low heart rates
or who are taking certain cholesterol-lowering drugs.
	   The warnings were prompted by reports that seven patients
suffered drug-associated muscle injury as the result of taking
Posicor together with the cholesterol-lowering medication
simvastatin.
	   ``In principle, drug interactions can be addressed by
appropriate labeling,'' Roche said. But in this case, ``the
complexity of such a prescribing information would make it too
difficult to implement.''
	   Known also as mibefradil, the drug was first launched in
mid-1997 and is available in 38 countries.
 &UR; (dj-gm)
</TEXT>
