<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Elections </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Center-right batters left in Italian regional elections
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Candidates backed by Italy's center-right opposition
swept to victory in regional run-off elections, final results
showed Monday, dealing a further blow to the center-left which
emerged defeated in the first round.
	   The center-right, led by media magnate and former premier Silvio
Berlusconi, claimed 10 of the 16 mayoralties in the provincial
capitals where a second round of voting was required.
	   Center-left parties, which form premier Romano Prodi's governing
coalition, won five. A new moderate movement created by former
president Francesco Cossiga put a mayor in office in Oristano,
Sardinia.
	   Even the traditional leftist strongholds of Parma, Piacenza and
Lucca, wealthy towns in central Italy, succumbed to the
center-right.
	   Some 3.5 million Italians were elegible to vote Sunday in 73
mayoral races up and down the country, and three provincial
presidencies.
	   Candidates who captured more than 50 percent in the first round
of ballotting May 24 were declared winners.
	   Partially turning around a sweep by the right in Sicilian
provincial elections, the center-left grabbed seats in Syracuse and
Caltanisetta from center-right incumbents. The left now holds three
of the nine provincial presidencies on the island.
	   Umberto Bossi's autonomy-minded Northern League clinched the
provincial presidency in Treviso, an industrial city in Italy's
north.
	   Voter turnout dropped from 76.6 percent in the first round to
53.4 percent Sunday.
	   (vg)	   
</TEXT>
