r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Commonwealth-T     06-08 0248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Commonwealth-Tickets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Poor overseas sales may push organizers to sell more at home
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ More tickets for the Kuala Lumpur
Commonwealth Games may have to be sold within Malaysia because of
the poor response overseas, the chief organizer said Monday.
	   Hashim Ali, executive chairman of the 1998 games committee, said
organizers might increase Malaysia's share of sales to 80 percent
if overseas purchases do not pick up.
	   Organizers had hoped to sell 30 percent of the 1.28 million
tickets overseas and the remaining in Malaysia. ``We will monitor
ticket sales until the end of this month,'' Hashim said.
	   So far, 31,000 tickets had been sold locally and 29,000 in other
countries, mostly within the Commonwealth, a grouping of former
British colonies.
	   Hashim blamed ticket agents appointed by the London-based
Commonwealth Games Federation for the poor response. The agents had
tried to package tickets in a tour along with air fares and
accommodation.
	   Now, the Federation had permitted the local organizers to try
and sell tickets overseas, he said. Agents would be appointed to
sell in Australia and New Zealand.
	   More than 4,100 athletes from 67 nations are expected to
participate in the 10-day event that begins on Sept. 11.
	   Last week, organizers said they were battling to meet a 33
million ringgit (dlrs 8.9 million) shortfall, caused mostly by the
poor response to the advance sale of tickets.
</TEXT>
