<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Opposition </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Opposition calls for coalition to prevent `police state'
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BETH DUFF-BROWN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Four opposition parties announced
Monday an effort to form a coalition that would safeguard against
Malaysia becoming a ``police state.''
	   The parties said freedom of speech and assembly had been badly
eroded in the last several weeks, after three public meetings were
denied police permits.
	   The Democratic Action Party, Malaysian Socialist Party, Islamic
Party of Malaysia and People's Party announced the formation of the
Council for Justice, Freedom, Democracy and Good Governance to
mobilize public support for their cause.
	   ``We hope that like-minded individuals in other groups will join
us in this struggle for justice, freedom and democracy,'' said Lim
Kit Siang, the opposition leader in Parliament and head of the DAP.
	   Last week, the police banned a consumer rights group from
organizing a public meeting to discuss the severe water rationing
in the capital, where nearly 2 million people have suffered dry
faucets for three months.
	   The previous Sunday, more than 50 police officers in riot gear
broke up a gathering organized by the DAP party leaders.
	   Police said the meeting in a city hotel was illegal as the
organizers had not applied for a police permit. But the party said
it had informed the police.
	   Lim and his son, Lim Guan Eng, were to speak at that meeting
about the younger Lim's 18-month prison sentence for printing a
pamphlet that criticized the government. Lim Guan Eng is also one
of nine DAP members of Parliament.
	   Lim said police in riot gear also broke up a meeting on June 2
organized by the DAP in the central state of Malacca.
	   There is no blanket ban in Malaysia on demonstrations and
protests, but police permission is required. The law states that a
meeting of more than five people who intend to hold a public
gathering requires a permit.
	   Several hours after the Council's news conference, the Malaysian
Trades Union Congress, with a half-million members, announced it
would publicly endorse the coalition Tuesday.
	   ``We feel that the crackdown on public forums is a big step back
in our bid for more freedom and democracy in the country,'' said
MTUC spokesman Premesh Chandran.
	   The call for an opposition coalition comes on the heels of a
potentially divisive crisis within the DAP, the leading opposition
party in Malaysia. Three senior officials were sacked last week for
``causing disunity'' among the party leadership by criticizing Lim
at several party meetings.
	   The infighting could erode what little political opposition
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad faces before general elections in
2000.
	   Lim worries that Mahathir could call for early elections so that
the governing party wins a new mandate before the economic crisis
further eats away its popularity.
</TEXT>
