w2468 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-SpaceStation     06-08 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Space Station </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Money shortage continues to stall Russian component of new space
</HEADLINE>
station &QL; 
 &UR; By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's cash-strapped government is dragging its
feet on funding a key component of the new international space
station, which could mean more delays in finishing the project,
officials said Monday.
	   ``The financial issue hasn't been resolved yet,'' said Anatoly
Kiselyov, director of the Khrunichev Company, which is building the
station's service module _ the crucial segment which will be the
crew's living quarters.
	   Kiselyov said the government has not paid 1.3 billion rubles
(dlrs 211 million) to make the module ready for launching.
	   Last month, representatives of all 16 countries involved in the
new station decided to push the launch of the first part of the
station back from June to November because of Russia's money
problems.
	   The first part, a cargo module built by Khrunichev under
contract with Boeing, has been completed and taken to the Baikonur
cosmodrome in the former Soviet republic of Kazakstan in
preparation for launching in November.
	   NASA is to follow Dec. 3 with the second part, a connecting
passageway.
	   The service module, financed by the Russian government, was
scheduled to follow in December, but its launch has been postponed
until next April.
	   The station's segments will be assembled in orbit and, if
everything goes as planned, the first American-led crew is expected
to board the station in July 1999, more than a year later than
originally planned.
	   The dlrs 21 billion space station is a joint project of Russia,
the United States, the European Space Agency, Canada and Japan.
	   When asked whether the fund shortage might cause new delays,
Kiselyov was cautious, saying the crew module has been virtually
completed but it must still undergo tests.
	   ``It will become clear in about three months after the tests are
completed,'' he said at a news conference.
	   Kiselyov reiterated that Russia will discard its Mir space
station in the fall of 1999 after the new international space
station is in orbit. He said that NASA had been able to gain
``invaluable'' experience by putting seven astronauts on Mir.
	   The U.S. space shuttle Discovery is scheduled to undock later on
Monday from the Russian space station, bringing home the last
American to live on Mir, Andrew Thomas.
	   (vi/ren)
</TEXT>
