w2481 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-Markets 4thLd-Writethru   06-08 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar tops 140 yen in Tokyo for first time in 7 years, stocks down
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS; UPDATES with closing bond, late afternoon currency
prices; ADDS trader comment in 7th, 11th graf; ADDS byline &QL; 
 &UR; By MARTIN FACKLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar topped 140 yen for the first time
in seven years in Tokyo trading on Monday as investors soured
further on Japan's torpid economy. Tokyo stocks slipped in
lackluster trading.
	   The dollar bought 140.56 yen at late afternoon, up 1.14 yen from
late Friday in Tokyo and its highest point since June 20, 1991. In
New York, the dollar settled at 139.75 yen on Friday.
	   The U.S. currency soared past the benchmark 140-yen level as
investors sold their yen for dollars to invest in a U.S. economy
that shows no signs of slowing down. On Friday, the Labor
Department said the U.S. jobless rate held at a 28-year-low of 4.3
percent in May.
	   The yen, meanwhile, looks less and less attractive to investors
as Japan's economy teeters on the brink of outright recession.
Investment returns are miserable with stock and property prices
mired in an eight-year slump.
	   Japanese officials including Finance Minister Hikaru Matsunaga
warned yet again about the dollar's ``excessive'' strength and
threatened ``decisive measures'' to reverse its rise. But traders
said that until the government shows itself willing to back the
comments up with intervention in currency markets, the yen will
keep on falling.
	   ``All those remarks are basically a repetition of what they've
been saying. Words alone can't stem the current trend,'' said
Ryuichi Takami, a senior trader at Sanwa Bank Ltd.
	   Also supporting the U.S. currency was the diminishing likelihood
finance officials from the Group of Seven top industrialized
nations will make a strong statement against the dollar when they
meet in Paris on Tuesday, traders said.
	   The dollar traded as high as 140.73 yen and as low as 139.89 yen
during the day.
	   Tokyo stocks followed the yen lower as investors dumped Japanese
stocks to shift funds into better-performing U.S. and European
assets.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
slipped 28.72 points, or 0.19 percent, to close at 15,294.71. On
Friday, the average lost 103.04 points, or 0.67 percent.
	   Investors ``are focusing on the currency, and the potential
reactions to the currency,'' said Geoffrey Bennett, a senior
salesman at the Tokyo office if ING Barings Securities.
	   A weaker yen also spooks foreign investors by driving down the
dollar value of Japanese stocks and bonds.
	   Trading was sparse, with an estimated 251 million shares trading
on the first section, down from 291 million of Friday. Declining
issues outnumbered gainers 3-to-2.
	   The Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section fell 3.58 points, or 0.30 percent, to 1,198.36. The TOPIX
closed down 5.56 points, or 0.46 percent.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond fell to 1.145 percent from Friday's 1.165 percent,
driving its price up to 112.46 yen from 112.31 yen on Friday.
 &UR; (mef-dj)
</TEXT>
