<HEADLINE>
Arrest warrant issued for ex-telecommunications minister
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: UPDATES with arrest warrant issued

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ In a corruption probe of past
government officials, prosecutors obtained a court-issued arrest
warrant Monday for an ex-telecommunications minister charged with
bribery.
	   Lee Suk-chae, who served as information and telecommunications
minister under the previous government of President Kim Young-sam,
was accused of receiving dlrs 20,000 in bribes from local companies
trying to win government licences for lucrative cellular phone
projects.
	   If convicted, Lee could face a prison term of up to five years.
	   Lee has ignored prosecutors' repeated calls to return home from
Hawaii to face investigationsend prosecutors' . Prosecutors said
they will subpoena Lee through the U.S. Justice Department.
	   The United States and South Korea have no extradition treaty.
	   Prosecutors declined to comment, but local media reported that
officials of LG Telecom and Hansol PCS also will be indicted on
charges of giving bribes to Lee and other government officials.
</TEXT>
