w2485 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Bosnia-WarCrimes     06-08 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-War Crimes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Alleged Bosnian Croat paramilitary chief goes on U.N. trial
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo planned &QL; 
 &UR; By MIKE CORDER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ An alleged Bosnian Croat
paramilitary leader charged with allowing a subordinate to rape a
prisoner went on trial Monday before the Yugoslav war crimes
tribunal.
	   Anto Furundzija, 28, was arrested in December by Dutch troops in
the central Bosnian town of Vitez. He has pleaded innocent to two
war crimes charges alleging that he stood by and watched as a
prisoner under interrogation was raped by one of his troops in May
1993.
	   Rape has been considered a war crime in other cases before the
U.N. court, but Furundzija's trial is the first to deal
specifically with sexual assault inflicted during the course of an
interrogation.
	   Although Furundzija is a relatively minor figure from the 3
1/2-year Bosnian conflict, tribunal prosecutors are keen to
establish case law involving sexual assault as a war crime.
	   He faces a maximum sentence of life imprisonment if convicted.
	   The alleged rapist, whose identity has not been released, has
not been arrested.
	   Furundzija allegedly commanded a paramilitary group called The
Jokers, which took part in a campaign by Bosnian Croat forces loyal
to Croatian President Franjo Tudjman to drive Muslims out of the
central Bosnian Lasva River Valley in 1993.
	   After opening the case, presiding judge Florence Mumba of Zambia
immediately called a closed session to discuss a prosecution
motion.
	   Before the trial began, the court publicized a stinging rebuke
by judges of prosecutors in the case, accusing them of ``a
consistent pattern of noncompliance with the orders of the trial
chamber.''
	   Listing six occasions that the prosecution had failed to comply
with court orders, the three-judge panel charged the prosecution of
``conduct close to negligence.''
	   The judges sent their written complaints to Chief Prosecutor
Louise Arbour ``to be dealt with as she sees fit.''
	   Furundzija's trial, the tribunal's sixth, could be one of its
shortest to date. Prosecutor Patricia Viseur-Sellers said she only
planned to call five or six witnesses. Other cases have dragged on
for months and heard evidence from dozens of witnesses.
	   Set up in 1993 to prosecute atrocities committed during
conflicts in the former Yugoslavia, the war crimes tribunal has
indicted 60 suspects and has 27 in custody.
	   Its most wanted suspects, former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan
Karadzic and his wartime military chief, Gen. Ratko Mladic, remain
free.
	   (mc/bk)
</TEXT>
