<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Tojo Film </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Controversial war criminal film tops box office in Japan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHESTER DAWSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A movie that depicts Japan's top war criminal as a
hero was the leading domestic film at Japanese box offices in the
first six months of the year, the movie's producer said Monday.
	   The film ``Pride'' is about World War II leader Gen. Hideki
Tojo. It was released last month and immediately provoked an outcry
from neighboring countries which were occupied by Japanese troops,
such as China.
	   ``All of the debate about it has helped boost its popularity at
the box office,'' said Toei Co. spokeswoman Chika Inamoto.
	   As Japan's prime minister from 1941 to 1944, Tojo authorized the
surprise attack on Pearl Harbor. He was found guilty of war crimes
after Japan's 1945 surrender and was hanged.
	   Toei declined to provide sales figures, but said ``Pride'' was
the top-grossing Japanese-made movie in the January-June period and
is on track to become the year's biggest domestic hit.
	   The film has made roughly 200 million yen (dlrs 1.43 million) in
Japan's five biggest cities, according to industry estimates. That
is well behind the 8.5 billion yen (dlrs 61 million) earned in the
same cities by Hollywood blockbuster ``Titanic'' since its release
late last year.
	   ``Pride'' cost 1.5 billion (dlrs 11 million) to make, three
times Toei's usual budget.
	   The film portrays Tojo as a peaceful man who went to war in
self-defense and to liberate Asia from Western colonialism _ a
popular view among Japanese who defend the country's wartime role.
	   The audience for the film consists largely of middle-aged males,
but also includes many 20-year-olds, the Toei spokeswoman said.
	   Toei hopes to release ``Pride'' overseas, but does not have a
set schedule yet for overseas distribution, she said.
 &UR; (cd)
</TEXT>
