<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asia Business Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore and South Korea. Some of these stories also moved earlier
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Australia, China, Japan, the Philippines,
today as separates. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Labor officials called an emergency
meeting Monday to try to resolve a strike by more than 600 pilots
at Philippine Airlines which has plunged the financially troubled
flag-carrier into crisis.
	   PAL fired all the striking pilots on Sunday, calling their
action illegal, except for a few who had complied with an airline
order to return to work to avoid dismissal.
	   Labor Secretary Cresenciano Trajano said the Philippine
government is intervening in the dispute because it affects the
national interest. Representatives of PAL's management and the
620-strong Airline Pilots Association of the Philippines were
summoned to the meeting.
	   Trajano said he ordered the strikers to return to work and the
airline to accept them back. He also urged both sides to refrain
from further hostile actions.
	   The union is protesting a new management policy of firing pilots
who have reached 20 years of service or flown 20,000 hours,
regardless of age. The policy puts about 200 pilots in danger of
forced retirement, the union said.
	   ___
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's trade surplus with the world jumped more
than tenfold in the first 20 days of May as a failing domestic
economy slashed demand for foreign products, the Finance Ministry
said Monday.
	   Japan's merchandise trade surplus _ the amount of goods the
country exports minus its imports _ soared to 360.9 billion yen
(dlrs 2.6 billion) from 34.9 billion yen (dlrs 250 million) during
the same period last year, the ministry said.
	   Imports dropped by 14.3 percent to 1.9 trillion yen (dlrs 13.6
billion) amid dwindling demand for raw materials like oil and wood.
The ministry said such sharp declines are unlikely to continue.
	   Exports remained a robust 2.3 trillion yen (dlrs 16 billion), up
0.3 percent, as strong overseas sales of cars and photographic film
offset a drop in demand for computer chips and electronics.
	   Measured on a monthly basis, Japan's surplus has risen for the
last 13 months, as a weakening yen made the country's exports
cheaper in key markets like the United States and a moribund
domestic economy eroded imports.
	   In the most recent monthly figure, Japan posted a 1.2 trillion
yen surplus in April.
	   ___
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ The chairman of one of Singapore's biggest
banks warned of a recession next year if the government does not
take action now to stimulate the economy, a newspaper reported
Monday.
	   Wee Cho Yaw, chairman of United Overseas Bank, told The Straits
Times that the current economic situation in the small island
republic was the worst he had seen in his 40-year banking career.
	   The Singapore government has stood staunchly by earlier
predictions that the economy would grow at least 2.5 percent this
year.
	   But the forecast was made before the economic turmoil in
neighboring Indonesia worsened and other regional economies began
to exhibit signs of a slowdown into zero growth or outright
recession.
	   At least two private investment houses have already predicted
that the Singapore economy will fall into recession this year,
though a recent newspaper survey of 15 analysts and economists
showed an average forecast of 1.5 percent growth.
	   ___
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Bankrupt Hanbo Steel Industry Co.,
South Korea's second largest steel maker, will be sold to foreign
investors later this year, its creditor banks said Monday.
	   The decision came after potential domestic investors, including
state-run Pohang Iron and Steel Corp., the nation's No. 1 steel
maker, gave up plans to take over the failed steel producer.
	   Hanbo, which once produced 3 million tons of steel a year,
borrowed heavily from banks to finance its aggressive expansion
programs. But sales lagged early last year amid an overall economic
slowdown, producing a cash crunch.
	   In mid-1997, Pohang offered 2 trillion won (dlrs 1.4 billion)
for key facilities of Hanbo, excluding its debts. Creditor banks
rejected the offer, saying the price was too low.
	   On Monday, creditors said they will soon select a lead manager
for the planned sell-off of Hanbo and complete takeover
negotiations before the end of this year.
	   So far, about nine foreign steel companies, including USX Corp.
of the United States, have shown interest in Hanbo, they said.
	   ___
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Mortgage loans by China's commercial banks rose
only by a sliver in the first quarter of 1998, despite the
government's announcement of a program encouraging private
apartment purchases, the China Securities News reported Monday.
	   Housing loans by the four state-owned commercial banks rose 0.3
percent or 834 million yuan (dlrs 100.97 million) to 264.3 billion
(dlrs 32 billion) in the first three months over the same period
last year, the report said.
	   Of the total, loans to individuals amounted to 33.7 billion
(dlrs 4.08 billion), it said.
	   China's four state-owned commercial banks _ the Industrial &AMP;
Commercial Bank of China, the Agricultural Bank of China, the Bank
of China and the China Construction Bank _ are intended to be at
the vanguard of reforms intended to build a commercially sound
banking system.
	   To boost flagging economic activity and fend off the economic
doldrums that have stricken much of Asia, the government has
declared the housing industry a key area of growth.
	   Earlier this year, the People's Bank of China, the central bank,
said banks can allocate up to 15 percent of their loan portfolios
to mortgages. The central bank has also raised ceilings for housing
debt so banks could accommodate more mortgage lending.
	   ___
	   ADELAIDE, Australia (AP) _ South Australian wines are well
placed to increase their share of the lucrative Japanese market,
state Premier John Olsen said Monday.
	   Speaking from Japan after visiting the South Australian Wine
Week exhibition in Okayama, Olsen said while local wines were
competing with those from France and Germany, South Australia had
lifted its exports of premium varieties.
	   ``Japan is Australia's largest export market in Asia with South
Australian wine accounting for more than two-thirds of national
exports,'' the premier said.
	   ``While the market in Japan is small, sales have grown
dramatically and we intend to capitalize on that.
	   ``More Japanese people are drinking dry red wine, with a volume
increase of 218 percent over the last year.''
	   Olsen was in Japan for a three-day business mission promoting
aquaculture, wine, tourism and education.
</TEXT>
