<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians, 1st Ld-Writethru,0614 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Angry clashes as Jewish settlers move into Arab neighborhood
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with fresh quotes, attorney general to look into
ownership, other details &QL; 
 &UR; By SAMAR ASSAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Jewish settlers moved into three buildings in
Arab east Jerusalem before dawn Monday, stringing barbed wire,
hanging Israeli flags and setting off angry stone-throwing clashes
with Palestinian neighbors.
	   It was the latest in a series of escalating confrontations in
Jerusalem's eastern sector as both sides accuse the other of trying
to grab land in the bitterly contested city.
	   At least two people were injured in Monday's clashes in the
Silwan neighborhood, including the top Palestinian official in
Jerusalem, Faisal Husseini. He was hit in the head with a stone and
slightly hurt before police and soldiers broke up the melee.
	   ``I see things getting worse,'' said Husseini, who has called
for massive Palestinian protests to block Jewish settlement
activity. ``This provocation is pushing the situation to the edge
of disaster.''
	   Adding to the volatile mix, about 20 activists from the Peace
Now group turned out at the site to protest the settlers' arrival.
Police roughly dragged them away after they refused to disperse.
	   The 15 settlers were from the Elad group, which claims it
purchased the homes legally. Settler leader Yehuda Mali said Jews
had a biblical claim to the area, overlooking the Kidron Valley
just outside the Old City walls.
	   ``It was the home of King David, here he wrote the Psalms, and
here Jews are not allowed to live?'' he said.
	   Police and soldiers tried to keep the two sides apart, but
repeated shoving and shouting matches broke out. In one skirmish,
settlers kicked Arabs who tried to block them from entering one of
the buildings.
	   ``I will surrender my life before I surrender my house!''
shouted Fatima Karaeen, 62, who said she has papers showing one of
the houses belongs to her Arab family. ``The cowards!''
	   Her lawyer said he was meeting with Israel's attorney general
later Monday to present the family's ownership claim.
	   The makeup of Jerusalem's neighborhoods is an explosive issue,
with Palestinians trying to block what they say are illegal
encroachments by Jewish settlers. Both sides are constantly
jockeying for position pending negotiations on the city's final
status.
	   The Palestinians claim east Jerusalem, which Israel captured in
the 1967 Mideast War, as capital of a future state. Israel insists
the city must remain undivided under Israeli sovereignty.
	   Settlers have been stepping up activity in recent weeks. Last
month, clashes broke out after the settler group Ataret Cohanim set
up sheds near the Old City's Herod's Gate.
	   Those sheds were dismantled, but the settlers were allowed to
stay on as guards and volunteers in an archeological dig that got
under way on Monday.
	   The latest confrontation comes at a delicate moment in efforts
to restart the stalled peace process. Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, who has been under American pressure to accept
a U.S.-authored troop withdrawal plan, said Sunday no accord was
imminent.
	   ``I don't work according to a stopwatch,'' Netanyahu told
reporters after meeting with his Cabinet.
	   Israel's army radio, citing sources close to the prime minister,
said the American plan will likely be brought to the Cabinet for a
vote before the end of the week.
	   The radio reported that Israeli Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh,
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat and U.S. Ambassador Edward
Walker met Sunday to discuss the proposal.
</TEXT>
