w2520 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EU-Kosovo     06-08 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU Foreign Ministers debate investment ban, assets freeze
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Yugoslavia-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT WIELAARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LUXEMBOURG (AP) _ The EU may ban investments in Serbia and
freeze the country's assets abroad on Monday, tightening sanctions
that have so far failed to get Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to reach a negotiated settlement in Kosovo.
	   The foreign ministers of the 15 European Union nations discussed
these measures to punish Milosevic for cracking down on his
independence-minded southern province and prevent another Bosnia.
	   They have already banned arms exports and restricted travel
visas for Yugoslav officials.
	   However _ at Washington's urging _ they have held off on
freezing Yugoslav assets abroad and the investment ban to give
Milosevic a chance to reach a peaceful settlement in Kosovo.
	   That has not worked and the escalating violence in Kosovo of
late has drawn parallels with West European waffling in 1991 and
1992 as Bosnia sank into civil war.
	   EU Foreign Affairs Commissioner Hans van den Broek said it was
more critical at this stage that the NATO ``defense ministers
accelerate their work.''
	   On Thursday and Friday, those defense ministers meet in Brussels
to consider a military response to Milosevic though in recent weeks
that option has sparked little enthusiasm.
	   And in London, on Friday, the foreign ministers of the G-8
nations _ United States, Britain, Germany, France, Japan, Italy and
Russia _ meet to discuss Kosovo.
	   Russia's involvement in any debate about sanctions or an allied
intervention of whatever kind is seen as crucial.
	   ``It gives us an opportunity to have dialogue with Russia and
for the Russian foreign minister to clearly understand the strength
of feeling in the rest of the international community,'' British
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said before coming here.
	   He said the EU expects Russia to ``be putting pressure on
Belgrade to understand both the strength of feeling condemning what
they have done and the growing consensus for action preventing it
from happening again.''
	   Cook, chairman of the EU meeting, said an investment ban would
``make clear how much we condemn the use of full army weaponry
against the civilian population'' in Kosovo.
	   In Kosovo, ethnic Albanians comprise 90 percent of the 2.2
million-strong population. Most demand to secede from Serbia, which
along with Montenegro makes up Yugoslavia. Western powers oppose
any change of borders, but want the Serbs to cease their offensive
and return to Kosovo the autonomy the region enjoyed within Serbia
until 1989.
	   NATO military planners have been drafting contingency plans,
including the holding of joint maneuvers in Albania and Macedonia
and help for these countries to seal their borders. The plans
include _ as a last resort _ the dispatch of as many as 20,000
allied troops to the region.
 &UR; (rw)
</TEXT>
