<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Clash </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Villagers in Caucasus hold bus to avenge alleged abduction
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Angry villagers in Russia's southern republic of
North Ossetia on Monday detained dozens of passengers from a bus
after the alleged kidnapping of several neighbors, officials said.
	   People from the village of Zamankul in North Ossetia detained
two buses with some 40 residents of the neighboring republic of
Ingushetia, but later let one vehicle go, Ossetian officials said.
	   Ossetian officials said the villagers' action came after the
abduction of seven Zamankul residents on Sunday was blamed on
Ingushs. The seven villagers were still missing Monday, officials
said.
	   Lev Zugayev, a spokesman for North Ossetian leader Alexander
Dzasokhov, said officials were holding talks with villagers to
persuade them to release the bus passengers.
	   North Ossetia, a republic of about 500,000 people in the North
Caucasus, is near the breakaway republic of Chechnya.
	   Predominantly Orthodox Christian, it has maintained warmer
relations with Moscow than other places in the region and served as
a base for the Kremlin's 1994-96 campaign against Chechen
separatists.
	   North Ossetia and neighboring Muslim Ingushetia fought a short
but bloody war in 1992. Hundreds of people were killed and most
ethnic Ingush were expelled from North Ossetia.
	   Both sides have blamed each other for numerous kidnapping
incidents.
	   (vi/ren)
</TEXT>
