w2543 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Impeachment     06-08 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Impeachment </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian Communists to request impeachment discussions in
</HEADLINE>
parliament &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Parliament's Communist faction will file a formal
petition on Tuesday to put an impeachment motion against President
Boris Yeltsin on the legislature's agenda, a leading Communist said
Monday.
	   The Communist Party's No. 2 man, Valentin Kuptsov, said his
faction will ask members of the agenda-setting Duma Council on
Tuesday to schedule discussions of an impeachment motion before
June 19, when parliament goes on a week-long break, the Interfax
news agency reported.
	   If the motion is put on the agenda, the next step would be to
set up a committee to study the proposal. The Russian Constitution
puts no time limit on how long the commission may take to review
the proposal, and it's likely to be months before the motion goes
for a second discussion in parliament.
	   Only 150 signatures are required to put an impeachment motion on
the Duma agenda, but 300 votes are needed to actually initiate the
proceedings.
	   Impeachment proceedings are long and complex, and even if the
motion is approved by the Duma, it would still need to clear
several legal hurdles to become effective.
	   Supporters of the motion _ the Communist, Agrarian and People's
Power factions _ have said they have collected 212 signatures, but
have postponed requesting that the motion be put on the agenda,
claiming they were still collecting signatures.
	   Together, the three factions have 210 members in the 450-seat
State Duma, the lower house of parliament.
	   Several previous impeachment drives have fizzled, in part
because Russia's Constitution gives the president the upper hand in
confrontations with parliament.
	   Communists and their allies launched the latest impeachment
campaign last month. They have accused Yeltsin of a range of
transgressions, including instigating the Soviet collapse,
launching the botched war in Chechnya and ruining the country's
economy.
	   Their frustrations intensified in April during a long test of
wills with Yeltsin, who threatened to disband the legislature
unless lawmakers approved his candidate for prime minister.
	   (ad/ren)
</TEXT>
