<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Dollar Slumps, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Aussie dollar slides toward record low
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: UPDATES with closing price of Aussie dollar on local market &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ The Australian dollar plunged further
toward 12-year record lows Monday despite attempts by the Reserve
Bank of Australia to halt its slide.
	   ``The Australian dollar will remain under pressure until
something fundamental changes in Asia,'' Commonwealth Bank senior
manager foreign exchange Kurt Magnus said.
	   At the end of local trade Monday, the currency was 59.68 U.S.
cents, a level not seen since 1986.
	   New Zealand's dollar is also on its knees, down to 50.88 U.S.
cents.
	   Since ratings agency Moody's said Friday it was reviewing New
Zealand's AA1 sovereign credit rating for a possible downgrade, the
Kiwi dollar has fallen more than one U.S. cent to a six-year low.
	   Dealers said the central bank intervened in the market as
recently as Monday morning to attempt to prop up the ailing
currency by buying Aussie dollars.
	   ``We've got it on good authority that the RBA's been in to
smooth and test the currency and take some heat out of the
market,'' Macquarie Bank foreign exchange associate director Brent
Aggar said.
	   The RBA has already spent about U.S. dlrs 1.8 billion (3 billion
Australian dollars) in a largely futile attempt to prop up the
currency.
	   The Australian dollar's record low of 57.10 U.S. cents was
struck in July 1986 after then-Treasurer Paul Keating's infamous
comments that the Australian economy was nearly that of a ``banana
republic.''
</TEXT>
