<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore stock market and currency down on yen's fall, bad news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in grafs 1-2 with market close; MOVES UP reference to
deputy PM speech; ADDS other recession predictions in last graf &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Singapore's stocks and currency plunged further
Monday on news of the republic's first major property development
default and the persistent weakness of the Japanese yen and other
regional currencies.
	   The benchmark Straits Times Industrial Index closed 3.4 percent
down, about 40 points off its 1168.46 opening. It dropped to a low
of 1127.33 and recovered only slightly, setting the stage for a
third straight week of dropping indexes.
	   Dealers said they were awaiting comments by Deputy Prime
Minister Lee Hsien Loong, also the chairman of Singapore's de facto
central bank, who planned a speech to bankers after the markets
closed.
	   The Singapore dollar was also sharply lower, breaking the
psychologically important 1.70 level against the U.S. currency. The
U.S. dollar broke above the benchmark 140 yen level as the market
opened in Tokyo, and the Singapore dollar followed suit.
	   News that a Singapore-Hong Kong joint venture missed a deadline
for a 68.6 million Singapore dollar (dlrs 40 million) payment on a
plot of land to develop condominiums also dampened sentiment.
	   The company, a joint venture between Singapore's Eltech
Electronics and Hong Kong's Lai Sun Development, missed the last
deadline Friday to pay the remaining 75 percent of the bid it made
last July.
	   Mounting fears that Singapore could head into a recession this
year are also depressing the stock market, according to dealers.
	   The chairman of United Overseas Bank, Wee Cho Yaw, warned in a
newspaper interview published Monday that the Singapore economy may
slip into a recession next year if the government does not take
immediate steps.
	   Several foreign investment houses have made the recession
forecast, but the government has said it would not change its
prediction of at least 2.5 percent growth until May's results are
available.
</TEXT>
