<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Summary,0542 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
An overnight summary of Caribbean news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; JAMAICA: Group of 43 Haitians lands near hotel &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ A group of 43 Haitians trying to reach
Miami landed instead on a beach in one of Jamaica's northern resort
areas, police reported Sunday.
	   The group of 36 men, 6 women and a 7-month-old baby had been at
sea for nine days on a 30-foot sailboat and had gone six days
without food, authorities said. Staff at the Golden Seas Beach
Hotel in Oracabessa, a town on the north coast, found the Haitians
after they landed Saturday morning.
	   Hotel officials said the migrants were hungry but in good
health. The Haitians told police they had left from Port-au-Prince,
the Haitian capital, on May 29 but had run out of food three days
later.
	   Bad weather blew them off course, they said.
 &UR; DOMINICAN REPUBLIC: President to present drug-control plan to
United Nations
	   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) _ Dominican President
Leonel Fernandez left Sunday for a United Nations meeting in which
he will present a regional drug-control proposal for the western
Caribbean.
	   He will present the plan Monday at a meeting of the
organization's General Assembly in New York City.
	   Drug experts say cocaine smuggling through the Dominican
Republic and adjacent Haiti has increased recently, and U.S.
officials have estimated that 25 percent of the cocaine reaching
the United States comes by way of Puerto Rico and the Dominican
Republic.
	   A United Nations report released Friday claimed money laundering
in the country has tripled in the last three years, with most of
the money finding its way into real estate, car sales and shipping
deals.
 &UR; JAMAICA: Prison escapee killed in shootout
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ A man who escaped from prison in March
and held a place on Jamaica's list of most wanted criminals was
killed during a shootout with police, authorities reported Sunday.
	   Sheldon Macintosh, 19, was found injured next to a 9mm
semi-automatic pistol after the shootout Friday, police said. He
was carrying another .38-caliber pistol.
	   Macintosh died on the way to a Kingston hospital, they reported.
	   Police said they were patrolling crime-plagued West Kingston
when they were fired upon by unidentified gunmen. They fired back,
injuring Macintosh.
	   Macintosh was one of 23 inmates who escaped from the Remand
Center jail in March. He was awaiting trial on two counts of
murder.
 &UR; PUERTO RICO: Island to get third telephone system
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Joining a rush of U.S. telephone
companies to Puerto Rico, New Jersey-based KMC Telecom Inc. says it
will begin construction within two months on the island's third
local telephone network.
	   KMC Vice Chairman Gary Lasher was quoted by weekly newspaper
Caribbean Business as saying the first lines would probably be laid
in the San Juan metropolitan area, where 40 percent of the U.S.
territory's population lives.
	   Eventually the network will cover the entire island and offer
intra-island long distance, off-island long distance service and
Internet service, Lasher said.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Caribbean-Summary; CT:i; 
(REG:CRB;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
</BODY>
