<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU Foreign Ministers debate investment ban, assets freeze
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS Canada to G8 nations in 10th graf; UPDATES with comments &QL; 
 &UR; With Yugoslavia-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT WIELAARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LUXEMBOURG (AP) _ The EU may ban investments in Serbia and
freeze the country's assets abroad on Monday, tightening sanctions
that have so far failed to get Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to reach a negotiated settlement in Kosovo.
	   The foreign ministers of the 15 European Union nations discussed
these measures to punish Milosevic for cracking down on his
independence-minded southern province and prevent another Bosnia.
	   The EU has already banned arms exports and restricted travel
visas for Yugoslav officials. But at Washington's urging, they have
held off on freezing Yugoslav assets abroad and the investment ban
to give Milosevic a chance to reach a peaceful settlement in
Kosovo.
	   Sources said while the investment ban well may be imposed,
France, Italy and Greece were not keen on freezing Yugoslav assets
abroad. They said these countries hold considerable assets _ bank
accounts and properties.
	   Other possible sanctions would include a ban on all flights by
JAT, the Yugoslav airline.
	   Officials said the EU ministers would unlikely make an immediate
difference. ``The fight clearly lies within the United Nations
Security Council,'' said a Dutch official.
	   Escalating violence in Kosovo in recent weeks has drawn
parallels with West European waffling in 1991 and 1992 as Bosnia
slipped into civil war.
	   EU Foreign Affairs Commissioner Hans van den Broek said here it
was more critical at this stage that the NATO ``defense ministers
accelerate their work'' to forge a military response to Milosevic.
	   On Thursday and Friday, those defense ministers meet in Brussels
to consider such a response though in recent weeks that option has
sparked little enthusiasm.
	   And on Friday the foreign ministers of the G-8 nations _ Canada,
United States, Britain, Germany, France, Japan, Italy and Russia _
will discuss Kosovo in London.
	   Those talks involve Russia whose support for any action against
Milosevic is seen as crucial.
	   On arrival, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, the chairman
of the EU meeting, warned Milosevic to ``back off'' or face the
prospect of western military intervention in Kosovo where Ethnic
Albanians comprise 90 percent of the 2.2 million-strong population.
Most demand to secede from Serbia, which along with Montenegro
makes up Yugoslavia.
	   Western powers oppose any change of borders, but want the Serbs
to cease their offensive and return to Kosovo the autonomy the
region enjoyed within Serbia until 1989.
	   At the NATO headquarters in Brussels, military planners have
been drafted contingency plans. These include accelerating joint
NATO maneuvers in Albania and Macedonia, NATO help for these
countries to seal their borders and _ as a last resort _ the
dispatch of as many as 20,000 allied troops to the region. Already
a 40-strong NATO mission has arrived in Albania.
 &UR; (rw)
</TEXT>
