<SLUG> BC-Bangladesh-Long March,0291 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Arms banned from protest march
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; BY HASAN SAEED &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DHAKA , Bangladesh (AP) _ Police warned protesters Monday not to
go armed on a two-day march by opposition parties to southeastern
Bangladesh that begins Tuesday.
	   Political demonstrations often erupt into violence in
Bangladesh, and the ``Long March'' announced by seven opposition
parties focuses on a particularly volatile issue.
	   The opposition, led by former Prime Minister Khaleda Zia, is
protesting an accord letting 2,000 Buddhist rebels end their
two-decade-old bush war in the southeastern Chittagong Hill Tracts
in exchange for greater political control over the region, rich in
timber and natural gas resources. Zia says Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina gave up too much to secure peace.
	   Some march leaders have directed their party workers to carry
licensed arms in case of attack by pro-Hasina activists. But the
police, in a statement Monday, noted the country's gun laws
prohibit the carrying of even licensed arms at political rallies.
	   The statement said carrying licensed arms ``may encourage
possessor of unauthorized arms to create chaos and disorder.''
	   The protesters plan to march 400 kilometers (250 miles) from
Dhaka to Khagrachari in the Chittagong hills. Opposition leader
Anwar Zahid said more than 2,000 vehicles carrying people from
different parts of the country would converge in Dhaka Tuesday to
start the march.
	   A senior official in the Home Ministry, which overseas law and
order, said Monday that more than 5,000 soldiers and paramilitary
troops will be deployed along the march route and in Dhaka over the
next few days. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
