r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Turkey-Balkans     06-08 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Balkans </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Impasse over Kosovo deepens at Balkan foreign ministers meeting
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SUZAN FRASER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) _ Balkan foreign ministers on Monday
sought ways to pressure Yugoslavia into discussing the deepening
crisis in Kosovo and break an impasse threatening to derail the
regional meeting.
	   ``Unfortunately, this issue continues to maintain its utmost
priority for the stability and security of our region,'' said
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem.
	   His remarks came at a two-day meeting of foreign ministers from
Albania, Bulgaria, Greece, Macedonia, Romania and Yugoslavia.
Bosnia and Slovenia have sent deputy ministers.
	   The meeting is part of a broad regional initiative to improve
economic cooperation. It will set the groundwork for an annual
summit of Balkan heads of states next October.
	   But the meeting has deadlocked over Yugoslavia's refusal to
allow any reference to the secessionist Albanian-dominated province
of Kosovo, which Yugoslavia insists is an internal matter.
	   All the foreign ministers seem adamant about including a
reference to Kosovo, but they are seeking a compromise.
	   Among them might be a call for the return of more than 10,000
refugees in Albania, but one tempered by a reassurance that Balkan
leaders are against changing Yugoslavia's borders.
	   Another could be giving Belgrade a diplomatic boost by referring
to a solution for Kosovo within the framework of the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia, instead of just Serbia.
	   Diplomats close to the talks say that so much pressure is being
applied to Yugoslav Foreign Affairs Minister Zivadin Jovanovic that
he may have no recourse but to walk out of the meeting.
	   Kosovo's ethnic Albanians, most of them Muslim, comprise 90
percent of its 2.2 million inhabitants, and most want to secede
from predominantly Orthodox Christian Serbia and Yugoslavia.
Milosevic revoked Kosovo's autonomy in 1989 in a bid to suppress
the independence movement.
	   Yugoslavia's stance has even irked Greece, an Orthodox nation
once considered one of its staunchest Western allies.
	   The change was clear at a Monday meeting between Greek Foreign
Minister Theordoros Pangalos and Ecumenical Patriarch Bartholomew
I, the spiritual leader of the world's 350 million Orthodox
Christians.
	   ``Let's hope the Holy Spirit will help,'' Bartholomew said.
	   ``Sometimes the Holy Spirit fails,'' Pangalos replied.
	   ``The Holy Spirit never fails,'' Bartholomew answered. ``It is
human weakness that fails.''
	   (sf-pq-cph)
</TEXT>
