<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bankers-Economy,0398 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bank says world economic prospects looking up, but advises caution
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BASEL, Switzerland (AP) _ Despite the economic turmoil in Asia,
prospects for growth in the rest of the world are looking positive,
according to a central bankers report released Monday.
	   Long-running economic expansion in the United States and Britain
is set to continue, says the annual report of the Basel-based Bank
for International Settlements, known as the central banker's
central bank.
	   Serious spread of the Asian crisis to other parts of the world
has so far been avoided and the worst may be over in Asia itself,
according to the 199-page study.
	   ``Congratulations on this generally happy state of affairs might
seem in order, yet central bankers should not be complacent,''
Alfons Verplaetse, chairman of BIS' board of directors, told the
bank's annual meeting.
	   Rekindling growth in another of the world's major economies,
Japan, ``will not be easy'' and the full impact on Europe of the
Asian crisis has still to be assessed, the report says.
	   In addition, tightening labor markets, larger trade deficits and
booming prices for financial assets show inflationary risks are
rising.
	   ``No one should be under any illusions as to the magnitude of
the problems still to be faced and the potential difficulties along
the way,'' the report says.
	   A ``new era'' of productivity and profit growth is discernible
in recent U.S. economic statistics, notes the study. A wave of
restructuring in Europe will lead to the same result.
	   Growth rates in most industrial countries have either remained
at high levels or are starting to build significant momentum, said
Verplaetse.
	   Preparations for the transition in Europe to the new single
currency, the euro, have been smooth, he said. Structural reforms
and more disciplined policies have generated solid growth in Latin
America, many Eastern European countries and ``significant'' parts
of Africa.
	   Japan's banking system needs to be restructured and the economy
stimulated through permanent tax cuts.
	   Economic growth, financial deregulation and low inflation should
be accompanied by vigorous but careful market opening, the study
recommends.
	   Financial systems everywhere should be strengthened to let them
face up to the ``larger shocks'' likely to be created in freer
markets.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Bankers-Economy; CT:f; 
(REG:ASIA;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:MEST;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
