<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo Scene </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Burnt-out houses, village ruins stand silent testimony of clashes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ALEKSANDAR VASOVIC &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DECANI-PEC ROAD IN KOSOVO, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Ghastly scenes
reminiscent of earlier wars in Bosnia and Croatia confronted the
first foreign diplomats allowed into the area of secessionist
Kosovo province that saw fierce fighting in the past week.
	   ``What we've seen is all sorrow, all grief... all those villages
burned and destroyed, all the people had left,'' said Dutch
ambassador Jan Sizoo.
	   The burnt-out, shelled houses and deserted villages seemed
likely to increase foreign pressure on Serbia to stop using its
police and army against militants battling for independence for
Kosovo's 9-to-1 ethnic Albanian majority.
	   After more than a week of clashes between Serb forces and
militants in the region of Decani, 75 kilometers (47 miles) west of
the provincial capital Pristina, a group of foreign diplomats from
Belgrade, state-run television and Tanjug news agency, as well as
one independent reporter, were escorted into the area Sunday.
	   With the main east-west artery traversing the province closed,
the diplomats' convoy, escorted by police, took several hours by
roundabout route to reach the Decani area.
	   ``We've only seen a part of what one could call a battlefield,
only a stretch of some 30-40 kilometers, we don't know what's
happening on the other side of the hill,'' Sizoo said.
	   ``We've been told that the blame is on the terrorists who
started first. But, this statement is very difficult to defend _
for a conflict you always need two parties,'' he added.
	   Last week's fighting triggered an exodus of 20,000 Kosovo
Albanians into northern Albania. Another 7,000 to 10,000 refugees
fled to the neighboring Yugoslav republic of Montenegro and more
than 50,000 people are believed displaced within Kosovo itself.
	   More than 250 people have died in Kosovo since early March, when
Serb forces began battling militants of the Kosovo Liberation Army,
which claims it is rapidly gaining ground and controls the rugged
center and west of the province.
	   Even Streoce, the first village the convoy saw some 5 kilometers
(three miles) south of Pec, in northwestern Kosovo, bore scars of
heavy fighting. More than 20 houses were completely burned or
shelled out. Apart from a few well-armed policemen, no living being
could be seen.
	   On the outskirts of Decani, a town of 35,000 inhabitants,
freshly painted-over shop windows could not conceal the UCK
graffiti _ the Albanian language acronym for the Kosovo Liberation
Army, the militants fighting to wrest the province away from
Serbia.
	   A few Serb townspeople lingered about the police station.
	   Some ethnic Albanians are said to be still in parts of Decani
untouched by fighting. But the visitors saw none.
	   ``How long will they keep burning us out? Somebody has to take
the blame for all this _ either we, they (Albanians) or the
state,'' said a 70-year-old Serb who gave only his first name,
Sreten.
	   Ilinka, a 47-year-old woman from the nearby Serb settlement of
Babaloc, said she was trapped three weeks ago when she came to
Decani, and fighting broke out. Her children and family remained
behind and she has had no word of them.
	   At the police station, the diplomats were shown an array of
weapons police said were confiscated from militants in the
fighting.
	   Further along the Decani road leading to Djakovica, the scenery
recalled some of the worst of Bosnia and Croatia.
	   Many heavily damaged houses were totally burned out. Cartridges
of different caliber littered streets.
	   ``They (the KLA) used houses built of concrete transformed into
real military bunkers,'' Maj. Gen. Sreten Lukic of the Serbian
police told the visitors. If able to, the ethnic Albanians carried
away their dead and wounded, he added, without giving any estimate
of casualties.
	   Ethnic Albanian leaders have said more than 50 people were
killed and that some 200 men were missing and presumed captured
following the offensive.
	   In Prilep, 7 kilometers (four miles) south of Decani, stray
cattle roamed the ghostly village. Houses were peppered with bullet
scars. Some had gashing holes made by grenades.
	   (str/kk/as)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
