w2596 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Pakistan-Bombing     06-08 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Bombing,0367 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bomb rips through jewelry store injuring 20 people
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ A bomb tore apart a jewelry store in
eastern Punjab province on Monday injuring 20 people, several of
them seriously, police officials said.
	   The explosion was the third to shatter Pakistan since last
Friday, when a bomb exploded in a theater in the eastern city of
Lahore, killing three people.
	   On Sunday a powerful bomb ripped through a train in southern
Sindh province, killing 26 people and injuring 45 others more.
	   The Pakistan government has come out strong against its uneasy
neighbor India, accusing New Delhi of sending infiltrators into
Pakistan to carry out acts of terrorism.
	   No one has taken responsibility for Monday's explosion in
Khanewal, in the heart of Punjab province, some 550 kilometers (330
miles) south of the federal capital of Islamabad.
	   The injured were in the jewelry store or walking past at the
time of the explosion, said police.
	   While there was no immediate comment from the government here,
it accusing New Delhi on Sunday of ``fomenting terrorism.''
	   India has denied the charges. Both countries routinely accuse
each other of carrying out acts of terrorism.
	   Pakistan and India have been uneasy neighbors since the British
left the Asian subcontinent in 1947 granting India its independence
and creating Pakistan as a homeland for the Muslims of the region.
	   They two neighbors have fought three wars since 1947.
	   Last month both India and Pakistan carried out underground
nuclear tests generating worldwide condemnation and threats of
economic sanctions. It also sparked fresh worries of a nuclear
confrontation between the two neighbors.
	   In a statement issued on Sunday Information Minister Mushahid
Hussein accused India of carrying out these terrorist acts to ``put
pressure on Pakistan ... and to divert attention away from domestic
political and economic frustrations.''
	   India's Hindu nationalist government, Hussein said ``is
apparently rattled by the restoration of the strategic balance in
South Asia (following Pakistan's nuclear explosions) ... and is now
resorting to terroristic actions.''
</TEXT>
