<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Recession, 2nd Ld-2nd Add </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGAPORE: Office said.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   The previous forecast was made in February, before a clear
picture of the severity of Asia's economic slump had emerged. Since
then, the turmoil in neighboring Indonesia has worsened and other
regional economies have begun to show signs of hitting zero growth
or outright recession.
	   Prior to the announcement, the Singapore government had insisted
that the economy would grow at least 2.5 percent this year, though
occasionally had said it was ready to revise the forecast if
necessary.
	   At least two private investment houses have already predicted
that the Singapore economy will fall into outright recession this
year, though a recent newspaper survey of 15 analysts and
economists showed an average forecast of 1.5 percent growth.
	   Finance Minister Richard Hu defended the government forecasts in
Parliament last week, though he conceded that the authorities stood
ready to implement a stimulus package soon if new figures indicate
a likely recession.
	   Such measures would include tax rebates, and the acceleration of
infrastructure projects, Hu said.
	    &UR; MORE	   
</TEXT>
