<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Recession, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URGENT
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Singapore says will revise rosy economic forecast &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: COMBINES urgent series; ADDS byline &QL; 
 &UR; By JONATHAN DRAKE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ In a sign Singapore will abandon predictions
for healthy economic growth this year, the government announced
Monday it will soon revise previous forecasts.
	   Until now, the government had stood by projections for between
2.5 percent and 4.5 percent growth, despite worrying indications
that the regional slowdown was deepening and the country was
sliding into recession.
	   ``The Ministry of Trade and Industry intends to revise this
growth forecast when data for the second quarter becomes
available,'' the Prime Minister's Office said.
	   The previous forecast was made in February, before a clear
picture of the severity of Asia's economic slump had emerged. Since
then, the turmoil in neighboring Indonesia has worsened and other
regional economies have begun to show signs of hitting zero growth
or outright recession.
	   Prior to the announcement, the Singapore government had insisted
that the economy would grow at least 2.5 percent this year, though
occasionally had said it was ready to revise the forecast if
necessary.
	   At least two private investment houses have already predicted
that the Singapore economy will fall into outright recession this
year, though a recent newspaper survey of 15 analysts and
economists showed an average forecast of 1.5 percent growth.
	   Finance Minister Richard Hu defended the government forecasts in
Parliament last week, though he conceded that the authorities stood
ready to implement a stimulus package soon if new figures indicate
a likely recession.
	   Such measures would include tax rebates, and the acceleration of
infrastructure projects, Hu said.
	   The chairman of one of Singapore's biggest banks warned of a
recession next year if the government does not take action now to
stimulate the economy, a newspaper reported Monday.
	   Wee Cho Yaw, chairman of United Overseas Bank, told The Straits
Times that the current economic situation in the small island
republic was the worst he had seen in his 40-year banking career.
	   He said Asia's financial crisis far exceeds the last major
economic challenge Singapore faced, a recession in 1985.
	   He said the previous government forecast was unlikely to be
achieved and urged immediate action.
	   ``If there is no growth, or a mere 1 percent growth, then the
government will have to inject more funds into the system,'' Wee
was quoted as saying.
	   These could include tax cuts and more spending on
infrastructure, he said.
</TEXT>
