<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-UNIFIL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. peacekeepers protest to Israel over shelling
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TYRE, Lebanon (AP) _ The U.N. peacekeeping force in south
Lebanon protested to the Israeli army after a mortar shell fired by
Israeli-allied militiamen hit a peacekeepers' position, a U.N.
official said Monday.
	   There were no casualties in the incident last Thursday, the
official said, speaking on customary condition of anonymity.
	   He said a 120mm mortar shell, with Hebrew markings, was fired by
the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army militia from Beit Leif
village on the edge of Israel's occupation zone in the south.
	   The shell struck a U.N. Nepalese post in the village of Hariss,
damaging prefabricated offices, the official added. Beit Leif, a
predominantly Shiite Muslim village, is across from the occupied
zone four kilometers (2.5 miles) north of the Israeli border.
	   Since it was sent to south Lebanon in 1978 after an Israeli
invasion, the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon has been caught in the
crossfire between Lebanese guerrillas and Israeli occupation
forces.
	   A total of 222 members of the nine-nation, 4,500-strong force
have died in fighting and accidents.
