<SLUG> BC-SKorea-US-Life Insurance </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. insurance firm plans to invest dlrs 1 billion in Korea
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ The U.S. insurance giant Metropolitan
Life Insurance Co. plans to buy a 50-percent stake in Korea Life
Insurance Co. for dlrs 1 billion, Korea Life officials said Monday.
	   A memorandum of understanding to be signed in New York on
Tuesday calls for Metropolitan to offer management and technical
know-how, they said.
	   Currently, Korea Life Insurance is owned 27.7 percent by its
chairman, Choi Soon-young, and 21.8 percent by his relatives. The
rest is owned by small local investors.
	   Korea Life Insurance, the nation's third largest life insurance
company, sold policies worth dlrs 5.6 billion last year _ 16
percent of the nation's dlrs 35 billion life insurance market.
	   ``Through the deal, we can learn advanced operational know-how
of Metropolitan, not to mention we can improve our financial status
significantly,'' said Choi Ji-ho, a spokesman for Korea Life
Insurance.
	   The deal, if successful, would enable Metropolitan to expand its
business in South Korea's fast-growing life insurance market, which
grew by 21 percent last year and is expected to expand by 14
percent this year.
	   Metropolitan already has a wholly owned life insurance
subsidiary in Seoul, called MetLife Insurance Korea Ltd., which
held less than 1 percent of the local life insurance market last
year.
</TEXT>
