<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-US-Protest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dozens of protesters demand Washington help speed up IMF bailout
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ About a dozen demonstrators staged a
peaceful protest outside U.S. Embassy on Monday, demanding
Washington speed up the reintroduction of a dlrs 43 billion
international economic bailout.
	   The protest, the latest in a series outside the embassy in
recent days, coincided with the arrival of an International
Monetary Fund team in Jakarta.
	   The team is to assess the state of Indonesia's battered economy
as the IMF considers whether to restart the payment of installments
under the plan.
	   The bailout was suspended several weeks ago amid political
turmoil, rioting and protests that climaxed on May 21 with the
resignation of ex-President Suharto.
	   His successor, President B.J. Habibie, who has introduced
wideranging political reforms, has promised full cooperation with
the IMF.
	   However, U.S. officials have cautioned that outside economic
assistance won't work unless there is political stability.
	   Monday's protesters waved banners and chanted: ``People are
hungry, how about the money!''
	   Police and army personnel kept watch from a distance.
	   Last week, a protester was arrested after he allegedly tore a
American flag at the U.S. consulate in Surabaya, Indonesia's second
largest city.
</TEXT>
