<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-US-Reyna,0527 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Midfielder carries a burden for this tournament
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo &QL; 
 &UR; By RONALD BLUM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAINT-JEAN D'ARDIERES, France (AP) _ Claudio Reyna no longer is
the future of U.S. soccer. More than anyone else, the midfielder is
counted on to carry the Americans' offense, which seems to sputter
without him.
	   ``I do feel pressure and I do feel responsible for how the team
does,'' Reyna said Sunday as roosters crowed in the courtyard of
the U.S. team's hotel.
	   Reyna, 24, had four goals in 28 games last season with VfL
Wolfsburg in Germany's Bundesliga. He was the youngest player on
the '94 U.S. team after leading Virginia to an unprecedented three
straight NCAA titles from 1991-93, twice winning the college player
of the year award.
	   He played for the U.S. team in the 1992 Barcelona Olympics and
was set to make a breakthrough at the 1994 World Cup, but he pulled
his right hamstring 10 days before the opener and missed the entire
tournament.
	   At the time, he was looked at as the future star of American
soccer. The injury clearly frustrated him.
	   ``I was 20 years old. I thought I'd never get another chance
again,'' Reyna said.
	   This time, he's the center of the team. In 1994, John Harkes and
Tab Ramos did most of the playmaking, but after two major knee
operations, Ramos isn't close to his old form.
	   Harkes, the captain the past three years, was cut by coach Steve
Sampson in April, partly because he wouldn't assume a defensive
role and allow Reyna to be the playmaker.
	   Sampson then adopted a 3-6-1 formation in which the Americans
start three defenders, six midfielders and a lone forward. It's
perfectly suited to Reyna's passing skills.
	   When there are at least two holding midfielders behind Reyna,
``it gives him the freedom to attack more, and a player with that
kind of freedom welcomes it, and you saw the result in Austria,''
Sampson said.
	   Reyna scored a goal and set up two others in the Americans' 3-0
victory at Vienna on April 22. But since then, his right hamstring
has bothered him again, an injury from the Bundesliga season.
	   With Reyna in the lineup, the Americans beat Kuwait 2-0 last
month. But when he sat out exhibition games against Macedonia and
Scotland, the U.S. team wound up with a pair of scoreless ties.
	   ``There are certain players that need to play well for us to
succeed as a team,'' Sampson said, ``and he is one of them.''
	   Reyna was ranked 25th among 311 players in the Bundesliga last
season, and an exceptional World Cup could turn him into a big
star.
	   Still, Reyna's coach at Wolfsburg, Wolfgang Wolf, said the
midfielder had to toughen up. ``If he gets hit three times, he's
basically taken out of the game. I want Claudio to show more
spirit,'' Wolf said.
	   Reyna said the criticism came after he played a poor game and he
could take it. He also expects a lot of pushing and shoving from
Germany, the opening opponent for the Americans on June 15.
	   ``German players play aggressively against anyone,'' he said.
``They kill each other in practice.''
</TEXT>
