<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai stocks hit 11-year low; currency down
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with stocks closing at 11-year low. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo BK102

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thai stock prices plumbed an 11-year
low Monday as investors dumped the stock of the country's biggest
finance company after it decided to sell half of its securities
subsidiary.
	   The Stock Exchange of Thailand closed down 5.79 points to
312.37. Dealers said the index hasn't seen such lows since 1987,
blaming the drop on regional currency woes and the move by Phatra
Thanakit PCL.
	   Phatra Thanakit announced last week that it would sell a 51
percent stake in a subsidiary, Phatra Securities Co., to Merrill
Lynch and Co.
	   Dealers said it could be the beginning of the end of Phatra's
listing on the exchange, since top Phatra executives said they were
considering merging the company's finance operations into those of
Thai Farmers Bank PCL, its biggest shareholder.
	   Earlier, Thai baht hit a 13-week low of 43.80 to the U.S.
dollar, off from 43.25 at Friday's close, as investors dumped
regional currencies after the dollar surged to a seven-year high
against the Japanese yen.
	   The weakness of the Japanese currency, dealers said, spells
trouble for crisis-hit Southeast Asian economies that have been
increasingly dependent on Japan as an export market.
	   Fears are rising that the Asian economic crisis could enter a
new, more devastating phase.
</TEXT>
