<SLUG> BC-Spain-Algeria-Asylum </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Algerian helicopter pilot granted temporary stay in Spain
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain _ Spanish police kept an Algerian military
helicopter pilot under observation Monday while the interior
ministry dealt with his request for political asylum.
	   The lieutenant, who was not identified by Spanish officials,
flew to Spain Sunday during military maneuvers, landing at the
Ibiza airport where he surrendered to authorities.
	   A foreign ministry spokeswoman said the pilot would be granted a
temporary stay under police observation while his request for
asylum is being reviewed by the interior ministry, a procedure that
usually takes several months.
	   Algeria sent a military crew to Spain to fly the helicopter back
home.
	   It was the first known case of asylum being requested by an
active member of the Algerian military forces, although many other
Algerians have sought asylum to escape poverty and alleged threats
from Islamic fundamentalists, the foreign ministry spokeswoman, who
declined to be identified, said.
	   At least 75,000 people have died in Algeria during an insurgency
resulting from the cancellation of the 1992 parliamentary elections
by the military-backed regime, apparently to head off victories by
Islamic candidates.
	   The revolt has worsened living conditions for many Algerians,
who have sought immigration visas at the embassies of Spain and
other European countries.
	   (mr/krt)
</TEXT>
