<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Farmers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine President-elect Estrada promises help to landless
</HEADLINE>
farmers &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo Available &QL; 
 &UR; By CLARO CORTES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ President-elect Joseph Estrada took
off his formal shirt, ate with his hands and promised protesting
farmers Monday they will get a fair hearing in a court case over
ownership of 100 hectares (250 acres) of land.
	   The legal appeal by the farmers for the return of fields awarded
under a land reform program but then taken away on a technicality
is seen as a test case for Estrada, who won the May 11 presidential
election on a ``pro-poor'' platform.
	   ``I am no longer campaigning, the elections are over,'' Estrada
said to 13 farmers and four children camped outside the agrarian
reform building in suburban Quezon City. ``I am here to really help
you.''
	   Estrada and his incoming agrarian reform secretary, Horacio
``Boy'' Morales, a former Communist leader, talked with the farmers
over a lunch of rice, cheap fried fish, boiled beans and sauteed
vegetable greens.
	   Estrada, Morales and the farmers ate with their hands while
several old women shooed away flies hovering over them.
	   Estrada told the farmers he cannot tell the Supreme Court how to
rule on the appeal, but promised the farmers they will get a fair
hearing.
	   ``It is very important to decide on the merits of the case and
not on a technicality,'' he said.
	   On November 1997, the farmers were awarded the land in Sumilao
in Bukidnon province.
	   The owner of the property, however, appealed to the Supreme
Court, which withdrew the award after the agrarian reform office
submitted its opinion on the case a day after the court-imposed
deadline. The farmers have appealed for a reconsideration of the
ruling.
	   Estrada, a former actor, small-town mayor and senator, will be
inaugurated June 30 as the Philippines' third president since the
late dictator Ferdinand Marcos was ousted in 1986.
	   Art Banzuela, leader of a support group for the farmers, said
sharing a meal with Estrada was important for them.
	   ``This was to show that Estrada is one of us,'' he said. ``This
is a symbol of his unity with the farmers.''
</TEXT>
