<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Estrada </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Estrada quits last vice _ smoking _ three weeks ahead of schedule
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Vice President Joseph Estrada says he
has quit his last vice _ cigarette smoking _ three weeks ahead of a
June 30 deadline, when he loses the ``vice'' in his title and
becomes the country's 13th president.
	   ``I advanced the quitting of my smoking,'' Estrada said after
receiving an award from the Knights of Rizal, a local association
which reveres the country's national hero, Jose Rizal. ``If I
cannot discipline myself earlier, how can I discipline my people?''
	   Estrada said that when he has the urge to smoke, he now eats
menthol candy instead.
	   But quitting has increased his appetite, he said. The
already-portly Estrada says he now eats a second helping at every
meal.
	   Estrada had promised to quit smoking on June 30, when he takes
over from outgoing President Fidel Ramos. Estrada was the runaway
winner of the May 11 presidential election against nine other
contenders.
	   He agreed to quit smoking after being asked to serve as an
example for other Filipinos on World No Tobacco Day on May 30, but
asked for one month to prepare.
	   Estrada, 61, a mustachioed ex-actor, admits to being a former
heavy-drinking womanizer and gambler, but says he has reformed.
	   He said he used to smoke three packs a day but slowly cut back
before finally quitting.
</TEXT>
