w2663 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-Markets     06-08 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine peso, stocks weaken on yen decline
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ The Philippine peso weakened against
the U.S. dollar Monday, following the trend of other regional
currencies after the dollar broke through the critical level of 140
Japanese yen, dealers said.
	   The dollar averaged 39.649 pesos, up 49.5 centavos from Friday's
39.154 pesos.
	   The dollar's gain against the peso was moderated, however, by
subdued corporate demand for the U.S. currency, dealers said.
	   A dealer for a large local bank said the peso could hit 40 to
the dollar if the yen depreciates further against the dollar.
	   The dealer said currency traders are closely watching Tuesday's
meeting of deputy finance ministers from the Group of Seven
industrialized nations to determine where the yen is headed.
	   If the G-7 meeting fails to address the yen's fall against the
dollar, the trader said the yen could slump further and that would
weigh down other Asian currencies, including the peso.
	   On the stock market, the weaker Asian currencies and prospects
for higher local interest rates pushed shares lower, analysts said.
	   Higher interest rates and a volatile currency make fixed-income
investments and the dollar more attractive alternatives to stocks.
	   The 30-share Philippine Stock Exchange retreated 27.17 points or
1.4 percent to 1,930.59 after gaining 3.88 points Friday.
	   The index slid by as much as 42 points as sellers remained the
dominant force. Only last-minute buying kept the main index from
closing at its low.
	   ``Foreigners are mostly sellers. Even locals aren't bottom
fishing,'' said Ramon Lucas, a trader for Kim Eng Securities.
	   Analysts see domestic interest rates rising after several weeks
of decline after inflation in May hit a 23-month high of 9.2
percent from April's 7.8 percent. Under a new consumer price index
that uses 1994 as a base year that was introduced by the government
Friday, inflation in May was 10.3 percent.
	   Vicente Unson, analyst for Dharmala Securities, said an active
currency market and prospects of higher rates in Monday's treasury
bill auction prompted investors still in the market to sell.
	   He said these developments compounded apprehensions over the
outlook of the Philippine economy, which has so far bucked a
region-wide contraction.
	   ``People are still concerned whether we can maintain our
growth,'' said Unson, referring to the country's first quarter
gross national produce growth of 2.5 percent. Growth was 5.4
percent in the same period last year.
</TEXT>
