<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Czech-Plane Accident </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two MiGs collide in mid-air, no casualties
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) _ Two fighter planes collided in
mid-air Monday, one of them crashing near a densely populated area,
slightly injuring six people, defense ministry officials said.
	   The two planes collided at 9:25 a.m. in heavy clouds over the
city of Ceske Budejovice, 130 kilometers (81 miles) south of
Prague, Petr Sykora a ministry press official said. No further
details were immediately given.
	   One of the planes crashed near an apartment complex, setting
three buildings on fire, local police officials said. The plane
first hit several parked cars and then slid towards the buildings,
damaging one of them heavily.
	   Six people were slighlty injured in the accident, but no
casulaties were reported.
	   The other plane crashed in an uninhabited area near the complex,
causing no immediate damages, CTK news agency said.
	   Residents were evacuated and given gas masks to prevent
inhalation of poisionous gasses from burning plastic in the
buildings.
	   At least 200 police and firemen brought the fire under control
within two hours, CTK reported.
	   One of the planes was a two-seat Russian-made MiG 21U and the
other was a MiG 21 with a single pilot. All three men ejected
safely, but were taken to a nearby hospital to be examinated,
Sykora said.
	   (oh/me) 	   
</TEXT>
