<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Jordan-Israel </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jordanian pilots to train in Turkey
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ An agreement between Turkey and Jordan to
hold joint military training exercises may draw further ire from
Arab countries already angry over a similar deal with Israel, a
newspaper reported Monday.
	   The report in the daily Cumhuriyet came a day after Jordan's
King Hussein confirmed his country will cooperate with Israel and
Turkey, prompting speculation a regional alliance was emerging
between the three.
	   An agreement allowing Jordanian and Turkish jets to train in
each others airspace was signed in Amman during a visit by Turkey's
air force chief last week, the paper said.
	   Turkish officials would neither confirm nor deny the report.
	   Military ties between Turkey and Israel have been rapidly
developing since Turkey and Israel signed a training deal in 1996.
	   Jordan and Turkey have conducted several joint maneuvers in the
last few years, but they were not made public in order not to anger
Syria.
	   (sh-pq-cph) 	   
</TEXT>
