w2674 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-PoliticalPr 1stLd-Writethru   06-08 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Political Prisoners, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian president to release more political prisoners
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS to UPDATE with plan to release 16 more prisoners; ADDS
byline &QL; 
 &UR; By HARIS SYAMAUN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ President B.J. Habibie plans to
release 16 more political prisoners later this week, bringing to 20
the number freed since his authoritarian predecessor Suharto quit
last month, Indonesia's justice minister said Monday.
	   ``I cannot give more details about their identity or from which
prisons they will be released, but the president has approved the
plan,'' Justice Minister Muladi told reporters after a meeting with
Habibie.
	   Earlier, members of Indonesia's National Human Rights Commission
urged Habibie to speed up the release of political prisoners.
	   The commission was appointed by Suharto in 1993, but has a
proven track record for independently investigating human rights
abuses.
	   Suharto ended 32 years in office on May 21 when he resigned and
was replaced by Habibie.
	   Within days the new leader ordered the release of four high
profile dissidents who had been jailed for criticizing Suharto's
regime. Habibie said more would be released in the future, but gave
no timetable.
	   Private human rights groups say at least 200 political prisoners
are still locked up.
	   Also on Monday about 100 protesters staged a peaceful rally
outside the Justice Ministry demanding the prisoners' immediate
release.
	   Some carried a banner that read: ``Hey government! What about
your promise to release more political prisoners?''
	   ``It seems that the government isn't really serious about
granting amnesties to more political prisoners,'' said Bonar Tigor
Naipospos, a former jailed dissident who now heads the Indonesian
Society for Humanity.
	   Last month Muladi said that most prisoners would be released.
	   However, the inmates to remain in prison would be those
convicted of working against the national philosophy Pancasila,
plotting against the state or simply of violent criminal acts.
	   They include many East Timorese rebels who have fought a
guerrilla war since 1975 against Indonesia's annexation of the
former Portuguese colony.
	   Among them are rebel leader Xanana Gusmao who is serving a
20-year prison term.
	   Last week United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan wrote to
Habibie urging him to release Gusmao.
	   However, the Indonesia's government maintains that he is a
violent criminal, not a political prisoner.
	   Pancasila is a five-point creed adopted when Indonesia declared
independence from Dutch colonial rule in 1945. It calls for social
tolerance among Indonesia's 202 million ethnically diverse people
scattered over 17,000 islands.
</TEXT>
