<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 1100 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Most Asian markets closed lower Tuesday on
fears that further depreciation in the yen, which fell to a
seven-year low, could spark another round of currency devaluations
in the region. Thai stock prices tumbled, with the key index
closing at an 11-year low as investors dumped the stock of the
country's biggest finance company, Phatra Thanakit PCL, after it
decided to sell half of its securities subsidiary. The Stock
Exchange of Thailand index closed down 5.79 points, or 1.8 percent,
to 312.37, its lowest level since late 1987. Singapore shares fell
3.4 percent, reacting to news of the republic's first major
property development default and the continued weakness of the
Japanese yen and other regional currencies. The Singapore's
benchmark Straits Times Industrial Index fell 39.89 points to
1,128.57. News that a Singapore-Hong Kong joint venture missed a
deadline for a 68.6 million Singapore dollar (dlrs 40 million)
payment on a plot of land to develop condominiums dampened market
sentiment. In Hong Kong,share prices closed generally mixed in
light trading. The Hang Seng Index, the market's key indicator of
blue chips, rose 17.16 points, or 0.2 percent, to 8,586.63. (ASIAN
MARKETS)
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ In a sign Singapore will abandon predictions
for healthy economic growth this year, the government announced
Monday it will soon revise previous forecasts. Until now, the
government had stood by projections for between 2.5 percent and 4.5
percent growth, despite worrying indications that the regional
slowdown was deepening and the country was sliding into recession.
The previous forecast was made in February, before a clear picture
of the severity of Asia's economic slump emerged. Prior to the
announcement, the Singapore government had insisted that the
economy would grow at least 2.5 percent this year, though
occasionally had said it was ready to revise the forecast if
necessary. (SINGAPORE-RECESSION)
	   BASEL, Switzerland (AP) _ Despite the economic turmoil in Asia,
prospects for growth in the rest of the world are looking positive,
according to a central bankers report released Monday. Long-running
economic expansion in the United States and Britain is set to
continue, says the annual report of the Basel-based Bank for
International Settlements, known as the central banker's central
bank. Serious spread of the Asian crisis to other parts of the
world has so far been avoided and the worst may be over in Asia
itself, according to the 199-page study. Rekindling growth in
another of the world's major economies, Japan, ``will not be easy''
and the full impact on Europe of the Asian crisis has still to be
assessed, the report says. In addition, tightening labor markets,
larger trade deficits and booming prices for financial assets show
inflationary risks are rising. (BANKERS-ECONOMY)
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Philippine Airlines said Monday a
crippling strike by pilots has caused potential foreign buyers of
the airline to break off talks and could force the company to shut
down. In an emotional statement, PAL said the 3-day-old strike by
more than 600 pilots is ``bleeding the airline dry,'' causing daily
losses of 150 million to 200 million pesos (dlrs 3.8 million to 5.1
million) in lost revenue. The union is protesting a new management
policy of ordering pilots to retire who have reached 20 years of
service or flown 20,000 hours, regardless of age. The policy puts
about 200 pilots in danger of forced retirement, the union said.
The airline earlier announced it must cut expenses by as much as 40
percent, slash flights, and sharply reduce its work force to
survive. PAL said Monday it lost 8 billion pesos (dlrs 205 million)
in the last fiscal year _ three times more than the previous year.
(PHILIPPINES-AIRLINE STRIKE)
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Bankrupt Hanbo Steel Industry Co.,
South Korea's second largest steel maker, will be sold to foreign
investors later this year, its creditor banks said Monday. The
decision came after potential domestic investors, including
state-run Pohang Iron and Steel Corp., the nation's No. 1 steel
maker, gave up plans to take over the failed steel producer. Pohang
last week called back four of its executives who had worked as
court-appointed managers for Hanbo since the steel firm collapsed
under dlrs 6 billion in bank debts in January, 1997. Along with the
return of its officials, Pohang said it also stopped selling Hanbo
products through its sales networks under an arrangement with
Hanbo's creditors. The decision to sever ties with Hanbo was aimed
at avoiding trade friction with foreign countries, the statement
said. (SKOREA-HANBO STEEL)
</TEXT>
