<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0672 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) _ Diplomatic efforts were under way to
prevent the border conflict between Eritrea and Ethiopia from
exploding into full-scale war. Officials hope Monday's summit of
African leaders will produce new ideas for a settlement. African
heads of state gathered for a meeting of the Organization of
African Unity in Ouagadougu, Burkina Faso, where finding a peaceful
solution to the Ethiopian-Eritrean crisis topped their agenda.
``We're anxious to see what they come up with,'' said Eritrean
government spokesman Isaac Yared. The OAU, hampered by the location
of its headquarters in Ethiopia and Eritrea's disinterest in the
organization, has played a minor role since the first border clash
on May 6. (ERITREA-ETHIOPIA)
	   LUXEMBOURG (AP) _ The EU may ban investments in Serbia and
freeze the country's assets abroad on Monday, tightening sanctions
that have so far failed to get Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to reach a negotiated settlement in Kosovo. The foreign
ministers of the 15 European Union nations discussed these measures
to punish Milosevic for cracking down on his independence-minded
southern province and prevent another Bosnia-style ethnic conflict.
The EU has already banned arms exports and restricted travel visas
for Yugoslav officials. But at Washington's urging, they have held
off on freezing Yugoslav assets abroad and the investment ban to
give Milosevic a chance to reach a peaceful settlement in Kosovo.
(EU-KOSOVO)
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ An alleged Bosnian Croat
paramilitary leader charged with allowing a subordinate to rape a
prisoner went on trial Monday before the Yugoslav war crimes
tribunal. Anto Furundzija, 28, was arrested in December by Dutch
troops in the central Bosnian town of Vitez. He has pleaded
innocent to two war crimes charges alleging that he stood by and
watched as a prisoner under interrogation was raped by one of his
troops in May 1993. Rape has been considered a war crime in other
cases before the U.N. court, but Furundzija's trial is the first to
deal specifically with sexual assault inflicted during the course
of an interrogation. (BOSNIA-WAR CRIMES)
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Jewish settlers moved into two buildings in
Arab east Jerusalem before dawn Monday, stringing barbed wire,
hanging Israeli flags and setting off angry stone-throwing clashes
with Palestinian neighbors. It was the latest in a series of
escalating confrontations in Jerusalem's eastern sector as both
sides accuse the other of trying to grab land in the bitterly
contested city. At least two people were injured in Monday's
clashes in the Silwan neighborhood, including the top Palestinian
official in Jerusalem, Faisal Husseini. He was hit in the head with
a stone and slightly hurt before police and soldiers broke up the
melee. The settlers took over five apartments in two buildings,
plus a plot of land. (ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS)
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee
reiterated his country's angry objections to pressure from the U.N.
Security Council to scrap its nuclear weapons program, telling
lawmakers India would not let anyone tell it what to do. His
statement in India's upper house of Parliament was quoted by local
news agencies. It came two days after the 15-member Council asked
both India and Pakistan, longtime rivals who escalated their arms
race with a series of tit-for-tat nuclear tests last month, to
resume talks to solve their disputes, especially over the Himalayan
territory of Kashmir they both claim. The Indian government on
Saturday released a statement calling the Security Council
resolution ``coercive and unhelpful.'' Monday, Vajpayee reiterated
his oft-repeated statement since his May 11-13 nuclear tests that
India will not let any other nation mediate in the Kashmir dispute.
(INDIA-NUCLEAR)
</TEXT>
