<HEADLINE>
Soldiers get officers' TV sets to watch World Cup
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) _ In an attempt to keep army discipline
high during the World Cup, the defense ministry has ordered
television sets removed from the offices of commanders to soldiers'
barracks, private Nova TV reported Monday.
	   Over the weekend, the TV station broadcast the removal of
several television sets from offices in the ministry building in
Sofia. A duty officer was quoted as saying 130 television sets
would be removed from the capital alone.
	   ``This is a smart move. Otherwise the barracks will be empty
during the games of the national team,'' said Stoyan Garvanov, 23,
who was doing his compulsory military service during the last World
Cup in 1994.
	   After a series of sensational victories then, Bulgaria's soccer
team made it to the semi-finals, causing an unprecedented outbreak
of mass jubilation.
	   Expectations are again high, although the Bulgarian squad is now
aging and faces a tough group: heavily favored Spain; Nigeria, gold
medalist at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics; and Paraguay.
	   (vt/mh/as)
