<HEADLINE>
Russian border guards kill two suspected Chinese poachers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian border guards shot and killed two
suspected Chinese poachers after they allegedly resisted arrest and
attacked the Russians, the border guard command said Monday.
	   Commander of the Russian Far Eastern border district Alexander
Golbakh said he has notified the Chinese government of the
incident, which occurred June 4 in Russia's Makarikha Bay, the
ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
	   Golbakh said that during an attempt to detain the fishermen, one
of them attacked a Russian border guard with an axe, and the
officer was forced to open fire with a machine gun. Both Chinese
fishermen died from wounds, ITAR-Tass said.
	   Last month, a Russian border patrol boat opened fire on a
Chinese fishing boat in the Bering Sea, off the Kamchatka
Peninsula, killing two people and wounding five.
	   China acknowledged the boat was in a Russian zone, but
criticized the border guards' response, saying the deaths could
have been avoided.
