w2694 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GuineaBissau-Fighting     06-08 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Guinea Bissau-Fighting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Reports: Loyalist troops in Guinea-Bissau attack holed-up rebels
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Heavy gunfire could be heard in the
capital of Guinea Bissau, West Africa, early Monday as troops loyal
to the government apparently tried to dislodge renegade soldiers
from two military barracks, news reports said.
	   The gunfire was centered on the Bissau suburb of Bra where an
unknown number of soldiers were holed up at a military base after
clashing with other troops on Sunday, the Portuguese state-run news
agency Lusa reported in a dispatch monitored here.
	   Troops and police ordered inhabitants of Bra to leave the area
where automatic weapons and heavy artillery were being used to oust
the rebels, Lusa said.
	   The military complex is also a weapons depot and the rebels were
believed to be heavily armed.
	   In a sign that the revolt could be spreading outside the
capital, Lusa reported an unidentified local source as saying that
fighting had also broken out at Mansoa, 60 kilometers (37 miles)
from Bissau.
	   The rebels, reportedly led by a former head of the armed forces
who was angered at being dismissed, took refuge at the Bra barracks
after sporadic clashes which began early Sunday at the military
high command building. Ten soldiers were killed in the fighting,
according to Lusa.
	   The capital reportedly was calm late Sunday, but fresh fighting
was reported in Bra at 2:30 a.m. (0230 GMT) Monday when government
forces apparently launched a first attack on the Bra barracks. A
second attack was launched at 5:30 a.m. (0530 GMT), according to
Lusa.
	   Few people were on the streets of the capital, where there was a
heavy troop presence, but no clashes were reported outside the Bra
suburb.
	   President Joao Bernardo Vieira said Sunday that former armed
forces chief Brig. Ansumane Mane was leading the revolt and was
backed by members of political opposition parties.
	   In a statement read on public radio, Vieira vowed to ``use all
possible means'' to quash the revolt.
	   Mane was fired six months ago during an official investigation
into the trafficking of arms to the separatist rebels of Casamanca,
a Senegalese province that borders north Guinea-Bissau.
	   Mane formally stepped down and was replaced at a ceremony in
Bissau last Saturday.
	   Reports said that troops had set up roadblocks on routes to the
presidential palace and other government buildings and military
installations.
	   Guinea Bissau, a former Portuguese colony, has a population of
about 1 million.
	   (bh/krt)
</TEXT>
