w2696 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Taiwan-Economy     06-08 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan to keep liberalizing currency market
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ The Taiwan dollar hit an 11-year low
against the U.S. dollar on Monday, but a top economic planner said
the drop won't prompt tighter regulation of the currency market.
	   The government will continue to let the market set the exchange
rate while attempting to keep speculation to a minimum, said Chiang
Pin-kung, chairman of the Council of Economic Planning and
Development.
	   ``We will respect the market,'' Chiang said at a briefing for
foreign reporters.
	   Reacting to the Japanese yen's dive and flagging exports, the
Taiwan dollar dropped to 34.69 to U.S. dlrs 1 on Monday, the lowest
level since March 1987.
	   Though anchored by solid fundamentals and U.S. dlrs 83 billion
in foreign currency reserves, Taiwan is feeling aftershocks from
the crisis in markets and currency shaking much of Asia. Japan's
economic woes are piling additional stress on the economy.
	   The local currency has fallen by about 18 percent since June
1997, and exports fell by 6.7 percent in the first four months of
1998, the CEPD announced.
	   But Taiwan's market is so open that it has become unfeasible to
defend the currency with foreign reserves, Chiang said, citing
rules permitting citizens to remit up to U.S. dlrs 5 million
overseas each year.
	   Even so, the Central Bank has also sought to deter speculators,
and banned trade in the non-deliverable forward market on May 22.
	   With the regional crisis still roiling, it will ``not be easy,''
for Taiwan to achieve 6 percent gross domestic product growth in
1998, Chiang said. The GDP grew by an estimated 6.8 percent last
year, and the CEPD had originally set a target of 6.7 percent
growth in 1998.
	   A cheaper yen has worsened Taiwan's already massive trade
deficit with Japan by motivating Japanese firms to make goods at
home instead of ordering them from Taiwan, Chiang said. That
contributed to a widening of the deficit with Japan to U.S. dlrs
1.39 billion in May, compared to 1.11 billion in May 1997.
	   Taiwan will look to domestic investment in infrastructure and
other areas to keep the economy moving, Chiang said.
</TEXT>
