<SLUG> BC-EU-Kosovo, 3rd Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU bans new investments in Serbia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Yugoslavia-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with comments by Kinkel; picks up 12th graf pvs &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT WIELAARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LUXEMBOURG (AP) _ The EU banned new investments in Serbia Monday
and denounced Belgrade for staging ``widespread house-burning and
indiscriminate artillery attacks on whole villages'' in the
province of Kosovo.
	   Serbia ``is engaged in a campaign of violence going far beyond
what could legitimately be described as a targeted anti-terrorist
operation,'' the EU foreign ministers said in a statement.
	   There was no word of freezing Yugoslav assets abroad, something
France, Italy and Greece opposed.
	   The EU urged Belgrade and Kosovo independence activists to seek
a negotiated solution to their conflict, but said President
Slobodan Milosevic bore ``special responsibility'' for that as the
Yugoslav head of state.
	   Citing ``the grave deteriorating situation on the ground,
involving the excessive use of force by the Serb security forces,''
it banned all new investments in Serbia.
	   The EU promised ``other measures'' unless the violence is
halted. It has already banned arms exports and restricted travel
visas for Yugoslav officials. But at Washington's urging, had held
off on the investment ban to give Milosevic a chance to reach a
peaceful settlement in Kosovo.
	   That has not worked. Further sanctions could include a ban on
all flights by JAT, the Yugoslav airline.
	   The EU move was unlikely make an immediate difference. ``The
fight (to get Milosevic to ease up on Kosovo) clearly lies within
the United Nations Security Council,'' said a Dutch official.
	   Escalating violence in Kosovo in recent weeks has drawn
parallels with West European waffling in 1991 and 1992 as Bosnia
slipped into civil war.
	   EU Foreign Affairs Commissioner Hans van den Broek said it was
more critical at this stage that the NATO ``defense ministers
accelerate their work'' to forge a military response to Milosevic.
	   On Thursday and Friday, those defense ministers meet in Brussels
to consider such a response though in recent weeks that option has
sparked little enthusiasm.
	   And on Friday the foreign ministers of the G-8 nations _ Canada,
United States, Britain, Germany, France, Japan, Italy and Russia _
will discuss Kosovo in London.
	   Russian support for any action against Milosevic is crucial.
``It is very important we include Russia in our efforts,'' said
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel but added to reporters ``that
will be difficult.''
	   Kinkel was to meet later Monday in Bonn with Yevgeny Primakov,
his Russian counterpart.
	   At the EU meeting, he and Austrian Foreign Minister Wolfgang
Schussel proposed similar road maps to peace in Kosovo through a
series of confidence-building steps, such as the deployment of
observers, a cease fire, an orderly return of refugees and
international mediation.
 &UR; On arrival, 12th graf
 &UR; (rw)
