<SLUG> BC-UN-Labor-Indonesia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Freed unionist: another protest possible in 2 weeks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos GEV101-102 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ Newly freed Indonesian labor unionist Muchtar
Pakpahan said Monday another national demonstration may be held in
two weeks' time ``to stop (President B.J.) Habibie.''
	   ``Our struggle is not yet ended,'' Pakpahan told a news
conference. He called for ``credible government,'' through the
convening of a special assembly to elect a transition president and
pave the way for fully democratic elections next year.
	   Habibie has said electoral reforms will be in place by August
this year and parliamentary and presidential elections held before
December 1999.
	   ``The government cannot solve all the problems itself without
involving civil society,'' Pakpahan said.
	   Massive riots in May killed 500 people and helped force
ex-President Suharto to quit, ending his iron-fisted three decades
in power.
	   Habibie, a former Suharto aide, is tainted by corruption and
nepotism, Pakpahan said.
	   Pakpahan, president of the independent Indonesian Welfare Labor
Union, was released from prison last month. He had served two years
of a three-year sentence for allegedly organizing a 1994 workers'
riot in Sumatra.
	   Last week, Habibie's government recognized Pakpahan's union and
said it would soon ratify an International Labor Organization
convention on workers' rights.
	   Pakpahan, who is attending an ILO conference in Geneva, said he
would not run for president in an election. The union could help in
establishing new political parties but wouldn't itself take a
political role, he said.
	   The International Monetary fund should halt aid to Indonesia
unless the government accounts for its use of the money, Pakpahan
said.
	   	   Habibie's government has pledged to abide by requirements of the
IMF's dlrs 43 billion bailout of the economy, suspended during the
uncertain days of political upheaval.
	   ``If there is no transparency, do not give the aid,'' Pakpahan
said.
 &UR; (gm)
</TEXT>
