<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Platini says French authorities don't care about World
</HEADLINE>
Cup &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Michel Platini, co-president of the World Cup
organizing committee, says French authorities have turned their
back on the soccer tournament and aren't providing enough support.
	   ``France has done what it had to do, but nothing more,'' Platini
said in an interview published Monday by the newspaper Le Parisien.
	   ``Take the big party in Paris on `Day One,' for example. Can you
believe that it's been hard to get authorizations? They don't give
a damn,'' he was quoted in the interview.
	   Platini said it had cost 50 million francs (dlrs 8.3 million) to
organize festivities on Tuesday night (June 9) _ ``Day One'' _
featuring huge processions and concerts around the capital.
	   The tournament kicks off the next day with the opening match
between Brazil and Scotland at Stade de France stadium in the Paris
suburb of Saint-Denis.
	   The World Cup, with 32 nations competing in the biggest-ever
final field, has already been undermined by a strike by Air France
pilots, threatening to disrupt travel during the month-long
tournament.
	   Platini said France could win the World Cup for the first time
and that 10 teams were in the running.
	   ``I think France can,'' he predicted in the interview. ``Never
has a World Cup been so open. Ten teams stand a chance of
winning.''
	   But France's greatest player and former national coach said
there was a laissez-faire attitude toward the tournament in general
in France.
	   ``Not everybody feels concerned by this event. For example the
Culture Ministry doesn't give a damn. We have no links with them,''
he was quoted. ``So in many areas nothing has been planned.''
	   Preparations at many of the 10 venues depended solely ``on the
personality of the (local) mayor,'' he was quoted saying.
	   (ip-dm)
</TEXT>
