<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serb police beat protesters in Kosovo's capital
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with U.S. ambassador and ethnic Albanian leader going
to area of fighting; color from the scene; EU weighing sanctions. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo PRI101
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ As Europe banned investment in
Serbia and weighed other ways to halt violence in Kosovo, Serbs
reported fresh clashes in the secessionist province Monday and a
U.S. diplomat and ethnic Albanian leader toured a battle-torn area.
	   European Union foreign ministers, meeting in Luxembourg, banned
investment in Serbia for ''a campaign of violence going far
beyond'' a legitimate strike against terrorists.
	   Britain, currently chairman of the EU, is sounding increasingly
determined to engage NATO troops in the southern Balkans, both to
stop the Kosovo violence spilling over into neighboring Macedonia
and Albania and maybe in Kosovo itself.
	   Washington also wants to stop Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic using police and army against militants battling for
independence for Kosovo's Albanians, who outnumber Serbs 9-to-1.
	   ``A credible discouragement in the direction of President
Milosevic is indispensible,'' said British foreign secretary Robin
Cook at the EU meeting.
	   ``I also hope for support in the steps Britain is taking to get
the measures within the United Nations and NATO agreed to stop the
violence in Kosovo,'' he added.
	   In Pristina Monday, a daily march by Kosovo Albanians for peace
passed off without incident. On Sunday, more than 100 Serbian
police broke up the demonstration, injuring at least six Albanians.
	   Christopher Hill, the U.S. ambassador to Macedonia, joined
ethnic Albanian Fehmi Agani on a trip to the Decani region in
western Kosovo, scene of fierce fighting last week.
	   A convoy of diplomats, joined by journalists for Serbian
state-run media and one independent journalist, toured the region
Sunday and saw ghastly scenes reminiscent of the earlier wars in
Bosnia and Croatia.
	   Independent journalist Aleksandar Vasovic said the group saw
many houses that had been shelled or burned out, and several
deserted villages. Serbian police said the militants started the
fighting, but Dutch ambassador Jan Sizoo was skeptical.
	   Up to 20,000 refugees from the Decani area have fled into
neighboring Albania. Another 7,000 to 10,000 are in Montenegro, the
only other Yugoslav republic, and some 50,000 are thought to be
displaced within Kosovo itself.
	   Many of that group are hiding out in the Drenica region in the
center of the province, where Serbian police began their crackdown
in early March. Since then, more than 250 people have been killed.
	   The Serbian Media Center, which is close to Kosovo authorities,
said militants attacked Drenica's last two Serb villages Monday.
But villagers returned fire, and no injuries were reported, the
Media Center said.
	   On Sunday, Serb forces reportedly continued shelling suspected
militant positions in western Kosovo. The diplomats' convoy saw no
fighting in areas it visited.
	   Ethnic Albanian officials say the campaign in the west has
killed at least 50 people and 200 others have gone missing since
late May.
	   Ethnic Albanians comprise 90 percent of the 2.2 million
inhabitants of Kosovo, and most want to secede from Serbia. Western
powers oppose any change of borders, but want Serbia to restore the
broad autonomy it took away in 1989.
	   U.S. President Bill Clinton spoke to British Prime Minister Tony
Blair on Sunday and they agreed to send a ``strong message'' that
the Serb offensive is unacceptable, a Blair aide said.
	   The United States and others planned deliberations this week on
what steps to take. British newspapers said the powers might
discuss military intervention.
	   In Washington, a top U.S. senator said Sunday that Kosovo ``has
the potential to become another Bosnia.''
	   ``We cannot allow this slaughter to occur. Once again the
Serbians are out of control. Something should be done,'' Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott said on CNN's ``Late Edition.''
	   Lott, a Republican from Mississippi, said he would not rule out
the use of American troops. He said the United States should
``always be reluctant to use military force,'' but ``I'm not saying
we should not consider troops if it continues the way it is
going.''
	   Balkan foreign ministers were meeting in Turkey Monday and may
discuss Kosovo. NATO is due to weigh its moves later this week, and
the foreign ministers of the Contact Group _ the United States,
Britian, France, Germany and Russia, joined by Canada and Italy _
is to consider further steps Friday.
	   (pvs/var/as)
</TEXT>
