<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyU-New Zealand-England </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Zealanders warm up to meet England
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) _ Embattled England rugby coach Clive
Woodward was on hand to watch a polished display by the likely All
Blacks squad in New Zealand's trial match on Monday.
	   The All Blacks will play two tests against England, which
suffered its biggest ever beating in Saturday's 76-0 loss to
Australia. While New Zealand talk back radio callers suggested the
English should play New Zealand's World Cup winning women's team,
instead of the All Blacks, Woodward maintained his optimism.
	   ``When you play rugby and get beaten by a score like that then
all you want to do is play again and set the record straight,''
Woodward said Monday. ``We're looking forward immensely to our next
game, and every other game on this tour.''
	   England plays five matches in New Zealand, starting with a game
against New Zealand A on Saturday.
	   That team will be based around the A team beaten 55-14 by the
shadow All Blacks squad Monday.
	   In a match which lacked the intensity and ruggedness of last
year's trial the All Blacks, playing as the New Zealand Barbarians
in a red strip, showed they would be a most dangerous proposition
for England.
	   New Zealand A lacked cohesion and teamwork, but looked a team
that will improve dramatically with time together ahead of next
Saturday's game against England in Hamilton.
	   The standout feature of the match was the performance by
Canterbury center Mark Mayerhofler who worked tirelessly and showed
himself to be a most accomplished player in the midfield.
	   The other player under pressure was scrum half Ofisa Tonu'u who
kept things simple in this match and did what was expected ahead of
Tuesday's naming of the test team.
	   There were a lot of mistakes in the game with the Barbarians
making the most of endless turnovers by the New Zealand A side.
	   ``We knew it would be intense, but it was a pity that the
conditions were slippery tonight,'' All Blacks captain in waiting
and Barbarians leader Taine Randell said.
	   ``The New Zealand A side wanted to run the ball, but it was too
slippery but we're happy with the win in the end. ``I think we were
a bit rusty to start but our defense picked up and we know England
had a bad game but they'll get better.''
