<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Obit-Welch </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lorne Welch, daredevil World War II escapee, dead at 81
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Lorne Welch, a daredevil British glider who was
central to two fabled escapes by British prisoners in World War II,
has died. He was 81.
	   Welch died May 15 at his home in Farnham, southwest of London,
where he lived in retirement indulging another favorite hobby,
yachting, Cause of death was not announced.
	   A test flight observer before the war, Welch, an outstanding
pilot, became a training instructor with the Royal Air Force. But
in 1942, with Britain seeking to flatten key German cities with
1,000 bombing raids, Welch flew his Wellington trainer into combat.
	   He was shot down over Nazi-occupied Holland on his fourth raid
and sent to the Stalagluft III prison camp in Silesia.. He was
later in Colditz, the huge Saxon castle where the Germans put their
most escape-prone Allied prisoners.
	   At Stalagluft III, Welch, an aeronautical engineer, put his
technical skills to work. Using parts of two beds, two duffel bags,
nine coathooks, four ice-hockey sticks, four table tennis bats and
leather from a flying boot, he built the ventilation pump for a 100
yard (90-meter) tunnel, ``Harry.'' through which 76 prisoners
escaped in 1944.
	   It was one of the largest mass breakouts by Allied prisoners,
ended in atrocity, and was made into a movie, ``The Great Escape,''
in 1963. Seventy-three of the escapees were recaptured and 50
summarily executed.
	   Before the tunnel escape, Welch had already left. On June 16,
1943, Welch and his cellmate, Walter Morison, walked out through
the main gate wearing fake German uniforms. They were recaptured a
week later on their second attempt to steal a German warplane and
fly to Sweden.
	   Obvious candidates for Colditz, Welch and Morison arrived at the
castle to find what might have been World War II's most audacious
escape in preparation: the construction of a full-sized, two-man
glider in a walled-off section of the castle attic.
	   Welch checked the glider for airworthiness, but before it could
be used, U.S. forces liberated Colditz in 1945. Prisoners displayed
the glider to openmouthed guards.
	   After the war, Welch was the first person to glide twice across
the English Channel, flew in four world gilding championships, and
worked as a glider test pilot and engineer.
	   Patrick Palles Lorne Elphinstone Welch, the son of an army
general, is survived by his wife, Ann, whom he married in 1953, and
their daughter.
	   (mj)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Britain-Obit-Welch; CT:i; 
