<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Irian Jaya </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesians to probe human rights abuses in Irian Jaya
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Investigators will probe allegations
that villagers were killed after a 1996 military operation to free
hostages held by separatists in remote Irian Jaya, a human rights
official said Monday.
	   Asmara Nababan, one of 25 members of Indonesia's National
Commission on Human Rights, said a three-person team was scheduled
to leave Jakarta on Wednesday for Jayapura, the provincial capital.
	   The investigation will focus on recent reports by three local
church leaders about violations following the rescue in May 1996 of
six foreigners _ four Britons, two Dutch _ and three Indonesians
held by rebels.
	   The six were rescued by Indonesian troops after being held for
four months by the Free Papua Movement, a rebel group fighting
Indonesian rule in the western New Guinea.
	   According to the Church leaders, at least 11 villagers were shot
dead and some were missing following the rescue. Some churches and
houses were also burned down in the villages of Bella, Alama, and
Jila, about 3,452 kilometers (2,157 miles) northeast of Jakarta.
	   More than 150 students recently occupied the local council in
demanding the investigation of the alleged killings.
</TEXT>
