<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Budget Deficit </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Top Hong Kong adviser: Hong Kong might see budget deficit
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Hong Kong could see its first budget deficit in
three years as the region's economic woes spill over into the
territory, a top government adviser said Monday.
	   Chung Sze-yuen, convenor of the Executive Council, Hong Kong
leader Tung Chee-hwa's de facto cabinet, told reporters ``it is of
course very possible'' that the budget for fiscal year 1998-9 may
end in the red.
	   Reduced revenues from land sales will strain the government's
budget this year, which has been characterized by extensive tax
cuts and higher public spending, he said.
	   Public spending also may exceed budget estimates as the
government pushes infrastructure projects ahead of schedule to
stimulate the economy and create jobs.
	   Pressure has been mounting for the government to adopt a deficit
budget next financial year as the local economy continues to suffer
from slumping property prices, sluggish retail sales and high
interest rates.
	   Last week, leaders of seven major political parties from across
the political spectrum agreed at a rare meeting to back a deficit
budget if necessary.
	   Frustrated with the government, the parties came up with their
own six-measure stimulus package, including cuts in government fees
and a refund of pre-paid taxes to taxpayers to boost consumer
spending.
	   The parties, which together won more than two-thirds of the 60
seats in last month's legislative election, are seen to have a
significant influence on Tung.
	   But despite the growing pressure, Financial Secretary Donald
Tsang told reporters Monday that it was too early to say whether a
deficit budget was needed next year.
	   ``One year's deficit is not going to solve the problem. The most
important task ahead is to improve the business environment in Hong
Kong,'' to attract foreign investment, Tsang said.
	   The economy shrank 2 percent in the first quarter, the first
contraction since 1985, which prompted the government to admit that
its initial annual forecast of 3.5 percent was unattainable.
Unemployment is at a 13-year high of 3.9 percent.
	   In February, Tsang forecast a fiscal surplus of 10.7 billion
Hong Kong dollars, based on a projected economic growth of 3.5
percent. He had declined to give a revised forecast.
</TEXT>
