<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sri Lanka-Civil War,0307 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government troops kill 81 rebels
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ Sri Lankan rebels said Monday they beat
back government troops trying to take a strategic northern town,
killing at least 11 soldiers and losing 20 of their own fighters.
	   Newspaper reports in Sri Lanka said government troops killed 81
guerrillas in the fighting Sunday.
	   In a statement faxed to news agencies in New Delhi from their
London office, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam said rebels
recovered the bodies of 11 soldiers after weekend fighting in
Mankulam and the nearby village of Ampakamam.
	   Mankulam, 250 kilometers (155 miles) north of the capital,
Colombo, is heavily fortified with mines, underground bunkers,
razor wire and booby traps. It is the largest town along a
77-kilometer (48-mile) road the army has been trying to capture
since May, 1997 in the longest and bloodiest offensive of its
15-year-old civil war against the Tamil Tigers.
	   The road would link Jaffna, a former rebel stronghold captured
by the army two years ago, with the rest of the country. Since the
army takeover, Jaffna's half million people have had to rely on air
and sea deliveries for food and other supplies.
	   A military spokesman in the Sri Lankan capital, Colombo, said
only that rebels fired mortars at troops near Ampakamam, but said
there were no casualties on either side.
	   No independent assessment of the battle situation was available
since the government bars journalists from independently visiting
the war zone. The government also censors reports about the
fighting in Sri Lanka.
	   The rebels among Sri Lanka's Tamil minority say they are
discriminated against in Sinhalese-majority country. The government
denies the charge and says that Tamils have equal rights and
opportunity to prosper.
</TEXT>
