w2759 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-AirlineSt 2ndLd-Writethru   06-08 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Airline Strike, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine Airlines says strike may force it to shut down
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with labor chief saying union refused to accept return
to work order or send appropriate officials to emergency meeting in
grafs 12-13; adds details on modernization program in graf 16 &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos Available
 &UR; By JIM GOMEZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Philippine Airlines said Monday a
crippling strike by its pilots has caused potential foreign buyers
of the airline to break off talks and could force it to shut down.
	   In a dramatic statement, PAL said the 3-day-old strike by more
than 600 pilots is ``bleeding the airline dry,'' causing daily
losses of 150 million to 200 million pesos (dlrs 3.8 million to 5.1
million) in lost revenue.
	   This has pushed the cash-strapped airline ``closer to the brink
of insolvency,'' PAL said.
	   ``With the breakdown of the talks with the foreign investors,
PAL may now have no other recourse but to shut down operations,''
it said.
	   The union is protesting a new management policy of ordering
pilots to retire who have reached 20 years of service or flown
20,000 hours, regardless of age. The policy puts about 200 pilots
in danger of forced retirement, the union said.
	   The airline earlier announced it must cut expenses by as much as
40 percent, slash flights, and sharply reduce its work force to
survive.
	   PAL said Monday it lost 8 billion pesos (dlrs 205 million) in
the last fiscal year _ three times more than the previous year.
	   PAL said that in an effort to stay afloat, it has been in talks
with a number of foreign carriers who were looking to take a
``significant'' stake in the airline.
	   ``But the work stoppage by the (pilots' union) ... has caused
investors to lose interest,'' it said.
	   PAL fears the breakdown in talks may have jeopardized its final
chance to stave off financial ruin. PAL didn't name the airlines
with which it had been in talks, but industry sources said the main
potential buyer was Northwest Airlines of the United States.
	   PAL fired all the striking pilots on Sunday, except for a few
who had complied with an airline order to return to work. Labor
Secretary Cresenciano Trajano said he issued orders to the strikers
to return to work and to the airline to accept them back.
	   Trajano called an emergency meeting Monday to try to resolve the
strike but the two union representatives refused to accept the
return-to-work order and said they had no decision-making
authority, Trajano said.
	   ``We have no other options but to find ways of keeping the
problem from worsening,'' he said.
	   The strike began Friday, forcing cancellations of more than 200
international and domestic flights and affecting thousands of
passengers.
	   PAL fired all 29 officers of the union on Saturday and warned
remaining members would also be dismissed if they didn't return to
work by noon Sunday. The 620 striking pilots represent the
airlines' total pilot force.
	   PAL had tried to recover from its spiraling losses with an
ambitious dlrs 4 billion modernization program in 1996, ordering 36
new aircraft. But Asia's currency crisis sharply reduced passenger
numbers and bloated the airline's debt in local currency terms.
	   PAL, Asia's first airline, is controlled by Chinese Filipino
tycoon Lucio Tan. It had been completely owned by the Philippine
government from 1941 until it was partly sold in 1992.
</TEXT>
