<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asian Markets, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian stock markets mostly lower
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: UPDATES with closing quotes for Taiwan dollar, graf 13 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Most Asian markets closed lower Tuesday on
fears that further depreciation in the yen, which fell to a
seven-year low, could spark another round of currency devaluations
in the region.
	   Thai stock prices tumbled, with the key index closing at an
11-year low as investors dumped the stock of the country's biggest
finance company, Phatra Thanakit PCL, after it decided to sell half
of its securities subsidiary.
	   The Stock Exchange of Thailand index closed down 5.79 points, or
1.8 percent, to 312.37, its lowest level since late 1987.
	   Dealers blamed the drop on regional currency woes and the move
by Phatra Thanakit PCL.
	   Earlier, Thai baht hit a 13-week low of 43.80 to the U.S.
dollar, off from 43.25 at Friday's close.
	   Singapore shares fell 3.4 percent, reacting to news of the
republic's first major property development default and the
continued weakness of the Japanese yen and other regional
currencies.
	   The Singapore's benchmark Straits Times Industrial Index fell
39.89 points to 1,128.57.
	   News that a Singapore-Hong Kong joint venture missed a deadline
for a 68.6 million Singapore dollar (dlrs 40 million) payment on a
plot of land to develop condominiums dampened market sentiment.
	   The Singapore dollar was also sharply lower, breaking the
benchmark 1.70 level against the U.S. currency.
	   In Tokyo, the dollar bought 140.56 yen at late afternoon, up
1.14 yen from late Friday in Tokyo and its highest point since June
20, 1991. In New York, the dollar settled at 139.75 yen on Friday.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
slipped 28.72 points, or 0.19 percent, to close at 15,294.71. On
Friday, the average lost 103.04 points, or 0.67 percent.
	   The Australian stock market was closed for a holiday, but the
Australian dollar fell to its lowest level against the dollar since
July 1986, hitting a low of 59.75 U.S. cents by afternoon.
	   The Taiwan dollar fell to 34.69 against the U.S. dollar, its
lowest level since March 1987.
	   New Zealand's dollar was also lower, down to 50.88 U.S. cents.
	   In Indonesia, the dollar was trading at 11,725 rupiah, compared
with its close Friday at 11,550.
	   Dealers in the region said institutional investors, spooked by
the weakening regional currencies and persistent pessimism over
Japan's economy, continued to dump shares.
	   The dollar's strength against the yen sprang from fresh evidence
of a robust U.S. economy after the Labor Department reported on
Friday that the nation's unemployment rate held to a 28-year-low of
4.3 percent in May.
	   Malaysian share prices closed lower, with the key slipping to
its lowest point in nearly six months. The Composite Index fell
7.26 points, or 1.4 percent, to 497.79.
	   Elsewhere:
	   TAIPEI: Share prices closed lower. The market's key Weighted
Stock Price Index fell 45.46 points, or 0.59 percent, to 7,591.27.
	   WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed following as a surge
in local interest rates. The NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 31.30
points, or 1.4 percent, to 2,104.40.
	   MANILA: Philippine shares closed lower, affected by declining
Asian currencies and prospects of an increase in domestic interest
rates. The Philippine Stock Exchange index of 30 selected stocks
fell 27.17 points, or 1.3 percent, to 1,930.59.
	   HONG KONG: Share prices closed generally mixed in light trading.
The Hang Seng Index, the market's key indicator of blue chips, rose
17.16 points, or 0.2 percent, to 8,586.63.
	   SEOUL: Share prices closed higher on expectations that President
Kim Dae-jung will be able to attract more foreign investment into
the country during his trip to the United States. The Korea
Composite Stock Price Index rose 4.35 points, or 1.2 percent, to
345.88.
	   JAKARTA: Share prices closed lower. The Composite Index slipped
0.097 point to 409.419.
</TEXT>
