<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Outspoken Spokesman </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Germany's outspoken government spokesman regrets
</HEADLINE>
`misunderstandings' &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Chancellor Helmut Kohl stuck by his
controversial government spokesman on Monday, even as the new
appointee promised to watch his words more carefully.
	   In office less than two weeks, Otto Hauser came under fire last
week after warning eastern Germans in a June 3 newspaper interview
that continuing to vote for former communists was ``over-straining
the solidarity of the west Germans.''
	   Coming just months before a federal election, his words were
widely interpreted as implying that continued financial support for
rebuilding the east was dependent on how east Germans voted.
	   Opposition politicians and even some members of Kohl's ruling
coalition criticized the comments as inappropriate for a government
spokesman.
	   Hauser, a conservative member of parliament and former
journalist, insisted he was expressing a widely held opinion in the
west and not government policy _ a position that Kohl has backed.
	   But in a television interview Sunday, Hauser said he regretted
the misunderstandings and would ``stick to the rules'' in the
future and ``concentrate on presenting government policies.''
	   After a meeting of party leaders Monday, Kohl said again he was
``in complete agreement'' with Hauser's remarks.
	   The chairman of the Bonn press corps, Heinz Schweden, said after
meeting with Hauser on Monday that his weekend remarks had helped
clear the air. But he said Hauser would continue to have problems
if he tried to constantly switch hats when making statements.
	   ``He has to see that he will always be taken as the government
spokesman when he says something,'' Schweden said.
	   Kohl dismissed his former spokesman, Peter Hausmann, last month
after more than three years on the job. He gave no reason, but
apparently blamed Hausmann in part for the government's poor
standing in the polls.
 &UR; (pfg-cb-aet)
</TEXT>
