<SLUG> BC-Russia-Teachers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Communists claim unpaid teachers take local leader hostage
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's Communist Party claimed Monday that a
group of Siberian teachers was holding a local government leader
hostage to demand overdue wages, but police said they had no
information about such an incident.
	   Russian media often report cases of ``hostage-taking'' by unpaid
workers, but the incidents rarely involve violence. Sometimes the
supposed hostages stay with their captors voluntarily, even after
they are told they are free to leave.
	   A statement released by parliament's Communist faction said
teachers from 12 out of 14 schools in the Maiminsky region of
Russia's republic of Altai seized the regional leader in his office
on Monday and were demanding three months of back wages in return
for his release.
	   A spokesman for Russia's Interior Ministry, Yevgeny Ryabtsev,
said he had no information to corroborate the report.
	   Officials in Altai, some 3,500 kilometers (2,000 miles) and four
times zones away from Moscow, could not be reached for comment
Monday afternoon.
