<HEADLINE>
Eurovision winner pleads innocent to disorderly conduct charge
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel's transsexual pop diva Dana
International, winner of this year's Eurovision song contest,
pleaded innocent Monday to charges that she attacked a spectator
and a waitress at a performance two years ago.
	   The singer is accused of throwing a bottle of mineral water at a
spectator's head and attacking a waitress during a November 1995
performance, Israel's Army Radio said.
	   The singer is charged with disorderly conduct in Magistrate's
Court in Rehovot, south of Tel Aviv. Her next hearing will be in
about six months, according to court spokesman Moshe Gorali.
	   Dana International, who was known as Yaron Cohen until
undergoing a sex change operation five years ago, won the 25-nation
Eurovision song contest last month with the song ``Diva.''
	   The singer's selection as Israel's representative was denounced
by Orthodox leaders, who called her a disgrace to the Jewish state.
