<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jewish settlers move into Arab neighborhood; Palestinians protest
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. Recasts, trims.
 &UR; By SAMAR ASSAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ In what Palestinians called a fresh threat to
the already tattered peace process, Jewish settlers took over a
pair of buildings in Arab east Jerusalem on Monday, clashing with
Palestinians as they did so.
	   At least two people were hurt in the melee, including Faisal
Husseini, the top Palestinian official in Jerusalem, who was
slightly injured when he was hit in the head by a rock.
	   The clash in the Silwan neighborhood was the latest in an
escalating series of confrontations in Jerusalem's eastern sector.
Each side accuses the other of trying to grab land in the bitterly
contested city.
	   Moving in before dawn, the settlers took over five apartments in
two buildings, plus a plot of land. They trucked in furniture,
strung barbed wire, and hung Israeli flags.
	   ``I see things getting worse,'' said Husseini, who has called
for mass street protests by Palestinians to block such settlement
activity. ``This provocation is pushing the situation to the edge
of disaster.''
	   About 20 activists from the Israeli group Peace Now staged a
protest at the site. Police dragged them away after they ignored
orders to disperse.
	   The 15 settlers were from the Elad group, which claims it
purchased the homes legally. Settler leader Yehuda Mali said Jews
had a biblical claim to the area, overlooking the Kidron Valley
just outside the Old City walls.
	   ``It was the home of King David, here he wrote the Psalms, and
here Jews are not allowed to live?'' he said.
	   Police and soldiers tried to keep the two sides apart, but
repeated shoving and shouting matches broke out. In one skirmish,
settlers kicked Arabs who tried to block them from entering one of
the buildings.
	   ``I will surrender my life before I surrender my house!''
shouted Fatima Karaeen, 62, who said she has papers showing one of
the houses belongs to her Arab family. ``The cowards!''
	   The makeup of Jerusalem's neighborhoods is an explosive issue,
with Palestinians trying to block what they say are illegal
encroachments by Jewish settlers. Both sides are constantly
jockeying for position pending negotiations on the city's final
status.
	   The Palestinians claim east Jerusalem, which Israel captured in
the 1967 Mideast War, as capital of a future state. Israel insists
the city must remain undivided under Israeli sovereignty.
	   Settlers have been stepping up activity in recent weeks in
Jerusalem.
	   Last month, clashes broke out after the settler group Ataret
Cohanim set up sheds in the Old City near Herod's Gate. Those sheds
were dismantled, but the settlers were allowed to stay on as guards
and volunteers in an archeological dig that got under way on
Monday.
	   The latest confrontation comes at a delicate moment in efforts
to restart the stalled peace process. Israel's army radio said an
American plan for an Israeli troop pullback from the West Bank will
likely to brought to the Cabinet for a vote before the end of the
week.
	   Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert told army radio the settler move to
Silwan was legal.
	   ``I don't wake up in the morning and ask myself what will please
the Palestinians,'' he said. ``People can buy wherever they want.''
	   But opposition Israeli lawmaker Yossi Beilin called the
settlers' actions a provocation.
	   ``It does all it can to make the relationship between Jews and
Arabs more tense in Jerusalem and elsewhere,'' he said.
 &UR; (pvs-lk)
</TEXT>
