<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-War Crimes, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Alleged Bosnian Croat paramilitary chief goes on U.N. trial
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. ADDS details from trial; RECASTS throughout; ADDS photo
numbers. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos AMS102-104 &QL; 
 &UR; By MIKE CORDER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ An alleged Bosnian Croat
paramilitary commander stood and watched as one of his troops
repeatedly raped a Muslim woman, prosecutors claimed Monday as his
war crimes trial began.
	   The suspected commander, Anto Furundzija, 28, has pleaded
innocent to two war crimes charges relating to his alleged
involvement in the May 1993 rapes.
	   Dressed in a dark suit, Furundzija looked calm as his trial
opened before the Yugoslav war crimes tribunal. He faces a maximum
life sentence if convicted.
	   Although rape has been considered a war crime in other cases
before the U.N. court, Furundzija's trial is the first to deal
specifically with sexual assault inflicted during an interrogation.
	   The alleged rapist, identified Monday by the names Cicko and
Bralo, has not been arrested. Furundzija was arrested in December
in the central Bosnian town of Vitez, near where his alleged
offenses were committed.
	   Furundzija allegedly was interrogating the victim, identified as
``Witness A,'' as she was raped at the headquarters of his unit,
called ``The Jokers.''
	   The Jokers allegedly took part in a violent campaign by Bosnian
Croat forces to drive Muslims out of the central Bosnian Lasva
River Valley in 1993.
	   ``Shortly after the interrogation started the other member of
The Jokers forced her to undress and began what turned out to be a
prolonged series of physical, mental and serious sexual abuses
including repeated rapes,'' prosecutor Michael Blaxill charged in
his opening statement.
	   By failing to stop the rapes, Furundzija became a ``direct
perpetrator committing the crimes of torture and outrages upon
personal dignity,'' Blaxill added.
	   Defense attorney Luka Misetic said the prosecution's case was
built on faulty recollections of the victim.
	   ``Her testimony will not convince you beyond a reasonable doubt
that Anto Furundzija is guilty as charged, and, make no mistake,
the prosecution's entire case is based on her testimony,'' Misetic
said.
	   The trial, the sixth to begin at the tribunal, could be its
quickest. Prosecutors will only call five witnesses _ including the
alleged victim. The first witness, a Muslim community leader from
Vitez, testified Monday about the background of the conflict.
	   Although Furundzija is a minor figure from the 3 1/2-year
Bosnian conflict, prosecutors at the U.N. court are keen to
establish case law involving sexual assaults as a war crime.
	   Before the trial began, judges publicized a stinging rebuke of
prosecutors in the case, accusing them of ``a consistent pattern of
noncompliance with the orders of the trial chamber.''
	   Set up in 1993, the war crimes tribunal has indicted 60 suspects
and has 27 in custody. Its most-wanted suspects, former Bosnian
Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and his wartime military chief, Gen.
Ratko Mladic, remain at large.
	   (mc/bk)
</TEXT>
