<SLUG> BC-Czech-Strike </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
State employees stage warning strike
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) _ Hundreds of thousands of
government workers staged a brief warning strike Monday after the
government refused to increase their wages.
	   Nearly 800,000 state employees abandoned their posts in state
and municipal offices for an hour starting at 9 a.m. (0700GMT),
demanding a 20 percent pay increase.
	   Pay negotiations between the government and 10 trade unions
representing state workers failed to reach an agreement last month.
	   During the strike, teachers organized debates with students
instead of teaching and road workers blocked roadways at dozens of
points. Nearly a dozen of the country's border crossings also
closed temporarily, the CTK news agency said.
	   Alena Vondrova, a spokeswoman for the trade unions, warned the
public could expect more strikes if their demands are ignored, CTK
said. She dismissed politicians' claims that the state does not
have the funds needed to satisfy the protesters.
	   ``The state just must find the money,'' Vondrova said.
	   On average, state employees in the Czech Republic earn about
1,500 koruna (dlrs 50) less than the average monthly salary of
10,438 koruna (dlrs 317).
	   The strike came less than two weeks before early parliamentary
elections scheduled for June 19-20.
	   (nr/me/scl)
</TEXT>
