<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Air France-Strike, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Air France pilots' strike enters second week
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with smaller unions rejecting proposal for special
flights. ADDS Air France to hold extraordinary meeting.
 &UR; By DEBORAH SEWARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Striking Air France pilots have offered to work for
free to fly foreign fans to the World Cup, but their walkout showed
no sign of ending Monday as it entered its second week.
	   The unexpected gesture came as the conflict appeared to harden
Sunday night, with Air France management expressing exasperation
with the pilots who walked off the job June 1.
	   No new talks were in sight, and Air France said the strike
already had cost 1 billion francs (dlrs 166 million).
	   France's flagship carrier says it will take three days for
service to return to normal once the strike ends, meaning the
walkout was sure to disrupt the World Cup, which begins Wednesday.
	   Christian Paris, spokesman for the SNPL, the main pilots' union,
proposed that Air France organize special flights for foreign World
Cup ticket holders and said the pilots would work without pay so
the fans would not miss the soccer championship.
	   Air France said it would study the measure, but three smaller
pilot unions on Monday rejected the proposal, saying they would
advise members not to collaborate.
	   Bernard Stasi, a government mediator in the talks, said the
proposal was ``unacceptable.''
	   ``This is a party which France is offering for the world.
Anything that might spoil the party would be a crime by France,''
he added in an interview with Europe-1 radio network on Monday.
	   Despite the goodwill gesture, the conflict appeared deadlocked.
	   Pierre-Henri Gourgeon, the director general of Air France, said
the airline had ``exhausted its capacity of understanding with
regard to the pilots.''
	   Air France said Monday it would hold an extraordinary meeting
later this week _ once the World Cup is underway _ to discuss the
impasse.
	   Meanwhile, the company sought to contain the strike by meeting
with 19 unions representing other airline workers who feel left out
of salary talks between Air France and the pilots.
	   Both sides are under pressure to end the strike from the
government, which has offered to intervene but has not put forward
concrete proposals.
	   Labor Minister Martine Aubry said the negotiations could go down
to the wire.
	   ``I believe in negotiation. Even if there are just a few minutes
left to talk, I'm convinced an agreement can be reached,'' she said
in an interview with France 3 television channel.
	   Rene Monory, president of the French Senate, said Sunday the
pilots were giving the country a ``lamentable image.''
	   Talks between Air France and the pilots were suspended Saturday
after the pilots walked out of negotiations.
	   The strike has inconvenienced thousands, including foreigners
fleeing fighting in Eritrea.
	   The pilots are protesting planned pay cuts of 500 million francs
(dlrs 83 million) Air France says are needed to modernize the
company.
	   Obstacles to an agreement are proposed salary reductions and a
plan to give pilots stock in exchange for the pay cut, as well as a
two-tier pay scale in which younger pilots earn less.
	   Only about 25 percent of Air France's flights were expected to
take off Monday.
	   Trains were running on schedule Monday after strikes disrupted
service this weekend. Train conductors have threatened a walkout
Wednesday.
	   (dgs-ip)
</TEXT>
