<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Slovakia-Nuclear,0393 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Slovaks start up controversial nuclear plant
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRATISLAVA, Slovakia (AP) _ Despite hefty protest from
anti-nuclear campaigners, Slovakia on Monday started up its
controversial nuclear power plant at Mochovce.
	   The plant is just 120 kilometers (72 miles) east of Austria,
which has campaigned strongly against its activation, arguing that
certain features of the heavy water pressure reactor make it
unsafe. Austria is the only country in the world to have built a
nuclear power plant, then voted in 1978 by referendum against
putting it online or having nuclear power.
	   Mochovce is a 440 MW Soviet-designed plant subsequently equipped
with Western technology.
	   Plant spokesman Rastislav Petrech said it received a go-ahead
from the Slovak nuclear authority on Sunday to activate its nuclear
fuel rods, as the authority deemed the plant ``met all the safety
and technical conditions.''
	   Last month, a team of 22 international experts inspected the
plant and noted safety changes made at the station, but also
complained that the company operating it failed to release
necessary documents.
	   Wolfgang Kromp, the Austrian head of that international team,
told the Austria Press Agency on Monday that he regretted that
Slovakia had gone ahead at Mohovce, but emphasized ``there is
currently no risk'' involved.
	   Austria is worried that a Chernobyl-type disaster at Mochovce _
or other nuclear plants in neighboring Slovakia and the Czech
Republic _ affect hundreds of thousands of its citizens.
	   Austria is particularly worried that the Czech-produced pressure
vessel made of special steel is safe for only the first five years,
and that nuclear reaction will weaken its quality.
	   Slovak officials angrily dismiss all the Austrian criticism.
	   ``Our plant is perfectly safe. We wouldn't be jepardizing the
lives of our families, would we?'' Petrech told The Associated
Press. ``The Austrians could never say of any nuclear power plant
that it was safe.''
	   Fuel will be fully activated, and the the plant's No. 1 reactor
will become critical this month, ``which means Slovakia will have
another reliable, effective and ecologically clean source of
electric energy for another 30 years,'' according to a press
release quoting Tibor Mikus, the director of Slovakia's electricity
company. 	   
</TEXT>
