w2791 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia     06-08 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thousands take part in protests in Indonesia; Suharto turns 77
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: INCORPORATES material from Indonesia-Political Prisoners,
Indonesia-Labor Protest, Indonesia-Suharto Birthday &QL; 
 &UR; By GEOFF SPENCER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Despite promises of sweeping reforms
by Indonesia's new president, more than 20,000 people took to the
streets in separate protests in two cities Monday.
	   As many as 10,000 striking workers scuffled with and threw rocks
at anti-riot police when they staged a 10-kilometer (6-mile) march
through the streets of Indonesia's second city of Surabaya.
	   On the tourist island of Bali, about 10,000 students and others
marched peacefully to the local legislature, demanding the
resignation of the provincial governor and other politicians
accused of corruption and collusion.
	   Pressure to speed up reforms continues to mount against
President B.J. Habibie despite his plan to hold elections in 1999
and to stage a general inquiry into graft and other misdeeds
committed during the 32-year rule of former President Suharto, who
stepped down last month.
	   The government said Habibie planned to release 16 more political
prisoners on Thursday, bringing to 20 the number fred since Suharto
quit on May 21.
	   Suharto, meanwhile, celebrated a lonely 77th birthday on Monday.
	   The Jakarta Post newspaper quoted an unidentified Suharto aide
as saying few of his friends and associates have visited him at his
home in central Jakarta since he was forced to quit. Formerly
lucrative ties to the former president are now seen as a liability.
	   Only a pet parrot, long ago trained to say, ``Good Morning
(Mister) President,'' still calls him by his former title, the Post
said.
	   Presidential security guards still stand watch over his home.
But their numbers are gradually being reduced, and they no longer
salute him, the aide was quoted as saying.
	   Not even Habibie has visited Suharto, though the two men are
longtime friends and allies.
	   The Post said Suharto is happy to a private citizen and spends
his days reading newspapers, full of accusations against him,
watching television and being with his grandchildren.
	   On the rare occasions that he leaves his house, Suharto's car
must stop at red lights _ not like the old days, when the
presidential limousine sped through the streets of Jakarta under
police escort.
	   In Surabaya, about 650 kilometers (400 miles) east of Jakarta,
violence broke out when a line of police blocked the path of
thousands of striking workers as they approached the East Java's
provincial parliament building.
	   Witnesses and police said at least five police and three
protesters were hospitalized. Some were bleeding after being beaten
with sticks or being hit with rocks.
	   The protest was the biggest since Habibie last week relaxed
tight restrictions on labor unions and signed an International
Labor Organization convention on respect for workers' rights.
	   Police later let the crowd pass and stage a noisy rally outside
the legislature.
	   The workers, employees of a household appliance manufacturer,
went on strike last Tuesday demanding higher salaries and better
conditions as the effects of Indonesia's worst economic crisis in
30 years begins to bite.
	   Indonesia is now suffering runaway inflation and mass
unemployment as the economic situation worsens.
</TEXT>
