r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Croatia-Tourism     06-08 0313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Croatia-Tourism </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Czechs and Slovaks to give up favorite holiday destination
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) _ A cold reception last season and economic
recession will cut tourist arrivals from Slovakia and the Czech
Republic by as much as 40 percent, tour operators said Monday.
	   Last summer, more than 579,000 Czechs and over 153,000 Slovaks
flocked to the shores of the Croatian Adriatic, their most popular
holiday spot also in the Communist era.
	   However, the Croatian Tourist Association, has already
registered a 30-40 percent drop in bookings as the peak season
approaches, compared with the same time last year.
	   Atlas, one of the prime tourist agencies, has canceled charter
flights to the ancient resort town of Dubrovnik, considered
Croatia's tourist jewel.
	   Other agencies have replaced larger airplanes with smaller ones
to reduce costs and cater for fallen demand.
	   Tihomir Studko, a public relations officer of the Tourist
Agency, attributed the drop to economic reforms in both Slovakia
and the Czech Republic, which he said have tightened family
budgets.
	   But he also said measures such as a new ban on food imports
worth more than 90 German marks (dlrs 50) may also have discouraged
guests.
	   Money-strapped Czech and Slovak tourists were the target of
stares and sour jokes last summer, as they brought their food for
the entire trip rather than pay significantly more in Croatia.
	   Tourists from former socialist countries are usually frowned
upon by Croats for their weaker spending power, unlike their richer
western neighbors Germany, Austria and Italy, for whom many are
prepared to roll out the red carpet.
	   Tour operators are hoping for a strong rise in arrivals from
west European countries, who avoided Croatia's pristine coastline
and islands during the precarious war years.
	   (eb/as)
</TEXT>
