<DATE_TIME> 06/08/1998 08:16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2796 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OAU-Eritrea-Ethiopia 2ndLd-Writethru   06-08 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OAU-Eritrea-Ethiopia, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Threat of war muffles OAU's message of peace
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATES with Ethiopia's foreign minister
accusing Eritrea of provoking war. Seyoum is correct on second
reference. ADDS photos numbers. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos ASM104,120,123 &QL; 
 &UR; By GLENN McKENZIE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   OUAGADOUGOU, Burkina Faso (AP) _ Ethiopia's foreign minister
launched a diplomatic assault Monday on neighboring Eritrea,
accusing it of provoking war by deploying forces into disputed
territory along their common border.
	   ``The first thing to be done is for Eritrea to withdraw its
troops and return to the status quo,'' Ethiopian Foreign Minister
Seyoum Meslin said. Eritrea is ``imposing war on Ethiopia by
occupying certain territories.''
	   Seyoum made the comments in Burkina Faso's capital of
Ouagadougou on the opening day of a pan-African heads of state
summit.
	   Ethiopian warplanes bombed Eritrean targets over the weekend in
retaliation for what it called a violation of existing border
agreements.
	   The summit touted as a forum for peace was focusing instead on
the potential for war between Ethiopia and Eritrea.
	   Amid heavy security African leaders were gathering in Burkina
Faso's capital of Ouagadougou for the Organization of African Unity
summit.
	   Others, including South Africa's President Nelson Mandela were
expected later Monday for the three-day summit.
	   ``The continent received as a shock and with concern the news of
the crisis,'' OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim said Monday
of the conflict in the Horn of Africa. ``This unfortunate
development constitutes a severe setback to our efforts at forging
peace, security and stability.''
	   OAU talks quickly shifted from developing peace to avoiding war.
On Saturday, OAU foreign ministers broke from their scheduled talks
and urgently appealed for Ethiopia and Eritrea to adopt a peace
plan.
	   ``The Council of Ministers appeals to the two parties to put an
end to all hostilities,'' their statement said.
	   South Africa's Mandela and the presidents of Djibouti, Uganda
and Kenya, called Eritrea's leaders over the weekend to encourage a
negotiated settlement.
	   Eritrea's President Isaias Afwerki, who earlier accused Ethiopia
of declaring war, dispatched his foreign minister, Haile Woldensae,
to Burkina Faso. Ethiopia's Seyoum was representing President Meles
Zenawi.
	   The OAU has had little impact on the border clash since it began
on May 6.
	   Diplomats in Burkina Faso said summit delegates plan to draft a
resolution on the conflict after making recommendations to their
leaders over the weekend.
	   Although host Burkina Faso have dubbed the event a ``summit for
change,'' so far the OAU has done little more than call for an end
to hostilities and offer support for a U.S.-Rwandan peace proposal.
	   OAU Assistant Secretary-General Pascal Gayama told journalists
that the organization would work closely with Rwandan and U.S.
mediators.
	   Other African conflict zones such as Sudan, where southern
animist rebels are fighting a protracted guerrilla war against the
northern Muslim government, are not expected to figure prominently
at the summit.
	   In addition to African heads of state, Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat is also attending.
	   There was much speculation about whether Libyan leader Moammar
Gadhafi, who is also trying to broker a peace accord between
Ethiopia and Eritrea, would attend the OAU summit.
 &UR; (gam/bo/ids) 	   
</TEXT>
