<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Heat Wave,0188 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Heat wave kills more than 2,500 in India
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ India's worst heat wave in the past 50
years has killed more than 2,500 people in the past month, Press
Trust of India news agency said Monday.
	   In the worst-affected eastern coastal region of Orissa, where
temperatures soared as high as 47 Celsius (116 Fahrenheit) last
week, PTI reported 97 deaths Sunday. A total of 1,131 people have
died from the heat since May 12.
	   The southern state of Andhra Pradesh reported 943 deaths, PTI
said. Other deaths have been recorded mainly in the northern states
of Uttar Pradesh and Bihar.
	   Meantime, the seasonal monsoon rains have hit the coast of
southern India, bringing some respite. The rains will take another
month and a half to reach the plains of northern India that have
been hard hit by the heat wave.
	   Pre-monsoon rains have started bringing down the temperatures.
Dust storms accompanied by light showers over the weekend brought
the mercury down from a peak of 46.5 Celsius (115 Fahrenheit) to 41
Celsius (105 Fahrenheit) in New Delhi, the Indian capital. 	   
</TEXT>
