r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-AIDS     06-08 0256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-AIDS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Number of registered HIV cases in Russia tops 8,100
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ AIDS is spreading rapidly in Russia, with a total
of 8,138 people registered as testing positive for HIV, officials
said Monday.
	   According to figures announced by the Health Ministry, the
number includes 367 children, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
HIV cases have been registered in 85 of Russia's 89 regions, the
ministry said.
	   Some 4,300 of new HIV cases were registered in Russia last year
_ a three-fold increase from the year before, it said.
	   Russian officials have repeatedly warned that the actual number
of HIV cases may be as much as 10 times higher. Russia still lacks
comprehensive diagnostic and treatment programs.
	   HIV and AIDS came to Russia late, but are quickly making up for
lost time. Officials say more than 90 percent of people testing
positive for HIV are intravenous drug users who have caught the
virus through infected syringes.
	   The vast plurality of HIV cases has been registered in Russia's
small Baltic enclave of Kaliningrad, whose 400,000 residents
account for a disproportionate 2,705 cases of HIV.
	   The next highest concentration is in the southern region of
Krasnodar, with 1,269 cases, ITAR-Tass said. Moscow has 823
registered HIV cases, it said.
	   Russia, which has no federal anti-AIDS program, received dlrs
170,000 in assistance from the United Nations AIDS program this
year to improve prevention, diagnosis and treatment, ITAR-Tass
said.
	   (ad/mr)
</TEXT>
