<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Namibia-German-Slaying </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German man being held in death of wife, whose remains were cooked
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) _ A German man was being held without
bail on a murder charge Monday after his wife's cooked bones and
skull were found in the ceiling of their house over the weekend.
	   Thoman Adolf Florin, 36, who is believed to be from the Bonn
area, had been making hurried arrangements to return to Germany
with his two children, aged 3 and 5, and already had bought the
plane tickets when he was arrested, police said.
	   An unidentified friend of Monica Florin, 32, had told police she
was missing. They found nothing amiss, said police Inspector
Hieronymus Goraseb.
	   ``But (Mrs. Florin's) friend went back to the house and noticed
something wet in the ceiling,'' Goraseb said. ``The police then
found some bones and her skull. Everything had been cooked.''
	   Most of the body had been disposed of in the sea, Goraseb said,
adding it was unclear why the remains had been cooked.
	   The children have returned to Germany where relatives plan to
care for them, authorities said.
	   Florin had lived in this southwest African country for some
time, operating a hotel and a pig farm.
	   (jg-aos)
</TEXT>
