<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Dance Controversy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Orthodox offended by dance featuring seminudity, prayer shawls
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Orthodox Jews on Monday denounced modern
dancers who performed clad only in prayer shawls during a cultural
festival in Jerusalem.
	   It was the latest dispute involving art and culture between the
country's secular majority and ultra-religious minority.
	   Earlier this year, Israel's premier modern dance troupe,
Batsheva, bowed out performing at the country's 50th anniversary
celebrations rather than alter a seminude dance number, as
religious lawmakers demanded.
	   The prayer shawl performance, staged over the weekend by a
troupe from central Israel, was meant as a protest against
religious coercion, choreographer Ido Tadmor told the Maariv
newspaper.
	   Shlomo Benizri, a lawmaker from an ultra-religious party, said
the dance was a disgrace.
	   ``It's people taking something holy and dancing with it in a
shameful way,'' Benizri told The Associated Press. ``It's against
Judaism.''
	   The festival's director of public relations, Ora Lapidot, said
the dance provoked no protest from the audience, and in fact won
loud applause.
