<HEADER>
w2823 &Cx1f; wstm-
b s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-FIFAPre 2ndAdd   06-08 0163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-FIFA President, 2nd Add,0164 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARIS: and privately.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   After Johansson's concession, Blatter and Havelange appeared
before the FIFA Congress. Havelange called Johansson ``a
gentleman.''
	   Johansson's strength was in Europe and Africa, while Blatter's
strongholds were Asia and the Americas.
	   Blatter, who formally joined the race just 2 1-2 months ago, and
Johansson, the sole candidate for more than a year before that,
both had said in recent days that they were confident of victory.
	   Each had surrounded himself with soccer stars of the past, with
Pele supporting Havelange and Michel Platini backing Blatter. Each
of those endorsements was in keeping with the personal nature of
the campaign _ Pele has had a long-running feud with Havelange, his
Brazilian countryman, while Platini is co-chairman of the French
World Cup and has been reluctant to share any stage with Johansson.
	    &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
