<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bankers-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0618 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bank says world economic prospects looking up, but advises caution
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS, UPDATES with further detail from report. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BASEL, Switzerland (AP) _ The worst economic turmoil in Asia may
be over and prospects for growth in the rest of the world are
looking positive, but there are still problems, a central bankers
report said Monday.
	   Long-running economic expansion in the United States and Britain
is set to continue, says the annual report of the Basel-based Bank
for International Settlements, known as the central banker's
central bank.
	   Serious contagion of the Asian crisis to other parts of the
world has so far been avoided and the worst may be at an end in
Asia itself, according to the 199-page study.
	   ``Congratulations on this generally happy state of affairs might
seem in order, yet central bankers should not be complacent,''
Alfons Verplaetse, chairman of BIS' board of directors and
Belgium's national bank governor, said at the BIS' annual meeting.
	   Rekindling growth in another of the world's major economies,
Japan, ``will not be easy'' and the full impact of the Asian crisis
on Europe has still to be assessed, the report says.
	   In addition, tightening labor markets, worsening trade balances
and booming prices for financial assets show inflationary risks are
rising.
	   ``No-one should be under any illusions as to the magnitude of
the problems still to be faced and the potential difficulties along
the way,'' says the study.
	   Growth rates in most industrial countries have either remained
at high levels or are starting to build significant momentum, said
Verplaetse.
	   A ``new era'' of productivity and profit growth is discernible
in recent U.S. economic statistics, the report notes. A wave of
restructuring in Europe will lead to the same result.
	   Preparations for the transition in Europe to the new single
currency, the Euro, have been smooth, Verplaetse said. Structural
reforms and more disciplined policies have generated solid growth
in Latin America, many Eastern European countries and
``significant'' parts of Africa.
	   Forecasts by the International Monetary Fund and the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development indicate the
United States will bear most of the burden resulting from an
expected improvement in Asian trade deficits, pushing the current
account deficit as a proportion of gross domestic product to
near-record levels, the report says.
	   However, there is a danger markets will lose patience with the
accumulation of U.S. external debt and drive the dollar sharply
lower.
	   A further danger, stemming from the strong dollar, is a possible
movement to protectionist policies in the United States.
	   ``While the robust economy has kept such sentiments below the
surface, a marked slowing of growth could easily change this
situation,'' says the study.
	   In Asia's emerging markets, politically committed responses to
the International Monetary Fund's recommended financial reforms
would do more to revive growth prospects ``than anything else,''
the study says.
	   The BIS urged an early, transparent and politically neutral
restructuring of domestic banking systems to raise liquidity in
many Asian economies.
	   Japan's banking system needs to be restructured and the economy
stimulated through permanent tax cuts, it said.
	   Economic growth, financial deregulation and low inflation should
be accompanied by vigorous but careful market opening, the study
recommends.
	   Financial systems everywhere should be strengthened to allow
them to face up to the ``larger shocks'' likely to be created in
freer markets. 	   
</TEXT>
