<SLUG> BC-Israel-Bridge Collapse </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Defense attorney charges state with shirking responsibility
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) _ The state's role in the collapse of a
footbridge that killed four Australian athletes should be
investigated, an attorney for the bridge's engineer said Monday.
	   ``We maintain that the state is shaking off responsibility for
this disaster,'' Avraham Landstein told The Associated Press
following a court hearing.
	   Landstein is defending the bridge's engineer, Micha Bar-Ilan,
who is among five people charged with negligence in the July 14
collapse during the opening ceremony of the Maccabiah Games.
	   About 100 Australian athletes were on the footbridge when it
buckled, plunging the athletes into a narrow river below, injuring
dozens. Four Australians died in the aftermath.
	   Police inspector Yonatan Silberman testified Monday that police
were not prepared for such an accident.
	   ``We were prepared for the event of an explosion or a similar
disaster, but no one expected something like this to happen,''
Silberman said.
	   Pathologist Yehuda Hiss, testifying on the cause of death of
Yettie Benis, blamed the chemical-laden polluted water she
swallowed.
	   The engineer, along with two contractors, the director of the
event, and the chairman of the Maccabiah organizing committee, have
been charged with negligent homicide and building without proper
permits.
	   They face up to three years in prison if convicted.
