<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Elections, 1st Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Beirut votes for religious harmony; Amal and Hezbollah split
</HEADLINE>
Shiites
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Berri's comments, new figures subs 7th-8th grafs
with new 5 grafs, pickup 9th graf pvs. &QL; 
 &UR; By SAM F. GHATTAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Muslims and Christians endorsed religious
harmony in Beirut and militant Shiite Muslims made major inroads in
south Lebanon in municipal elections held after a break of 35
years, preliminary results showed Monday.
	   With Beirut having shifted to a Sunni Muslim majority city since
the last elections, many feared only Muslim candidates would win in
Sunday vote, driving Christians out of local politics in Lebanon's
largest city.
	   But a half-Christian, half-Muslim ticket backed by Prime
Minister Rafik Hariri swept to victory for the 24-member city
council, the results showed.
	   Hariri and other moderate Sunnis had campaigned feverishly to
urge a Muslim vote for Christians so that the delicate sectarian
balance could be maintained in the city, as it is in senior
government posts in this country of 18 religious sects.
	   Smelling victory from early returns, Hariri told the leading
newspaper An-Nahar overnight that national consensus has been
preserved, showing that the Lebanese have ``abandoned the logic of
war and upheld democracy.''
	   In the south, the Iranian-backed Hezbollah that is the major
guerrilla group fighting Israel scored major gains, chipping away
at the power base of the pro-Syrian Amal faction of Parliament
Speaker Nabih Berri.
	   Berri, in a news conference Monday, maintained that Amal alone
stood up against a coalition of Shiite militants, Communists,
leftist nationalists and traditional right-wing politicians.
	   He estimated that Amal won 51 of 75 wholly Shiite towns, tied
with Hezbollah in five others and took control of 22 mixed
Christian-Shiite towns.
	   The prize win for Amal was in the southern city of Tyre.
	   Preliminary results estimated Hezbollah won 18 municipalities, a
further signal that it has succeeded in transforming itself from a
guerrilla force into a populist movement.
	   Berri confirmed the Hezbollah gains, including the capture of
the teeming market town of Nabatiyeh.
 &UR; Municipal elections, 9th graf pvs
