<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Armenia-France-Brandy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
French Pernod-Ricard wins bid for Yerevan brandy distillery
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   YEREVAN, Armenia (AP) _ France's Pernod-Ricard group will buy
the Armenian distillery whose brandy was said to be Winston
Churchill's favorite, officials said Monday.
	   Pernod-Ricard has agreed to pay dlrs 30 million for the Yerevan
Cognac Distillery and to invest 30 million francs (dlrs 5 million)
in developing vineyards in the former Soviet republic, said Vagram
Avanesian, Armenia's minister for economic reforms.
	   The government and Pernod-Ricard are discussing distribution of
profits and expect to formally sign an agreement next week,
Avanesian said at a news conference.
	   The distillery was established in 1897 by Russian wine merchant
Nikolai Shustov.
	   Distillery officials say that Josef Stalin presented Churchill
with a bottle of its 10-year-old, 100 proof brandy during the 1943
Tehran conference and that it remained the favorite of the British
wartime leader until his death.
	   Since Soviet times, Armenian brandy has been called cognac,
drawing angry protests from France, which insisted its producers
have exclusive use of the term. Pernod-Ricard agreed that the
brandy will be called Armenian Cognac or Armenian Brandy in
Armenian, English and Russia.
	   Pernod-Ricard also agreed to continue production of existing
brands of brandy, maintain production at no lower than 4.25 million
liters (1.1 million gallons) a year, use only local raw materials
and bottle the brandy in Armenia.
	   The sale has still drawn criticism from some lawmakers and
others who argued the distillery was being sold at a giveaway
price.
	   Seagram Co. of Canada was among the losing bidders for the
distillery.
	   (str/vi/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
