<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-CompuServe </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bavarian prosecutors weighing appeal in CompuServe case
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MUNICH, Germany (AP) _ Bavarian prosecutors appealing the
conviction and sentence of the former chief of CompuServe Germany
said Monday they were waiting for the judge's written decision
before deciding how to proceed.
	   Prosecutors, who had reversed course and sought an acquittal for
Felix Somm at the end of his trial, filed their intention to appeal
the May 28 conviction last Wednesday with the state's highest
court.
	   Prosecutor Manfred Wick said Monday his office needed to review
the judge's written opinion, expected in the coming weeks, before
deciding whether they would challenge the verdict on points of law
or seek a new trial.
	   He said the appeal is being made independent from defense
efforts to have the verdict overturned. ``But we're striving for
the same result,'' he said.
	   In a much-criticized decision, Somm was convicted of complicity
in the distribution of illegal pornography in 13 cases by not
blocking access to such sites on the Internet for CompuServe
customers.
	   He was given a two-year suspended sentence and ordered to pay
100,000 marks (dlrs 57,000).
	   The case began more than two years ago, when Bavarian
prosecutors raided CompuServe offices in Munich. But by the end of
the trial, prosecutors agreed with the defense that there was no
technology available at the time that would have enabled CompuServe
to block illegal content.
	   Internet experts warned that the verdict would stifle
development of the multimedia industry in Germany if allowed to
stand.
 &UR; (pfg-cb)
</TEXT>
