<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Banks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore monetary authority outlines banking changes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LAURINDA KEYS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Singapore's banks will no longer hide reserves
and bad loans, will open to foreign competition and have more
liquidity, the head of the country's de facto central bank said
Monday.
	   Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong, who heads the Monetary
Authority of Singapore, said the first change, reducing banks'
minimum cash balance requirement from 6 percent to 3 percent, will
take effect next month.
	   Also in July, banks will be allowed to settle payments on
individual transactions during the day, using their cash balance,
to help ``avoid the liquidity risk inherent in deferred end-of-day
settlement,'' Lee told the Association of Banks in Singapore.
	   But Lee appeared to caution nervous currency traders when he
said the reduction in the minimum cash balance does not ``signal
any easing of monetary policy or credit conditions. The target of
monetary policy in Singapore is the exchange rate, not interest
rates or money supply.''
	   The two measures will increase liquidity and provide banks more
interest income, but to avoid the chance of any run on a Singapore
bank with insufficient funds, the Monetary Authority will impose
stricter cash balance requirements on banks with financial
difficulties.
	   In announcing the changes, Lee referred to the heavily depressed
bank stocks on the Singapore exchange.
	   ``An early rebound in bank profits is unlikely,'' he said, ``and
banks will make more provisions for regional exposures.''
	   The measures should provide some short-term relief to banks that
have been hit hard by non-performing loans in Indonesia and
elsewhere.
	   Lee acknowledged that lack of full information about such
exposure makes investors nervous and said, ``We will raise our bank
disclosure norms to international standards.''
	   He said the six major banks, with the Monetary Authority's
approval, have agreed to ``stop the current practice of maintaining
hidden reserves.''
	   They have agreed to ``disclose the market value of their
investments, which have largely been valued at book cost, and hence
contributed to their hidden reserves,'' Lee said. ``They should
also disclose the level of their non-performing loans, and past and
future provisions.''
	   Over the next five years, ``we will progressively open up the
financial sector to greater foreign competition,'' he said.
	   As a ``modest first step,'' the Singapore dollar resident loan
limit on offshore banks is being raised from 200 million to 300
million Singapore dollars (dlrs 117 million to dlrs 175 million).
</TEXT>
