<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Romania,0347 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Romanians train together behind locked gates
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By VIOREL URMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALBI, France (AP) _ Looking refreshed after a night's rest from
their trip to France, seeded Romanian trained Monday at the squad's
practice site behind closed doors, guarded by more than a dozen
uniformed French policemen.
	   With reporters climbing atop cars at a distance to look over a
concrete wall around the field, the players held 1 1-2 hours of
stretching, passing and running _ with and without the ball _ for
their first practice since arriving Sunday.
	   After the practice, coach Anghel Iordanescu gave players a
lengthy speech, apparently explaining tactical plans for the
opening game against Colombia on June 15 in Lyon.
	   That game is much on the Romanians' minds, and team officials
said it well might decide which team will advance to the second
round.
	   ``If we lose, we can say goodbye and return home,'' said one
team official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. Romania plays
in Group G, which also includes England and Tunisia.
	   All the 22 players took part in the practice and were declared
fit.
	   But one of the biggest problems for Iordanescu is defense, where
23-year-old Cristian Dulca of Rapid Bucharest, with only five caps,
looks likely to replace Atletico Madrid's Daniel Prodan as central
marking defender. Prodan, who is accompanying the team as an
onlooker, had surgery on his right knee last month and is still
recuperating.
	   Another problem for the Romanians is that they are short on
match practice. Iordanescu has complained that his team had been
refused the chance to attend a training camp in Switzerland and met
second-rate opponents in friendly matches, the last one against
Moldova last week.
	   ``The (Romanian Football) Federation has repeatedly told me they
do not have the necessary funds,'' he said.
	   The Romanians instead had to be content with a training camp in
the Carpathian Alps, north of Bucharest.
	   (urma-dm)
</TEXT>
