<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Layoffs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian government to layoff 231,100 state employees
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The Russian government announced plans Monday to
lay off 231,100 employees this year in an attempt to cut budget
spending and reduce the deficit.
	   Government officials told lawmakers that the layoffs _ which
represent 3.6 percent of government employees _ would save about
5.86 billion rubles (dlrs 953 million), the Interfax news agency
reported.
	   The government also said it would cut federal subsidies, reduce
utility supplies and lower credit limits to public organizations,
Interfax said.
	   Significant spending cuts were among the first measures
announced by Russia's new Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko after his
appointment this spring.
	   The Finance Ministry has said it plans to cut 62.4 billion
rubles (dlrs 10.2 billion) from this year's planned spending of
499.9 billion rubles (dlrs 82 billion).
	   Because of falling revenues, that would still widen budget
deficit, originally forecast at 133.9 billion rubles (dlrs 22
billion), by 1.5 billion rubles (dlrs 246 million).
	   (ad/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
