<BODY>
<SLUG> GOVT-WON'T-HINDER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Govt won't hinder long march, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Govt won't hinder long march, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina has rejected the propaganda of the
Leader of the Opposition that the government will foil the long
march towards the Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT).
	   Addressing a huge public meeting at the Paltan Maidan in the
city yesterday, the Prime Minister assured Begum Khaleda Zia that
neither the government nor the ruling party would create any
obstruction on the long march of the BNP.
	   ``Did I ever say that we will prevent the long march? Why should
I prevent her long march? I believe in democracy,'' Sheikh Hasina
said.
	   ``She (Khaleda Zia) is organising the long march to disturb the
peaceful environment in CHT and now-a-days tg march, it would be because of the
terrorists and infighting within the BNP.
	   The Awami League organised the meeting to mark the historic June
7. On this day in 1964, several persons, including Monu Mia, a
labour leader, were killed in police firing while observing a
hartal to realise the six-point demand, announced by the Father of
the Nation Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman.
	   The activists and supporters of the Awami League and its front
organisations gathered at the meeting venue chanting slogans. Sri
Lankan Foreign Minister Lakshman Kadirgamar also spoke at the
meeting. Twenty two leaders of the Awami League and its front
organisations addressing the meeting vowed to maintain peace in the
country at all costs. They said the peace-loving people of the
country would give a befitting reply to the BNP by holding a peace
procession against the so-called long march programme.
	   The meeting was addressed, among others, by Abdus Samad Azad,
Zillur Rahman, Sajeda Chowdhury, Abdur Razzak, Amir Hossain Amu,
Tofail Ahmed, Abdul Jalil, Mohammad Nasim, Begum Motia Chowdhury,
Muzaffar Hossain Paltu, Mohammad Hanif, Prof Abu Syed and Mofazzal
Hossain Chowdhury Maya.
	   In her presidential speech, the Prime Minister urged the people
to remain alert against the ill motives of the opposition BNP.
	   Referring to the restoration of peace in the CHT, Sheikh Hasina
said the peace accord was signed on December 2, 1997 following long
deliberations between the National Committee and the Jana Sanghati
Samity. The members of the Shanti Bahini returned to normal life
after surrendering their arms at Khagrachhari on February 10. She
said the people from all walks of life, including the tribal and
non-tribal men and women, attended the historic function on that
day ignoring the hartal called by the opposition.
	   ``The Leader of the Opposition does not accept the peace accord
and has been demanding its annulment,'' the Prime Minister said,
adding the scrapping of the peace accord would follow a war and
bloodshed there and the CHT would be again be isolated from the
rest of the country.
	   ``Does the Leader of the Opposition want to see there only dead
bodies, conflicts, terrorist activities and disturbances?'' Sheikh
Hasina asked and said: `` She (Khaleda) believes in disturbance...
The Oshanti Begum (mrs disturbance) does not feel well without
disturbance.''
	   About the movement launched by the Awami League during the BNP
regime, the Prime Minister said that at that time they had launched
the movement for the restoration of the people's right to vote and
against the corruption of the then ministers, MPs and the
plundering of national wealth by the family members of the then
Prime Minister Khaleda Zia.
	   Rejecting the propaganda of Begum Khaleda Zia that the
Bangladesh territory upto Feni would become part of India in
accordance with the CHT peace accord, Sheikh Hasina said that now
they were waiting to see whether Khaleda Zia would go to the CHT by
taking Indian visa or not.
	   Sheikh Hasina said the Leader of the Opposition and other
leaders of the BNP had been spreading lies continuously to confuse
the people and to create disturbances in the country. She urged the
people to remain alert about such 'liars'.
	   In this connection, the Prime Minister said the BNP leaders had
been trying to create troubles in the country by resorting to
conspiracies. In the past, they had made attempts to increase the
prices of rice and salt through conspiracies, she added.
	   During her 25 minute speech, the Prime Minister also dealt with
the issue of electricity and the measures taken by the government
to overcome the problem.
	   ``We are aware that you are suffering because of shortage of
electricity,'' Sheikh Hasina told the people expressing her
sympathies with them.
	   But, she said, the problem has become acute as the previous BNP
government did not install any power plant despite the growing
demand for electricity in the country. The of loadshedding and the
disaster in the power sector had started since the last year of the
BNP government.
	   The Prime Minister said the BNP government did not even carryout
the overhauling and maintenance of the existing power plants
although it claimed that Taka six to seven thousand crores had been
spent in the power sector. But the present government could not
locate where the money had been spent. ``The previous government
actually misappropriated the money and failed to increase the power
generation,'' she said.
	   Sheikh Hasina said her government had taken steps to increase
the generation of electricity in the private sector on an emergency
basis. It was not possible to solve the problem overnight as the
installation of power plant is time consuming.
	   Stressing the need for shopping pilferage and wastage of
electricity, the Prime Minister said her government took measures
to minimise the sufferings of the common people by closing shops
and offices during the peak hour demand for power. In this
connection, she sought the cooperation of the people from all walks
of life.
	   The Prime Minister said the government was taking steps to
increase the generation of electricity in accordance with the
future demand.
	   ``We are working hard to build the country on the basis of the
spirit of the liberation war,'' Sheikh Hasina said, adding: ``The
21st century's Bangladesh will become a prosperous Bangladesh. We
will turn Bangladesh into 'Sonar Bangla' (prosperous Bangladesh)
which was dreamt by the Father of the Nation, Bangabandhu Sheikh
Mujibur Rahman.''
	   
</TEXT>
