<BODY>
<SLUG> BANGLADESH-CANNOT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bangladesh cannot be another Sikkim says, Khaleda, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Bangladesh cannot be another Sikkim says, Khaleda, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   BNP chief Begum Khaleda Zia yesterday said that the long march
to the Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) would lay the foundation to
resist to conspiracies against the country's independence and
sovereignty.
	   Addressing a press conference at her Minto Road official
residence Begum Zia termed the Awami League government anti-state
and said that it had no right to continue in power any more. ``Time
has neared for it to be accountable to the people,'' she added.
	   In a seven-page written statement read out at the press
conference, the BNP chief said that the agreement on CHT was most
controversial and contrary to the Constitution and to the
fundamental rights of citizens.
	   The agreement and the laws enacted to make it effective had
endangered the territorial integrity and independence, undermined
the sovereignty of Parliament and had also put national security
under threat, she said.
	   She said that the people had once again been forced into a
struggle to save the motherland. ``We cannot allow the state,
achieved at the cost of blood of three million shaheeds, to turn
into Sikkim,'' she observed.
	   Begum Zia, however, told a questioner that they looked forward
to amending the four laws to delete the provisions that were
contrary to the Constitution and ensure equal rights for all
citizens.
	   She said that the Long March would be a ``march past to save the
country, not to capture power,'' and that the programme of
resistance would be peaceful ``because we believe in democracy and
constitutional politics.'' The responsibility for any violence by
the use of police or political workers would fall on the
government, she warned.
	   The BNP chief said that her party had invited delegates from all
districts to take part in the march to sympathise and express
solidarity with the citizens at risk and stricken by terrorism. On
the way to the CHT ``we will urge the people to pledge to resist
the enemies of the nation,'' she said.
	   Secretary General Abdul Mannan Bhuiyan, members of the National
Standing Committee Barrister Abdus Salam Talukdar, Col (retd) Oli
Ahmed, Abdul Matin Chowdhury, Barrister Moudud Ahmed, Dr. Khondker
Mosharraf Hossain; central leaders Salahuddin Quader Chowdhury, MK
Anwar and Anwar Zahid were also present among others.
	   Begum Zia said the CHT problem had its origin in an address of
Prime Minister Sheikh Mujibur Rahman at Rangamati in 1973 when
tribals were asked to become Bangalees. The then government had
even sought help from the Indian army to quell the rebellion, but
failed. The armed struggle turned into a separatist conflict
because of Indian support. Over 400 jawans of the army, the BDR,
Police and Ansar and thousands of Bangladeshi nationals had been
killed in the two decades of conflict, she said.
	   She said that her party had never neglected the CHT problem.
Late President Ziaur Rahman had tried to unite all including the
tribals under the banner of Bangladeshi nationalism and started
large scale development of the CHT, she said adding that her
government continued the process.
	   She said that her government had started repatriation of tribal
refugees in 1994 after having talks with India and that the Shanti
Bahini had declared a ceasefire. She said when a permanent
settlement of the problem was being reached, anarchy was created in
the country through repeated hartals. At that point, the Chakma
rebels suddenly raised some new demands that were contrary to the
Constitution and the interests of the people.
	   She said that a national problem the CHT one could only be
solved on the basis of a consensus, and within the framework of the
Constitution. All citizens, tribals and non-tribals should enjoy
equal rights, and all the people living in the area should be
directly involved in the peace process.
	   The BNP chief said that her party was the largest opposition in
Parliament in Bangladesh history but was consulted neither before
signing the treaty nor after it. Not even the Ministers and MPs of
the ruling party had been taken into confidence. The government had
not only betrayed the nation but had also thrown it into a new
crisis. The life and property of people of small tribes and of the
Bangla speaking settlers had become unsafe due to threats of Chakma
terrorists.' An extremist' Chakma group had started activities to
drive away Bangla speaking settlers by fanning separatism, she
said.
	   Begum Zia said that the government had lost control over the
CHT. The intrusion of more than one lakh Indian nationals into the
CHT had proved this, she said.
	   She said that the four new laws had termed the CHT a tribal area
and had vested the executive power of the area with a Regional
Council. The Bangla-speaking people had thus been turned into
second class citizens. Referring to the 8th Amendment to the
Constitution, knocked down by the Supreme Court for bifurcating the
highest court, she said that the creation of a Regional Council
amounted to sowing the seeds of separatism.
	   Through the agreement the government had sacrificed its
jurisdiction to order the movement of the army in the CHT where the
border now remained unguarded, she said. Acquisition of land had
also been made subject to approval of the Regional Council, she
said.
	   Provision for a tribal Minister on CHT affairs had been made in
contravention of the Constitution. Chakmas would dominate all
bodies whereas Bangla-speaking settlers who comprise 48 per cent of
the CHT population would have insignificant representation, she
said.
	   Parliament was sovereign to make laws for the whole country or
any part of it, but in formulating laws on the CHT it would have to
take prior approval of the Regional Council.
	   She said that the Constitution was against all forms of
discrimination, but that the new laws gave tribals preference in
government jobs there. The Bangla-speaking citizens would thus get
no jobs. The laws also provided that only tribals would be eligible
to become chairmen of the three hill district councils and the
Regional Council, and that Bangla-speaking citizens would have to
take 'non-tribal' certificates from Circle Chiefs. Such
discrimination had existed only under the erstwhile racist regime
of South Africa, she said.
	   She said that the agreement provided for cash grants, land,
waiving of bank loans with interest as well as clemency for crimes
like murder and terrorism for tribals; but did not ensure
compensation for Bangla-speaking citizens who had lost their
relatives, and whose homes had been burnt.
	   She alleged that the only objective of such a system of naked
discrimination opposed to fundamental rights was to drive away the
Bangla-speaking citizens and lay the foundation of a separate
state.
	   Begum Zia said that the anti-state terrorism was now not only
restricted to the CHT. The whole country was suffering. She said
that the rule of law had broken down, the economy had collapsed,
there was no electricity, no water and women and children had no
security of life. The people were under severe strain due to toll
collection and armed activities of terrorists of the ruling party,
she alleged.
	   Against this backdrop attempts were being made to plunder
natural wealth in the name of extracting the resources while bank
loans were being utilised to finance government propaganda. These
were parts of a blueprint to cripple Bangladesh and make it
dependent on foreign support, she said.
	   
</TEXT>
