<SLUG> BC-Japan-Tutankhamen Ring </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Ring of Tutankhamen's queen found in Egyptian tomb
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese archeologists have unearthed a ring
inscribed with the name of Egyptian king Tutankhamen's wife along
with thousands of other relics at an ancient tomb outside Cairo, a
news report said Monday.
	   Researchers from Japan's Waseda University and Tokai University
said they found the ring with Ankhesenamen's name in March in a
tomb some 30 kilometers (20 miles) southwest of the Egyptian
capital, Kyodo News reported.
	   ``We believe the person buried there was an extremely close
relative or an aide,'' Sakuji Yoshimura, a professor at Waseda
University who attended the excavation, was quoted as saying by
Kyodo.
	   Team members said they found the bluish ring, made of clay, in a
pit connected to the tomb's seven underground rooms. The ring is
two to three centimeters (one inch) long and about one centimeter
wide (a half inch), the report said.
	   The tomb, discovered by archaeologists after analyzing satellite
images, apparently had been broken into.
	   However, the 4,000 accessories from Tutankhamen's tomb as well
as a ring with the inscription of Tutankhamen's accession name were
apparently overlooked by the looters, the archeologists said.
	   The tomb is believed to be that of a minister-class official.
	   The team plans to resume excavation in December. They have also
found a pit believed to be connected to the room in which the
coffin is placed, team members said.
	   (jc)
</TEXT>
