<SLUG> BC-EU-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writehtru,0619 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU bans new investments in Serbia; freezes assets abroad
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with ministers agreeing to freeze of Serb assets
abroad, comments. No pickup &QL; 
 &UR; With Yugoslavia-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT WIELAARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LUXEMBOURG (AP) _ The EU banned new investments in Serbia and
froze the country's assets abroad on Monday to punish Belgrade for
staging ``widespread house-burning and indiscriminate artillery
attacks on whole villages'' in separatist Kosovo province.
	   Serbia ``is engaged in a campaign of violence going far beyond
what could legitimately be described as a targeted anti-terrorist
operation,'' the EU foreign ministers said in a statement.
	   The EU urged Belgrade and Kosovo independence activists to seek
a negotiated solution. However, it said President Slobodan
Milosevic bore ``special responsibility'' as the Yugoslav head of
state.
	   Citing ``the grave deteriorating situation on the ground,
involving the excessive use of force by the Serb security forces,''
it banned all new investments in Serbia and froze the country's
assets in the 15 EU nations.
	   The EU promised ``other measures'' unless the violence is
halted. It has already banned arms exports and restricted travel
visas for Yugoslav officials. At Washington's urging, it earlier
held off on the investment ban and the assets freeze to give
Milosevic a chance to reach a peaceful settlement in Kosovo.
	   Further economic sanctions could include a ban on all flights by
JAT, the Yugoslav airline.
	   The EU move was unlikely to make an immediate difference. ``The
fight (to get Milosevic to ease up on Kosovo) clearly lies within
the United Nations Security Council,'' said a Dutch official.
	   Escalating violence in Kosovo in recent weeks has drawn
parallels with West European waffling in 1991 and 1992 as Bosnia
slipped into civil war.
	   NATO defense ministers are scheduled to meet Thursday and Friday
in Brussels to consider a military response to Milosevic, though in
recent weeks that option has sparked little enthusiasm.
	   In London on Friday, the foreign ministers of the G-8 nations _
Canada, United States, Britain, Germany, France, Japan, Italy and
Russia _ will discuss Kosovo.
	   ``It is very important we include Russia in our efforts,'' said
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel, but added to reporters ``that
will be difficult.''
	   Kinkel was to meet later Monday in Bonn with Yevgeny Primakov,
his Russian counterpart. Russia is a permanent member of the U.N.
Security Council. Military intervention by NATO in Kosovo would
require a United Nations mandate. However, the prospect of that
emerging appeared dim.
	   Relations between Russia and NATO are already on edge since NATO
looks to expand into eastern Europe. Russia opposes using external
forces in Kosovo, saying it is an internal matter for Serbia
	   NATO military planners have been drafting contingency plans.
These include accelerating joint NATO maneuvers in Albania and
Macedonia, NATO help for these countries to seal their borders and
_ as a last resort _ deploying up to 20,000 troops to the two
countries.
	   Meantime, Kinkel and Austrian Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schussel
proposed similar peace efforts in Kosovo, including sending
observers, calling a cease fire and having an orderly return of
refugees and international mediation.
	   British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, chairman of the EU
meeting, warned Milosevic to ``back off'' or face a military
intervention in Kosovo, where Ethnic Albanians comprise 90 percent
of the 2.2 million-strong population. Most want to secede from
Serbia, which along with Montenegro, makes up Yugoslavia.
</TEXT>
