<SLUG> FIGHT-TO-SAVE-GIRL-FIRE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fight to save girl fire victim, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Fight to save girl fire victim, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   martin WongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DOCTORS on Sunday night were battling to save the life of a
seven-year-old girl who suffered 70 per cent burns in a fire that
gutted a 12th-floor flat in Yau Ma Tei early Sunday.
	   Three other members of the family living in the flat were rushed
to hospital.
	   Lau Yeuk-ting was in critical condition in the intensive care
unit of the Kwong Wah Hospital. Her 41-year-old father, Lau
Kwok-chuen, was also in serious condition.
	   Two other family members _ Lau Hoi-ying, 4, and mother Lau
On-lee _ were said to be in stable condition.
	   A 66-year-old woman living on the 20th floor of the building was
also admitted to hospital for smoke inhalation.
	   ``The girl suffered 70 per cent burns. It can be very dangerous
because a child's body is smaller and her immune system is often
weaker,'' said the hospital's accident and emergency department
acting senior medical officer Ma Hing-man.
	   The fire broke out at 6 am and was put out in 30 minutes.
	   
</TEXT>
