<HEADLINE>
Jamaat's long march programme, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Jamaat's long march programme, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Joint Secretary General of Jamaat-e-Islami Muhammad
Quamaruzzaman yesterday urged the government not to intervene in
the long march and allow the peaceful termination of the opposition
action programme.
	   The Jamaat will begin the long march towards Chittagong Hill
Tracts (CHT) tomorrow from Ramna Park in the city centre at 7.30 in
the morning. Party Chief Prof Golam Azam will lead the long march
and address the gathering prior to its start. The marchers from
Rajshahi and Barisal divisions would join their compatriots from
Dhaka division at Ramna, he said.
	   Briefing newsmen at the National Press Club in the city
yesterday, Quamaruzzaman said the marchers would move by motor
vehicles including buses, trucks and cars and stay overnight in
Chittagong city.
	   In the morning of June 10, the marchers would assemble at
Laldighi Maidan and move to Rangamati. Party workers and
well-wishers from Chittagong and the eastern regions will also move
from there.
	   The Jamaat chief would make a policy statement at Laldighi
Maidan before the start of the march, he said.
	   The marchers are expected to reach Rangamati at noon. A grand
rally will be held in the afternoon marking the end of the
programme. The marchers including, central leaders are scheduled to
leave Rangamati for Dhaka after the rally, he said.
	   Party leaders Mokbul Ahmed, Abdul Kader Mollah, Prof Mujibur
Rahman, ATM Ajharul Islam and Dr Abdullah Mohammad Taher attended
the briefing.
	   
</TEXT>
