<HEADLINE>
China and US to hold joint naval exercise, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
China and US to hold joint naval exercise, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Cary HuangASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The bilateral sea rescue operation _ the first exercise between
the two Pacific powers since World War II _ is included in a
package of proposals which have been put together by Chinese and US
diplomats preparing for the upcoming summit between presidents
Jiang Zemin and Bill Clinton.
	   The diplomats said the naval exercise would implement and extend
the ``constructive strategic partnership'' announced by both
presidents during Mr Jiang's landmark visit to Washington in
October last year. Negotiators have been working over the last few
months on proposals to implement pledges made by both presidents.
	   The package includes a series of exchanges and co-operation
between the two armies, including their military forces with
strategic implications.
	   All of these will be scrutinised and finalised by Mr Jiang and
Mr Clinton in their second summit this month in Beijing.
	   It is understood both sides are keen to engage in wider areas to
ensure that conflicts would be avoided following the crisis in the
Taiwan Straits in 1996 when Washington sent a fleet led by two
aircraft carriers to monitor Beijing's war games.
	   ``The joint navy exercise is of both symbolic and substantial
significance if it materialises,'' a Chinese diplomat said, adding
that it was the first time since the US army and the communist-led
Eighth Route Army fought together against the Japanese in World War
II.
	   However, the US army and the People's Liberation Army
subsequently fought each other in the Korean and Vietnam wars.
	   A mechanism for information exchange between the two armies _
for strategic forces and nuclear units _ will also be endorsed.
	   It is understood that regular annual visits by top officers of
the three services and various kinds of armed forces units and
warships from each side will also be pushed through.
	   Co-operation in maritime operations, civilian uses of nuclear
energy, environmental protection and the fight against
international crimes, including terrorism, will be widened. These
moves will enable more bilateral exchanges of information and
visits by experts, according to Beijing-based diplomats.
	   Chinese military officers and nuclear experts are expected to
pay a visit to the US National Laboratory for Nuclear Energy in
Arizona some time next year, with reciprocal visits by the US side
to follow.
	   Considering the current US Congressional investigation of the
Clinton administration's involvement in the alleged transfer of
missile technology to China, Chinese diplomats said some of the
proposals in the exchange package might not be made public until
the events had actually taken place.
	   Nevertheless, diplomats on both sides suggested that military
co-operation be put high on the agenda for the summit late this
month.
	   
</TEXT>
