<SLUG> CLINTON-DOESN'T-WANT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Clinton doesn't want to blow it, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Clinton doesn't want to blow it, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Fong Tak-hoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   US President Bill Clinton has turned down an invitation to play
the saxophone with a group of Beijing musicians during his China
trip, saying that wants to avoid criticism ``of detracting from the
solemn atmosphere'' of the state visit.
	   Beijing bookstore proprietor Li Siqiang sent an invitation to
President Clinton inviting him to play saxophone with the store's
musicians.
	   Mr Li's privately-run bookstore, which sells books on Western
culture and political philosophy, has held jazz concerts every
weekend, attracting a throng of artists as well Western diplomats.
	   Mr Li wrote to the US embassy hoping the US President would
share his favourite songs with the Chinese people.
	   ``They recently replied to me, saying they were afraid the event
would spark criticisms from Mr Clinton's opponents, who might say
this is not in line with the solemn atmosphere required for a state
visit,'' Mr Li said.
	   The shop owner said the US embassy had given serious thought to
his proposal as it would have put the US President in direct touch
with the Chinese people. However the proposal was shunned by other
US officials.
	   Mr Li said Chinese intellectuals were looking forward to Mr
Clinton's visit and hoped that the landmark visit would bring about
a long-term open door policy.
	   
</TEXT>
