<BODY>
<SLUG> SHARE-PRICES-PLUMMET sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Share prices plummet by 89 points, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Share prices plummet by 89 points, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Faruque AhmedASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Dhaka Stock Exchange (DSE) yesterday witnessed a big shock
and pandemonium on the street as the all share price index
nosedived by 89 points after bullish business transactions over the
last week.
	   Kerb market operators yesterday demonstrated outside the stock
exchange buildings in the afternoon and tried to enter the DSE
building forcibly. Police intervened to control the unruly kerb
traders, and the DSE's shutters remained closed for sometime to
avoid untoward incident.
	   The bourse on Saturday witnessed 81.28 points gain in the share
index recording a 11.65 per cent positive change in the day's
business over that of Thursday last. It was in continuation of a
steady rise on prices of almost all shares -- good and bad during
the last week following the previous week.
	   The DSE management was witnessing the developments with
increasing uneasiness as the market fundamentals were not
supportive of it. They were specially alarmed about the forward
trading' of shares from the Dhaka Stock Exchange floor to the
unauthorised kerb market operating on the city streets nearby.
	   Yesterday as the share index eclipsed by 11.43 per cent from the
previous day's record of a similar rise by 11.65 per cent or 81.28
points, the kerb market operators became restive. The market crash
memory of December 1996 made them nervous of losing their fresh
capital once again. The raised slogans against alleged market
manipulations and besieged the stock exchange building.
	   Earlier the Dhaka Stock Exchange (DSE) authorities expressed
grave concern over the bullish business transactions during the
past couple of days and warned the Securities and Exchange
Commission (SEC) about the unusual upward movement in the market
not justified by market fundamentals.
	   The market was heading for another undesirable situation, a DSE
letter informed the SEC on June 4 demanding strict surveillance of
the causes of the sudden price hike of all kinds of shares and
immediate corrective steps against irrational market behaviour to
avoid new crisis.
	   The DSE further informed the SEC of the unusual price hike of
shares of 27 companies in a separate a letter on June 4 and urged
the supervisory body to look into it.
	   The DSE also demanded an explanation of the price movements from
the issuers of these shares that were not supported either by the
prevailing market situation or the market rating of their shares,
said a source.
	   Another source said more than 50 companies were asked to explain
their share position recently in view of the soaring prices of
their shares. About 30 companies received such letters last week,
said the source.
	   The sources said that the market observers were really at a loss
as to what caused this upward price movement. Even those shares
which were totally ignored by investors previously were on the
gainers' list last week and on Saturday, the first business day of
the current week.
	   On Saturday's trading in the Dhaka stock exchange a total of 141
issues gained while only seven lost and one remained unchanged.
Contrary to it yesterday (Sunday) only five issues gained in value
while 124 lost. The market totally reversed overnight and observers
were quite confused to explain it.
	   The sources said the DSE management drew the attention of the
SEC to the missing link between the market fundamentals and the
share prices. They had also pointed to the intense activities in
the kerb market which appeared to be supplied from the DSE floor.
This was going in violation of the business rules adopted by the
SEC and the DSE.
	   Who were those violators supplying the kerb market with shares
and how a new manipulation was taking shape -- this required to be
immediately sorted out, the DSE is reported to have warned the SEC.
	   A DSE source told The Independent that fraud, counterfeiting of
shares and market manipulations might happen in the new situation
and, besides the SEC actions to stop these things, the DSE might
also caution the public about the risk of trading in the kerb
through news paper advertisement soon.
	   Explaining why the share prices were suddenly soaring, the
sources pointed to several factors. They said with the introduction
of the daily settlement of the business transactions as against
twice weekly netting system many brokers who were previously doing
business in the bourse both ``without shares and money'' now
required to possess some reserve of shares.
	   So they might have started to buy shares in the market after the
introduction of the daily settlement system.
	   Secondly, the many sponsor directors of the listed companies who
had sold part of their mandatory holding of shares earlier might be
buying shares to meet their requirement.
	   But the sudden slide in the market yesterday questioned the
validity of these reasons. Some sources said that actually the
bourse was currently exploited as a spot market to gain profits
from short term business instead of long term portfolio
investments.
	   As the price rose significantly over the last week, the lack of
investors' confidence in the market for a long term period forced
most of the buyers of the last week who even bought on Saturday to
become seller yesterday.
	   It reflected the poor confidence level of the investors although
many people wanted to invest in the bourse, said these sources.
	   
</TEXT>
