<SLUG> US-PRIVATE-INVESTMENT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US private investment will go up to one billion dollars by year-end, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
US private investment will go up to one billion dollars by year-end, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Some of the major American companies have shown ``tremendous''
interest in investing in Bangladesh foreseeing it as a country with
bright development prospect.
	   ``Bangladesh has been identified as a destination for investment
by a number of US companies. And they are very much interested in
investing here,'' said Commerce Minister Tofail Ahmed.
	   Talking to newsmen at the Zia International Airport on his
return from the United States on Sunday, he said US private
investment would go up to one billion dollars by the year-end.
	   ``The US investment in Bangladesh was only 25 million dollars
when we took over nearly two years back,'' said the minister
explaining the outcome of his visit to the United States.
	   He said the US companies are not only interested in the oil and
gas sector but also in downstream business like setting up of
fertiliser factory and petrochemical units.
	   Also the US companies showed their keen interest to invest in
Bangladesh's telecommunications sector and banking business, he
told journalists.
	   Tofail went to Washington on June 1, mainly to present a
key-note paper at the launch of the US-Bangladesh Business Council
(USBC), an investment catalyst forum set up by some US companies.
	   During his tour he met with US Secretary of Commerce William
Daley, the first ever meeting between a Bangladesh Commerce
Minister and his US counterpart since independence.
	   Four issues were discussed at the meeting.
	   First, Tofail said, he discussed about the planned visit of US
President Bill Clinton to Bangladesh. ``The visit is positive,'' he
said without elaborating.
	   The minister mentioned that the US investors were also
enthusiastic about the visit of Clinton because it would bring the
businesses of the two countries close.
	   The second issue was the Bangladesh proposal for raising the
quota of ready-made garment export to US market by 30 per cent.
``The matter is now under consideration,'' Tofail said.
	   Next was the debt under PL-480, he said, adding that the
Bangladesh side requested the Clinton administration to write off
8000 million dollars accumulated since 1972.
	   ``Finally we have again called upon the United States to provide
duty-free market access for the export products of the least
developed countries, including Bangladesh,'' he said.
	   The minister informed that during his meeting with US
under-secretary for Economic and Agricultural Affairs Stuart E
Eizenstat, he also discussed the same issues.
	   In another meeting with US Permanent Representative to the
United Nations Bill Richardson, the business issues dominated.
Richardson requested Tofail to facilitate US investment in
Bangladesh.
	   The Bangladesh minister had also meetings with some US
Congressmen, other business leaders and World Bank President James
D Wolfensohn during his trip to the US.
	   Wolfensohn assured that the Bank would raise its lending to
Bangladesh by 200 million US dollars from the current level of 450
million dollars and provide assistance for the development of
Chittagong Hill Tracts.
	   Tofail said all the people he met during the visit highly
appreciated Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina for promoting peace in
CHT. ``They also appreciated her initiative to defuse tensions
between India and Pakistan,'' he said.
	   The minister said he was invited to attend a high-level meeting
of ECOSOC in the USA on July 6 to 7 when the trade ministers from
developed and developing countries would discuss the duty-free
access issue.
	   
</TEXT>
