</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BADC-UNDERTAKES-TK-100 sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BADC undertakes Tk 100 cr uplift project for Pabna, Natore, Sirajganj, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
BADC undertakes Tk 100 cr uplift project for Pabna, Natore, Sirajganj, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Bangladesh Agricultural Development Corporation (BADC) has
taken up a Tk 100 crore socio-economic development project for
Pabna, Natore and Sirajganj districts.
	   The project, included in the Annual Development Programme (ADP)
of the current fiscal, aims at increasing food production,
alleviating poverty and ensuring irrigation system development in
the districts, BADC sources said.
	   The five-year project which was to have been started from July
97 would soon get off the ground, the sources added. A primary
allocation of Tk 50 lakh has already been made for the purpose.
	   Around 75 kms of canals and 300 derelict ponds would be
re-excavated and 25 cross-dams constructed in the areas. This
project would also arrange for irrigation through the installation
of a 250-cusec pump.
	   As a result, it will be possible to irrigate some 5,300 acres of
land, targeting an additional food production of 795 tonnes, valued
at nearly Tk 5 crore.
	   The project includes the installation of some 250 deep
tube-wells (DTWs), enabling irrigation of some 15,000 acres of land
for an additional output of 22,500 tonnes of food-grains worth more
than Tk 14 crore.
	   Under the project, the deep tube-wells will be sold to the
farmers in the project areas at lower prices.
	   The growers would be trained o ensue minimum wastage of
irrigation water, bringing it down from 5 per cent to 17 per cent.
An additional 17,832 acres of land would be brought under
irrigation in the three districts.
	   Some 493 deep tube-wells, currently lying inoperative will be
repaired and rehabilitated helping hectares of land a year.
Electric supply would be ensured to another 250 deep tube-wells of
the areas.
	   Around 250 power tillers would be supplied to the farmers. The
growers would be provided with seeds.
	   Some 24 fishing farms will be set up to train 1,500 owners of
ponds and fishermen. Poorer ones will be supplied with fish fry,
nets and improved breeds of ducklings.
	   Under the project 10 kms of feeder roads will be constructed in
the villages.
	   Nearly 35 lakh trees will be planted in the project areas to
stem the desertification process.
	   The literacy programme under the project would focus on some
15,000 youths and 15,000 adult people.
	   A number of non-government organisations (NGOs) will be involved
in the project.
	   
</TEXT>
