<SLUG> BC-Asian Crisis-Migration </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian economic crisis may spark rise in illegal foreign labor
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ The Asian financial crisis is likely to spark a
surge in smuggling of illegal foreign laborers and unauthorized
cross-border movements of job-seekers, an intergovernmental
migration agency said Monday.
	   Growing hardship in Thailand, Malaysia and other countries in
the region will force more people to travel abroad to find work,
said a statement from the Geneva-based International Organization
for Migration.
	   This could fuel an increase in exploitation by unscrupulous
employers across the region, the IOM said.
	   ``The situation is ripe for smugglers to exploit people's
insecurity. This is a real worry,'' said Yorio Tanimura, the IOM's
senior expert on Asia.
	   The region lacks effective ways to manage migration, the agency
says. It wants governments to cooperate to prevent the
``potentially damaging mass movements.''
	   The region already hosts an estimated two million or more
irregular migrant workers, said the IOM, which promotes orderly
migration between countries.
	   Thailand has an estimated 943,000 irregular immigrants, three
times the number of authorized immigrants in the country.
	   The International Labor Organization has reported the number of
Indonesians caught and suspected of trying to illegally enter
Malaysia doubled in the first two months of this year compared to
the same period in 1997.
	   Indonesia's surplus of unskilled labor creates emigration
pressure which has been worsened by the recent financial crisis and
the domestic economy's severe contraction, the IOM said.
	   ``What is clear is that the intra-regional population movement
will continue to grow,'' said Tanimura. ``Unless this is done in a
regulated, orderly way, it could provide a destabilizing factor.''
	   The problem and possible solutions are due to be raised at a
regional Asia-Pacific consultation meeting in Bangkok on June 9-10.
 &UR; (pw)
</TEXT>
