<SLUG> 'NO-OBSTACLE-ON-BUDGET' sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Basic Law `no obstacle on budget', HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Basic Law `no obstacle on budget', HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Cynthia WanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A PRO-BEIJING legislator has thrown his support behind a deficit
budget for the next financial year.
	   Ng Ching-fai, re-elected without party affiliation, said on
Sunday he did not see how a deficit budget would violate the Basic
Law.
	   His remarks came after Tsang Hin-chi of the National People's
Congress Standing Committee said deficit spending was inevitable in
a slump.
	   Echoing Mr Tsang's thinking, Mr Ng said a deficit budget would
not violate the ``spirit of the Basic Law'' because the government
would seek to spend moderately only to overcome difficulties.
	   He said it was acceptable for the financial secretary to produce
a deficit budget if it was for only one year ``and that deficit is
not a huge one''.
	   But he said, ``if we are to have a budget running in the red for
the long term, of course that would not be possible''.
	   ``We have to examine the spirit of the Basic Law,'' he said.
``The mentality of the drafters at that time, according to our
understanding, was to have a moderate financial management.
	   ``If the budget is designed to avoid a deficit, then that has
fulfilled the principle of moderate planning.'' Article 107 of the
Basic Law states that the SAR ``shall follow the principle of
keeping expenditure within the limits of revenues in drawing up its
budget, and strive to achieve a fiscal balance, avoid deficits and
keep the budget commensurate with the growth rate of its gross
domestic product''.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
