<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Kosovo, 5th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU bans new investments in Serbia; freezes assets abroad
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Yugoslavia-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: AMs; UPDATES with comments from EU statement on possible
military action &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT WIELAARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LUXEMBOURG (AP) _ Worried that a new wave of ethnic cleansing
may ignite another Balkan war, the EU tightened sanctions against
Belgrade Monday and urged the NATO alliance to study a military
intervention to stop the bloodshed and suffering in Kosovo.
	   The European Union foreign ministers banned new investments in
Serbia and froze the country's assets abroad to punish it for
``widespread house-burning and indiscriminate artillery attacks on
whole villages'' in Kosovo.
	   Yet given the limited effect sanctions have had so far on
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic, they urged ``international
security organizations ... to consider all options,'' including
those requiring specific United Nations Security Council support.
	   That could mean a military intervention by NATO. The sort of
actions requiring specific U.N. blessing would be the imposition of
a no-fly zone, air strikes against Serb artillery, beefing up U.N.
forces in Macedonia or _ the most extreme scenario _ sending an
allied force into Kosovo.
	   Until now, NATO has been considering only joint but small-scale
maneuvers with Albania and Macedonia and the deployment of up to
20,000 troops in Albania along the Kosovo border.
	   Looming over the Kosovo debate is the fear Serbia's crackdown
there will only ignite another Balkan war.
	   On Thursday and Friday, the NATO defense ministers meet in
Brussels to consider a military response to Milosevic, a prospect
that so far has met with little enthusiasm.
	   On Friday, the foreign ministers of the G-8 nations _ Canada,
United States, Britain, Germany, France, Japan, Italy and Russia _
will discuss Kosovo in London bringing Russia into the
international deliberations.
	   ``It is very important we include Russia,'' German Foreign
Minister Klaus Kinkel told reporters. ``But that will be
difficult.''
	   Russia, a permanent member of the U.N. Security Council, would
be called on to endorse any NATO action under a U.N. mandate.
	   In their statement, the EU ministers said Serb security forces
have been ``engaged in a campaign of violence going far beyond what
could legitimately be described as a targeted anti-terrorist
operation.''
	   They urged Belgrade and Kosovo independence activists to seek a
negotiated solution to their conflict and spoke of ``the grave
deteriorating situation on the ground, involving the excessive use
of force by the Serb security forces.''
	   ``We are disturbed by reports that these attacks are beginning
to constitute a new wave of ethnic cleansing,'' the ministers said.
They called the flow of refugees into Albania a ``threat to
regional security and stability.''
	   The investment ban and the asset freeze come in addition to
previously announced measures including a ban on arms exports and
restricted travel visas for Yugoslav officials.
	   At Washington's urging last month, the EU held off on the
investment ban and assets freeze to give Milosevic a chance to
reach a peaceful settlement in Kosovo.
	   Escalating violence in Kosovo in recent weeks has drawn
parallels with West European waffling in 1991 and 1992 as Bosnia
slipped into civil war.
 &UR; (rw)	   
</TEXT>
