w2935 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 1stLd-Writethru   06-08 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru,0654 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serb police beat protesters in Kosovo's capital
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with U.S. ambassador, ethnic Albanian leader going to
area of fighting. EU freezing assets abroad; Kosovo Albanian
reaction. Trims outdated material. No pickup &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ As Europe banned investment in
Serbia and weighed other ways to halt violence in Kosovo, Serbs
reported fresh clashes Monday in the secessionist province where a
U.S. diplomat and ethnic Albanian leader toured a battle-torn area.
	   In Luxembourg, European Union foreign ministers banned
investment in Serbia and froze the country's assets abroad for ``a
campaign of violence going far beyond'' a legitimate strike against
terrorists.
	   A Kosovo Albanian leader welcomed the sanctions but said they
were only a ``small step.''
	   ``NATO should become involved in Kosovo, because the Serbian
regime has had practice with sanctions and knows ways of bypassing
them,'' said Nekibe Kelmendi, head of the Albanians' largest party,
the Democratic League of Kosovo. ``It is a regime that only
respects the language of force.''
	   Britain, currently chairman of the EU, has become increasingly
determined to send NATO troops in the southern Balkans, both to
stop the violence from spilling over into neighboring Macedonia and
Albania and perhaps to quell the violence in Kosovo itself.
	   Washington also wants to stop Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic from using police and army against militants battling for
independence for Kosovo's Albanians, who outnumber Serbs 9-to-1.
	   ``A credible discouragement in the direction of President
Milosevic is indispensible,'' British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
said at the EU meeting. ``I also hope for support in the steps
Britain is taking to get the measures within the United Nations and
NATO agreed to stop the violence in Kosovo.''
	   In Pristina on Monday, a daily march by Kosovo Albanians for
peace passed off without incident, unlike the previous day's march,
when more than 100 Serbian police broke up the demonstration,
injuring at least six Albanians.
	   Christopher Hill, the U.S. ambassador to Macedonia, joined
ethnic Albanian Fehmi Agani on a trip to the Decani region in
western Kosovo, scene of fierce fighting last week.
	   A convoy of diplomats, joined by journalists for Serbian
state-run media and one independent journalist, toured the region
Sunday and saw ghastly scenes reminiscent of the earlier wars in
Bosnia and Croatia.
	   Independent journalist Aleksandar Vasovic said the group saw
many houses that had been shelled or burned out, and several
deserted villages. Serbian police said the militants started the
fighting, but Dutch ambassador Jan Sizoo was skeptical.
	   Up to 20,000 refugees from the Decani area have fled into
neighboring Albania. Another 7,000 to 10,000 are in Montenegro, the
only other Yugoslav republic, and some 50,000 are thought to be
displaced within Kosovo itself.
	   Many of that group are hiding out in the Drenica region in the
center of the province, where Serbian police began their crackdown
in early March. Since then, more than 250 people have been killed.
	   Ethnic Albanian officials say the campaign in the west has
killed at least 50 people and 200 others have gone missing since
late May.
	   Ethnic Albanians comprise 90 percent of the 2.2 million
inhabitants of Kosovo, and most want to secede from Serbia. Western
powers oppose any change of borders, but want Serbia to restore the
broad autonomy it took away in 1989.
	   In Turkey on Monday, Balkan foreign ministers were meeting and
may discuss Kosovo. NATO is due to weigh its moves later this week,
and the foreign ministers of the Contact Group _ the United States,
Britian, France, Germany and Russia, joined by Canada and Italy _
is to consider further steps Friday.
</TEXT>
