<HEADLINE>
Scientific seminar on Lacidipine held, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Scientific seminar on Lacidipine held, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Speakers at a scientific seminar held at the National Institute
of Cardiovascular Disease (NICVD) in the city expressed optimism on
the introduction of Lacidipine, a new drug for the management of
hypertension.
	   A large number of specialists and doctors working at the premier
cardiac institute of Bangladesh attended at the seminar.
	   The seminar was presided over by Professor Dr M A Zaman,
Director NICVD. In the key-note paper presented by Dr Md Nur
Hossain, Assistant Professor of NICVD, international data on the
efficacy and safety of this new calcium channel antagonist was
presented.
	   The speaker highlighted the many unmet needs in the management
of hypertension faced by the medical profession and demonstrated
the favourable profile of Lacidipine to meet many of these needs.
	   Following the presentation of the key-note paper, a lively
question-answer session was held.
	   Dr Tanvir Mobarak Ali, Medical and Regulatory Affairs Manager
and Hasan Ferdausi, Marketing Director, both from Glaxo Welcome
Bangladesh Limited also spoke on the occasion.
	   Lacidipine (LACIPIL) is a novel third generation calcium
antagonist which provides effective blood pressure control over 24
hours in a wide variety of patients while protecting the vital
organs.
	   Developed by the Glaxo Welcome Group, it has currently been made
available in Bangladesh.
	   Glaxo Welcome is a research-based company, whose people are
committed to fighting disease by bringing innovative medicines and
services to patients throughout the world and to the health-care
providers who serve them.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:SCIENTIFIC-SEMINAR sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
