<HEADLINE>
`No help' for youth on jobs, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
`No help' for youth on jobs, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Martin WongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE 12 measures announced by the government to revive the
economy and ease unemployment are of little use to fresh graduates,
the Democratic Party (DP) said.
	   ``According to the latest figure provided by the Education and
Manpower Bureau, a total of 148,620 students will soon graduate
from Form 5, Form 7 classes and the tertiary institutions.
	   Among them, 70,190 will have a chance to go for higher studies .
. . It means that 78,430 graduates will enter the labour market
soon,'' Democrat Chan Kwok-leung said.
	   He said only two measures in the government's 12-point plan were
related to fresh graduates _ extending the tertiary students' loan
scheme and creating more places in post-graduate courses.
	   ``And these two measures are in fact useless in helping the
fresh graduates find new jobs.
	   ``The government did not have any practical measures in
assisting these graduates.'' Mr Chan urged the government to look
into the problem of youth unemployment because it was often over
15.5 per cent. He suggested the government improve the Labour
Department's services.
	   ``Other than just introducing jobs to people who go there, it
should offer one-on-one consulting services, especially to fresh
graduates because they may not know what they actually want to
do.'' Mr Chan also asked the government to offer more temporary
jobs to young people so that the problem of unemployment could be
eased _ temporarily at least.
	   ``But in the long run, the government should think of how to
stimulate the economy, like introducing tax cuts so that more jobs
will be created.'' 
</TEXT>
