<HEADLINE>
Food of Kings: White Asparagus at the Pen, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Food of Kings: White Asparagus at the Pen, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   For over 2,000 years, man has recognized the virtues of white
asparagus, prizing its large, tender, and delicately-flavored
spears as a culinary temptation of unsurpassed value.
	   Asparagus derives its name from ancient Greek, which means
``sprout'' or ``shoot''. The ancients had long considered the white
asparagus -- cousin to the onion, leek, and garlic -- a delicacy,
but it was the Romans who developed gardening techniques to grow
them. They enjoyed it in season and were the first to preserve it
by freezing. In fact, so familiar were the characteristics of white
asparagus to them that the Emperor Caesar Augustus defined
``haste'' as ``quicker than you can cook a white asparagus.''
	   Emperors and kings put a high premium on white asparagus, which
is why it has always been referred to as the ``Food of Kings.''
King Louis XIV of France, the Sun King, was so enamored of the
tender young spears of white asparagus, which are harvested as soon
as they appear above the ground, that he built special greenhouses
so he could have a ready supply year-round.
	   ``Fortunately, you don't have to be a king these days to enjoy
white asparagus,'' says The Peninsula Manila's Old Manila Chef
David Senia. ``From June 5 to 12, we are flying in white asparagus
spears fresh from Bruchsal, Germany for our food festival. The
delicate white asparagus is the most luxurious of all asparagus
varieties and has a full-flavored, delicious taste.''
	   Taking stellar turns in his White Asparagus Festival menu are
Terrine D' asperges blanche et vertes aux fois gras (White and
green asparagus terrine with duck liver), Filets de rougets a la
puree d' olives, mille feuille de chips aux asperges et piments
(Fillet of red mullet withminced black olives, layered potatoes,
and white asparagus served with chili oil), Filet mignon de veau a
la fricasse d' asperges et ecrevises Pate Touge aux Deux Jus
(Pan-fried veal loin with fricassee of asparagus and crayfish in
natural jus), and Troncon de Saumon Gratine a la Fondue d' Asperges
blanche sa sauce poulette (Gratinated salmon with foundue of white
asparagus and light chicken sauce).
	   ``For purists,'' he promises, ``there will be the classic
Asperges blanches servient et ses pomme de terre a l'anglaise
(White asparagus served with boiled potatoes, Hollandaise sauce or
butter, with side order of Black forest ham, Smoked Salmon, Cooked
Ham, Breaded Sweetbreads, Russian Sevruga Caviar, Sauteed Foie
Gras).''
	   And for a novel twist, the dessert cart will feature something
of a first for a lot of Filipinos: asparagus desserts. There will
be Moelleux a l'orange et asperges caramelisees dans son chapeau
renverse (Chocolate top hat filled with orange mousse and
caramelized asparagus), Mille-feuille d' asperges blanche a la
creme d' avocat vanillee (Mille-feuille of white asparagus and
avocado cream), and Fruits frais de saison et son sorbet aux
asperges (Tropical fruit platter with asparagus sherbet).
	   For inquiries and reservations, call 810-3456 or 812-3456 ext.
2953 and 2949.
	   
</TEXT>
