<HEADLINE>
Forex market steady, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Forex market steady, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The local forex market was steady on Sunday. US dollar was
traded between
	   Taka 46.45 and Taka 46.48. Even though T-bills worth Taka 138.50
crore matured, call money rate did not fall as T-bills were already
discounted and the call rate was between 9 per cent and 10.5 per
cent, says a StanChart Bank.
	   International markets were closed on weekend on Sunday. On
Friday, in New York, US dollar gained against both yen and DEM.
Dollar gained against yen because of rumours of Bank of Japan's
high officials' scandal and weak financial structure. On the other
hand, dollar's rise against DEM was attributed to the healthy
growth in the US job market.
	   In New York, on Friday, Dollar closed at 1.7745/55 DEM,
139.60/70 yen and GBP closed against 1.6334/44 US dollar.
	   
</TEXT>
