<SLUG> REGIONALS-HOSTAGE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Peso, Regionals Hostage To G-7's Yen Defense 'We Are Anticipating Action', BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Peso, Regionals Hostage To G-7's Yen Defense 'We Are Anticipating Action', BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Arvin P. PanesASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Failure of the world's top seven industrialized nations to come
up with effective measures to stop the Japanese yen from further
depreciating could lead to renewed volatility and afurther drop in
the value of the peso.
	   In an interview with The Business Daily, traders said it was
possible for the peso to return to P40 -P50 to a dollar levels
should the yenfall below the N140 to a dollar range.
	   ``The region is anticipating Group of Seven (G-7) policies to
defend the yen. Failure to do so could be a major psychological and
economic factor,''
	   a trader at a commercial bank said.
	   Analysts and investment houses said the yen's continued
depreciation could create a domino effect in the region, leading to
yet another round of wholesale depreciations of currencies.
	   Finance officials from the G-7 countries are due to meet in
Paris next week to discuss the issue.
	   The Perils of Globalization Local sources pointed at the
country's exports being hampered by more rapid depreciation in the
currencies of competitors like Indonesia, Malaysia, China, and
Thailand.
	   A particularly wary eye is cast by many on reactions by Chinese
policy makers who at an earlier meeting of international economic
experts in Davos, Switzerland, had hinted at the strong possibility
of a guided depreciation in the value of the yuan.
	   A different angle, meanwhile, was adopted by brokerage house
Goldman &AMP; Sachswho advised its clients that ``a declining yen makes
a mockery of International Monetary Fund-driven policies in
countries like South Korea and Thailand, where currency stability
is regarded as a major priority.
	   Additional yen weakness may worsen the Asian contagion to other
emerging countries like Russia, Brazil, and Mexico by weakening
commodity prices and introducing higher risk premiums to compensate
foreign investors, Goldman said.
	   It is feared by analysts that dollar bloc economies will be
impacted by correlations to the yen because of Japan's importance
as an export market and the steep slide in commodities prices.
	   Goldman &AMP; Sachs further stated it was ``inevitable at some stage
that G-7 countries will try to halt the yen's weakness, and while
the market will doubt its effectiveness, it is quite likely that
the G-7 could stabilize the yen at stronger levels until Japan's
fiscal package has an impact from Q3 onwards.''
	   Japanese policymakers believe the recently announced fiscal
stimulus plans will have a positive impact on the economy but
measures have yet to be implemented, said Goldman.
	   Without G-7 intervention, dollar/yen was expected to move toward
N142 to the dollar or lower.
	   The yen, meanwhile, was not able to sustain its recovery from
Wednesday's N137.72 to a dollar, dropping to N138.12 to a
dollarWeak Thai Baht As Culprit -- BREAKERStill an unwilling
participant in the ebb and flow of the turmoil surrounding regional
currency markets, the peso closed slightly weaker yesterday after
corporations bought dollars when the exchange rate hit the P38/$1
range.
	   Corporations are buying on dips in the dollar buying rate,'' a
trader said.
	   ``Although banks are still scared to take big positions ...
there are still some holding on their dollars,'' he added.
	   The peso was weighed down by sluggish regional currencies,
especially the Thai baht.
	   The peso closed at P39.16 to the dollar, down from P38.88 on
Wednesday.
	   Turnover was moderate at $86.5 million.
	   ``The peso went down primarily due to the baht. The baht did not
depreciate even when the yen strengthened,'' a trader said.
	   The Thai currency hit a low of 43.15 to a dollar before settling
at 42.9 to a dollar.
	   The baht fared poorly after Moody's said on Wednesday that it
was unlikely to change Thailand's Ba1 sovereign rating in the next
six to 18 months as there might be fresh difficulties if the
government was unsuccessful in implementing planned reforms.
	   Thai central bank chief Chatu Mongol Sonakul said the baht at
the 40-45 per dollar level would not hurt the economy, but added
that the central bank would be watching developments and would try
and keep baht volatility down.
	   A 'Well Behaved' BSP -- BREAKERThe Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas
(BSP), which was expected to raise overnight rates to prevent
attacks on the peso, did not make an adjustment.
	   BSP Director for Economic Research Diwa Guinigundo stressed
central monetary authorities would not intervene in the market
unless absolutely necessary.
	   Traders had commented that the BSP was ``well-behaved,'' saying
the fall in the value of the peso did not warrant intervention.
	   Guinigundo also stressed prudent economics and a newfound market
oriented approach.
	   ``We do not subscribe to devaluation engineering as its efficacy
has been repudiated by recent events. It does not make sense to
propose absorbing capital inflows, avoid sterilization, and allow
the money supply to expand and induce interest rates to drop,'' he
said ``Where was the BSP in all these twists and turns of the peso
in recent times? Since the beginning of the year until May 8, the
BSP sold only $3 million to the foreign exchange market, while
buying $104.5 million.
	   Without such a stance, the peso could have been stronger,'' he
argued.
	   Guinigundo said BSP bought dollars to boost up its gross
international reserves and not ``to pursue a certain exchange rate
level.''
	   However, he admitted there were ``structural weaknesses''
present in varying degrees in all the regional economies, including
the Philippines.
	   ``There was undoubtedly some force that triggered the concerted
attack on regional currencies. There is no doubt, however, that the
ability of these economies to weather the storm and emerge from it,
whether bloodied or unscathed, whether sooner of later, depends
ultimately on the soundness of their policy environment,'' he said.

</TEXT>
