<SLUG> RP-SEEN-BUYING-GRAINS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RP Seen Buying More Grains, Sugar, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
RP Seen Buying More Grains, Sugar, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Philippines is likely to import more grain and sugar to
cover a domestic shortfall because of drought, officials and
industry analysts said yesterday.
	   Rain in the past few days will not have an immediate impact on
crops.
	   ``At least 1.5 million tons,'' Rolando Dy, director of the
Institute of Agribusiness Development and Policy of the University
of Asia and Pacific said when asked to give his forecast on the
country's rice imports this year.
	   ``For corn, (we) have to import some more. El Nino will continue
to affect coconut and sugar in 1999,'' he added.
	   The Philippines has had below-normal rains since April 1997.
	   Officials and meteorologists said the arrival of rains starting
in the middle of May eased drought in most parts of the country but
they also raised fears that El Nino's sibling -- La Nina -- may be
on its way and with it, torrential rain and flooding.
	   Theweather bureau has predicted a 30% probability for La Nina
hitting the country later this year.
	   So far this year government has imported a record 1.35 million
tons of rice, the staple of the 71 million Filipinos.
	   On Monday, President Fidel Ramos said he expected national rice
output in the second quarter to fall 28% from the year-ago 2.283
million tons.
	   The harvest in the first quarter dropped to 2.22 million tons
from the year-ago's 2.56 million tons.
	   The corn shortage is expected to reach between 500,000 tons and
1.5 million tons this year, analysts said.
	   ``We imported a lot already because of the drought. If La Nina
turns out to be a brat, then we might have to bite the bullet and
import more,'' an executive in one of the country's largest
feedmills told Reuters.
	   Feedmillers are set to seek tenders for the supply of 80,000
tons of corn on Friday.
	   The country has so far imported 245,000 tons of yellow corn from
the US, Argentina and China since the start of the year.
	   Industry executives said they do not expect feedmillers, poultry
and hog farmers to shift to buying substitutes like sorghum, rye
and barley despite the reduction by government on the tariff on the
import of the commodities this year.
	   ``Sorghum, rye and barley are poor substitutes. They have less
carbohydrate content. We are not interested to buy these
products,'' the feedmill executive said.
	   ``We wantgovernment to bring down the tariff on corn instead,''
he added.
	   The Philippines imposes a tariff of 35% to 80% on corn imports.
	   The country is also expected to import shortly 200,000 tons of
sugar because of increased demand from the local beverage industry,
which reported a 35% rise in sales in the first quarter, sugar
industry sources said.
	   The dry weather and the run-up to the May 11 presidential
elections, when candidates distributed food and drinks, spurred
increase in beverage and ice cream consumption, they said.
	   ``The rains should change the sugar picture in the next crop
year,'' Sugar Regulatory Administration chief Michael Suarez said.
	   This would enable farmers to replant wilted crops, he added.
	   But other industry sources said too much rain may bring down
yields because of lower sucrose content of the sugarcane.
	   Suarez had earlier predicted that the Philippines will import
360,000 tons of sugar in the next crop year.
	   Farmers also said the combined effects of El Nino and La Nina
may push down coconut output by as much as 41% this year.
	   ``Coconut trees need water but not too much,'' said Efren
Villasenor, president of the National Coalition of Small Coconut
Farmers and Workers Organizations.
	   Government has predicted a 10% drop in coconut output in copra
terms this year from 2.6 million in 1997.
	   
</TEXT>
