<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Injury to Helmer causing problems for Vogts
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: REPEATING to CORRECT slug to conform to digest. &QL; 
 &UR; By NESHA STARCEVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NICE, France (AP) _ The latest injury to hit versatile defender
and midfielder Thomas Helmer is the biggest shadow over Germany's
sunny headquarters on the French Riviera.
	   With one week to go before Germany opens its quest for a fourth
World Cup title against the United States in Paris, Helmer failed
to practice Monday because of a right thigh injury. Also missing
was wing back Christian Ziege, who is battling a fever.
	   ``It's a real, real shame for Thomas,'' coach Berti Vogts said
at his first news conference since the team's arrival Sunday.
	   ``He was being treated this morning and perhaps he can do some
light jogging this afternoon,'' Vogts said.
	   Helmer had just gotten over a thigh strain and played one half
and scored a goal in Germany's 7-0 thrashing of Luxembourg Friday.
Vogts said the new injury, a tensing of the muscle, was different
from the old one.
	   Dr. Hans-Willhelm Mueller-Wohlfahrt, a team physician who also
is Helmer's club doctor at Bayern Munich, was flying in and would
examine the player before giving an update on Helmer's condition.
	   ``The doctor's arrival was planned long in advance, it has
nothing to do with this injury,'' Vogts said.
	   Helmer, the 33-year-old Bayern Munich captain, had to break off
Germany's first practice Sunday afternoon, which also was missed by
Ziege.
	   ``He was coming back very well after his original injury,
especially mentally, and I hope he doesn't get down again now,''
Vogts said.
	   Helmer is one of the team leaders who can play as a central
defender, a defensive midfielder, or even as a libero.
	   The 20 healthy players had a light workout Monday morning at the
Charles Ehrmann stadium at a Nice suburb, not far away from the
team's headquarters at the four-star Mas d'Artigny, a wooded,
secluded compound in the hills above Nice.
	   ``We have ideal conditions, from the hotel to the training
grounds and I hope we stay here a long time,'' Vogts said. The team
has reserved its rooms for a month, obviously hoping to reach at
least the semifinals.
	   Monday evening, the Germans played a charity match against a
local selection made up mostly of juniors.
</TEXT>
