<HEADLINE>
Hip-pocket pain `priority', HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Hip-pocket pain `priority', HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   May TamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PRO-BEIJING party boss Jasper Tsang Yok-sing has expressed
reservations about the immediate need to amend the Basic Law to
bring forward full democracy.
	   Speaking on the RTHK program Letter To Hong Kong, the chairman
of the Democratic Alliance for the Betterment of Hong Kong said
nobody ``apart from a few demagogues'' believed the solution to
economic problems lay in holding more elections.
	   ``Many now realise we have been too pessimistic about our
political situation and too optimistic about our economy.'' Mr
Tsang, a legislator-elect, stressed that any successful political
reform must have public support.
	   He pointed out that Hong Kong people's greatest worry about
interference from the Central Government had eased one year after
the handover.
	   Although they still wanted democracy, people no longer believed
it was the answer to their most pressing economic problems, he
said.
	   ``People are unhappy with the devaluation of their property and
stocks, with the closing down of large department stores, and with
the rising unemployment rate.
	   ``The Basic Law can be changed, and the date of realising the
goal of full democracy can be brought forward, but only when the
majority of the population understand fully the implications of the
change and support it,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
