<HEADLINE>
Never Too Early, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Never Too Early, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Cha Cha is desirable and should be initiated at the earliest
time possible.
	   The consensus is that the Constitution can stand a lot of
improvement. But the process of revision should be deliberate, not
rushed.
	   Thus, with retired Supreme Court Justice Cecilia Munoz Palma
taking the lead in organizing a Constitutional Convention, we
should be able to put together a credible organization of delegates
(hopefully a majority) with vision. Planning for the assembly will
likely be as important as the convention itself.
	   Camouflaged Revisions What undoubtedly will be a major issue is
a shift from a presidential to a parliamentary system. Certainly,
both systems have their merits and shortcomings. But whichever the
assembly's final choice should ensure that current major
infirmities are totally eliminated from either of the systems and
are not reinserted as camouflaged, insidious revisions. The
fundamental change should revolve around a strong party system that
will nevertheless ensure for independent candidacies as close to
equal playing fields as possible. The mechanism should neutralize
the advantages of highest bidders.
	   
</TEXT>
