	   TAI chi has taken centre stage in Central Park, New York, where
the Hong Kong Tourist Association launched a colourful campaign to
attract American tourists.
	   More than 1,000 lovers of the ancient Chinese martial art turned
out at the ceremony officiated by Chief Secretary for
Administration Anson Chan Fang On-sang to open the ``Hong Kong _
City of Life'' tourist promotion.
	   Mrs Chan urged New Yorkers to ``come and see for yourselves''
what made Hong Kong a city of life.
	   ``Hong Kong is at the cutting edge of Asian creativity, as New
York is the creative heartland for America,'' she said.
	   Mrs Chan attributed the attraction of Hong Kong to its
diversity, citing the availability of shopping places and the wide
variety of restaurants.
	   Of course, the most amazing experience would be to land in the
world's newest airport in Chek Lap Kok, to be opened in July, she
said.
	   ``Take the trip in the next few months, you will be among the
first to land at the world's newest airport _ Hong Kong
International at Chek Lap Kok _ a US$20 billion (HK$155 billion)
project,'' Mrs Chan told crowds at Central Park's Wollman Rink.
	   A series of Tai chi demonstrations by expatriates was staged in
the venue.
	   Tai chi is considered by foreigners as one of the mysterious
aspects of Chinese culture.
	   Hong Kong tourism has seen an unprecedented decline in the wake
of the Asian financial turmoil.
	   
</TEXT>
