<SLUG> URGE-CREDIT-CRUNCH-PROBE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Alliance head to urge credit crunch probe, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Alliance head to urge credit crunch probe, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   May TamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE leader of the new alliance of seven political parties is to
demand a probe into why local banks have brought on a credit
crunch.
	   Liberal Party chairman Allen Lee Peng-fei on Sunday said he
would ask Financial Secretary Sir Donald Tsang Yam-kuen on Tuesday
to look into why local banks were refusing to offer loans to their
customers.
	   Mr Lee, along with other party leaders, and Sir Donald will also
discuss the government's response to a package of six measures
proposed by the alliance to boost the sagging economy.
	   Mr Lee, who is also a member of Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa's
think-tank on long-term development strategy, told the City Forum
that the banks' practices had led to a credit crunch which had
brought ``great harm to our business environment''.
	   ``I will ask him to investigate the reasons for such practices,
and secondly, I will ask him to probe into how the banks use the
money they get from deposits,'' Mr Lee said.
	   ``The banks now refuse to offer loans to business firms, refuse
mortgages, and shrink the lending money for letters of credit,
too.'' Other speakers at the forum showed the same concern over the
credit crunch.
	   Dr Frances Lui Ting-ming, director of the Centre for Economic
Development of the Hong Kong University of Science and Technology,
said: ``The seriousness of the blows to the economy brought by the
shrinking of bank credit is three times that brought by
unemployment.'' Mr Lee said he would ask Sir Donald to accept all
six of the alliance proposals, stressing that there could be no
compromise.
	   The six measures include reducing property rates and government
charges, speeding up infrastructure projects, and looking into
problems of high interest rates.
	   He gave a strong hint that the legislature could make it
difficult for the government to enact its pet measures if these
proposals were not carried out.
	   However legislators who spoke at the forum said they were not
striking against the executive-led principle of SAR government.
	   Independent legislator Eric Li Ka-cheung, who represents the
Accountancy constituency, said: ``We are not forcing the government
but such a move is very meaningful because the politicians have
moved a first step to form a consensus, and the government has
emphasised they will co-operate with us.'' All speakers regarded
the government as financially able to reduce rates and public
charges with its enormous reserves.
	   Other measures suggested to ease the downturn included scrapping
the existing labour importation scheme, urging real estate owners
to reduce rents, and encouraging the private sector to start
businesses with tax rebates or subsidies.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
