<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Hunger,0364 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Number of malnourished children rises six-fold in southern Sudan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ The number of severely malnourished
children in six feeding centers in Sudan's southwestern Bahr el
Ghazal province has increased six-fold in the past three months
weeks, a humanitarian group said Monday.
	   The number of children requiring supplementary feeding has
jumped from 808 on March 22 to 5,037 May 31, Medicins Sans
Frontieres, or Doctors Without Borders, said in a statement.
	   ``There is a serious deterioration in the nutritional status of
the vulnerable population in southern Sudan,'' the statement quoted
Marc Hermant, head of mission, as saying. ``Over half of the
children attending our feeding centers are not improving because
the distribution of food to the general population is inadequate.''
	   The statement said the MSF, which operates in the area in
conjunction with Operation Lifeline Sudan, a United Nations
umbrella organization of aid agencies, cannot deliver enough food
for 930,000 needy people in areas in southern Sudan where both
government troops and the Sudan People's Liberation Army are
present.
	   Bahr el Ghazal has already suffered two consecutive poor
harvests due to fighting between the predominantly African, animist
and Christian southerners who are pressing for autonomy from the
Muslim and Arabized north.
	   ``It is crucial that sufficient food is distributed to sustain
families in the period up to and beyond the next harvest and seeds
and tools must also be in place before the onset of heavy rains,''
Hermant said.
	   An estimated 1.5 million people have died due to fighting and
accompanying famines.
	   Meanwhile, fighters of the National Democratic Alliance, which
is allied with the SPLA, said Monday they had captured two
garrisons near Kassala, about 425 kilometers (265 miles) east of
the Sudanese capital, Khartoum.
	   A statement released in Nairobi said the battle took place
Friday and that NDA troops captured an assortment of arms from the
government forces.
	   The rebel claim could not be independently verified, and it was
not immediately possible to obtain comment from Khartoum. 	   
</TEXT>
