<SLUG> CPA-REJECTS-ADB'S sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CPA rejects ADB's preconditions to package investment, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
CPA rejects ADB's preconditions to package investment, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Chittagong Port Authority rejected the preconditions tagged
by ADB to a multi-million-dollar package investment for upgrading
the seaport, reports APB.
	   Officials said the Asian Development Bank asked for full
privatisation of port operations while holding out 43 million
dollars in loan for modernising the Chittagong and Mongla ports.
	   A few days back, ADB had submitted the final report on
``Bangladesh Port Upgrading Project'' to CPA asking them to reply
by June 10 whether they were ready to accept the terms and
conditions.
	   CPA in a meeting yesterday disapproved of the ADB preconditions
``in greater interest of the national economy as well as of the
Chittagong Port.'' CPA's acting Chairman Zahiruddin Mahmood
presided.
	   However, CPA agreed on partial offloading of the port activities
for bringing competitiveness, raising efficiency and gearing up
operations of the country's biggest seaport.
	   ``Main thrust of privatisation is on creating a competitive
atmosphere in port operations,'' the meeting observed.
	   ``But full-scale privatisation of port activities would create a
private monopoly which might breed manifold problems.''
	   Moreover, several thousand workers and employees of the port
will be jobless if the port activities, now conducted under direct
supervision of the CPA, are fully made over to the private sector.
That will spark labour unrest.
	   ``Considering all this the preconditions of full privatisation
of port activities cannot be accepted at this stage,'' the meeting
concluded.
	   
</TEXT>
