<SLUG> BC-Russia-Clash, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Villagers in Caucasus hold bus to avenge alleged abduction
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with 6 passengers released. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Villagers in Russia's southern republic of North
Ossetia detained five bus passengers on Monday in apparent
retaliation for the kidnapping of several neighbors, officials
said.
	   The bus passengers were from the neighboring republic of
Ingushetia. Ingush were blamed for abducting seven residents from
the village of Batako in North Ossetia on Sunday.
	   Both North Ossetia and Ingushetia are located in the North
Caucasus, a restive region that also includes breakaway Chechnya.
	   The Interfax news agency quoted Ossetian officials as saying
residents of Batako detained two buses with 40 residents. They let
one bus go and released women and elderly people from the second
bus. Six men were released after talks with government officials.
	   Talks continued to gain the release of the remaining five
passengers, the ITAR-Tass news agency said.
	   Predominantly Orthodox Christian North Ossetia has maintained
warmer relations with Moscow than other parts of the North Caucasus
and served as a base for Russia's 1994-96 campaign against Chechen
separatists.
	   North Ossetia and neighboring Muslim Ingushetia fought a short
but bloody war in 1992. Hundreds of people were killed and most
ethnic Ingush were expelled from North Ossetia.
	   Both sides have blamed each other for numerous kidnappings.
	   (vi/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
