WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A three member delegation of Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujib Medical
University made a courtesy call on President Justice Shahabuddin
Ahmed at Bangabhaban yesterday.
	   Vice-Chancellor of the university Professor Dr MA Quaderi led
the delegation.
	   The members of the delegation apprised the President, who is
also the Chancellor of the University, of the initial problems
faced by the management of the newly-established university,
including transfer of some teachers and staff of the new defunct
IPGMR, absorption of some of them in the university, allocation of
fund to the university and related matters.
	   They said private initiatives for setting up specialised
hospitals in the country are essential for taking care of the
patients who now abroad for treatment.
	   They said the university could render better service to the
patients, specially to the heart patients, at a lower cost if the
government comes forward with necessary fund for setting up such
treatment facilities.
	   President Shahabuddin said time has come to take positive steps
for setting up specialised treatment facilities in the country.
	   He said he will talk to the appropriate authorities for solving
the problems faced by them.
	   Prof Mohammad Tahir, pro-vice-chancellor and Prof KM Iqbal,
treasurer of the university, were present on the occasion.
	   
