<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Media-Zimbabwe, HFR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
For release at 0001 GMT Tuesday June 9
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to fix overline garble &QL; 
 &UR; Anticensorship group criticizes Zimbabwe government control of
media &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Zimbabwe's government exercises tight control over
the mass media, and recently ordered radio and TV reporters to
highlight unfounded allegations that whites were behind
antigovernment protests, an international organization against
censorship said in a report released Tuesday.
	   The group, Article 19, said President Robert Mugabe's
government, which faces increasing unrest, and charges of
corruption and economic mismanagement, tolerates independent
newspapers as long as they cater only for a small business
readership.
	   ``Recently staff at the Zimbabwe Broadcasting Corporation have
been reprimanded and even sacked for coverage of political protest
deemed to be too sympathetic,'' said Article 19, named after the
provision in the Universal Declaration of Human Rights for freedom
of expression.
	   It added that the editor of The Herald, the main daily
newspaper, was recently fired after an editorial criticized the
government's handling of food price protests in January. Tommy
Sithole, who the report said ``was always seen as an uncompromising
defender of the government,'' was replaced by a Mugabe relative.
	   Article 19 urged broader ownership of the media, repeal of
censorship laws, a Freedom of Information Act and the right of
journalists to protect their sources.
	   The government owns all radio and TV in Zimbabwe, as well as the
main newspapers through a state-controlled trust.
	   ``The government exerts a degree of direct control over the mass
media almost without parallel in southern Africa,'' said the
report. '' ... The independent press is often outspoken but is
constantly inhibited by both legal and economic restrictions.''
	   Article 19 said the independent media has produced some skilled
and courageous journalists. It did not identify individuals, but
said many of these journalists now work on publications such as the
Zimbabwe Independent, a weekly, and Horizon, a monthly. But between
them, these publications sell fewer than 60,000 copies, compared
with the 200,000 daily circulation of The Herald and The Chronicle,
the other main daily based in the southern province of
Matabeleland.
	   Citing other forms of official censorship, Article 19 said the
mass media has been used to promote Mugabe's antipathy toward
homosexuals.
	   The group praised the Zimbabwe Supreme Court for upholding
constitutional rights, but the government responded by swiftly
amending the constitution ``when it finds itself on the wrong end
of a court decision.''
	   (mj)
</TEXT>
