<SLUG> PM-OPENS-BANGABANDHU sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PM opens Bangabandhu Museum: Memories of 6-point movement recalled, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
PM opens Bangabandhu Museum: Memories of 6-point movement recalled, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina yesterday said a nation cannot
raise its head with dignity and honour if it does not know the
glorious history of its independence movement and liberation war.
	   ``This museum will remain as a symbol in the national history
and project the glorious history of our liberation struggle,'' she
said inaugurating the Bangabandhu Museum at Dhaka Cantonment
yesterday morning.
	   The museum was built to preserve the memories of the historic
Agartala conspiracy case. Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman and 34
others accused in the case were arrested and confined to this
building during the Agartala trial case.
	   The trial of the case, State versus Bangabandhu and others or
the so-called Agartala conspiracy case, began on February 21 in
1968 at a special tribunal.
	   Later, in the face of mass movement, the then Ayub regime was
forced to release Bangabandhu Mujib.
	   The building touched with the memory of Sheikh Mujib has now
turned into a museum. It preserves the room where Bangabandhu was
detained. There is a library, lobby, photo gallery, reception room,
office room and document room.
	   The lobby of the museum was decorated with photographs on the
historic six-point movement, photographs of the accused in the
Agartala conspiracy case and paper cuttings of those eventful days.
A spectacular fountain was set up in front of the museum.
	   Speaking at the function, the Prime Minister recalled the
memories of the six-point movement, the days of Bangabandhu's
confinement in the building and historic events of independence
movement.
	   ``Our independence did not come in one day, a lot of sacrifices,
bloods, movements and memories are behind it,'' she said, adding
that the nation should know the sacrifices of its heroes.
	   Hasina said the glorious history had been suppressed for a long
time, the nation was not allowed to know the sagas of its heroes.
``We want to free the nation from the grip of distorted history and
taking steps in this regard.''
	   She recalled the sacrifices of the martyrs of the independence
movement, liberation war and the democratic movements of the
country.
	   The Prime Minister thanked the members of the armed forces for
preserving the building touched with memories of the Father of the
Nation Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman.
	   An accused in the Agartala case, Col (retd) Shawkat Ali, MP and
Chief of Army Staff Lt Gen Mustafizur Rahman spoke at the function.
	   Later, the Prime Minister unveiled a plaque opening the museum
for the public. She went round different rooms of the museum and
talked to members of the families of some accused in the case.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
