<BODY>
<SLUG> MUSLIM-CEMETERY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Grave plots `re-used' in Muslim cemetery, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Grave plots `re-used' in Muslim cemetery, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Virginia MaherASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   LEADERS of the Muslim community have expressed shock over what
is being politely termed ``the indiscriminate removal of
gravestones'' and the summary sacking of two grave diggers.
	   The Incorporated Trustees of the Islamic Community Fund of Hong
Kong are being accused of ignoring evidence that moving the stones
has led to at least one burial plot at the Chai Wan cemetery being
re-used.
	   Although there is no law _ religious or otherwise _ against the
re-use of grave plots in Muslim cemeteries, there is no such
understanding in Hong Kong.
	   Matters came to a head on 24 December last year when at least
one grave was exhumed and two of the grave diggers who spoke out
against re-using the plot were sacked on ``trumped up charges''.
	   The accusations come from a former appointed member of the
Muslim Cemeteries Management Committee who claims the trustees have
refused repeated requests to meet and discuss the issue.
	   He is A Ramjahn who said this indiscriminate removal of the
gravestones, especially in older sections of the cemetery where
many graves have been flattened by years of rain and soil erosion,
means ``there is no way of tracing the graves''.
	   He pointed to places along the road leading from the Cape
Collinson Crematorium down to the Muslim Cemetery, where discarded
grave markers have been unceremoniously tossed on the hillside.
	   Repeated attempts to get the trustees to look into the matter of
the missing stone grave markers were met by silence, he said.
	   The Hong Kong Standard managed to speak to the Treasurer, Rubbya
Hassan, who said she was not the right person to comment when asked
if the two workers had been sacked unfairly.
	   She promised to pass the questions on to the secretary.
	   The secretary when called, refused to answer any questions. The
chairman was not available for comment.
	   On 24 December last year, parts of a human skeleton were
unearthed by diggers preparing a ``fresh'' grave at the Chai Wan
cemetery.
	   The grave was covered up and work began on the plot next to it.
	   When bones were found in the second grave, one of the grave
diggers, Amir Bahadur, refused to defile the grave and reported the
matter to an alternate trustee who went with him the next day to
the site.
	   A second grave digger, Aijaz Mohammed, who made a similar
discovery, was not as fortunate _ he was ordered to keep working.
Mr Mohammed complied, but was refused permission to see the
trustees when he tried later to tell them what had transpired.
	   Haji A R Karamdin, to whom Mr Bahadur had turned for help,
called in Mr Ramjahn and together they went to the Chai Wan
cemetery on 25 December and examined the bones found in the grave.
	   Removal of one of the wooden frames used in Muslim burials
revealed parts of a skull and a set of false teeth. The skull
appeared to have been crushed by the burial frame.
	   Further examination showed that the digging for the ``new
grave'' had exhumed half an old grave. Mr Ramjahn subsequently
submitted a report on the matter to the council.
	   Almost five months on, he has had no acknowledgment of his
report.
	   The only movement of any sort in the case has been the summary
dismissal of Mr Bahadur and Mr Mohammed on 31 March.
	   Their almost identical letters of dismissal list allegations of
misconduct dating back to December.
	   Neither was given the opportunity to appeal against the
allegations.
	   Two members of the Chinese Muslim community were visibly shaken
when told of the saga of the bones in the Chai Wan graves.
	   ``It is very shocking. It makes us all feel uncomfortable,''
said Haji Ebrahim Yang, secretary of the Chinese Muslim Cultural
and Fraternal Association.
	   Haji Kassim Ma, a member of the executive committee, called for
a review of how work at the cemeteries was carried out.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
