<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Islam </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Islamic women sidestep Turkish headscarf ban by wearing wigs
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ In the ongoing battle between the
religious and secular in Turkey, some women have found an ingenious
way to bypass the government's ban on headscarves: wearing a scarf,
but hiding it with a wig.
	   The government says headscarves have become a political gesture,
a symbol of too-fervent Islam that threatens Turkey's secular
system. It has cracked down on the practice, calling for stricter
enforcement of the scarf ban in schools and public offices.
	   To sidestep the law, some women have turned to wigs, boosting
the business of people like Emel Ozkaynak, of the Princess Wig
House in Ankara. ``It is very profitable,'' he said. ``I hope it
lasts a long time.''
	   Under Turkish law, women can be fined up a fourth of the
salaries for wearing scarves in public offices and schools.
	   Men would face even stiffer punishment under a measureparliament
is expected to approve shortly. It provides for prison terms for up
to a year for laymen wearing Islamic headgear in public.
	   (ht-sh)
</TEXT>
