<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Markets, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai stocks hit 11-year low; currency down
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with new graf 2 as baht finishes lower. More currency
info in last 3 grafs.
 &UR; AP Photo BK102

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thai stock prices hit an 11-year low
Monday as investors dumped the stock of the country's biggest
finance company after it decided to sell half of its securities
subsidiary.
	   The Thai baht also tumbled Monday, ending the trading day at 44
to the U.S. dollar, it's lowest level in 13 weeks. The baht has
dropped 40.3 percent against the dollar since it was floated last
July, triggering economic problems across the region.
	   The Stock Exchange of Thailand closed down 5.79 points to 312.37
on Monday. Dealers said the index hasn't seen such lows since 1987,
blaming the drop on regional currency woes and the move by Phatra
Thanakit PCL.
	   Phatra Thanakit announced last week that it would sell a 51
percent stake in a subsidiary, Phatra Securities Co., to Merrill
Lynch and Co.
	   Dealers said it could be the beginning of the end of Phatra's
listing on the exchange, since top Phatra executives said they were
considering merging the company's finance operations into those of
Thai Farmers Bank PCL, its biggest shareholder.
	   Currency traders attributed the baht's fall to a regional
currency sell-off as the dollar rose above 140 Japanese yen for the
first time since June 1991.
	   The weakness of the Japanese currency, dealers said, spells
trouble for crisis-hit Southeast Asian economies that have been
increasingly dependent on Japan as an export market.
	   Fears are rising that the Asian economic crisis could enter a
new, more devastating phase.
</TEXT>
