<BODY>
<SLUG> STARS'-TRASH-DIVE-FALLS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Stars' trash dive falls flat, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Stars' trash dive falls flat, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Valerie BolcinaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   LOCAL film stars and directors dived into Hong Kong waters for
garbage on Sunday _ and came up almost empty-handed.
	   The celebrities were called in to help clean up Middle Bay beach
in time for today's World Oceans Day.
	   They donned deep-sea diving equipment but kept well within the
shark nets in the wake of a suspected shark sighting last month.
	   The aim was to scour the seabed for litter, but as action man
Tung Wai said: ``No lap-sap (garbage).'' The World Wide Fund for
Nature Hong Kong was behind the cleansing operation, and had agreed
with the Urban Services Department (USD) on which beach to clean
up.
	   Some campaigners and celebrities were surprised to find the
beach spotless, and wondered whether the USD had sent an advance
party of cleaners to the beach to make a pleasant environment for
the beautiful people.
	   A total of 35 pounds of rubbish was collected by 15 divers in a
half-hour's underwater action.
	   Most of the rubbish was in the form of rusty pipes and
soft-drink cans.
	   Actress Theresa Lee Yee-hung, WWFHK's ambassador for the past
three years, did not take part in the dive, and said she usually
avoided Hong Kong waters as they were too polluted.
	   She said: ``Hong Kong people are very unknowledgable about the
environment _ I want to help raise awareness.'' Director Michael
Hui Koon-man said: ``I came here 25 years ago with my girlfriend,
and we threw coins into the sea. Now I am helping take things out
of the water.'' Director Teddy Chan Tak-sum often dives with
friends, but not in Hong Kong waters.
	   Windsurfer-turned-actor Wong Hop Hei said: ``We want all Hong
Kong beaches to be clean.'' Middle Bay was recently downgraded from
a Grade 1 to a Grade 2 beach.
	   
