	   The Dairy Poultry and Fishery Federation of Bangladesh (DPFFB)
yesterday demanded an allocation of Tk 1,500 crore in the budget to
promote a ``white revolution'' in the country.
	   Addressing a press conference at the National Press Club,
Marshal Shah Alam, President of the DPFFB, said that improvement of
the country's dairy, poultry and fisheries sectors could not only
solve the unemployment problem but also provide the people of the
country with nutrition.
	   Demanding stoppage of the advertisement of all types of milk
powder on the state-owned radio and television, he said that
marketing of milk powder and its pasteurised liquid in polibags was
a great hazard to the health of children.
	   He observed that import of milk powder from member states of the
EC would destroy the live-stock sector of the country.
	   ``Though the fisheries sector became one of the major sources of
foreign exchange, there were no direction for this sector in the
national budget'', Shah Alam said adding that fish worth Tk 70,000
crore were misused in the last 11 years due to the lack of a
national policy.
	   Harun-or-Rashid, Abdur Rouf, Khayer Chowdhury and Ziaul Haq
Bulbul, leaders of Live-stock, Poultry and Fishery Firm Owners
Associations of Gajipur, Nandail, Brahmanbaria and Gaibandha
respectively were present at the press conference.
	   
