<BODY>
<SLUG> SAFETY-PLAN-LAUNCHED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Safety plan launched to curb road mishaps, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Safety plan launched to curb road mishaps, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The National Road Safety Strategic Action Plan aimed at curbing
road accidents and fatalities was launched by Communications
Minister Anwar Hossain in the city yesterday.
	   Organised by Bangladesh Road Transport Authority (BRTA) in
association with the Department for International Development of
the United Kingdom and the IDC project, the launching ceremony was
chaired by Syed Rezaul Hayat, Secretary of the Roads and Railway
Division.
	   The inaugural ceremony was addressed by AN Hossain, Chairman of
BRTA, National Professor Dr. MR Khan of ICDDRB and Roger
Weatherell,
	   IDC Team Leader.
	   Over 3,000 persons were killed in road accidents in the country
last year. The number of the people killed in road accidents was
only 1,156 a decade ago in 1987.
	   The Action Plan is the result of extensive reviews of road
safety issues and inputs from overseas safety specialists. It has
components for improving the roads and vehicles.
	   Until recently in Bangladesh, road safety was addressed only
through temporary measures occasionally taken after major road
accidents. As a result, previous road safety initiatives suffered
from a lack of co-ordination and continuity.
	   The National Road Safety Council (NRSC) was constituted in July
1995 and assigned the responsibility of preparing and implementing
a national plan on road safety. The NRSC, chaired by the Minister
for Communications, consists of representatives from the government
and professionals from other organisations.
	   Speaking on the occasion, the Communications Minister, called
upon the people to cooperate with the government in making road
communication safe and accident free.
	   The minister said the growth in our road network is proceeding
at a breathtaking rate providing more jobs and greater and faster
mobility for all. In this regard, he mentioned that the opening of
the Bangabandhu Bridge on June 23 would be a big step toward
integrating the country divided by the river Jamuna. The Minister
stressed on the need for a co-ordinated approach to tackle the road
safety problem.
	   AN Hossain, Member-secretary of the NRSC said road safety
committees have been formed in the metropolitan cities and
districts with the Metropolitan Police Commissioner and the
District Commissioner as the convener of the committees
respectively. These committees are already working in accordance
with the action plan, he added.
	   Later, a day-long workshop on the Action Plan was held. It was
participated by some 75 representatives from government and private
agencies involved in the road safety strategic plan.
	   
</TEXT>
