<SLUG> SURVEY-REVEALS-PARENTAL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Survey reveals parental ignorance of schooling, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Survey reveals parental ignorance of schooling, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Cynthia WanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SOME parents are still ignorant about certain education policies
such as the nine-year compulsory education and the prohibition of
corporal punishment, a survey has shown.
	   Of a total of 1,763 parents polled by the Education Policy
Concern Organisation (Epco), 42 were unaware of the fact that
children had to complete at least nine years of basic education
under Hong Kong laws, with another 23 saying they were uncertain
about it.
	   As many as 301 of them still believed school heads could inflict
corporal punishment on students, and another 130 were not sure
about that policy.
	   Also, 134 were mistaken that all secondary schools would have to
use Chinese as the medium of instruction from September, with a
further 315 unable to answer ``yes'' or ``no'' to the question.
	   Up to 45 per cent were either unaware or unsure that schools are
answerable on education quality.
	   About 29 per cent did not know of any channels to express their
opinions about education.
	   The interviewed parents are from seven secondary schools, seven
primary schools and three kindergartens.
	   
</TEXT>
