<HEADLINE>
Historic 7th June observed, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Historic 7th June observed, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The nation yesterday observed the historic June 7 commemorating
the blood-strained struggle for realisation of the historic
six-point demand, that inspired the whole nation to fight for
self-rule.
	   The movement of the 6-point demand led by Bangabandhu Sheikh
Mujibur Rahman culminated into a mass upsurge in 1969, that
eventually led the nation to launch the heroic War of Liberation
from Pakistan in 1971.
	   The day's programme began with the laying of wreaths by the
portrait of the Father of the Nation Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur
Rahman, at the ``Bangabandhu Smriti Jadughar'', by hundreds of
leaders and workers of Awami League and its front organisations.
	   Prime Minister and Awami League president Sheikh Hasina placed a
wreath by Bangabandhu's portrait early in the morning.
	   On this day in 1969, industrial workers Monu Mia, Shafiq and
Shamsul Huq were killed by the Pakistani police during a
nation-wide hartal, called by Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman to
press for realisation of the six-point demand.
	   By observing the nation-wide hartal, the Bengalees of the then
East Pakistan demonstrated their total support to the six-point
demand.
	   The day was observed amid various programmes by Awami League,
Chhatra League and Sramik League. Awami League and its front
organisations hoisted national and party flags atop ``Bangabandhu
Bhaban'' and their party offices across the country. Prayers were
also held for the peace of the martyrs of June 7.
	   The main programme of the day was a public meeting at Paltan
maidan where Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina spoke as the chief guest.
	   Bangladesh Betar and Bangladesh Television presented special
programmes commemorating the day, while major national newspapers
published special articles highlighting the significance of the
historic June 7.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
