<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Nuclear, 1st Ld-Writethru,0615 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
India says U.N. resolution on nuclear, missile programs
</HEADLINE>
unacceptable
 &UR; Eds: RESTORES Monday in lead, ADDS comments from Japanese
ambassador visiting Bombay. Trims. No pickup.
 &UR; By ASHOK SHARMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee
mantained his refusal to shut down India's nuclear weapons program
despite pressure from the U.N. Security Council.
	   ``The call made in the resolution that we should stop our
nuclear programs or missile programs is unacceptable ...,''
Vajpayee said in a statement faxed to The Associated Press.
	   Vajpayee made a similar statement in India's upper house of
Parliament earlier Monday, two days after the 15-member Security
Council passed a resolution asking longtime rivals India and
Pakistan to resume talks to solve their disputes, especially over
the Himalayan territory of Kashmir
	   The two countries escalated their arms race with a series of
tit-for-tat nuclear tests last month.
	   The Indian government on Saturday released a statement calling
the Security Council resolution ``coercive and unhelpful.''
Vajpayee has said in the past that India went nuclear because of
its fears of being surrounded by the nuclear weapons of neighbors
China and Pakistan.
	   Vajpayee also reiterated his oft-repeated statement since his
country's recent nuclear tests that India will not let any other
nation mediate in the Kashmir dispute.
	   India has consistently resisted international pressure on
Kashmir, while Pakistan welcomes intervention because it feels at a
disadvantage in one-on-one talks with its much larger and more
powerful neighbor.
	   India has been seeking talks with Pakistan since January, but
Islamabad has not replied, Vajpayee told Parliament.
	   The Security Council also called on India and Pakistan to sign
the nuclear nonproliferation treaty and a test ban accord.
	   India has repeatedly refused to sign the treaties because they
do not require the five traditional nuclear powers _ Britain,
China, France, Russia and the United States _ to give up their
nuclear arsenals. Pakistan says it will sign the treaty only if
India does so.
	   In India's financial hub of Bombay on Monday, Japanese
Ambassador Hiroshi Hirabayashi told Indian and Japanese businessmen
that the economic sanctions Tokyo imposed to punish India for its
nuclear tests would affect only new government proposals, not
ongoing development aid or loans and humanitarian aid.
	   He urged the Japanese private sector ``to continue business with
India as usual .... The Japanese government had no intention to
restrict trade with India.''
	   Japan is India's biggest aid donor third largest trading
partner.
	   ``We hope that with dialogue between India and Pakistan in the
not so distant future we can put this issue (nuclear testing)
behind us,'' Hirabayashi said. ``The international community will
lend a helping hand if asked by both countries.''
	   The United States, Australia and other countries also imposed
sanctions, the effect of which is yet unclear.
	   In its response to the Security Council, Pakistan said Sunday
that it cannot be compelled to sign the nuclear arms control
treaties. It also expressed disappointment that the council's
resolution did not offer concrete steps toward resolving the
Kashmir dispute.
	   Two of the three wars India and Pakistan have fought in the last
50 years were over Kashmir, a former kingdom that had a Muslim
majority and a Hindu ruler. Officially Islamic Pakistan holds
one-third of Kashmir, and India's two-thirds is the only
Muslim-majority state in the predominantly Hindu country. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-India-Nuclear, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
