</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Train Derails </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rail officials try to restore confidence after deadliest postwar
</HEADLINE>
crash &QL; 
 &UR; By COLLEEN BARRY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Still unsure how a wheel on one of its
premier high-speed trains could have broken, the German railway on
Monday intensified safety checks and assurances it would spare no
costs to restore confidence in rail travel.
	   Workers laid new tracks in the northern village of Eschede, the
scene of Germany's worst postwar rail disaster, in hopes of
reopening the Hanover-Hamburg line by midweek. Rescue workers
continued sifting through loose dirt five days after the crash in
search of personal effects and human remains.
	   Officials lowered the death toll on Sunday after a new analysis
of remains so badly damaged in Wednesday's wreck of InterCity
Express 884 that forensic experts say DNA analysis will be
necessary to make some identifications.
	   They now believe 93 people died at the scene; 73 victims have
been identified. Five died in hospitals.
	   German rail director Johannes Ludewig said that inspectors
checking wheels on the 59 original high-speed trains have found no
defects so far. By Monday, 400 of the 700 wheels had passed
inspections.
	   Officials doubled the number of ultrasound machines and
inspectors on Monday to restore full service at the normal top
speed of 280 kilometers (175 miles) as soon as possible.
	   ``You win trust only with safety,'' said Ludewig. He and
Transport Minister Matthias Wissmann are considering new safety
features, such as a wheel alarm system. They have not ruled out
redesigning the trains.
	   But Ludewig conceded that the railway still had a long way to go
to resume its place as one of the most trusted German institutions.
The high-speed rail has been a source of national pride since its
introduction in 1991.
	   ``Of course, our image was damaged by the catastrophe. Only
complete openness will reverse that,'' Ludewig said.
	   It remains unclear whether the train's wheel broke due to a
defect, or an outside force.
	   Investigators know that somehow the steel rim encircling the
wheel broke off and was propelled into the wheel carriage. They
theorized that the train derailed when it hit a rail switch about
300 meters (985 feet) from an overpass. Traveling at a speed of 200
kilometers (125 miles) an hour, the train struck the overpass,
bringing down 200-300 tons of concrete, steel and roadway onto the
jackknifing cars.
	   German President Roman Herzog will lead a memorial service for
the victims and their families on June 21 in Celle, the main town
outside of Eschede. Officials delayed the service, originally
scheduled for Friday, due to the slow job of recovering and
identifying the dead.
	   (cb/aet) 	   
</TEXT>
