<BODY>
<SLUG> STEPFATHER-FACE-A-HIDING sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Stepfathers face a hiding for `cruelty', HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Stepfathers face a hiding for `cruelty', HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Ceri WilliamsASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE stereotyping of the cruel stepfather was even stronger in
Chinese families than in the West, a leading welfare expert said on
Sunday.
	   Thomas Mulvey, director of the Hong Kong Family Welfare Society,
said children could be torn apart by their natural father's family
if their mother remarried.
	   ``The father's family can create problems and portray the
stepfather as a cruel figure. The problem for children can be even
more intense in Chinese societies which emphasise more
relationships along the father's line than those in the West.'' Mr
Mulvey said even if the natural father did not feel any hostility
towards the new stepfather, his own family might still try to turn
the children against him.
	   He said his group also came across cases of children feeling
very hostile to stepmothers and had completely rejected them.
	   ``But this problem is found as often in Western families as
Chinese.'' Mr Mulvey said the Hong Kong Family Welfare Society had
launched a new divorce mediation service as figures showed the
number of divorce cases had increased from 537 in 1974 to 10,492 by
the end of October last year.
	   And new research shows that stepfathers can get the ``baby
blues'' too. They were especially at risk if their wives or
partners are depressed, it was revealed yesterday.
	   A study of British men found that stepfathers were particularly
at risk of such depression.
	   Mr Mulvey said he had come across cases of husbands developing
physical symptoms like appendicitis before their wives gave birth,
but he had not come across any such cases involving stepfathers.
	   Researchers wrote in the American Journal of Psychiatry: ``Men
in step-families may be at greater risk for depression than those
in traditional families, and this risk is closely linked to their
partners' depressive symptoms.'' Kirby Deater-Deckard and
colleagues at the University of Bristol surveyed more than 7,000
men before and after their wives or partners had babies.
	   Post-natal depression is a well-known phenomenon, affecting 13
per cent of all new mothers in a variety of different countries and
cultures.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:STEPFATHER-FACE-A-HIDING sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
