<SLUG> CIVIC-AMENITIES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Civic amenities, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Civic amenities, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Abdur Rahman KhanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Coordination Committee on civic services has not only failed
to improve the civic amenity situation in Dhaka city, but has
failed to coordinate within itself as well, according to City
Corporation sources.
	   The committee was formed immediately after the present
government assumed power in June 1996 with the LGRD Minister Zillur
Rahman as Chairman and Dhaka City Mayor Mohammad Hanif as
Co-chairman. The chief executive officer of the City Corporation
was made member secretary of the committee.
	   Seventeen agencies, engaged in providing civic services,
including the electric supply authority, Water and Sewerage
Authority, RAJUK, Public Works Department, T&AMP;T, Titas gas
authority, Public Health Department, Social Welfare Department,
Roads and Highways Department, Environment Department, transport
authorities, civil surgeon district administration and the
metropolitan police were involved in the city co-ordination
committee.
	   It had been planned that co-ordination meetings would be held
every month. However, only 10 meetings were held with the first
meeting on November 15, 1996 and the last one on May 27, 1998.
	   The city mayor who had promoted the idea of a metropolitan
government with authority on various service providers in the city
was, however, discouraged with the formation of a co-ordination
committee, said an executive of the corporation.
	   The outcome of the meetings was nothing promising, said a
participant referring to the proceedings recorded by the member
secretary. A clear lack of co-ordination surfaced since the same
observation was made in a series of meetings on the same problem.
	   The sources referred to the problems like water logging, sewage
overflows, garbage cleaning and removal of construction materials
from the roads to show that the problem remained the same as
before. The minutes of the ninth meeting mentions that `` same
instructions were delivered in the past meetings''.
	   Similarly, the proceedings of the consecutive meetings recorded
``should be done'' ``will be made available'', ``will convey the
instructions'', ``made recommendation'' and such similar
expressions as made by different agencies in response to the city
problems.
	   No meeting could record appreciation for any job done to
mitigate the sufferings of the city dwellers, an official of the
LGRD ministry said in despair.
	   The meetings were becoming simply rituals, the sources added, as
many of the agencies were sending substitutes for their chief
executives to attend them. As a result, no concrete decision could
be taken in any of the cases needing attention.
	   
</TEXT>
