<BODY>
<SLUG> POLICE-HIT-16-BOOKMAKERS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police hit 16 bookmakers with $80 million turnover, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Police hit 16 bookmakers with $80 million turnover, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Simon NgASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   POLICE have smashed 16 illegal bookmaking syndicates which
accepted horse racing bets with a turnover of $80 million per
racing day.
	   Nineteen people _ 14 men and five women aged between 17 and 52 _
were arrested in a territory-wide operation over the weekend.
	   A large quantity of banking and betting records and more than
$140,000 in cash was seized.
	   Two of the syndicates were operating in Hong Kong, while the
remaining 14 were accepting bets in Macau and coastal cities in
Guangdong on Hong Kong races.
	   The police investigation was launched at the start of the racing
season in September last year.
	   One of the syndicates was also involved in betting on football
matches.
	   Organised Crime and Triad Bureau Superintendent Steve Tarrant
warned punters intending to bet on the coming World Cup that they
might be charged even if they were placing their stakes on a legal
overseas bookmaker.
	   ``If the betting in other jurisdiction is legal, there is still
a possibility that you can be involved in money laundering by
settling the bet in Hong Kong,'' he said.
	   Supt Tarrant said further advice had been sought from the
Department of Justice for clear guidelines, because the relevant
ordinance was very complicated.
	   Under the Organised and Serious Crimes Ordinance, bookmakers
based in Hong Kong who accept bets from outside Hong Kong were
guilty of money laundering.
	   The syndicates were believed to be controlled by triads.
	   ``Most of them had operated for more than a year, while the
longest had been in business for seven years,'' said OCTB Chief
Inspector Lam Man-wing.
	   They were making about 10 to 15 per cent of the turnover as
profit, Supt Tarrant said.
	   The largest single bet found was about $1 million.
	   Those arrested have been released on bail ranging from $10,000
to $50,000. The maximum penalty upon conviction is 14 years'
imprisonment and $5 million fine.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
