<HEADLINE>
RU students' rally demands smooth power supply, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
RU students' rally demands smooth power supply, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   About 2000 resident students of different halls of the Rajshahi
University took out a procession on the campus at about 10-30 last
night demanding uninterrupted supply of electricity.
	   The students came out en masse from their respective halls and
assembled in front of the official residence of the Vice-Chancellor
of the university. They chanted slogans demanding power supply.
	   The power supply on the campus remained disrupted from the
evening till midnight yesterday.
	   The angry students held a meeting in front of the main gate of
the VC's residence. The meeting was addressed, among others, by
Nahid, Kamal and Sabur. The speakers at the meeting alleged that
the power supply on the RU campus remained disrupted for about 10
hours within a span of 24 hours.
	   Moreover, the ``loadshedding till midnight'' has become a common
phenomenon, they further alleged.
	   The power supply situation in Rajshahi city further worsened
during the last 24 hours. The PDB sources said, there were only 7-8
megawatts of power available against the total requirement of 40
megawatts in the city. The city residents, particularly, the
examinees, the children and elderly people were the worst
sufferers.
	   Last night, the power supply in most areas remained disrupted
for about 6-7 hours. The situation became normal around 3-00 am.
The Registrar of the Rajshahi University has appealed to the Chief
Engineer of the Power Development Board of Rajshahi to take
immediate steps to restore normalcy in power supply on the campus.
	   According to the official letter of the Registrar, severe
loadshedding had made the lives of thousands of teachers, students
and employees on the campus miserable. Studies of the students have
been greatly hampered, it added.
	   The students even gheraoed the residence of the Vice-Chancellor
demanding supply of electricity. The letter expressed grave concern
over the deteriorating law and order situation on the campus due to
continued loadshedding.
	   The students may turn more violent if the power supply situation
was not improved before the beginning of the World Cup Football,
the letter said.
	   
</TEXT>
