<BODY>
<SLUG> TRAINS-TO-RUN-ON sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Trains to run on Jamuna bridge from June 23, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Trains to run on Jamuna bridge from June 23, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Enamul HuqASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Trains will run on the broad gauge rail track from Rajshahi and
Parbatipur to the eastern side of the Bangabandhu (Jamuna) Bridge
from the opening day of the bridge on June 23. However rail
connection between Joydevpur and Bhuapur will commence after at
least one year.
	   The construction of the railway station on the eastern side of
the bridge is about to be completed.
	   This was disclosed by Engineer Muhammad Shamsur Rahman, General
Manager, Jamuna Bridge Railway Link Project of the Ministry of
Communications, while briefing a group of journalists who visited
the bridge site yesterday. Railway Project Director Engineer
Iqbaluddin Choudhury also spoke.
	   Engineer Rahman said a special train would run from Jamtoli
(Bangabandhu Bridge west) station to the Bangabandhu Bridge east
station on the broad gauge. The train will consist of some saloon
cars and some passenger coaches. Later two to three trains would
run every day from Parbatipur and Rajshahi. The trains would
terminate at the Bangabandhu East station.
	   He told newsmen that Bangladesh Railway (BR) has procured 3,000
metric tonnes of rail from China for the first phase of the project
which would be completed by June 20. He said the BR had also
procured 27000 wooden sleepers for the first phase. He said about
27,500 metric tonnes of rail would be required for the entire
project.
	   Engineer Rahman said under the Bangabandhu (Jamuna) Bridge
Railway Link Project, 94 kilometre (excluding 5 kilometre Jamuna
Bridge)-long new dual gauge railway line was being constructed from
Joydevpur to Jamtoli in Sirajganj district. He said the work
started on December 8 last year on the west side of the Jamuna
Bridge and it would be completed by June 20.
	   He said the project was scheduled to be completed by May 2001.
He said the construction of culverts and bridges, nine station
buildings and embankments etc would be done at a cost of Tk 514.96
crore (US dollars 117.71 million) under the project.
	   Engineer Rahman said the existing 245 km broad gauge track from
Jamtoli to Parbatipur via Ishwardi would be converted into dual
gauge at a cost of Tk 235 crore (US dollars 50 million). This would
be completed by October this year.
	   He said the dual gauge rail line would be installed from
Joydevpur to Dhaka under a Tk 60 crore project. Tongi to Bhairab
Bazar double line project would be implemented with German aid. He
said the Bangladesh Railway had plans to extend the broad gauge
rail line to Chittagong port.
	   He said the total estimated cost of the railway link project was
Tk 1155.40 crore (US dollars 268.70 million). Of the total amount,
Tk 473 crore was being provided by the Asian Development Bank
(ADB), Tk 504.39 crore by the government of Bangladesh (GOB), Tk
34.40 crore by France, Tk 49.00 crore by Spain, Tk 30.10 crore by
the Export Development Corporation (EDC) of Canada and Tk 64.50
crore by OPEC.
	   
</TEXT>
