r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  WARNS-OF-EROSION-OF-FREE     06-08 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> WARNS-OF-EROSION-OF-FREE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Academic warns of erosion of free press, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Academic warns of erosion of free press, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Lucia Palpal-latocASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AN academic has warned of the possible erosion of press freedom
because of the recent trend of businessmen with interests in the
mainland buying into the local media.
	   In a paper to be read at Oxford University this weekend, Richard
Cullen, visiting fellow at the City University's faculty of law,
says the Hong Kong press remains one of the freest and most
informative in East Asia even almost a year after the handover.
	   In his paper entitled ``Law, Politics and Freedom of the Press
in Hong Kong'', Mr Cullen says local media ownership has been
passing more and more not to specialist media operators but to
people with a general business background involving business with
the mainland.
	   ``There are now signs that mainland interests are buying into
the Hong Kong media with some vigour,'' he writes.
	   ``The fact that Hong Kong media outlets are increasingly falling
into business hands with close links to (or homes in) the mainland
does not automatically spell erosion of freedom of the press, but
it does indicate an increased potential for such erosion.'' Mr
Cullen will deliver the paper at a conference on the independence
of Hong Kong's judiciary at Oxford University this weekend.
	   Solicitor-General Daniel Fung Wah-kin will be the keynote
speaker at the conference, which will also be attended by judges
and members of the legal profession.
	   Mr Cullen co-authored a book entitled Media Law in the PRC with
Fu Hua-ling, a research fellow at University of Hong Kong's faculty
of law.
	   The approval of the change in the ownership of Asia Television
(ATV) by businessmen with mainland links almost two weeks ago was
cited as an example.
	   A consortium led by Phoenix chairman Liu Changle, who is a
former People's Liberation Army officer, bought 46 per cent of the
shares owned by former ATV chairman Lim Por-yen.
	   Although the future chief executive Wu Ching promised to
maintain the station's editorial independence, various sectors have
voiced their concern.
	   Mr Cullen says in his paper that there is nothing wrong if
businessmen bought stakes in local media as part of their empire.
	   But he warns that such a set up could lead to a conflict of
interest in future.
	   Although Mr Cullen has noted some incidents of self-censorship
in the media in recent years, he also maintains that the Hong Kong
press is still among the freest in the region.
	   There are about 20 dailies for Hong Kong's 6.3 million people
while there are only two or three dailies in most Western cities of
comparable size.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:WARNS-OF-EROSION-OF-FREE sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
