<SLUG> MEDIA-OWNERSHIP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Media ownership `good for business', HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Media ownership `good for business', HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Lucia Palpal-latocASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   COMMERCIAL rather than political reasons have motivated
businessmen with mainland links to penetrate the local media, an
academic said.
	   Professor Lau Siu-kai, head of the Chinese University's
Department of Sociology, said the community should not be alarmed
over the recent trend towards changes in media ownership.
	   ``I think it is purely a commercial decision,'' he said.
	   ``These businessmen with mainland links buy shares in local
media because they want to eventually enter the huge mainland
market.'' Prof Lau said businessmen with mainland links may have
greater success in penetrating the mainland market.
	   ``A number of local media have tried to enter the mainland
market but none of them has been successful,'' he said. ``I won't
be surprised if more businessmen with mainland links buy into local
media, especially if they want to tap the mainland market.'' Prof
Lau does not believe the trend will lead to the erosion of press
freedom.
	   ``Businessmen are more concerned about making profits and they
cannot afford to lose their readers and viewers because they have
censored a story.'' Hong Kong Journalists Association chairwoman
Carol Lai Pui-yee agreed that businessmen had been investing in the
local media for commercial reasons.
	   But she said journalists were concerned that editorial
independence could be undermined should businessmen with mainland
links dominate the local media.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
