<SLUG> BC-Croatia-US Aid </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Town promoting reconciliation receives U.S. aid
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to fix slug

<TEXT>
	   DARDA, Croatia (AP) _ The United States gave dlrs 13.7 million
Monday to the eastern-most town of Darda, rewarding city fathers
for promoting reconciliation in this war-torn region.
	   The money will be used to rebuild homes and infrastructure, and
revive the local economy.
	   Darda, in the region known as eastern Slavonia, was the first
Croatian town to receive such financial support.
	   ``We chose Darda as it does need reconstruction and has shown a
real desire for reconciliation,'' said U.S. Ambassador William
Montgomery.
	   Last month, a group of foreign diplomats pledged to aid towns
across Croatia that cooperated in efforts to allow the return of
refugees and the development of multiculturalism.
	   Serbs and Croats fought a bloody war in 1991, when local Serbs
rebelled against the country's independence from former Yugoslavia.
Thousands of Croats and Serbs were killed or left homeless, and
tensions and hatreds persist in many communities.
	   Darda, some 300 kilometers (187 miles) east of the capital,
Zagreb, was badly damaged during the conflict. But unlike other
municipalities, it has set up a successful multi-ethnic leadership.
	   Before the war, Darda's population was more than 6,000. A slight
majority were Croat.
	   Now the population is predominantly Serb, but the government
already has rebuilt more than 100 homes for Croats.
	   (str/eb/scl)
</TEXT>
