<SLUG> JOY-PASSING-OF-ERA sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Joy and sorrow at passing of era, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Joy and sorrow at passing of era, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Anthony SzetoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE closing of Kai Tak Airport next month will be a cause for
celebration as well as dismay for businesses in Kowloon City.
	   Most people in the area feel that the relocation of the airport
will mean the departure of many of the consumers the airport
attracts.
	   The diverse selection of restaurants lining the streets of
Kowloon City are the first stop for many incoming travellers
getting their first meal after a long flight.
	   This will no longer be the case after Kai Tak shuts on 5 July to
clear the way for Chek Lap Kok Airport the next day.
	   ``Business is definitely going to decline after the airport
closes,'' said Lam Lai-kuen, manager of the Chui Yuen Restaurant.
	   ``But hopefully when the new developments begin, business will
pick up again.'' The 380,000 residents who live under the flight
path will likely rejoice in the absence of the roar of jetliners
landing or taking off every three minutes or so.
	   Or will they? When asked if she would be glad that the screaming
of planes ceased for good, Mrs Lam replied: ``I don't know if I
could get used to it.'' Others, like employees of the Chan Xian
Fang cafe, have other concerns.
	   ``The new airport will be very inconvenient because it is so
far,'' said a bartender named Toby.
	   ``But at least it won't be as noisy when the planes pass by.''
The good news is that the closure of the airport calls for a
commemorative campaign, complete with a set of souvenirs and
publicity gimmicks.
	   Yesterday, Kowloon City Plaza kicked-off its ``Farewell to Kai
Tak'' campaign, officiated by Lee Cheuk-fan, in his capacity as a
member of the Kowloon City District Board.
	   The event involved the introductions of a photo exhibition of
Kai Tak Airport and Kowloon City, as well as the unveiling of a
countdown board.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
