<SLUG> BC-Japan-NKorea </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan says no new talks with North Korea amid abduction suspicions
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Prospects for talks on normalizing ties with North
Korea have dimmed because of suspicions Pyongyang has withheld
information about alleged kidnappings in Japan, a top Japanese
official was quoted as saying Monday.
	   Tokyo had asked North Korea to investigate allegations its
agents had abducted as many as 10 Japanese, but the reclusive
communist government said Friday it knew nothing about any missing
Japanese.
	   Japan was dissatisfied with the response. Vice Foreign Minister
Shunji Yanai was quoted as saying Monday by Kyodo News that any new
bilateral talks would likely end in failure.
	   ``We will ask North Korea to offer information and
investigate,'' Yanai was quoted as saying.
	   North Korea, ravaged by food shortages and a devastated economy
and isolated politically, is eager for ties with wealthy Japan.
	   Preliminary talks on normalizing relations between the two
neighbors collapsed in 1992 over the kidnapping issue.
