<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Austria,0397 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Tension rises before first match against Cameroon
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By GEORGE JAHN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ARSAC, France (AP) _ The Austrians are happy with their
surroundings, training opportunities and state of fitness ahead of
their World Cup opener against Cameroon. So why all the tension in
the air?
	   It's simple nervousness as Austria focuses on Thursday's match
in Toulouse. Some signs of tension were palpable Monday, during the
squad's morning training at the local stadium in Arsac, a
picturesque wine-growing town north of Bordeaux.
	   Midfielder Arnold Wettl, for instance, was unhappy with the
ball. He said was different than in Austria, where he plays for
Rapid.
	   ``It's inflated a bit too much,'' he complained. ``We hope we
can control it better during the games than in practice.''
	   Coach Herbert Prohaska, normally a picture of staidness, also
showed some strains, chewing out an interviewer from state-run
Austrian television for asking what he considered a silly question.
	   Still, the team has little to complain about. The practice field
is perfectly manicured, the weather is late spring rather than hot
summer, and the players are as fit as they will be.
	   Hannes Rainmayr was out for the full 90-minute practice session
Monday, showing no signs of that a bruised knee sustained two days
ago was slowing him down.
	   ``I can keep up again!'' Rainmayr, of Austria's Sturm Graz,
yelled toward the sidelines. ``There's no problem if it stays this
way.''
	   Wolfgang Feiersinger collided with another player during
practice Monday, bruising his shin, but Prohaska said it would not
slow the star defender down. Generally, ``the team's physical
condition is not a concern,'' he said.
	   Asked about general fitness, fellow-defender Peter Schoettel
said: ``It's getting better all the time.''
	   Midfielder Andreas Herzog said condition was extremely important
against Cameroon, a young and fast team, saying: ``If we're in the
best physical shape, we can really cut loose.''
	   He waved off questions about Austria's other first-round
opponents, Italy and Chile.
	   ``We should only be thinking of Cameroon now,'' he said. ``In
the final analysis, this game is a kind of qualifier for us _ if we
don't do well here, we're in trouble further on.''
	   (gj-dm) 	   
</TEXT>
