<HEADLINE>
Culprits to be punished without reprieve: President, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Culprits to be punished without reprieve: President, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   President Justice Shahabuddin Ahmed yesterday said culprits
perpetrating repression on women and children would be punished
without reprieve, reports APB.
	   He said, ``I will instruct concerned authorities to see that the
culprits are handed exemplary punishment in accordance with the law
of the land.''
	   The President said this while talking to a 14-member delegation
of the Repression Complaint Cell, which called on him at
Bangabhaban yesterday. Convenor of the cell and former MP Farida
Rahman led the delegation.
	   Earlier, the delegation submitted a memorandum to the President
expressing grave concern at the rising incidents of cruelty to
women and children.
	   ``The women and children are being kidnapped, raped and murdered
almost everyday. But the perpetrators of such crimes are going
scot-free'', the delegation told the President.
	   They referred to the rape of 6-year-old Tania, in a police
control room in broad daylight. ``But no action was taken against
those who cannot avoid their responsibility,'' they said.
	   The delegation noted with deep dismay that persons committing
rape and murder are being granted anticipatory bail, which is
encouraging many others to commit such crimes.
	   The members of the delegation urged the President, to instruct
all concerned to combat such crimes ruthlessly and to ensure that
culprits are given exemplary punishment.
	   President Shahabuddin gave them a patient hearing and said he is
aware of the state of things as regards cruelty to women and
children.
	   Former state ministers Sarwari Rahman and Jahanara Begum were,
among others, present on the occasion.
	   
</TEXT>
