<HEADLINE>
Plea to watch airport opening from home, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Plea to watch airport opening from home, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Sanna SoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DON'T go to the new Chek Lap Kok airport when it opens on Monday
6 July, authorities are advising the public.
	   People are being advised to ``stay home'' and watch the grand
opening ceremony on television.
	   The weekend prior to opening day will be of vital importance and
people are being asked to prevent traffic congestion and not to
disturb the operations.
	   The most critical hours will start at midnight of 5 July, a
Sunday, when vital equipment will be moved from Kai Tak airport to
Chek Lap Kok.
	   Commissioner for Transport Fanny Law Fan Chiu-fan on Sunday said
members of the public should understand the urgency of ensuring a
smooth operation to avoid any delay.
	   ``As the removal of the airport should be done in a limited
period of time, it is hoped that commuters and drivers would avoid
using the roads at that time,'' Mrs Law said.
	   She added that the process would be broadcast live on television
and the public should stay home to watch it. Details of traffic
arrangements will be announced later.
	   Mrs Law was speaking after the 20th anniversary launching
ceremony of Rehabus, which provides a door-to-door transport
service for the physically disabled.
	   Some 20 Rehabuses took more than 300 disabled people to the new
airport to try out the facilities before the official opening.
	   Speaking at the ceremony, Lee Man-bun, chairman of the Hong Kong
Society for Rehabilitation, said the Rehabus service started 20
years ago, with two borrowed buses. Today it boasts a fleet of 74
Rehabuses _ 71 12-seater minibuses and three single-deck buses.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
