<SLUG> BC-Norway-Oil Fund </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Norway 's first oil fund investments in stock markets produce
</HEADLINE>
gains &QL; 
 &UR; By DOUG MELLGREN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) _ After three months of dabbling in the
world's stock markets, the Norwegian government has turned a profit
that would the envy of any novice investor: about dlrs 1 billion.
	   Norway, the world's second-largest oil exporter, has for several
years been salting away some of its oil revenue in a fund to
cushion the country once the wells run dry.
	   This year, parliament allowed the Central Bank of Norway to
expand oil fund investments into stocks instead of placing them
exclusively in safe but lower yield government bonds. About 40
percent of the fund is now invested in 21 countries and 2,000
companies.
	   On Monday, the state bank announced that the fund's value
increased 6.3 percent to 120.5 billion kroner (dlrs 16.2 billion)
during the first three months of the year. Money was transferred
slowly and quietly into stocks to avoid affecting markets with a
sudden infusion of cash.
	   ``We have been through a very important phase. The increase has
happened stepwise, at about 8 percent a month. It has been
important to us to transfer the funds to the stock markets without
effecting the markets,'' the fund's director, Knut M. Kjaer, said
by telephone.
	   Because Norway's currency, the krone, has weakened recently,
Kjaer said the international buying power of the fund was a better
measure of the fund's gains. That increase was 3.74 percent, or
about 4.2 billion kroner (dlrs 560 million), during the three
months.
	   ``We are quite satisfied, but one quarter with good results is
no guarantee for what will happen in the next quarters. We know
there are big swings in these markets,'' said Kjaer.
	   He also said there was little impact from Asia's economic
crisis.
	   ``There has been a somewhat lower return in Asia then in the
other countries but just the same a relatively positive return. We
can't expect, in such a large portfolio spread over the whole
world, that all regions and all countries at any given time will
show positive developments,'' he said in presenting the results.
	   Kjaer said the value of the fund's bonds rose 2.17 percent while
its stock values gained 12.47 percent during the three months. By
comparison, the Oslo stock market increased 7.83 percent in the
same period.
	   The fund placed Norway's money through four external managers _
Banker Trust of New York, State Street Global Advisors of Boston,
and the London firms Barclays Global Investors and Gartmoe
Investment Management _ with the Chase Manhattan Bank as overall
global custodian of the fund.
	   (dm-jh)
</TEXT>
