<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-War Crimes, 1st Ld-Writethru,0435 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Prosecutor says Bosnian Croat commander watched rape of Muslim
</HEADLINE>
woman &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: ADDS photo numbers. RECASTS to add details from trial. No
pickup &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos AMS102-104 &QL; 
 &UR; By MIKE CORDER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ The commander of a Bosnian Croat
paramilitary unit watched as one of his men raped a Muslim woman
during an interrogation, a U.N. war crimes prosecutor said Monday.
	   The defendant, Anto Furundzija, 28, has pleaded innocent to two
war crimes charges relating to his alleged involvement in the May
1993 attack.
	   Furundzija looked calm as his trial opened before the Yugoslav
war crimes tribunal. He faces a maximum life sentence if convicted.
	   Although rape has been considered a war crime in other cases
before the U.N. tribunal, Furundzija's trial is the first to deal
specifically with sexual assault inflicted during an interrogation.
	   The alleged rapist has not been arrested. Furundzija was
arrested in December in the central Bosnian town of Vitez, near
where the alleged offenses occurred.
	   Furundzija allegedly was interrogating the victim, identified as
``Witness A,'' as she was raped at the headquarters of his unit,
called ``The Jokers.''
	   The Jokers allegedly took part in a violent campaign by Bosnian
Croat forces to drive Muslims out of the Lasva River Valley in
central Bosnia in 1993.
	   ``Shortly after the interrogation started, the other member of
The Jokers forced her to undress and began what turned out to be a
prolonged series of physical, mental and serious sexual abuses
including repeated rapes,'' prosecutor Michael Blaxill said Monday.
	   By failing to stop the rapes, Furundzija became a ``direct
perpetrator committing the crimes of torture and outrages upon
personal dignity,'' Blaxill said.
	   Defense attorney Luka Misetic said the prosecution's case was
built on faulty recollections of the victim.
	   ``Her testimony will not convince you beyond a reasonable doubt
that Anto Furundzija is guilty as charged, and, make no mistake,
the prosecution's entire case is based on her testimony,'' Misetic
said.
	   Prosecutors have said they will only call five witnesses _
including the alleged victim. The first witness, a Muslim community
leader from Vitez, testified Monday about the background of the 3
1/2-year Bosnian war.
	   Set up in 1993, the war crimes tribunal has indicted 60 suspects
and has 27 in custody. Its most-wanted suspects, former Bosnian
Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and his wartime military chief, Gen.
Ratko Mladic, remain at large. 	   
</TEXT>
