<SLUG> BC-Poland-Germany-Slave Labor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Polish-German foundation presses for slave labor compensation
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ A Polish-German foundation appealed Monday
to German companies that had employed slave laborers to consider
reparations for Poles forced to work in Nazi Germany during World
War II.
	   The Polish-German Reconciliation Foundation urged Chancellor
Helmut Kohl and Polish Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek to discuss slave
labor reparations when they meet Thursday, said Jan Parys, the
foundation's deputy chairman.
	   Kohl and Buzek will open an international youth center in the
southwestern Polish town of Krzyzowa, or Kreisau, which was part of
Germany before 1945.
	   Foundation members argue that Poland's 1953 decision not to seek
war reparations from Germany does not mean that Poles are not
entitled to civil compensation claims, the PAP news agency
reported.
	   Created in 1991, the foundation is currently distributing 500
million marks (dlrs 295 million) it received from the German
government for payments to Polish slave laborers.
	   The foundation already paid one-time compensation to more than
half a million people and plans to review claims from 250,000
others this year.
	   Foundation members say some 200 existing big German companies
had employed slave laborers and thus should start paying
compensation to Poles.
	   About 7 million people were forced to work in Nazi Germany
during the war. Most were from Poland and the Soviet Union, and
many were Jews.
	   Some big German industrial firms, including Siemens and
Mercedes-Benz, paid reparations to some former slave-laborers, but
those behind the Iron Curtain were unable to apply.
 &UR; (ajs-pfg)
</TEXT>
