<BODY>
<SLUG> PRIVACY-CHIEF-CALLS-LAW sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Privacy chief calls for vigilance on law, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Privacy chief calls for vigilance on law, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Susan LanninASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Privacy Commissioner has called on Hong Kong companies not
to break laws protecting personal information when upgrading
computer systems to get rid of the millennium bug.
	   Stephen Lau Ka-men said organisations needed to make sure the
personal data they held was accurate and protected against
unauthorised or accidental access, processing or erasure.
	   The problem, also known as the year 2000 bug, is caused by the
inability of many computer systems and micro-processors to
recognise dates in the year 2000.
	   Mr Lau said the biggest danger when it came to privacy
protection lay in mistakes made when converting figures such as
bank account statements or changing passwords.
	   ``All practical steps must be taken to ensure the accuracy of
personal data and the security of computers,'' he said.
	   Mr Lau said banks, in particular, should be aware of the risk of
breaking the Personal Data (Privacy) Ordinance when upgrading their
computer systems to get rid of the bug.
	   While big business was taking steps to deal with the problem,
many small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) were often unaware
of the pitfalls, he said.
	   ``There are half a million SMEs and a lot of personal computers
are not compliant with the year 2000, because the firms lack
resources and are buying off-the-street software,'' he said.
	   Legislator-elect Sin Chung-kai called on the Information
Technology and Broadcasting Bureau to issue guidelines to safeguard
the protection of personal information.
	   ``It's the very minimum the government should do,'' he said.
	   Mr Sin, a Democrat who represents the Information Technology
functional constituency, said the Hong Kong Productivity Council,
which is helping SME's to take on the millennium bug, should draw
attention to the privacy implications of the changeover.
	   ``Privacy protection is a major issue of the year 2000 bug, it
should be addressed,'' he said.
	   The HongkongBank said most of its computer systems were already
compliant with the year 2000.
	   It said it regarded the protection of personal data as
``sacrosanct''.
	   
</TEXT>
