<BODY>
<SLUG> TREATMENT-HYPERTENSION sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Treatment of hypertension, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Treatment of hypertension, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Md. Gias UddinASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Hypertension is defined as a sustained diastolic blood pressure
greater than 90 mm Hg accompanied by an elevated systolic blood
pressure above 140 mm Hg. Elevated blood pressure is an extremely
common disorder affecting approximately 20 per cent of the entire
population of the world. Although many of these individuals have no
symptoms, chronic (long-term) hypertension can lead to congestive
heart failure (CHF), myocardial infarction, renal damage and
cerebrovascular accidents. The incidence of morbidity and mortality
significantly decreases when hypertension is diagnosed early and is
treated properly.Although hypertension may occur secondary to other
disease processes, more than 90 per cent of patients have essential
hypertension, a disorder of unknown origin affecting the
blood-pressure regulating mechanism.
	   A family history of hypertension increases the likelihood that
an individual will develop hypertensive disease.Essential
hypertension occurs four times more frequently among blacks than
among whites and it occurs more often among middle-aged males than
among middle-aged females. Environmental factors such as a
stressful lifestyle, high dietary intake of sodium (sodium
chloride-table salt), obesity and smoking - all lead to the
occurrence of hypertension.A patient of essential hypertension must
adopt a philosophical attitude toward life. He should avoid heavy
manual work but continue moderate activities. He should have 8/10
hours sleep at night. Fatty hypertensive patients should modify
eating menu to reduce body weight up to normal. Salt intake should
be restricted but not stopped.No drug can cure blood pressure
completely, but the above mentioned measures help to keep the
pressure down to a reasonably lower level.
	   Careful designing of treatment varies according to the blood
pressure studies of individual patients and their emotional
background.Mild hypertension can often be controlled with a single
drug. More severe hypertension may require treatment with several
drugs that are selected to minimise adverse effects of the combined
regimen. Treatment is initiated with any of four drugs depending on
the individual patient: (1) a diuretic, (2) a beta-blocker, (3) an
ACE inhibitor, or (4) a calcium channel blocker.If the blood
pressure is not adequately controlled, a second drug is given.A
general scheme of treatment may be as follows.(1) Mild case: Oral
diuretic (e.g. chlorthiazide) plus tranquilliser (e.g. Relaxeu
tablet). (2) Moderate case: Oral diuretic plus methyldopa. (3)
Severe case: Diuretic plus prazocin. (4) Hypertension with angina:
Beta blocker (e.g. propranolol) plus ACE inhibitor (e.g.
captopril). (5) Hypertensive emergency: Diuretic (frusemide) plus
reserpine.Lack of patient compliance is the most common reason for
failure of antihypertensive therapy.
	   Treatment of hypertension is directed at preventing the disease
that may occur in future, rather than in relieving present
discomfort of the patient. The side effects associated with
hypertensive therapy (e.g. depression, fatigue, insomnia, asthmatic
breathing, etc.) may influence the patient more than future
benefits. Thus, it is important to enhance comfort of the patient
by carefully selecting a drug regimen that minimises adverse
reactions.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
