<HEADLINE>
World Cup: French return, but is Zidane healthy for opener?
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CLAIRFONTAINE, France (AP) _ After a four-day escape to Finland,
``Les Bleus'' of host France returned home bearing a message of
high anxiety: Is their creative genius, Zinedine Zidane, healthy?
	   After a hard-fought 1-0 win over Finland last Friday, playmaker
Zidane has been struggling with an injured ankle, and reassuring
messages from the medical staff have hardly lifted the dark cloud
hanging over the World Cup team.
	   Zidane, without whom any French hope of winning the World Cup
seems a pipe dream, had to be rested on Saturday and could only run
for 10 minutes on Sunday because his right ankle was still acting
up.
	   The Juventus Turin star hopes to return to regular training on
Tuesday, just three days ahead of the World Cup opener against
South Africa in his hometown of Marseille. Saudi Arabia and Denmark
are the others in Group C.
	   ``It is preoccupying because there is always that fear that he
will not be able to play the first match,'' said team doctor
Jean-Marcel Ferret. But he added Zidane was fighting the worst pain
a few days after the injury. ``I wouldn't worry too much,'' he
added.
	   All through the weekend, coach Aime Jacquet criticized Friday's
refereeing that could have cost France its brightest star. Zidane
was tackled often and hard, and Jacquet even considered pulling him
off to protect him. ``It was a scandal,'' the coach declared.
	   In case Zidane cannot recover in time, his place would most
likely be taken by Robert Pires, 24, the playmaker of Metz,
runner-up in the French league.
	   Zidane's was the only injury for the French. Other difficulties
were tactical, centering on who would provide the French goals.
	   Jacquet had long promised that France would turn from a
defensive and conservative team into an ``audacious'' one for the
World Cup, but words have come easier than performances.
	   Captain Didier Deschamps knows that an overnight change is
tough.
	   ``We will never produce fireworks,'' he was quoted by L'Equipe
sports paper. ``We cannot have a revolution in one week.''
	   On top of that, the French expect South Africa to do little else
than defending and hoping on a lucky break next Friday.
	   ``We won't fall for that trap,'' said Deschamps, arguing against
an all-out assault from the start.
	   The French team will stay for three days at its training camp
here in the woods southwest of Paris before heading to Marseille on
Thursday, ready for their Coupe du Monde.
	   ``The team is bubbling with impatience,'' said Jacquet.
</TEXT>
