<HEADLINE>
Airport Rail track damaged in test, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Airport Rail track damaged in test, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Simon NgASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A JUNCTION point of the Airport Rail tracks was slightly damaged
during a trial run on Wednesday, but the Mass Transit Railway
Corporation on Sunday shrugged off the accident as ``minor''.
	   The incident, caused by a defective track and not by a
subsidence of the reclaimed land, would not delay the opening of
the line, the MTRC said.
	   The junction, known as ``scissors point'', about 200 metres from
the Olympic Station of the Tung Chung Line, was damaged when an
engineering train rolled through during a test.
	   The junction is located in a newly reclaimed land near Tai Kok
Tsui.
	   The accident sparked concerns that land subsidence caused the
defect and would be a potential danger to the Airport Rail's
operation.
	   But MTRC public relations manager Betty Chan Lee Pik-hang said
the damage was only slight and not caused by the reclaimed land.
	   ``The defect was fixed shortly afterwards on Thursday, so it is
no longer a problem,'' she said. The method of reclamation had
taken into account that a railway would be built on the land.
	   But she refused to comment on the consequence that would occur
if the fault was not promptly discovered, saying this was ``only an
assumption''.
	   Citing the example of Hang Fa Chuen station of the MTR, Mrs Chan
stressed that railway tracks built on reclaimed land should not be
a problem.
	   ``We are confident the line can start operating as planned on 22
June.'' The Olympic Station was opened to the public on Sunday.
	   
</TEXT>
