<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Israel </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Egyptian, Israeli activists propose solution to peace deadlock
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Egyptian and Israeli peace activists Monday
proposed a 7-point peace plan, which includes a united Arab-Jew
Jerusalem, to resolve the Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
	   The activists, who worked on the plan for more than a year, say
they will try to mobilize Arab and Israeli peoples into pressuring
their governments to speed up negotiations and reach peace.
	   The activists represent Peace Now, Israel's largest peace group
with thousands of members, and the Egyptian Peace Movement, a small
group of about 120 members including prominent writers, lawyers and
former politicians.
	   A joint statement by the two groups said they decided to join
hands to counter the hard line policies of Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, which have forced the talks into a ``virtual
standstill.''
	   ``We deeply believe that ... both Jews and Arabs throughout the
region urgently desire peace,'' the statement said. ``We are also
convinced that a comprehensive peace is not only desirable but also
attainable.''
	   Among the seven points offered as the solution, one proposes
that Jerusalem remain a united city in which Palestinians and
Israelis can co-exist under coordinated municipalities and have
their own capitals.
	   The statement says that some Israeli settlements be allowed to
remain within the boundaries of the agreed Palestinian state but
others must be evacuated with appropriate compensation from the
Israeli government.
	   The proposal also says that the Palestinian state should be
allowed to absorb the 1948 refugees and displaced Palestinians from
the 1967 Arab-Israeli war. The refugees should also receive
compensation from the international community.
	   The official Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have left the issue
of Jerusalem and the historical disputes to be resolved last,
pending a resolution of major issues such as Israeli troops pullout
from West Bank, the opening of an airport in Gaza and the free
passage of Palestinians between West Bank and Gaza.
	   Netanyahu's government says the peace process cannot proceed
until it has ensured the security of its people and secured
guarantees from the Palestinian Authority that it will curb
terrorism in its area.
	   The peace talks between the two sides are currently stalled over
Israel's refusal to accept a U.S. proposal for a further 13.1
percent Israeli troop withdrawal from the West Bank. The
Palestinians, who originally demanded a bigger pullout, are ready
for 13.1 percent.
