<HEADLINE>
Thieves target tractors, trailers, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Thieves target tractors, trailers, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Valerie BolcinaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THEFTS of tractors, trailers and containers in the border
district of the New Territories increased sixfold last month.
	   While the monthly average of tractor, trailer and container
thefts for the January to April period was only three, the figure
jumped to 19 last month.
	   Police yesterday advised truck drivers to take precautions
against theft, particularly when in the northern New Territories.
	   Drivers are advised to take simple, common-sense measures to
ensure their vehicles are kept under surveillance where possible,
are securely locked and easily identifiable, in order to deter
thieves.
	   Acting Chief Superintendent Leslie Burton, Border District
police commander, said police would give further advice to truck
drivers if needed.
	   Several guidelines were issued yesterday, such as not parking
containers, trailers or tractors in remote areas or on roadsides
sheltered by thick undergrowth which could provide cover for
thieves.
	   The best place to park is at a car park with security
facilities, where surveillance can be kept on the vehicle.
	   Drivers and owners were warned to use ``mushroom locks'' or
other good-quality locks resistant to prising and bumping.
	   Owners were also advised to paint the company name in a
prominent position on the vehicle so that it could be easily
identified. And car park management should be told not to allow
vehicles to leave the car park without prior notice.
	   
</TEXT>
