<SLUG> THE-RELATIONSHIP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
The relationship between sino-nasal with chest diseases, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
The relationship between sino-nasal with chest diseases, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Dr. Major Md. Ashraful IslamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Sino-nasal disease is a very common disease to the people of all
classes in our population. Sino-nasal disease means the disease
which involves the paranasal sinuses and the nose itself. Although
amongst all the Sino-nasal diseases, sinusitis is very common and
the term is almost known to everybody. Many patients directly
report to the physician or ENT specialists with diagnose of
sinusitis and ask for treatment. Some patients think that this
disease does not cure permanently so no need of treatment at all.
One quarter of patients is well experienced with wash treatment of
sinusitis and many of them, their relations or associates express
their dissatisfaction when the treatment does not alleviate the
sufferings. What is sinusitis?Sinusitis is the inflammation of the
lining membrane of the sinus wall. There are four groups of sinuses
and situated on each side of the nose.
	   These are maxillary, ethanoidal, frontal and spenoidal.
Inflammation may be restricted to a single sinus or may be present
in several or in all of one or both sides but the maxillary sinus
is the commonest victim of all the sinuses. The lining of the nose
and paranasal sinuses is continuous and it would be rare for
inflammation to affect one without the other. The term rhinitir
implies an inflammation lining membrane of the nosal fossae. Owing
to the continuity of the lining membrane of the nasal fossae with
that of the sinuses, some degree of inflaming is very often present
in the latter at the same time, so constituting a
rhinosinusitis.Effects of rhinosinusitis on chest
diseaseRhinosinusitis is a disease of the respiratory tract and the
respiratory tract for better understanding is classified into two
subdivisions namely the upper respiratory tract and the lower
respiratory tract.
	   The upper respiratory tract mainly includes the nose and
paranasal sinuses and the lower respiratory tract includes the
trachea (wind pipe) and lungs. These two subdivisions i.e. the
upper respiratory tract and the lower respiratory tract are very
much closely related, not only in anatomy, but also in a number of
physiological functions and also to the responses to the various
environmental factors. Since the upper and lower respiratory tracts
share the common defence mechanisms, defects in them will be
reflected as infective presentation to either ENT Specialists or
chest physician or both. Since the upper respiratory tract brooks a
higher rate of environmental attack, the ENT specialists usually
come across the infections first which will later affect the lung.
Therefore, chest disease is frequently associated with
rhinosinusitis.
	   So naturally ENT specialists look for the principles of
actiology, pathology, investigation and management of diseases of
one tract reflected in the other.In fact, the complex relationship
of sino-nasal disease and the chest disease is well exemplified by
the presence of sinusitis in association with a purulent lung
disease such as bronchiectasis, acute bronchitis and recurrent
bronchitis. In one study it has been observed that chronic purulent
sputum production, most with proven bronchiectasis showed a high
prevalence of rhinosinusitis. In another study, it revealed that
asthma occurred in 17-19 per cent of patients with nasal disease,
particularly allergic rhiniter, and 56-74 per cent of patients with
asthma were found to have allergic rhinitis.
	   How do the patients of rhinosinusitis present to the ENT
specialists? The patient may present with one or more of the
following: (1) Nasal obstruction - one or both sides. (2) Nasal
discharge - watery or purulent (3) Itching in the nose or throat
(4) Sneezing (5) Snoring (6) Facial pain and headache (7) Nose
bleeding (8) Abnormal smell or difficulty in nasal smell (9)
Foul-smelling nasal discharge (10) Weakness (11) Feverish condition
(12) Cough (13) Feeling of something in the throat (14) Blocked
feeling in the ear or pain in the ear etc. Whatever may be the
clinical presentation, if the patients suffer with the above, he or
she is advised to consult ENT specialists to get the timed
diagnosis and its definitive treatment.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
