<SLUG> BC-Slovakia-Nuclear, 1st Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Slovaks start up controversial nuclear plant
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with reaction from Austrian chancellor &QL; 
 &UR; By JANA DOROTKOVA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRATISLAVA, Slovakia (AP) _ Despite strong protest from
anti-nuclear campaigners and neighboring Austria, Slovakia on
Monday started up its controversial nuclear power plant at
Mochovce.
	   The plant is just 120 kilometers (72 miles) east of Austria,
which has campaigned against its activation, arguing that certain
features of the heavy water pressure reactor make it unsafe.
Austria is the only country in the world to have built a nuclear
power plant, then voted in 1978 by referendum against putting it
online or having nuclear power.
	   Mochovce is a 440 MW Soviet-designed plant subsequently equipped
with Western technology.
	   Plant spokesman Rastislav Petrech said it received a go-ahead
from the Slovak nuclear authority on Sunday to activate its nuclear
fuel rods, as the authority deemed the plant ``met all the safety
and technical conditions.''
	   Austrian Chancellor Viktor Klima on Monday condemned the startup
as ``an irresponsible and unfriendly act,'' the Austria Press
Agency reported.
	   In recent weeks, Klima and Slovak Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar
have repeatedly discussed concerns over Mochovce.
	   Klima said Meciar broke an agreement by failing to notify him
about the startup of the power plant.
	    &UR; Last month, 5th graf
	   (pvs/scl/dc)
</TEXT>
