<SLUG> TUNG-FONG-HUNG-FINANCE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tung Fong Hung to buy into DC Finance, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Tung Fong Hung to buy into DC Finance, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Patricia LeeASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   TUNG Fong Hung Property Holdings on Sunday officially agreed to
acquire a 34.9 per cent stake in DC Finance Holdings for $408
million.
	   The price is equivalent to $0.465 per share of DC Finance.
	   According to the sale agreement, Tung Fong Hung will transfer
property assets involving a total floor area of 222,959 square
feet.
	   The properties include 17 commercial, retail and residential
assets, worth $460.9 million.
	   In addition, Tung Fong Hung chairman Lo Siu-fai, agreed to sell
his own properties with a total floor area of 9,672 sq ft to DC
Finance for $196.5 million.
	   Compared with the average closing price of $0.1376 per share
over the past 10 trading days on the stock exchange, the
acquisition price for DC Finance represents a 237.9 per cent
premium.
	   But the acquisition price represents a 7 per cent discount to
net asset value as of last December.
	   Under the agreement, DC Finance will pay back $140 million in
its loan portfolio as soon as the transaction is completed.
	   The loan portfolio, as of 15 May, amounted to a total of $915
million with loan maturities ranging from two to 20 months.
	   As agreed, Tung Fong Hung will not make a general offer to DC
Finance's shareholders.
	   The transaction is expected to be completed no later than 31
July if approved by Tung Fong Hung shareholders at an extraordinary
general meeting and other conditions stated in the agreement are
met.
	   Valuation of Tung Fong Hung's assets sold to DC Finance totalled
$606.7 million, according to reports from Vigers (Hong Kong) and
Chesterton Petty.
	   The most expensive of these assets, located in Sai Kung, is
worth $93 million or $6,011 per sq ft.
	   
</TEXT>
