<SLUG> RUSH-FOR-FLATS-AS-PRICE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rush for flats as price war hots up, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Rush for flats as price war hots up, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Karen ChanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE price war among property developers intensified over the
weekend with the Paliburg Group discounting the price of its Park
Royale development in Yuen Long by 15 per cent compared with other
new developments in the area.
	   The move drew overwhelming response from flat-buyers, prompting
Paliburg to extend the deadline for registration from 7.30 pm to 10
pm last night.
	   With an attractive launch price of $2,834 per square foot, the
project received more than 300 applications during the first day of
registration on Saturday for the first batch of 100 units.
	   Total registration figures for the first two days were not
available last night.
	   The strong response to Paliburg's 15 per cent discount is an
indication that prices of flats for new developments may drop
further in the coming weeks as other developers undertake similar
price cuts, property analysts said.
	   The decline in property prices in the primary market is
carefully watched by the government and private sector which are
concerned about a too-rapid decline in Hong Kong property prices.
	   To cope with the strong market response to Park Royale, Paliburg
announced on Saturday that it would put another 100 units on the
market at the same price.
	   While the secondary market was hard hit by the prolonged
property market slump, many real estate agents have turned to the
primary market.
	   Industry watchers said half of the applications for purchases in
the primary market were submitted through real estate agents.
	   Park Royale is scheduled for completion by early 1999. The
development offers 680 flats, a 180,000 sq ft club house and a
podium garden.
	   Wheelock &AMP; Co also sold almost 80 per cent or 33 units of its 45
remaining Regalia units in Tower I, King's Park on Saturday at an
average price of $6,455 per sq ft.
	   The spokeswoman of Wheelock Properties, Eva Ho, said they have
put all the remaining units in Tower II on the market.
	   Henderson Land was also able to sell some 30 Metro City units in
Tseung Kwan O and 10 Dawning Views units in Fanling on Saturday
through real estate agencies which generate more than $100 million
for the group.
	   
</TEXT>
