<HEADLINE>
UN resolution coercive, unhelpful': India, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
UN resolution coercive, unhelpful': India, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   India has objected to the ``coercive and unhelpful'' resolution
adopted by the UN Security Council and reiterated that it does not
want any external involvement in resolving disputes with Pakistan,
reports Reuters.''We regret that the Security Council has acted in
the way it has and produced a resolution which is coercive and
unhelpful in respect of the objectives it seeks to address,''
India's External Affairs Ministry said late on Saturday.It said
India was committed to fostering friendship and cooperation with
all neighbours and was determined to resolve all outstanding issues
with Pakistan through direct bilateral dialogue.''There is no place
for third party involvement of any nature whatsoever in this
process,'' the statement added.
	   The UN Security Council on Saturday unanimously condemned India
and Pakistan for nuclear tests carried out in May and urged the two
to stop all nuclear arms development programmes.Reflecting
Thursday's Joint Communique by the five declared nuclear
powers--the United States, Russia, Britain, France and China--the
15-member UN body said neither India nor Pakistan could have ``the
status of a nuclear-weapon state''.India's foreign ministry has
questioned the Council's authority to decide on disarmament
matters, and called for a global and comprehensive approach towards
adopting a Nuclear Weapons Convention.''The problem of
non-proliferation cannot be arbitrarily confined to a geographical
segment, but can be addressed meaningfully only in a global
framework.''''The narrow focus and approach by the Council will
heighten tensions, not lessen them,'' it warned.It said India was
committed to fostering friendship and cooperation with all
neighbours and was determined to resolve all outstanding issues
with Pakistan through direct bilateral dialogue.
	   ``There is no place for third party involvement of any nature
whatsoever in this process,'' the statement added.The UN Security
Council on Saturday unanimously condemned India and Pakistan for
nuclear tests carried out in May and urged the two to stop all
nuclear arms development programmes.Reflecting Thursday's Joint
Communique by the five declared nuclear powers--the United States,
Russia, Britain, France and China--the 15-member UN body said
neither India nor Pakistan could have ``the status of a
nuclear-weapon state''.India's foreign ministry has questioned the
Council's authority to decide on disarmament matters, and called
for a global and comprehensive approach towards adopting a Nuclear
Weapons Convention.''The problem of non-proliferation cannot be
arbitrarily confined to a geographical segment, but can be
addressed meaningfully only in a global framework.''''The narrow
focus and approach by the Council will heighten tensions, not
lessen them,'' it warned.
	   
</TEXT>
