<SLUG> BC-Belarus-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. diplomat ordered to leave summer residence in Minsk, gates
</HEADLINE>
welded &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MINSK, Belarus (AP) _ Belarusian authorities ordered the
American ambassador to vacate his summer residence so that it can
be repaired, and tried Monday to weld shut the gates, Ambassador
Daniel Speckhard said.
	   Diplomats from 22 countries were notified in April that they had
to leave their summer homes because the post-World War II-era
complex outside the Belarusian capital, Minsk, needed long-term
repairs, Speckhard said at a news conference.
	   Speckhard took reporters to his residence in the diplomatic
complex at Drozdy and arrived to find two workers and a policeman
trying to weld shut the side gate. A small American flag was lying
on the ground. The workers left when Speckhard protested.
	   The ambassador said the government told him no vehicles will be
allowed into the complex starting Wednesday. He said his parents
were arriving in Minsk that day and he had hoped they could stay at
the residence, commonly called a dacha.
	   He said the United States has occupied the dacha since 1992, the
year after Belarus gained independence with the collapse of the
Soviet Union, and has since then spent dlrs 800,000 on repairs.
	   Speckhard said governments have no right to insist that foreign
diplomats leave their residences against their will. He appealed to
Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko to rescind the order.
	   ``I am hopeful that this press conference today will help to
inform the president of the situation in case he has not been
receiving the right information from his bureaucracy,'' Speckhard
said.
	   ``I think it very important that the government of Belarus sends
some different signals today or tomorrow on this issue.''
	   (str/ls/mr) 	   
