<HEADLINE>
No power can stop building of Ram temple: VHP, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
No power can stop building of Ram temple: VHP, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Indian Premier AB Vajpayee on Saturday asserted that no
construction activity for a temple was going on near the disputed
temple-mosque site at Ayodhya only to be contradicted by temple
makers who say preparations are in full swing and no power on earth
can stop us building the shrine,.Vajpayee's counter comes a day
after the entire opposition walked out of parliament charging that
workmen were giving finishing touches to prefabricated materials in
different cities to build a temple at the site where Babri mosque
was demolished in December 1992 and demanded a categorical
statement from the government. Prime Minister's assertion focusing
on 'the site'' is not dissimilar to that of the Home Minister IK
Advani's that court orders in this regard would be scrupulously
adhered to.
	   The opposition's contention that the temple fabrication activity
is going on in 'different cities'' has not been contested by the
leader of the pro-Hindu ruling Bharatiya Janata Party which has
been supporting the cause of temple and the government-opposition
tussle is likely to continue.Prime Minster told reporters ``I will
ascertain all facts and the information I have is that no
construction activity is going on anywhere near the disputed
site''.''Preparation is in full swing to construct Ram Temple in
Ayodhya and no power on earth--not even the Supreme Court-- can
prevent Vishwa Hindu Parishad (vhp) from achieving the goal, vhp
general secretary Acharya Giriraj Kishore said.
	   In an interview to the latest issue of Outlook' magazine, the
vhp leader said that the cutting and carving of stone for the Ram
Temple, now being done in Ayodhya in full swing, would be completed
in two years, according to a press release by the
periodical.Expecting the BJP government ``to remove all impediments
and hindrances'' in the construction of the temple, Kishore
remarked ``The land will be definitely handed over to us.
	   ``The vhp's assertion is in striking contrast to assurances
given by Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee and Home Minister
Advani in parliament this week that the BJP-led coalition
government would maintain the status quo ordered by the apex
court.''What is our work now ? only to make the temple Bhavya'
(grand),'' he said, adding ``in India there is only one Dharma' --
that is Hinduism. The others are Mazhabs.''''The Puja at the
disputed site cannot be stopped. Nobody can move the makeshift
temple,'' Kishore said.Although the title suits are still in court,
the vhp leader said that would pose no problem.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
