<SLUG> C-&AMP;-W-TO-DELIST-IN-HK sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
C&AMP;W to delist in HK as volume falls, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
C&AMP;W to delist in HK as volume falls, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Karen ChanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE British telecoms giant, Cable and Wireless (C&AMP;W), announced
on Sunday that it would delist its shares from the Stock Exchange
of Hong Kong on 29 June.
	   The move comes shortly after C&AMP;W announced it had filed an
application to delist its stock from the foreign section of the
Tokyo Stock Exchange on 13 May and shares would be delisted from
the Tokyo exchange on 21 August.
	   C&AMP;W company secretary Ken Claydon said C&AMP;W shares were hardly
traded on the Hong Kong exchange.
	   As of Friday, only 265 shareholders, holding 749,050 shares or
0.03 per cent of the C&AMP;W's issued capital, were registered with the
Hong Kong exchange.
	   Records indicate that an average daily trading volume for C&AMP;W
shares within the six-month period from 6 December 1997 to 5 June,
was only 87 shares.
	   According to the exchange records, there were no transactions
for C&AMP;W shares over the past five weeks, with the last active
trading date being on 27 April involving only 500 shares at $86.45
per share.
	   ``There are comparatively few shareholders who trade our shares
trade on the Hong Kong exchange, and trading volume is low. And
compared with our listing on the London Stock Exchange, we decided
the Hong Kong listing's costs were not justifiable,'' Mr Claydon
said.
	   Mr Claydon, however, emphasised that the group still had full
confidence in Hong Kong' future prospects and economy.
	   Although Hong Kong is the biggest profit contributor to C&AMP;W, the
company has been decreasing its presence in Hong Kong since the
handover.
	   The group posted an 8 per cent rise in net income before
exceptional items to 732 million (HK$9.22 million) for fiscal 1997.
With the exceptional gain, net income was 1.28 billion.
	   A one-time gain of 837 million was posted, including 519 million
from the sale of 5.4 per cent in Hongkong Telecom, and 524
compensation for the early termination of an exclusive IDD licence
for Hongkong Telecom.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
