<HEADLINE>
Owners likely to slash flat prices, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Owners likely to slash flat prices, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Karen ChanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FLAT owners may soon reduce the asking price for flats in the
secondary market by 5 to 8 per cent because of the recent
undercutting by property developers.
	   Ricacorp Properties area manager for Tuen Mun and Yuen Long
Jacky Fung said the Paliburg Group's Park Royale development in
Yuen Long had received a favourable response owing to its
attractive average launch price of $2,834 per square foot.
	   In contrast, the secondary market in Yuen Long was quiet.
	   Managing director of Ricacorp Properties Barry Law said all eyes
were on the primary market with the undercutting, flexible payment
terms and top-up mortgages.
	   While most of the new projects launched during the first half of
the year have been in the New Territories, the area's secondary
market has been hardest hit.
	   According to a survey conducted by Centaline Property Agency,
the transaction price of major developments in the New Territories
has fallen across the board.
	   Senior Supervisor of Centaline Property Agency (Royal Ascot)
branch Ray Au said the launch price for most new developments was
about 10 to 20 per cent lower than the market price, and there had
been a big fall in transactions in the secondary market.
	   Mr Au said another 22,000 new flats would come on to the New
Territories market by the end of the year and there was pressure on
prices in the secondary market.
	   He said the latest transaction in Royal Ascot, Fo Tan, had
recorded a 50 per cent fall in price from when it was at its peak.
	   He said the transaction price for Block 6 of Royal Ascot, which
contains flats of 1,236 sq ft, was $6.05 million, or $4,895 per sq
ft.
	   According to Hong Kong Property Services (Agency), the price of
flats has fallen to 1994 and 1995 levels.
	   
</TEXT>
