<SLUG> FEAR-OF-INDO-PAK-WAR sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fear of Indo-Pak war overplayed, say analysts, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Fear of Indo-Pak war overplayed, say analysts, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Fears of a war between India and Pakistan, after a display of
nuclear prowess, were overplayed and the two neighbours are likely
to return to the negotiating table to resolve their dispute over
Kashmir, analysts said on Sunday.''What has happened is both sides
which had missiles and bombs have exploded them. Now they (will)
proceed with the talks,'' said analyst BG Verghese.The UN Security
Council on Saturday unanimously condemned India and Pakistan for
the nuclear tests and urged the two to stop all nuclear arms
development programmes.India voiced its regret over the ``coercive
and unhelpful'' resolution adopted by the Security Council and
turned down any third party involvement in resolving its disputes
with Pakistan.Analysts said the reactions of the Security Council
and its five permanent members were along expected lines, and their
condemnation of India and Pakistan was not a surprise.
	   They said the SAARC (South Asian Association For Regional
Cooperation) summit in Colombo next month could provide a forum for
Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee and Pakistan Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif to discuss contentious issues.Analysts said
any fears of a nuclear war in the region were unfounded. ``There
are no war clouds hanging...nuclear weapons prevent a war,'' said
Savita Pande of the Institute of Defence Studies and Analysis.She
said there was no mad arms race in South Asia like the one that
existed between the two superpowers during the Cold War. ``If
nuclear weapons could ensure peace and stability in Europe, they
will definitely do it in Asia.''Verghese said the fear of a nuclear
war ``is all bogus'', adding: ``The notion that these are
irresponsible leaders leading weak governments is all imagined
fears.''In the next few weeks, he said, things would settle down
and a dialogue between India and Pakistan would be put back on
rails.
	   ``I think now there will be negotiations on the issue of Kashmir
because direct talks is the hallmark of Indian diplomacy on this
issue,'' said Pande.But a lot would depend on Pakistan's stance,
since India had made a set of proposals in January for reopening
talks, she said.Talks between the two nations were stalled last
year because of their dispute over Kashmir, the cause of two of the
three wars they have fought since independence from Britain in
1947.Tension between the two countries escalated last month after
India carried out five nuclear tests, followed by Pakistan.''India
has had talks with Pakistan in the past and it will agree to have
them again,'' said Pran Chopra of the Centre for Policy Research.
	   ``The ball is in Pakistan's court since India has already made a
set of proposals.''Sharif was quoted on Sunday as saying that South
Asia was on the verge of a ``disastrous'' nuclear arms race, and
urged the global community to address the Kashmir issue to avert
the risk of a nuclear conflict.In an interview with the official
UAE newspaper Emirates News published on Sunday, Sharif said
Pakistan's protracted dispute with India over Kashmir was the root
of regional tension.
	   But Vajpayee said on Saturday that Kashmir should be kept
separate from the nuclear issue.Analysts said too much should not
be read into Sharif's remarks since Pakistan had always sought to
link the nuclear issue with Kashmir.Chopra said the Kashmir issue,
on which the global view had been limited, was brought back into
sharp focus after the blasts.Sharif, in his Saturday interview,
invited Vajpayee for talks to end the arms race. Separately,
Vajpayee said India was always ready for talks with Pakistan to
resolve all outstanding bilateral issues, including Kashmir.
	   
</TEXT>
