<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Toxic Chemical </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Toxic chemical found at former Mitsubishi plant site
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Dangerous amounts of a toxic chemical that causes
cancer was discovered at a former Mitsubishi Heavy Industries Ltd.
plant site under consideration for a sports center, officials said
Monday.
	   Ground water at the site in the central Japanese city of Nagoya
contains seven times the legal concentration of CIS-1,
2-dichloroethylene, said Masao Sugiura, an environmental official
with Nagoya city.
	   Mitsubishi used the chemical, a dirivative of the carcinogenic
chemical trichloroethylene, while making diesel engines at the site
until 1985, a company official said.
	   Sugiura said the chemical was found in a concentration of .28
milligram per liter, seven times higher than the maximum allowable
limit of .02 milligrams per liter.
	   The government surveyed the groundwater near the former plant in
preperation for building a sports center in the city, 269
kilometers (168 miles) west of Tokyo, Nagoya official Toyohiko
Owaki said.
	   Last week, officials announced that they found ground water at a
Toshiba Corp. plant in Nagoya with trichloroethylene, or TCE,
15,670 times the level the environmental agency considers safe.
	   TCE causes cancer in laboratory animals, and studies indicate it
may be the cause of lupus erythematosus and other connective-tissue
and immune-system diseases.
	   (sk-jc)
</TEXT>
