<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Nigeria Training,0497 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Nigeria gets defensive in practice; Kanu sits
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HOWARD FENDRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   RESSONS, France (AP) _ The attack is out of synch and Nwankwu
Kanu's latest injury does not bode well. Yet Bora Milutinovic
devoted Nigeria's first full-squad World Cup practice Monday to the
real crisis: defense.
	   Kanu did not take part in the morning training session because
of a bothersome left ankle, a team source said.
	   The Inter Milan striker, who inspired Nigeria to the 1996
Olympic gold medal, could help boost the sagging offense. Nigeria
managed just one goal in its last three tuneup games.
	   Of more concern to Milutinovic, though, is a defense that
conceded 12 goals in that span.
	   ``All those goals are not just our goalkeeper's fault,'' the
coach said. ``Everyone is to blame. The whole team let those in.''
	   With defender Jero Shakpore in Italy having his left shoulder
examined by his club doctor, defender Mobi Oparaku had a long spell
at right back Monday.
	   Oparaku, who plays for Belgian club Kapellen, is not on the
official 22-man roster. But teams have until Wednesday to replace
injured players, and Oparaku seems destined to replace Shakpore if
the rising star is ruled out.
	   Shakpore, 19, hurt the shoulder in the first half of Nigeria's
5-1 loss at the Netherlands last week.
	   None of the roster members plays club soccer in Nigeria, and
Milutinovic has not had many chances to work with them since taking
over the team in December.
	   He ran a mostly leisurely, 1 1/2 hour practice at the team's
facility in Resson, a small village 80 kilometers (50 miles) north
of Paris.
	   The final 30 minutes featured an animated half-field scrimmage,
with the Yugoslav coach barking instructions in a mix of English,
French and Spanish.
	   He emphasized positioning and midfield help, areas that have
been disastrous in the Super Eagles' last two outings, the drubbing
at Amsterdam and a 3-0 loss at Yugoslavia.
	   Veteran 'keeper Peter Rufai _ who let in two goals in one half
of play against Netherlands _ worked with the first-team unit
Monday, an indication he will start Saturday's opener against Spain
in Nantes.
	   Rufai plays for Deportivo La Coruna in the Spanish league and
started at the 1994 World Cup, when Nigeria went close to knocking
off eventual finalist Italy in the second round.
	   The team arrived in France Saturday night, and Milutinovic gave
most of his charges the day off Sunday, when only a handful of
reserves and the three 'keepers worked out. The team is set to
practice twice a day until Friday, when it will travel to Nantes by
train.
	   Milutinovic said he expects Kanu to join his teammates in
practice Tuesday.
	   Kanu, 21, has been beset by a series of lingering leg injuries
over the past six months, hampering his comeback from 1996 heart
valve surgery.
	   (hjf-rjm) 	   
</TEXT>
