<SLUG> BC-Japan-US-Marines </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Marine released on bail from Japanese jail in high-profile case
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A U.S. Marine was released on bail from a Japanese
prison Monday after three American congressmen lodged protests last
week with Japan's Ambassador in Washington.
	   Pvt. Rocky Stubbs of Coshocton, Ohio, was handed over to U.S.
military forces on 1.7 million yen (dlrs 12,600) in bail paid by
his family and a lawyer, the Marine Corps said in a statement
released late Monday.
	   Stubbs and Pfc. William Costello of Farmingdale, New Jersey,
have pleaded innocent to charges stemming from fight on March 7 at
a bar near their base on Japan's southernmost island of Okinawa.
	   Costello was released Friday on the same amount of bail.
	   Also Friday, Sens. Robert Torricelli of New Jersey and Mike
DeWine of Ohio and Rep. Christopher Smith of New Jersey met with
Japanese ambassador Kunihiko Saito to express concern over the
case. The lawmakers were troubled by reports the two Marines were
interrogated for 10 to 12 hours.
	   The congressmen had previously written a joint letter to Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto about the pair's treatment by Japanese
authorities and the prospects for a fair trial.
	   Stubbs has acknowledged striking a local plaintiff in the case
and Costello has admitted head butting, kicking and hitting the
man, but both Marines said they did so in self-defense.
	   Final arguments in the case will be heard on July 6 and the
sentencing has been scheduled for July 22, the Marines said.
