<SLUG> HUNGER-IGNITING sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hunger igniting another wave of riots in Indonesia, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Hunger igniting another wave of riots in Indonesia, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Jakarta is still clearing away the debris from the May riots
that turned parts of the city into a wasteland of gutted buildings
and burned-out cars and left more than 1000 dead.But the spectre of
mass unrest has not been exorcised by the departure of former
President Suharto, analysts say. And next time, they warn, it could
be even worse.As Indonesia's economy lurches deeper into
depression, an explosive mixture of rising prices, mass
unemployment and worsening poverty is posing an ever-increasing
risk of igniting another wave of rioting and violence.Indonesia's
Central Bureau of Statistics forecasts an economic contraction of
10.1 percent this year and inflation of 80 to 85 percent. If more
unrest breaks out, according to bureau chairman Sugito Suwito,
inflation will hit 100 percent or more.The labour ministry expects
1998 unemployment to reach 15.4 million -- 17.1 percent of
Indonesia's 90 million workforce.
	   Marie Pangestu, an economist at Jakarta's Centre for Strategic
and International Studies, says by the end of the year 58 million
of Indonesia's 200 million population will be living below the
poverty line, compared with 22.5 million before the crisis.And as
the income of the poor is falling, the price of basic foods and
commodities is rocketing.''The food situation is very serious,''
said Thee Kian Wie, senior research associate at Indonesia's Centre
for Economic and Development Studies.''This is not just a problem
for the urban centres, it affects the rural poor also. And of
course, there is a strong connection between increasing poverty and
food shortages and the prospect of further unrest.''A severe
drought has battered this year's rice harvest, while the price of
imported foods like rice, sugar and wheat flour has been catapulted
upwards by the collapse of the currency--the rupiah has plunged
almost 80 percent against the dollar since July.
	   Food scarcity has been worsened by damage to the distribution
network after thousands of ethnic Chinese, who make up the bulk of
Indonesia's traders, fled the country. Food riots broke out in
Indonesia in February and March as the economic crisis began to
bite, and when the government removed fuel subsidies in early May
the North Sumatran capital of Medan was shaken by several days of
fierce rioting.The riots spread to Jakarta when at least four
students were killed during an anti-Suharto protest. The official
human rights commission put the number of dead in the capital at
more than 1,100.Suharto resigned on May 21 but new President B.J.
Habibie faces the task of maintaining control through even worse
hunger and higher inflation. Many analysts doubt his ability to
survive.''You've got high unemployment, the country is on the brink
of hyperinflation and at the same time, at the very apex of the
political system you have a president who is a weak president,''
said Bruce Gale, manager of the Political and Economic Risk
Consultancy in Singapore.''He's not enthusiastically supported by
the army.
	   If there was massive unrest, how long could Habibie
last?''Indonesia had been due to remove subsidies on basic foods on
October 1, one of its promises to the International Monetary Fund
in return for a $41.2 billion bail-out package.But the Medan riots
showed the risks of removing subsidies, and the government says it
has agreed with the IMF that subsidies can stay for the moment and
be phased out more gradually.Given the ruinous state of the
country's public finances and the persistent weakness of the
rupiah, however, the government may find itself unable to cope with
the cost of keeping prices down.And if unrest does explode, the
army may be unable--or unwilling--to prop up Habibie.''The
military, even if it wanted to control the situation, may not be
able to. It's not large relative to the population.
	   As a rule of thumb, they could hold only two urban centres
simultaneously, if you assume massive unrest,'' Gale said.Financial
markets have shown little faith in Habibie's chances of survival.
The punch-drunk rupiah is lying inert below 11,500 to the dollar
and shares have failed to make a significant advance beyond the
lows they hit during the Jakarta riots. Analysts say Jakarta's
markets are paralysed by the fear of more upheaval and unrest.''The
markets are dominated by political uncertainty and I think that
will last at least until we have elections, whenever that may be,''
said David Chang, head of research at Jakarta's Trimegah
Securities. ``You have various groups calling for the removal of
Habibie and his position is not strong. And the poor and unemployed
made up the mobs that rioted in Jakarta. As people get poorer you
could see it happening again.''Warnings of a doomsday scenario of
economic collapse and national disintegration are growing louder.
	   Amien Rais, opposition figurehead and leader of a Moslem group
claiming 28 million members, said last week economic crisis and
political uncertainty could turn multi-ethnic Indonesia into
``another Yugoslavia''.If the country does slide towards anarchy,
the military may seize its chance to take political control.''If
the situation worsens and we see more unrest, Habibie will not
last. What we may have then is a military government,'' Gale said.
``Given the difficulties faced by the country, that may not
necessarily be a bad thing.''
	   
</TEXT>
