<SLUG> BC-UN-Drug Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Clinton meets at U.N. to discuss anti-drug efforts
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Precede WASHINGTON &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Clinton at UN. &QL; 
 &UR; By SONYA ROSS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Armed with plans for a dlrs 2 billion
media campaign to help stanch the flow of drugs across
international borders, President Bill Clinton huddled Monday with
otlivering the opening address at the U.N. General Assembly special
session on drugs before representatives of about 150 countries,
including 35 heads of state and government.
	   In his address, Clinton was announcing a dlrs 2 billion,
five-year media campaign against drugs, targeting young people,
said national security adviser Sandy Berger. Clinton will ask
Congress to provide dlrs 175 million of that money, with the rest
coming from businesses and philanthropic organizations, Berger
said.
	   The money will be used for public service advertisements
spreading anti-drug messages to young people, and a ``virtual
university'' for preventing and treating substance abuse, using the
Internet and other media for discussions on reducing the drug
supply and the demand that feeds it, Berger said.
	   A list of talking points distributed by the White House
indicates a 49 percent drop in overall U.S. drug use in the United
States since 1979 and a 70 percent decrease since 1985. Arguing
that changing young people's attitudes is an urgent matter, the
president also points out plans to launch the media campaign in
July and asks Congress to extend the program until 2002.
	   The focus of the U.N. session is on curbing the laundering of
drug proceeds and reducing demand among drug users. Clinton wants
the world to unite behind a common strategy for fighting both,
White House spokesman Josh Silverman said Sunday.
	   In the talking points released Monday, Clinton pledged a
crackdown on money laundering with other nations that will ``extend
the long arm of the law, as well as the hand of compassion, to
match the global reach of the problem.''
	   That would give Clinton a chance to advance his own proposal for
containing other international threats, such as terrorism, illegal
immigration, trafficking in people and global crime rings that are
a threat to newer, weaker democracies. He made the proposal last
month before the annual summit of the world's eight largest
industrialized nations in Birmingham, England.
	   Among those scheduled to attend the session were Presidents
Jacques Chirac of France, Ernesto Zedillo of Mexico, Rafael Caldera
of Venezuela, Alberto Fujimori of Peru, Hugo Banzer of Bolivia and
Ernesto Samper of Colombia.
	   In a prepared text of his remarks, Zedillo called for a
``balanced strategy'' to combat drug trafficking ``so that no one
can become the judge of others and no one feels entitled to violate
other countries' laws for the sake of enforcing its own.''
	   This is a clear reference to the controversy over ``Operation
Casablanca,'' a major U.S. money-laundering sting which led to the
arrests month of 42 people _ including about two dozen Mexican
bankers.
	   Zedillo, reflecting the views of most Latin American leaders,
said efforts by consumer countries to reduce demand for drugs
``must be significantly strengthened'' and ``should be seen as a
public health issue'' rather than strictly a law enforcement
problem.
	   The United Nations has estimated that, even with aggressive
interdiction, law enforcement agencies would be able to seize only
about 10 percent of heroin shipments and 30 percent of cocaine
shipments worldwide.
</TEXT>
