<HEADLINE>
Slovaks start up controversial nuclear plant
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with reaction from Austrian chancellor. PICKS UP 5th
graf pvs'' Last month, a ... ADDS byline &QL; 
 &UR; By JANA DOROTKOVA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRATISLAVAr campaigners and neighboring Austria,
	   The plant in Mochovce is just 120 kilometers (72 miles) east of
Austria, which argues that certain features of the heavy water
pressure reactor make it unsafe. Austria is the only country to
have built a nuclear power plant, then voted in 1978 by referendum
against putting it online or having nuclear power.
	   Mochovce is a 440 MW Soviet-designed plant subsequently equipped
with Western technology.
	   Plant spokesman Rastislav Petrech said it received a go-ahead
from the Slovak nuclear authority on Sunday to activate its nuclear
fuel rods after the authority deemed the plant ``met all the safety
and technical conditions.''
	   Austrian Chancellor Viktor Klima on Monday condemned the startup
as ``an irresponsible and unfriendly act,'' the Austria Press
Agency reported.
	   In recent weeks, Klima and Slovak Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar
have repeatedly discussed concerns over Mochovce.
	   Klima said Meciar broke an agreement by failing to notify him
about the startup of the power plant.
