<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-World Cup Fever </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lebanon gears up for World Cup with war of flags
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo BEI101 &QL; 
 &UR; By ZEINA KARAM &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Looking at the multitude of national
flags hanging from buildings and street corners, one would think
that Lebanon is preparing to host an international conference.
	   Not so. It is the World Cup 1998 fever.
	   Lebanon may be nowhere near playing in the tournament that
begins Wednesday, but that hasn't dampned the enthusiasm of
Lebanese soccer fans who are waging a war of flags to root for
their favorite team.
	   The flags mix strangely with pictures of candidates running for
Lebanon's municipal elections, with portraits of solemn-looking
contestants competing for space with the colorful flags of World
Cup participants.
	   Brazil's flags are everywhere, hanging from buildings,
fluttering on street corners, draped on car windshields and
adorning shop fronts. So are the flags of Germany, Italy, France
and Britain.
	   Lebanese fans of all ages seem to be split between Brazil,
winner of four World Cup titles, and three-time champion Germany.
	   ``I have always been a German fan,'' said Fuad Khoueiry, a
grocer whose customers are greeted with a large picture of
Germany's team.
	   ``That's because the Germans, Hitler aside, are the best people
in the world. They are intelligent, hard-working and persevering,''
said the man in his 50s who has never visited Germany.
	   Tony Zoghbi, 28, has a slightly less passionate reason for
putting up the green Brazilian flag outside his home.
	   ``I did it to spite my next-door neighbor, who's a German
fanatic,'' he laughed. ``Plus, the Brazilians are excellent
players,'' he added.
	   The World Cup has also proved to be an opportunity for many to
make money.
	   Street peddlers are selling a range of World Cup accessories _
pirated, of course _ such as flags, T-shirts and caps on street
corners.
	   Some restaurants are scrambling to buy small television sets to
attract _ and keep _ clientele during matches.
	   Sales of small TV sets have reportedly shot up 50 percent in the
runup to the competition. At least a couple of giant screen for
more lavish, open air attractions are being set up.
	   Even during the 1975-90 civil war, the World Cup was a hit in
this soccer-mad nation of 3.2 million. Militiamen stopped shooting
and residents cranked up electrical generators just to watch
matches on TV.
	   Although Arab countries Tunisia, Morocco and Saudi Arabia are
taking part in the 1998 games, they are receiving little support
from fellow Lebanese Arabs.
	   ``In short, many Lebanese are doing to football what they do in
their everyday lives: admire the foreigner and back the winner,''
an editorial in the English-language Daily Star said Monday.
	   What remains to be seen is whether Brazilian flags will be left
in place after the tournament to welcome President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso who arrives here next month.
 &UR; zk-sfg/vj
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Lebanon-World Cup Fever; CT:i; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
