w1136 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  007-NEW-T-&AMP;-T'S-LICENCEs     06-08 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> 007-NEW-T-&AMP;-T'S-LICENCE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
007 New T&AMP;T's licence to make a killing, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
007 New T&AMP;T's licence to make a killing, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   David EvansASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   NEW T&AMP;T Hong Kong, the telecom subsidiary of the Wharf Group,
has been so successful it has become a victim of its own success,
says New T&AMP;T president Leslie Harris.
	   New T&AMP;T's launch three years ago introduced competition into
Hong Kong's fixed network telecommunications market as part of the
de-regulation of the local telecommunications industry.
	   Since then the company's share of telephone lines previously
registered with Hong Kong Telecom (it switched to a new operator
while retaining its original number) has seen a staggering rise.
	   In July 1996, New T&AMP;T had a 39 per cent share of these lines
with the rest being distributed among the other fixed telephone
network operators.
	   By February this year it had grown to an 85 per cent market
share, a performance the company attributes in part to the
organisation's aggressive advertising campaign of its International
Direct Dialing (IDD) services.
	   Mr Harris admits the New T&AMP;T's ``in your face'' advertising
campaign has been successful, too successful perhaps.
	   Market research conducted by the company show that many telecom
users think of New T&AMP;T as primarily an IDD provider.
	   The company now needs to raise consumers' perceptions to boost
its image as a $2 billion telecom network investor, Mr Harris said.
	   New T&AMP;T wants its blue-chip customer base to recognise the
firm's image with its contract to supply high-speed data links to
HongkongBank and global conferencing.
	   ``We are famous for not being a shy kind of company. We tend to
be pretty much in your face with our kind of marketing,'' Mr Harris
says. Part of that success was the clever acquisition of one of the
most memorable numbers in the world for the company's code to
access the international telecommunication services, 007.
	   By not participating in the draw for the 008 number, the company
picked up a number it hoped would be a licence for making a killing
in Hong Kong's telecommunications market.
	   ``We were particularly successful with IDD 007,'' said Mr
Harris.
	   ``We continue to ride on the back of that success and it has
been our major promotional vehicle. It's also probably the most
memorable number in the world,'' he said.
	   ``On the other hand, so powerful was our marketing and
advertising of it, that people forgot there was this new company
called New T&AMP;T that was building the best network in Hong Kong,''
Mr Harris said.
	   Such unabashed modesty is difficult to challenge in a man at the
helm of a company that since its launch, has achieved enviable
success within Hong Kong's burgeoning newly-deregulated
telecommunications market.
	   Being part of the Wharf Group, New T&AMP;T can benefit from the
synergy it creates with Wharf Cable, Hong Kong's exclusive cable
television provider.
	   ``Technology has now brought cable telephony into existence so
instead of us having to build a telecom network to pass 600,000
homes, we can access the homes that Wharf Cable have and utilise
their expertise and resources,'' said Mr Harris.
	   ``We've been waiting for technologies to come along so we can
realise the opportunity for our investments much more
cost-effectively,'' he said.
	   The company has grown steadily in its short history and has
reached a point where it's time to take a more measured approach
towards its future business strategy, Mr Harris said.
	   ``Managing growth is a very difficult thing because the
temptation is that as you're growing, you keep piling in the
resources in a relatively unthinking way,'' he said.
	   ``When you cease to be a small company which you can direct
personally and you've become a large company with more complex
structures, you have to take a deep breath and work out how to
convert your company into something that is more measured,'' he
said.
	   Mr Harris says the regional crisis has speeded up this process.
	   ``We have reached that point earlier because of the changed
climate in Hong Kong. Normally we might have let the company rip
for another year before we started to refer to issues that we had
put aside for future attention,'' he said.
	   ``We are now beginning to work the measures and ratios to see
how we can improve our business by making it more inherently
efficient, rather than just putting more bodies against the
problem.'' The company's transition to a large organisation, coming
as it does in the middle of the region's downturn, calls for a
review of company and staff structures and adopting ``efficiency''
as the watchword.
	   ``We are ensuring we maximise the output of our workforce to
make it as efficient as we can,'' Mr Harris said.
	   ``That means looking at our structures to see if any are getting
in the way. Now that we've become a big company, we can no longer
do some of the things we used to. We are trying to remain dynamic
because it would be easy for operations to become
institutionalised,'' he said.
	   Mr Harris said employees have expectations and when the concept
of change is introduced people start to put little fences around
their turf.
	   The key to the company's success comes from adopting classic
market entry strategies and remaining focused on its core product,
Mr Harris added.
	   ``We're not like the other companies, we don't have any
distractions. We don't have a mobile licence, we don't have paging,
we just focus on the fixed network service and what that brings,''
he said.
	   ``We are focused on being a fixed line operator bringing all the
benefits to customers that we can through that technology. There
are approximately 350,000 in Hong Kong and they were the neglected
underclass of the market,'' he said.
	   ``It wasn't a sector of the market the monopoly (Hongkong
Telecom) tended to bother with until there was competition. These
businesses are feeling very happy at the moment because we started
addressing them,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
