</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Elections,0491 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Beirut votes for religious harmony; Amal and Hezbollah split
</HEADLINE>
Shiites &QL; 
 &UR; By SAM F. GHATTAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Muslims and Christians endorsed religious
harmony in Beirut and militant Shiite Muslims made major inroads in
south Lebanon in municipal elections held after a break of 35
years, preliminary results showed Monday.
	   With Beirut having shifted to a Sunni Muslim majority city since
the last elections, many feared only Muslim candidates would win in
Sunday's vote, driving Christians out of local politics in
Lebanon's largest city.
	   But a half-Christian, half-Muslim ticket backed by Prime
Minister Rafik Hariri swept to victory for the 24-member city
council, the results showed.
	   Hariri and other moderate Sunnis campaigned feverishly to urge a
Muslim vote for Christians so that the delicate sectarian balance
could be maintained in the city, as it is in senior government
posts in this country of 18 religious sects.
	   Hariri told the leading newspaper An-Nahar overnight that
national consensus has been preserved, showing the Lebanese have
``abandoned the logic of war and upheld democracy.''
	   In the south, the Iranian-backed Hezbollah that is the major
guerrilla group fighting Israel scored major gains, chipping away
at the power base of the pro-Syrian Amal faction of Parliament
Speaker Nabih Berri.
	   Berri, in a news conference Monday, maintained that Amal alone
stood up against a coalition of Shiite militants, Communists,
leftist nationalists and traditional right-wing politicians.
	   He estimated that Amal won 51 of 75 wholly Shiite towns, tied
with Hezbollah in five others and took control of 22 mixed
Christian-Shiite towns. The prize win for Amal was in the southern
city of Tyre.
	   Preliminary results estimated Hezbollah won 18 municipalities, a
further signal that it has succeeded in transforming itself from a
guerrilla force into a populist movement.
	   Berri confirmed the Hezbollah gains, including the capture of
the teeming market town of Nabatiyeh.
	   Municipal elections have not been held since 1963 because the
1975-90 sectarian civil war and the political tensions that led to
and followed the conflict.
	   Local elections have been held in various parts of the country
for the past two weeks and another round will be held next Sunday.
Official results from Beirut and the south were still not available
since vote counting is manual.
	   Not all were happy with the Beirut outcome. The leftist As-Safir
newspaper on Monday criticized the sectarian character of the
Beirut election campaign.
	   ``It is difficult to speak about democracy in the light of
dominating religious slogans and sectarian fever,'' As-Safir
publisher Talal Salman said in a front-page editorial.
	   ``This is Lebanon after civil war,'' he wrote, adding ``it is
difficult to build a nation'' based on such sectarian feelings. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Lebanon-Elections; CT:i; 
