<BODY>
<SLUG> SOLAR-POWER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Solar power, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Solar power, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Bangladesh is launching its first utility project of renewable
energy with a 62 kw photovoltaic pilot project under final stages
of implementation by the Rural Electrification Board (REB). The
utility will meet energy demands of rural markets, homes and
livestocks in Karimpur and Nazarpur unions of Sadar Thana of
Narsingdi district. The pilot project covers an area of 29 square
kilometres with 8500 households of 21 villages.The REB has already
undertaken planning in the expectation of World Bank funding to
initiate, on completion of the pilot project, two more projects in
Astagram of Kishoreganj district and Shingra of Natore district.
	   The World Bank may provide US $ 5 million for the new projects
from its Global Environment Fund, for which socio-economic survey
and commercial feasibility study are already under preparation. An
expansion in the immediate neighbourhood of the Photovoltaic Pilot
Project of Narsingdi Sadar Thana is also envisaged, to include 5000
consumers of Alokbali and Chardighaldi unions of the thana. French
grant provided the foreign currency requirement of the pilot
project, and further French funding is also expected for its
expansion. Commercial energisation of the project started in
August, 1996. At the current stage, the project is expected to
provide electricity to 1000 different categories of consumers, and
the tariff has been designed in a way that will generate enough
revenue to cover the one-time investment in appliances and their
long-term maintenance.
	   Solar energy as the cleanliest energy with daily recharges from
nature is no doubt most desirable. But for rural users of
electricity, tariff commensurate with initial costs of installation
of photovoltaic charging stations or units including electronic
controls may still be discouraging. Research to bring down those
costs is essential if renewable energy is meant to benefit the
poorest sections of the people. Lower consumer density also may
render such utilities less cost-effective by systems losses and
costs in extended lines of supply. Individual home units are
therefore the answer if the one-time installation costs could be
significantly reduced.
	   
</TEXT>
