<HEADLINE>
Popular journalist freed of slander charges
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) _ A prominent independent journalist was
freed Monday of slander charges filed by an alleged Bosnian warlord
currently standing trial.
	   The alleged warlord, Mladen Naletilic, accused Davor Butkovic, a
former senior editor at the weekly Globus, of slander in an article
describing him as ``a most notorious warlord.''
	   Naletilic, also known by his nom de guerre of Tuta, is thought
to have been a major criminal figure in Mostar, behind crooked
police and politicians who wanted to keep the Bosnian city firmly
split between Muslims and Croats in order to maintain their
political and economic power.
	   During the Bosnian war, he headed the so-called ``Convicts'
Brigade,'' which has been accused of some of the most brutal
massacres of Muslims.
	   A district court judge, Goran B. Hersak, declared Butkovic
innocent, specifying that the reporter was only referring to
Naletilic in the way he had created himself in the public's eyes.
	   Naletilic, 50, has been in custody since his arrest last year on
charges of abduction, assault and battery, inciting murder and
aiding and abetting crime.
	   He has spent most of the time in the jail's hospital ward,
suffering from tuberculosis, and faces 20 years in prison if
convicted.
	   However, his trial has hardly budged, with witnesses unwilling
to appear and testify against him, reportedly fearing reprisals.
	   Naletilic said he had already filed 20 similar lawsuits against
other Croatian papers, adding that he would do the same against
foreign agencies and publishers.
	   (eb/as)
</TEXT>
