<SLUG> DU-THE-GOOD-OLD-DAYS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DU: The good old days, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
DU: The good old days, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Teacher-Student Centre, Dhaka University thronged with
nearly 1100 ladies and gentlemen as the first convention of the DU
Alumni Association was inaugurated by Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina
last Saturday. The PM in her speech stressed the foundation of a
sound higher education system like that which led to Dhaka
University acquiring its reputation as the Oxford of the East'. She
expressed the belief that such a mode of study depended on the kind
of family values that enabled peace to reign at home. Here the
teacher's role is vital in the forging of a society where talented
individuals bring the nation to the forefront in the international
arena.
	   Many of the elderly students (a few in their 80s and even 90s)
from the golden days of Dhaka University shared their memories
during the alumni reunion. The oldest alumni, a 96-year-old
professor, who had been among the poorest when a student, announced
the donating of all his property to the old alma mater now that he
was a rich man. This is a step worthy of emulation by others in
their own way to help the university regain its glory. A general
consensus was that an end should be put to student politics with
the cooperation of all political parties. If students concentrated
on their studies as in the former days of academic eminence, there
could be stimulating debates and enlightening seminars. Students
would also be able to engage in informal discussions on the campus
relating there subject to everyday life.
	   At that time libraries were also extensively used and papers
prepared diligently by many a student. No wonder in those days
after taking the Master's degree one did not have to go through two
years of preliminary studies abroad preparatory to enrolment for
Ph.D. Today students, as a general rule, have to even take a
language test and, on that basis, a language course in English
before taking up their studies in the foreign university. Muscle
power counted for naught then, it was the meritorious who
flourished with scholarships to inspire them in endeavouring to
attain further heights of academic brilliance.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
