<SLUG> BC-Portugal-Road Safety </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Portuguese traffic fatality rate, still worst in Europe, falls
</HEADLINE>
slightly &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Tough new traffic laws have lowered the
number of highway accidents and fatalities in Portugal, but the
country still has the worst road death record in the European
Union, Prime Minister Antonio Guterres said Monday.
	   ``Portugal has a particularly tragic history in road accidents,
which in 1997 killed five times more people than the number of
homicides,'' Guterres told an international road safety conference.
	   However, Portugal is succeeding in changing attitudes and
driving habits, Guterres said.
	   The new highway code, which introduced higher fines for traffic
violations, took effect in March.
	   During April and May, the total number of road deaths fell by 20
percent and accidents causing injuries dropped by 30 percent,
Guterres reported. Detailed figures were not available.
	   The EU statistical agency Eurostat reported last week that per
one million inhabitants, 217 people died on Portuguese roads in
1995, the last year for which European figures were available.
	   The second-worst country was Greece, with 195 per million.
	   Guterres said that efforts were underway to correct road danger
spots, especially poor sign posting and badly-designed junctions.
	   Sixteen people were killed and 316 injured in 594 accidents over
the weekend in Portugal.
	   Meanwhile, 56 people were killed in vehicular accidents from
Friday through Sunday in neighboring Spain, which has five times
the population of Portugal. The figure compared with an average of
20 weekend fatalities so far this year.
	   (bh/mr/krt)
</TEXT>
