<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hungary-Crime </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Four foreigners arrested in connection with bombings
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By EVA KEKES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) _ Two Russians, a German and an Israeli
were taken into custody in connection with bombings that have
rocked Hungary in recent years, senior police officers said Monday.
	   The foreigners were arrested after police raided three houses
around the capital Wednesday and found a laboratory and several
warehouses set up to produce explosives, Laszlo Forgacs, the
national police chief, told reporters.
	   ``This was the first case that police found a laboratory to
produce explosive devices and we hope that this will help us solve
several such attacks,'' police Brig. Gen. Enroe Kiss said.
	   Officers searching the houses found more than 10 kilograms (22
pounds) of explosives, 42 kilograms (92 pounds) of chemicals that
can be used to manufacture explosives and several M25 and M75
Yugoslav-made hand grenades.
	   ``According to preliminary investigation, these materials and
devices are similar to the ones used in several bombing attacks,''
Kiss said.
	   Officials also discovered almost 1 ton of paper that could be
used to print money.
	   Since 1991, the country has seen 111 bombings, killing five
people. Of that number, 38 explosions were attributed to hand
grenades, 36 to bombs, 18 to Molotov cocktails, and the rest were
caused by makeshift devices, such as fire extinguishers, Kiss said.
	   The bombings have largely been associated with battles between
domestic and foreign gangs, including trafficking in drugs and
women. In most cases, victims were from rival gang.
	   The detained foreigners were all in Hungary with valid papers,
and all had legal businesses in the country.
	   Officials refused to release information about the suspects, but
did say one of the Russians is a woman.
	   (ek/scl) 	   
</TEXT>
