w1160 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  QUESTION-MARKS-OVER-SFCs     06-08 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> QUESTION-MARKS-OVER-SFC sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Question marks over SFC after Morgan Stanley debacle, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Question marks over SFC after Morgan Stanley debacle, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   David EvansASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Securities and Futures Commission's (SFC) spat with Morgan
Stanley Asia Ltd (MASL) over its reprimand of the American
investment bank's failure to disclose information in connection
with an injection of assets into China Everbright IHD-Pacific, has
again raised questions over its effectiveness.
	   The SFC accused Morgan Stanley of failing to inform the
investing public that Everbright expected to receive approval from
Beijing authorities for its acquisition of a stake in Everbright
Bank of China.
	   ``It (Morgan Stanley) had not fulfilled its regulatory
responsibility to ensure the public was told this information,''
the SFC said.
	   Immediately after the SFC's reprimand, Morgan Stanley
counter-attacked with a denial that it had violated any regulatory
guidelines saying it had made all the proper disclosures.
	   This was quickly followed by an even stronger attack from the
SFC who admitted they had been taken completely by surprise by
Moragn Stanley's response.
	   According to Mark Dickens, the SFC's executive director of
enforcement, the wording of the initial reprimand had been
carefully negotiated with the company prior to its release.
	   ``Ours (reprimand) would not have been as sweet as it was had we
had any forewarning of their action,'' he said.
	   The apparent nonchalance with which Morgan Stanley rebuked the
SFC's reprimand clearly implies a perception in the industry that
the regulator has a bark that is worse than its bite.
	   Analysts are asking how effective a regulator can be if it has
to engage in a tit-for-tat war of words every time it reprimands an
industry rule breaker.
	   A spokesman for the SFC admitted this was the third time it had
reprimanded Morgan Stanley.
	   ``It received its first about two to three years ago,'' a
spokesman said.
	   ``It received the second in April 1996 for inadequate audit
trials for its brokerage operations.'' Perhaps more importantly,
the latest reprimand comes at a time when the SFC has come under
fire for allowing a number of brokerages to use clients shares
without their knowledge.
	   And even when the SFC does exercise its regulatory powers it
seem this is still not enough of a deterrent.
	   Forluxe Securities director James Mui Kwong-nok had his licence
suspended for five days and was fined $20,000 for illegally using
client's shares the year before he left Hong Kong.
	   Forluxe collapsed and police received over 270 complaints from
clients involving $47 million.
	   Many within the industry are asking whether the SFC has got its
priorities right.
	   The spectacular collapse of Peregrine Investment Holdings, a
company many bankers believe has misled the investing public, has
so far escaped the reach of the SFC's investigative arm.
	   Hopefully the announcement that Peregrine's liquidators are
pursuing $23 billion in assets, a figure far higher than previous
estimates, may provoke some kind of response.
	   According to an SFC source, the public should ``watch this
space'', a statement as ominous as it is vague.
	   The SFC said that since Morgan Stanley acted as an adviser to
Everbright in a $1.9 billion capital raising exercise last June, it
should have disclosed more information about pending mainland
acquisitions at a time when red-chip fever was most intense.
	   Morgan Stanley says it feared any more positive statements could
be interpreted as being falsely optimistic about the deal's
prospects and be seen as an effort to talk up the share price.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
