<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Chemical Warfare </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bumbling apartheid scientist describes poisoned umbrellas,
</HEADLINE>
screwdrivers &QL; 
 &UR; By PAUL HARRIS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ An apartheid-government scientist
testified Monday how he made poisoned umbrellas and screwdrivers
that could kill enemies of white rule, and how his bumbling almost
cost him his own life.
	   Dr. Jan Lourens said the umbrellas, walking sticks and
screwdrivers outfitted with concealed needles were made at the
request of apartheid-era security forces, but that he did not know
if they were ever used to kill anyone.
	   At one point during his testimony before the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission, Lourens described taking vials of poison
to a contact in Britain, known only as ``Trevor.''
	   ``It is rather like a James Bond movie,'' commented Truth
Commission member Dumisa Ntsebeza.
	   ``Unfortunately,'' replied the tall, bespectacled Lourens.
	   However as Lourens told of the encounter, he appeared to have
been more of an Inspector Clouseau.
	   Lourens described accidentally spilling the poison on his hand
as he demonstrated one of the needle units in a cottage near Ascot,
just outside London.
	   ``I don't know how it happened, but I wiped my mouth and I lost
consciousness very quickly,'' Lourens recounted.
	   He said he survived because when he awoke, he staggered to a
bathroom and drank antiseptic until he vomited.
	   Lourens testified to sending equipment to an army research
laboratory for fertility experiments on baboons. He said he had
suspected experiments were being carried out to discover ways of
reducing birth rates among black women.
	   Reports that such research was conducted has surfaced in recent
years, although there is no indication the research ever escalated
into actual attempts to reduce fertility among blacks.
	   Earlier Monday, the Truth Commission turned down a government
request to hold the hearings behind closed doors.
	   The ruling African National Congress, which ended apartheid by
winning all-race elections in 1994, believes some of the
information should not be revealed in public for fear of spreading
dangerous technologies.
	   However, Truth Commission chairman Desmond Tutu rejected the
request, saying potentially sensitive documents had already been
withdrawn from the public hearings.
	   The Truth Commission was set up by President Nelson Mandela in
1995 to probe apartheid-era human rights abuses and promote racial
healing.
	   (ph-aos)
</TEXT>
