<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Middle East Business Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Egypt, Jordan &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ The government will sell all state-owned
inter-city bus routes to private companies next month, the public
sector minister, Atef Obeid, said Monday.
	   The Middle East News Agency quoted Obeid as saying that
state-owned shipping companies will also be sold soon. He gave no
figures for the imminent sales, which are part of Egypt's
7-year-old privatization program to reform the economy.
	   Since 1991, the government has sold to private hands more than
300 state-owned factories, hotels and department stores.
	   Egypt's parliament approved last March the sale of 20 percent of
a government-owned telecommunications company. The government also
put up for sale 30 percent stakes in a company that will take over
the state-run cellular telephone network.
 &UR; ___
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Investments increased 53.9 percent to 131
million dinars (dlrs 184.5 million) in the first half of this year
compared with the same period in 1997, an official said Monday.
	   The rise was due to ``professional servicing, attractiveness and
transparency'' offered by Jordanian investment bills, Muntasser
Oqlah, director general of the semi-independent Investment
Promotion Corp., said.
	   Jordanian laws provide investors with incentives such as tax
exemption and export guarantees and offer foreigners equal rights.
	   Oqlah told The Associated Press that 68 projects in various
sectors benefited from the investments between January and June
this year.
	   In addition to Jordanians, Americans, Canadians, Europeans and
Gulf Arabs invested, he said. He declined to provide a breakdown.
	   Of the total money invested this year, 37 percent was spent in
the hotel sector, 25 percent on industrial projects, 19 percent on
hospitals, 10 percent on transportation and nine percent on
agriculture, he said.
 &UR; ___
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ A group of 28 Jordanian businessmen headed
for Iraq on Monday to explore ways to increase trade.
	   The group, headed by former Trade and Industry Minister Bassam
Saket, comprises leading industrialists and members of the
Jordanian Exporters Association.
	   ``We want to probe the needs of the Iraqi market and discuss
increased trade exchange in the future,'' Saket told The Associated
Press before embarking on the 12-hour overland trip to Baghdad.
	   He said the group will meet with Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammed
Mehdi Saleh and other senior officials as well as private sector
businessmen during its four-day visit.
	   Trade with Iraq is set at dlrs 220 million annually, or 25
percent the volume of exchange between the two neighbors before
Baghdad came under sweeping U.N. sanctions in 1990 for its invasion
of Kuwait.
 &UR; ___
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Egypt's net international reserves climbed
to dlrs 20.1 billion in March from dlrs 20 billion in February, the
Central Bank of Egypt said Monday.
	   Egypt's reserves in March 1997 were dlrs 19.5 billion
	   Before March, the country's foreign exchange reserves had
declined every month since September 1997 with the exception of
January.
	   The decline in reserves followed the Nov. 17 massacre of
tourists in Luxor, which hit receipts from tourism, while revenues
from petroleum exports also came under pressure as a result of a
sharp fall in international oil prices.
