<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Belarus-US, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Diplomats ordered to vacate residences in Minsk
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to ADD byline, ADD that diplomats from about
20 countries been asked to leave residences, that many live their
year-round. &QL; 
 &UR; By MARINA BABKINA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MINSK, Belarus (AP) _ Belarusian authorities ordered diplomats
from 22 countries to vacate their homes for repairs, and tried
Monday to weld shut a gate to the American residence, U.S.
Ambassador Daniel Speckhard said.
	   The government served notice in April that it wanted to overhaul
water and sewage pipes in the post-World War II-era complex on the
outskirts of the Belarusian capital, Minsk, Speckhard said at a
news conference.
	   Speckhard took reporters to the ambassador's residence in the
diplomatic complex at Drozdy and arrived to find two workers and a
policeman trying to weld shut the side gate. A small American flag
was lying on the ground. The workers left when Speckhard protested.
	   The ambassador said the government received a diplomatic note
from the Foreign Affairs Ministry that it planned to start the
repairs Wednesday, the day his parents are scheduled to arrive for
a visit. The note said the repairs cannot begin until the
residences are empty.
	   He said the United States has occupied the residence since 1992,
the year after Belarus gained independence with the collapse of the
Soviet Union, and has since then spent dlrs 800,000 on repairs.
	   Under international law, ambassador's residences are considered
foreign territory and governments have no right to enter them
without permission or insist that diplomats leave against their
will.
	   He appealed to Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko to
rescind the order.
	   ``I am hopeful that this press conference today will help to
inform the president of the situation in case he has not been
receiving the right information from his bureaucracy,'' Speckhard
said.
	   ``I think it very important that the government of Belarus sends
some different signals today or tomorrow on this issue.''
	   The Belarusian Foreign Ministry told the Interfax news agency it
proposed that diplomats move either to new buildings in central
Minsk or begin building new accommodations near Minsk.
	   (str/ls/mr) 	   
</TEXT>
