<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Romania-Miners </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thousands of miners protested throughout Romania
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) _ Almost 20,000 miners throughout the
country protested Monday against the government's failure to reform
the mining system and demanded more help for another 95,000
colleagues who have been laid off.
	   ``The situation is explosive,'' Marin Condescu, the leader of
the Miners Unions Confederation, told to the Associated Press.
	   Miners traditionally were among the best-paid workers in
Romania. Since Communism fell in 1989, radical miners twice
rampaged through Bucharest, violently attacking opponents and
causing the downfall of one premier, Petre Roman.
	   Last summer, the center-right reform government began a massive
program of layoffs, perhaps the biggest in the history of European
mining. Initially, miners were happy to accept payoffs, but now
seem to be realizing their lives have not improved.
	   Miners from five regions marched through local cities shouting
anti-government slogans and submitted lists with their requests to
local authorities.
	   ``We want to work, not to beg!'', ``We voted you but you
betrayed us!''' shouted miners in one town, Targu Jiu in the Jiu
valley area.
	   Inefficient and loss-making state-run companies are currently
being shut down by the reformist government.
	   Some 108 mines will be closed soon, endangering the jobs of many
of the remaining 110,000 miners, Condescu said.
	   The protesters demanded the government compensate miners being
laid off by providing low interest bank loans and land to set up
small farms.
	   They also wanted increased investment for the country's coal,
gold, silver and copper mines.
	   Almost 100,000 miners have been laid off since September 1997 in
a scheme in which the government gives them up to 20 months'
salaries.
	   Miners' groups say the most of the miners have spent this money
and only 10,000 found new jobs.
	   (ma/as)
</TEXT>
