<HEADER>
w1169 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  TRAFFICKING-IN-WOMENsked     06-08 1421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> TRAFFICKING-IN-WOMEN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Trafficking in women: The fallout of their migration, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Trafficking in women: The fallout of their migration, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Mahbub Husain KhanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Trafficking in humans are in the news again. This time six women
and a minor girl have been returned from Pakistan. They are now
staying at Prashanti' a home for rehabilitation and shelter for
women and children run by the Bangladesh National Women Lawyers'
Association. All of these women were taken to Pakistan via India,
and sold to persons for sexual exploitation. Such is the present
situation that the BNWLA officials are hesitant about handing them
over to their guardians, who themselves have been compliant in
handing over their dependents to these traffickers against
pecuniary gain. It is also reported that these rescued women are
among the one hundred or so women taken away to India, Pakistan or
even the Middle East for purposes of sexual abuse.
	   Next to what benefits the poor, perhaps the most controversial
problem with which any modern society must contend is that of
migration. In practical terms, this is the movement of people from
the less to the more advantaged countries. The worst kind of such
movement is the trafficking of women and children for the purposes
of physical and sexual exploitation. While overt forms of slavery
have gradually been erased from almost all countries of the world,
the new form of forced sexual labour seem to be on the rise. Even
countries only marginally above Bangladesh on the economic scale
seem to attract the victims of the racketeers in women. As the
modern economy develops, it comes increasingly to rely on immigrant
labour from abroad.
	   Without this labour supply, there would be grave economic
disorientation, even disaster. Yet there is a strong current of
thought that deeply deplores immigration, is deeply resentful of
migrants and campaigns ardently against their entry and continued
presence. There are today no industrially advanced country, Japan
being the exception, on which the question of migration does not
obtrude as a major political issue. In the case of Bangladesh, we
find the issue of illegal migrants to India and Malaysia, a prickly
political issue for the countries concerned as manifest in the
actions of push-backs' and incarceration. Yet the traffickers of
women seem to have a hold on the law enforcing personnel of India
and Pakistan to avoid arrest and deportation.
	   Despite the obvious resistance of governments and peoples to
migration, particularly, such types of illegal migration leading to
sex trafficking, the rewards must be very high to allow such a
traffic to continue quite unabated. In the Western world we have
seen the increase of women trafficking through the new mafia that
has grown up since the disintegration of the Soviet Union. And it
is now quite possible to come across women belonging to countries
of the former Soviet Union, sustaining themselves in the resorts
and entertainment centres of the developed world, and even in
Bangkok and Manila which have a large Western clientele. In a
similar manner and strategies the underworld in South Asia are
managing to supply sex workers from among the least privileged. The
real tragedy lies, as it does in all contraband dealings including
sex, the street level partners in crime get the least of the
payoffs, which accrue mainly to the underworld bosses.
	   In the latest case of the six Bangladeshi women, they were
probably paid a pittance aside from food and shelter. In the long
run, they would have been much better off at home. However, that
should in no way imply that they are willing participants in this
trafficking, but it also underscores the difficulties of women to
seek and receive justice within the social and legal structures of
South Asia. The example of the East European women indicate that in
some cases there is willing compliance and complicity. But in the
case of the South Asian regions, it is the absence of effective
mechanisms of redress that prevent the victims from breaking out of
their involuntary incarceration for the purposes of sexual abuse.So
much for the dialectics of the phenomenon. What are the mechanisms
of redress? Some of the problems to be encountered in finding
remedial solutions are related to population pressures.
	   Poverty, which is inversely related to population, encourages
the trend of taking shortcuts to augment income whether such
shortcuts are legal and moral or not. And the more the population
growth the less grows the moral pressures to adhere to legal means.
Enter the tempter, in the form of the go-between who suggests to
the woman herself or her guardians, a substantial improvement in
present earnings by the apparently innocent employment in domestic
service with a much enhanced pay. Added to this is the pecuniary
enticement offered to the guardians, in many cases a parent or a
husband. Once the deal is completed and the woman handed over, it
is very difficult to trace her in the multitudes of people in the
urban areas where she is mostly taken, before being transported
across borders. The operation of border transfer is also difficult
to trace with shortage of border patrols and the realities of
corruption amongst a section of the law enforcing agencies.
	   But solving the problem of the population and stricter border
controls are not possible in the short term. In that case the only
solution is accelerated community awareness, resistance, and
effective remedies developed by the communities. Both rural and
urban communities have to be educated in the mechanics of resisting
the allure of illegal employment abroad, and the prospect of
windfall incomes. The persons who do offer such inducements have to
be identified. By now we are quite aware of such famous gangland
figures. In smaller village communities and urban communities
lesser figures of criminal repute can be identified if the effort
is taken. If these people are identified and the law enforcement
authorities kept informed on a regular basis, even corrupt cops
have to do something about the continuing clamour for action
against these criminals. The government departments of Social
Welfare and Women's and Children's Affairs have to have field level
staff responsible for creating awareness about the mechanisms of
illegal trafficking and the resistance to it, amongst the people in
their command areas.
	   Simultaneously organisations such as the Bangladesh National
Women Lawyers' Association have to be encouraged by both the
government, and the donor agencies aiding NGOs, to take effective
steps in preventing trafficking as well as rescuing the victims of
trafficking. Relevant agencies within the SAARC umbrella have to be
activated to combat this problem within the SAARC countries, which
will effectively show the way to techniques applicable to other
destinations such as the Middle East, or Myanmar and thence to
Bangkok. Also this should be treated at par with the political
issues involved in migrations of other types, legal or illegal. No
country really enumerates the numbers engaged in sex trade as it is
a twilight zone, sometimes literally, of labour employment. Neither
tax, nor labour, nor police authorities know for sure the numbers
of such workers within their areas of responsibility. It is
therefore time that the new techniques of information technology
were harnessed to this end.
	   The public and political actions proposed in outline in this
article are in keeping with the controlling forces of the good
society, and consistent with them there is much to be urged, much
to be done. The accommodation to past historical trends can be
improved, made more compassionate. This will bring about a better
life for the more vulnerable elements in our society, a majority of
whom are the poor women in rural areas. We must henceforth consider
in all earnestness how the future can be made safer and better for
them.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
