<HEADER>
w1170 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  END-TO-UK-EXPATS'-TAXske     06-08 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> END-TO-UK-EXPATS'-TAX sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
End to UK expats' tax breaks, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
End to UK expats' tax breaks, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Debbie AnnellsASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ABUSE of foreign earnings deductions could and should have been
specifically targeted by anti-avoidance measures rather than a
withdrawal which penalises many thousands of genuine
short-to-medium term British resident expatriates.
	   Most multi-national employers recognise that an expatriate
assignment requires a package of incentives, and this often
includes a guaranteed level of net pay for the duration of the
assignment.
	   Wherever an employee is seconded to a lower tax jurisdiction,
the abolition of the foreign earnings deduction will increase the
overall payroll costs for employers. What the British government
does not seem to realise is that expatriation is far from being a
holiday.
	   If the Government's rationale was correct, it is hard to see why
any incentives subsidised by the general body of taxpayers should
remain, such as the foreign earnings deduction for seafarers.
	   There will be many situations in which the United Kingdom
resident expatriate will be able to claim relief under a double
taxation treaty to avoid what would otherwise be double taxation on
the same income.
	   But the mechanics of this do not exactly help the cash flow of
expatriates and, in some cases, it is necessary to pay tax in two
countries and recover in the appropriate jurisdiction by making a
treaty claim after the event.
	   Multi-national employers will find themselves picking up the
cost of this in some situations where the foreign earnings
deduction would have prevented the situation from arising.
	   Many expatriates will continue to ``escape'' UK income tax on
their income through a period of non-residence covering a tax year.
	   The Finance Bill makes it clear expatriates who were relying on
foreign earnings deduction can do so for emoluments attributable to
the period to 16 March.
	   But it is clear that the Bill aims to catch schemes put in place
afterwards and is designed to cover attributed additional income to
the period covered by the foreign earnings deduction. However,
there is still time for a change of heart before it becomes an Act.
	   Debbie Annells is director of taxation services at Edsaco
Horwath Hong Kong.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:END-TO-UK-EXPATS'-TAX sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
