<BODY>
<SLUG> FOOD-FOR-EVERYBODY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Food for everybody and the success of population programmes, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Food for everybody and the success of population programmes, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   A M AlimuzzamanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The world population is expected to double by the end of this
century when the total is likely to exceed six billion from 5.5
billion (1992). It is predicted to reach about 10 billion by 2050.
Over the next 35 years, population density in Bangladesh will more
than double from 860 per sq. km. to 1755. Thus when in 1988-89
fiscal the food grain import was twenty-four lakh metric tons, this
seemed to the World Bank more than the requirement. The World Bank
advised not to import any further food grains but to concentrate on
the grow more food' programme by giving the farmers incentive
prices. The key to the food problem is thus to give the farmers
incentive prices, gear up internal procurement programme during the
harvesting season and create lesser demand by gearing up a tight
population programme supported by concerted plans in all the
educational institutions. By 2010 Bangladesh must produce at least
30 million tons of cereals to maintain self-sufficiency provided a
tight population programme is adhered to.
	   Tight population programme is certainly a detailed sterilisation
programme supported by free abortion facilities in each Hospital
and Thana Health Complex. Otherwise the success of the population
so far achieved is likely to rebound as most of the clientele are
illiterate, poor and live in the rural areas. Let there be a debate
over this without wasting any more time. It is said about the
Untied States, the surplus food country,: ``Debate within the
United States on population control might have ended in the 1970s
when birth rates plunged below zero population growth levels.
However, the Supreme Court's decisions in Roe v. Wade and Doe v.
Bolton (1973) ignited new controversy over abortion, and of course
the abortion issue is closely related to population control...
Abortion clinics are developing rapidly in large cities and it was
predicted that within a few years the number of abortions will rise
to 30 to 50 percent of the number of live births.
	   The Supreme Court held that the fetus is not a ``person'' within
the meaning of the Constitution and therefore not entitled to life
under ``due process of law''. Women, however, are guaranteed the
``liberty'' to control their own bodies, that is, to have abortions
at least in the first six months of pregnancy with limited
interference by the states''. Abortions or no abortions but
sterilisation, there must be a systematic and programmed way.
Vigorous efforts are therefore needed by all irrespective of
political affiliations, castes, and cultures now and for years to
come. South Korea's baby boom crowded nurseries and schools during
the 1960s and 1970s. The increasing number of babies later flooded
the labour market in the 1970s and 1980s and the industrial boom
made the family planners to apprehend that the sudden slowdown of
the population growth rate might result in labour shortages as the
population start ageing. But the present economic austerity and
labour retrenchment shows that South Korea's population planning
was justified.
	   There is a similarity between South Korea's baby boom and that
of our experience. Before 1960 the typical South Korean woman used
to bear as many as six children, similar to a typical Bangladeshi
woman. The US experience is different in that the average American
woman's fertility was far below this. Still then, the US women
adopted harsher family planning practices. In South Korea also
fertility declined with remarkable speed. Even then, contraception
and abortions are common. Abortions are about equal to the number
of live births. The South Korean women are averaging fewer births
than in either the US or Japan.'' About 43 per cent of women are
already working in South Korea as child bearing responsibilities
are declining. Population, food and famine are thus a world-wide
phenomenon and concern. A cable sent by Clement Attlee to President
Truman on January 3, 1946 is still relevant.
	   Mr. Attlee told the President that there was a deficit of seven
million tons of food grains between available supply and demand.
``It is our view that unless the maximum quantities that can be
spared are exported from all the producing countries there is a
grave danger of wide famine in Asia and Europe''. Such threats have
now extended to Africa as well. Britain also put greater emphasis
on her population programmes in right earnest and made considerable
changes to the 1971 Abortion Act. Termination of pregnancies was
made available under the National Health Services. Even then the
Area Health Authorities pressed for further and better services in
the 1970s. They urged that ``there should be greater provision for
abortion within the NHS''. The health authorities pointed out that
termination of unwanted pregnancies would make a lot of savings on
the cost of confinements, delivery and after-care alone.
	   In any case the sight of poor women begging for alms while
hugging her new-born baby or women surrounded by small kids cooking
food beside the vacant land along the footpath or parks is common
in the streets. Whenever a visitor goes to the rural areas he is
almost overtaken by the onrush of youngsters, many of whom are not
well cared for and most of whom do not go to school. It is time
that the rich and the upper middle class section of our society
agreed to tighten their belts and were ready to pay more price for
one kg of food grains so that the very poor can be fed at a cheaper
rate and are also ready to abide by the family planning norms, so
that the farmers can get incentive prices for growing more food
grains. Half our population is under 15. About 3 per cent are 65 or
over. The condition of our demographically advanced neighbours is
also not better. Thus they can help us marginally. The US and
Europe can help us but how long? Hence we are to be ready to help
ourselves. Otherwise social discontent at mass level will soon
overtake us thereby undoing all the good deeds of successive
generations.
	   
</TEXT>
