<SLUG> BC-Uganda-Abducted Students </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rebels abduct at least 10 students in bus ambush
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) _ Rebels abducted at least 10 students when
they attacked a passenger bus near a major garrison town in
northern Uganda, a newspaper reported Monday.
	   Fourteen people later died of their wounds and 25 others were
hospitalized after the June 1 ambush near Kitgum, about 300
kilometers (185 miles) north of Kampala, said the government-owned
New Vision newspaper.
	   A police officer, who spoke on condition he was not identified
further, told the newspaper among the dead were students and
soldiers.
	   He said some of the people who fled into the bush might have
also been captured by the Lord's Resistance Army.
	   The rebels, who say they want to oust President Yoweri
Museveni's government, have terrorized northern Uganda for 11
years.
	   Uganda accuses Sudan, its northern neighbor, of arming and
giving refuge to the rebels, who are led by Joseph Kony. Sudan
denies the charge and in turn accuses Uganda of helping rebels in
southern Sudan.
	   The rebels routinely abduct school children. The boys are given
military training and the girls are often distributed among Kony's
fighters as ``wives.''
	   The government has been attempting to secure the release of 21
girls kidnapped by the LRA from a Catholic school in northern
Uganda in February 1997. They turned over 42 Sudanese prisoners of
war to Khartoum and expected to get the girls in return, but the
deal fell through.
