</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> PLANNING-IS-KEY-HAPPY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Planning is key to happy retirement, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Planning is key to happy retirement, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Christopher ReddyASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   BEFORE you buy a flat, you shop around to find the one you want.
You plan and save for a down payment. You compare prices and shop
for the best financing and start saving your money.
	   You do the same when you plan a vacation. You pick a
destination, find out how much the trip costs, who offers the best
value and service, and start saving.
	   Saving for retirement requires similar planning.
	   To retire in the lifestyle you want you need to know what it
costs to live the way you want, how much you need to do that, and
then start saving accordingly.
	   If you want to retire in a grand style (in a big flat, taking
exotic vacations and golfing weekends), you'll need to save far
more than if you plan to retire quietly, taking care of
grandchildren and doing yoga.
	   There are other factors that affect how much you need to save
for retirement. How many working years do you have left? What is
your current salary and your spending habits? What rate of return
are you earning on your investments? What is the inflation rate?
The more working years you have before retirement, the less you
need to save now.
	   A 25-year-old with 30 or more years to save needs to save less
now than does a 50-year-old as he has a lot more time to put money
away.
	   On the other hand, the more the 25-year-old puts away now, and
earns interest on, the greater savings and better lifestyle he will
have when he retires. So don't think because you're young you only
need to save a small amount.
	   The more money you make and the more luxurious your current
lifestyle, the more money you probably will want for retirement.
	   When you are used to receiving big pay checks and living a good
life, you expect to live well even after you stop working.
	   Many doctors, lawyers, senior company executives and other
well-paid professionals save a lot every year for retirement
because they are keen on living comfortably, if not luxuriously,
after they retire. Lucky for them, their good salary makes it
easier to save more! By comparison, less well-paid workers may be
saving less for retirement, partly because they don't have as much
money to set aside once they have paid their living expenses.
	   Secondly, with a modest current lifestyle, they might not expect
to live grandly after they retire.
	   Studies in the US have shown retirees generally need 80 per cent
of their pre-retirement income to live the same lifestyle that they
were used to before retirement. They need less because they no
longer have the same work-related expenses such as transportation,
work clothes, dining out, and socialising.
	   If you are paying a mortgage and expect to own your flat at
retirement, you may need to save a smaller percentage of your
pre-retirement income since you will not need to pay rent.
	   On the other hand, if you expect to rent your flat at
retirement, you need to secure a higher percentage of
pre-retirement income for your years in retirement.
	   The earlier you start to save, the sooner you achieve your
retirement income goal for the same amount of principal.
	   The higher the return your investments generate, the more you
can save. And interest compounds at a surprising speed! You will
need to save more in an environment of high inflation.
	   Once you decide how much you need to save to retire in the
lifestyle that you want, you might start thinking about investing
your money in a way that will best preserve its value in the long
run.
	   Christopher Reddy is marketing director at Principal Insurance.
	   Next week: The Capital Preservation Fund: its pros and cons

</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:PLANNING-IS-KEY-HAPPY sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
