<SLUG> BC-Guinea Bissau-Fighting, 1st Ld-Writethru,0464 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Reports: Loyalist troops in Guinea-Bissau fight off coup attempt
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with about 30 reported dead, comments from U.S.
embassy spokesman. No pickup. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Troops loyal to the government were
Monday involved in heavy fighting in the capital of Guinea Bissau,
West Africa, where they tried to crush a coup attempt led by a
former chief of the armed forces, according to reports.
	   Heavily armed troops were attempting to dislodge renegade
soldiers from military installations about 16 kilometers (10 miles)
outside Bissau on the road to the airport, the Portuguese state-run
news agency Lusa reported in a dispatch monitored here.
	   An unknown number of rebels were holed up at the two separate
military bases _ a military barracks and an arms depot _ in the
suburb of Bra after clashing Sunday with loyalist troops, according
to Lusa.
	   The bases are next to the Russian embassy where staff were
observing the fighting from the roof, a U.S. embassy spokesman said
in a telephone interview.
	   Bryan Hunt said automatic weapons, rocket-propeled grenades and
mortars were being used in the clashes. However, the Russian
embassy staff were unable to identify the two sides, nor could they
say how many were fighting on the rebel side.
	   ``They can't tell who's who. They're all wearing the same
uniforms,'' Hunt said.
	   A reporter for Guinea-Bissau national radio, interviewed by
Lisbon radio TSF, said he counted about 30 bodies scattered around
the two bases.
	   Hunt said gunfire from automatic weapons and small arms could
also be heard in downtown areas.
	   ``We firmly believe that this is a coup d'etat,'' Hunt said.
	   Representatives at peace corps projects around the country
reported that everything was quiet in their areas, according to
Hunt.
	   Reports said troops set up roadblocks on routes to the
presidential palace and other government buildings and military
installations.
	   The rebels took refuge at the Bra installations after sporadic
clashes which began early Sunday at the military high command
building.
	   President Joao Bernardo Vieira said Sunday that former armed
forces chief Brig. Ansumane Mane was leading the revolt and was
backed by members of political opposition parties.
	   In a statement read on public radio, Vieira vowed to ``use all
possible means'' to quash the revolt.
	   Mane was fired six months ago during an official investigation
into the trafficking of arms to the separatist rebels of Casamanca,
a Senegalese province that borders north Guinea-Bissau.
	   Mane formally stepped down and was replaced at a ceremony in
Bissau last Saturday.
	   Guinea Bissau, a former Portuguese colony, has a population of
about 1 million. 	   
</TEXT>
