w1186 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BEATING-THE-HEATsked     06-08 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BEATING-THE-HEAT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Beating the HEAT, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Beating the HEAT, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Dr. Maswoodur RahmanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The entire country has been sizzling with an unprecedented heat
spell. Temperature on the average was around 40 degree Celsius in
the last week of May. Occasional shower for the last couple of days
along with a relatively cool breeze has cooled the situation to a
bearable position. There has been report of deaths due to
heat-stroke. Incidentally all the deaths have been reported from
the northern part of the country which usually experience
relatively much more hotter summer than the other parts of the
country. Seven deaths have been reported from Kurigram district due
to heat-stroke.Knowing about all these deaths, the consequence of
heat spell and subsequent heat-stroke, one is tempted to know more
about heat-stroke, the identifying features, prevention and
management of heat-stroke.
	   Heat-stroke may then be scrutinised and information may be
disseminated to all so that people could combat heat-stroke
resulting from abnormal heat spell or heat wave.There are as many
as 14 disorders resulting from exposure to heat have been
recognised, the most serious one is being heat-stroke.Heat-stroke
is attributed to the failure of the heat relating mechanism.
Characteristic features are the rise of body temperature to a big
height, for example, even up to 110 F., profound disturbance
including convulsions and partial or complete loss of
consciousness. The skin becomes dry and hot. Death is often sudden
and may be due to hyperpotassemia.Hyperpotassemia may be due to
release of potassium from red blood cells which have been injured
by heat.
	   Treatment of heat-stroke patients is rapidly cooling the body in
ice-water-baths till the rectal temperature falls below 103 F.
Temperature should be monitored (rectally) every 10 minutes and
active cooling be stopped when the temperature is between 102 F and
101 F. Patients should be kept in bed for a few days until the
temperature control becomes stable. Though there are two other
clinical condition resulting from exposure to high temperature -
heat exhaustion (heat collapse or heat prostration) and heat cramp,
the most serious consequence of exposure to high temperature is
heat-stroke. The fatality rate is about 40 per cent if the
temperature rises around 110F and 80 per cent or more if the
temperature rises above 110F.
	   Now let's try to know how to beat the heat or prevent the
effects of high temperature. The harmful effect of exposure to high
temperatures may be avoided by certain preventive measures. The
most important measure is to replace the water and salt which have
been lost from the body through sweat. The best method is to drink
abundant quantities of water containing about 0.1 per cent sodium
chloride. People working or living in high temperatures losing 5 to
8 litres of fluid per day require about 15 gms of salt per day.
Normal intake of salt with food is about 10 gms per day. So an
additional 5 gms per day is recommended during unusual hot days
along with at least 5 litres of water.
	   Another method of reducing the incidence of heat during unusual
hot spell is to reduce the amount of physical work and the duration
of exposure to hot environments. Strenuous exertion in a very hot
environment, inadequately ventilated space, or heavy and insulating
clothing should be avoided. Loss of fluid and electrolytes (often
imperceptible in very hot and dry air) should be replaced by intake
of oral fluids slightly salty to taste (i.e. near isotonic).
Sometimes exertion in a hot environment cannot be avoided. Every
effort should then be made to replace the lost fluid and salt and
to keep the skin temperature cool by evaporation.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BEATING-THE-HEAT sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
