<HEADER>
w1189 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BANGLADESH-A-LAGGARDsked     06-08 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BANGLADESH-A-LAGGARD sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bangladesh: A laggard, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Bangladesh: A laggard, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Dr. Saadat HusainASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   It is a popular fad in the sub-continent to compare our
performance vis-a-vis South Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong or Malaysia
and produce a dismal note by declaring that we have lagged behind
miserably though we started from a similar position in the early
sixties. Implicit in the declaration is the assumption that we
could do at least as well as these countries if we took all steps
in the right direction and in right time. I have studied the
statement carefully and have come to the conclusion that at least
in the context of Bangladesh the statement is not wholly true. It
is a self-disparaging statement which ignores our achievements and
magnifies the failures. An inter-temporal comparison of development
indicators across the countries leads me to conclude that
Bangladesh is a late-starter rather than a laggard in the field of
economic development.
	   Many problems including that of slow growth could be
characteristics endemic at the early stage of development. Many of
these problems will give in once the country crosses the threshold
of low level development and gathers momentum for a higher growth.
It is true that the per capita income of each of these East Asian
countries was low in the sixties. Per capita income of Bangladesh
(the area now comprising it) was, however, lower compared to these
countries. The difference was clearly visible in the seventies.
Indicators of development like life expectancy, calorie supply,
enrolment in the primary education, share of agriculture in GDP put
the East Asian countries on a much higher plane. Singapore, Hong
Kong, South Korea, Malaysia, Thailand, and Sri Lanka were in a
different league even in the mid-sixties. Their superiority
vis-a-vis Bangladesh was firmly established in the mid-seventies.
	   Bangladesh was a poor country, its underdevelopment clearly
captured by all relevant indicators, while the East Asian countries
were poised for a take-off at that point of time. It is true that
South Korea's position in terms of per capita income was near to
Pakistan or slightly higher than Bangladesh in the sixties. This
will, however, give a misleading impression because all other
indicators decidedly put South Korea at a much superior position.
South Korea was like an aircraft poised for taking off while
Bangladesh or Pakistan was an aircraft standing still in the
hanger. Both are apparently on the same plane, their positions are
however, not comparable. Each represents a distinct state of
movement though apparently both of them are in a sedentary state.
	   It is therefore inaccurate to say that starting from a similar
situation a few years back, Bangladesh had lagged behind the East
Asian countries inordinately. The statement is inaccurate on two
counts: (a) Except Korea, all other countries had a substantially
higher per capita income than Bangladesh, (b) In terms of all other
indicators of economic development, East Asian countries were way
ahead of countries like Bangladesh. It is natural that in the
nineties Bangladesh will be way behind the East Asian countries.
There is virtually no reason for lamenting over such a situation.
Bangladesh is not a laggard, it is a late starter. She was never in
the same league with the East Asian Countries. Countries whose
conditions were similar to Bangladesh have not in any way
outstripped her in the last two and half decades. A few countries
have gone down the league.
	   Bangladesh has maintained its position rather well. She has
improved her position in certain cases. In case of Bangladesh all
the indicators are moving in the right direction, some indicators
are not moving as fast as one would like them to do. A small but
steady growth has put Bangladesh ahead of at least a few countries
which did not do well in the last two decades. One would be tempted
to hypothesise that countries at the lower end of the per capita
income demonstrate a modest growth rate for a number of years. They
start leapfrogging only when they cross the threshold income level,
say US$ 600 per capita. Some countries find it extremely difficult
to cross the threshold. Some would stagnate or decline like
Tanzania or Kenya. Even the top achievers may attain a growth rate
around six percent. Once the threshold is crossed a propitious
environment is created, a spurt of activities is observed and
growth rate may jump to double-digit number.
	   Countries at the lower rung of the income ladder showing a
modest growth rate should not be viewed as laggards, they are
conditioned to behave in a particular way at this stage of their
development. A modest but steady growth performance will gradually
lead them to a stage of transition (threshold income), from a stage
of utter poverty and despondency to that of hope and
respectability. As a late starter our aim should be to maintain a
steady growth performance through good management of resources at
our command. We have no reason to worry or feel small. We should
instead work to maintain a growth rate that promises to lead us to
threshold income in due course of time.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
