<SLUG> PARABLE-OF-PERFECT-ALIBI sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
The Parable of the Perfect Alibi, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
The Parable of the Perfect Alibi, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The three barrio schoolboys were tardy as usual. Like in the
past, they tarried along the way instead of proceeding directly to
school.
	   A flock of birds attracted them. They spent the bette part of
the morning firing their sling shots. The birds hovered around the
newly-harvested field to nourish on the left over grains on their
pannicles. The boys had fun chasing the birds. And as each animal
flew to safety, the stone from the force of the sling shot followed
them.
	   Now they were late to school by almost an hour. It was not the
first time.
	   But somehow, they always put one over their young
city-bredteacher. They invariably had good alibis.
	   It was either the farm chores, or some last minute unavoidable
errand or some mishap. One time, they spent the morning swimming in
the river. Yet they convince their teacher of an emergency. A
little girl was drowning so they took time to save her.
	   Or the alibi of helping an old woman carry her heavy load. Their
excuses were endless.
	   They also knew the teacher was getting suspicious and fed up. So
the three boys made sure theirexplanation was fool-proof.
	   I have a good idea, said the fat one of the three boys. Let us
tell the teacher we saw this carabao in pain. Yes, the second
agreed. The carabao was wounded. No, the third remarked. It must be
more serious than a wound. Let us say was fractured. That way it is
acceptable and will justify the length of our delay Right .
Brilliant. The perfect alibi, they chorused.
	   And so in as dramatic a way they could master, the alibi was
presented. The teacher listened patiently.
	   How pitiful is the carabao, she commented. It is good the three
of you were on the spot to assist and save the poor helpless
animal. That is right, Maiam, confirmed the fat one with a shade of
cocksureness.
	   Without us, the carabao is a goner (tepok na). It is good only
one leg got broken. Otherwise, it is the slaughter house for the
hapless animal. We should be commended. Maybe even awarded
medals.Tama na ang kalokohan (enough of your lunacy), she said with
a trace of anger, Now spread out, one on each corner of the room.
Get a piece of paper and ready your pencil. Are you giving us a
special quiz? asked the fat one with apprehension.
	   The three were certainly not ready for a test.
	   No, this is not a quiz, she said with a naughty and big smile. I
just want you separately to write a short essay indicating which of
the four legs of the carabao got fructured. And be specific whether
it is a hind or front leg and whether right or left 
</TEXT>
