<SLUG> BC-Britain-Yemen Reporters </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BBC TV reporters held in Yemen say they were forcibly separated
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Three British Broadcasting Corp. television
journalists cleared of filming without state permission in Yemen
said Monday they were forcibly separated and denied access to
British diplomats for most of their first day in custody.
	   Producer Robin Barnwell, reporter Rageh Ommar and cameraman
Frank Smith arrived in London after being cleared Sunday by a
Yemeni court.
	   They filmed in an area where tribesmen have carried out numerous
kidnappings, including of a British teacher, and were arrested May
26 when they returned to the Yemeni capital, San'a. The men were
held for 50 hours and then allowed to return to their hotels.
	   ``We were denied diplomatic representation or any contact with
diplomats for 19 hours,'' Barnwell told reporters at London's
Heathrow Airport.
	   He said the three tried to stay together, but were eventually
forcibly separated for questioning.
	   ``We were constantly deprived of sleep overnight by people
turning on lights, coming in and disturbing us. The next day there
was then a full day of interrogation,'' added Barnwell.
	   The men said they didn't eat in custody because they feared the
food would make them ill.
	   ``During the first two days, there were difficult moments, but
afterwards it was just the uncertainty of when things were going to
be over,'' said Ommar.
	   (mj)
</TEXT>
