<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyU-Dallaglio Deal </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dallaglio signs for quality schedule
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Injured England Five Nations rugby captain
Lawrence Dallaglio on Monday struck a deal with his club, Wasps,
restricting his matches to give him more chance of being fit for
England duties.
	   Dallaglio, one of the dozen test players missing from the
England team which was thrashed 76-0 by Australia in Brisbane
Saturday, has challenged other injured stars to consider similar
agreements.
	   Tours by England, Ireland, Scotland and Wales to the southern
hemisphere this summer have been marred by player unavailability
due to the demands of a hectic domestic schedule during winter.
	   Dallaglio, who was singled out by the Australian hierarchy for
playing in a club match after being ruled out of the England tour,
will limit his rugby to 35 matches next season.
	   The rangy forward estimated he played 80-plus matches between
the start of the 1996/97 season and May this year, including
League, Cup, Europe, England and Lions matches.
	   The deal negotiated with Wasps Rugby Club effectively means
Dallaglio misses selected League games from a total commitment of
26 Premiership fixtures, eight internationals and up to five cup
ties.
	   ``Let's hope the other clubs and their international players can
take similar action. Wasps are continuing their support of
England,'' he said Monday.
	   ``It remains to be seen whether other clubs are prepared to take
tough decisions and give their stars a break occasionally.
	   ``I am not now in Australia and I don't ever want to be absent
recovering from wear and tear when there is a tour on.''
	   Dallaglio said he hoped tour compilers had learned a lesson and
the current tour should never have gone ahead in the background of
the current English match structure.
	   ``It is very tough on the young players in Brisbane who should
normally have the chance of being brought in slowly and judiciously
to learn international rugby surrounded by older heads,'' he said.
	   (jp/sw)	   
</TEXT>
