<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Kosovo, 6th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU bans new investments in Serbia; freezes assets abroad; URGES
</HEADLINE>
NATO to get ready for intervention &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: ADDS Cook comments; UPDATES with details of UN force in
Macedonia &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT WIELAARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LUXEMBOURG (AP) _ Worried another wave of ethnic cleansing may
ignite another Balkan war, the EU tightened sanctions against
Belgrade Monday and urged NATO to consider military action to stop
the bloodshed in Kosovo.
	   The European Union foreign ministers banned new investments in
Serbia and froze the country's assets abroad to punish it for
``widespread house-burning and indiscriminate artillery attacks on
whole villages'' in Kosovo.
	   Yet given that sanctions have had no effect on Serbian President
Slobodan Milosevic, they urged ``international security
organizations ... to consider all options,'' including military
ones that need a U.N. mandate.
	   British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, speaking of Milosevic,
told reporters:
	   ``This is his last warning. If he continues to cross the line
and to use unacceptable military measures against civilian
populations, he should not be surprised'' the international
community will reply with military means.
	   ``We cannot tolerate in any part of Europe a return to ethnic
cleansing.''
	   Actions needing a U.N. mandate would include imposing a no-fly
zone, air strikes against Serb artillery, beefing up U.N. forces in
Macedonia or _ the most extreme scenario _ sending an allied force
into Kosovo.
	   Until now, NATO has been considering only joint, small-scale
maneuvers with Albania and Macedonia and deploying up to 20,000
troops in Albania along the Kosovo border.
	   U.N. Secretary General Koffi Annan has recommended the Security
Council keep the 750 peacekeepers in Macedonia beyond the end of
its mandate on Aug. 31. The troops have been there since 1992. Next
week, Annan will propose how to strengthen the force that includes
Danish, Finish, Indonesian, Norwegian, Swedish and U.S. troops.
	   On Thursday and Friday, the NATO defense ministers meet in
Brussels to consider a military response. On Friday, the foreign
ministers of Canada, United States, Britain, Germany, France,
Japan, Italy and Russia will discuss Kosovo in London.
	   As a permanent U.N. Security Council member, Russia can veto any
military action against Serbia, a traditional ally.
	   ``It is very important we include Russia,'' German Foreign
Minister Klaus Kinkel told reporters. Cook said Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeni Primakov will be made to ``understand the gravity
of the situation.''
	   In their statement, the EU ministers said Serb security forces
have been ``engaged in a campaign of violence going far beyond what
could legitimately be described as a targeted anti-terrorist
operation.''
	   They urged Belgrade and Kosovo independence activists to seek a
negotiated solution to their conflict and spoke of ``the grave
deteriorating situation on the ground, involving the excessive use
of force by the Serb security forces.''
	   The investment ban and the asset freeze come in addition to
previously announced measures including a ban on arms exports and
restricted travel visas for Yugoslav officials.
	   Cook could give no details on the impact of the investment ban
and the assets freeze but termed them ``considerable.''
 &UR; (rw)
</TEXT>
