<SLUG> BC-Russia-Transportation </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian government to cut rail transportation fees
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The government will reduce by 25 percent the fees
it charges for transporting coal, iron ore, oil and fuel oil by
rail in an attempt to support Russia's industries, a top official
said Monday.
	   ``This is a key structural step in the government's industrial
policy,'' Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov was quoted as saying
by the Interfax news agency.
	   Railroads stand to lose 6 billion rubles (nearly dlrs 1 billion)
through the fee cuts, which will take effect June 15, Nemtsov said.
But the cuts are expected to help Russia's struggling
power-engineering, iron, steel and ore-processing industries.
	   ``The railway people volunteered to take the financial blow,''
Nemtsov said.
	   Russia's gas monopoly, Gazprom, and electricity monopoly,
Unified Energy Systems, are expected to introduce similar cuts in
gas and energy rates, Nemtsov said.
	   (ad/ls) 	   
