<HEADLINE>
Red Cross presses Chechnya to investigate aide workers' deaths
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The international Red Cross said Monday it will
keep pressuring the Chechen government to find and punish those
responsibility for the 1996 killings of six Red Cross workers.
	   No progress has been made so far in the investigation, said
Francois Warin, head of the Red Cross mission in the North
Caucasus.
	   The six Red Cross workers were gunned down while they slept in
their hospital compound on Dec. 17, 1996.
	   The Red Cross and other aid agencies withdrew their foreign
workers in response. The Red Cross will not return until the
investigation is completed, Warin said, according to Interfax news
agency.
	   Chechnya has seen a rise in kidnappings and other crimes since
the end of its 1994-96 war of independence against Russia. Chechnya
insist it is an independent state, although no country has
recognized its sovereignty, and Moscow says it remains part of
Russia.
