<HEADLINE>
Sharing with the people experience of party veterans, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Sharing with the people experience of party veterans, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SUNGAI PETANI, Sun.- Umno members should avoid speculating why
party veterans are being roped in to help the Government explain
the economic problems to the people, party vice-president Datuk
Seri Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said today.
	   He said their wealth of experience could be shared with the
people.
	   ``Veterans are very influential, enjoying the people's respect.
I feel it is timely for them to come forward to help the
Government,'' he told reporters after giving a talk at a motivation
camp organised by the Kepala Batas Umno Youth Division at Pantai
Merdeka, about 20km from here.
	   Asked if the veterans' help could be misconstrued as an attempt
at political comeback, Abdullah said: ``There is no such intention
and there should also be no speculation why the veterans are
offering help. We have to be serious in overcoming the economic
problems and everyone should concentrate on the job at hand.''
	   The fears that veterans might make a comeback were unfounded.
	   He was asked to comment on former Deputy Prime Minister Tun
Ghafar Baba's statement yesterday that Umno veterans would be
called to explain the economic problems to the people.
	   Ghafar had said they would include former Menteris Besar,
Ministers and Members of Parliament.
	   Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad is expected to
meet 200 of them next Saturday for a briefing.
	   
