<DATE_TIME> 06/08/1998 11:23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1235 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  KAMPUNG-HOUSE-THE-JENKIN     06-08 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> KAMPUNG-HOUSE-THE-JENKIN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kampung house the Jenkins built, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Kampung house the Jenkins built, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Merina HewASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THERE is something odd about the kampung house on stilts
nestling in Henry Barlow's hilly tea estate in Genting Sempah,
Bentong.
	   This is especially so when it is juxtaposed with Barlow's
multi-tiered stone one or the casino and high-tech theme park for
which this area is most renowned.
	   What makes this kampung house - or the `rumah ibu' - unique is
that it belongs to sculptress and British expatriate Waveney
Jenkins and her husband Peter, who salvaged it from a dilapidated
kampung house they had found in Perak.
	   And as if that were not enough, the Jenkins' rumah ibu (the main
section of the generally multi-sectioned traditional Malay house)
fronts what used to be the home of the tea-plantation's foremen
which they had extensively renovated.
	   ``Oh, it was ghastly when we first got it from Henry late last
year,''
	   says Jenkins of the foreman's residence which current
estate-owner, Henry Barlow, had sold to Waveney and Peter after
they had decided to move out of their home in Ampang.
	   ``For the longest time,'' says Waveney of their ex-home in Jalan
Ampang, ``205 was a peaceful enclave - it was a lovely home - but
recently, it seems to have become the hub of activity and
consequently besieged by pollution and noise.''
	   The Jenkins' move to Genting Sempah marked the moment when
Waveney finally had the time and space to realise her dream of
owning a kampung house.
	   ``It's really a shame that it has taken us 30 years to achieve
this. We didn't start working on it until last October, and it's
finally beginning to feel like home,'' Waveney declares, gesturing
at the cozy room that is the rumah ibu.
	   As the need to move away from the ``metropolis into which Kuala
Lumpur had degenerated'', the Jenkins decided to materialise, once
and for all, their dream of a kampung house.
	   They put out word that they were looking for old kampung houses
but did not have to wait long. Peter's driver told them that there
were two old houses in his kampung in Perak.
	   A trip to Perak later, and the Jenkins were proud owners of two
almost decrepit kampung houses, one of which they then remodelled
into their very own rumah ibu.
	   ``The house from which this rumah ibu was built was in very bad
shape. We only managed to salvage enough wood for the rumah ibu
section,'' explains Waveney.
	   To rebuild the kampung house, the Jenkins commissioned a
``rather chaotic but very dear'' Kelantan man who moved the house,
bit by bit, to Genting Sempah in small lorries.
	   ``If you are to undertake a proper Malay house move, you would
number every piece of wood and replace it accordingly. We didn't do
this; we basically remodelled the house as we were constrained by
the fact that we could only use salvageable wood.
	   ``As a result, it's more of a Kelantan rather than Perak house
though, ultimately, it's neither,'' says Waveney laughing with
delight.
	   She said kampung houses in Perak generally have an anjung
whereas those in Kelantan often have a rumah ibu with an adjoining
rumah bujang (section of the house where the bachelors of the
family live).
	   The Jenkins' rumah ibu which is now used as a study and a guest
room of sorts, was rebuilt according to tradition.
	   When the original house was dismantled, the Jenkins learnt that
it was built in the 1920s by the coins placed at the base of every
tiang (pillar or stilt).
	   ``It's a tradition that you place a coin of the year in which
the house is built at the base of each tiang. In the second house,
we found coins dating back to 1905.
	   ``So when we rebuilt it, we placed coins with last year's dates
on them along with the original coins,'' says Waveney.
	   Aside from this, they also had a traditional Malay house-warming
ceremony and prayers.
	   Waveney's interest in Malaysian heritage and culture is merely
the spritely offspring of her passion for art and her love for the
country.
	   After attending school and art schools in London and Paris,
Waveney married Peter and moved to Malaysia in 1962. By 1963,
Waveney was preparing dioramas and the Hang Tuah mural for Muzium
Negara, Kuala Lumpur.
	   Throughout the years, she has had seemingly countless
exhibitions of her numerous projects in art galleries; she is by no
means a new kid on the local art block.
	   Aside from this, Waveney is also a very active member of the
Badan Warisan Malaysia (the Malaysian Heritage Trust). She was a
council member of BWM from 1983-1994 and an honorary member from
1994.
	   ``Although I've always had an interest in the traditional Malay
house, I'm especially into its preservation right now as I fear
that it may all disappear with urbanisation,'' Waveney says.
	   What she finds most disturbing is that many Malaysians seem to
regard the traditional Malay house as sub-standard and symbolic of
poverty.
	   In her mind, the Malay house is under threat from two fronts:
its general association with poverty and traditional inheritance
laws that seem to encourage the neglect of these houses.
	   During the quest for their house, the Jenkins found that many
beautiful Malay houses were in tragic states of disrepair as their
ownerships were in dispute.
	   ``Many of the houses we saw were often in the name of a dead
grandfather as the surviving members of the family could not find a
way of dividing the house.
	   ``Usually, the poorest members of the family are allowed to live
in the traditional house whose ownership is in dispute. As a
result, no one wants to chip in for the repair of the place,''
Waveney says.
	   Nevertheless, she feels that there is hope yet for the
traditional Malay house.
	   ``I am finding that more and more young Malaysians are beginning
to appreciate their heritage. This may be because many of them have
been abroad and from learning another culture have come to
appreciate their own better,'' she adds.
	   For more information on the traditional Malay house or BWM, call
03- 2449273 or fax 03-2457884.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:KAMPUNG-HOUSE-THE-JENKIN sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
</BODY>
