<BODY>
<SLUG> NO-RATES-INCREASE-TO-PAY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ting: No rates increase to pay for waste management, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Ting: No rates increase to pay for waste management, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   GOPENG, Sun.- Local authorities should not raise assessment rate
during the interim takeover period by solid waste management
consortiums, Housing and Local Government Minister Datuk Dr Ting
Chew Peh said today.
	   This was because the interim would last only until the Solid
Waste Management and Cleansing Bill was approved.
	   Although they had to pay a certain amount to the consortiums to
handle waste management, ``local authorities are only paying what
they would normally spend on waste management,'' he said after
opening a MCA Langkawi project exhibition organised by the MCA
Gopeng division today.
	   The Ipoh City Council is said to be planning to increase rates
because it is unable to pay Northern Waste Industries an estimated
RM21 million for managing solid waste.
	   Some councillors had claimed the City Council planned to use the
assessments collected to pay the amount, claiming the council would
go bankrupt if it did not increase the rates.
	   Ting said the adjustment required during the interim takeover
was minor and this did not warrant an increase in assessment rates.
	   If they had trouble raising the money, it was an internal matter
to be resolved by the authorities.
	   ``The Kuala Lumpur City Hall paid Alam Flora Sdn Bhd RM100
million to manage solid waste during the interim period and it has
not increased the assessment rates.
	   ``Likewise, Johor Baru, where Southern Waste Management Sdn Bhd
is managing solid waste for the City Council and Johor Baru Central
District Council, has not increased the rates.''
	   Four consortia have been appointed to manage the country's solid
waste.
	   They are DRB-Hicom (Alam Flora Sdn Bhd), Northern Waste
Industries (NWI), Southern Waste Management Sdn Bhd and MMC
Engineering (Eastern Waste Management).
	   Alam Flora will cover Kuala Lumpur, Selangor, Pahang, Kelantan
and Terengganu; NWI for Perak, Kedah, Penang and Perlis; Southern
Waste for Johor, Negri Sembilan and Malacca; and MMC for Labuan,
Sabah and Sarawak.
	   Alam Flora took over from Kuala Lumpur City Hall in January last
year while Southern Waste Management took over in Johor Baru and
Johor Baru Central District Council this year.
	   NWI is scheduled to enter the interim period on August 1.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
