	   Former banker and accused money-launderer Angel Isidoro
Rodriguez attacked Banco de Mexico President Guillermo Ortiz,
saying Ortiz and other federal authorities knew of illegal bank
transactions, French news agency AFP reported Sunday.
	   Rodriguez, who is better known by his nickname ``El Divino,''
told journalists Mexico's bank privatization in the early 90s was
rife with corruption.
	   ``They always knew who was going to buy the banks,'' Rodriguez
said about the bank-purchase process.
	   ``El Divino'' was extradited from Spain on Monday in connection
with defrauding Mexican banks out of 400 million pesos -- valued on
today's market at about 47 million dollars.
	   Rodriguez lashed out against Ortiz and Eduardo Fernandez, former
president of the federal National Banking &AMP; Securities Commission
(CNBV).
	   Rodriguez said authorities favored some purchasers over others,
such as jailed former Confia bank head Jorge Lankenau.
	   Lankenau is accused of defrauding banks out of 180 million
dollars. Rodriguez said authorities provided ``facilities and even
resources to buy the banks.''Both bankers have complained that they
are ``scapegoats'' and that officials are trying to silence them by
putting them in prison.
	   Authorities are afraid alleged fraudulent bankers Lankenau and
Rodriguez will make more damaging accusations, alleging officials
promoted shady management of the banking rescue plan.'' Copyright
1998 THE NEWS all rights reserved as distributed by WorldSources,
Inc. 	   
