<HEADLINE>
Kamaruzzaman: Keeping KL clean is everyone's job, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Kamaruzzaman: Keeping KL clean is everyone's job, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - Datuk Bandar Tan Sri Kamaruzzaman Shariff
today reprimanded residents of the federal capital for not doing
enough to stop littering.
	   In future, more stringent action would be taken against
litterbugs.
	   Kamaruzzaman said the city's cleanliness was still not up to the
required standard. The main reason for this, he said, was the
attitude of residents who did not seem to care enough about the
well-being of their city.
	   Kamaruzzaman was speaking at a Press conference after launching
the Malay Mail Big Walk 98 at Menara Kuala Lumpur.
	   Thus far, City Hall has imposed a fine of RM300 on litterbugs.
	   Kamaruzzaman announced that from now on anyone found polluting
rivers and drains would be brought to court.
	   During the next two months, City Hall will launch a campaign
titled ``Care For Your Rivers and Drains''.
	   Specific details were not given but it is hoped that the
campaign will help instil in people's minds the need to care for
their city.
	   ``It is not just up to City Hall and Alam Flora to pick up
rubbish left by other people. While the authorities are doing their
best to clean up the city, it is also the responsibility of the
residents to play their part.''
	   On another important note, Kamaruzzaman said that it was
absolutely vital for Kuala Lumpur to project an image of
cleanliness to visitors attending the 1998 Commonwealth Games.
	   ``People must realise that Malaysia will be hosting the second
largest sporting event after the Olympic Games and it is not just
the tourists and athletes who will be watching us. All eyes around
the world will be focused on our capital city.
	   ``We have to show the world that we truly are a healthy,
clean-living nation.''
	   
</TEXT>
