	   Capital legislators say they will recommend that delegation
governments comply with new laws against street merchants setting
up shop near public markets.
	   Official news agency Notimex reported the recommendations would
be sent Monday.
	   Veronica Moreno Ramirez, president of the Commission on
Wholesale Food Markets and Food Distribution, said that the Law of
Public Markets and Government Regulation prohibits businesses in
public thoroughfares and at a distance of 200 meters from markets,
schools, hospitals and churches.
	   The local legislator said lawmakers were influenced by the fact
representatives from more than 70 percent of the city's 318 public
markets attended meetings and voted on the issue.
	   Moreno Ramirez said established merchants are demanding laws be
followed through to protect established businesses.
	   Besides, Moreno Ramirez said, market owners are asking for help
in obtaining short-term needs, such as the management of sewers and
trash collection.
	   Moreno Ramirez said she was confident local authorities would
follow through with the law.
	   At the same time, Moreno Ramirez said more resources and funds
are needed to provide for the rebuilding of markets'
infrastructure. The large La Merced market, for example, suffered
heavy fire damage recently and much of that has not been repaired.
	   
</TEXT>
