	   MALACCA, Sun. - Police have intensified their investigation into
the killing of two men whose bodies were found in a car at a
roadblock last Tuesday.
	   Although two Singaporeans have been arrested to facilitate
investigations into the murder, police have not ruled out the
probability that others might also be able to shed light into the
case.
	   The New Straits Times learnt today that among others, police are
working on the theory that more than two people might be linked to
the killings.
	   Police also believe that the person or persons involved may have
been known to the victims and hope to trace them.
	   The widows of the victims are expected to be interviewed when
they arrive from Singapore and Sabah tomorrow to identify the
bodies at the Muadzam Shah Hospital in Rompin.
	   Malacca police chief Senior Assistant Commissioner Arthur
Edmonds today urged those with information on incidents leading to
the killings to come forward.
	   He said those who had business dealings with the victims or knew
them personally, should contact the police to facilitate
investigations.
	   In Tuesday's incident, two Singaporeans were detained after
police found the bodies of Chai Cheon Keat alias Peter, 30, and an
unidentified Singaporean man in a white Toyota Corolla car at a
roadblock at the 100km Kuantan-Segamat highway.
	   One of the foreigners was driving the car while the other was a
passenger when they were nabbed near the junction of Bandar Muadzam
Shah about 3.30pm.
	   Of the two victims, one who was found in the boot of the vehicle
is believed to have had 24 stab wounds in the chest and abdomen.
	   The other, who is believed to have been strangled, was found in
the rear seat.
	   
</TEXT>
