<SLUG> BC-EU-Kosovo, 3rd Ld,0363 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU bans new investments in Serbia; freezes assets abroad
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS Cook comments; UPDATES with details of UN force in
Macedonia. PICKS UP 6th graf pvs: On Thursday and ... &QL; 
 &UR; With Yugoslavia-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT WIELAARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LUXEMBOURG (AP) _ Worried that a new wave of ethnic cleansing
may ignite another Balkan war, the EU tightened sanctions against
Belgrade on Monday and urged the NATO alliance to study military
solutions to stop the violence in separatist Kosovo province.
	   The European Union foreign ministers banned new investments in
Serbia and froze the country's assets abroad to punish it for
``widespread house-burning and indiscriminate artillery attacks on
whole villages'' in the Serb-ruled province, where ethnic Albanians
outnumber Serbs 9 to 1.
	   Yet given the limited effect sanctions have had so far on
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic, they urged ``international
security organizations ... to consider all options,'' including
those requiring specific United Nations Security Council support.
	   ``This is his last warning. If he continues to cross the line
and to use unacceptable military measures against civilian
populations, he should not be surprised,'' British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook told reporters. ``We cannot tolerate in any
part of Europe a return to ethnic cleansing.''
	   Actions needing a U.N. mandate would include the imposition of a
no-fly zone, air strikes against Serb artillery, beefing up U.N.
forces in Macedonia or _ the most extreme scenario _ sending an
allied force into Kosovo.
	   Until now, NATO has been considering only joint but small-scale
maneuvers in neighboring Albania and Macedonia and sending up to
20,000 troops in Albania along the Kosovo border.
	   U.N. Secretary General Koffi Annan has recommended that the
Security Council keep the 750 peacekeepers in Macedonia beyond the
end of its mandate on Aug. 31. The troops have been there since
1992. Next week, Annan will propose how to strengthen the force
that includes Danish, Finish, Indonesian, Norwegian, Swedish and
U.S. troops.
	   On Thursday and, 6th graf pvs.
</TEXT>
