<SLUG> CHICKEN-PRICE-EXCEEDS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chicken price exceeds RM5.10 per kg ceiling, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Chicken price exceeds RM5.10 per kg ceiling, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - All outlets surveyed today sold dressed
chicken above the ceiling price of RM5.10 per kilogramme.
	   Today's prices ranged between RM5.20 and RM5.65 per kg.
	   The price of red chillies has also soared, with the Lucky Garden
wet market topping the list at RM18 per kg.
	   In Johor Baru, there was a drop in the price of Labour Brand
pure palm olein in the supermarkets.
	   Carrefour hypermarket, which sold Labour Brand cooking oil at
RM13.29 per 5kg last week, priced it at RM12.99 today, while Tops
supermarket priced it at RM12.95 today, up from RM13.35 last week.
	   The price of eggs (Grade A) at Tops increased to RM3.25 for 10
today, while the price of chicken at Carrefour increased to RM5.19
per kg today.
	   In Ipoh, the price of ikan kembung was exceptionally high at
Jaya Jusco, retailing at RM7.90 per kg while at the other outlets,
the fish cost between RM3.50 and RM6.50 per kg.
	   Although imported beef fillet from India was lowest at Jaya
Jusco at RM7.90 per kg, imported mutton chops cost RM15.90 per kg
at the supermarket compared to RM11 per kg at Super Kinta and RM9
at the Central wet market.
	   A kilogramme of whole dressed chicken was cheapest at Super
Kinta at RM3.90 while at the other outlets, the bird was going for
between RM4.50 and RM5.60 per kg.
	   Greens, especially red chillies, were still expensive although
Super Kinta was offering chillies at RM14.70 per kg, compared to
prices at the other outlets which ranged from RM16 to RM18 per kg.
	   A kilogramme of pisang emas, which was not available at the
supermarkets, was going for RM1.50 at the Central wet market and
RM1.60 and RM1.70 respectively at the Buntong and Canning Garden
wet markets.
	   In Penang, ikan kembung was sold at RM8.50 at the Pulau Tikus
wet market compared to RM4 and RM5 respectively at the Datuk
Keramat and Chowrasta wet markets.
	   At all three wet markets, imported beef was sold at RM8 per kg,
while imported mutton cost between RM12 and RM13 per kg.
	   Both meats were unavailable at all the supermarkets surveyed.
	   
</TEXT>
