<SLUG> DATEK-PLANS-RM20M sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Datek plans RM20m investment in business, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Datek plans RM20m investment in business, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Shyla SangaranASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   JAVA software developer Datek Sdn Bhd plans to invest RM20
million over the next three months to carry out its business
development strategy. The company intends to step up its marketing
drive and further promote its technology.
	   Datek's chairman and chief executive officer Darryl Carlton said
the company has managed to establish its business presence in
Malaysia and its next objective is to reach targeted markets in
Asia, Europe and America.
	   Datek has so far invested some RM35 million to develop its
business.
	   ``It is very hard to get presence today, and we have to work
much harder than before,'' Carlton said at the worldwide launch of
its Solo 3270 solution which was held in Petaling Jaya last week.
	   The first software house to be granted the Multimedia Super
Corridor (MSC)-status, Datek is now actively recruiting local
workers for its projects.
	   Carlton said Datek has started to work on projects such as
systems for accounting, airlines and banking.
	   On Solo 3270, Carlton said the product is aimed at personal
computer (PC) users who need access to IBM mainframe systems.
	   He claimed that SOLO 3270 is the country's first IBM mainframe
terminal emulator that allows PCs access to IBM mainframe systems
anywhere in the world through its Internet browser embedded
software.
	   ``The market for Solo 3270 is huge. Altogether there are some
450,000 mainframes worldwide and they contain roughly 70 per cent
of the world's data,'' Carlton said. ``These mainframes are
configured to the IBM 3270 computer protocol, including those
produced by computer giants such as Amdahl, Hitachi, Fujitsu, NEC
and IBM.''
	   He said for the new product, Datek is targeting North Asia
because China, Japan, Korea and Taiwan will make a good market for
the market to grow. ``In fact, statistics show that these countries
are Asia's top five growth markets for information technology,'' he
said, adding that Datek is targeting to sell between 13 and 15
millions units of Solo 3270 each year.
	   The product is aimed at companies that intend to replace their
PCs with IBM terminals, telephone companies and other large
corporations.
	   Carlton said the company is also in discussions with a large
computer manufacturer for the inclusion of Solo 3270 as a standard
software.
	   Solo 3270 functions with both Netscape's Navigator and
Microsoft's Internet Explorer browsers.
	   Priced at US$29.95 (about RM115), Solo 3270 is written in 100
per cent pure Java programming language, which means that it can
run on any operating system.
	   Developed in nine months, Solo 3270 is now made available
worldwide via the Internet through an ongoing electronic commerce
arrangement set between Datek and Release Soft Inc, a leading
Internet-based e-commerce facility in the United States.
	   Customers can download Solo 3270 from the Internet through
Datek's Web site (http://www.bata via.com or http://www.
datek.com.my). Payment is transacted over the Internet through the
validation of major credit cards.
	   Datek has 43 software development staff operating in Petaling
Jaya, and another five in Australia. Its first product, Batavia,
has made a considerable impact in Malaysia, Japan, and the US via
online retail stores.
	   
</TEXT>
