<SLUG> BC-Czech-Plane Accident, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two MiGs collide in midair, no fatalities reported
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES number of injured, pilots hospitalized with spine
injuries, all military flights temporarily suspended &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) _ Two fighter planes collided in
midair Monday and one of them crashed near a densely populated
area, injuring 10 people, Defense Ministry officials said.
	   The two planes collided at 9:25 a.m. in heavy clouds over the
city of Ceske Budejovice, 130 kilometers (81 miles) south of
Prague, ministry spokesman Petr Sykora said.
	   One of the planes crashed near an apartment complex, setting
three buildings on fire, local police officials said. The plane
first hit several parked cars and then slid toward the buildings,
heavily damaging one of them.
	   Seven civilians were slightly injured in the accident, but no
fatalities were reported.
	   The three pilots ejected but were hospitalized with spine
injuries, the news agency CTK quoted air force commander Ladislav
Klima as saying.
	   One of the planes was a two-seat Russian-made MiG 21U and the
other was a MiG 21 with a single pilot.
	   The second plane crashed in an uninhabited area near the
complex, causing no serious damages, CTK said.
	   Residents were evacuated and given gas masks to prevent them
from inhaling poisonous gases from burning plastic in the
buildings.
	   At least 200 police and firefighters brought the blazes under
control within two hours, CTK reported.
	   All military flights were immediately suspended, CTK said.
	   (pvs/nr/scl)
</TEXT>
