<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Boy's Journey,0399 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Honduran boy hitchhikes to Mexico in search of brother
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ISAAC GUZMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GUADALAJARA, Mexico (AP) _ He set off on foot from his small
village in Honduras carrying few belongings, no money, in search of
an older brother who was merely distant memory.
	   It took five months of hitchhiking, hiding and working odd jobs,
but 11-year-old Ivan Lopez made it more than 1,930 kilometers
(1,200 miles) to Guadalajara, where he had heard his brother had
gone.
	   ``I always got rides. I got into trucks and people took me
along. But I never told them my story,'' said Ivan, who speaks with
the confidence of someone much older and bigger. ``People with good
hearts helped me with food and money.''
	   Ivan said he left his village of San Antonio el Coco on Jan. 9
because he was ``bored,'' because there wasn't any work, and
because he had heard about his brother Juan Carlos, who had left
for Guadalajara six years ago when Ivan was only 5.
	   He ignored warnings from his father and uncles, and slipped out
of his village. He said a policeman stopped him on the road, but
let him continue after he said he was going to a nearby town.
	   The boy made it into Mexico in nine days, he said, sneaking
under a bridge along the border.
	   ``That's how I got past the immigration agents,'' he said.
``They're the only ones who scared me.''
	   Ivan said he got odd jobs working as a porter to make a little
money, then met a family who took him to the state of Nayarit. He
lived with them for two months, he said.
	   ``I went to sixth grade there, but I told them I had to continue
with my voyage and find my brother,'' he said.
	   In Guadalajara, Ivan found a television station that broadcast
his story in the hopes of finding his brother, whom Ivan said works
at a hotel.
	   The news director at the television station is caring for Ivan
while immigration officials study his case, and is in contact with
Honduras' consul in Guadalajara.
	   Ivan's case echoes that of another Honduran boy, Elmer Javier
Licona, who as a 10-year-old who was found in Guadalajara in 1996
while trying to reach his mother in the United States. Elmer was
eventually returned to Honduras.
	   Ivan has not yet found his brother, but he said that didn't
worry him.
	   ``It doesn't matter,'' he said, ``because I've already decided I
want to stay here.'' 	   
</TEXT>
