<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Roundup, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0893 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Blatter is new head of FIFA, arrests made, pilots make free offer
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with France's arrival, South Korea practice &QL; 
 &UR; By JOSEPH WHITE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Sepp Blatter won a contentious fight for the FIFA
presidency on Monday, while two other battles _ against terrorism
and a potentially disruptive airline strike _ wore on just two days
before the start of the World Cup.
	   And somewhere in between, more teams set up training camps
throughout the countryside in anticipation of their first-round
games. Oddly enough, the latest arrivals were the French, who had
escaped all the hype to work out in Finland for a few days.
	   ``The team is bubbling with impatience,'' coach Aime Jacquet
said as his squad settled in Clairfontaine, among the woods
southwest of Paris.
	   Blatter, FIFA's general secretary and choice of outgoing
president Joao Havelange, defeated European confederation chief
Lennart Johansson 111-80 in balloting among FIFA membership.
Blatter, from Switzerland, needed two-thirds of the votes for an
outright victory, but his Swedish opponent conceded before a second
ballot could be held.
	   ``I would like to thank all of you _ those who voted for me and
those who did not vote for me, because we are in a democracy. The
great thing to do is to unite the family,'' said Blatter, who then
praised Johansson as a ``gentleman'' and a ``friend.''
	   Both candidates had promised to make FIFA more open and
democratic, a contrast to the dictatorial style associated with
Havelange. Among their differences was the proposed location for
the 2006 World Cup: Blatter has all but promised the tournament to
Africa for the first time, while Johansson favored Germany.
	   ``The result is there, consequently he is the winner and we will
have to cooperate for the good of the game,'' Johansson said. ``But
we're not dropping our program. I'm loyal to the president, but I'm
not going to obey everything he says.''
	   The election ended a bitter, globe-trotting campaign that cost
more than a million dollars.
	   ``There may have been a few fouls, but we never tackled from
behind,'' Johansson said. ``Now we need to think of what is fair.''
	   Havelange, 82, who chose not to run for another four-year term
amid questions of corruption and growing criticism of his
administration, wiped away tears after the result was announced.
His 24-year tenure as FIFA president expires at the end of the
World Cup.
	   As the ceremonies continued inside the Equinox Hall, French
authorities were combing the country in their vigilant campaign
against terrorist threats to disrupt the World Cup. Nine more
suspects were arrested Monday, and police urged the public to watch
out for bombs.
	   The suspects were considered close to aides of Hassan Hattab, a
leader of the Armed Islamic Group in Algeria, who allegedly has
ordered an attack during the tournament.
	   ``We have to be vigilant, every citizen must be vigilant without
losing their cool,'' Interior Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement
said. ``If you see something suspect, first get away, then call.''
	   Seven of the suspects were arrested in the Paris area, while two
other people were apprehended in the southern city of Carpentras
and the northern city of Roubaix, police said.
	   Meanwhile, there was a novel twist in the eight-day old strike
by Air France pilots. The SNPL, main pilots' union, made an
unexpected offer to work for free to fly foreign fans to the World
Cup games.
	   Air France said it would study the measure, but three smaller
pilot unions on Monday rejected the proposal, saying they would
advise members not to cooperate.
	   The walkout shows no sign of ending soon, and is certain to
disrupt the World Cup, which begins Wednesday when Brazil plays
Scotland and Norway faces Morocco.
	   The huge cache of political developments overshadowed the
supposed centerpiece of the tournament _ the players.
	   Belgium, in its fifth consecutive World Cup, began training at
Monthieux in the eastern part of France and wasted no time praising
its neighbor, the Netherlands. The two teams meet in the first
round Saturday.
	   ``I'm so impressed with the Dutch,'' coach Georges Leekens said.
``It's a machine that is far better than we are.''
	   Another injury to versatile defender and midfielder Thomas
Helmer provided a damper to Germany's first full day of practice in
Nice.
	   Helmer showed up lame after hurting his right thigh in Sunday's
workout. Also missing was wing back Christian Ziege, who is
battling a fever.
	   ``It's a real, real shame for Thomas,'' coach Berti Vogts said.
``He was being treated this morning and perhaps he can do some
light jogging this afternoon.''
	   South Korea worked out under a cloak of secrecy, revealing few
tactics in a two-hour session opened to the public. Coach Cha
Bum-kun, who would not let his players speak to the foreign media,
said his biggest concern was a knee injury suffered last week by
three-time World Cup veteran striker Hwang Sun-hong.
	   ``It is a very grave situation,'' Cha said. ``... He's out of
the first game against Mexico, but I hope that he might recover to
play later in the tournament.''
</TEXT>
