<SLUG> RM-10M-IT-DEVELOPMENT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sirim in RM10m IT development, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Sirim in RM10m IT development, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Sharifah KasimASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   RESEARCH and standards body Sirim Berhad is spending RM10.4
million this year in developing mission-critical information
technology (IT) applications to computerise its business and
workflow activities.
	   Its general manager IT department Abdullah Abd Hamid said these
applications are aimed at meeting the day-to-day IT requirements of
its five departments, namely Standards and Quality Services,
Engineering Services, Research and Development (R&AMP;D) Services,
Operations, and Corporate Services.
	   He said Sirim has so far developed a number of applications
which are the Quality Assurance System that handles ISO
certification for its clients, and the Project Monitoring System
which manages its internal and external projects including R&AMP;D
initiatives carried out with partners.
	   ``Under the allocated budget, we have also developed our
information kiosk system called Sirim Active X, our Sirim Active I
home page, and the Asset Management System,'' he told Computimes in
Shah Alam last week.
	   According to Abdullah, another application which is in the
development stage is the lead management system or help desk system
that keeps track of calls made to Sirim for enquiries, complaints
or comments, with regards to quality or standards.
	   Apart from that, Sirim is also working on another application -
the Testing Management System - which manages the process workflow
of product testing.
	   ``This system, to be implemented in the Standards and Quality
Services department, will be able to track down the process, from
the point Sirim receives a product for testing to the actual
testing of the product,''
	   Abdullah said.
	   According to him, Sirim completed a two-month study of the
system's requirements last month, and will immediately begin
developing the system.
	   Valued at RM600,000, the Testing Management System is expected
to be deployed within the Sirim environment by year-end.
	   Abdullah also said that Sirim, in collaboration with the Small
and Medium Industries Development Corporation (Smidec), is also
building an electronic database comprising a list of companies
categorised as small and medium-sized industries (SMIs).
	   ``Available database systems on SMIs in the country today are
either paper-based, or not comprehensive,'' he said, adding that
setting up an electronic database on SMIs is therefore important.
	   The SMIs database, which costs about RM200,000 to develop, is
targeted to go live next year.
	   ``It will be like the Yellow Pages of SMIs, but with more
detailed information such as profiles and business activities of
the companies,''
	   said Abdullah.
	   He added that the database was developed in order to assist
Sirim in evaluating applications from SMIs for capital incentives
under the Government's Industrial Technical Assistance Fund (ITAF)
programmes.
	   Sirim is responsible in assessing applications for the ITAF2
programme, which covers product development and design, and ITAF3,
for quality and productivity improvement.
	   In addition, the database is also expected to facilitate foreign
companies seeking local partners among the SMIs.
	   Abdullah said information from the database could also be shared
electronically among SMIs via a common network, thus enabling these
companies to exchange expertise and resources in their
manufacturing and business activities.
	   
</TEXT>
