<SLUG> INSTILLING-AWARENESS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Instilling awareness, love for environs, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Instilling awareness, love for environs, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Esther TanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - Education Minister Datuk Seri Mohd Najib
Tun Razak today urged teachers not to depend too much on textbooks
but to be creative when educating their pupils on environmental
protection.
	   He said the aim should be to instil a deep-rooted awareness of
and love for the environment.
	   He said this after launching the ``Wira Alam'' project and the
``Malaysia: Agenda 21 Versi Kanak-kanak'' (Malaysia: Agenda 21
Childen's Edition) and ``Alam Sekitar Anugerah Tuhan''
(Environment, a Gift from God) books at the Malaysian Islamic
Understanding Institute (Ikim).
	   The launch was jointly conducted with Science, Technology and
Environment Minister Datuk Law Hieng Ding.
	   Najib also said there should be an environment club in all
schools to create awareness among schoolchildren.
	   ``Most schools have already set up the club. The ones that have
yet to do so should do it soon,'' he said.
	   He said teachers and headmasters should encourage pupils to
participate in activities organised by the club.
	   The book ``Environment, a Gift from God'' was jointly published
by the Department of Environment and Ikim.
	   Law said its aim was to instil a love for the environment and to
create understanding about environment issues among schoolchildren.
	   The children's edition of the Agenda 21 was published by the DOE
based on the 1992 Rio de Janeiro Earth Summit.
	   Both books are being distributed to all schools, public
libraries, universities and non-governmental organisations.
	   Najib said schools could use these books as a reference when
conducting lessons on the environment.
	   The ``Wira Alam'' project was initiated by the DOE and the
Malaysian Nature Society to provide motivation and an opportunity
to pupils to contribute to environmental conservation via
activities of school environment clubs.
	   
</TEXT>
