<SLUG> AM-Sports-Soccer-Blatter Profile,0499 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dictator, showman both sides of new soccer boss
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Sports-Soccer-FIFA President &QL; 
 &UR; By LARRY SIDDONS &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ He's clowned with Robin Williams and cooed with
Sophia Loren. He's also banished long-time aides and been labeled a
despot.
	   Just like the sport he now runs, Sepp Blatter has many sides,
from whimsical to vicious.
	   Blatter was elected Monday as president of FIFA, the
international soccer federation. He won when the only other
candidate, European soccer union chief Lennart Johansson, conceded
after a first ballot in which neither man gained enough votes for
victory but cast Blatter as a surefire winner in the second round.
	   While he was in the race officially for only 2 1-2 months,
Blatter has been preparing for the FIFA presidency for more than 17
years, since he became secretary general running the federation's
day-to-day operations from a hilltop office in Zurich, Switzerland.
	   Since FIFA's executive committee meets just twice a year, it's
been up to Blatter to implement policy for the world's most popular
sport, and even he admits he has not always done that to everyone's
liking.
	   ``They've called me a dictator, a despot. They want Blatter
out,'' he said of his critics last week. ``But I do not do this for
personal ambition. I do it as someone who cares for sport.''
	   Joseph ``Sepp'' Blatter was born March 10, 1936, in the Swiss
village of Visp. He played soccer and became general secretary of
the Swiss Ice Hockey Federation after receiving business and
economics degrees from the University of Lausanne.
	   He joined FIFA as director of technical development programs in
1975 and six years later was appointed secretary general. He added
the title of chief executive office in 1990, and he said last week
that he'd run the presidency as if he were heading a corporate
business.
	   Four years ago, when it looked as if Joao Havelange might be
vulnerable in a run for a sixth term as FIFA president, Blatter
briefly toyed with opposing his boss, but he dropped the idea and
watched the Brazilian win again by acclamation. When they got back
to Zurich after the World Cup in the United States, he and
Havelange cleaned house of staff members they thought were disloyal
or otherwise dangerous, and Havelange backed Blatter this time.
	   Blatter speaks five languages and enjoys being in the spotlight.
At the World Cup draw in Rome in 1990, he shared host duties with
the stunning Loren, a difficult task for any trouper. Blatter loved
it.
	   Four years later, the draw was in Las Vegas, and Williams, the
comic actor who makes a hummingbird seem calm, was on the stage as
co-emcee.
	   ``Oh, Mr. Blatter!'' Williams cried, rolling the ``t's'' into
`'d's.'' ``I've waited all my life to meet you.''
	   Blatter laughed and enjoyed the joke.
	   Blatter is divorced and has one daughter.
</TEXT>
