<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Unemployment </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German presidents admonishes companies not to neglect job-creation
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) _ A day before the release of new
figures that should show some easing of Germany's unemployment
crisis, President Roman Herzog admonished businesses Monday not to
neglect their responsibility to create jobs as well as profits.
	   Speaking before union leaders at the annual convention of the
German Labor Federation, Herzog said some companies have taken to
downsizing and job cuts ``like an Olympic discipline'' in the
pursuit of higher earnings.
	   But, he added, ``whoever focuses only on stock market records
loses public trust easily.''
	   Concessions by workers in raises and other areas need to be
rewarded through job security, Herzog said. He also called for more
union flexibility in the creation of part-time jobs and for a
crackdown on the shadow economy, which is growing outside the reach
of tax collectors.
	   Meanwhile, statistics to be released by the Federal Labor Office
on Tuesday were expected to show unemployment in Germany dipping
below 11 percent for the first time since 1996.
	   In a preview last week, Chancellor Helmut Kohl said the number
of unemployed in May dropped to 10.9 percent, or 4.2 million, down
from 11.4 percent in April.
 &UR; (pfg)
</TEXT>
