<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Teachers-Strike </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Talks held in bid to avert South African teachers strike
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ The government and a teachers
union met on Monday to try to negotiate an agreement and avert a
strike over new regulations that the union claims will result in
layoffs of thousands of teachers.
	   Talks were proceeding in a constructive spirit and both sides
were willing to continue meeting for as long as necessary in order
to reach an agreement, said Education Minister Sibusiso Bengu.
	   The South African Democratic Teachers' Union planned to begin
protest actions, including work slowdowns and picketing, on Tuesday
if the talks fell through. SADTU has more than 170,000 members.
	   The smaller National Professional Teachers Organization and the
South African teachers Union have also served notice they plan to
organize a strike. They have not announced specific plans.
	   The unions say new regulations could result in at least 50,000
teachers losing their jobs and an increase in student-teacher
ratios. The unions want the regulations rescinded.
	   (aos)
</TEXT>
