<HEADLINE>
Witness: I received many complaints against Nanang, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Witness: I received many complaints against Nanang, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - A former officer with the Domestic Trade
and Consumer Affairs Ministry told the High Court today that she
received numerous complaints about direct selling company Nanang
International Sdn Bhd.
	   Noriyah Ahmad said the complaints were made in July 1995 through
telephone calls and letters to her office.
	   She had earlier testified that the complaints were about the
marketing plan used by the company in selling its Chinese herbal
products and also the company's licence.
	   Noriyah, now with the Energy, Telecommunications and Posts
Ministry, said she had given this information to The Malay Mail
journalist Yushaimi Yahaya when he called her at her office to find
out about Nanang International.
	   She was giving evidence in a defamation suit filed by Nanang
International against Yushaimi, New Straits Times Sdn Bhd group
editor Datuk A. Kadir Jasin, and the publisher, The New Straits
Times Press (M) Bhd.
	   Nanang International claimed that a series of articles published
in The Malay Mail and the New Straits Times between April and May
1996 had defamed it as they meant, among others, the company was
operating illegally, was marketing the product by using the
outlawed pyramid system and had used influential persons to put
pressure on enforcement officers.
	   The company is claiming damages with interest and costs.
	   The defendants pleaded justification and claimed that the
articles were not defamatory.
	   On the Ministry's rejection of Nanang International's
application to renew its licence, Noriyah said the Ministry was not
compelled to inform the company of the reasons for rejection.
	   Nanang International was represented by Harpal Singh while
Lorraine Cheah appeared for the defendants. Hearing continues.
	   
</TEXT>
