w1317 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  IMT-GT-BORDERLESS-MARKET     06-08 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> IMT-GT-BORDERLESS-MARKET sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Modest venture paving the way for IMT-GT borderless market, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Modest venture paving the way for IMT-GT borderless market, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   A. Rahman OsmanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A MODEST wholesale market offering Malaysian-made goods and
agricultural produce to shoppers to be opened in Padang Besar in
mid-June, will provide the foundation for the proposed Common
Border Wholesale Market.
	   The Common Border Wholesale Market (CBWM) is one of the
Indonesia- Malaysia-Thailand Growth Triangle's high priority
projects.
	   As Thailand will also start a similar venture on its side of the
border, the two are expected to merge eventually into the proposed
CBWM.
	   The Seventh IMT-GT Senior Officials' Meeting in Perak last
November hoped the project would be in place in three years.
	   The CBWM was recommended by the Asian Development Bank and
endorsed by the grouping in December 1995. Its formation was
confirmed last October in Perlis during the Fourth IMT-GT Meeting
of Working Group on Agriculture and Fisheries Co-operation.
	   The CBWM's main objectives are to organise existing activities,
create a proper trading place and serve as a collecting and
auctioning centre for agricultural, livestock and fisheries
products.
	   When the project eventually takes off, Indonesia can also
purchase properties developed within the CBWM and take part in its
trading activities.
	   The CBWM itself is a mere component of a Friendship City which
the IMT- GT envisages as a commercial and industrial centre on the
Malaysia-Thai border.
	   The city - a 50-hectare site straddling the common border has
been allocated for its creation - is conceptualised as a stop-over
destination to facilitate movement of goods and people. It would
have a common entry point and operation procedures.
	   Perlis Mentri Besar Datuk Seri Shahidan Kassim was visibly
pleased when announcing the launch of the wholesale market.
	   ``Big business usually starts from a small scale. It may
initially resemble those markets and bazaars often found in
Europe's frontier regions.
	   ``The basic aims are similar - to nurture more aggressive
shopping and encourage retailers to expand across the border,'' he
adds.
	   ``Since consumers on the Malaysia-Thai border have always been
sensitive to price differences, a wholesale market may increase the
incentive for them to shop around.''
	   Shahidan says the CBWM is a signal that viable projects within
the IMT- GT, and even within Asean, should not be delayed because
of the current difficulties.
	   ``This will at least fill the void created by the slowdown of
public sector investments at a time when Asean economies are facing
currency fluctuation problems,'' he says.
	   Of course, the Perlis Government is particularly keen on the
CBWM as it has high hopes for the project to help check plummeting
business at Malaysia's northernmost border checkpoint.
	   Traditionally, Padang Besar is a major exit point for Thai
products destined for export via the Penang deep-sea port.
	   However, following the opening of the North-South Expressway
linking Penang and Bukit Kayu Hitam five years ago, local traders
have been moaning about a 30 per cent fall in business activities.
	   They claim with some justification that the highway has diverted
a significant share of their business to Bukit Kayu Hitam.
	   Meanwhile, the Malay Chamber of Commerce and Industry Malaysia,
Perlis branch, chaired by Shahidan until recently, has proposed
three projects to complement the CBWM.
	   Its Smart Regional Agricultural Marketing will provide on-line
digital information services on the marketing of agricultural
produce by IMT-GT member countries to create wider opportunities
for producers and consumers.
	   The chamber says the project is based on the borderless
marketing strategy, using a web site on-line facilities which could
be made available to subscribers.
	   ``The system will be an information-rich outfit capable of
providing vital statistical data on all aspects of marketing within
the sub-region, encompassing technical specifications of products,
home shopping, order entry and on-line payment.'' Its Hort Garden
Centre project aims at providing a platform for easier exchange of
agricultural produce and inputs required by businessmen and
farmers.
	   As complete product listings of important commodities from
member countries will be made available, the project will help
simplify sourcing of agricultural inputs.
	   Through the arrangement, the chamber says any trade encumbrances
in the form of unnecessary taxation would be done away with.
	   ``The transaction of goods will be either on a bulk-order or
exchange basis, or both, based on the `nearest location supply and
delivery base' concept.
	   ``Orders could be made in advance and supplies delivered on time
using the Smart Regional Agricultural Marketing outfit,'' it
explains.
	   The chamber's Agro-Link Food Processing joint venture is
intended to take advantage of the availability of raw materials
like chicken, meat and even fruits and vegetables for the
production of value-added processed goods.
	   The project is based on the concept of sharing of resources to
produce goods expected to be demanded by the sub-region's
fast-growing population.
	   The chamber argues that production costs could be maintained to
a minimum and competitive level because the project tends to
utilise raw materials available locally.
	   ``Finished products will be sold in member countries through a
smart marketing outlet which allows placing of orders through
digital home- shopping.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
