<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Linda McCartney, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Paul McCartney wants memorial service for late wife to be
</HEADLINE>
celebration &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: AMs. New throughout; adds byline. Service starts at 1930 GMT. &QL; 
 &UR; By SUE LEEMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Paul McCartney penned the Beatles hit ``Let it
Be'' in homage to his mother, who died of breast cancer when he was
just 14. On Monday, McCartney gathered family and friends to
remember his wife Linda, who died of the same disease in April _
and, again, he sought solace in the haunting ballad.
	   The singer's office said hundreds of mourners would sing ``Let
it Be'' at a private service in the historic church of St.
Martins-in-the-Fields Monday night in tribute to Mrs. McCartney,
photographer, vegetarian, animal rights campaigner, musician, wife
_ and mom. The other two surviving Beatles, Ringo Starr and George
Harrison, were scheduled to attend.
	   In adjoining Trafalgar Square, animal rights activists were
setting up a giant pair of angel's wings for condolence messages.
And vegetarian children were to lay flowers beside a large
photograph of Mrs. McCartney, the singer's office said.
	   McCartney, 55, said he wanted the service to celebrate the full
range of his wife's passions.
	   His office said Harrison and Starr were invited to be part of
the congregation but there were no plans for the three former
Beatles to sing together. John Lennon, the fourth Beatle, was shot
to death in New York City in 1980.
	   McCartney will be accompanied by the couple's children, Heather,
36, his wife's daughter by her first marriage, and Mary, 27,
Stella, 26, and James, 21. Attendance is by invitation only.
	   Hundreds of animal activists planned a candlelight vigil outside
the church.
	   Writer Carla Lane, a longtime family friend, said she will
represent them inside.
	   ``I will be reading a message to Linda from the people in the
square,'' she said. ``I believe there will be a brief mourning and
then a celebration of Linda's life. Paul does not want it to be a
morbid affair.''
	   She said the service will comfort the mourning star, who
willingly spent only one night apart from his wife in nearly 30
years of marriage. ``He's a very sad man. I think he needs today
and then he'll go forward,'' she told Independent Television News.
	   Singer Elton John delayed plans to fly out of Britain so he
could attend. ``Linda was always very kind to me and she was a
special person,'' he told ITN. ``Out of respect to her family I
want to be there.''
	   The animal rights group People for the Ethical Treatment of
Animals said supporters are coming from many countries, including
Germany, France and Italy. ``Linda inspired a generation with her
activism, much as her husband inspired people with his music,'' the
group said in a statement.
	   The McCartneys, married since 1969, announced in December 1995
that Mrs. McCartney was being treated for breast cancer.
	   The treatment at first appeared to be working well, but in March
the cancer was found to have spread to her liver. Mrs. McCartney
died at the family's ranch in Arizona on April 19.
	   She was cremated soon afterward and her ashes were scattered on
the family farm in Sussex county south of London.
	   McCartney, who was knighted last year, has hardly been seen in
public since his wife's death, but was recently photographed
lighting a candle in Paris' Notre Dame Cathedral after visiting
Stella, the chief fashion designer for the French house Chloe.
	   (scl/eml)
</TEXT>
