WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALACCA, Fri. - MCA president Datuk Seri Dr Ling Liong Sik said
he would not say ``a single bad word'' against businessman Datuk
Soh Chee Wen who had yesterday resigned from all his party posts.
	   ``This is what I hope to promote in the party ... cooperation
and the interest of the party must be placed above one's personal
interest.
	   ``My attitude towards party members is that I will not say one
single bad word against them,'' he said.
	   Dr Ling, who is also Transport Minister, was asked to comment on
Soh's resignation.
	   A statement faxed by Soh's special assistant Lee Chai Huat said
Soh had resigned as deputy chairman of MCA Selangor, chairman of
the Selangor Councillor Selection Committee and MCA divisional
chairman for Petaling Jaya Selatan.
	   Soh had confirmed he had been asked to submit his resignation by
Dr Ling.
	   It was learnt that Soh was not re-appointed after the end of his
one- year term as an appointed member of the presidential council.
	   He was appointed a central committee member after the party's
last triennial election held in 1996. He has also resigned from the
post.
	   Soh is president and chief executive officer of Promet Bhd,
executive chairman of Uniphoenix Corporation Bhd, executive
director and chief executive officer of Plantation and Development
Bhd and managing director of Kelanamas Bhd and Inno-Pacific
Holdings Ltd.
	   Asked if the party would convene a central committee meeting to
discuss the matter, Dr Ling said it was up to the president to
decide who will replace Soh. ``I have the power to do so and I can
do so at any time.
	   ``If there are interested persons who can present us with good
ideas, we can appoint them right up for the post in the central
committee,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
