MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - Police today arrested a man in connection
with a RM50,000 heist at a goldsmith shop in Jalan Kelang Lama,
where its proprietress was shot and injured by one of three robbers
last month.
	   A police party from the City Criminal Investigation Department
nabbed the man at a house in Bandar Sri Damansara about 10.30am.
	   He then led the party, led by Assistant Superintendent Thomas
Navamoney, to a workshop in Sri Segambut where a .45 Colt pistol
and a .38 Colt revolver were seized.
	   This brings to two, the number of people detained in connection
with the robbery at the Kedai Emas Lei Kim which occurred about
3.30pm on May 21.
	   The other man was detained when he sought treatment for a
gunshot wound in the shoulder at the Kuala Lumpur Hospital, a day
after the robbery.
	   City Criminal Investigation Department chief Senior Assistant
Commissioner II Mat Drus Sudin confirmed the arrest of the second
man and the seizure of the guns.
	   It is learnt the police have established the identity of the
suspected robber who is still at large.
	   In the robbery, the 36-year-old goldsmith shop proprietress was
shot and injured in the abdomen by one of the three robbers who
opened fire.
	   On seeing the commotion, a security guard at the shop returned
fire at the three men while they were trying to escape with three
trays of jewellery worth about RM50,000, hitting one of them.
	   However, the robbers escaped in a car which was found abandoned,
about a kilometre away from the shop.
	   
</TEXT>
