w1329 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 3rdLd-Writethru   06-08 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede PRISTINA
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Grim scenes visible to Kosovo visitors; shelling continues &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: AMs. UPDATES with Balkan foreign ministers' criticism, woman
quoted as surviving artillery siege in cellar, other new material;
incorporates Yugoslavia-Kosovo Scene, changes byline, dateline &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By ALEKSANDAR VASOVIC &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DECANI, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Scenes of devastation reminiscent of
Bosnia confronted diplomats escorted into battle-torn western
Kosovo _ target of a Serb offensive that prompted foreign powers
Monday to impose new sanctions on Serbia.
	   Besides burned-out houses and deserted villages, whose forced
evacuation have provoked comparisons to ethnic cleansing, visitors
to the besieged zone saw evidence of fierce fighting between the
Serbs and ethnic Albanian guerrillas.
	   Along with continued clashes and shelling Monday, the first-hand
look at the devastation provides stark evidence of a fast-worsening
scenario that Western powers fear could turn into another, broader
Balkan war.
	   ``What we've seen is all sorrow, all grief... all those villages
burned and destroyed, all the people had left,'' said Dutch
ambassador Jan Sizoo.
	   Sizoo was in the first group of foreign diplomats to visit the
Decani region of western Kosovo, on Sunday, since Serb police and
army forces began a punishing offensive there in late May.
Journalists were turned back from another convoy that went into the
region Monday.
	   The destruction in the southern Serb province has increased
foreign pressure on Serbia to stop using its police and army
against militants battling for independence for Kosovo's 9-to-1
ethnic Albanian majority. Tens of thousands of villagers have fled
during the latest offensive.
	   The European Union tightened sanctions against Belgrade on
Monday _ banning new investments in Serbia and freezing its assets
abroad _ and urged NATO to consider military intervention.
	   Washington also has vowed to take strong action in the face of
the crackdowns by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
	   A prominent Kosovo Albanian, Nekibe Kelmendi, welcomed the EU
sanctions but said they were only a ``small step'' compared to the
situation on the ground.
	   Serb forces continued shelling the area around the Albanian
border Monday, according to the Kosovo Information Center, close to
the ethnic Albanian leadership. Its Serb counterpart, meanwhile _
the pro-Serb Media Center _ said ethnic Albanian militants attacked
two Serb villages in the Drenica region.
	   State-employed Serb journalists and this independent reporter
saw evidence Sunday of the fierce clashes and what the EU assailed
as ``widespread house-burning and indiscriminate artillery attacks
on whole villages.'' There also were clear signs of actions by the
pro-independence Kosovo Liberation Army, which Serbs have accused
of attacks on Serb citizens as well as police.
	   After seeing only ``part of what one could call a battlefield,''
Sizoo said: ``We've been told (by Serb authorities) that the blame
is on the terrorists who started first. But, this statement is very
difficult to defend _ for a conflict you always need two parties.''
	   Streoce, the first village the convoy saw in northwestern
Kosovo, bore the marks of heavy fighting. More than 20 houses were
burned or shelled out, and only a few armed policemen were present.
	   On the outskirts of Decani, a town of 35,000, freshly
painted-over shop windows could not conceal graffiti praising the
Kosovo Liberation Army. A few Serb townspeople lingered about the
police station.
	   ``How long will they keep burning us out? Somebody has to take
the blame for all this _ either we, they (Albanians) or the
state,'' said a 70-year-old Serb who gave only his first name,
Sreten.
	   At the police station, the diplomats were shown an array of
weapons police said were confiscated from militants.
	   On the road to Djakovica, the scene recalled some of the worst
damages in Bosnia and Croatia. Many houses were gutted by flames.
Cartridges of different caliber littered the area.
	   In Prilep, seven kilometers (four miles) south of Decani, stray
cattle roamed the empty village. Houses were peppered with bullet
holes. Some had gashing holes made by grenades.
	   Ethnic Albanian leaders say more than 50 people have been killed
in the offensive and some 200 men were missing and presumed
captured.
	   In Kosovo's capital Pristina, a daily march by Kosovo Albanians
for peace passed off without incident Monday. On Sunday, more than
100 Serbian police broke up the demonstration, injuring at least
six Albanians.
	   A woman who survived heavy fighting last week in Decani was
quoted by the ethnic Albanian daily Bujku as saying Serb shelling
was so heavy that several families hid in her cellar for a week.
Gasoline was uset to set fire to their crops, Donji Carabreg said.
	   Also Monday, Balkan foreign ministers meeting in Turkey
criticized Yugoslavia for human rights abuses in Kosovo but failed
to agree on a joint declaration on the deepening crisis.
	   (pvs/dc)
</TEXT>
