<BODY>
<SLUG> BUMIPUTERA-FUND sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RM500m more for Bumiputera fund, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
RM500m more for Bumiputera fund, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Freddie NgASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PENANG, Fri. - Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim
today announced a further allocation of RM500 million for the
Bumiputera Entrepreneurs Fund.
	   The Government had approved the sum to help small and
medium-sized Bumiputera companies recover their businesses.
	   ``Bank Negara will be directed to manage the implementation of
this fund as soon as possible,'' said Anwar, who is also Finance
Minister.
	   He said this after chairing the State Bumiputera Steering
Committee and State Umno liaison committee meetings today. He
criticised some local banks for withholding much needed credit for
businesses.
	   ``On the whole, banks have responded positively to the
Government's call to help businesses to carry on.
	   ``However, from the latest information received from Bank
Negara, it is clear that a few local banks have adopted an
irresponsible attitude in giving out very little credit - less than
five per cent to help businesses.
	   ``These banks instead chose to focus their lending solely for
inter-bank loans,'' he said, adding that this was against
Government policy.
	   ``While we don't say to whom loans should be given, the banks
should know that loans are needed by businesses and should lend out
to the credit lending limit we have set,'' he said.
	   ``I know of some local banks which are given the flexibility to
exceed the 15 per cent credit lending ceiling fixed by the
Government, with some even reaching 20 per cent.
	   ``However, on the whole, the credit lending ceiling should be at
15 per cent.''
	   He said the Government would continue to monitor the credit
demand through various funds like the national housing fund which
has been given RM2 billion, the Small and Medium Enterprises Fund
which has been granted RM1 billion and would give export credit to
help businesses.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
