<SLUG> WE-WILL-SUPPORT-SABAH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
We will support Sabah as much as possible, says Dr M, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
We will support Sabah as much as possible, says Dr M, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KOTA KINABALU, Fri. - Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir
Mohamad said there should be maximum communication between the
Federal and Sabah Governments for a close working relationship.
	   Speaking during a brief stopover at the Kota Kinabalu
International Airport en route to Kuala Lumpur from Tokyo, he said
newly-appointed Chief Minister Tan Sri Bernard Dompok understood
the need for cordial ties with the Federal Government.
	   ``I have spoken to Dompok and he agrees that there should be
maximum communication so that when we do things we do it
together,'' he said.
	   Dr Mahathir had a 20-minute meeting with Dompok at the airport's
VIP lounge.
	   On the appointment of Datuk Osu Sukam as Sabah Deputy Chief
Minister and Finance Minister, he said it was aimed at further
strengthening the State Government in view of the forthcoming State
election.
	   He said Osu and Dompok could act as bridge between the State and
Federal Governments as both had served in the Federal Cabinet.
	   Dr Mahathir said Osu understood the importance of working
together in the Sabah Government and Barisan Nasional.
	   ``As we know, some day we will have an election and we cannot go
on thinking about minor things,'' he said.The Federal Government
would like to support the Sabah Government as much as possible.
	   The Prime Minister said there were many problems in Sabah, such
as water and electricity supply and other basic infrastructure.
	   He said the State's finances must be managed efficiently in view
of the economic problems.
	   ``We have to manage the finances of Sabah very well because
these are hard times and we cannot chop down trees the way we used
to before; so we have to be very careful.''
	   He said considering the coming State election, Sabah needed the
strongest possible combination in the State Cabinet.
	   ``We need the strongest possible combination and although Osu is
a Federal Minister, we think he has a big responsibility here.''
	   On Osu's replacement in the Federal Cabinet, Dr Mahathir said he
had yet to make a decision but it would be an Umno leader from
Sabah.
	   Asked about Dompok's unprecedented move to appoint his
predecessor Datuk Yong Teck Lee in the Cabinet, Dr Mahathir said
Yong had told him he would like to continue.
	   However, he said Yong did not want a post higher than an
ordinary Minister so that he could focus on other matters including
looking after his party.
	   He also said Yong's predecessor Datuk Salleh Tun Said was not
re- appointed to the Cabinet after his term expired on May 28, 1996
as he wanted a rest.
	   
</TEXT>
