<HEADLINE>
Osu to take oath of office on Monday, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Osu to take oath of office on Monday, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KOTA KINABALU, Fri. - Chief Minister Tan Sri Bernard Dompok said
today Finance Minister-designate Datuk Osu Sukam would take the
oath of office before the Yang di Pertua Negeri Tun Sakaran Dandai
at 11am on Monday.
	   Osu resigned as Federal Minister of Land and Cooperative
Development effective Monday to pave the way for his appointment.
	   It follows Datuk Abdul Ghapur Salleh's decision not be
re-appointed when the Cabinet under Dompok took the oath on May 28.
	   Dompok said Osu's appointment would further strengthen the State
Government, considering his 12 years in the Federal Government.
	   ``I have known him even before politics. With the experience we
have in Government all these years, I think there is no reason
people like us cannot work together for the good of the State and
the Government,'' he said.
	   Osu met Dompok at the Chief Minister's office this morning.
	   Meanwhile, Osu said although the State Cabinet comprised
experienced people, team work was more important.
	   The State Government must prove that despite the economic
problems, it could still meet the aspirations of the people.
	   On Ghapur's decision against re-appointment, Osu said it was his
(Ghapur) right.
	   ``What is important is he is sincere to give others a chance to
be appointed to the post,'' he told reporters before leaving for
Kuala Lumpur.
	   He added that Ghapur was still Sabah Umno deputy liaison chief.
	   
</TEXT>
