<SLUG> BC-EU-Bosnia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
While hailing progress, EU urges Bosnia to accelerate peace
</HEADLINE>
implementation &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LUXEMBOURG (AP) _ The EU said Monday Bosnia-Herzegovina remained
en route to integration with the rest of Europe, yet urged its
foreign minister to accelerate implementation of the 1995 Dayton
peace accord.
	   ``The European Union will continue to help you if you help
yourselves and accept your responsibilities ... to build a
peaceful, democratic and open nation,'' British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook told Bosnian Foreign Minister Jadranko Prlic.
	   The EU has donated more than dlrs 2.2 billion in humanitarian
and economic aid for Bosnia-Herzegovina.
	   It will remain the single biggest donor if the country remains
faithful to economic reform conditions dictated by the
International Monetary Fund, Cook said.
	   In his comments _ at a luncheon attended by Prlic and the 15 EU
foreign ministers _ Cook assessed the progress Bosnia has been
making to becoming a democratic nation since the 1995 Dayton peace
agreement and the road it must still travel.
	   He said political parties and freedom of expression must be
strengthened and ``the EU looks for substantial progress ... in
getting displaced persons and refugees safely back to their
homes,'' Cook said.
	   International and local officials have been at pains to combat a
trend of increasing ethnically motivated violence in Bosnia as they
seek to speed up refugee returns, a cornerstone of Bosnia's peace
accords.
	   Prlic told the EU more than 400,000 Bosnian refugees have
returned to their homes since 1995. That, however, contrasts with
1.8 million who must yet do that.
 &UR; (rw)	   
</TEXT>
