<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Religion </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. Reform Jews kept from praying at Jerusalem's Western Wall
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HILARY APPELMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ A delegation of Reform Jews from the United
States held an emotional prayer session near Judaism's holiest site
on Monday, but Israeli police kept the group penned behind
barricades, far back from the Western Wall itself.
	   Some of the 150 men and women wept as they recited prayers and
sang songs, standing arm-in-arm behind metal police barriers about
100 yards (meters) from the Wall. A loose ring of police surrounded
the group.
	   The delegation, made up of rabbis and leaders of the American
Reform movement, is here to celebrate Israel's 50th anniversary and
to express its opposition to a bill that would deny recognition to
religious conversions performed in Israel by non-Orthodox rabbis.
	   The bill has outraged members of the non-Orthodox Reform and
Conservative movements, which are tiny in Israel but dominant among
Jews in the United States and other western countries.
	   ``We have come to stand with the people of Israel,'' said Rabbi
Eric Yoffie, president of the Union of American Hebrew
Congregations. ``But our joy is combined with worry and concern.''
	   Yoffie said the conversion bill would divide the Jewish people,
and was a ``slap in the face'' to overseas Jewry.
	   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has moved forward with the
bill under pressure from the Orthodox political parties in his
coalition, which have threatened to bring down the government over
the issue.
	   The U.S. group will meet Friday with Netanyahu.
	   Yoffie also expressed frustration Monday that the group was kept
so far from the Wall.
	   ``Why do we need to pray in a corner, far from the Wall?'' he
asked. ``All Jews stood at Sinai. The holy places belong to all of
us.''
	   Following the prayer session, the group's members made
individual visits to the Wall, where worshippers are divided by sex
according to Orthodox custom. Yoffie said the group did not plan to
violate police orders and pray as a group at the Wall.
	   ``We're not here to provoke a fight,'' he said.
	   Earlier this month, ultra-Orthodox protesters threw garbage at a
mixed-sex group of Reform and Conservative Jews who prayed together
at the Wall, the first time that police allowed men and women to
pray together there.
	   On Monday, the American group was kept so far back that there
was almost no interaction with other worshippers, aside from the
curious glances of passersby.
	   Richard Heinrich of Buffalo Grove, Ill., said he was deeply hurt
by Israel's attitude toward Reform Jews
	   ``They don't believe that we're Jews,'' he said. ``It's going to
backfire _ blow up in their faces. They stand to lose the support
of American Jews.''
	   Heinrich said he was making his third visit to Israel, but did
not know if he would be back.
	   ``If you tell me that the way I worship _ I'm not a Jew _ it
bothers me to the core,'' he said.
	   hla
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Israel-Religion; CT:i; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
