<HEADLINE>
Rain interrupts women's Wimbledon warm-up
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) _ Heavy rain washed out all matches
Monday on the opening day of a women's Wimbledon warmup tournament
where Steffi Graf is making her latest comeback.
	   The DFS Classic features the seven-time Wimbledon singles
champion, who accepted a wild card entry and was installed as the
No. 1 seed.
	   Graf, who has played in only two tournaments since surgery on an
injured knee last year, is looking for much needed match practice
before Wimbledon, which starts June 22.
	   The German star was given a bye into the second round here and
is not scheduled to play until Wednesday.
	   ``I'm happy to be here in Birmingham and I look forward to
competing again,'' Graf said after arriving Monday following a week
of practice in London. ``I'm hoping to play some matches before
Wimbledon _ I want to play as much as I can.''
	   Qualifying matches left over from the weekend were moved indoors
Monday to aviod a backlog as the tournament gets underway.
	   If the seedings hold form, Graf is expected to meet Romania's
Irlina Spirlea, the No. 2 seed, in the DFS Classic final.
	   The other top seeds are defending champion and No. 3 Nathalie
Tauziat of France, No. 4 Dominique Van Roost of Belgium and No. 5
Lisa Raymond of the United States.
	   It's been almost exactly one year since Graf, who turns 29
Sunday, had surgery to correct a knee injury.
	   She has attempted seven times to return to the WTA tour but
problems with her hamstring, ankle and knee have kept her away from
all but two tournaments.
	   In February, Graf won a match at Hanover before losing a
quarterfinal clash with Sabine Applemans of Belgium 6-3, 7-6.
	   The next month she dropped just nine games in her first three
matches at Indian Wells but had to retire in the third set of the
semifinals against Lindsay Davenport.
	   Graf also plans to play next week at Eastbourne before starting
the challenge for her eighth Wimbledon singles title.
	   (str/jp/sw)
</TEXT>
