<HEADLINE>
DAP men call for impartial hearing, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
DAP men call for impartial hearing, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Alex ChoongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PETALING JAYA, Fri. - Three senior DAP members, who were
suspended on Wednesday, have called for an ``independent and
impartial'' committee to investigate charges levelled against them.
	   In a two-paragraph statement, national vice-chairman Liew Ah
Kim, party treasurer Fung Ket Wing and national publicity secretary
Wee Choo Keong said they were innocent of all charges levelled
against them by party secretary-general Lim Kit Siang.
	   Yesterday, during a Press conference in Malacca, Kit Siang said
the decision to remove them was taken following complaints from the
Malacca and Perak State committees.
	   Kit Siang charged they had made statements that had undermined
party morale, created confusion and caused disharmony as well as
disunity among members.
	   Meanwhile, at a Press conference at the party headquarters
today, Kit Siang said he could accept criticism at specific forums
but not falsehoods and baseless allegations.
	   Kit Siang read from a prepared text, and when asked to elaborate
by reporters, refused to answer any questions.
	   He declined to answer questions on what were the ``falsehoods
and baseless allegations'' levelled at party leaders but said the
central executive committee removed Wee because it had lost
confidence in him as the national publicity secretary.
	   He said the CEC did not decide on whether the three had breached
party discipline, as this matter had been referred to the
disciplinary committee headed by Ahmad Nor.
	   Kit Siang said he had spoken to Fung yesterday and hoped that
there would be a new beginning whereby every party leader could
come together to work for the greater good of the party and
country.
	   In another development, Kit Siang said the CEC had decided to
bring forward the party congress by four months to Aug 22-23. He
said this was decided at Wednesday night's meeting.
	   ``This is to allow the party to elect a new leadership,
especially as a general election is imminent,'' he added.
	   
</TEXT>
