w1366 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  CANNONBALL-TREE-'ODDITY'     06-08 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> CANNONBALL-TREE-'ODDITY' sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cannonball tree an `oddity' with lovely flowers., NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Cannonball tree an `oddity' with lovely flowers., NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Lam Peng SamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Cannonball tree has always been considered as unusual. When
it flowers, it is something to marvel at: long stems bearing large
pinkish/white/yellow flowers which exude a fragrance.
	   The unusual trait of this tree species is that the
inflorescences are borne on the tree trunk where large
cannonball-like fruits later form.
	   There are not many of these in Kuala Lumpur. It was introduced
from South America almost 100 years ago together with the
well-known Brazil nut tree.
	   Many of the latter can still be found in the Lake Gardens in
Kuala Lumpur. However, sad to say, the cannonball trees planted in
the Lake Gardens have since been destroyed.
	   Known as Couroupita guianensis, the beautiful and remarkable
Cannonball tree is native to the northern part of South America. It
was first introduced in the Singapore Botanical Garden and later to
the Lake Gardens in Kuala Lumpur and other gardens in Malaysia.
	   It was a pleasant surprise to see a few of these planted (and in
flower) in one of the town parks in Kuching last year.
	   Couroupita is a small genus of trees in the Lecythidaceae
family, commonly called the Brazil nut family.
	   Other plants like the Barringtonia (native to Malaysia),
Bertholletia (Brazil nut), Couroupita guianensis and lovely garden
ornamental tree- shrub Gustavia all belong to this family.
	   There trees are commonly planted in must tropical climates where
they are grown successfully in botanical gardens and parks.
	   Couroupita guianensis is native to the jungles of northern South
America, along the Amazon river and towards Venezuela.
	   Flowering stems arise from the main trunk of the tree. The tree
gets its name from the round woody fruits that are as big as a
child's head. The fruits are brown in colour and dangle all over
the ``tree trunk''.
	   Many have described the tree as an oddity and it is considered
one of the strange wonders of the world.
	   The tree has a tall and rather narrow crown. It does not spread
out much.
	   The unusual trait of this tree is that the whole trunk can be
thickly set with the long woody inflorescences from the base
upwards.
	   The flowers are about 10-12cm across. They are fragrant and
stalked on rather long inflorescences 30-60cm long which are
usually not branched.
	   Each flower has six sepals and six petals. They are broad,
yellow on the outside, bright pink inside, and are beautifully
veined in apricot yellow.
	   The flowering stems arise directly from the tree trunk and never
from the branches or amongst the leaves like other flowering trees.
	   When flowering time comes, small special ``little'' branches or
protrusions sprout from the trunk for the blossoms to develop on.
	   These ``little'' branches get longer and longer from year to
year as more and more flowers are added to the inflorescence.
	   There are usually hundreds of blooms extending frequently from
the bottom level of the trunk upwards.
	   If the tree grows well, you can expect to see a sort of
beautifully decorated column, the reddish pink colouring of the
flowers contrasting with the greyish bark and the brilliant green
of the tree's foliage. It is indeed a lovely colour combination.
	   The flowers exude a sweet scent even at night.
	   The most unusual part of this tree is that after the flowers
come the ``cannonballs''. These are the seed pods or fruits.
	   These are round balls ranging from 10-18cm in diameter. They are
reddish brown to dark brown and these are suspended ``loosely''
from the trunk.
	   These ``cannonballs'' have a hard shell and when too many dangle
on the long stems they do look funny. The fruits take a long time
to mature - sometimes up to nine months or a year. These fruits
have a rather disagreeable odour.
	   In fact, the smell can be quite bad. Lots of seeds are embedded
in this cheese-like pulp.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:CANNONBALL-TREE-'ODDITY' sked; CT:w; 
