<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto Racing-Acropolis Rally </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
French driver takes lead in Acropolis Rally
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ French driver Didier Auriol outpaced
Britain's Richard Burns to take a commanding lead in the second day
of the 45th Acropolis Auto Rally Monday.
	   Auriol, with Denis Giraudet as co-driver in a Toyota Corolla
WRC, took advantage of a problem Burns had in the special stages to
move from third to first place in total time of 2 hours, 52
minutes, 52 seconds.
	   Burns, in a Mitsubishi Carisma, dropped to fifth place after a
tree branch broke his windshield during the first of the five
scheduled special stages of a total of 128 kilometers (80 miles).
	   The British driver was only 11 seconds ahead of Auriol in the
opening day Sunday.
	   Another British team, Colin McRae with co-driver Nicky Grist in
a Subaru Impreza WRC, won two special stages to retain second place
in a time of 2:52.57.
	   Of the 103 cars which were flagged off at the foot of the Athens
Acropolis hill, 70 are still in the gruelling rally, considered to
be one of the toughest in the world.
	   Unlike previous races, this year's rally will end in the western
town of Delphi. The ancient Greeks considered Delphi to be the
center of the world. It was also the site of the oracle that
ancient Greeks consulted for prophesies of the future.
	   Two-time Acropolis Rally winner Juha Kankkunen of Finland in a
Ford Escort WRC improved his position by moving from fifth to third
place on the provisional standings.
	   The drivers will cover a total of 1,036 kilometers (647 miles)
through Greece's best and worst roads in the three-day rally.
	   The rally counts towards the world driving championship.
Mitsubishi, Subaru and Toyota of Japan, and Ford of Britain are
competing for the manufacturer's trophy.
 &UR; kc 	   
</TEXT>
