<SLUG> BC-Israel-Hamas </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israel debates whether to allow return of Hamas leader
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DAFNA LINZER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) _ Where does the leader of the militant
Palestinian group Hamas present a greater risk to Israel _ at home
or abroad?
	   While Sheik Ahmed Yassin roamed world capitals raising funds,
Israeli leaders and talk show hosts debated Monday whether he
should be allowed to return to his home in the Gaza Strip.
	   Yassin, who was serving a life sentence in an Israeli jail for
ordering the deaths of Palestinians who collaborated with Israel,
was released in October as part of a swap to free Israeli agents in
Jordan.
	   Pressure is mounting on Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who
made the decision to release Yassin, to block Yassin's planned
return to the Palestinian-run Gaza Strip. Israel still controls
Gaza's borders.
	   Netanyahu's inner security Cabinet met Monday to discuss Yassin,
Israeli media reported.
	   ``The issue of Sheik Yassin is a very important one to the state
of Israel,'' Netanyahu told reporters.
	   Carmi Gillon, former head of Israel's Shin Bet security agency,
said the 61-year-old quadriplegic Yassin was a threat to both
Israel and the Palestinians, and should not be allowed to return to
his followers in Gaza.
	   ``The threat of Yassin is in his presence in Gaza. It is a
threat to Israel, a threat to peace and a threat to our only
possible Palestinian partner,'' Gillon said on Israel Television,
referring to Yasser Arafat's Palestinian Authority.
	   On Monday, Netanyahu defended his decision to release the sheik
as necessary to improving shaky relations with Jordan last fall. He
said the decision was based in part on assessments by security
officials who feared Hamas retribution if the ailing sheik died in
an Israeli jail.
	   But Yassin's health has not prevented him from traveling through
the Muslim and Arab world and raising funds for Hamas, which
opposes peace with Israel. The Hamas military wing has killed more
than 100 Israelis in scores of attacks in recent years. Israeli
reports suggest Yassin has raised over dlrs 70 million in the past
four months of travels.
	   Yassin's fiery comments on his tour, such as ``Suicide attacks
are only seen as such by other countries. For us they are holy
missions, and whoever dies, dies for his country,'' have been
widely reported in Israel.
	   In Gaza, Hamas spokesman Mahmoud Zahar said that Yassin, who is
currently in Sudan, was planning to return home later this month,
but gave no specific date.
	   ``We will drum up international and Arabic support and organize
protest demonstrations in the streets,'' Zahar told The Associated
Press. Zahar said Hamas has sent letters to Arab leaders urging
them to stop Israel from making ``a reckless decision that can lead
the region to problems.''
	   Israeli President Ezer Weizman said Monday he would support
Yassin's return, because ``It's better for him to sit in Gaza close
to us.''
	   Arafat adviser Ahmed Tibi said the Palestinian Authority, which
issued Yassin a diplomatic passport, would insist that Yassin be
allowed to travel freely.
	   Israeli lawmaker Haggai Merom suggested Yassin be allowed to
return to Gaza, but not to leave again.
	   ``We should have been left him in jail because he was quiet
then,'' he said on Israel Television. ``Now he is running abroad,
raising millions of dollars for Hamas and appearing as a legitimate
alternative to Yasser Arafat. In my opinion, the best thing is to
accept him back and not allow him out of there again.''
 &UR; dl-hla
</TEXT>
