<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Georgia-Provinces, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Georgia negotiates with separatist provinces
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with three U.N. observers injured
when their car hit mine; TRIMS pvs. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TBILISI, Georgia (AP) _ An armored car carrying United Nations
observers hit an anti-tank mine in Georgia's breakaway region of
Abkhazia on Monday, and three people were injured, news agencies
reported.
	   The car carrying five military observers ran over the mine while
patrolling the Ghali district of Abkhazia, where more than 300
people died in recent clashes between separatists and Georgian
government troops.
	   Two Russians, interpreter Madonna Gurtskaya and military
observer Col. Sergei Isayev, have been hospitalized, the ITAR-Tass
news agency said. An Albanian observer was also injured, the
Interfax news agency said.
	   Two more mines were later found and defused on the same road,
Interfax said.
	   Meanwhile, Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze said Monday
that a meeting with the leader of another breakaway province, South
Ossetia, may be postponed because he is too busy monitoring talks
with Abkhazia. That meeting was set for Tuesday.
	   Georgian and Abkhazian officials have been meeting in Moscow to
arrange talks between Shevardnadze and Abkhazian leader Vladislav
Ardzinba, but little progress has been made.
	   Shevardnadze accused Abkhazia on Monday of failing to meet
Georgia's key condition _ permitting the return of 38,000 ethnic
Georgian refugees who fled the recent clashes in Abkhazia.
	   However, Abkhazian Prosecutor General Anri Dzhergenia recently
said his government has put no restraints on the return of civilian
refugees, and only opposes the return of Georgian militants who
took part in the clashes.
	   But the biggest impediment to a peace settlement is the lack of
agreement on Abkhazia's political status: Georgia is only willing
to allow the province broad autonomy, while Abkhazia refuses to
accept anything less than full independence.
	   Some 38,000 ethnic Georgians left Abkhazia during the fighting
May 19-25. They included 30,000 people who had only recently
returned to their homes after fleeing Abkhazia's 1992-93
independence war.
	   Abkhazia, a Black Sea province in northwest Georgia, declared
independence in 1992. Separatists drove out Georgian troops and
300,000 ethnic Georgian civilians in a 13-month war, and fighting
erupts frequently in the region.
	   The other secessionist region, South Ossetia, broke away from
Georgia in 1990, when it was still part of the Soviet Union. The
region's mostly ethnic Ossetian populace has been calling for unity
with ethnic brethren in Russia's North Ossetia.
	   The fighting ended after Russian peacekeepers were deployed in
1992, but talks on political settlement have stalled.
	   (str/ad/ren/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Georgia-Provinces, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
