<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigera-Abacha-Profile,0904 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gen. Sani Abacha: brutal even by Nigerian standards
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Nigeria-Abacha &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Even in a country long battered by
hard-line military regimes, Gen. Sani Abacha stood out as icy and
unforgiving, willing to flout world opinion in his quest for
absolute power.
	   Critics, be they Nobel laureates, former heads of state, or
environmental activists, faced certain arrest and sometimes
execution if they persisted in challenging Abacha and the military
government that emerged from his November 1993 coup.
	   Increasingly paranoid as opposition to his rule increased,
Abacha spent his final years a pariah to the world, blocked by
diplomatic sanctions from getting a visa to seek medical treatment
in the West.
	   And he was a recluse in his oil-rich but impoverished country.
He rarely traveled, fearing a coup in his absence, and when he
visited neighboring countries it was usually for less than 24
hours. He never gave news media interviews and appeared in public
with his eyes hidden behind dark glasses.
	   Abacha died of a heart attack, friends of his family said
Monday.
	   Born Sept. 20, 1943 in the northern state of Kano, he was a
career soldier, enrolling in the army as an infantryman at the age
of 18 and attending military training colleges in the United
Kingdom and United States as well as at home.
	   He became a familiar figure to Nigerians watching a succession
of military governments come and go: When generals ousted Nigeria's
last civilian government in 1983, it was Abacha who announced it on
national television.
	   Two years later, Abacha went on state-run TV to announce that
dictator Gen. Mohammed Buhari was being replaced by Gen. Ibrahim
Babangida.
	   Babangida would soon appoint Abacha his defense minister, and in
1993 he used his power in that position to force Babangida's
resignation amid the civil turmoil that followed the army's
cancellation of civilian elections.
	   Babangida named a civilian government to rule in his place, but
three months later Abacha was on television again, this time
announcing that he had seized power himself.
	   Abacha's bloodless coup at first brought hope for relief from
the civil strife that developed after Babangida refused to accept
the outcome of 1993 elections that were to have returned Nigeria to
civilian rule.
	   Although Abacha banned most democratic institutions, he did
promise a return to civilian government and met with the
businessman who won the aborted 1993 vote, Moshood Abiola.
	   But Abacha's promises of democratic reform proved as hollow as
those of his predecessors. Elections that were to have given
Nigerians a civilian government in 1996 never materialized, and
Abacha announced that he was stretching his rule until the end of
1998.
	   When Abiola, frustrated by his stolen victory, marked the 1993
election's first anniversary by declaring himself president, he was
jailed on treason charges.
	   Others soon followed, among them former military ruler Gen.
Olusegun Obasanjo and 50 others accused of plotting a coup and
sentenced after a secret trial to terms ranging from 15 years to
life.
	   Not even Wole Soyinka, winner of the 1986 Nobel prize for
literature and a frequent government critic, was immune.
	   Tipped off that his arrest was imminent, Soyinka slipped out of
Nigeria in 1994, saying the country was ``retreating into the Dark
Ages.'' That didn't stop Abacha from charging him in absentia with
treason, a crime punishable by death.
	   But no act drew such public condemnation as the 1995 hanging of
environmentalist and playwright Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other
political activists convicted in a closed military tribunal of
conspiring in the slaying of political opponents.
	   Critics said the charges were false, Abacha's revenge for
Saro-Wiwa's challenges to the military government and his criticism
of the environmental damage wrought by the oil industry.
	   The brazen brutality of the act stunned the world, coming even
as the Commonwealth and South African President Nelson Mandela
appealed for mercy. In response, the 53-member Commonwealth took
the unprecedented step of suspending Nigeria, and Mandela called
for international sanctions against Nigerian oil, which accounts
for more than 80 percent of foreign currency earnings.
	   As massive corruption and political unrest combined to send
Nigeria's economy plummeting, Abacha sought to regain some
credibility by portraying Nigeria as a regional peacemaker and
political powerhouse.
	   In 1996, he won credit for a peace agreement ending Liberia's
seven-year civil war and cleared the way for elections. The
peacekeeping army that oversaw the vote and was lauded for keeping
order throughout the country was led by Nigeria.
	   When army officers ousted the civilian president in neighboring
Sierra Leone, Abacha stepped in again, sending his troops on a
military assault in an attempt to restore the democratically
elected government.
	   Critics said it was all an attempt to sway public opinion in
advance of the elections he had promised for 1998 _ elections his
opponents said were certain to be unfairly tilted in his favor.
	   Abacha is survived by his wife, Maryam, and nine children. A
tenth child, their eldest son, Ibrahim, died in a plane crash in
January 1996.
</TEXT>
