w1385 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 2ndLd-Writethru   06-08 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0595 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede PRISTINA
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Grim scenes visible to Kosovo visitors; shelling continues &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Balkan foreign ministers' criticism, other new
material. CHANGES byline, dateline. No pickup &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos BAJ103-104 &QL; 
 &UR; By ALEKSANDAR VASOVIC &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DECANI, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Diplomats saw devastation reminiscent
of the wars in Bosnia as they were escorted into battle-torn
western Kosovo province _ target of a Serb offensive that prompted
other European countries on Monday to impose new sanctions on
Serbia.
	   Besides burned-out houses and deserted villages, whose forced
evacuation have provoked comparisons to ethnic cleansing, visitors
to the besieged zone saw evidence of fierce fighting between the
Serbs and ethnic Albanian guerrillas.
	   Along with continued clashes and shelling Monday, the first-hand
look at the devastation provides stark evidence of a fast-worsening
scenario that Western powers fear could turn into another, broader
Balkan war.
	   ``What we've seen is all sorrow, all grief... all those villages
burned and destroyed, all the people had left,'' said Dutch
ambassador Jan Sizoo, who was among the first group of foreign
diplomats to visit the Decani region on Sunday since Serb police
and army forces began a punishing offensive there in late May.
	   Journalists were turned back from another convoy that went into
the region Monday.
	   The destruction in the southern Serb province has increased
foreign pressure on Serbia to stop using its police and army
against militants battling for independence for Kosovo's 9-to-1
ethnic Albanian majority.
	   Last week's fighting triggered an exodus of 20,000 Kosovo
Albanians into Albania. Another 7,000 to 10,000 refugees fled to
the neighboring Yugoslav republic of Montenegro and more than
50,000 people are believed displaced within Kosovo itself.
	   The European Union tightened sanctions against Belgrade on
Monday _ banning new investments in Serbia and freezing its assets
abroad _ and urged NATO to consider military intervention.
	   Washington also has vowed to take strong action in the face of
the crackdowns by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
	   A prominent Kosovo Albanian, Nekibe Kelmendi, welcomed the EU
sanctions but said they were only a ``small step.''
	   Serb forces continued shelling the area around the Albanian
border Monday, according to the Kosovo Information Center, close to
the ethnic Albanian leadership. Its Serb counterpart, meanwhile _
the pro-Serb Media Center _ said ethnic Albanian militants attacked
two Serb villages in the Drenica region.
	   Serbs, in turn, have accused the pro-independence Kosovo
Liberation Army of attacks on Serb citizens as well as police.
	   After seeing only ``part of what one could call a battlefield,''
Sizoo said: ``We've been told (by Serb authorities) that the blame
is on the terrorists who started first. But, this statement is very
difficult to defend. For a conflict, you always need two parties.''
	   Ethnic Albanian leaders say more than 50 people have been killed
in the offensive and some 200 men were missing and presumed
captured.
	   In Kosovo's capital Pristina, a daily march by Kosovo Albanians
for peace passed off without incident Monday. On Sunday, more than
100 Serbian police broke up the demonstration, injuring at least
six Albanians.
	   Also Monday, Balkan foreign ministers meeting in Turkey
criticized Yugoslavia for human rights abuses in Kosovo but failed
to agree on a joint declaration on the deepening crisis.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:ASIA;)
