<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Drift Nets,0439 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU struggles with imposition of gradual ban of drift nets
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANNA SATHIAH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LUXEMBOURG (AP) _ The EU governments struggled Monday with a
proposal that would gradually ban drift nets that are kilometers
(miles) long and cause the death of thousands of species such as
seals, dolphins and whales.
	   After seven hours of talks, the EU fisheries ministers were
deadlocked on when the ban should begin. France, Italy, Ireland and
Greece object to a ban in general, arguing it threatens the
livelihood of fishermen. The ban would be for all vessels, those
registered in EU as well as non-EU boats.
	   The issue has been on the table for years without EU nations
being able to reach an agreement.
	   EU Fisheries Commissioner Emma Bonino, and Britain, which now
holds the EU rotating presidency, have proposed to phase out all
drift nets as of Dec. 31, 2000 ``because of the side effects on
dolphins,'' Britain's Agriculture Minister Jack Cunningham told
reporters on arrival here.
	   France, which has some 40 vessels using drift nets based in its
Atlantic ports, says if it comes to a transitional period, it wants
at least six years.
	   Italy argues Morocco and Tunisia are worse offenders. But EU
officials say Italy is the worst in the EU and estimate that its
plan to convert 500 vessels that now drag drift nets would still
leave some 200 in operation.
	   In 1992, the United Nations imposed a general moratorium on
drift nets. The EU responded by limiting them to 1.5 miles (2.5
kilometers), but under the EU proposal all nets would be banned as
of 2000.
	   Ecological groups, including Greenpeace have denounced the use
of the nets, which they say catch animals that fishermen don't want
such as sharks, dolphins, whales, turtles and diving birds.
	   The drift nets are dragged through the water. Because they are
so long, they have been nicknamed ``walls of death.''
	   In a statement, Greenpeace said 1998 ``is the UN International
Year of the Ocean and, after dragging its feet for years, the EU
can make a real contribution to protect the oceans.''
	   The organization displayed part of a drift net outside the EU
conference building where foreign ministers met.
	   The RSPCA, the British animal protection organization, published
a report last September highlighting the devastation and suffering
caused by drift nets.
	   The report revealed that in one season alone, almost 83,000 blue
sharks were caught by French boats, 8,000 dolphins by Italian
fishermen. Additionally, as many as 800 leatherback turtles died in
drift nets. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-EU-Drift Nets; CT:i; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
