<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Chile-Zamorano,0319 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chileans breathing easier: Zamorano is back
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SERGIO CARRASCO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MARIGNAC, France (AP) _ Calm returned to Chile's World Cup
headquarters Monday with Ivan Zamorano resuming training one day
after experience an alarming pain in the meniscus of his right leg.
	   Doctors gave the 31-year-old striker of the Italian club
Internazionale a clean bill of health.
	   ``You saw me, I trained normally and full of enthusiasm. There's
no problem,'' a smiling Zamorano told reporters after the two-hour
training session at the Robert Brettes Stadium in this southern
French town.
	   Zamorano complained about what he called exaggerated reports
back home that his injury was serious and could sideline him from
the World Cup debut against Italy on Tuesday.
	   ``It is a pity that that this sort of psychological war comes
from our own Chilean journalists,'' he said.
	   Teammates were delighted to see their captain back in action.
	   ``Ivan is our leader, the man who we follow in the field and it
is a real privilege having him,'' goalkeeper Nelson Tapia said.
	   Head coach Nelson Acosta also told reporters that they should
forget about Zamorano's health.
	   ``Ivan is fine. Period,'' he said.
	   Zamorano showed no affect from the injury during Monday's
training session, repeatedly practicing long distance shots along
with offensive teammate Marcelo Salas.
	   The Chile federation reported no injury problems in the team,
although defenders Javier Margas, Ronald Fuentes, Francisco Rojas
and Cristian Castaneda along with midfielder Luis Musrri were seen
just running casually around the field instead of training with the
rest of the team.
	   ``It's just a precaution, I feel 100 percent,'' Margas said.
	   He quickly ran onto the field to join a vigorous informal
scrimmage.
</TEXT>
