<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Rail Strike Threat </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
British railroads could face chaos in track workers strike
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DIRK BEVERIDGE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Business Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Workers who repair Britain's railroad tracks
threatened Monday to strike for 11 days, stirring fears that
travelers and commuters will face numerous delays and
cancellations.
	   ``It's going to have a very serious impact,'' acknowledged
Georgina Walsh, a spokeswoman for Railtrack PLC, which operates the
nation's railroad infrastructure. ``It's going to be chaotic, from
the look of it.''
	   It was impossible for anybody to predict just how bad the
disruptions could be, however.
	   Union bosses said the workers will stop maintaining tracks for
four days beginning June 19, then for seven more days beginning
June 29.
	   Unlike a strike by people who run the trains, the effects of
this walkout would be determined by how many problems occur on the
tracks, how bad the problems are, and how quickly the engineering
companies can fix them. Some minor problems require only that
drivers slow down; others can completely shut a section of track.
	   Roughly 9,000 of the nation's 15,000 railroad maintenance
workers are represented by the Rail Maritime and Transport union,
and managers are making contingency plans to operate with as many
non-union workers as possible.
	   The union threatened to walk off the job at nine engineering
companies that work as contractors to maintain Railtrack's
infrastructure.
	   The union's general secretary, Jimmy Knapp, says the engineering
companies want too many concessions from workers in a new deal that
would raise basic pay but force drastic changes in working rules.
	   While basic rates of pay might rise by as much as 20 percent
under proposals being made by some of the engineering companies, a
typical rail worker might see actual weekly pay fall to 260 pounds
(dlrs 424) per week from 300 pounds (dlrs 490) per week because of
less overtime, union spokesman Lawrie Harries said.
	   One of the big track engineering companies, Jarvis Facilities
Ltd., accused the union of playing dirty by calling a strike before
pay talks had even broken down.
	   ``Part of the agreement was that neither side would operate
under the threat of duress,'' said Ian McKellar, a spokesman for
the company's parent, Jarvis PLC. ``Clearly, the threat of four
days followed by seven days of strike action would be duress.''
	   The privatized operators who run the trains in Britain are not
directly involved in the labor dispute and declined to predict what
would happen to services during a strike.
	   ``Our point is to sit back and wait to see what happens,'' said
Jay Merritt, a spokesman for the Association of Train Operating
Companies, a lobbying group for 27 British rail operators.
	   (db/eml)
</TEXT>
