<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Czar Funeral </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian prime minister urges church to take part in czar funeral
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's prime minister has urged the Russian
Orthodox Church to decide how it intends to participate in the
burial of the country's last tsar, a news agency reported Monday.
	   Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko sent a letter to the patriarch
urging the church to take part, noting that the event will be an
important day of national reconciliation, Interfax said, quoting an
unidentified source.
	   The church has been hesitant about next month's ceremony, saying
that some believers still have doubts about the identity of bones
recovered from a pit in the Ural Mountains city of Yekaterinburg in
1991.
	   The nine skeletons have been examined by genetics labs in
Russia, Britain and the United States and identified as those of
Czar Nicholas II, his wife, three children and four servants.
	   After six years of deliberations, a government commission
declared the remains authentic earlier this year and scheduled a
funeral for July 17, the 80th anniversary of the family's execution
by a Bolshevik firing squad. Hundreds of foreign representatives,
including many royals, have been invited to attend.
	   Russian media have said that President Boris Yeltsin will not
take part unless the head of the church, Patriarch Alexy II, does.
	   The ceremony will be held in St. Petersburg's Peter and Paul
Cathedral, the traditional burial site of the Romanovs, who ruled
Russia for 300 years and were related through intermarriage to many
other royal families in Europe.
	   The church's ruling body, the Holy Synod, is scheduled to
discuss the church's representation on Tuesday. Russian media have
suggested that the synod may allow St. Petersburg priests to
officiate, but will not permit the church's highest officials to
attend.
	   The church has started proceedings to consider sainthood for the
royal family, which would make their bones holy relics.
	   The church has previously suggested that the bones, still held
in a police morgue, be interred in a temporary tomb until all
doubts about their identity have been removed.
	   Moscow Mayor Yury Luzhkov endorsed that idea Monday, saying the
decision to proceed with a funeral was too hasty. He had earlier
proposed that they be buried in Moscow's newly rebuilt Cathedral of
Christ the Savior.
	   (mr/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
