<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Briefs, 1st Ld,0657 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Includes items on Kanu injury; Italian transfer talk; customs
</HEADLINE>
problem for Scottish fans; Lebanese World Cup fans; oldest and
youngest players &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   RESSONS, France (AP) _ Nwankwo Kanu sat out Nigeria's first
full-squad practice in France with what a team source called a
minor ankle injury.
	   At the start of a morning training session in this small village
80 kilometers (50 miles) north of Paris, Kanu walked over to coach
Bora Milutinovic and pointed at his left foot.
	   The two spoke for a few minutes while other players began light
jogging. The Inter Milan striker walked off the field, accompanied
by a trainer.
	   The source said Kanu, who led Nigeria to the gold medal at the
Atlanta Olympics, met one of the team doctors and had his ankle
iced.
	   Kanu, 21, has been beset by a series of lingering leg injuries
over the past six months, hampering his comeback from 1996 heart
valve surgery.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   SENLIS, France (AP) _ Negotiations for the transfer of Italian
World Cup stars are officially suspended for the duration of France
'98. But rumors about club maneuvers for next season are a common
subject for discussion at Italy's training camp.
	   Midfielder Roberto Di Matteo blocked suggestions that he may
return to the Italian league from Chelsea, saying the English club
announced he's not for sale.
	   ``I'm going to respect the decisions of the club,'' he said.
	   Juventus striker Filippo Inzaghi denied rumors of his possiblek of
the Scottish World Cup fans on their arrival at Charles de Gaulle
airport.
	   They told them to remove their ginger wigs and tartan caps and
wash off the face-paint before they would let the fans through
customs.
	   ``It is absolutely ridiculous,'' said 36-year-old Andy Finley,
who was wearing a tailor-made Black Watch tartan suit complete with
waistcoat and top hat.
	   ``It took me hours to paint this flag on my face and the next
thing I'm told to wash it off or they won't let me in the country
because I don't look like my picture in my passport.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Flags from Italy, Brazil and Germany dot
the streets, covering campaign posters for municipal elections.
Restaurants are scrambling to buy TVs. Street peddlers are hawking
a range of France '98 accessories.
	   Lebanon is not participating, but World Cup fever is in full
force here.
	   The tournament has always been a hit in this soccer-mad nation.
During the civil war from 1975 to 1990, militiamen were known to
stop shooting and residents would crank up electrical generators to
watch matches.
	   ``I have always been a German fan,'' said Fuad Khoueiry, a
grocer whose customers are greeted with a large picture of the
European champions.
	   Tony Zoghbi, 28, has put up the green Brazilian flag outside his
home.
	   ``I did it to spite my next-door neighbor, who's a German
fanatic,'' he said.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   PARIS (AP) _ At 39, Scottish goalkeeper Jim Leighton is 22 years
older than the youngest player at the World Cup, Cameroon's
17-year-old midfielder Samuel Eto'o.
	   Like German defender Lothar Matthaeus, who is back at age 37,
Leighton played in the 1982 World Cup in Spain. The 'keeper turns
40 July 24, 12 days after this World Cup ends.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   PARIS (AP) _ FIFA took time off from its war of succession to
honor a dozen soccer greats and promoters of the game in various
parts of the world.
	   While the battle between Lennart Johansson and Sepp Blatter over
the presidency of the world body entered its final round, the
organization, 2nd graf
