w1418 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Nigeria-Abacha 4thLd-Writethru   06-08 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Abacha, 4th Ld-Writethru,0436 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede ABUJA
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 
 &UR; Family friends: Abacha dead, soldiers seal off residence &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with journalists summoned for
second time to the State House in Abuja, CLARIFY that family
friends include members of the military junta, RAISE reference to
no official confirmation. ADDS byline. &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Nigeria-Abacha-Profile &QL; 
 &UR; By FRANK AIGBOGUN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Nigeria's military strongman Gen. Sani
Abacha has died after suffering a heart attack, close friends of
Abacha's family said Monday.
	   In keeping with Muslim practice, a funeral will be held within
the next 24 hours, said the family members who spoke to The
Associated Press on condition of anonymity.
	   The government had no official confirmation of Abacha's death,
but leaders convened an emergency meeting in the capital, Abuja.
	   It was not immediately clear who would assume power. Abacha, 54,
had wielded absolute power since 1993 and was always secretive on
the issue of succession.
	   Abacha was supposed to have been at a special function in Lagos
last week but failed to appear. He has made few public appearances
since he greeted Pope John Paul II in March.
	   Legions of soldiers sealed off Abacha's residence and office in
the capital early Monday. Only top military brass were permitted to
enter the secluded leader's compound.
	   Senior military junta officials, including members of the
family, said they had chartered an airplane to take them from the
southern hub city of Lagos to Abuja for the funeral.
	   By late afternoon, journalists had been summoned for a second
time to the State House in Abuja. In an unusual move, senior aides
had called journalists a in earlier as well, but they were quickly
turned away by soldiers.
	   Scores of reporters, including those with state-controlled
media, were camped outside the State House awaiting an explanation.
	   Although the army and police usually maintain a high profile on
the streets of Nigeria, the extraordinary move of sealing the head
of state's residence triggered a wave of rumors in Abuja.
	   Abacha seized power in Nigeria in 1993 after canceling
presidential elections and suspending the constitution.
	   Although he has pledged to hand the government over to an
elected civilian administration, in April he became the only
nominated candidate for the presidency.
	   Opposition to Abacha's rule has been mounting in recent months
with the prospect that his junta might not honor its pledge to
stand down.
</TEXT>
