<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Argentina-Veron,0248 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Veron remains a starter, despite doping rumors
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   L'ETRAT, France (AP) _ Argentine midfielder Juan Veron, the
subject of rumors concerning a failed drug test, practiced as usual
with the starting lineup Monday.
	   The fact that Veron was allowed to work out was a possible
indication that the Argentine federation considers his case closed,
especially considering that coach Daniel Passarella is a
disciplinarian who vowed to clean things up following Diego
Maradona's expulsion for failing a drug test at the 1994 World Cup.
	   Veron and the rest of the team kept silent on the issue Monday.
Practice was closed to the reporters, who managed to follow the
action from a hill 200 meters (yards) away. The team will hold on
open practice Tuesday.
	   The team was shaken Saturday by rumors, originating from a radio
station in Argentina, that Veron had failed an internal doping
test.
	   The team denied the report, although its physician Luis Seveso
admitted ``something might have showed up'' in one test.
	   Seveso suggested Veron took an anti-flu medicine containing a
banned substance and considered it a minor issue because the test
was administered more than a week before the start of the World
Cup. FIFA has not acted on the report because the test was given by
the Argentine Soccer Association.
	   Argentina plays Japan in its World Cup opener Sunday in
Toulouse.
	   (str/jw)
</TEXT>
