w1445 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  WellsFargo Norwestagreeondlrs34bill   06-08 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> Wells Fargo, Norwest agree on dlrs34 billion merger,0698 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
include bkgrd on problems Wells had with First Interstate
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: SUBS 6th-7th grafs pvs, Wells Fargo ... with four grafs to
consolidation, UPDATES stock price. Picks up 8th graf pvs, Under
the ... &QL; 
 &UR; By CATALINA ORTIZ &QC; 
 &UR; AP Business Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) _ Wells Fargo and Co. and Norwest Corp. are
merging in a stock swap that values Wells Fargo at about dlrs34
billion and would create a financial powerhouse with banks in 21
states in the West and Midwest.
	   San Francisco-based Wells Fargo and Minneapolis-based Norwest
would combine under the deal announced Monday to form a company
with about dlrs191 billion in combined assets, more than 90,000
employees, about 20 million customers and 5,777 financial services
outlets worldwide.
	   The new company would be the sixth-largest bank in the United
States if all other bank mergers announced this year are completed.
	   The proposed deal would be the seventh largest overall and the
third biggest in the banking industry after Citicorp's planned
merger with Travelers Group and Nationsbank Corp.'s proposed
combination with BankAmerica Corp.
	   The financial services industry has been a hotbed of merger
activity as banks, brokers and insurers are striking alliances that
can instantly expand their base of customers while lowering costs.
	   Wells Fargo has been in a big deal before, winning with an
dlrs11.3 billion bid for First Interstate Corp. of Los Angeles in
1996.
	   But Wells had to close hundreds of branches and eliminated 7,000
jobs after that deal. It also lost customer deposits, bounced good
checks and incorrectly withdrew money from some accounts and
deposited it in others.
	   Norwest, the nation's biggest mortgage underwriter, has been one
of the industry's top performing banks this decade.
	   In midday trading Monday on the New York Stock Exchange, Wells
Fargo shares were up dlrs1.50 at dlrs3647.75 while Norwest shares
were down dlrs2.50 at dlrs37.18 3/4.
	   Under the latest deal, Wells Fargo shareholders would get 10
shares of common stock of Norwest in exchange for each share of
Wells Fargo common stock. That would leave Wells Fargo stockholders
with about 52.5 percent of the combined company and Norwest with
approximately 47.5 percent.
	   The combined compay would retain the Wells Fargo name and would
be based in San Francisco. Minneapolis will be headquarters for the
combined Midwest banking business.
	   Paul Hazen, chairman and chief executive of Wells Fargo, would
be chairman of the combined company, while Richard M. Kovacevich,
chairman and chief executive of Norwest, would become president and
chief executive.
	   The combined company would have offices nationwide for mortgage
and consumer lending and have banks in 21 states across the
Midwest, Rocky Mountain and Western regions. It would also have
outlets in Canada, the Caribbean, Latin America and other
countries.
	   Wells Fargo and Norwest expect to save at least dlrs650 million
in costs annually by the third year in operation. Norwest spokesman
Larry Haeg said there have been no decisions made on job cuts, and
said efforts would be made to retrain any employees whose jobs may
be cut for other positions.
	   ``We believe the partnership of these two companies offers
terrific opportunities for customers, employees, and
shareholders,'' Hazen said in a statement.
	   Kovacevich said the merger would unite high performing companies
with complementary businesses, products, technology, markets and
customers.
	   ``It will be a leading franchise in the western United States
with all the resources necessary to meet all of our customers'
financial needs and serve them when, where and how they want to be
served,'' he said.
	   The deal has been approved by the boards of both companies, but
must also get approval from regulators and stockholders.
	   As part of the deal, each company was given an option to buy up
to 19.9 percent of the other company on favorable terms. Such
arrangements are commonly included in merger pacts to discourage
unwanted suitors from breaking up the deal.
</TEXT>
