w1449 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Iraq-ChristianFlight     06-08 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Christian Flight </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bishops and Vatican try to stem exodus of Iraqi Christians
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo Planned
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ In black turbans and red sashes, Christian
bishops gathered Monday to try to stem the flight of the faithful
from Iraq. But few held out hope of slowing an exodus that has cut
Christian numbers by a third since 1990.
	   ``This immigration is stripping us of our best brains and the
most well-off among us,'' the Rev. Youssef Habbi, an Iraqi
historian, told The Associated Press.
	   The rush of immigration dates to the Gulf crisis. Many Christian
clergymen blame the U.N. trade sanctions, sparked by Iraq's 1990
invasion of Kuwait, for the flight of the Christians, mostly young
people.
	   The sanctions limit Iraq's export of oil and have devastated the
economy. Habbi said the flight since 1990 has cut from 750,000 to
500,000 a once thriving Christian community whose roots go back to
the first century.
	   About 80 percent of Iraqi Christians are Chaldaean Catholics,
but the three-day meeting of the bishops is also represented by
other denominations: Syriac Orthodox, Syriac Catholics, Armenian
Catholic and Armenian Orthodox.
	   Pope John Paul II's envoy, Cardinal Roger Etchegaray, is
attending, with a message beseeching Iraqi Christians to stay.
Others attending are bishops from Palestine, Lebanon and Russia.
	   The pontiff has repeatedly criticized sanctions on Iraq. He has
expressed a wish to visit the birthplace of Abraham, the Iraqi city
of Ur, and Etchegaray also will go to Ur to discuss a possible
papal trip.
	   The meeting is the third organized since 1991, but Habbi said
the gatherings did very little to check the flow, nor did a plea
from the pope read in churches in 1994.
	   Indeed, among Christians interviewed Sunday, several said
nothing would really be done to relieve their economic problems.
	   ``The pope lives in his mansions in the Vatican and knows very
little about our situation,'' said Jubrael Marouki who has already
sold his belongings to leave the country.
	   Added Daniel Auraha: ``The church is rich but it has practically
done nothing to help us.''
	   Patriarch Rafael Bedaweed, head of the Iraqi church, admitted
his failure in checking the immigration.
	   ``They are not fleeing because of religious or ethnic
oppression. They want us to solve their economic problems and
simply we are not able to do that,'' said Bedaweed, a Chaldaean.
	   More than 30,000 Iraqi Christians are now stranded in
neighboring Jordan waiting for visas to Western countries which
they rarely get, said Habbi, also a Chaldaean Catholic.
	   ``Frustrated, they give all they have to professional smugglers
who illegally transfer them to a Western country where they ask for
asylum mostly on humanitarian grounds,'' he added.
	   Iraqis traveling abroad must pay an exit fee of 400,000 dinars
(dlrs 300) and can only carry on leaving is dlrs 50. Moreover,
people with higher degrees like university professors, doctors and
engineers are banned from leaving.
	   To skirt the exit measures, several thousand Christians sold
belongings recently and fled to Greece via Turkey through the
Kurdish rebel enclave in northern Iraq.
	   Stories abound of families perishing on the snow-capped
mountains of Kurdistan or drowning when their boats capsized on the
way to Greece.
	   Habbi said Iraqi Christians have illegally made it to Sri Lanka,
New Zealand and even Iceland, adding, ``We simply cannot keep track
of this diaspora.''
 &UR; lb-ggl/vj
</TEXT>
