<SLUG> BC-India-Landslides,0191 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Landslides, rain kill six in India's remote northeast
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GAUHATI, India (AP) _ Landslides triggered by pre-monsoon
torrential rains in India's northeast swept away a family of five
and flattened a mosque, killing a Muslim priest, officials said
Monday.
	   The deaths occurred Sunday night in Cachar, 380 kilometers (285
miles) south of Gauhati, the capital of Assam state, Superintendent
of Police J. H. Ahmed said.
	   More than 150 people were injured in the landslides in the
province, where flooded rivers also disrupted road and railroad
links.
	   Meanwhile, a severe cyclone with wind speeds up to 120 kph (70
mph), was moving in the Arabian sea and expected to hit western
Gujarat state on Tuesday.
	   In the eastern part of Assam state, a river flooded 400 villages
over the weekend. Nearly 6,000 villagers fled their homes and took
shelter in the relief camps set up by the military and the state
government, district officials said on telephone.
	   Earlier this week, another landslide flattened a cluster of
tin-roofed mud huts and killed at least 21 sleeping tea plantation
workers in Assam state. 	   
</TEXT>
