<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Havelange in Tears,0187 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Emotions choke outgoing FIFA president
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Sports-Soccer-FIFA President &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Stepping down from the helm of world football after
almost a quarter century, even the normally businesslike Joao
Havelange choked with emotion.
	   Hundreds of delegates and guests attending FIFA's pre-World Cup
Congress rose to applaud their outgoing 82-year-old leader as
colleagues presented him with a gold-plated plaque as a token of
their gratitude for transforming a sleepy, eight-person bureau into
a giant with a projected budget of dlrs 184 million in 1998.
	   After receiving the prize, Havelange approached a microphone to
express his gratitude, but turned away when he broke into tears.
	   ``We understand the emotions confusing the president,'' said
FIFA's deputy secretary general Michel Zen-Ruffinen, who quickly
took over as Havelange composed himself and wiped his eyes with a
handkerchief.
	   Sepp Blatter, FIFA's general secretary, won the election to
secede Havelange, who was named honorary president.
	   (sl/jw) 	   
</TEXT>
