	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - Dewan Rakyat Speaker Tan Sri Mohamed Zahir
Ismail heads the list of 1,951 recipients of numerous awards in
conjunction with the 76th birthday of the Yang di-Pertuan Agong
Tuanku Ja'afar tomorrow.
	   Zahir, 74, will be the only recipient to be bestowed with the
Darjah Kebesaran Seri Setia Mahkota award, which carries the title
Tun.
	   The late Corporal Md Nosruddin Yeob will be posthumously awarded
the country's highest bravery award, the Seri Pahlawan Gagah
Perkasa.
	   Md Nosruddin was killed on March 26, when detainees at the
Semenyih Immigration Detention Centre clashed with the police.
	   Twenty-one others will receive the Darjah Panglima Setia Mahkota
which carries the title Tan Sri.
	   They are Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad's chief
private secretary Datuk Abdul Aziz Ismail, Education Ministry
secretary-general Datuk Dr Johari Mat, Public Works Department
director-general Datuk Omar Ibrahim, Defence Ministry
secretary-general Datuk Azizan Husain, Sarawak State Secretary
Datuk Amar Hamid Bugo, Sabah State Secretary Datuk Khalil Datu
Jamalul, Deputy Inspector General of Police Datuk Norian Mai,
Universiti Putra Malaysia vice-chancellor Professor Datuk Dr Syed
Jalaludin Syed Salim, Guthrie Group chief executive Datuk Abdul
Khalid Ibrahim, Naza Motor Trading Group managing director Datuk
Sheikh Mohamad Nasimuddin Kamal Sheikh Mohamad Amin and DRB-Hicom
Group chairman Datuk Wira Mohd Saleh Sulong.
	   Also on the list are former Asean secretary-general Datuk Ajit
Singh, Selangor Hokkien Association president Datuk Low Keng Seng,
veteran Umno politician Datuk Abdul Aziz Tapa, Talam Corporation
Berhad executive chairman Datuk Chan Ah Chye, the King's daughter
Tunku Dara Tunku Datuk Seri Tunku Naquiah, Tassmag Group director
Datuk T. Tharumagnanam, Parti Gerakan treasurer Datuk Soong Siew
Hoong, Airod chairman Datuk Ahmad Johan, Dr Cheah Cheng Kooi and
Malaysian Timber Council chairman Tunku Datuk Osman Ahmad.
	   Thirty-five will receive the Panglima Jasa Negara award while
five will receive the Panglima Setia Diraja award.
	   Both awards carry the title Datuk.
	   The recipients of the PJN award include Prime Minister's
Department Research Division director-general Datuk Zakaria Abdul
Hamid, Kuching High Court judge Steve Shim Lip Kiong, PM's
Department senior deputy secretary- general Datuk Abdullah Kuntom,
former PM's Department Implementation Co- ordinating Unit
director-general Datuk Syed Alwi Syed Nordin, PM's Department
National Security Division director-general Datuk Ja'afar Ismail
and Chemistry Department director-general Ti Thiow Hee.
	   Others are Health Ministry deputy director-general Datuk Dr M.
	   Jegathesan, former Health deputy secretary-general P. Venugopal,
Health Ministry secretary-general Datuk Wira Mohd Zam Abdul Wahab,
former Education Ministry director-general Datuk Matnor Daim,
Customs and Excise Department director-general Datuk Ahmad Padzli
Mohyiddin, Malaysian ambassador to Indonesia Datuk Zainal Abidin
Alias, Prisons director- general Datuk Omar Mohamed Dan and Works
Ministry secretary-general Datuk Yahya Yaacob.
	   Other recipients are Energy, Telecommunications and Posts
Ministry secretary-general Datuk Nuraizah Abdul Hamid, Housing and
Local Government Ministry secretary-general Datuk Umar Abu, KL
International Airport Bhd managing director Datuk Dr Jamilus
Hussein, Bank Negara deputy governor Datuk Fong Weng Phak and
Universiti Malaya Medical Faculty lecturer Professor Alexius Ernald
Delilkan.
	   Also on the list are Shell Malaysia chairman Megat Zaharuddin
Megat Mohd Nor, Datin Ann Abdul Majid, Federation of Malaysian
Manufacturers president Paul Low, Malaysian Red Crescent Society
former secretary- general Datin Paduka Ruby Lee, Malayan Banking
Bhd managing director Amirsham A. Aziz, Sapura Group president and
chief executive Shahril Shamsuddin, Technology Park Malaysia chief
