<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Norway-Eagle Attack </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Eagle engages model airplane in air combat
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) _ A golden eagle didn't like the noisy
intruder over its turf and immediately engaged it in aerial combat.
	   The tiny model airplane didn't have a chance.
	   A tourist was flying a radio-controlled plane near the town of
Roeros late last month when the eagle swept down on it, grabbed the
model in its talons and shook it for several minutes, the Arbeidets
Rett newspaper reported Monday.
	   Local bird expert Oeyvind Lunde, who has studied eagles for 25
years, told the newspaper that he never heard of anything like it.
	   The model plane, with half the eagle's two-meter (yard)
wingspan, suffered a broken wing, and severe tears in its cloth
fuselage, said the local newspaper in Roeros, about 325 kilometers
(200 miles) north of Oslo. The tourist's name was not reported.
	   (dm-jh)
</TEXT>
