<HEADLINE>
Aircraft to be installed with GPS devices, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Aircraft to be installed with GPS devices, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - Aircraft used for aerial surveillance and
cloud- seeding will be installed with global positioning system for
more effective land and forest fires monitoring.
	   Science, Technology and Environment Minister Datuk Law Hieng
Ding said today the GPS, a network of satellites, could help the
authorities immediately detect fires and pinpoint the exact
location of the incidents.
	   ``These aircraft can be used not only for Malaysia, but also for
our neighbouring countries, particularly Indonesia.
	   ``As such, we have to get consent from Indonesia to allow our
aircraft to cross the borders when the need arises,'' he said after
launching the Wira Alam project, and the Malaysia: Agenda 21 -
Children's Version and Alam Sekitar Anugerah Tuhan books at the
Islamic Institute of Understanding Malaysia, at Langgak Tunku, off
Jalan Duta.
	   The launch was carried out jointly with Education Minister Datuk
Seri Najib Tun Razak.
	   Information Minister Datuk Mohamed Rahmat, who will be meeting
with Indonesian officials soon to discuss the implementation of the
Memorandum of Understanding on Disasters, is seeking approval for
future cross-border operations.
	   At present, 10 aircraft including helicopters being used for
aerial surveillance and cloud-seeding have already been installed
with GPS.
	   Law said a mobile GPS unit would cost about RM25,000 each and a
fixed one RM53,000. The battery for the mobile unit can only last
for two hours.
	   He said the units were easily available in Malaysia.
	   The Malaysian Centre for Remote Sensing has been asked to assist
in the installation process.
	   
</TEXT>
