<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Hoddle-England </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hoddle confident with World Cup preparation
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Coach Glenn Hoddle takes his England squad to
France on Tuesday confident he has done everything possible to make
the team a legitimate contender to win the World Cup.
	   Hoddle put the squad through its final preparations on home soil
Monday at Bisham Abbey and is now eager to face the first test of
the World Cup campaign against Tunisia on June 15.
	   Hoddle said the squad enjoyed the fact they had big expectations
on them.
	   ``After the way we qualified after last summer, there's no
reason not to be positive,'' he said Monday.
	   ``We're prepared better than any other England team has been.
The times when we've put a World Cup head on, when we've had a
World Cup team, we've been very impressive.''
	   Hoddle, who sparked a major controversy in Britain by dropping
star midfielder Paul Gascoigne from his 22-man squad for fitness
reasons, said his team had been prepared for seven games.
	   ``If it goes wrong, it goes wrong, but the approach has been
right,'' he said. ``Everything has been planned right through to
the final _ it's no good when something comes up halfway through
and for us to say `we didn't think of that'. That's not arrogance,
just professionalism.''
	   After omitting Stuart Pearce and Paul Gascoigne, Hoddle is
taking a squad to France which has no experience of playing in a
World Cup.
	   Hoddle admitted that was not ideal but was not insurmountable.
	   ``If we'd been going into it without the likes of David Seaman,
Tony Adams and Alan Shearer, if they'd all been injured, I'd have
said our chances were slim,'' Hoddle said.
	   Hoddle said the situation put extra responsibility on him as the
coach, as well as Ray Clemence and Kenny Sansom from his backroom
team.
	   All three were in the squads in 1982 and 1986, and Hoddle is
determined the lessons learned in Spain and Mexico will be put into
practice.
	   Hoddle has scheduled a behind-closed-doors match against French
Second Division side Caen when the squad arrives in France Tuesday.
	   The coach, forced to leave Graeme Le Saux (flu) and Sol Campbell
(leg injury) on the sidelines for Monday's session, said the reason
for the game was to keep players fresh.
	   ``We had to look at certain people in certain position and this
is an ideal time for us to play this kind of game,'' he said.
	   ``It's one step further than you'd get on a training ground and
a chance to try a few things out.''
	   (jp/sw) 	   
</TEXT>
