<BODY>
<SLUG> TRIP-TO-KLIA-ALL-THE-WAY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`Smooth' trip to KLIA all the way, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Smooth' trip to KLIA all the way, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Tony EmmanuelASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - Twelve hours after collecting vehicles from
the manufacturers, limousines and executive coaches which
complement the Kuala Lumpur International Airport's public
transportation system were put on trial runs today.
	   Traffic congestion on major city roads following this morning's
downpour, delayed the ``scheduled'' trial runs by almost an hour.
	   Despite the downpour and late arrivals, the journey proper from
the temporary terminal at the Tun Razak hockey stadium car park in
Jalan Duta, went without a hitch.
	   Drivers taking part in the trial run said the vehicles were
collected from the manufacturers last night.
	   To get a first-hand view of operations, Entrepreneur Development
Minister Datuk Mustapa Mohamed turned up to take part in the trial
runs.
	   Accompanying him were his deputy Datuk Idris Jusoh, Ministry
secretary- general Datuk Abdullah Tahir, Commercial Vehicle
Licensing Board chairman Zakiah Hashim and senior Ministry
officials.
	   Also present were Datuk Mohd Nor Mohamad, DRB-Hicom senior group
director, which is invovled in the Kuala Lumpur City Bus company,
and Badardin Ahmad, Airport Limo managing director.
	   Besides the Airport Limo limousines, KLCB executive coaches and
PlusLiner coaches, red-and-white taxis were also invited to take
part in the trial runs.
	   Speaking to the media later, Mustapa said the journey went
without a hitch.
	   ``I am glad we had a smooth trip,'' he said.
	   He also expressed satisfaction with facilities for the executive
coaches and limousines available at the KLIA.
	   Leaving the hockey stadium carpark at 10.10am, the convoy of
vehicles proceeded towards the North Klang Valley Expressway, via
the Jalan Duta exit.
	   Proceeding along the NKVE, the convoy turned into the Elite
expressway at the Batu Tiga interchange.
	   At 11am, the convoy pulled into the KLIA's main terminal where
KLCB and Airport Limo's depots are located.
	   Present at the main terminal were senior officials from KLIA
Berhad, including its chairman Tan Sri Clifford Herbert, and
Malaysia Airports Bhd executives.
	   The ``passengers'' alighted at the KLCB terminal and were shown
check-in counter facilities at the bus terminal.
	   ``This enables passengers to check in their luggage, collect the
boarding passes and proceed to their departure gates without having
to lug their baggage around,'' a senior MAB official said.
	   For the return journey, passengers would be able to board the
limousines at the main terminal's arrival lounge while those
boarding the buses can do so at the KLCB terminal.
	   
