<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkish president rejects premier's early election deal
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) - President Suleyman Demirel has refused to
back the early election deal presented by Turkey's premier last
week, reports said Monday.
	   ``I won't allow a government formula to be imposed on me,'' the
daily Hurriyet quoted Demirel as saying.
	   Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz and Deniz Baykal, leader of the
Republican People's Party, agreed last week to call early polls on
April 18.
	   Yilmaz said he would resign in December in favor of an interim
government. Yilmaz and Baykal said they would not take on the
premiership.
	   ``It is up to the prime minister to resign and it is up to me to
decide what will happen afterwards,'' Demirel said on state
television Sunday after meeting Yilmaz.
	   The president traditionally designates the largest party's
leader as prime minister. Currently Turkey's largest party in
parliament is the Islamic Virtue Party with 143 seats.
	   Yilmaz's center-right Motherland Party has 140.
	   But nomination of an Islamic prime minister appears unlikely,
since Turkey's last Islamic-led government was forced to resign
last year under pressure from the staunchly pro-secular army.
	   Claiming it would bring political stability to the country,
Demirel has been lobbying for major constitutional reform that
would change the parliamentary system to a presidential system.
	   Three coalition governments have collapsed since 1995.
	   (ht/djw)	   
</TEXT>
