<HEADLINE>
Anwar: Stake still small in business, housing, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Anwar: Stake still small in business, housing, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PENANG, Fri. - Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim
said today that Bumiputera control in the State's business and
housing was still very small.
	   He said this was reflected in reports received by the State
Bumiputera steering committee and the State Umno.
	   It was thus understandable, he said, that the State Umno Youth
had been calling on the Government here, local authorities and
agencies to be fairer in the distribution (of projects and
licences) to Bumiputeras.
	   ``We cannot allow the gap to widen among the races as it will
cause problems,'' he told reporters after chairing the meetings of
the two bodies today.
	   Anwar said he had told the two bodies to relay their grievances
through the proper channels so as not to jeopardise inter-party
relations and cooperation.
	   ``I have advised them to negotiate directly with the State
Government, the local authorities or agencies concerned.
	   ``I have also asked the State Government, the Penang Island
Municipal Council (MPPP) and Seberang Prai Municipal Council (MPSP)
to consider their dissatisfaction because some of the reports and
figures are really worrying,'' he said.
	   Commenting on a memorandum from the State Umno Youth calling for
the presidents of the MPPP and MPSP who are politicians to be
replaced with administration officers, Anwar said: ``Their
memorandum stems from the unsatisfactory figures gleaned from the
point of the implementation of projects, Bumiputera control of
business, housing and sites for doing business,'' he said.
``However, the solution is not in replacing any person or
department, but in ensuring that implementation is in accordance to
agreed policies,'' he said.
	   Asked about an apparent split in the DAP, Anwar said it was an
internal party matter. ``The more members they sack, the less our
problems (will be),'' he quipped.
	   The DAP yesterday announced the indefinite suspension of
national vice- chairman Liew Ah Kim and treasurer Fung Ket Wing.
National publicity secretary Wee Choo Keong was relieved of his
post for criticising the party leadership.
	   
</TEXT>
