<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Spain-Clemente,0523 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Clemente calls Nigeria toughest opponent in tough group
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: REPEATING to CORRECT category coding. &QL; 
 &UR; By CIARAN GILES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CHANTILLY, France (AP) _ Puffing away and swearing as usual,
Spanish coach Javier Clemente told a press conference Monday that
he and his team were focusing exclusively on opening opponent
Nigeria, who he described as the toughest team in a tough group.
	   ``The team is thinking solely about Nigeria. I've watched them
14 times and I've studied them all over,'' Clemente said in an
hour-long conference, his first since Spain arrived in France on
Thursday.
	   ``I know very little about Paraguay and Bulgaria,'' the
tough-talking, red-headed Basque coach said about his other Group D
opponents.
	   He added that he would begin studying video tapes of his other
foes once Olympic champion Nigeria was out of the way.
	   ``We start out against the toughest team in a tough group,'' he
said, adding that although Nigeria ``played like dogs'' against the
Netherlands in a 5-1 loss on Friday, he felt friendly game results
were meaningless once the World Cup begins.
	   Obviously in good humor _ despite his customary grumpy frown _
and in the mood to talk, Clemente puffed away on cigarettes, made
frequent witty remarks and used common Spanish expletives
throughout the conference, which was attended by some 80 reporters.
	   ``I'm not in any way uptight,'' he said, answering a question
about reports to the contrary. ``I'm very relaxed and really having
a good time.''
	   On several occasions the 48-year-old, small, stocky coach
sparked rounds of laughter as he chastised journalists whose mobile
phones were ringing. He refused to continue talking until they
stopped.
	   Boasting that his squad was capable of taking the trophy, he
said the it was the fastest he's ever coached for Spain, and
technically and talent-wise in great shape. He went on to dispute
criticism that Spain has never been mentally focussed toward
winning the World Cup.
	   ``What's all this mentality stuff?'', he asked. ``Which player
in hell is not mentally prepared to win? Anyway, mentality is all
very well, but legs are what put goals in.''
	   He said the fact that Spain was now considered among the
favorites was due to its hard work, taking an 8-2-0 qualifying
record into the finals.
	   ``I like it being a favorite, but that doesn't help you win.
Only hard work does that,'' he said.
	   He announced that from Tuesday until Sunday, Spain would train
behind closed doors each day at 2:30 p.m. _ Saturday's kickoff time
_ so that the team would get accustomed to playing at an hour when
Spaniards normally have their main meal of the day.
	   For the first time in weeks, the Spanish squad also was without
any noteworthy injury problems, Clemente said. He stressed that
veteran goalkeeper Andoni Zubizarreta and Real Madrid forward Raul
Gonzalez were totally recovered, and also noted that only defender
Fernando Hierro and striker Kiko Narvaez had slight nagging ankle
problems.
</TEXT>
