<HEADLINE>
Bus fire in Armenia injures at least 11 schoolchildren, teacher
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: UPDATES with one death, report that 20 were injured. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   YEREVAN, Armenia (AP) _ A bus exploded and burst into flames on
a country road south of the Armenian capital, killing one student
and badly injuring at least 10 others and a teacher, officials said
Monday.
	   The explosion occurred late Sunday near the village of
Bartsrashen, 30 kilometers (19 miles) south of Yerevan, when 40
students, teachers and parents were returning from a picnic.
	   Officials said the explosion was apparently caused by a gas
leak.
	   Most buses and other vehicles in Armenia run on natural gas.
Gasoline is in short supply due to an economic blockade imposed by
neighboring Azerbaijan because of the territorial conflict over
Nagorno-Karabakh.
	   The victims were hospitalized in the Yerevan Central Hospital
and some were in critical condition, said Norair Davidian, the
hospital's leading burn expert. The students were between the ages
of 12 and 14.
	   Hospital officials said 11 people were injured, and that one
later died. The ITAR-Tass news agency said 20 people were injured.
	   (str/vi/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
