<HEADLINE>
30-point memo on resolving water crisis, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
30-point memo on resolving water crisis, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Annie Freeda CruezASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHAH ALAM, Fri. - The Federal Territory Counselling and Service
Centre today submitted a 30-point memorandum to the State
Government on ways of solving the water problem.
	   The 11-page memorandum was handed over to State Secretary Datuk
Hashim Meon at his office by FTCSC president P. Gunaseelan.
	   Gunaseelan was accompanied by his assistant secretary S.
Selvaraj, treasurer Jaspal Kaur and technical adviser M.
Ghanaseharan.
	   During the brief closed-door meeting, Hashim reportedly welcomed
the proposals and assured FTCSC that their suggestions would
receive due consideration.
	   State Agriculture and Fishery, Research and Development
Committee chairman Datuk Abdul Fatah Iskandar, who heads a
committee set up to study underground sources of water and ponds,
said some of the FTCSC proposals had already been implemented.
	   ``There are some that we are seriously looking into as they are
long-term measures to prevent water shortage in future,'' he said,
adding that the proposals would be referred to Menteri Besar Datuk
Abu Hassan Omar and State Executive Councillors.
	   He said the proposals would also be forwarded to the State
Waterworks Department and Puncak Niaga (M) Sdn Bhd.
	   The State Government, he added, welcomed proposals and
suggestions from the private and public sectors, non-governmental
organisations, experts and individuals on how best to resolve the
water crisis affecting Selangor and the Federal Territory.
	   The FTCSC is the first NGO to come forward with suggestions in
the wake of the water crisis.
	   Gunaseelan said it took FTCSC three weeks to draw up the 30
proposals as it was felt the time had come for the organisation to
do their part to assist the authorities resolve the water problem.
	   The FTCSC proposals include the formation of ``Independent Water
Producers'', more water catchment areas and setting up a computer
data centre to ensure proper distribution of water.
	   Gunaseelan said the centre had also proposed sending volunteers
to assist in manning the Waterworks Department hotlines and also
accompanying water tankers to affected areas.
	   ``The centre is prepared to give whatever assistance the State
Government needs in terms of voluntary service,'' he added.
	   Set up two years ago, the centre, which has some 250 members,
has been active in raising issues of public concern and offering
suggestions to help resolve problems affecting the nation.
	   
</TEXT>
