<SLUG> BC-Honda-Pollution, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0476 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. fines Honda dlrs17 million on pollution charges
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: New throughout with official announcement. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; By H. JOSEF HEBERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) - Honda Motor Corp. agreed Monday to pay
dlrs17.1 million in fines and restitution for disconnecting
pollution-monitoring equipment in 1.6 million cars. Honda also will
spend dlrs250 million on free tuneups and warranty extensions for
the cars.
	   The consent agreement that Honda reached with the government
included dlrs12.6 million in civil penalties, the largest ever
under the Clean Air Act.
	   The automaker also agreed to spend an additional dlrs4.5 million
to implement various environmental projects.
	   ``This settlement means cleaner air for the American people,''
said Attorney General Janet Reno. ``It will help eliminate
thousands of tons of exhaust emissions ... . And it will help save
Honda owners money because they will get an early warning that
their car needs repair.''
	   In a separate action, the Justice Department and the
Environmental Protection Agency also reached agreement with Ford
Motor Co. on the recall of 45,000 Econoline vans because of
emission-control violations. The alleged violations already have
been corrected by Ford on 15,000 Econoline vans, EPA officials
said.
	   Ford, as part of a dlrs7.8 million settlement, agreed to pay
dlrs2.5 million in civil penalties and spend another dlrs5.3
million on environmental programs.
	   The government alleged that Ford illegally installed a device
that defeated the emissions-controls system in the 1997 Econoline
vans, increasing fuel economy but causing higher tailpipe emissions
at highway speeds.
	   ``This action is another step taken by this administration to
ensure that companies fulfill their responsibility to protect
public health and environment,'' EPA Administrator Carol M. Browner
said of the Ford settlement. ``High levels of smog can cause
breathing problems for millions of Americans and aggravate asthma
attacks in our children.''
	   The actions involving the two automakers were announced at a
news conference by the Justice Department and EPA.
	   Honda and Ford spokesmen did not comment immediately.
	   The charges against Honda involved the 1995 Civic and the 1996
and 1997 Accord, Civic, Prelude, Odyssey and Accura. The automaker
was charged with disabling certain emission-control diagnostic
equipment.
	   As part of the consent agreement filed in U.S. District Court
here and a related agreement with the California Air Resources
Board, Honda will extend the emissions warranty for all affected
models to 14 years or 150,000 miles, provide an engine check and
any emissions-related repairs needed between 50,000 and 75,000
miles of use, and provide a free tuneup between 75,000 and 150,000
miles of use.
</TEXT>
