<HEADLINE>
Selangor folk get to air their grievances, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Selangor folk get to air their grievances, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHAH ALAM, Fri. - The State Government will hold meet-the-people
sessions on the water crisis to give them an opportunity to voice
their grievances, Menteri Besar Datuk Abu Hassan Omar said today.
	   He said the sessions would initially be held at a centralised
location in the next two weeks and if the response was good,
similar sessions would be held in affected areas.
	   ``State Assemblymen, politicians, community leaders,
representatives from the Waterworks Department, other relevant
departments and agencies and Non-Governmental Organisations will be
represented at the sessions.''
	   He said there was a need for such sessions as people should be
given the correct picture of the water problem, the causes, the
short and long-term measures taken by the Federal and State
Government to resolve it.
	   ``They should also be made aware of the water levels in the
catchment areas and dams and the alternative measures to boost
water supply in Selangor, especially by tapping underground water
and from lakes, ponds and mining pools.''
	   Abu Hassan said the government also welcomed ideas, suggestions
and proposals to resolve the water problem.
	   On the revocation of the permit for a dialogue session on the
current water crisis organised by the Federation of Malaysian
Consumers Association, Abu Hassan said it was the prerogative of
the police.
	   ``They have their reasons,'' he said.
	   Abu Hassan advised those badly hit by the water rationing
exercise to get in touch through the Waterworks Department
hotlines.
	   
</TEXT>
