	   KOTA BARU, Fri. - Local authorities were today told to speed up
the signing of the interim agreement with private companies for
solid waste disposal.
	   Housing and Local Government Minister Datuk Dr Ting Chew Peh
said speed on their part would enable privatisation of solid waste
management to be carried out smoothly throughout the country.
	   ``Although the Government has yet to table a Bill, we have to go
ahead with the privatisation.
	   ``Hence, the local authorities should sign the interim agreement
with the concessionaires as soon as possible,'' he told reporters
after launching a fire prevention campaign at Sekolah Menengah
Chung Cheng here.
	   Also present were Kota Lama Assemblyman Leong Su Siang, Kota
Baru MP Illani Isohak and State Fire and Rescue Department director
Saari Mian.
	   The Government had appointed four companies to manage solid
waste disposal. They were DRB-Hicom Group, Northern Waste
Industries, Southern Waste Management Sdn Bhd and MMC Engineering.
	   ``This covers the whole country - south, north, central and east
region,''
	   he said.
	   The northern region comprising Penang, Perak, Perlis and Kedah
would be managed by Northern Waste Industries.
	   The Southern Waste Management Sdn Bhd would manage solid waste
disposal in Malacca, Negri Sembilan and Johor while DRB-Hicom
Group, through its subsidiary, Alam Flora, would be responsible for
the central region comprising Kelantan, Trengganu, Pahang and
Selangor.
	   In Sabah, Sarawak and Labuan, the concessionaire is MMC
Engineering.
	   
