<BODY>
<SLUG> PHILIPPINES-RATES-LOW-F sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippines Rates Low ``F'' in Heart Management, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Philippines Rates Low ``F'' in Heart Management, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The results of the Asia Pacific Collaboration on Coronary Heart
Disease Risk Factor Intervention (ASPAC) study was released last
May in a press conference supported by Merck Sharp &AMP; Dohme
Philippines to the Philippine College of Physicians. The study
indicates that the Philippines has one of the lowest ratings in
terms of high cholesterol diagnosis and management and obesity
management, both being significant factors in coronary heart
disease (CHD).
	   The ASPAC studies was conducted by a team of cardiologists,
physicians, nurses, and healthcare workers in Australia, Indonesia,
Japan, Korea, Malaysia, New Zealand, Philippines, Singapore,
Thailand, and Taiwan. Data from over 180 hospitals and 4,000
patients from these countries were included in the study.
	   The study examined major risk factors of CHD, including high
blood pressure, smoking, obesity, diabetes, and high cholesterol.
Other information, such as dietary advices, drug treatments, and
heart treatment procedures were also collected and analyzed.
Results indicated that the Philippines requires much improvement in
diagnosis and treatment of high cholesterol and obesity; otherwise,
the incidence of heart attacks in the country will increase
dramatically.
	   Dr. Antonio Dans, the Philippine ASPAC study coordinator,
explains, ``We have to sit down and talk about what is the ideal
way of managing heart disease...the best information needs to
trickle down to the private practitioners, so that we know the
patients are getting the best care.''
	   One of the reasons the Philippines has such a low rating is that
many patients with high cholesterol do not follow their diet
requirements nor take medication that will prevent their condition
from developing into more serious cardiovascular disease.
	   Dr. Cesar Recto II of the Philippine Heart Association Council
on Preventive Cardiology explains, ``A large part of the problem is
patient noncompliance with therapy. Responsibility for proper
compliance, however, lies with both the patient and the
physician.''
	   What can help boost the rating of the Philippines is the
development of disease prevention programs by the government,
especially with CHD.
	   Government is an essential player in improving the health of
citizens, especially in making sure that they receive the proper
healthcare.
	   ``The current state of treatment of coronary risk factors in the
Philippines has shown us that proper therapy is not reaching all of
our patients. We know how to treat these patients. Now we must make
it a priority to see they receive all the benefits they deserve,''
says Dr. Dans. - JTNones
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:PHILIPPINES-RATES-LOW-F sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
