<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian markets waiting for news from Yeltsin trip to Germany
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian stocks drifted slightly lower in light
trading Monday, while traders waited to see whether President Boris
Yeltsin would bring home an aid package from his two-day visit to
Germany.
	   The Russian Trading System closed down 1.1 percent, a far cry
from the wild swings caused by panic-selling late last month. The
ruble was unchanged at 6.18 to the dollar.
	   ``The stocks were too cheap to sell, and people too scared to
buy,'' said Eric Kraus, chief strategist at Regent European
Securities.
	   Although the markets have stabilized and the Russian government
insists no formal aid request has been made, traders still expect a
bailout either from Yeltsin's German trip or the meeting of Group
of Seven deputy finance ministers in Paris on Tuesday.
	   ``Without aid, the situation might get out of control,'' said
Mikhail Yemelyanov, a trader with Inkom Capital. ``Money from the
West might stimulate growth on the market, but that will also
depend on the timing and the size of the aid.''
	   Russia's financial crisis began two weeks ago week with a steep
drop in the stock market that many feared could lead to a run on
the ruble _ followed by price rises and possible social unrest.
	   The new government of Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko responded
by tripling a key interest rate to keep investors in the market,
spending hundreds of millions to prop up the ruble and selling dlrs
1.25 million worth of bonds.
	   The government also announced a new crackdown on tax cheats to
bring in more revenue and enlisted the help of the country's
leading businessmen to draft longer-term solutions.
	   As part of Russia's desperate attempt to reduce its budget
deficit, the government announced Monday it will lay off 231,100
employees, or 3.6 percent of its workforce, the Interfax news
agency reported. The layoffs should save 5.86 billion rubles (dlrs
953 million), Interfax said.
	   And, in an attempt to spur economic growth, the government will
reduce rail transport rates for coal, iron ore, oil and fuel oil by
25 percent, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported. Russia's economic
growth has been hampered by rapidly rising rail transport costs.
	   (dj/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
