<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-House of Lords </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tories balk at bluebloods losing voting powers in Lords
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ With confrontation looming over plans to strip
aristocrats of voting rights in the upper House of Lords, the Labor
Party government said Monday it will if necessary force through a
bill to carry out its campaign promise.
	   ``Quite frankly, the idea of the (Conservative Party) opposition
wheeling out their army of hereditary peers to try to block the
government's fulfillment of a manifesto commitment would itself be
a constitutional outrage,'' said Lord Richard, a lawyer who is the
Labor leader in the Lords.
	   Prime Minister Tony Blair pledged in the platform on which Labor
swept to power 13 months ago to remove the right of dukes,
marquises and peers with hereditary titles to vote.
	   Negotiations have run into trouble with Lord Cranborne, scion of
an ancient family and heir to the 6th Marquis of Salisbury leading
opposition from Conservative Party peers.
	   The Conservatives are threatening not to cooperate in reforming
the Lords because Labor has failed to produce so far an alternative
long-term plans for the upper chamber of Parliament.
	   Initially Labor plans to put forward a bill, probably toward the
end of the year, to reduce the chamber of about 1,200 peers _
largely hereditary _ to some 500 commoners, many career
politicians, who have been given titles for life.
	   The Lords' powers are restricted to delaying for about six
months legislation passed by the elected House of Commons. But the
Lords, where the Conservatives have a built-in majority, could
frustrate the government by clause-by-clause challenges to the
bill.
	   Richard addressed a conference at the House of Lords organized
by London's Daily Telegraph, a pro-conservative daily.
	   A Gallup poll commissioned by the newspaper indicated that
two-thirds of people want the Lords abolished or reformed, with 35
percent wanting no change. The poll of 1,011 adults had a 3 percent
margin of error either way.
	   Labor, which has a huge majority in the Commons, denied charges
by critics that it plans to flood the Lords with appointed
supporters.
	   Cranborne said Tories will fight the plan until Labor produces
an alternative ``at least as independent'' as the hereditary Lords
- and accused Prime Minister Tony Blair of not wanting an
independent upper chamber.
	   ``He hates being held accountable to Parliament. He hates the
threat to his unfettered power that the existence of an independent
second chamber represents,'' said Cranborne.
	   ``He needs to unite his House of Commons troops against an enemy
which looks sort of formidable but which they feel is morally
indefensible,'' he said.
	   (mj/eml)
</TEXT>
