<HEADLINE>
Over 500 cases of domestic violence solved, says Zaleha, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Over 500 cases of domestic violence solved, says Zaleha, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   TUMPAT, Fri. - The National Unity and Social Development
Ministry has solved 502 cases of domestic violence since the
Domestic Violence Act was introduced in June 1996.
	   Its Minister Datin Paduka Zaleha Ismail said they were part of
852 cases reported to the Welfare Department, especially by
housewives.
	   She said this after launching the formation of Tumpat's Women
Affairs (Hawa) counselling committee at the District Council office
today.
	   Also present were State Unity Department director Abdul Ghani
Awang Hamat and Tumpat Umno division chief Datuk Kamaruddin Jaafar.
Zaleha attributed the rise in reported cases to the awareness among
women of their rights provided by the Act.
	   ``With the counselling services provided to the victim of
domestic violence, the response we received was overwhelming.
	   ``They do not hesitate or feel shy about reporting the violence
that they have been through,'' she said.
	   She added that some of the victims admitted that their lives
become more secure after receiving the counselling.
	   ``So, I urge those facing such problems or involved in quarrels
with their spouses which led to threats to their safety, to forward
their cases to the department.
	   ``We can apply for temporary protection from the court for them
if they feel their lives are in danger,'' she added.
	   Zaleha said the department had 29 centres to provide shelter for
the victims of domestic violence.
	   ``The centres will become safe places for them before any
decisions are made,'' she added.
	   
</TEXT>
