<BODY>
<SLUG> FITTING-FINALE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fitting Finale, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Fitting Finale, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The much-awaited Grand Centennial Ball - set to be the year's
most prominent social event - will cap celebrations marking a
Republic's 100 years of existence.
	   A festival of music, dance, and fashion will be the year's
fitting finale to the Centennial celebration of Philippine
Independence. Organized by Index Events and presented by the
National Centennial and Visitors Corporation (PCVC), the Philippine
Centennial Ball - to he held at the World Trade Center on June 13 -
will be graced by His Excellency President Fidel V. Ramos, and is
expected to draw over 5,000 guests.
	   For the occasion, the spacious World Trade Center will be
transformed into an elegant ballroom setting where Filipiniana-clad
guests will pay tribute to the country's 100 years of Independence.
Ballroom dancing, to be opened by Mr. Ramos' Presidential Waltz,
will commence after a formal dinner.
	   Musical performances will be provided by the Manila Philharmonic
Orchestra, Moonstrucks, and Family Birth Control Band. A program
will feature a dance showcase from the national champions of the
Asian Dance Sport Competition and socialite/dance school directress
Becky Garcia.
	   Ten Centennial Gowns will be showcased by members of the Fashion
Designers' Group (FDG), representing 10 decades of fashion design
trends, each highlighting the beauty and splendor of Filipino
fashion as well as the talent and ingenuity of local designers. The
designers will present the evolution of Philippine fashion from
1898 to 1998.
	   The FDG has assigned members with different decades in the
Republic's 100 years of existence: Danilo Franco (1898-1908), Bubum
Melgar (1909-1918), Cesar Gaupo (1919-1928), Gregg Centeno
(1929-1938), Lulu Tan Gan (1939-1948), Loretto Popioco (1949-1958),
Efren Ocampo (1959-1968), Rei Bancil (1969-1978), Mike de la Rosa
(1979-1988), and Rina Go Thorp (1989-1998). All designers did
research on historical fashion trends to come up with creations
displaying the fabulous styles of the Islands.
	   ``The Centennial Gowns,'' proceeds of which are intended help
raise funds for the Intramuros restoration project, will be
exhibited at the National Museum after the ball. A preview of the
gowns, featuring the designers, their stylists, and the models
(dubbed as ``The Centennial Ladies'') will be held at the Coconut
Palace.
	   Special events will also be incorporated into the ball.
	   There will be an auction featuring a showcase of prized
collections and valued memorabilia rich in cultural heritage like
masterpieces and contemporary artworks of Filipino artists to be
presided by art collector Joel Cruz. The Connoisseur's Lounge will
offer exquisite cigars, vintage wines, and spirits in a refined
setting. The Gallery will hold a formal portrait photography
exhibit, adorned with lavish period backdrops, dramatic lighting
effects, and framing treatments for guests' Centennial mementos of
the gala affair. - JTNones [Inquiries regarding the affair may be
forwarded to Index Events, tel.
	   726-3350 or 725-8286, while ticket reservations may be placed
with PCVC, tel. 522-2294 or 525-9318 ext. 244.] photo captions: 1.
World-renowned Philharmonic Orchestra, with conductor Rodel
Colmenar, will be featured during the Grand Centennial Ball.
	   2. Some of the designs for the Centennial Gowns: Gregg Centeno's
classic interpretation of '30s Filipiniana fashion; Efren Ocampo's
toned-down yet intricately adorned Filipiniana creation
representing the decade of 1959-1968; and Mike dela Rosa's spunky
interpretation of Filipiniana during the decade of 1970-1988.
	   
