<HEADLINE>
Teacher pleads not guilty to corruption, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Teacher pleads not guilty to corruption, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SEREMBAN, Fri. - A 38-year-old vocational school teacher pleaded
not guilty to three charges under the Emergency (Essential Powers)
Ordinance 1970 at the Sessions Court here, today.
	   Badrudin Mohd Taha, from Sekolah Menengah Vokasional, Ampangan,
faces a first charge of allegedly using his position as a member of
the school's Quotation Committee (Jawatankuasa Sebutharga) for
personal gain.
	   He is charged with approving quotation No (27) SMV 05/09/01
Volume 3, from a company, Sri Bukti Elektrik, in which his wife,
Rusni Bakar had an interest, to supply electrical items worth
RM2,336 to the school.
	   He is alleged to have committed the offence at the school on
March 20, 1995 between 11.15am and 12.45pm.
	   The offence, under Section 2(1) of the Ordinance, carries a
maximum 14 years' jail term or a fine not exceeding RM20,000 or
both upon conviction.
	   Badrudin faces a second charge under the same section for using
his position to approve a second quotation, No (7) SMV 05/09/01
Volume 4, from the same company to supply items worth RM13,596.60.
	   He is charged with committing the offence at the school on July
11, 1995 between 10am and 11am.
	   On the third charge, Badrudin is alleged to have used his
position to approve quotations No (30) and (32) SMV 05/09/01 Volume
4, from Sri Bukti Elektrik to supply items worth RM2,441.40.
	   The charge is under the same section, for committing the offence
on August 30, 1995 between 10am and 1.30pm.
	   Prosecuting officer Ramlee Muhamood from the Anti-Corruption
Agency prosecuted before Judge Abdul Rahman Abdol who fixed July
14, 15 and 16 for the hearing.
	   The accused was granted RM5,000 bail in one surety.
	   
</TEXT>
