<SLUG> BC-Croatia-Bosnia-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bosnian Croat party carved in two
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) _ The Croat member of Bosnia's joint
presidency backed away from an agreement to maintain a united
political front in Bosnia, and said Monday he would persist in
forming a new party.
	   In an open letter to Croatia's president, Kresimir Zubak said he
was fed up with hard liners bent on concentrating power away from
Bosnia's capital and effectively ostracizing Croats in a small
southwestern pocket of the country.
	   Croatian President Franjo Tudjman, who has acted as a patron to
Bosnian Croats since Yugoslavia's break up in 1991, tried to iron
out rifts within the Croat Democratic Union, hosting a meeting of
its leading members Friday in Zagreb.
	   Although Zubak appeared to have backed down over the weekend
from his plan to create a new party, his letter indicated he had
changed his mind.
	   ``I've come to the conclusion that the differences within the
political leadership of the party are unbridgeable,'' the Croatian
state-run HINA quoted Zubak as saying.
	   ``The reduction of fundamental Croat interests to only certain
specific regions in Bosnia is political suicide,'' Zubak wrote,
appealing for Tudjman's backing.
	   A moderate politician, Zubak pledged to respect the 1995 Dayton
peace plan, which envisages a united country and unimpeded return
of refugees of all ethnic groups _ something hard-line Croat
nationalists in Tudjman's party oppose.
	   Zubak also is dissatisfied with party leaders, who he said are
corrupt and have amassed wealth while in office.
	   Other prominent Croat politicians, including several ministers,
are likely to follow Zubak and join the new party.
	   The move comes only three months before general elections in
Bosnia and is expected to weaken the Croatian Democratic Union,
which has grown increasingly hard line in recent months.
	   International officials last week said Zubak's party would be
allowed to run in September elections.
	   A similar split in the Bosnian Serb leadership last year marked
one of the biggest breakthroughs in Bosnia since the 1995 end of
the war. Western powers used that chance to support Serb moderates
and sideline the old hard-line leadership.
	   (eb/ac/scl)
</TEXT>
