<HEADLINE>
Parallel software by USM in two years, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Parallel software by USM in two years, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PENANG, Fri. - Universiti Sains Malaysia, with the help of an
Indian computer scientist, aims to produce a parallel compiler
software system in two years.
	   Indian professor Dr R.K. Subramaniam heads the three-man USM
team to research and produce the software. He said the parallel
processor system would be a major asset for the growth of the
Multimedia Super Corridor.
	   ``The parallel software will distribute the workload of a single
processor, which is used now in all the sequential programme-based
computers, to various processors.
	   ``This will accelerate the execution of the workload by the
computers and produce computerised outputs faster and better,''
Subramaniam told a Press conference here today.
	   Also present was Professor Dr Zaharin Yusoff, dean of USM's
School of Computer Sciences.
	   The software project is financed by a RM200,000 Federal grant.
	   Subramaniam has so far spent three years on the project.
	   With the parallel processor software, Zaharin said USM would be
the first local university to produce a system with general
applications to all systems, programmes and computers.
	   ``Under the sequential software system, a processor in a
computer can only do one thing. But the parallel system will
distribute workload of a single processor to more processors in a
computer.
	   ``This will accelerate and multiply a computer's work in a far
quicker time,'' he said.
	   Zaharin meanwhile said USM had over the past four years produced
680 computer graduates skilled in the parallel software system.
	   This year 150 more will graduate to be followed by another 300.
	   Zaharin said USM now aimed to produce post-graduate experts with
masters degree in parallel computer system to meet the demand of
local computer experts for the MSC.
	   
</TEXT>
