	   Q: I read that Jimmy Smits is leaving NYPD Blue. Is that really
true? - P.J.
	   A: It seems likely. Smits, 42, who was brought in to replace
David Caruso when he decided to opt for what turned out to be an
unsuccessful movie career, is getting restless and is looking at
other possibilities, such as cable movie and features. No doubt ABC
would like to keep Smits, and at this writing, the two sides are
still talking.
	   Q: I recently saw the young actress Natalie Portman in Everyone
Says I Love You, and I thought she was wonderful. Will she be in
anything else? - G.N.
	   A: The 16-year-old, who made quite an impression with her first
film role in The Professional (1994), has been onstage in New York
starring in The Diary of Anne Frank, so hasn't been available the
last few months for movie roles.
	   But that should change next month when Portman begins filming
Anywhere But Here, the adaptation of Mona Simpson's 1992 novel,
with Susan Sarandon, starring as a mother and daughter who relocate
from Michigan to Beverly Hills and undergo culture shock. Wayne
Wang (The Joy Luck Club) has signed on as the director.
	   Portman will also be seen next May as the young queen who is the
mother of Luke Skywalker and Princess Leia in the first of three
Star Wars prequels.
	   She's also set to continue the role in the two follow-up films.
	   Q: I think Antonio Sabato Jr. is the handsomest. Is he involved
with anyone? And where is he from? - E.H.
	   A: The 26-year-old heartthrob is from Rome, where his father,
Antonio Sr., was a famous actor whose career suffered when he moved
the family to the United States. (Father and son recently
co-starred, however, in the HBO movie High Voltage).
	   At this writing, Antonio Jr. isn't involved with anyone. The
light of his life seems to be his three-year-old son, Jack, his
child with former girlfriend, actress Virginia Madsen.
	   Q: I was a big fan of last year's Lilith Fair concert. Will
there be another one? - P.L.
	   A: Indeed; the tour grossed more than $16 million last year, so
this year there will be a sequel. It kicks off June 19 in Portland,
Ore., and ends Aug. 31 in Vancouver, British Columbia, after
hitting cities such as New York, Detroit, Houston, Seattle, and San
Francisco.
	   And this year it will be even bigger, spotlighting local artists
in various cities and up-and-comers, in addition to the core group
of Sarah McLachlan, Natalie Merchant, Sheryl Crow, Erykah Badu,
Indigo Girls, and Shawn Colvin.
	   In the meantime, a two-CD set from last year's performances has
just been released.
	   Q: I thought Larry Hagman looked very good in the movie Primary
Colors.
	   Wasn't he sick just awhile ago? - G.S.
	   A: The 66-year-old actor, who recently re-created his most
famous role, J.R. Ewing, on a Dallas TV reunion movie, was very
sick three years ago, but he's fine now. He received a liver
transplant after years of heavy drinking produced cirrhosis of the
liver and then cancer. He's one of the lucky survivors, and he
truly appreciates that fact.
	   Got a question? Write to Robin Adams Sloan in care of this
newspaper, or by e-mail: asksloan &LR; hearst.com.
	   
