<BODY>
<SLUG> MAKE-A-BEAUTIFUL-IMPACT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Make a beautiful impact with petunias, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Make a beautiful impact with petunias, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Lam Peng SamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PLANTING annual flowers for colour is fast becoming popular. It
is not that difficult if you follow certain basic requirements in
soil preparation.
	   Most of the annuals planted here are from the summer-flowering
varieties, including marigolds, zinnias, asters, salvias,
sunflowers, cosmos, vincas, impatiens, phlox celosias, verbenas,
portulacas, calliopsis, coreopsis and balsams. Of course, there are
a lot more varieties available that are suitable for our tropical
gardens.
	   As mentioned earlier, all that's needed is a bit of effort to
dig the ground well and prepare the beds accordingly.
	   One variety I would like very much to recommend is petunia, both
for pot culture and for open beds.
	   While petunias need good sunshine, a little shelter from the hot
afternoon sun is preferred.
	   Petunias have bright colours and stunning colour combinations
especially those new varieties that are available in packets.
	   There are many types available nowadays, including those
imported seeds from Australia which have been available here for
many years now.
	   Petunias come speckled, striped or solid, and they let you adorn
your garden with a multitude of colours.
	   Most Petunia varieties nowadays combine interesting petal
designs and shapes with stunning colours. The blooms are still
typically trumpet- shaped, which may be short or long.
	   Blooms are wide and loose and these often dominate the smaller
leaves.
	   The petunia is a sun-loving plant. Its name is derived from
petun which is the Brazilian name for ``tobacco''.
	   As a matter of fact, the petunia is closely related to the
tobacco plant. It belongs to the family solanaceae to which popular
plants like tomato, brinjals and tobacco also belong.
	   Petunias are at their best during the hottest days of summer.
Our climate is thus very suitable for petunias. They bloom quickly
from seeds and grow well in a variety of soils.
	   The bedding petunias can be tall - some can grow up to 30cm in
height - while others can be rather dwarfish.
	   To a certain extent, petunias are rather hardy. The exhibition
types, especially, can withstand dry conditions. The double and
single exhibition varieties are good for pot culture.
	   To grow petunias, the soil should be well-tilled for good
drainage and aeration. It should be enriched with well-rotted
organic manure, in the absence of which you can safely rely on a
good soil conditioner upgraded with a compost or any organic
manure.
	   A good dressing of lime (ground magnesium limestone) is
necessary to ensure the soil is not too acid. A suitable pH reading
would be between six and 6.5 as for most other annual flowering
plants.
	   The use of organics in the soil will tend to decrease the pH
level. This build-up in acidity has to be rectified to a more
agreeable level, that is, pH 5.5 to 6.5.
	   Seeds should first be sown in seed boxes or seed pans.
	   When large enough, they are transplanted into polybags and
nurtured until they are at least 8-10cm height.
	   Then, they are transplanted into the open bed or into larger
pots. This should save you a lot of problems in the field.
	   Cultivation When planting, space the plants 20-25cm apart
depending on varieties.
	   After planting, always mulch the beds to ensure the soil is
protected from the hot afternoon sun.
	   Mulching also benefits the plants/beds in the following ways:
Conserves soil moisture, keeps the moisture in; Maintains an even
soil temperature; Suppresses weeds, thus reducing competition for
nutrients and water; Any organic mulch like peat will decompose and
in time adds to the nutrient level of the soil.
	   Petunias in mixed beds or borders make wonderful companions for
most strong hued flowers, particularly annuals in single strong
colours.
	   Petunias mix well and will complement marigolds and deep red
salvias.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:MAKE-A-BEAUTIFUL-IMPACT sked; CT:w; 
