<HEADLINE>
Rain washes out play at Queen's Club
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Rain washed out most of the play Monday at
Queen's, the prestigious grass-court tournament which serves as a
tuneup for Wimbledon.
	   Defending champion Mark Philippoussis of Australia managed to
split just four games with Spain's Jordi Burillo before play was
halted.
	   Only four other matches got underway, and none were completed.
	   Cedric Pioline, a semifinalist at the French Open last week and
runner-up at Wimbledon last year, was forced to withdraw with a
stomach ailment. The sixth-seeded Frenchman was replaced in the
draw by American Brian McPhie.
	   Never stepping on court was 11th-seeded Todd Martin, who was to
play Switzerland's Ivo Heuberger. Goran Ivanisevic, seeded No. 10,
never started his match against David Wheaton.
	   Ivanisevic was the losing finalist last year and will be seeking
to end a loss of form that saw him surrender in the first round of
the French Open and slide out of the top 20.
	   Also anxious to get the feel of grass under his feet is top
seeded Pete Sampras, who after an early exit at the French Open is
determined to raise his game after a mediocre season.
	   The four-time Wimbledon champion, who lost in the quarterfinals
here last year to Jonas Bjorkman, got a first-round bye and will
face qualifier Alejandro Hernandez of Mexico or Wayne Black of
Zimbabwe in the second round.
	   Second-seeded Greg Rusedski of Britain will play Jerome Golmard
of France or Denmark's Kenneth Carlsen. U.S. Open champion Pat
Rafter is seeded No. 3 and Bjorkman is No. 4.
	   (str/sw) 	   
</TEXT>
