<SLUG> HAVE-SPACE-WILL-GET-LOST sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Have Space, Will Get Lost, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Have Space, Will Get Lost, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Roel Hoang Manipon
	   Lost in Space (New Line, PG-13) directed by Stephen Hopkins
written by Akiva Goldsmith starring by Gary Oldman, William Hurt,
Matt LeBlanc, Mimi Rogers, Heather Graham, Lacey Chabert, Jack
Johnson
	   Lost in Space ran on TV from 1965-68. It was cheesy, they say, a
pioneer of the papier-mache set, the miniature saucers that didn't
look like anything except miniature saucers, and foil costumes.
	   Now they have turned it into a big movie marking William Hurt's
comeback and the no-nonsense effects of the '90s. Akiva Goldsmith
-- who wrote the last two Batman installments which turned out to
be more flash than flavor -- wrote the script. Surprisingly, this
one is different; it is riveting, touching, and wholly
entertaining.
	   The movie is set in 2058 and people are able to live in all that
is inhabitable in the universe. It will only take a few more years
for earth to be able to sustain human life. Dr. John Robinson
(William Hurt), in this sense, has been working on the Jupiter 1
project. This mission will take the Robinson family to Alpha Prime,
another planet deemed inhabitable, to colonize it. Dr. Robinson is
so involved with the project that he neglects to give the necessary
attention to his own family. He is not able attend his son Will's
(Jack Johnson) science fair, and Penny (Lacey Chabert) is being
rebellious, unwilling to leave all her earthly attachments.
	   Off they go, however, their grudges and sentiments against each
other still unresolved. But they are all intellectually compatible
and show their mettle at a time of distress. The wife (Mimi Rogers)
is a biochemist, eldest daughter Judy (Heather Graham) is also a
scientist, Will is a genius, and Penny is competently
technology-literate. Their cooperation is exciting to see. But they
have to put up with their emotional baggages during the flight
though these become both intense and dispensable when they get lost
in space.
	   Piloting Jupiter 1 is Maj. Don West (Matt Le Blanc of TV's
Friends), who considers himself the best fighter pilot and gripes
about this current job of piloting a family to who is, in his
words, going into ``an intergalactic picnic.'' Trouble is
personified by Dr. Smith (Gary Oldman). Involved with a seditious
gang, he re-programs the robot to destroy the Robinsons and the
ship, but gets trapped in it on flight. The Robinsons manage to
abort the robot's mission but the incident drives them off-course.
By using the hyperdrive to escape being scorched by the sun, they
eventually end up lost, not just in space but in time.
	   They realize that they have ended up in the future when they
discover the ship Proteus, abandoned and infested with menacing
space spiders, which is purported to have searched and rescued
Jupiter 1. They next crash in a desolate planet and need a
radioactive material to boost the ship into space again. The
material, however, is located in a time bubble. Robinson and Maj.
West venture into it, thus, entering another time frame of the
future where they discover a tragic fate that will befall the
Robinson family. After a lot of trouble, the Jupiter 1 people
escape the planet before it blows up, the family problems are
resolved, and the movie ends with anticipation of their next
thrilling adventure.
	   Lost in Space is an adventure story that truly entertains. Matt
LeBlanc is a plus, boyishly egotistic but lovable. The romance
between him and Judy Robinson is an obligatory addition to complete
the entertainment. I must mention that the ending is quite jolting
with techno music and flashy credits, but it is a good additional
blast.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
