<HEADLINE>
Addicts strip lampposts of costly covers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Addicts strip lampposts of costly covers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Bhavani Krishna IyerASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DADAH addicts are believed to be behind the theft of RM95,000
worth of aluminium covers from antique lampposts erected by Kuala
Lumpur City Hall in preparation for the Commonwealth Games.
	   City Hall Press Officer Rozielawatie Rahmat said the thefts
began soon after the lampposts, costing RM450 each, were erected at
the beginning of the year. ``We have found that the lamp covers are
a favourite target of thieves as the covers or domes are made of
pure aluminium which fetches a good price in the market,'' she
said.
	   She said City Hall had lost about 200 covers up to last month.
``The number of covers lost is on the rise every month,'' she
added.
	   Asked what City Hall had done to prevent such thefts,
Rozielawatie said contractors had been appointed to inspect the
lampposts between 8pm and 12am daily.
	   However, this does not seem to have deterred the culprits.
	   ``They still continue stealing the covers. We believe this is
the work of dadah addicts trying to make a quick buck and that they
do it in the wee hours of the morning.''
	   She said police reports had been lodged over the thefts. City
Hall enforcement officers have also detained two suspects believed
to be behind the thefts at Jalan Sultan Ismail.
	   ``We are also in the midst of tracing buyers of the aluminium
covers,''
	   she said.
	   She added that City Hall enforcement officers would be directed
to make their rounds after 12am to curb such thefts. The antique
lampposts have been erected along Jalan Sultan Idmail, Jalan Syed
Putra, Jalan Tuanku Abdul Rahman, Jalan Raja Laut and Jalan Raja
Abdullah.
	   
</TEXT>
