<HEADLINE>
Fund for Small Farmers Won't Work: Enriquez, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Fund for Small Farmers Won't Work: Enriquez, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Jenniffer D. BaldivinoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Outgoing Finance Secretary Salvador Enriquez said yesterday the
incoming administration's plan to set up a guarantee fund for small
farmers would not work.
	   Enriquez said there had been a low compliance to the agri-agra
law, which required banks to allocate 25% of their total loanable
funds to agriculture and agrarian sector.
	   ``It's more for a show than for do,'' said Enriquez.
	   He said farmers were having a hard time complying with the
requirements set by commercial banks.
	   In a meeting Friday with President-elect Joseph Estrada, the
Bankers Association of the Philippines proposed the setting up of a
guarantee fund that would extend credit to small farmers.
	   The group noted that while there were various guarantee funds
for various sectors, there was no legitimate guarantee fund
catering solely to small farmers.
	   For Enriquez, however, the best solution to help small farmers
was not to put up another guarantee fund but for government to free
the prices of agricultural products.
	   ``Through this, they will make agriculture a business and not as
a subsistence occupation,'' he said. 
</TEXT>
