<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OAU-Eritrea-Ethiopia, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Threat of war muffles OAU's message of peace
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS to UPDATE with African, U.N. leaders calling for
peace. Edits to conform thruout. No pickup.
 &UR; AP Photos ASM104,120,123
 &UR; By GLENN McKENZIE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   OUAGADOUGOU, Burkina Faso (AP) _ African and U.N. leaders on
Monday condemned Ethiopia and Eritrea for escalating deadly border
clashes, as Ethiopia's foreign minister unleashed a war of words
against Eritrea.
	   Several leaders attending an Organization of African Unity
summit in the Burkina Faso capital despaired that the 35-year-old
organization was unable to end strife on the continent.
	   Addressing the opening ceremony, OAU Secretary General Salim A.
Salim expressed shock at airstrikes traded by Ethiopia and Eritrea
in the Horn of Africa.
	   Ethiopian warplanes bombed an Eritrean military airport in the
capital, Asmara, for what it called incursions into Ethiopian
territory. Eritreans hit an Ethiopian town, killing at least 40
people.
	   ``Despite all efforts to contain and defuse the dispute, the
crisis has dramatically escalated in the course of the last few
days,'' Salim said. ``Everything should be done to secure an
immediate cessation of hostilities.''
	   U.N. assistant secretary-general Louise Frechette also deplored
the conflict, saying both Ethiopia and Eritrea had delayed making
serious efforts to end the conflict.
	   ``The U.N. will continue to work closely with both countries to
end this serious crisis,'' Frechette said.
	   Nelson Mandela, attending his last continental summit as South
African president, urged the OAU to devise new ways of solving
African conflagrations, saying old methods risked failure.
	   The summit, billed as a forum for peace, focused instead on
averting a potential war.
	   ``We must seriously address the question of what we need to do
to ensure that the continent truly and collectively takes charge of
its security and stability,'' the 79-year-old Mandela said in a
statement.
	   The OAU's outgoing and incoming chairmen also offered pleas for
peace.
	   Zimbabwe President Robert Mugabe, who gave up the one-year OAU
chairmanship, said the two ``brotherly'' northeastern African
countries had turned nationalist pride into violence causing
``losses of human life and destruction of property.''
	   In his first speech as OAU chairman, Burkina Faso President
Blaise Campaore deplored the ``saber-rattling'' and ``fratricidal
conflict'' between the two nations.
	   On the sidelines of the summit, Ethiopian Foreign Minister
Seyoum Mesfin launched a diplomatic assault on Eritrea, demanding
that Eritrean troops be withdrawn from the disputed border zone.
	   ``The first thing to be done is for Eritrea to withdraw its
troops and return to the status quo,'' Mesfin said. Eritrea is
``imposing war on Ethiopia by occupying certain territories.''
	   Eritrean President Isaias Afwerki, who earlier accused Ethiopia
of declaring war, dispatched his foreign minister, Haile Woldensae,
to Burkina Faso. Ethiopia's Seyoum was representing Prime Minister
Meles Zenawi.
	   The OAU has had little influence on the conflict since border
clashes began May 6. But diplomats in Ouagadougou said delegates
plan to draft a resolution on the conflict after making
recommendations to their leaders.
	   OAU Assistant Secretary-General Pascal Gayama told journalists
that the organization would work closely with Rwandan and U.S.
mediators who have drafted a peace proposal.
	   In addition to African heads of state, Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat is also attending the summit.
	   There was speculation that Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi, who
claimed Sunday to be brokering his own accord between the two
warring neighbors, might also show up at the summit for the first
time in more than a decade.
	    &UR; (gam/ids/sl)	   
</TEXT>
