<HEADLINE>
Erap Administration to Review IMF Program, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Erap Administration to Review IMF Program, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Arvin P. PanesASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   President-elect Joseph Estrada's economic team was taking a
second look at government's two-year ''precautionary arrangement''
with the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
	   Estrada told reporters over the weekend that a review of the
special arrangement with the IMF was underway to make it more
reflective of the current economic realities. The arrangement is
contained in the Memorandum of Economic and Financial Program
(MEFP).
	   ``We are presently reviewing that (MEFP). And we are talking
with the right (government) authorities,'' Estrada said.
	   Estrada revealed that he and his designated Cabinet officials
were conferring with monetary and finance authorities as well as
with private bankers.
	   Government graduated from IMF tutelage in March but forged a
stand-by deal with the Fund involving an ''emergency fund'' of $1.4
billion.
	   Analysts who requested anonymity said adjusting MEFP to
realistic terms would help economic officials achieve targets
easily.
	   They noted that May inflation rate of 10.3% went beyond the 7.5%
to 8.5% range provided in the agreement.
	   The rate was the highest in the last two years. The last time
the country reached a double-digit inflation was in July 1996 at
10.4%.
	   Moreover, economic growth in general slowed down to 2.5% during
the first three months of the year from the end-December 5.5%.
	   Under the MEFP, a gross national product of 3% to 4% should be
attained by the close of the year as against the actual 5.7% GNP
for the entire 1997 which resulted from the severe depreciation of
the peso and the impact of high interest rates.
	   A review team commissioned by the Bretton Woods institution are
returning in August to conclude its assessment of the country's
performance.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
