WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   EVERY Sunday when I pick up the New Sunday Times, the first
article I glance at is the Photo Finish section, for those cute
little creatures of the week. These little animals never fail to
amuse me.
	   One day, as I was driving along Jalan Masjid India in Kuala
Lumpur recently, something caught my eye. People were gathered to
watch other people's fortunes being read. The idea is to pay the
elderly chap some money, whereupon he will release a bird from a
cage, to pick a fortune card that supposedly tells your future.
	   I decided to try it. I paid this chap five ringgit and the bird
emerged to select a card. Going by the appearance of the bird, it
was starving to death! In my mind was the greatest plan ever ....
	   This old person interpreted my card, which stated that my dreams
would come true, specifically with regard to my SPM results. I
could expect a Grade One. I stood up just as he concluded reading
my so-called ``future''.
	   In the blink of an eye, I snatched up the cage and dashed away
as fast as I could! You know, just like Leo Di Caprio did before
boarding the Titanic? Mission accomplished! Today, those two birds
are free in my garden at home.
	   I am not attempting to be Ace Ventura or Captain Planet - it's
only that I hate watching animals suffer. The extinction of some
animals has made me realise how important they are to our lives. We
are today in the midst of the greatest mass extinction in human
history.
	   Although extinction is an ordinary part of the evolutionary
process, humans have drastically changed things. If extinction used
to take thousands of years, today it happens in decades.
	   In the next 40 or 50 years, various endangered species will
vanish from the wilds. These include the Siberian tiger, whales,
the giant panda, the African black rhino, Asia's black bear,
Africa's elephant, the polar bear, the list goes on.
	   Also on the hit list is our mascot for the Commonwealth games,
the orang-utan! Steps are being taken by non-profit organisations
like the World Wide Fund For Nature, Wildlife Conservation
International, non-governmental organisations and even local
authorities. They have launched conservation projects, campaigns
and public-awareness blitzes, and increased penalties for poaching.
The problem is these steps are not sufficient as they need your
co-operation in facing such overwhelming odds. Now, you may be
wondering - what can you do to protect these precious creatures?
	   Step One: When travelling to another state or country, watch out
for products made from scarce and endangered species. These include
medicines, ointments, ivory, carvings, figurines. Try to avoid
buying feathers from birds like the bald eagle, the bird of
paradise and others.
	   Parts of leopard, panther, tiger, ocelot, margay are no-nos.
Although such souvenirs may look attractive, they are more
beautiful if they are alive! Step Two: Preserve the environment and
prevent pollution. Basically, everyone knows pollution is
displeasing. The question is, why do we still pollute? Protection
of the environment can't be attained by authorities and
non-governmental organisations, as it requires commitment, concern
and interest to save the eco-system. All over the world, pollution,
deforestation and human encroachment has devastated many innocent
species and their habitat. We would be fortunate if polluters are
reported to authorities and sued! Many thousands of ringgit are
what you obtain for prosecuting them! Step Three: Plant more greens
at home. I'm not demanding that you plant an acacia or durian tree,
just several flower plants like roses, orchids or bougainvillaea.
For those with ample space, try planting a palm or a fruit tree. In
a few months, you can expect to encounter little creatures like
butterflies, grasshoppers, birds and others swarming around your
tree. Furthermore, these trees colour your garden and supply your
tummy with yummy fruit. Nowadays, with hydroponics, it's easier and
faster! I remember a documentary on doom called Faces Of Death
(Part 4, and banned in Malaysia). One segment depicted an East
Asian family boiling a puppy for soup. Step Four is to prevent this
from happening. Eating animals is one of the reasons for our
decreasing species. Not only dogs, but bear's paws, elephant meat,
squirrel meat, bats, pangolin, monkey's brains and even rats are
being devoured by humans - the so-called ``intelligent'' beings! I
believe if dinosaurs were alive, humans would eat them, too! Don't
they have some other food to eat? If you belong to this cannibal
category, do try changing your meals to something better and
kinder. These innocent creatures won't bring you luck, as this
practice adds to your sins and mortality rate.
	   Various endangered species are being hunted off the face of the
earth and poached out of existence. It's difficult to picture the
world without the beauty and strength of the tiger, the majesty of
the elephant, the ancient howl of the wolf and the equanimity of
the birds.
	   Failure to halt this destruction could threaten our own survival
as a species. If each of us can work together with NGOs and local
government to protect wildlife, we wouldn't need a Noah's Ark.
	   As Mahatma Gandhi wrote: ``The greatness of a nation and its
moral progress can be judged by the way its animals are treated.''
	   
</TEXT>
