<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-War Crimes, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0529 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Alleged Bosnian Croat paramilitary chief goes on U.N. trial
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS to raise defense attorney's quotes, new quotes from
prosecutor. EDITS to conform. No pickup &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos AMS102-104 &QL; 
 &UR; By MIKE CORDER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ An alleged Bosnian Croat
paramilitary commander accused of allowing one of his troops to
repeatedly rape a Muslim woman went on trial Monday at the Yugoslav
war crimes tribunal.
	   Anto Furundzija, 28, has pleaded innocent to two war crimes
charges relating to the May 1993 rapes, allegedly committed while
he was interrogating the victim. He faces a maximum sentence of
life imprisonment if convicted.
	   His attorney, Luka Misetic, said the prosecution's case was
built on faulty recollections of the victim.
	   ``Her testimony will not convince you beyond a reasonable doubt
that Anto Furundzija is guilty as charged, and, make no mistake,
the prosecution's entire case is based on her testimony,'' Misetic
said. Her evidence ``is not credible, let alone convincing beyond
reasonable doubt.''
	   But prosecutor Michael Blaxill insisted testimony from five
witnesses would prove Furundzija's guilt.
	   ``The evidence will show that the accused conducted
interrogation and arranged a confrontation with another detainee
during which both were beaten and the female victim was again
subjected to further horrendous sexual abuse in the presence of her
interrogator,'' Blaxill told the three-judge panel.
	   Furundzija sat calmly in court throughout Monday's hearing.
	   Although rape has been considered a war crime in other cases
before the U.N. court, Furundzija's trial is the first to deal
specifically with sexual assault inflicted during an interrogation.
	   The alleged rapist, identified Monday by the names Cicko and
Bralo, has not been arrested. Furundzija was arrested in December
in the central Bosnian town of Vitez, near where his alleged
offenses were committed.
	   The victim, identified in court only as Witness A, was raped at
The Jokers' headquarters just outside Vitez, prosecutors claim.
	   The Jokers allegedly took part in a violent campaign by Bosnian
Croat forces to drive Muslims out of the central Bosnian Lasva
River Valley in 1993.
	   By failing to stop the rapes, Furundzija became a ``direct
perpetrator committing the crimes of torture and outrages upon
personal dignity,'' Blaxill said. Furundzija maintains he was not
present when the woman was raped.
	   The trial is the sixth to begin at the tribunal. Prosecutors
will only call five witnesses, including the alleged victim. A
Muslim community leader from Vitez testified Monday about events
leading up to the conflict.
	   Although Furundzija is a minor figure from the 3 1/2-year
Bosnian conflict, prosecutors at the U.N. court are keen to
establish case law involving sexual assaults as a war crime.
	   Set up in 1993, the war crimes tribunal has indicted 60 suspects
and has 27 in custody. Its most-wanted suspects, former Bosnian
Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and his wartime military chief, Gen.
Ratko Mladic, remain at large. 	   
</TEXT>
