<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Balkans, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yugoslavia increasingly isolated by Balkan neighbors
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: AMs, UPDATES with fresh quotes, color, background, recasts
throughout; changes byline &QL; 
 &UR; By PATRICK QUINN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) _ Yugoslavia's campaign against its ethnic
Albanian minority in Kosovo left it isolated Monday even by its
traditional supporters.
	   Foreign ministers from other Balkan nations joined forces at a
two-day regional meeting to press Yugoslavia to sign on to a
statement addressing the violence in the province, where Yugoslav
Serbs are fighting Albanian separatists.
	   They failed. Even Greece, a fellow Orthodox Christian nation and
once one of Yugoslavia's staunchest supporters in the West, was
unable to sway the Yugoslavs.
	   ``There is an ethical problem, a problem of civilization ... .
This concerns all people and not just the country where it is
occurring,'' said Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos,
referring to Yugoslavia's human rights record in Kosovo.
	   The meeting, held in a sultan's palace built shortly before the
collapse of the Ottoman empire, once again showed that solving a
Balkan regional problem can be an endeavour of Byzantine
proportions.
	   Problems with Yugoslavia over Kosovo bodes ill for the broad
Balkan initiative the meeting is designed to represent. The third
of its kind, the meeting aims at improving the economies of the
region and their infrastructures.
	   ``It is high time to overcome the difficulties which still
persist among ourselves and to develop appropriate tools to
transform into practice a common vision for our future,'' said
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem.
	   Foreign ministers from Albania, Bulgaria, Greece, Macedonia,
Romania, Turkey, Yugoslavia and high-level officials from Bosnia
and Slovenia failed to issue a unanimous declaration that would
address Kosovo also.
	   Host Turkey is expected to issue a separate statement that will
include a condemnation of Yugoslavia.
	   ``If the tragedy in Bosnia is fixed in our memories with the
images of bombed villages, the massacred civilians and the biblical
exodus, I assure you that the same thing is happening in Kosovo,''
Albanian Foreign Minister Pascal Milo said.
	   More than 90 percent of the population in Kosovo is Albanian and
mostly Muslim. Western powers are against any change of borders in
the volatile Balkans, but want the Serbs to give Kosovo the
autonomy taken away by Serbia in 1989 as a way to suppress the
independence movement.
	   (sf/pq/djw)	   
</TEXT>
