<HEADLINE>
Ethos of financial crisis, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Ethos of financial crisis, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IT'S been a year since the Asian economic tiger was mauled by
the claws of a financial crisis. In its April/June installment,
Ethos, the ``journal for the International Malaysia Forum'', takes
an in depth look at the crisis.
	   Tan Soo Chuen analyses it while V.K. Tang examines the causes of
the crisis.
	   Race relations, a simmering topic that just about every
Malaysian is obsessed with, are also dealt with extensively in this
quarterly magazine.
	   Chen Tien Yue defines multiracialism and examines the Malaysian
case.
	   Next, we have three writers who speak frankly about belonging to
a different race in Malaysia's plural society.
	   Would a professor of economics be used as a yardstick to measure
coolness? Well, Khairy A. Jamaluddin takes a walk on the wild side
with ``cool'' academician Jomo K. Sundram, Universiti Malaya's
professor of economics - and is mesmerised by him.
	   
