------- a0480 ----- r ibx  &UR; PM-Offshore Drug Lawsuit,614
 &UR; U.S. alarms industry by demanding drug profits from offshore bank
 &UR; By ROBERT HOFFMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 
 &UR; With AP Photo
	   ST. JOHN'S, Antigua (AP) _ A landmark U.S. lawsuit aimed at
forcing an offshore Caribbean bank to surrender millions in drug
profits is unnerving a secretive banking industry that thrives on
lack of scrutiny and perceived inviolability.
	   The case dates to the 1980s, when two Massachusetts brothers ran
a large-scale marijuana business in New England. Once convicted,
they fingered their money launderer, who confessed and promised to
forfeit $7 million to the U.S. government.
	   The effort went awry when the man, John E. Fitzgerald of Boston,
died before handing over the money. Now the Justice Department
wants a Boston court to order the Antiguan bank where Fitzgerald
said he deposited the money to pay up.
	   The case against Swiss American Bank Ltd. and its non-offshore
sister Swiss American National Bank of Antigua Ltd. is now being
heard.
	   Local critics see the lawsuit as bullying of small island states
by Washington, which already had pressured its Caribbean neighbors
into allowing U.S. law enforcers to take their war on drugs into
their territory.
	   The Antiguan government, feeling both its sovereignty and its
prized offshore banking industry threatened, sent a diplomatic
protest urging the United States to withdraw the action.
	   Undaunted by the protest, Washington is looking for tougher
legislation to close ``loopholes related to foreign banking secrecy
laws,'' a U.S. State Department official said.
	   In addition to asset seizure and forfeiture laws, U.S. officials
want to use ``foreign-based crimes'' such as fraud against foreign
governments to justify U.S. money laundering prosecutions, the
official said.
	   For Caribbean offshore bankers, who contribute significantly to
the region's economy, it is an unwelcome assault at a time when
Britain is pressing them to release secret account information for
the drug fight.
	   That, they say, would destroy the industry by scaring away
legitimate clients.
	   ``We will not stand by and allow them to kill off our
business,'' said Neville Grant, managing director of the Cayman
Islands Monetary Authority, which controls about 500 banks and
companies, second only to Switzerland as an international banking
center.
	   Analysts estimate that up to 10 percent of the $5 trillion held
in offshore centers worldwide is laundered money.
	   Some governments voluntarily repatriate drug money to the United
States, which shares it with the cooperating government.
	   Antigua, which has been tarred with allegations of drug-related
corruption, shut down five offshore Russian banks last year under
U.S. pressure. But the government is supporting Swiss American
Bank's argument that the United States has no jurisdiction over an
Antiguan bank.
	   The $7 million was promised the U.S. government by Fitzgerald,
who pleaded guilty in 1993 to racketeering and money laundering.
	   However, Fitzgerald concealed the true ownership of the money a
little too well _ failing to prove his link to the string of shell
companies that held it.
	   Complicating matters, the bank now claims that one of its
managers, who was authorized by Fitzgerald to manage his account,
took $2 million and disappeared.
	   The remaining money was given to the Antiguan government in 1994
under a law about frozen accounts with no clear owner, the bank
said.
	   The United States says the bank had no right to touch
Fitzgerald's _ now the U.S. government's _ money. And Washington
has a big stick to wield: The offshore bankers depend on U.S. banks
to make investments, including treasury bonds. 
