<HEADER>
w1552 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  MANNERS-FOR-THE-GAYsked     06-08 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> MANNERS-FOR-THE-GAY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Manners For the Gay, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Manners For the Gay, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   There are two ways of reading Etiquette for Filipino Gay Men: as
gay (and the book is written expressly for them), or as non-gay. I
use the term non-gay for fear of stepping on toes. Should I say
normal or straight, I could be treading on the politically
incorrect. As author Jomar Fleras writes: ``Normal is relative and
standards differ from place to place, time to time. What is
'normal' is for a gay man to be sexually attracted to another man.
To deny that feeling is abnormal.''
	   Now it's my turn to feel disoriented. I thought all along that I
was ``normal''.
	   Maybe, I am only part of this ``continuum'' that allows
everybody to stand up and be counted. We all differ only in
degrees. At one end are the super ``straight'' men (and women), at
the other, the transsexuals and in between in various degrees of
orientation, the gays. As Gore Vidal wrote, ``there is no such
thing as a homosexual, no such things as a heterosexual. Everyone
has homosexual desires and impulses and responses.''
	   Fleras takes potshots at the homophobic -- those afflicted with
irrational fear of homosexuals? ``Heterosexuals guilty of
homophobia,'' he writes, ``are bigots who call themselves religious
but run around condemning us. That's not about religion. That's
about hate. Your relationship with God is a personal issue.'' The
gays are urged always to be on guard, to protest each and every act
of discrimination.
	   Are you homophobic? The book lists indicators. But go get a copy
and find out for yourself. A word of advice, though, before
plunking down some pesos for the Fleras opus: Be sure your feet are
on stable ground. You know who you are, what you are. You're
getting the book because you're curious. You want to know how the
third sex lives. If, however, reading Etiquette for Filipino Gay
Men makes you confused and wondering, where you have been all the
time, go see a psychiatrist.
	   There's no reason why heterosexuals may not enjoy reading
Etiquette and find it both entertaining and enlightening. At least,
you pick up some sward lingo about which you were always curious
but were afraid to ask.
	   Words and expressions homosexuals use among themselves and
create an exclusive circle where no other may tread unless he can
tell lip service from intrafemoris sex.
	   'Coming out', for instance. If you thought that coming out
refers to debutantes' balls, think again. Coming out, in the
homosexual sense, is letting the world know you are neither male
nor female. You're gay. ``It is a long painful process,'' writes
Fleras. ``It may take years from the time you had your first blow
job (oops!) to the time you ventured into gay bars to the time you
came completely out of the closet proclaiming to all and sundry,
I'm gay and I'm proud.''
	   On coming out, a few pieces of advice: Be sure that when you
come out to your family, your father has not recently suffered a
heart attack. You do not have to come out to your parents when it
means you will lose millions in inheritance. (Get the money first).
Come out to a good lawyer first before you come out to your boss
(just in case you will need to file discrimination charges).
	   It is nice to know: Winston Churchill, Marlon Brando, Marcelo
Mastroianni, Richard Burton, Davie Bowie are not gay but have
publicly acknowledged that they have had at least one homosexual
experience. Sort of like Clinton admitting he experimented on
marijuana when he was in college but gave it up after the first
try.
	   If the book does not tell one which fork to use and whether
bread should be broken with the fingers (ala Miss Manners), it
still carries very practical advice from which one can pick up a
trick or two. Trick here, by the way, is used in the American
Heritage Dictionary-sense of a special skill, a knack. Not the
homosexual meaning of ``a lover picked up while cruising.''
	   Cruising, if you're wondering, does not mean getting into the
presidential yacht Ang Pangulo and going around the Bay (although,
why not? The coming administration promises to be less uptight than
Cory's). Cruising as Fleras defines it is ``going out on a prowl,
looking for a guy to love for a night or for eternity.''
	   Item: Smiling will make you look prettier and more approachable.
Never scowl as it will reveal all of your wrinkles (and the
foundation might crack).
	   Item: If your partner hurts you, walk out.
	   Item: Never talk about politics or religion. In science,
opposite poles attract. But in politics and religion, opposite
poles kill each other.
	   Like heterosexuals, homosexuals come in various types. (Need one
also specify sizes? Homosexuals don't seem bothered about size. In
the chapter titled ``How long is long?'' Fleras makes clear, he is
not referring to ``long dongs,'' whatever they be, but to
``relationships''. Nor about Viagra, incidentally. Maybe for the
aging gays, says Fleras, but so far, he hasn't come upon Filipino
gays who have problems of, uhm, ``impotency''.
	   Still, it should be useful to be able to size them up. If there
is the ``pa-Min'' - the butch (military style cropped hair, jeans,
tight-fitting shirts), there is also the ``pa-Girl'', the
``proverbial woman trapped in a man's body. She takes birth control
pills for breast augmentation.'' The bisexual -- AC-DC -- goes for
both sexes but is really more gay than straight, has a wife or
girlfriend as a front. The MSM -- man who has sex with another man
-- is a young professional (doctor, engineer, lawyer, sales
executive, money market broker, advertising executive), wears
slacks and neckties, has barber's cut hair, goes to Giraffe and
Fashion Cafe. The transsexual or operada is self-explanatory. The
``parlorista'' are the hairdressers or manicurists but the word is
also a pejorative for the scandalous and uncouth gays. You can tell
the closet queen from his chunky gold jewelry.
	   Naturally, the book will have pointers on safe sex. Flera,
managing director of ReachOut, the Reproductive Health Foundation,
has been into AIDS prevention and awareness work. They once planned
to put up a condom cafe in Makati but Jejomar Binay refused to give
them a permit.
	   Whatever one's sexual orientation, safe sex, defined in Fleras'
book as ``any sexual activity where there is no possibility for
blood, semen or vaginal fluids to enter the bloodstream,'' may not
be ignored. Thus, considered safe are kissing, hugging, embracing,
masturbating, massaging each other, urolgania, frottage,
coprolalia, intrafemoris (there go those words. But, sorry, I do
not have all the space to go into what they mean), etcetera....
O..hum.
	   For homosexuals, there is, as yet, no legally acceptable
marriage bond that keeps a couple tied till death do them part. It
becomes more imperative for them to watch out for signs that tell
them, life is no fairy tale, it is seldom that couples live happily
ever after. One is reminded: letting go is very painful, even if
both partners realize it's not working. The first morning you wake
up alone can be devastating. But here's a cliche that often works:
time heals all wounds.
	   
</TEXT>
