<BODY>
<SLUG> LONG-LIFE-THE-UNDERDOGS! sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Long life to the underdogs!, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Long life to the underdogs!, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Dina ZamanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   LAST week saw Raz and me tearing about in a tall building smack
in the middle of where they hold illegal motor races - and there is
a foreign palace being built. We were hired to help organise a week
of seminars pertaining to the film industry.
	   After being holed up in the seminar room for three days, we
pontenged for a quick breather outside the room and found a new
world had appeared in the empty rooms across us. Across the
function room, the world's youthful elite moved briskly around us
as they discussed Southeast Asia's relationship with the world,
nuclear tests in India and saving whales.
	   We plonked ourselves at the table outside our room to observe
the confidence and suggestion of arrogance with which they
swaggered about, as they mingled with counterparts from Ivy League
and Oxbridge schools.
	   Heavily-accented English was spoken - from the
grapes-in-the-mouth variety to the clipped diction used by the Ivy
Leaguers.
	   They were young, they looked good, Louis Vuitton bags were the
order of the day and they knew they were important; one day, they
knew, they would be part of their conglomerates and governments,
and perhaps rule their countries.
	   Raz and I noticed with great interest that most of the young
women scholars, who swooshed by us kutus, had big boobs. We
pondered about a correlation between their ample curves and their
intelligence and looked at each other. We deduced that was why we
hadn't attended their schools and ended up as writers and aspiring
filmmakers, instead of would-be politicians and policy-makers.
	   Their ``do'' was very well-attended by members of the Press,
recognised names in politics, Malaysian business and economics.
According to Raz, who had met these students when she was studying
in the UK, the sustageniuses and their causes/work are greatly
supported by our Government and the suits.
	   Cut to OUR humble abode for the past week. Azhar (a pseudonym)
was bargaining with the ladies in charge of ticketing. He was an
Arts student from ITM, and he truly wanted to attend one of our
seminars. It's just that he didn't have enough money, so could they
bring down the price a bit? He was saving up for Awards night. No
go.
	   Another bunch of bedraggled kids who had come all the way from
Bandar Utama lined up. When they found out the price of the
seminars, they squawked, ``Aiyoh, so mahal-lah! Miss, we are
students, where can pay so much one? We also want to go for the
other seminars!'' After much haggling, they had to pay the hefty
levies, and helped two of their friends who did not have enough
money to pay. I blinked.
	   I mentioned the incident to the powers-that-be and was told
that, hey, if their parents can afford to pay RM25,000 a year for
their tuition, they can jolly well cough up money to pay for the
seminars. Raz and I gaped - did they truly think all parents who
send their children to colleges and universities are millionaires?
Some of them have to mortgage their homes to pay for school! Some
of the kids are on grants and scholarships; does that make them any
richer? A young person from the OTHER SIDE turned up to inspect our
little exhibition. She carried herself well. She had the poise we
adults are still struggling to find, and she spoke well. I felt
like a hooligan in my shirt, jeans and boots. Azhar popped out of
the seminar room for a quick dash to the loo. He was in an old Tee,
worn jeans and very scuffed sandals.
	   I thought, how good to know that governments and corporations
are supporting the young and bright by sponsoring such events, and
their studies. It shows they are more than willing to invest and
help train these Einsteins and Madeleine Albrights for better
futures, theirs and their countries'. Yes, many of these kids came
from affluent backgrounds, but you can't blame them for being
privileged can you? They lead a blessed life. Parents supporting
them in all their endeavours, personalities encouraging them in
their pursuit of success.
	   And here we have a bunch of scarecrow kids who weren't bright
enough to receive prestigious scholarships to preppy universities.
Who are their parents, anyway? Just normal parents who want the
best for their kids, but they aren't intellectual and don't hold
high positions in society.
	   These kids pulak, have chosen a different path - filmmaking.
There is nothing wrong with that career, I happen to think anything
creative is nobler than anything else in the world - apart from
religion, of course.
	   But do you seriously think anyone would sponsor these kids'
ambitions? A play maybe, for the prestige; we Malaysians are big on
fame and prestige, and plays are pretty elitist in this country.
The kids may not rule our country one day, but they do deserve some
form of support! Raz and I perused the susta-geniuses' magazine. Ya
Allah, apa punya bahasa ni? You needed to wade through a dictionary
to understand what they were pontificating about! Wargh! They must
have eaten books and encyclopaedias when they were babies!
Scrutinised the contributor's column - aiyoma, these kids are not
normal-lah! They read law, biology, politics; you name it - some
high-falutin' subject! Read the stuff in the mag. This new breed of
intellectuals - they write very well, but are they in touch with
the grassroots? Do they truly understand what the rakyat needs and
demands? It's all very well to TALK and WRITE about it, but, baby,
if you go to a prep school and mingle with the right people, you
ain't never gonna be in touch with the real world.
	   It is very cle-vah to talk about the NEP, and it sounds
impressive when one debates politics, but to a kutu like me, it's
hollow.
	   The scenario reminded me of the years I spent in a boarding
school. One night as we slogged through prep (I daydreamed of
running away and setting the school on fire), my dorm-mate sighed,
``Adoi, kalau aku dapat 24 aggregate pun cukup. Sure tak dapat JPA
punya. Kesian mak bapak aku, depa sape; dah lah aku ni kes blur -
lingkup la.'' (If I get 24 aggregate, I'd be happy. I won't get
that JPA scholarship for sure. My poor parents, they'll be so
ashamed, who are they anyway. I'm not smart. I'll fail.) I believe
it's high time for the powers-that-be to look at underdogs in a
different light. These kids may not be on debating teams, may not
participate in some crazy scheme their schools concocted, but they
have fertile minds, which may not exist in the bright sparks.
	   Schools, teachers and educationists should stop berating the
kids' for so-called laziness and worthlessness. What makes them
think a kid who does not finish her homework and prefers to
daydream is worthless? How dare they look down on these youths, for
not scoring straight As or being school prefects! They must believe
in them. Teachers should stop thinking of how much more money they
can make at tuition. Do they know how it hurts inside and how it
screws up your mind when they constantly put down your
capabilities? I should know, okay, I was one of those kids destined
to fail.
	   Raz wondered out loud, ``Dins, imagine if we attended Yale or
Oxford, where do you think we would be now?''
	   Oh God, can you just imagine us? Raz an economist and me a
finance minister? We'd bleed the country dry with our shopping
sprees, arts festivals, saving the orangutan and propping up the
film industry! We packed our bags and left for home.
	   Kids, don't back down from a fight. You go out there and make a
movie.
	   When you do, that snotty geek from school will want to rub
shoulders with you and you'll have the privilege of using his
character as villain in your next movie. Ain't life sweet?
	   
</TEXT>
