<SLUG> FOR-A-GREAT-HOLIDAY-TRY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
For a great holiday, try Selangor, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
For a great holiday, try Selangor, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Andrew PonnampalamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IMAGINE being cuddled up beside a crackling fireplace bundled
snugly in warm clothing, enjoying a hot cup of cocoa with the
family while a chilly wind roars outside your Scottish-built
bungalow; or reeling in a thrashing big fish out at sea, then
actually staying overnight with the fisherman and his family at
their island village.
	   If those vacations don't grab you, then how about checking into
a rustic jungle lodge in the primeval rainforest, followed by an
arduous camping trek to a native settlement deep inside the jungle?
	   Alternatively, if you are the sort of person who prefers your
creature comforts when on vacation, you could choose from several
scenic golf resorts, or even have a beach getaway with lots of
sand, sun and fun while remaining in comparative luxury.
	   And the most remarkable thing is that there are NO tiring
flights or tedious sea voyages involved! Every single one of the
vacations described above can be found within Selangor itself -
dramatically proving the point that Malaysia is one of the most
fascinating destinations around, even for the jaded domestic
tourist! A phone call to the Hulu Selangor district office will get
you a booking at the quaint Scottish-built resthouse at The Gap,
the forested mountain pass at the foot of Fraser's Hill, just an
hour's drive from Kuala Lumpur.
	   The western food here is evocative of a grandiose and bygone
era, while the rooms with their high ceilings seem to resemble
something out of the film Sense and Sensibility.
	   To add to the adventurous ambience, the lights go out a little
after midnight, ensuring that you get into bed for a deep, restful
sleep in the cool mountain climate, with jungle insects chirping a
quiet lullaby.
	   For an entirely different vacation experience, take the
air-conditioned KTM Komuter train to Port Klang. The train stops at
the jetty, where a representative of Riverview Fishing Tours will
meet you and help you board a motorboat to Pulau Ketam.
	   A rustic fishing village on the island comprises houses, streets
and other buildings built entirely on stilts! Apart from fishing
and birdwatching trips, you can visit the last traditional kelong
in the area, and stay overnight at a fisherman's home.
	   Needless to say, all meals are included in the package, and they
feature the freshest and most delicious seafood you can imagine.
Caribbean sites will face stiff competition! For the more
adventurous, the Jungle Lodge in Gombak is just a short distance
from the Orang Asli Centre. Situated at the 20km Jalan Gombak, the
centre nestles amidst lush forest and features an Orang Asli museum
and craft shop.
	   Apart from providing attractive accommodation in a jungle
setting, the Jungle Lodge management also organises barbecues,
jungle hikes and even a camping trek to a native village deep
inside the jungle.
	   Business executives and committee members looking for a quiet
hideaway for planning workshops or training programmes need not
check their passports or flight schedules any longer because there
is an idyllic new resort at Sepang, just off the KL-Seremban
Expressway at Salak Tinggi.
	   Commanding a panoramic view of the surrounding countryside, the
DePalma Resort is built on a steep hillside and provides
air-conditioned chalets and all the basic facilities for a good
retreat.
	   In the three days I spent there, I sighted no less than 25
different species of birds, including raptors, kingfishers and
woodpeckers. Serious birdwatchers and nature-lovers, however,
should head for Kuala Selangor, less than an hour away from Klang
or Kepong by road.
	   The Kuala Selangor Nature Park is well-known in international
birdwatching circles, with over 150 species recorded in the 240
hectares of coastal scrub, mangroves, wetlands and intertidal
mudflats.
	   Run by the Malaysian Nature Society, KSNP, as it is popularly
known, also organises nature camps and workshops for groups.
	   For those who insist on three-star comfort, the DePalma hotel is
a posh replica of KSNP, with birdwatching towers, air-conditioned
chalets, swimming pool, tennis courts, seminar rooms, restaurant
and conference facilities.
	   To reach this oasis, drive past the fire station and police
station at the older part of Kuala Selangor town.
	   The world-famous firefly colony at Kampung Kuantan and the Pasir
Penambang seafood village are equidistant from Kuala Selangor, in
opposite directions from the foot of historic Bukit Melawati.
	   If mangrove-fringed coastlines aren't your idea of a seaside,
check out the secluded beach at Bagan Lallang. Although quite
modest by east coast standards, it is clean and fairly serene,
fringed by typical Malaysian rural greenery.
	   The Hotel Seri Malaysia has 100 air-conditioned rooms, a
swimming pool, outdoor fitness station and reflexology walk,
barbecue area, restaurant and conference facilities.
	   Sea fishing and horseback riding along the beach are favourite
leisure activities here, while the more sedate visitor can go
birdwatching, walking or just take a refreshing rest in the
landscaped grounds of the hotel.
	   Veteran domestic tourists looking for a seaside holiday in
Selangor can head for the recently-renovated Hotel Sri Morib, a
classic feature in the area for decades.
	   The adjacent golf course is an additional draw to Morib,
although the dedicated golfer might prefer the luxurious golf
resorts such as Hyatt Saujana in Subang or the Pan Pacific
Glenmarie Resort in Shah Alam.
	   The latter is a firm favourite for a couple of busy doctors I
know, who check in with their children for a restful weekend when
the going gets tough and a long journey seems just too rough.
	   Like many hardworking Malaysians, they are discovering that
there are amazingly exotic and enjoyable holidays easily available
at attractive and affordable prices within our own country - even
in an unexpected place like surprisingly Selangor! 
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998
NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
