<BODY>
<SLUG> DEBT-SERVICING-GOVT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Joker Proposed Cap on Debt Servicing, Gov't Borrowings, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Joker Proposed Cap on Debt Servicing, Gov't Borrowings, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Maria Mirasol B. NgASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Rep. Joker Arroyo (Ind., Makati) has urged President-elect
Joseph Estrada to address the $45 billion debt problem by working
for the imposition of a cap on debt servicing and on government
borrowings.
	   In a statement, Arroyo also proposed the repeal of the Automatic
Appropriations Act contained in Presidential Decree 1177. PD 1177
mandates the allocation of at least 30% of the national budget for
debt servicing.
	   ``There is no law that limits what the government can barrow.
Without such a law, the government can adopt a sky-is-the-limit
borrowing attitude,'' he maintained.
	   The Makati lawmaker, a candidate for House Speakership, recalled
that the late dictator Ferdinand Marcos left the country with a P26
billion foreign debt which President Corazon Aquino inherited in
1986.
	   When Aquino's term ended in 1992, her successor President Fidel
V.Ramos inherited some $29 billion debt. The administration stands
to inherit $45 billion external obligations.
	   Congress in 1993 had attempted but failed to put a limit on
government borrowings. Attempts by progressive legislators to
repeal PD 1177 had also been unsuccessful.
	   Arroyo also slammed finance officials for being ``less than
candid'' about their reports on the country's debts.
	   ``When Estrada spoke only of foreign debt, finance officials
interspersed both the foreign and domestic debts,'' he said.
	   At the same time, Arroyo urged the Finance department and the
Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas to make public how government spent the
$45 billion or how much of the amount was guaranteed by the
national government.
	   Meanwhile, the Freedom from Debt Coalition (FDC) also asked
Estrada to closely monitor the debt-management procedures to be
implemented by his officials.
	   FDC President Ma. Theresa Diokno-Pascual, said the Ramos
administration's penchant of labeling the country's financial
obligation as ''manageable'' was over-simplistic as funds borrowed
from other sources were used to service debts.
	   ''These government officials would like us to ignore the
disturbing manner by which government pays these debts. The
incoming Estrada administration would be wise to seriously examine
and address this problem, because it (debt) has not gone away,
contrary to the officials claim,'' she added.
	   ''The only way government knows how to get out of the crisis is
to borrow some more. That is not an option, it is a necessity. So
the debt is manageable only for as long as government can continue
to borrow. That does not speak much of our economic independence as
a nation,'' she pointed out.
	   Diokno-Pascual said government allocated an average of $4.362
million a year for external debt service between 1992 and 1996.
	   ''This amount together with interest in domestic debt of over P1
trillion would have easily eaten up 60%-70% of tax revenues last
year,'' she stressed. FDC also appealed for the abolition of PD
1177.
	   ''It has been a grave injustice that Filipino taxpayers have
been carrying the burden of government's debt while the poor are
severely neglected through the lack of vital infrastructure and
social services,'' Diokno-Pascual argued.
	   ''The economy's dependence on foreign money has not diminished
over the years. In fact, the recent crisis only shows how much
bigger that dependence has grown,'' she pointed out.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
