w1558 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Norway-Strikes     06-08 0268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Norway-Strikes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Expanding labor conflict threatens air traffic in Norway
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) _ A union on Monday began ordering key
aviation workers to join a strike that already has crippled much of
Norway's surface transportation.
	   A more than three-week strike by about 10,000 transport workers
has hobbled bus routes, road transport and delayed mail in much of
the country. Meanwhile, the national Academics Union expanded a
separate strike to 8,500 workers, including some airport staff, on
Monday.
	   The Civil Aviation Administration closed the local air service
from the western town of Kristiansund Monday after air traffic
controllers, technicians and aviation administration employees
organized by the union walked out on strike.
	   Geir Ingebrethsen of the air administration said if the strike
hits technicians at the main Norwegian Aeronautical Information
System, or ANISE, in the city of Bergen it could disrupt air
traffic in much of the country.
	   The union has temporarily exempted technicians needed to keep
the traffic control system running. If they do strike, even a small
technical problem would stop the crucial system.
	   The Academics Union ordered a strike on May 28, after rejecting
pay raises averaging about six percent. The strike has so far hit
some schools, universities, hospitals and public administration.
Friday's escalation will effect airports and road works.
	   The transport workers rejected pay raises averaging about 10
percent, and walked out on May 14 in a conflict that mainly over
benefits.
