<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Ancient Church </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ancient cathedral discovered in Kiev construction site
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Workers repairing underground
communications cables in central Kiev stumbled upon the foundations
of an 11th century cathedral, archaeologists said Monday.
	   The church discovered last week may be one of two cathedrals
that archaeologists have been searching for in Kiev, a religious
and cultural center of the Slav people with more than 1,500 years
of history.
	   Archaeologists hailed the find but complained that city
authorities had nearly destroyed the remains by failing to notify
them in advance about their repair work.
	   ``There was a lack of technological coordination. The
authorities wanted to end the repairs as soon as possible and did
not take into account the archaeological character of the site,''
said Ivan Movchan of the Academy of Sciences' Archaeological
Institute.
	   ``It takes more time for an archaeologist to dig than for a
foreman,'' he complained.
	   Although proper procedures call for municipal authorities to
consult with archaeologists before starting major projects, they
failed to do so in this instance, said Gleb Ivakin, deputy director
of the archaeology institute's Kiev department.
	   But Yakiv Dihtyar, the Kiev city administration official in
charge of protecting historical monuments, suggested that
archaeologists should thank the city for locating the site.
	   ``Without our repairs, nobody would have discovered the ancient
foundation for another 10 to 15 years,'' he said.
	   The site is near Kiev's most famous church, the Cathedral St.
Sophia.
	   (ms/sms/mr/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
