<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Gerry Weber Open </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Korda and Krajicek advance at Gerry Weber Open
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HALLE, Germany (AP) _ Top-seeded Petr Korda, still fighting a
flu, advanced into the second round of the Gerry Weber Open Monday
by struggling to a two-set victory over Germany's Kevin Goellner.
	   The Czech player, who dropped five kilos (13 pounds) while sick
at the French Open, beat Goellner 6-1, 7-6 (7-5) at the dlrs
875,000 grass court tuneup for Wimbledon.
	   ``I'm still very weak,'' said Korda, the Australian Open
champion. ``But I'm sure I'll get better and better with each
round.''
	   Yevgeny Kafelnikov, the no. 2 seed and defending champion, and
no. 3 Richard Krajicek of the Netherlands both started slowly but
recovered to claim three-set victories.
	   Krajicek, the 1996 Wimbledon winner, ousted Vincent Spadea of
the United States, 5-7, 6-2, 6-2, while the Russian stopped Andrei
Medvedev of the Ukraine, 1-6, 7-5, 6-1.
	   The tournament has drawn five top 10 players including French
Open finalists Carlos Moya and Alex Corretja of Spain.
	   Korda, ranked third, again failed to claim the world No. 1
position at the French Open, then arrived early to practice his
grass game on the center court that replicates the one at
Wimbledon.
	   ``It's a perfect place to practice,'' Korda said.
	   Korda, ousted Goellner after the German argued a call in the tie
break, then netted an easy volley at match point.
	   The Czech player broke through at the event last year, showing
he had shaken off a two-year groin injury by reaching the event's
final. Afterwards, his ranking soared.
	   Sweden's Magnus Larsson also reached the second round by
sweeping Austria's Thomas Muster, 6-3, 6-2. A last-minute
replacement for Andre Agassi, Steve Campbell, also upset Germany's
Jens Knippschild, Germany, 1-6, 7-6 (7-4), 6-3.
	   Boris Becker said he will use his performance at the grass event
to gauge if he's ready to play Wimbledon, starting June 22.
	   ``On Friday, I will announce if I will play Wimbledon or not,''
said Becker, a three-time champion of the grand slam event.
	    &UR; (rk)	   
