<HEADLINE>
DBP to Earmark P500M For Rehab of Thrift Bank, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
DBP to Earmark P500M For Rehab of Thrift Bank, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Jenniffer D. BaldivinoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Development Bank of the Philippines (DBP) will set aside
some P500 million in minimum capital infusion in line with its
proposed rehabilitation of the Cavite-based Unified Savings and
Loan Association Inc. (Uni-Save).
	   DBP said the fresh new capital will provide Uni-Save the
much-needed resources after it suffered from liquidity problems due
to increasing withdrawal of funds by depositors.
	   For the past few months, government has been supervising the
sale of Uni-Save so as not to disrupt the present stability of the
local banking system.
	   DBP, which has offered to help rehabilitate the thrift bank,
reportedly had initial talks with the Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas
(BSP) and the Philippine Deposit Insurance Corp. (PDIC) on the
financial assistance to Uni-Save.
	   Aside from the P500-million capital infusion, 20% of the total
loans, including the exposure to all affiliates which have not been
past due for more than 90 days with satisfactory security, will be
assumed by DBP.
	   DBP earlier planned to conduct a due diligence procedure on
Uni-Save to determine the extent of assistance that will have to be
provided to help rehabilitate the bank.
	   Because of its presence in various parts of the country, many
banks have expressed interest in buying out Uni-Save from its
present owners. Uni-Save has 32 branches strategically located in
Rizal, Nueva Ecija, Laguna, Batangas, Bulacan, Pangasinan, Isabela,
and Cavite.
	   Last year, it was among the top five savings and loans
associations in the Philippines but suffered from liquidity
problems after its real estate projects were severely affected by
the financial crisis.
	   As of the first quarter of the year, Uni-Save's operational cost
has reached P27.5 million.
	   
</TEXT>
