<BODY>
<SLUG> YESTERDAY'S-TEENAGERS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yesterday's Teenagers Communicate About Today's Teens, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Yesterday's Teenagers Communicate About Today's Teens, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Los Angeles -- The striking picture of contrast presented by
teenagers of at least two decades ago vis a vis their counterparts
of today -- more specifically, their own offspring -- is something
that has held the conversational spotlight in many close and
friendly gatherings.
	   A good number of parents have a great deal in common.
	   High on their list is: how they cope with their teenagers ,and
vice versa, without being considered ``weird'' by the latter.
	   The consensus is that specific periods have been accompanied by
experiences close to trauma and even parents who are specialists in
their respective fields, M.D.s and Ph.Ds, admit that their
professional and academic problems are nothing compared to
monumental tasks involved in coping with their teenagers.
	   (This parent-child relationship, as everyone has been quick to
describe, has all the earmarks of a gathering storm. Though they're
getting used to it, they that even the diplomacy and skills of a
Madeleine Albright would not suffice to handle such turbulent
relationships). The requisites of being parents of today's teens
include vigilant, unscheduled -- and if possible -- uninterrupted
incessant threshings-out of pros and cons of issues, all boiling
down, of course, to that oft-heard process called communication.
	   Naturally, yesteryears' teenagers would and could not help but
point out how fortunate these children of their are today: these
children are allowed to speak out as long as they do not raise
their voices. And if they do raise their voices, they claim it's
for emphasis and clarity (''I can't help it if I talk this way. .
.'').
	   How many among us can remember how we reacted to one-way
conversations (lectures would be a more appropriate description),
and how we weren't supposed to leave the lecture scene unless we
were dismissed by our parents?
	   Too, how many of us can recall how we ever made acquaintances
with the opposite sex without the surveillance that was considered
acceptable, and taken with resignation (not with resentment,
because that was part of being obedient)?
	   And how many were allowed by their elders to do as they pleased
because they had ``come of age''? Hardly any.
	   I could go on and on with more and more comparisons of the two
sets of teenagers; however, we would still return to one double
solution to the dilemma that has engulfed today's teenagers in the
US - communication, and more communication, when necessary.
	   I now pause to wonder if today's teenagers realize that their
parents really try hard (even harder than they can dream of), not
because they wish to impose their own value systems on their
children. Instead, they let them know that these very systems
worked for them.
	   For myself, I thank all those participants who unwittingly
contributed their insights and sentiments to this column. Their
opinions and openmindedness reflect both an encouragement and
caution to the parents who try to make a go of the situation here.
They demonstrate that it is possible, with patience, understanding,
and constancy, to arrive at a meaningful and rewarding relationship
with their children.
	   Yesteryears' teenagers will no longer worry about today's ones
when they make the latter realize that, after all, there isn't that
vast a difference between generations when everyone takes time to
seek and learn.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:YESTERDAY'S-TEENAGERS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
