Unit trust firm sees hope amidst turmoil, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Unit trust firm sees hope amidst turmoil, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DESPITE the seemingly never-ending economic turmoil, KL Mutual
Unit Trusts, a member of the Public Bank Group, believes there is a
silver lining waiting to emerge from the dark clouds.
	   To prove this, KL Mutual organised its sixth annual awards nite
and dinner themed Cultural Extravaganza at a hotel in Sungai Besi,
Selangor recently.
	   The function was to reward its long serving staff, besides
saying thank you to all staff for contributing to the company's
success.
	   Long service award recipients for 15 years were Charanjeet Kaur,
Foong Kuan Mun and Wong Woon Cheng while those who had served for
10 years were Juraidah Jabar, Azmah Ismail and Yong Nyee Chin.
	   Among others awarded that night were S. Ramachandran Seevaratnam
(Top Personal Producer), T. Manogaran (Top Group Agency Manager),
Thniah Lily (Top Agency Manager), Zaridah Zainal Abidin (Top Agency
Supervisor) and Selvarani K. Thuraichamy (Top Agent).
	   As at other dinner functions, staff were to good food and ample
fun.
	   Entertainment was provided by Elaine Kang, after which lucky
draws were held.
	   All in all, the staff enjoyed themselves at the event.
	   KL Mutual chairman Mohamed Nizam Tun Abdul Razak, in a
statement, said the achievements that KL Mutual was enjoying was
made possible by the loyalty and dedication of staff who helped
make it happen by pulling together and persevering through hard
times.
	   He said KL Mutual reported a 29 per cent increase in sales and
20.1 per cent increase in profit last year, compared to the
previous year, despite the economic turbulence faced by Malaysians.
``Every single agent and staff of KL Mutual is responsible for this
achievement and tremendous success,''
	   he noted.
	   He added that Malaysians were now faced with tougher times and
the collective conscientious action of agents and employees would
set a good company apart from the rest.
	   ``This as an impetus to boost not only the morale of the
workforce but also the confidence of investors and public,'' he
said.
	   Meanwhile, chief executive officer Edmond Cheah said 1997 was a
good year for KL Mutual despite the economic turmoil that rocked
Asia in the latter part of the year.
	   ``KL Mutual emerged relatively well, by industry standards, a
good margin ahead of our nearest competitor,'' he said.
	   ``It is precisely this excellent teamwork between agents and
staff that has made this company the leading private unit trust
manager in Malaysia.''
	   He, however, stressed that the success did not mean they should
celebrate too hastily.
	   ``The mounting macro problems, crystalised by the recent
financial fiasco, will not simply disappear though we are
encouraged to note that the Government is determined to restore
investor confidence by maintaining tight monetary and fiscal
policies.''
	   He urged the people involved to concentrate more on the
financial planning programme, which KL Mutual had developed,
essentially to support and assist the sales force of the trust
fund.
	   
</TEXT>
