<HEADLINE>
Lebed says premature to talk of meeting with Yeltsin
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Former national security chief Alexander Lebed,
starting work as governor of a huge region of Siberia, said Monday
it was premature to talk of a meeting with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin.
	   Lebed said he plans to be in Moscow next month for a meeting of
the Federation Council, the upper house of the Russian parliament,
whose members include regional governors.
	   ``I do not preclude that some questions for the Russian
president will mature in a month,'' Lebed said, according to the
Interfax news agency. But he said no meeting has been arranged.
	   Lebed placed third in the 1996 presidential elections in which
Yeltsin was re-elected for a second term. Yeltsin appointed the
former general his national security adviser, but fired him months
later.
	   Lebed was sworn in Friday as governor of the Krasnoyarsk region,
a job seen as a springboard for another run at the presidency in
2000.
