<SLUG> PPA-URGED-TO-OFFSET sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PPA Urged to Offset Cargo Rate Hike Effects, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
PPA Urged to Offset Cargo Rate Hike Effects, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Arvin P. PanesASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Philippine Ports Authority (PPA) should devise measures to
counteract the adversarial outcomes of the recent cargohandling
rate hike, otherwise, there would be ``no more foreign shipcalls at
the Port of Manila.''
	   The point was raised by a key official of one of the major
shipping in reaction to the government port agency's jacking up of
cargohandling fees for containerized shipments by 15% and
conventional shipments by 10% at the Port of Manila.
	   ``This has made the country the second costliest port of
destination in Asia. We are now next to Hongkong,'' the official
told The Business Daily over the weekend.
	   The official, who agreed to be quoted on condition of anonymity,
noted such development should not put a laurel over the head of
port authorities since this threatens the competitiveness of the
local shipping enterprise.
	   ``We cannot be happy with this because we are severely affected.
It is very possible large ocean liners which contribute to
government's collections will skip the Port of Manila. They can
look for other cheaper yet more upgraded ports in the region,'' he
said.
	   The PPA made the adjustment a couple of weeks ago after
cargohandlers Asian Terminals Inc. (ATI) and International
Container Terminal Services Inc.
	   (ICTSI) applied for a 20% increase.
	   The increase was on top of the 20% cargohandling rate hike port
authorities granted ATI and ICTSI in January.
	   ATI, exclusive contractor of the Manila South Harbor and ICTSI,
sole operator of the Manila International Container Terminal,
pointed out in their petition that the severe depreciation in the
value of the peso has made them cash-strapped.
	   They noted expansion projects were deferred after steep falls in
the peso-dollar exchange rate pulled up the cost of their foreign
currency-denominated loans.
	   Moreover, return on investments has been minimal to cushion the
financial imbalance.
	   However, the official lamented that the PPA had to involve other
port users in the economic problems of the two terminal operators.
	   ``The two cargohandlers made the loans themselves and this does
not concern us. I think this is unfair. Now, we have to pass this
additional cost to our clients which is unfavorable to the
public,'' he said.
	   ``The increase exacerbates the problematic financial conditions
of the liners. This is not to mention that importation, which makes
up the bulk of the port industry, continues to be sluggish,'' he
said.
	   The official said a ``co-loading trend'' among shipping lines is
expected to result from the cargohandling rate hike. ``For example,
Sea-Land's cargoes will be loaded in APL's ship since operational
costs are now too high.''
	   
</TEXT>
