w1579 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Ethiopia-Eritrea     06-08 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ethiopia-Eritrea </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Meles threatens more military action if Eritrea does not withdraw
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DIANNA CAHN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) _ Ethiopia will be forced to resort
again to military action against Eritrea if its neighbor to the
north does not withdraw from Ethiopian territory, Prime Minister
Meles Zenawi said Monday.
	   ``What we have is a pattern of prevarication, a pattern of
trying to draw out the process and consolidate the hold on our
territory,'' Meles told The Associated Press. ``If that's the case,
and it appears to be the case, then the opportunities for resolving
this problem peacefully could be fastly disappearing.''
	   The 43-year-old former rebel leader would not be drawn on who
struck first on June 5. But he said Ethiopian aircraft only hit a
military airport in the Eritrean capital, Asmara, while Eritrean
fighters bombed a school in Mekele in northeastern Ethiopia,
killing at least 40 people, among them children. Ethiopian fighters
	   ``I can't think of any rational reason for their invasion. It's
true we have our disagreements on border issues, we have
disagreements on trade and related issues, but you don't go
invading a country whenever you have a dispute on trade issues,''
he said. ``We have more civilized mechanisms on resolving such
problems.''
	   Eritrea claims its forces are within internationally recognized
borders drawn by colonizer Italy in the late 19th century.
	   Meles said Ethiopia was trying to work towards a peaceful
solution to the border conflict but was preparing for war at the
same time.
	   ``So clearly the ball is in the Eritrean court, and whatever
international efforts at peacemaking there might be, I think they
are perhaps rightly directed at Eritrea,'' he said.
	   In Asmara, Yemane Gebremeskel, spokesman for President Isaias
Afwerki, said Ethiopia had effectively declared war on its small
neighbor and was using the threat of renewed air strikes to
blockade air and seaports.
	   ``They have refused to negotiate,'' Yemane said. ``These are not
the actions of a nation that wants peace.''
	   The United States and Rwanda have put forth a four-point peace
proposal that includes a recommendation that Eritrea withdraw to
positions it occupied prior to May 6 when border skirmishes first
broke out. Ethiopia has accepted the plan, but Eritrea says it
needs more work.
	   The war of words between the two countries continued Monday as
the Ethiopian Foreign Ministry accused Eritrea of expelling 3,000
Ethiopian citizens and jailing another 500. An estimated 100,000
Ethiopians live in Eritrea, which was part of Ethiopia from 1962
until 1993.
	   Although several African leaders deplored the Horn of Africa
conflict at an Organization of African Unity summit in Ouagadougou,
Burkina Faso, Monday, Meles said there were no plans for a meeting
there between the Ethiopian and Eritrean foreign ministers there.
	   He said Eritrean troops had ``practically destroyed'' the town
of Zala Ambessa, 600 kilometers (372 miles) north of Addis Ababa,
and that its 15,000 residents had fled.
	   ``It is not a surprise that the Ethiopian people are very angry
at a government they considered to be a close friend would stab us
in the back at a time when we are exclusively focussed on the war
against poverty and ignorance,'' Meles said.
	   With per capita annual incomes of less than dlrs 300 a year,
Ethiopia and Eritrea are among the world's poorest countries.
	   Asked whether the Ethiopians would try to retake the town, Meles
said: ``We would not necessarily be limited to the scope of action
on Zala Anbessa only. We have to address the whole invasion.''
	   (dc/sl)	   
</TEXT>
