<BODY>
<SLUG> DISHES-SPECIALLY-MADE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dishes specially made for garlic lovers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Dishes specially made for garlic lovers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE chef at the Kuala Lumpur Parkroyal Hotel has come up with
something different for patrons at the Parkroyal Court located at
the lower lobby.
	   Roger Leong, who has been preparing traditional Chinese dishes,
particularly Cantonese cuisine, for the past five years, has
created a new combination of garlic-filled dishes.
	   ``The creations are a combination of Western and Asean
ingredients. The prawn, lobster and crab shells are brewed first
before making the chowder soup,'' Leong explained.
	   ``These preparations are more suited for the Chinese as they are
used to taste of garlic and its aroma.''
	   Leong said others who liked garlic might also want to give the
dishes a try.
	   Among his creations are superior seafood chowder with toasted
garlic flakes, deep fried soft-shell crab with garlic pepper,
pomfret with minced garlic and shark's fin in crab gravy, steamed
crab with rice wine and smashed garlic, among others.
	   Reasonably priced, these dishes will be prepared steaming hot
for guests.
	   Parkroyal Court food and beverage manager Jason Pope said the
idea of using excess garlic in these preparations was to give
guests a different taste.
	   ``Guests need not order every dish that comes in the
garlic-list. They can order other dishes available in the outlet,''
Pope said.
	   ``This way, those who are not able to stand the taste of excess
garlic or its smell have other dishes to choose from.''
	   He said soft-shell crabs were imported from Vietnam, deep fried
with minced garlic and shredded conpoy, which made the shell even
softer and more edible.
	   ``Garlic is extensively used in Asia and more so in Malaysia.
Though Malaysians use garlic almost every day in their daily
cookings, these special creations with `extra' garlic really gives
a different and unique taste,'' he added.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
