w1592 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EU-India-Pakistan     06-08 0307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-India-Pakistan,0306 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU calls for review of loans to Pakistan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LUXEMBOURG (AP) _ The European Union recommended Monday a delay
of loans to Pakistan through international financial institutions
such as the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund.
	   EU foreign ministers issued the same recommendation against
India on May 25 for carrying out five nuclear tests. Pakistan
responded with six tests of its own, and tension between the two
neighbors is high.
	   After recommending a delay of loans to India, EU countries
``will likewise review the advisability of (international financial
institution) lending to Pakistan,'' the ministers said in a
statement.
	   But the extent to which the loans are delayed for Pakistan
should be decided ``in light of the economic and financial
circumstances'' of the country, the statement said.
	   The ministers said the EU executive Commission should examine
whether Pakistan can still benefit from an EU system under which
selected developing countries enjoy certain privileges in trade
with the 15-nation bloc. A similar recommendation was issued
against India last month.
	   They reiterated their appeal to India and Pakistan to sign and
ratify the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban treaty and to open talks
towards a peaceful settlement.
	   ``The European Union calls upon the leaders of both countries to
engage urgently in dialogue on regional stability issues, including
with China,'' they said.
	   They warned that the EU would take ``all necessary measures
should India and Pakistan not take early steps to accede to ...
international non-proliferation treaties and resume their bilateral
political dialogue.''
	   India and Pakistan have fought three wars in the last 50 years,
two of them over the Himalayan territory of Kashmir, now divided
between them. 	   
</TEXT>
