<HEADLINE>
Company'declines to build pedestrian bridge, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Company'declines to build pedestrian bridge, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PROJEK Lintasan Kota Sdn Bhd or Prolintas, the concessionaire
for the country's first elevated highway, will not build a
pedestrian bridge over Jalan Hulu Klang to facilitate Sekolah
Menengah Hulu Klang students to cross the road.
	   A Prolintas spokesman said the bridge was beyond the company's
jurisdiction.
	   Jalan Hulu Klang, which is now part of the Middle Ring Road II
project, is under the jurisdiction of the Public Works Department.
	   The spokesman said the company would be building a bridge over
Sungai Ampang for vehicles and would keep the service road in front
of the Flamingo Hotel partly open for pedestrians, especially
students.
	   ``When the bridge over the river is ready, it can be used by
motorists to go to the school while students who walk or cycle to
the school can still use the service road as we will not close it
entirely,'' she said.
	   The plan to build the bridge, she said, had been included in the
original highway plan but until now it was still being deliberated
by the four authorities involved - Prolintas, Malaysia Highway
Authority, Ampang Jaya Municipal Council and the Drainage and
Irrigation Department.
	   Prolintas' response came following a query by Ampang Jaya
Municipal Council councillor Tai Beng Hoe during the council's full
board meeting last month.
	   Tai had asked the council to pursue the pedestrian bridge
construction matter with Prolintas as the project had not
materialised despite having had few discussions.
	   Tai had claimed Prolintas had totally closed the service road
and this had forced students to go through Kampung Berembang, cross
Sungai Ampang and take Lorong Awan 14 in Kampung Kuala Ampang
before reaching the MRRII.
	   ``We have not closed the service road entirely and we will not
do so even after the bridge over Sungai Ampang is completed,'' she
said, adding that safety of the students using the service road
would be taken care of.
	   ``We will also have workers to facilitate our machinery to go in
and out of the area and ensure the safety of the students when
plying the road,''
	   she said.
	   To date, she said, the elevated highway construction at the
service road site had not been carried out in full swing but the
piling work was nearing completion.
	   The 7.4 km stretch from Sultan Ismail to Ampang, which is the
first phase of the elevated highway project, will be completed in
the middle of next year.
	   The second phase will begin in 2013.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
