<SLUG> BC-UN-US-Mexico,0340 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Top U.S. officials defend `Operation Casablanca'
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With UN-Drug Summit &QL; 
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The top U.S. drug policy official Monday
defended using U.S. undercover agents in a money-laundering sting
in Mexico but acknowledged ``there is room'' for other tactics in
the cross-border war on drugs.
	   Mexico has criticized the three-year ``Operation Casablanca'' as
a violation of its sovereignty. U.S. undercover agents appear to
have operated in Mexico without the government's approval of the
sting, which netted 160 indictments and the seizure of millions of
dollars and several tons of drugs.
	   Retired Gen. Barry McCaffrey defended the operation in a news
briefing with Attorney General Janet Reno during the U.N. General
Assembly special session on drugs.
	   Echoing many of the speakers Monday, McCaffrey said one country
cannot fight the drug problem alone.
	   ``We have to do this in partnership with our neighbors and with
absolute respect and deference for their own sovereign
institutions,'' said McCaffrey, director of the White House Office
of National Drug Control Policy.
	   He acknowledged, however, ``there is room here for us to look
through how we can even more effectively coordinate these
(operations) in the future.''
	   Reno pledged that the U.S.-Mexican effort to fight drugs was
still on course. ``In any investigation, there may be problems that
arise, but we always work through them,'' Reno said.
	   In his speech to the General Assembly earlier Monday, Mexican
President Ernesto Zedillo referred indirectly to the operation,
which has prompted Mexican officials to call for the extradition of
the U.S. agents to face trial.
	   He called for a ``balanced strategy ... so that no one can
become the judge of others; and no one feels entitled to violate
other countries' laws for the sake of enforcing its own.''
	   U.S. officials have said they needed to keep the operation
secret to ensure the safety of American agents. 	   
</TEXT>
