<BODY>
<SLUG> JOANNE'S-WACKY-WORLD sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Joanne's wacky world, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Joanne's wacky world, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Francis DassASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AS a stand-up comedienne, everything about Joanne Kam Poh Poh is
jolting when she's up on stage. For starters, the sight of her in
full costume, draped in an ``in-your-face'' attitude, will knock
anyone's socks off.
	   Then, there's the fact that she's big, brash, loud and
hilariously funny.
	   But like the rest of humanity, Kam is all these and much more, a
multi- dimensional character for the rather colourful times we live
in now.
	   While the rest of us can safely say that our first day at our
respective first jobs was unspectacular, she lays claim to slightly
more. Kam still remembers her first day at work clearly.
	   ``It was July 4, 1990,'' she gleefully recalls.
	   She had just joined the troupe of performers at Singapore's Haw
Par Villa, having been hired to entertain visitors there. And what
a riotous troupe it was with the likes of BiBi Kay Poh and Kumar in
it.
	   BiBi is now Kam's partner in crime on stage while Kumar is a
drag show personality from south of the border (Singapore), who
also happens to be famous up north in Penang in the club circuit.
	   ``I was a very naive Chinese girl from Johor with poodle hair,
black stockings, wearing a short skirt and pink chiffon blouse with
polka dots ... very the Ah Lian one,'' Kam recalls, grimacing at
the thought.
	   Ah Lian is, of course, the national term of ridicule describing
the village girl whose small town sensibilities make her the butt
of jokes in the city.
	   Born in Johor, she was living there at the time with her mum,
having just completed her Sijil Pelajaran Malaysia exams. At Haw
Par Villa, the Chinese theme park across the causeway, Kam
underwent training for three months before becoming a full-fledged
performer.
	   Kam remained there for two years and she acknowledges that the
place did a lot of good for her - the training, discipline and
exposure.
	   If on the first day she was scared and nervous about stepping
out onto the stage, today, the fear has subsided somewhat, although
she does admit that some butterflies still manage to break free and
create havoc in her stomach before that crucial first step, from
out of sight into the limelight.
	   But once she is on stage, ``Joanne the Showgirl'' takes over.
	   For those unfamiliar with Kam's performance, its content ranges
from fat jokes done in self-mockery and parody to sex organ jokes.
	   The words ``subtle'' and ``understated'' do not exist in her
vocabulary when onstage. And the audience that seeks her out,
revels in the grotesquery of her performances.
	   Needless to say, she was a hit when she was performing in KL's
former party central, the Boom Boom Room, for two years till 1995.
Since then, she has been performing on a freelance basis.
	   Kam, today, is an eight-year veteran of the local entertainment
business. As many would imagine, in person, off stage, Joanne is
much more subdued. She does not threaten people with her body or
bawdy jokes.
	   Instead, one will be confronted by a very animated person, with
a permanent smile plastered on her face and always bursting with
dramatics.
	   This is when her feet-firmly-on-the-ground side comes to the
fore.
	   ``I'm in transition now. I am now trying to groom a lot of
talent and would like to see more of my productions on stage,'' she
says.
	   She has always performed with a group of performers although
people usually think of her as being a solo artiste. Her troupe,
almost always comprising a trendy set of young dancers and an
assortment of talented transsexuals (more politely referred to as
divas in the club circuit), usually performs the opening number to
warm up the crowd for Kam and also takes to the stage when the
comedienne takes a breather or does a change of costume.
	   Since Kam and her dancers perform on a freelance basis nowadays,
correspondingly, she uses a lot of freelance dancers.
	   The entertainment circle in the country being small and mainly
concentrated in the capital, she says that it is easy to get in
touch with the dancers when a job comes their way.
	   There are 10 freelancers whom she uses regularly, but the number
varies depending on the nature of the show, the budget for it and
also the venue.
	   Like a business pro, she has memorised the good times when she
can capitalise on bookings.
	   ``There are peak and low seasons. The period from the end of the
year till the Chinese New Year - it's the time to try and cash in
on the demand for shows.
	   ``After Secretaries' Week in April, things will slow down. May,
June and July are the quiet months. August onwards, things start to
pick up again,''
	   she says, reading off a mental showbusiness chart.
	   During off-peak seasons, Joanne digs into her ``rainy day''
stash and travels a lot. Usually, it is to places like Bangkok,
Thailand and Australia where she has many friends.
	   She also goes to India but it's for a whole different reason,
one that very few people know about.
	   ``I go to India, to a place near Goa, for spiritual purposes...
to do some meditation. I'm into Tibetan Buddhism and have a teacher
in India, a Tibetan who was brought up in America.''
	   He is a guru, a friend and also a teacher to her.
	   ``I usually go up there to work out stress, take in the fresh
air, go mountain climbing and visit the holy places.
	   ``After working in this environment (the entertainment field),
there are so many things you have to deal with.''
	   Just as this sort of unwinding is spiritually and emotionally
important to her, so does her work on stage help audiences loosen
up in the evenings after a long, hard day at work.
	   Kam mines for material from her very self in order to do this.
She makes fun of her body. ``It is part of the itinerary. To get
people comfortable with me, I make fun of the obvious. Then, it is
easier for the rest of the jokes to follow,'' is her explanation. A
typical line during her show would be: ``Hey you... I saw you
staring at my watermelons! Yes, you in the green shirt with the big
smile on your face. Come up here!''
	   On her part, Kam is very fussy about her audience.
	   She strongly feels that clubgoers need to have the same
wavelength. Boom Boom Room, a trendy club, was an ideal place for
Kam. The trendiest of sets hung out there flanked by numerous
tourists who'd heard of the place and Kam's shows.
	   Kam currently wouldn't mind invitations to perform in clubs in
the capital.
	   ```I am open to the prospect of performing in a `permanent'
space in a club here. I would like to go back to the party scene in
KL but the venue will have to be appropriate,'' she says.
	   Seeing how the nightlife here badly needs a... err, life, having
her back in the circuit would definitely give KL's nightlife a
boost it desperately needs.
	   As a stand-up comedienne, Kam says that she still enjoys doing
it.
	   ``When I am up on stage, entertaining people, it gives me an
inner sense of achievement,'' she says.
	   Ladieeeess and gentleeeeemen, that's Joanne Kam for now.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:JOANNE'S-WACKY-WORLD sked; CT:w; 
