<HEADLINE>
Gabor's Mission Impossible, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Gabor's Mission Impossible, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Tourism Secretary Mina Gabor gets things done because she knows
what she is doing, and odds never seem to daunt her. Her crowning
achievement thus far is getting the majority of Bureau
International des Expositions (BIE) in Paris to vote for Quezon
City as site of the first Recognized World Expo in 2002. It was
pretty much mission impossible but the Philippines won over
Australia in an unprecedented second balloting.
	   Unknown to the public was the backbreaking preparation,
planning, and lobbying (country by country) over the past year that
went into the country's final bid. The QC Recognized Expo in 2002
will be the first ever, and in a developing country at that. It is
an international tribute to the Philippines. It elevates the
country to the big league of hosting world class expositions.
	   Launching Pad Evidently, the 2002 Expo in QC will provide the
Philippines an extraordinary launching pad to showcase its wares
and the capacity of its human resource to compete in the big
leagues. It will also establish a world class environment that will
compel Filipinos to thereafter perform accordingly.
	   
</TEXT>
