<SLUG> OMEGA'S-LICENCE-REVOKED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Omega's licence revoked on failure to restructure, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Omega's licence revoked on failure to restructure, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Securities Commission yesterday revoked the licence of Omega
Securities Sdn Bhd following its failure to come up with a
restructuring exercise by April 30, 1998.
	   Omega Securities ceased trading on May 4 for failing to meet the
minimum liquid funds requirement and was subsequently issued a show
cause letter on the same day on why its stockbroking licence should
not be suspended or revoked.
	   The decision not to grant written consent was due to the deficit
of RM555.59 million which Omega Securities failed to address.
	   The Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange, on the directives of the SC,
had informed the stockbroking firm on April 15 to undertake a
restructuring exercise in the form of a merger or acquisition
within a two-week period.
	   However, Omega Securities failed to comply with the directive.
	   The SC said Hwang DBS Sdn Bhd has agreed to participate in the
reimbursement of Omega Securities clients by undertaking to pay
them a total sum of RM70 million.
	   It (the scheme) will involve clients closing their accounts with
Omega Securities and Hwang DBS reimbursing each client a
pre-determined and pre- approved value for the net amounts owing to
them.
	   All clients are entitled to the full amount of their claims if
it is below RM100,000.
	   For those with claims of RM100,000 and above, they will be
reimbursed for their first RM100,000 in full, while reimbursements
for the excess of the claim will be pro-rated in decreasing
percentages.
	   If there is any sum remaining at all from the reimbursement
scheme it will be deposited in the Compensation Fund.
	   The reimbursement scheme was structured by SC to mitigate
potential losses which stockbroking company clients may suffer as a
result of mismanagement and violations of rules, regulations and
securities laws.
	   The scheme involves a willing stockbroking firm deemed fit by
the SC to reimburse clients of a stockbroking company whose licence
has been revoked.
	   By undertaking to implement the scheme, the firm will be allowed
to open a branch or branches depending on the amount it commits to
the scheme.
	   The scheme is only possible if there are third parties willing
to participate, otherwise clients will have to resort to the
Compensation Fund.
	   The KLSE will oversee the implementation of the scheme and will
be providing details of it in another announcement.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
