<HEADLINE>
SCANS institutes default proceedings against brokerage, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
SCANS institutes default proceedings against brokerage, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SECURITIES Clearing Automated Network Services Sdn Bhd has
instituted default proceedings against Halim Securities Sdn Bhd due
to its inability to meet its obligations as a Clearing Member.
	   In a statement yesterday, Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange said Halim
Securities' clearing and settlement privileges were revoked
effective 5pm on June 5.
	   KLSE's on-site team, in place at Halim Securities since the KLSE
took control, will together with other KLSE officials address
investors' concerns.
	   KLSE officials will be on hand to handle investors' enquiries on
June 8 from 9am to 5pm.
	   Meanwhile, clients of Halim Securities can continue to conduct
their normal CDS transactions while those who wish to trade can
transfer their shares to a CDS account with another stockbroking
company.
	   Representatives from KLSE's subsidiary, Malaysian Central
Depository Sdn Bhd, will be available to assist with the transfer
beginning Monday.
	   The KLSE will also waive the fee for ordinary transfers for
affected clients of Halim Securities.
	   ``Investors should note that shares held in CDS accounts are
fully protected as stockbroking companies act as authorised
depository agents of the principal which is MCD. Shares in the CDS
accounts are protected under the provisions of the Securities
Industry (Central Depositories) Act 1991.
	   ``All share transactions executed through the KLSE's automated
trading systems are protected by virtue of the rules of the
exchange requiring monies received by the stockbroking companies to
be paid into a trust account. Clients with margin accounts are
advised to refer to the terms of the Margin Facility Agreement
signed with Halim Securities.''
	   Where appropriate, an investor can make a claim from the KLSE's
compensation Fund against stockbroking companies.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
