<HEADLINE>
Nylex's engineering unit well-placed to weather slowdown, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Nylex's engineering unit well-placed to weather slowdown, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   LIKE most companies in times of an economic slowdown, Nylex
(Malaysia) Bhd is not spared the consequences and has seen its
profit margin eroding with the weakened ringgit for the first four
months of this year on the back of higher sales.
	   Furthermore, the rising bill for imported materials is only
partially recouped through modestly higher sales prices.
	   However, the company feels that prospects are promising,
especially for its engineering division as it banks on large orders
from overseas markets such as China, Hong Kong, and Australia.
	   Nylex has four main divisions; engineering, packaging, polymer
and building products.
	   The engineering division manufactures switchgears, and
electrical and electronic products.
	   Glass containers are produced by the packaging division and the
polymer unit produces films and coated fabrics, golf bags, sub-soil
drainage and rotomoulded products.
	   The building products unit manufactures glasswool insulation and
roofing products.
	   ``For the first four months of 1998, order bank and sales for
the group were higher than for the same period last year with good
performance achieved by all units in the engineering division,''
said Nylex chairman Graeme Charles Pearson.
	   ``However, due to the sharp depreciation of regional currencies
and the economic turmoil pervading the Southeast Asian region,
profitability of the group has been affected by increased material
costs, of which only a portion has been recovered from the market
through modest price increases.''
	   He told reporters this after Nylex's annual meeting in Petaling
Jaya yesterday.
	   Pearson said that steps to cut cost and attention to working
capital are bearing fruit, with a reduction in gearing to 29 per
cent for the year ended Dec 31, 1997.
	   He added that the company is aiming to further reduce its
gearing.
	   Nylex has traditionally operated within a gearing of 20-to-29
per cent of shareholders' funds.
	   For the year ended Dec 31, 1997, it recorded a group pre-tax
profit of RM69.89 million on a turnover of RM590.93 million. Total
shareholders' funds stood at RM440.48 million.
	   The company's borrowings totalled RM120 million at the end of
last year, comprising mainly short-term trade or working capital
type of borrowings.
	   Asked if there is a possibility of the company going into the
red, he said: ``Absolutely not. We are trading profitably and there
is no reason this will not continue.''
	   For the rest of the year, Nylex will develop products for
expansion into new markets especially in the Asia Pacific.
	   Currently, about 30 per cent of its turnover is derived from
exports.
	   This contribution is set to grow as the company positions itself
for larger export volume in order to benefit from increased
competitiveness brought on by the weakened ringgit.
	   As the company's strength lies with its operations in the Asia
Pacific, it will take steps to entrench its position in those
markets.
	   The engineering division will focus on China, the Middle East,
Singapore and Vietnam. For the roof tile business, the main markets
are Europe, Sri Lanka and the Indian Ocean islands.
	   Its insulation materials are mainly sold to Asean countries,
while glass containers are mainly exported to the Philippines and
Australia.
	   On the outlook for the domestic market, Pearson said it depended
on the type of product, but the group largely commanded a big share
of the markets it operated in.
	   It is currently the leader in the polymer and switchgear
businesses.
	   
</TEXT>
