<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Japan-Ihara, 1st Ld-Writethru,0326 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Coach delays decision on injury
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Monday practice in 3rd graf; SUBS last three
grafs to trim and ADD Akita comments.
 &UR; By YURI KAGEYAMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AIX-LES-BAINS, France (AP) _ Japan's coach says he may not
decide until the last minute whether to allow injured captain
Masami Ihara to play in the World Cup opener against Argentina.
	   On Monday, Ihara took part in a regular practice with his
teammates for the first time since hurting his right knee during
training last week. He ran about and kicked the ball lightly with
his teammates for 15 minutes. The rest of the practice was closed
to the media.
	   Ihara did not play in Japan's two warmup matches last week _ a
1-0 loss to Yugoslavia in Switzerland, and a 1-0 victory over
Gueugnon of the French second division on Sunday.
	   Coach Takeshi Okada said hopes were high that Ihara, one of
Asia's best defenders, will be ready for by June 14 for the
Argentina match in Toulouse.
	   ``If I decide at the last minute that he is not ready, I will
tell him,'' Okada said after Sunday's game. ``But I don't want to
pressure him by setting a date for that.''
	   The team canceled a jog scheduled for Monday morning to give the
players a rest.
	   Calm and soft-spoken, Ihara is the most experienced player on
Japan's World Cup squad. The 30-year-old defender has taken part in
more international A matches than any other Japanese player.
	   Midfielder Motohiro Yamaguchi has been captain in Ihara's place.
	   ``If he can't make it, I know I can do a good job,'' Yamaguchi
said.
	   Defender Yutaka Akita said the team is adjusting well to Ihara's
defense replacement, Toshihide Saito.
	   ``Of course, Ihara as the captain has a certain presence,''
Akita said. ``But Toshi is gaining experience, too, so there's no
problem.''
</TEXT>
