<HEADLINE>
Clean job expected in emptying of trash bins, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Clean job expected in emptying of trash bins, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Balan MosesASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   UNCOLLECTED rubbish, stinking to high heaven, can rile even the
calmest of people on the best of days.
	   Alam Flora Sdn Bhd, of course, is well aware of this. Its
experience in Kuala Lumpur has left it rich with knowledge on what
happens when collection schedules are not met.
	   But this writer feels it, nevertheless, necessary to repeat the
dire consequences of leaving garbage uncollected.
	   This will at least underline the importance of the task, being a
perpetual reminder to those charged with ensuring empty garbage
bins in areas currently served by several local authorities.
	   Come July 1, Alam Flora Sdn Bhd will assume, besides garbage
collection, other urban services like drain cleaning and grass
cutting in areas including Petaling Jaya, Kajang, Semenyih,
Beranang, Ulu Semenyih, Hulu Langat and Cheras.
	   The guardians of our garbage bins in Kuala Lumpur will take on
the task with the benefit of hindsight.
	   The numerous run-ins with residents, traders and sometimes
elected representatives will be of great help to the company as it
leaves the city centre for less developed areas.
	   Petaling Jaya may stand out from the rest of the new areas as it
is a developed area in its own right, sharing many similarities
with Kuala Lumpur.
	   But for the rest of the new areas, it will almost be a new ball
game for Alam Flora Sdn Bhd, given the peculiarities of garbage
collection and grass cutting and drain cleaning services in small
towns.
	   We are told that the company will be responsible for the
clearing of all illegal dumps, a major problem in the rural areas.
	   Illegal dumps have cropped up in Kuala Lumpur before, perhaps
not with the regularity of areas out of the city where supervision
is sometimes lax and civic-consciousness wanting. It is in this
context that Kuala Lumpur City Hall director-general Datuk Noordin
Razak's recent reminder to Alam Flora Sdn Bhd to improve services
in the outskirts of the city must be seen.
	   While unhappy with services provided by contractors hired by the
company in these areas, he qualified his statement by saying he was
satisfied with services provided in Kuala Lumpur.
	   Alam Flora Sdn Bhd's no-nonsense acting chief executive officer
Mohammed Siraj Abdul Razack should, therefore, keep all new
contractors coming into the fold on a tight rein.
	   It is quite natural for contractors away from the direct
scrutiny of headquarters to relax a little when it comes to the
job.
	   It is here that he and his officers have to draw the line. They
have to make it crystal clear that they will not tolerate any such
behaviour from the contractors.
	   The quality of service in both urban as well as less developed
areas has to be the same - the people will accept no less.
	   With a work force dedicated to specific tasks unlike the local
authorities which had to handle almost all urban services besides
development projects, Alam Flora Sdn most certainly has its work
cut out for it.
	   The company has scheduled training sessions for workers and
contractors later this month, surely a step in the right direction.
	   While teething problems may make their presence felt, they have
to be handled swiftly and efficiently. The public will expect this
as the company is no newcomer to the field.
	   In this respect, local authorities have to set up panels to
monitor urban services provided by Alam Flora Sdn's contractors.
	   The MPPJ is in the process of setting up a unit to monitor and
receive complaints on garbage disposal services, according to
council president Mohamad Nor Bador.
	   Other councils should follow suit in their best interest.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
