<BODY>
<SLUG> THEMED-GARDENS-GAMES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Themed gardens lure for Games, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Themed gardens lure for Games, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Sager AhmadASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE 16th Commonwealth Games to be held between Sept 11 and 21
will have an added attraction in the form of a 35ha International
Garden in Bukit Jalil.
	   The garden will have a boating pond, ornamental lake, picnic
site and a cascading waterfall as well as 28 international themed
gardens with 10 of them being ready for the games.
	   The international themed gardens include those depicting
English, Japanese, Iranian, Holland, Peruvian, Indonesian, Thai,
Canadian, Chinese and Malaysian gardens.
	   The RM30 million project is being undertaken by Seri Merga
Construction Sdn Bhd on a turnkey basis from the Kuala Lumpur City
Hall. Its deputy general manager Raffique Osman said about 40 per
cent of the work had been completed. It is expected to be ready by
October.
	   He said although contractually the company was not obliged to
complete the garden before the Games, it is going to oblige with a
request from City Hall to complete the portion facing the road and
Games village.
	   He said some 400 indigenous tree saplings will also be planted
in between the existing rubber trees. These will include saplings
of ciku (achras zapota), damar minyak (agathis dammara), buah keras
(aleurites moluccana) and kelempayang (anthocephalus chinensis).
	   Others include mata pelanduk (ardisia elliptica), terap
(artocarpus elasticus), sukun (artocarpus incisus), mambu
(azadirachta indica), berangan (castanopsis inermis), kapok (ceiba
pentandra) and pong pong (cerbera menghas).
	   Raffique said work on the cascading waterfall and other water
features will begin this week, including the fabrication of
elevated features while City Hall's Parks and Recreation section
assumed a supervisory role.
	   He said the company had to come up with concepts on how a
particular garden should look like and so far it had identified the
garden with an Islamic theme with a lot of water features, while
phoenix palms will take the place of date palm trees.
	   He said the company had sent someone to study gardens overseas
and it found the Malaysian garden at an international gerden in
Osaka was very disappointing as it did not project a Malaysian
identity at all.
	   ``We shall ensure that the Malaysian garden will have the
multi-racial nature of the people living here and other features
will include fragrant flowering plants,'' he said.
	   Datuk Bandar Tan Sri Kamaruzzaman Shariff said earlier more
areas in Kuala Lumpur will be turned into gardens under a Kuala
Lumpur City Hall plan to create a bigger green belt giving it a
``garden city'' look.
	   He had said a total of land area of 400ha in several areas
including Pudu Ulu, Taman Metropolitan Kepong, Taman Metropolitan
Jinjang Utara, Taman Manjalara and Tamam West Valley in Bukit Kiara
had been identified for the project.
	   He had also said City Hall was embarking on planting shady trees
and landscaping mining areas and rivers in the municipality, like
Sungai Kuyoh in Bukit Jalil, where the Commonwealth Games Village
is sited.
	   Kamaruzzaman has said the landscaping and beautification project
will include routes which were being used for the Games. A sum of
RM7 million has been allocated for landscaping projects.
	   City Hall's budget for landscaping and tree-planting activities
this year is RM3 million while that for cleaning, beautification
and upkeep of rivers is RM11 million.
	   
</TEXT>
