<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Romanians train together behind locked gates
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with evening practice. &QL; 
 &UR; By VIOREL URMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALBI, France (AP) _ Looking refreshed after a night's rest
following their trip from Bucharest, Romania's World Cup squad
trained twice Monday _ once behind closed doors and guarded by more
than a dozen uniformed French police.
	   With reporters climbing atop cars at a distance to look over a
concrete wall surrounding the field, the squad took part in a
90-minute workout _ their first since arriving Sunday.
	   Coach Anghel Iordanescu followed the training session with a
lengthy address to the team. The squad opens its World Cup schedule
June 15 against Colombia.
	   In late afternoon, the Romanians allowed the public and media
into their second training session, but made no statements to
reporters.
	   In a possible indication that Iordanescu is looking to take the
iniative against Colombia, the Romanian coach worked intensively
with playmaking midfielder Gheorghe Hagi of Turkish club
Galatasaray, striker Ilie Dumitrescu of Mexico's Atlante, Chelsea
wingback Dan Petrescu and midfielder Gheorghe Popescu, the team's
leading scorer in qualifying with eight goals.
	   However, one of the biggest problems for Iordanescu is defense,
where 23-year-old Cristian Dulca of Rapid Bucharest, who has only
five caps, seemed more likely to replace Atletico Madrid's Daniel
Prodan as the central marking defender. Prodan had surgery on his
right knee last month and is still recuperating.
	   Another problem for the Romanians is that they are short on
match practice. Iordanescu has complained that his squad was denied
a chance to attend a training camp in Switzerland and has faced
only lightly regarded opponents in friendly matches, the last
against Moldova last week.
	   ``The federation has repeatedly told me they do not have the
necessary funds,'' he said.
	   The Romanians instead had to be content with a training camp in
the Carpathian Alps, north of Bucharest.
</TEXT>
