w1630 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  A-MEANDERING-PLOT-ABOUTs     06-08 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> A-MEANDERING-PLOT-ABOUT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A meandering plot about nothing, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
A meandering plot about nothing, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Jeff LeeASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Chair is about how one event can change someone's life.
	   This monumental ``event'' concerns a retired septuagenarian
newspaper editor in a town in China. He uses his pension to buy a
simple yet elegant wooden chair from an antique shop.
	   The chair soon becomes his source of misery as it's mistaken for
a ``national treasure'' that was reported stolen from a museum. The
old man goes to great lengths to clear his name.
	   Viewers won't understand the hullabaloo over a chair, albeit a
national treasure. Although this is different from the usual
``stolen-property-puts- innocent-man-in-trouble'' story, The
Chair's meandering plot and leisurely pace make it a dud.
	   I was willing to overlook the controversy over the chair in the
hope that the movie would provide an insight into family, community
and cultural relationships in a China that's slowly opening up to
the world, but to no avail.
	   The most viewers can take from The Chair is that twentysomething
single women spend most of their time on exercise machines and
``hang out'' with their good-for-nothing boy-friends.
	   The old man is Gu Yifu (Bi Geng), who has his hands full with
the chair.
	   His daughter Millie (Jiang Li Fen) takes a dislike to the chair
and asks him to return it. But the store won't accept it. So Gu
goes all over town trying to offload it.
	   There's also been a break-in at a museum, and the police suspect
that the missing chair is in Gu's possession.
	   Everyone gets on Gu's case over the chair, and the old man can't
have a single moment of peace.
	   Millie's boyfriend Yang Cong (Ma Chuan) purports to want to help
Gu by secretly selling the chair to an antique dealer.
	   The deal, however, backfires when the chair is discovered as
being nothing more than ... a chair.
	   Yang's presence is hard to fit into the puzzle of The Chair. It
isn't certain what he does, and the movie at one stage dissolves
into grainy images of him performing in a music video.
	   Millie, too, is hard to categorise. When we're first introduced
to her, she's on one of those machines that supposedly pares down
the tummy. For the rest of the movie, she harangues her father to
get rid of the chair.
	   In one scene, Millie, wearing a vest, looks into the mirror and
examines her breast for lumps.
	   This may be what writer-director Zhang Tae Lin would like
viewers to think, and he gets no complains from me, but it comes
off as a gratuitous piece of titillation with no bearing on the
movie.
	   Bi does enough as the old man with too much time on his hand.
His character introduces us to the others. His role is passive as
he reacts to others' actions.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
