<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-US-Martinez-Latin Record,0774 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Martinez makes his pitch for Latin record
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PAUL NEWBERRY &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ATLANTA (AP) _ In this country, 243 is hardly a number that
stirs baseball passions like 56, 61 or 755.
	   In Latin America, though, it's big. Very big.
	   Dennis Martinez of the Atlanta Braves has equaled Juan Marichal
as the winningest Latin-born pitcher in baseball history, winning
his 243rd game last week with a 12-hit shutout at Milwaukee.
	   On Tuesday night, the 43-year-old Nicaraguan will go for No. 244
against the Boston Red Sox in an interleague game at Turner Field.
A thousand miles away, Nicaragua waits to unleash the sort of pride
it felt on that night in 1991 when he pitched a perfect game.
	   Viva, El Presidente!
	   ``We as a Spanish-speaking population see it a different way
than the American population,'' said Martinez, who is 243-189 in a
major league career that began in 1976 _ one year before Braves
teammate Andruw Jones was born. ``The people of Nicaragua feel the
most proud. Now they feel like, `Yeah, we are somebody. He put our
country on top now.'''
	   While Marichal led a wave of players from the Dominican Republic
to the majors leagues, Martinez is the only significant player to
emerge from Nicaragua. That makes him more determined to give the
Central American country a lasting spot in baseball history.
	   ``People will know where we're coming from, where we are,''
Martinez said. ``They can see us on the map and find out where
Nicaragua is. All that recognition will allow most people to know
where I come from. It's great.''
	   The significance of the record hasn't escaped Martinez's
teammates, especially those of Latin descent. When he finished the
record-tying victory against Milwaukee, Ozzie Guillen and Andres
Galarraga _ both natives of Venezuela _ were the first ones to
arrive at the mound with smiles and hugs.
	   ``There's probably not too many people making a lot out of what
he's doing right now, but for all the Latin players it means a
lot,'' Galarraga said. ``It's a lot of games, it's a lot of wins,
it's a lot of years. It's something really special for us.''
	   Marichal, who injured his head in a car wreck in April, has been
recuperating in the Dominican Republic. Elected to the Hall of Fame
in 1983, he had a 243-142 record and 2.89 ERA while pitching for 16
seasons, mostly with the San Francisco Giants. He worked in 471
games, winning 20 or more six times.
	   Martinez, pitching in his 21st season, needed 657 games to reach
243 wins. He has never won 20 games in a season and his career ERA
(3.68) is much higher than Marichal's, but the Nicaraguan has
managed double-figure wins 15 times _ the first in 1977, the most
recent in 1995.
	   The keywords for Martinez are consistency and durability.
	   ``He's unbelievable,'' Galarraga said. ``He's a good role model
for the young guys from any country in South America, or even the
United States. This guy, he works hard every day. He's running,
he's doing anything he can to stay in the big leagues. He is
something special, the way he works.''
	   They call Galarraga the Big Cat, but it's Martinez who has nine
lives. His career was in tatters after three straight seasons with
ERAs above 5.00 for the Baltimore Orioles in the first half of the
1980s, but he became one of the NL's top pitchers after a trade to
Montreal.
	   In May 1997, the end was at hand again when Martinez, bothered
by knee and elbow problems, was released by Seattle after going 1-5
with a 7.71 ERA. The right-hander sat out the rest of the season,
then earned a spot with the Braves during a spring training tryout.
	   Martinez was hit hard the first three weeks of the season, but
his ERA is 1.11 since April 24. Overall, he's 2-2 with a 3.86 ERA.
	   For the second time, he's filling in for John Smoltz in
baseball's best rotation. Martinez made two April starts with
Smoltz on the disabled list after offseason elbow surgery, then
returned to a starting role when Smoltz's elbow began bothering him
again two weeks ago.
	   When Smoltz comes back, it's back to the bullpen for Martinez,
who has made 14 relief appearances this season. His 43-year-old arm
has shown amazing resiliency in a variety of roles, which is only
appropriate for a pitcher who's made that the trademark of his
entire career.
	   ``I feel like a Hall of Famer, too,'' he said. ``You look at
yourself and start thinking about what you have done in this game,
what you have achieved. Luckily, I put some good numbers out
there.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Baseball-US-Martinez-Latin Record; CT:s; 
(REG:CRB;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
