<HEADLINE>
French drive to promote Val d'Oise, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
French drive to promote Val d'Oise, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Conseil General (General Council) responsible for the Val
d'Oise industrial area in France is on an aggressive drive to woo
foreign companies, including Malaysian ones, to set up base there.
	   Val d'Oise is situated some 20km from Paris.
	   Saying that there were five Malaysian companies mostly involved
in the manufacture of electronic components that had settled there
in the last three years, export manager attached to the council
Yves Gitton said the industrial area had the advantage of being a
transportation hub to the rest of Europe.
	   The area, which boasts the Roissy Charles de Gaulle airport as
well as a TGV train station, is expected to attract more companies
in the near future, as European integration draws near.
	   ``It is ideal for foreign companies that want to have a foothold
in Europe,'' Gitton told a Press conference at the Mines exhibition
centre in Sri Kembangan, Selangor, yesterday.
	   Some of the incentives offered are tax exemption for a minimum
of five years (depending on size and sector), lower social
contribution if the company employs the jobless, and a 25 per cent
discount on the price of land purchased from the conseil.
	   On its language barrier, Gitton said the French who have
traditionally identified strongly with their language were now
beginning to give more importance to the English language as a
result of the Internet.
	   Currently 450 foreign companies operate there with the bulk from
the US and Japan. Most are in the high-technology business.
	   
</TEXT>
