<HEADLINE>
Malaysian company to purchase MDF plant from China, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Malaysian company to purchase MDF plant from China, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   NEGOTIATIONS are underway for a Malaysian company to purchase
from Sichuan Donghua Machinery Works of China, a complete MDF
(medium-density fibreboard) plant to manufacture furniture.
	   The US$3 million (RM11.7 million) deal is pending as ``they (the
Malaysians) are hoping for a better exchange rate'', said Yang
Jinchun, general manager of CMIC International Exhibition Co Ltd.
	   CMIC was formed in 1980 specifically to coordinate economic and
technological co-operation between Chinese and foreign companies.
	   Yang was speaking at a Press conference during the five-day
International Machine Tool &AMP; Metalworking Exhibition (IMX) in Kuala
Lumpur yesterday.
	   He said the 10 participants from China were fewer this year
because of ``worries about the Malaysian economic condition''.
	   Last year, a total of US$300,000 was contracted on site by the
Chinese delegation which represented 20 companies.
	   Yang said for the last three years, a joint venture for
operating the complete plant for the manufacture of non-bake bricks
has been ongoing between China-East Resources Import &AMP; Export
Company and a Malaysian company.
	   The Chinese company had invested US$1 million in the project.
	   On how Chinese-made machinery can compete with other countries,
Yang said: ``The quality of Chinese-made machinery is comparable to
those made in Japan or other countries.
	   ``China is also near Malaysia in terms of physical distance,
culture and language, thus facilitating after-sales service.''
	   Since its establishment, CMIC had acquired more than 1,000
technological transfer projects for the mechanical and electrical
industries in China.
	   
</TEXT>
