<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-France, 1st Ld-Writethru,0491 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: French return, but Zidane's health for opener still
</HEADLINE>
questioned &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with French arriving, quote on Zidane health, PICKS UP
8th graf.
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CLAIREFONTAINE, France (AP) _ The World Cup must be close when
even the French are in the country.
	   After a four-day escape to Finland, the French team returned
Monday but with a certain amount of anxiety _ is their creative
genius, Zinedine Zidane, healthy?
	   After a difficult 1-0 victory over Finland on Friday, playmaker
Zidane has been struggling with a sore ankle, and reassuring
messages from the medical camp have hardly lifted the dark cloud
hanging over the team.
	   Zidane, with whom all French hopes of winning the World Cup rest
upon, had to be rested on Saturday and could only run for 10
minutes on Sunday because his right ankle still was bothersome.
	   Upon their return to France, team Dr. Jean-Marcel Ferret was
swamped with questions about the team's biggest star.
	   ``Yes, for sure, for sure,'' he will be able to start in the
opening match, Ferret said.
	   The Juventus Turin midfielder hopes to resume regular training
Tuesday, just three days before France's World Cup opener against
South Africa in his hometown of Marseille. Saudi Arabia and Denmark
complete Group C.
	   Ferret said Zidane was fighting through the worst pain a few
days after the injury.
	   ``I wouldn't worry too much,'' he said.
	   All through the weekend, coach Aime Jacquet criticized Friday's
referee that could have cost France its brightest star. Zidane was
tackled often and hard and Jacquet even considered pulling him off
the field to protect him.
	   ``It was a scandal,'' Jacquet said.
	   In case Zidane does not recover in time, his place would most
likely be taken by 24-year-old Robert Pires of Metz, the runner-up
in the French league.
	   Zidane's was the only injury for the French. Other difficulties
were tactical, centering on who would provide the French goals.
	   Jacquet had long promised that France would turn from a
defensive and conservative team into an ``audacious'' one for the
World Cup, but words have come easier than performances.
	   Captain Didier Deschamps knows that an overnight change is
tough.
	   ``We will never produce fireworks,'' he was quoted by the sports
daily L'Equipe. ``We cannot have a revolution in one week.''
	   On top of that, the French expect South Africa to do little else
than defend and hoping for a counterattack goal.
	   ``We won't fall for that trap,'' said Deschamps, arguing against
an all-out assault from the start.
	   The French team will stay for three days at its training camp in
the woods southwest of Paris before heading to Marseille on
Thursday for their Coupe du Monde debut.
	   ``The team is bubbling with impatience,'' Jacquet said.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-France, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:s; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
