<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Germany-Scrimmage,0445 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Germans squeak past young French side 2-1
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NESHA STARCEVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NICE, France (AP) _ One week before its opening match against
the United States, Germany did not look like a World Cup favorite
in struggling to a 2-1 victory over a selection of young French
second-division players Monday.
	   It was the final warmup game for the European champion before
its clash with the United States June 15 in Paris.
	   The Germans, who arrived in France Sunday, obviously did not
push hard but their defense was caught embarrassingly flat-footed a
few times.
	   Coach Berti Vogts used 17 players. Thomas Helmer was out with a
thigh injury, Christian Ziege because of fever and Andreas Moeller
because of a foot blister, while Christian Woerns and third
goalkeeper Jens Lehmann were spared.
	   Before the match, a minute of silence was observed for the
victims of last week's train disaster at Eschede, Germany.
	   Playing a professional but mostly junior selection of players
from second-division clubs Nice and Cannes, Germany used a starting
lineup that is not likely to take the field against the United
States.
	   The three-time World Cup champion started as follows: Andreas
Koepke, Juergen Kohler, Markus Babbel, Lothar Matthaeus, Stefan
Reuter, Jens Jeremies, Dietmar Hamann, Thomas Haessler, Michael
Tarnat, Ulf Kirsten, Olaf Marschall.
	   Marschall scored the only goal in the first half with a
long-range shot that was deflected by a French defender in the 32nd
minute.
	   While the Germans naturally dominated the game, their defense
was caught off guard several times by some clever French moves. The
Germans based their game on attacks down the wings with a lot of
crosses into the penalty area, something they have been doing a lot
in practice.
	   In the second half, Germany used the following lineup: Oliver
Kahn, Steffen Freund, Babbel, Olaf Thon, Joerg Heinrich, Jeremies,
Hamann, Haessler, Tarnat, Oliver Bierhoff and Juergen Klinsmann.
	   Bierhoff made it 2-0 in the 57th, slamming the ball home from
close range after good work on the right by Heinrich. Klinsmann
soon hit the bar, but then the French side scored a magnificent
goal. A through ball split the German defense, David Andreani
picked up the pass, danced around Kahn and put the ball under the
bar in the 69th.
	   Vogts used the game to practice several tactical moves. Thon
played a more offensive libero than Matthaeus in the first half and
the combination of Klinsmann and Bierhoff in attack looked sharp.
	   (ns/hjf)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-Germany-Scrimmage; CT:s; 
