<BODY>
<SLUG> WATER-SHORTAGE-CAUSES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Water shortage causes FTZ factories to lose millions, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Water shortage causes FTZ factories to lose millions, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Trina Thomas RajASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FACTORIES in the Hulu Klang Free Trade Zone which are hard hit
by the water crisis in the Klang Valley have been forced to cut
their production by as much as 50 per cent, forcing them to suffer
losses running into millions of ringgit.
	   If the lost business and other opportunity costs are taken into
consideration, the water fiasco may have cost the country billions
of ringgit in export earnings.
	   Major factory operators in the FTZ who have been complaining to
the Ministry of International Trade and Industry are reported to
have issued an ultimatum at a meeting on Wednesday.
	   They cannot go on suffering losses especially when water supply
is still uncertain. The companies, as investors in the country,
hoped MITI will be able to highlight their plight.
	   Some have even allocated money to increase their water storage
capacity.
	   Harris Semi-Conductor (M) Sdn Bhd had to reduce 30 per cent of
its production due to water shortage while SEH Malaysia Sdn Bhd,
one of the world's largest manufacturers of silicon wafers, had
previously stated that it had to reduce production by almost 50 per
cent.
	   Harris Semi-Conductor, which prides itself in its ``On Time
Delivery''
	   programme, had to delay some of its deliveries, thus ending up
paying penalty fees to its customer, a source said.
	   ``Apart from that, the company has been receiving complaints
from its customers about the poor delivery. Deliveries have been
delayed for a day or two and, in some cases, it had to cancel
deliveries.''
	   It is believed that Harris Semi-Conductor has incurred a total
loss of between RM15 million and RM18 million for the past nine
months due to the water shortage.
	   For production SEH, which claims to be Klang Valley's single
largest user of water, previously used between 9,000 and 10,000
cubic metres of water for a full-day operation.
	   Since the water shortage hit Selangor and Kuala Lumpur, water
supply to the companies has been inconsistent.
	   ``Due to the poor transparency and planning in supplying or
rationing water, Harris Semi-Conductor, which has invested nearly
RM600 million in the country for the past 24 years, has to suffer
significant losses.''
	   Harris Semi-Conductor has to date allocated RM300,000 for the
construction of three wells. Currently, its contractor has
completed a 630-feet well.
	   The three wells are expected to provide the company with at
least 68.10 cubic metres of water.
	   However, Harris Semi-Conductor has to analyse the water content
before the company can use it for the production of
semi-conductors.
	   Another company hard hit is Texas Instruments (M) Sdn Bhd. To
date it has spent RM2 million to increase its water storage
capacity.
	   ``The money was used to build new wells and purchase water
recycling equipment,'' managing director James Lamn said.
	   ``We purchased water recycling equipment in order to reduce our
consumption. We recycle the water used for manufacturing.
	   ``Apart from that, we have also dug more wells. If our stored
water runs out, we will use the well water,'' he said, adding that
the measures taken do not increase the company's storage capacity
but helps reduce its water consumption.
	   On the current water situation, he said: ``For the past two
months, water was supplied every other day. However, our taps have
been dry for the last five days. If the situation persists, Texas
will be in jeopardy.''
	   The company, which has been in Malaysia for 25 years, needs 4.54
litres of water per minute.
	   
</TEXT>
