<BODY>
<SLUG> CAMELOT-SURE-TO-TICKLE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`Camelot' sure to tickle the young, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Camelot' sure to tickle the young, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Francis DassASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CUTE characters - check! Humour - check! Plot - err, raincheck.
Memorable songs - nyet! Voice - oh dear! Like this checklist, the
formulaic animated film from Warner Bros. has its moments and loses
them, both with equal ease.
	   Quest For Camelot tells the tale of litle Kayley, the daughter
of Sir Lionel who is one of King Arthur's knights.
	   Kayley gets embroiled in the search for the King's magic sword,
Excalibur, after Lionel is killed during an attempt on the King's
life by the evil Ruber and the sword is stolen by a griffin.
	   For adults, the story is pretty ho hum and the action picks up
only after Kayley enters the forbidden forest when the two-headed
dragon, Devon and Cornwall, comes into the picture.
	   Up to this point, the humour is weakly sustained by Bladebeak,
an amorous... err, male chicken who is... err, henpecked by his
missus! When Devon and Corn-wall come into play, the humour gets
distinctly wicked and hilarious. Campy even.
	   The gem of jokes comes from this duo when they sing that they
are one of the reasons why cousins shouldn't marry.
	   The hero, Garrett, is a strange one. Being blind, he is a total
departure from the physically perfect leading men we normally see
in animations, with the possible exception of Disney's Hunchback of
Notre Dame.
	   At the risk of being petty, it must be said that some of the
plot developments are improbable - like how Garret is blinded or
how Lionel is killed.
	   Hey, these are things that are only supposed to happen in real
life, in a cartoon, the audience would surely like to forget such
things and have a good time, right?
	   And also, some intriguing characters are on for too brief a
period, especially the rock ogre and the magician Merlin.
	   It's like eating a teensy weensy bit of a delicious chocolate
cake on an empty stomach. You want more.
	   VERDICT: Regardless of whatever grouchy and jaded reviewers say,
for kids this animated feature should be a nice distraction. Devon
and Cornwall are sure to provide them with endless laughter in the
cinema hall.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:CAMELOT-SURE-TO-TICKLE sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
