<SLUG> BC-Russia-Embezzlement </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Siberian mayor to stand trial for embezzlement, tax fraud
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The mayor of a small Siberian city will stand
trial for tax fraud and embezzlement, the ITAR-Tass news agency
said Monday.
	   The charges against Gennday Konyakhin relate to his work as a
businessman before he became mayor of Leninsk-Kuznetsky, the news
agency said, quoting local prosecutors.
	   Konyakhin as been in custody since his arrest in October 1997.
	   Prosecutors on Monday charged him with causing 800,000 rubles
(dlrs 131,000) worth of damages to the state, including
misappropriation of 235,000 rubles (about 38,500 dollars) of budget
funds and 55,000 rubles tax fraud (dlrs 9,000) in tax fraud
resulting from improper registration of automobiles.
	   Konyakhin was elected in the spring of 1997 and became known
nationwide after the influential newspaper Izvestia accused him of
being linked to the mob.
	   President Boris Yeltsin threw his weight behind the newspaper
story, calling for a thorough investigation of Konyakhin's
activities and saying the case exemplified the growing criminal
infiltration of officialdom.
	   (ls) 	   
</TEXT>
