<SLUG> INTERNET-FRAUD sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Internet fraud: `Two students were caught red-handed', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Internet fraud: `Two students were caught red-handed', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   P. Selvarani in LondonASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   TWO of the four Malaysian students charged with conspiracy to
commit fraud via the Internet at the Stoke-on-Trent magistrate's
court on Thursday were believed to have been caught red-handed by
Staffordshire police.
	   It is learnt that police detained Khairul Anuar Ariffin, 28, and
Norlie Mohamad Shah, 23, following a tip-off.
	   The two were in the midst of processing a credit card
transaction via the Internet at a house in Shelton, Stoke-on-Trent,
about 240km from London.
	   Sources said the police were alerted by a bank about the
transaction and managed to trace the address in Shelton.
	   It is learnt that the other two students, Shafik Rizal Shaaban,
23, and Riza Musauwir, 22, were roped in to fence the goods.
	   The group is believed to have been operating since January and
had made purchases worth about STG6,000 (RM39,000).
	   Khairul Anuar, a private computer science student at the
University of Staffordshire, is believed to have master-minded the
transactions.
	   The four were remanded for seven days under the custody of the
Staffordshire police for conspiracy to defraud a number of
companies.
	   Norlie, a computer science student at the University of
Liverpool, is a Public Services Department scholar.
	   Shafik Rizal, a Mara scholar and Riza, a Yayasan Perak scholar,
are also students of the University of Staffordshire.
	   Meanwhile, Malaysian Students Department director Abdul Rahim
Mohamad said its warden in Birmingham had been visiting the
students at the police lock-up to check on their welfare.
	   ``We have submitted a report on the incident to the Education
Ministry in Kuala Lumpur and the parents of the students are being
kept informed of the latest developments.''
	   Two local lawyers have been assigned to provide legal aid to the
students.
	   The four are expected to be brought to court again early next
week.
	   In Kuala Lumpur, Mara said it would wait for a complete report
on the arrests.
	   ``The information available to us is based only on media
reports,'' Deputy Entrepreneur Development Minister Datuk Idris
Jusoh said today.
	   ``We will liaise with the Malaysian Students Department and our
High Commission there to obtain a clear picture,'' he added.
	   Idris was asked whether Mara would revoke the financial aid
provided for its sponsored student following the incident.
	   ``We will wait for a complete report and the Minister will
decide accordingly,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
