<HEADLINE>
Policemen claim trial to two counts of graft, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Policemen claim trial to two counts of graft, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SEREMBAN, Fri. - A police lance corporal and constable claimed
trial in the Sessions Court today to two separate charges under the
Anti-Corruption Act 1997.
	   Lance Corporal Nordin Abd Rauf, 51, and constable R.
Nuthukrshnan, 41, from the Seremban district police station face a
charge of accepting 200,000 rupiah (RM82) from Mustangin Kasmidi
and RM40 from Suryani  &LR;  Supriadi Juli for not taking action againt
Suryani for offences under the Road Transport Act 1987.
	   Suryani is alleged to have been riding a motorcycle without a
licence and road tax.
	   The accused are alleged to have committed the offence on Jan 1,
1998 about 10pm at an unnumbered house in Taman Pinang Gading.
	   They face a second charge of accepting RM300 from Mustangin
Kasmidi at the same place on Jan 25, 1998 about 8.20pm.
	   They are charged under Section 11(A) of the Anti-Corruption Act
1997.
	   The offence carries a maximum jail term of 20 years and a fine
of not less than five times the amount received or RM10,000,
whichever is higher.
	   Prosecuting officer Ramle Muhamood from the Anti-Corruption
Agency prosecuted before judge Supiah Meon.
	   Supiah later allowed bail of RM3,000 each and fixed June 30 and
July 1 for the hearing.
	   Ramle also asked the court for the case to be given priority as
the work permits for the foreigners who were witnesses to the case
would expire in September.
	   
</TEXT>
