<SLUG> BC-Britain-Castle Award </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Windsor Castle fire renovation shares design award with American
</HEADLINE>
Air Museum &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Windsor Castle's renovation following a
devastating fire shared a top design award Monday with the American
Air Museum near Cambridge.
	   Restoration of the castle's badly damage octagonal lobby and the
museum's futuristic half-dome were joint winners of the Building of
the Year Award 1998, sponsored by the Royal Fine Art Commission and
British Sky Broadcasting.
	   The fire at Windsor Castle in November 1992 gutted the octagonal
lobby, which was once a private chapel. As part of the 37 million
pound (dlrs 60 million) restoration, it was remodeled into an
anteroom with a roof reminiscent of a timber umbrella with eight
oak columns supporting a fan of 25 curving ribs.
	   The room was designed by the Sidell Gibson Partnership as part
of the restoration by Donald Insall Associates. The air museum's
design work was by Foster and Partners.
	   A panel of judges chaired by Lord St. John of Fawsley chose the
winners and the awards were presented at a luncheon at the Savoy
Hotel.
	   (eml)
</TEXT>
