<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Drugs-EU,0246 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With UN-Drug Summit
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Britain's Prescott calls for improving social conditions &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Combatting the drug problem requires
comprehensive programs which include education, treatment and
rehabilitation, Britain's deputy prime minister told the opening
session of the U.N. drug summit Monday.
	   But deputy Prime Minister John Prescott also said the answer
does not lie entirely in reducing demand in the major drug-consumer
countries.
	   ``It is no good hoping to eliminate the demand for drugs without
tackling the supply,'' he said.
	   Speaking for the European Union, Prescott said Britain and other
European states ``have learned that tackling drugs successfully
means looking at the whole range of social problems, covering
housing, unemployment, poverty, crime and family life.''
	   ``Education, prevention, rehabilitation and treatment must be
part of any program,'' he added. ``To coin a phrase, we need to be
tough on drugs crime and tough on the causes of drugs crime.''
	   He said the goal was not simply to eradicate crime ``but to also
give people a fresh chance.''
	   He acknowledged that rich countries such as Britain must do more
to reduce demand -- a major argument of Latin American leaders
whose nations account for much of the world's supply.
	   But he said those efforts will not succeed without programs to
convince farmers to abandon illicit crops and help them make the
transition to legal cultivation. 	   
</TEXT>
