<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-Serbs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Moderate Bosnian Serbs to run together in September elections
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANJA LUKA, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ In a move aimed at
consolidating moderate Serbs' influence in Bosnia, three reformist
Bosnian Serb parties said Monday they would join forces to win key
posts in September elections.
	   The three parties, with Western support, already dominate the
government of the Serb-controlled half of Bosnia _ the Serb
Republic.
	   They said the new alliance, which is expected to win formal
approval soon from their party boards, is intended to jointly
secure them three top positions: the republic's presidency and two
posts reserved for Serbs in Bosnia's joint presidency and
government.
	   The Serb National Alliance, Socialist Party and Independent
Social Democrats are expected to agree on a joint slate of three
candidates for the posts, with each party contributing one. The
leader of the Serb National Alliance, Biljana Plavsic, is thought
likely to be the consensus choice for Serb Republic president, a
post she already holds.
	   If successful, the alliance could unseat two key Bosnian Serb
hardliners: Momcilo Krajisnik, who holds the Serb seat in the
three-man Bosnian presidency, and Boro Bosic, who is a co-chairman
in Bosnia's joint government.
	   The parties said they will run independently in the Serb
Republic's parliamentary elections, also to be held in September.
	   (str/ms/dc)
</TEXT>
