<HEADLINE>
Killers may have moved bodies for dumping, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Killers may have moved bodies for dumping, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Gerald Raja; Hamidah AtanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALACCA, Fri. - Two Singaporeans, arrested in connection with
the murder of two men whose bodies were found in a car at a police
roadblock in Pahang on Tuesday, may have been looking for a place
to dump them.
	   Initial police investigations indicate the possibility that the
foreigners had travelled about 300km from Malacca to Kuantan to
dispose the bodies of Chai Cheon Keat  &LR;  Peter, and a Singaporean,
both 30.
	   One of the victims who had a stab wound in the chest and wrapped
in a blanket, was found in the boot of the vehicle while the other,
believed to have been strangled, was found in its rear seat.
	   When the two Singaporeans arrived at a police roadlblock at the
100km Kuantan-Segamat highway, Pahang police arrested the duo after
finding the bodies in the white Toyota Corrolla bearing
registration number MAF 433 about 3.30pm.
	   It is understood that this morning, police took the two
Singaporeans to a stretch of road to retrieve an assortment of
documents which they were believed to have dumped while heading
towards Pahang on Tuesday.
	   The New Straits Times learnt today that police suspect that Chai
and the foreigner were killed at a house in Taman Cheng Perdana in
Malacca when a business transaction reportedly involving a group of
Singaporean businessmen, failed.
	   It is believed that a meat cutter and a rope, believed to have
been used in the killings, were found in the house.
	   Chai was the manager of Syarikat Latem Metal Industry Sdn Bhd
based in Malacca while the foreigner who police declined to
identify, was one of its directors.
	   Police believe that following the killings, the bodies were
taken in a car driven by the two Singaporeans for disposal when the
vehicle was stopped at the roadblock near the junction of Bandar
Muadzam Shah.
	   Malacca police chief Senior Assistant Commissioner I Arthur
Edmonds said today that apart from the probability that the bodies
were taken to Pahang for disposal, police were looking into other
leads as well.
	   A new court order has beeen obtained to remand the two
Singaporeans for 14 days.
	   ``We are also working closely with the Interpol branch of the
Federal police headquarters in Bukit Aman and the Singapore police
to assist us in the probe,'' added Edmonds.
	   
</TEXT>
