<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Au Pair </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fired lawyer accuses Woodward mother of submitting phony bill
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Dan Sharp, husband of the lawyer fired by Louise
Woodward, on Monday accused the mother of the British former au
pair of submitting a forged bill for accommodation to a fund for
her defense, Sky TV reported.
	   Sharp, whose British-born wife, Elaine Whitfield Sharp, was
fired by Woodward last week, said a dlrs 15,400 (9,131.50 pound)
bill purportedly for four months accommodation for Sue Woodward at
the Sharp home was phony.
	   ``It is a forgery, and I would note a poor one at that,'' Sharp
said, shown on Sky examining the bill at his home in Marblehead,
Mass., near Boston.
	   ``I don't believe we ever charged her (Sue Woodward) a dime for
anything, but we certainly never charged her dlrs 15,400 for
anything,'' added Sharp.
	   The bill showed charges for accommodating Mrs. Woodward last
year during her daughter's trial in the death of an 8-month-old
baby in the young Briton's care.
	   A jury convicted Louise Woodward last fall of second degree
murder of Matthew Eappen. A judge reduced the verdict to
manslaughter and sentenced her to the 279 days she had served in
prison since her arrest. She has to stay in Massachusetts while
defense lawyers and prosecutors appeal the verdict.
	   Sky TV said it obtained the accommodation bill from a vicar, the
Rev. Ken Davey, a vicar who runs the Woodward appeal fund in her
home village, Elton, in Cheshire, England.
	   Davey has said the fundwas at dlrs 400,000 (245,000 pounds) in
December, but dropped to about dlrs 80,000 (50,000 pounds) after
paying for the appeal.
	   Sky said lawyers for the Susan Woodward denied the bill was a
fake, and agreed that the amount shown on the bill had been paid to
the Woodward parents in January.
	   Ms. Whitfield Sharp was fired last week after allegedly telling
a trooper who arrested her for drunken driving May 22 that she now
believes Louise Woodward, now 20, is guilty and is having ``a hard
time handling it.'' She denied making the remark.
	   Sky said it spoke to Dan Sharp, also a lawyer, because Ms.
Whitfield Sharp has been advised not to talk to the media. She was
shown in background during the news item examining pictures of the
dead baby's brain.
	   Asked how he could prove the accommodation bill was phony, Dan
Sharp said that, for example, the name ``Elaine Whitfield-Sharp''
was printed on the front, and his wife never used a hyphen in her
name.
	   He said the handwriting on the bill, which was on the Sharps'
office letterhead, was the same as that on a note to his wife that
Susan Woodward had enclosed with a gift.
	   The charges marked the latest step in soured relations between
Louise Woodward and the lawyer who was once a key supporter.
	   A London tabloid, The Mirror, last week reported that Ms.
Whitfield Sharp had said in a taped phone conversation that Louise
Woodward lied to her and negotiated secret book and newspaper deals
about the highly publicized case.
	   Louise Woodward moved out of Ms. Whitfield Sharp's home two
months ago, her lawyers say.
	   (mj)
</TEXT>
