<BODY>
<SLUG> WITTY-LOOK-AT-BUSKERS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Witty look at buskers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Witty look at buskers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Zainal Alam KadirASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   OMAR Ahmad, Jamaluddin Rashid and Romainun Zakaria are not big
names. They are not even as glamorous as Ogy Ahmad Daud, Erma
Fatima or Raja Azura.
	   In fact, you may not have heard of Omar, Jamaluddin and
Romainun.
	   That, however, should not deter you from catching Kena Main, the
play they are involved in, that is now showing at Matic in Jalan
Ampang, Kuala Lumpur.
	   The play, written by Khalid Salleh and presented by the Society
of the Blind Malaysia, is about the blind, and since the three are
visually- impaired, you can probably imagine the rest. Really, Kena
Main, which made its debut more than five years ago (and has been
staged by different parties several times) offers a good laugh and
a big dose of humility.
	   It delves into the lives of the visually-impaired, particularly
four people who make their money busking by the roadside and
shopping complexes.
	   Kena Main, in a light-hearted way, shows us life from a
different perspective. The play hinges on their dreams, aspirations
and motivation, which are not really that different from what the
rest of us have.
	   Kena Main also touches on exploitation and under-estimation,
while highlighting that certain ``human spirit'' each of us
possesses.
	   It cautions us about the danger of being too protective about
those whom we think are ``helpless'', while reminding us about
respect (and self- respect).
	   Rest assured, however, that the play does not have that
condescending tone, as shown during its Press preview last
Wednesday.
	   Having ``real people'' playing the roles does have its
advantages. The three unknowns, Omar, Jamaluddin and Romainun, fit
the characters so well.
	   And since the script is well-written, they did not seem to have
that much problem ``fitting in''.
	   In fact, the three simply upstaged everyone, with all the right
timing and clever ad-libbings at all the important junctures.
	   Romainun gave that ``sensitive and cute'' touch to Mona, the
timid blind girl who runs away from home to escape her family who
has been making her feel ``useless and hopeless''.
	   Jamaluddin, on the other hand, triumphed through his
interpretation of the Mr Knowall (with little up there), Daud, a
bongo player who seeks the attention of Mona, who plays the
tambourine in his blind busking troupe.
	   The most juicy character, the street-wise and pragmatic Pie, is
played by Omar brilliantly. During the preview, Omar also ``saved''
the show with his wit several times when there were slight
technical hitches. Khalid, who also directs, is a good anchor to
all the characters in the play, while the other non-blind actor who
shone was Mohamed Rodi Mohamed Nor who played the sly drug-addict
to a T.
	   Other ``incidental'' cast members include Safian Arshad (Jamil)
and Ambang Klasik singer Alina Hassan (Laila).
	   Of course one would wish for a tighter presentation, but when
you have a high level of humour, why complain?
	   
</TEXT>
