<HEADLINE>
Guidelines on sale of Felda land for redevelopment, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Guidelines on sale of Felda land for redevelopment, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Patvinder SinghASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri - The National Land Council has decided on
guidelines on the sale of Felda land for redevelopment in a bid to
ensure that the interests of both Felda settlers and developers are
protected.
	   Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim said today these
guidelines were important to ensure the price paid for Felda
settlers' land was fair and in tandem with prevailing market
prices.
	   He said among other measures adopted by the council was to have
two- thirds of the settlers' agreement before any approval was
given to sell the land for redevelopment.
	   Settlers will also be discouraged from giving power of attorney
to developers who can use it to the settlers' detriment.
	   Anwar said this after chairing the council's 54th meeting at
Wisma Tanah here.
	   ``I feel this is important as in the past concerns have been
raised about efforts made by developers to coax Felda settlers to
sell their land at very low prices,'' he said.
	   Anwar also said problem would arise when some settlers in a
Felda scheme sold their land while others did not as the developer
only got part of the land required to complete his development.
	   He said the Land and Co-operative Development Ministry would
distribute the guidelines to all Felda settlers to ensure they did
not fall victim to unscrupulous developers.
	   Asked about the position of Malay reserve land, Anwar said the
land and its importance would continue to be defended in line with
the country's Constitution.
	   He said to acquire and replace a piece of Malay reserve land
with an area of the same size but of lower value was unreasonable,
especially in the case of land taken in strategic parts of cities.
	   ``This will adversely affect the Malay ownership of land. The
matter is being studied so that the procedures and regulations are
strengthened.''
	   Anwar said the council stressed the importance of early approval
of State land for agricultural purposes and had received progress
reports from State Governments.
	   ``The level of approvals has been encouraging and the States are
giving their full co-operation to ensure land is developed for
agriculture. We hope the whole machinery is put in motion to reduce
food imports.''
	   
</TEXT>
