<SLUG> LAW-OF-NEGLIGENCE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People `lack awareness on law of negligence', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
People `lack awareness on law of negligence', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - Malaysians generally have a low awareness
of matters relating to the law on negligence, which explains the
high rate of road crashes due to carelessness on the part of
motorists.
	   The Chief Justice of the Federal Court, Tun Mohd Eusoff Chin
said this was why the insurance premium for motor vehicles was high
as claims relating to crashes due to negligence ran into millions
yearly.
	   ``About 60 per cent of cases in the civil and magistrate's
courts involve such accidents,'' he said after launching a book
titled Nathan on Negligence today.
	   The author, High Court of Malaya judge Datuk R.K. Nathan, said
there was a need to instil public awareness on negligence law as it
could help reduce traffic accidents, careless driving and even road
rage cases.
	   He said negligence law was about the right of the victims of
negligence cases to get the right compensation, a factor that would
make people more careful in what they did as they become aware of
the claims related to accidents.
	   For example, Nathan said, people would get vehicle insurance if
they have a basic understanding of negligence law as they would
realise in the event of an accident, they would be liable to
charges of negligence and costly lawsuits.
	   In other words, negligence law could become a deterrent that
could stop people from wrongdoing not just in traffic related
cases, but also in professional fields like accountancy and
medicine.
	   The 400-page book, published by the Malaysian Law Journal Sdn
Bhd, was aimed at lawyers dealing in negligence cases.
	   Eusoff described it as an authoritative text that would serve
practitioners, law lecturers and students alike.
	   MLJ editor Zahid Taib described it as a complete source of
reference on Malaysian negligence law.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
