<SLUG> PROMOTING-MALAYSIA-IN-US sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`Promoting Malaysia in US costly', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Promoting Malaysia in US costly', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - The cost of promoting Malaysia as a tourist
destination in the United States has shot up by 15 per cent since
the currency devaluation.
	   Culture, Arts and Tourism Minister Datuk Sabbaruddin Chik said
today the cost of putting up billboards and the likes in major
cities in the US like New York, was much more expensive now.
	   However, although the Ministry had to cut down on expenditure,
the budget for promoting tourism overseas would not be affected, he
said.
	   ``Last year between RM40 million and RM50 million was allocated
for promotional efforts.
	   ``We will be spending that same amount this year and next
year,'' he said after meeting with officials from the Kuala Lumpur
and Selangor Chinese Chamber of Commerce and Industry which are
organising the forthcoming ``Love Malaysia Consumer Fair 1998''.
	   Sabbaruddin said a balance had to be struck between expenditure
cuts and promoting the country overseas which was crucial now.
	   This was so, he said, because tourists from countries using
dollars and sterling pounds found Malaysia a cheap holiday
destination.
	   He said there was a 13 per cent drop in tourist arrivals in 1997
compared to 1996.
	   ``Last year there were 6.2 million tourist arrivals bringing in
RM10.5 billion in tourist receipts compared to 7.1 million tourist
arrivals and RM11.2 billion earned in revenue in 1996,'' he said.
	   Sabbaruddin said there was a marked decrease in the number of
tourists from the top five countries visiting Malaysia every year.
	   On the consumer fair, Sabarruddin said those from the travel
industry promoting their services at the fair should only be
allowed to promote local destinations.
	   Organising chairman Mew Jin Seng said so far the fair had
attracted 320 participants.
	   
</TEXT>
