<HEADER>
w1692 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  PAS'-POLICY-THREATENSske     06-08 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> PAS'-POLICY-THREATENS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pas' policy threatens Malay culture, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Pas' policy threatens Malay culture, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Farish A. NoorASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED I Pas's domestic cultural policy seems to be driven by a
narrow and exclusivist conception of Malay culture which is shaped
by its own ideological slant. In its claim to represent what it
thinks is the ``true''
	   nature of Malay-Islamic identity, the party has single-handedly
drawn back the cultural and historical boundaries of the Malay
world by hundreds of years.
	   Its condemnation of traditional Malay arts such as Mak Yong and
Wayang Kulit was motivated mainly by a paranoid fear that these art
forms might still be able to beguile and mesmerise ordinary Malays
and turn them back into superstitious pagans and idol-worshippers.
Presumably, Pas would have us believe that any Malay who watches a
Wayang Kulit performance would immediately proceed to the nearest
bomoh and order a magic spell or two, or perhaps stop and worship
the first rock or tree he comes across.
	   In this respect, at least the ideologues of Pas seem to share a
common view with the famous Islamophobe V.S. Naipaul, that the
Malays are essentially a backward and primitive people who are
prone to such neurotic fits all the time.
	   Linked to this is Pas's own over-heated rhetoric of
``purifying'' Islam of all un-Islamic elements which has now turned
into a witch-hunt against all those who continue to cherish the
cosmopolitan and universal elements which make up the diverse and
complex structure of Malay culture and civilisation. Not only does
Pas see fit to condemn performances like Wayang Kulit and Mak Yong
as ``un-Islamic'', it also seems to be suggesting that those who
enjoy such performances are bordering on apostasy as well.
	   The net effect of the campaign to demonise traditional forms of
art and culture, however, is the narrowing of the cultural
frontiers of the Malay world. It leads to a situation where the
only acceptable history and culture of the Malays is that which has
been officially cleared by the ideologues of Pas.
	   Lest it be forgotten, we need to remind ourselves that Malay
history extends backwards for more than a millennium and that the
pre-Islamic elements that existed in the Malay world are as much a
part of Malay identity as the Islamic ones. Our ancient fables,
hikayats, syairs and pantuns are replete with examples of different
cultural influences from practically every part of the world: from
China to India, Persia to Europe.
	   Many of these ideas, concepts and forms were retained even after
the coming of Islam to the Malay world. (Which ranks as one of the
most amazing events in world history considering the manner in
which Islam managed to penetrate into the Malay archipelago with
such ease).
	   Furthermore, much of what has come to us from the Islamic world
is also a result of the interaction between cultures and
civilisations. The Malay- Islamic Hikayat Iskandar D'zulkarnain,
for instance, is fundamentally a Malay version of a Persian epic
which is based on the life of the Macedonian conqueror Alexander
the Great (who, in the Malay version, travelled to the East and
whose descendants decided to buy some real estate in Minangkabau,
Sumatra, and sow the seeds of every royal family in Malaysia
today).
	   These elements remained part and parcel of the Malay identity up
to the beginning of the 20th century: they made up the basic
components of Malay folk tradition and assumed the status of
hallmarks of the Malay identity itself. For hundreds of years, art
forms like Wayang Kulit, Mak Yong, and Dikir Barat were seen as
being both - the Malay and Islamic identity, without any problems
whatsoever.
	   Ironically, the early Malay-Muslim activists and nationalists
who fought for the independence of the Malays were also more
broad-minded than most of the so-called ``Muslim activists'' who
make up the vanguard of Pas today.
	   Dr Burhanuddin al-Helmy, for example, was an individual who was
comfortable with his identity as both a Malay and a Muslim. Being
one of the latter did not entail having to exclude the former for
him. Like many other Muslim activists of his generation, he worked
to create a political environment where the cosmopolitan and
multicultural nature of Malaysian society would be protected and
cherished, and argued against a monolithic and mono-cultural
society.
	   These activists knew that the dynamism and vitality of
Malay-Muslim society could only be maintained if the Malay world
remained open to the flow of ideas and concepts from outside. They
understood that one of the most important factors that ensures the
civilisational dynamics of any society was its willingness to
engage with the Other, both from without as well as from within. It
was a broader, more cosmopolitan and universal Malay-Muslim world
that these early Muslim pioneers were working for.
	   Today the question that needs to be asked is this: How far do
the epistemological, cultural, philosophical and historical
boundaries of the Malay world extend?
	   Do the cultural frontiers of the Malay world extend as far as
Gunung Mahameru and the land of Indraprashtha? Do we still include
among our gallery of epic heroes figures like Iskandar and
Darmawangsa?
	   Or are we going to go the other way and turn our backs on our
complex and multicultural past, with its cacophony of vibrant and
contending voices, its myriad of genealogies and topographies?
	   Will the Malays of today choose to live in a homogeneous world;
a ``microwave'' culture with a history lasting all of 20 seconds
(or maybe slightly more) that begins only with the consolidation of
Islam not too long ago and ends with the monocultural utopia
envisaged by Pas?
	   Like Darmawangsa longing for the day when he and his brothers
would be able to return to Indraprashtha, there are many Malays and
Malaysians who long to return to the vast legacy of history,
literature and art that is Malay in the broadest sense of the word.
They do not fear the loss of their Islamic identity in the process:
Indeed, the encounter with the Other of our past will only
strengthen our awareness of our own identity in the present.
	   The advent of globalisation ought to inspire us to broaden our
horizons rather than retreat to refuge of the coconut shell. For it
is within the narrow and suffocating confines of that coconut shell
that we will find the exclusivist utopia that is the dream of Pas
and the nightmare of others.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:PAS'-POLICY-THREATENS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
</BODY>
