<DOCNO> APW19980608.1244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 06/08/1998 15:04:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1695 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  ENVIRONMENTAL-AWARENESSs     06-08 1419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> ENVIRONMENTAL-AWARENESS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Environmental awareness is vital for future generations' sake, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Environmental awareness is vital for future generations' sake, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Dr Abu Bakar Abdul MajeedASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   YESTERDAY was World Environment Day. It is perhaps a good time
for each one of us to ponder upon our personal report cards on how
we have treated Mother Nature, at the very least in the past year.
	   All of us are constantly interacting with the environment. In
the process, we can either make it a better place to live in or
otherwise.
	   Nobody can claim immunity from this.
	   It is a known fact that most of our daily activities have
deleterious effects on the environment. Some are inadvertent,
though.
	   For example, we have no other mode of travel except for
motorcycles and cars. Buses are also extensively used to ferry
passengers. Goods have to be transported via lorries and trucks.
	   Such hustle and bustle of vehicles contributes to pollution in
urban areas.Like it or not, all road users are actually party to
this repulsive phenomenon.
	   Although we cannot avoid polluting the urban air, why not try to
minimise it? The less travel we do, the better.
	   When our vehicles start to emit black smoke, it is time to have
the engine checked and repaired. If we can car-pool, and the crowd
is right, then why not? If the LRT runs along the routes convenient
to us, then we should take it.
	   If any of these is not possible, and you still have to drive
your own car, then practise eco-driving. This is actually a
two-in-one concept, that is driving with economy and ecology in
mind.
	   Thus, you should go easy on the accelerator. Also, do not leave
the car engine idle for too long. Not only would you save fuel, but
also reduce the emission of pollutants into the air.
	   Then, there is refuse. Everyday we consume food, lots of it.
Some indulge in more courageous activities like smoking. The amount
of leftovers, by-products and other forms of garbage that come out
of these rituals are simply mind-boggling. Fortunately, most
Malaysians know how and where to dump these. Sadly, a few do not.
	   How many times have you missed being hit by missiles in the form
of plastic bags and fruit skins thrown out of moving vehicles? And
surely you must have been fortunate enough to catch a glimpse of
the smoker dropping his cigarette butt on the floor and
extinguishing it with a Humphrey Bogart-like twist of the sole?
	   The only problem with this seemingly exquisite scene is that
almost always, our Bogarts never pick up the stubs to put them in
the ashtray or dustbin.
	   It is evident that a portion of the waste material and products
generated by both the public and industry still finds their ways
into our waterways. Despite an extensive media blitz and a ``Love
thy River''
	   campaign, there are those who continue to dump rubbish, toxic
waste and sewage into rivers without the slightest feeling of
guilt.
	   Wastes that are put into rivers are carried downstream. But
there is a limit to the amount of wastes a river can take before it
begins to suffer.
	   A number of our rivers are so heavily polluted that they have
been considered uninhabitable. They do not support any forms of
biological life anymore. They are virtually dead.
	   The apathy towards maintaining a healthy river system by the
litterbugs and polluters may be attributed to the fact that they
consider the river as a mere conduit for transporting rubbish to
the borderless dumping site, otherwise known as the sea.
	   This type of ignorance is contributing to three-quarters of
marine pollution. In addition to the waste, certain areas of coral
reefs are being threatened by silt deposition. The silt normally
originates way upriver where extensive soil erosion takes place due
to indiscriminate and uncontrolled deforestation.
	   The seas and oceans are important components of the global
ecosystem.
	   These huge water systems play a major role in setting our
weather and climate.
	   They also play a vital role in the water-cycle by contributing
to atmospheric moisture that falls back on land to replenish our
freshwater supply.
	   The marine ecosystems are also crucial in maintaining the
desirable proportion of gases in the atmosphere. Marine plants and
bacteria absorb carbon dioxide and release oxygen during the
process of photosynthesis.
	   Thus, polluting the marine ecosystems is like choking Earth's
life support system.
	   The seas and oceans are also important for a variety of economic
activities. Among these are fishing, the search for energy and
mineral resources, trade, transport, tourism and recreation. That
is why securing control of the seas and oceans has been the goal of
every nation.
	   In view of the urgency of creating awareness the world over on
the importance of protecting and maintaining sustainable marine
ecosystems, the United Nations has declared 1998 as the
International Year of the Ocean. It is appropriate that the theme
``For Life on Earth: Save our Seas''
	   has been chosen to mark this year's World Environment Day.
	   Some of us who are inland dwellers might feel that we have no
dealings whatsoever with the seas and oceans. But pollutants
released by thousands of smokestacks and millions of vehicles are
carried by winds and dropped over the waters off the coasts.
	   Domestic and industrial waste and sewage flow into rivers and
eventually into the sea. So do excess fertilisers and residues of
pesticides used for agriculture.
	   The bulk of marine sediment is also attributed to man's
overzealous clearing of the forest along the rivers. Therefore, we
cannot underplay our responsibility to save the sea.
	   The environmental-care report card of our generation reveals
that we have not performed well. How could this be? The environment
is not ours.
	   We have merely borrowed it from the future generation.
	   Before we leave this world, we have to return it, intact, to our
children and grandchildren. This is one loan the future generation
cannot afford to write-off.
	   Many of us realise that the greed and apathy of a certain
section of our generation have contributed to the rather sad state
of the environment.
	   And it seems that not much can be done to right this obsession
for quick material gain.
	   If we are unable to honour fully our loan agreement, then
probably some kind of remedial work has to be initiated. While the
good Samaritans among us go on working extremely hard to conserve
and preserve the environment, the rest should also help out in
various ways.
	   A noble gesture that we can easily carry out is instilling the
love for nature in the hearts and minds of our children. We must
equip them with sufficient understanding of the man-nature
interaction. This can be started at a very early age and has to be
done on a continuous basis.
	   Numerous books and magazines on nature are now available in
libraries, information centres and book stores. Newspapers
regularly carry articles on ecology and conservationism. Good
documentaries on the environment are broadcast over television.
	   Best of all though, a first-hand encounter with nature would
undoubtedly put the whole concept of environmental care in the
right perspective in the minds of the youngsters.
	   Parents should take their children to some of the forest
reserves, sanctuaries and marine parks located all over the
country. By doing so, we may be able to minimise the possibility of
having greedy and apathetic individuals among the next generation.
	   Finally, let's not wait another year to review our report cards
on care for the environment. Prophet Muhammad advises Muslims to do
this every evening, just before we tuck ourselves into bed. By
doing so, we could begin to work on improving our grades the very
next morning.
	   Institute of Islamic Understanding Malaysia 
</TEXT>
