<BODY>
<SLUG> RULES-OF-REAL-LIFE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rules of real life, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Rules of real life, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ACCEPTED rules of democracy do not require the electorate to be
unquestioningly obedient to every administrative or political
decision that is made. Conversely, it is the elected government
that must respond to the vox populi, especially if this carries
distinct tones of dissent from the majority who want change for the
better. There is nothing abnormal or threatening about this process
within social development, even if the debate does heat up to an
uncomfortable degree for decision- or policy-makers.
	   The past week saw the police rejecting an application by the
Federation of Malaysian Consumers Association to hold a public
forum on the water shortage that has hit parts of the Federal
Territory and Selangor. It was to have brought decision-makers
face-to-face with expectedly irate consumers, for clarification,
feedback and solutions. The meeting was not allowed to be held
because of worries over ``internal security''.
	   That the police should be empowered to preserve public safety
without hindrance is beyond question. This presumes, though, that
intelligence work has uncovered probable cause that can be backed
by irrefutable evidence. What exactly prompted refusal of Fomca's
application, however, has not been made clear.
	   Was there imminent danger to racial or religious harmony if the
forum had been held? Is discussing the issue of water shortage
seditious, slanderous or against the Constitution? If the answers
are ``No'', then the police will have to concede they have been
inflexible this time around.
	   The handling of the application has given rise to the
unfortunate impression that the police acted more in the interests
of a public-service agency, rather than the public.
	   Where services break down to the point of disrupting daily
routines, taxpayers have a right to have their misgivings heard
out. The forum may have answered their needs without being
subversive in intent, or attracting law-breakers. Within a society
striving to attain the ideals of transparency and participatory
governance in a responsible and reasonable manner, all authorities
have to accommodate the fundamental human right of citizens to
freedom of speech.
	   The present system of discretionary approval of permits needs to
be reviewed, to provide space for civil society discourse and
prevent misunderstanding. Where there is reason to believe that an
event may be hijacked by disruptive elements, the evidence must be
presented to the organiser first for a satisfactory explanation. If
none is forthcoming, the police would then have grounds for
rejecting the application.
	   However, where there is no justification for anything other than
caution, the police could set down conditions that hold organisers
accountable for order. As a precaution, security could be stepped
up, using plainclothes personnel, so as not to place the public in
a state of fear or to stifle free participation.
	   A progressive police force would keep pace with a changing
social environment in which complexities and contradictions are
challenges to be met and overcome, not avoided. It would know how
to differentiate between situations that threaten public order and
those in which citizens are staking a claim to well-being. As the
force heads into the next millennium, it should confidently leave
behind the frayed security blanket to which it has clung in past
years of uncertainty and suspicion.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
