<SLUG> BC-Israel-Abacha-Soyinka </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Soyinka: Abacha's death `incredible opportunity' for Nigeria
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos JRL111 and JRL112 &QL; 
 &UR; By HILARY APPELMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Dictator Gen. Sani Abacha's death is an
``incredible opportunity'' for Nigeria to return to democracy,
exiled playwright Wole Soyinka said Monday.
	   Soyinka, winner of the 1986 Nobel Prize for literature and an
outspoken opponent of military rule, fled Nigeria in 1994. Abacha's
military regime charged him with treason, a crime punishable by
death.
	   In an interview with reporters in Jerusalem, where he was
lecturing at Hebrew University, Soyinka said Abacha's death was
``an opportunity for Nigerian civic society, an opportunity for the
Nigerian military, and an opportunity for the international
community.''
	   Even while Abacha was still in power, Nigerians were struggling
to restore democracy, Soyinka said.
	   ``The people were sick of military dictatorship,'' he said. ``So
it's up to the military to recognize this _ and up to the
international community to say that we're sick and tired of the
degeneration of a potentially great society.''
	   Soyinka said he did not know whether Nigeria would return
immediately to democracy, or whether there would be a power
struggle within the military to succeed Abacha.
	   ``But there is an opportunity,'' he said.
	   Soyinka said the military should release all political
prisoners, including Mashood Abiola, the apparent winner of
Nigeria's aborted 1993 presidential elections, and name Abiola head
of a transitional national unity government.
	   ``There's only one choice for Nigeria _ that's a democratic
option,'' he said. ``And the structure is there. The
president-elect is waiting.''
	   Until that happens, the international community should increase
pressure and sanctions on the military government, Soyinka said.
	   Asked his personal feelings about Abacha's death, Soyinka said,
``I think he is a very lucky person.''
	   ``If it's a natural death, he got a very graceful exit,'' he
explained. If Abacha had continued flouting the will of the people,
``his end would have been very nasty.
	   ``So if he's really gone, I think Allah was very kind to him,''
he said.
	   Soyinka said he could not wait to return to Nigeria and resume
his life there, but did not know if that would happen soon.
	   ``If the military wants to prolong ... this `hiatus,' that's
OK,'' he said.
	   ``I have no expectations. We set out on this democratic struggle
as a marathon. We didn't delude ourselves it was going to be a
100-yard sprint.''
	   ``The ball is in the court of the military,'' Soyinka added.
``They have an incredible opportunity to bow out gracefully. Let us
pray that they take it.''
	   hla
</TEXT>
