<HEADLINE>
Businessman sues for return of forfeited bail, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Businessman sues for return of forfeited bail, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHAH ALAM, Fri. - A businessman, who posted bail for his brother
and had part of it forfeited by a magistrate's court, filed a suit
in the High Court today seeking a declaration that the forfeiture
was unlawful.
	   Pua Kok Sang, who filed the suit at the Shah Alam High Court
registry, named the magistrate and the prosecuting officer of the
Kuala Selangor magistrate's court and the Malaysian Government in
his suit.
	   In his statement of claim, Kok Sang said he stood bail for his
brother, Pua Kok Sheong, who was facing a gaming charge at the
Kuala Selangor magistrate's court and had deposited RM12,000 as
bail.
	   Kok Sang said he was not told of his responsibilities as a
bailor by the court when he posted the bail.
	   He said that on March 11, Kok Sheong did not attend his hearing
and an arrest warrant was issued for him (Kok Sheong).
	   Kok Sang said his brother asked him to attend the court at the
next hearing date (April 24) and when he did, the magistrate asked
him why RM10,000 of his bail money should not be forfeited.
	   Kok Sang said the magistrate then ruled that RM10,000 be
forfeited for Kok Sheong's absence. He also increased the bail to
RM60,000.
	   Kok Sang claimed that he was then taken to a lock-up until the
RM10,000 (which was in a bank) was deposited to the court.
	   Kok Sang said that although he was not put in a lock-up, he was
asked to sit near the lock-up for about three hours until a court
staff who had gone for lunch could return and assist him in
depositing the forfeited sum in the court.
	   He said that only after he had deposited the sum was he allowed
to leave.
	   Kok Sang claimed that he was treated like a criminal and was not
allowed to eat, drink or move about without the magistrate's
permission.
	   Kok Sang is also seeking declarations that: his rights were
violated by the defendants by their actions, and, the prosecuting
officer had not carried out his duties in protecting him from being
put under wrongful confinement.
	   Kok Sang is also seeking the return of the RM10,000 with other
damages with interest and costs.
	   
</TEXT>
