<SLUG> BC-NIreland-US-Business </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. delegation weighs prospects of business, violence in N.
</HEADLINE>
Ireland
 &UR; Eds: `Shorts' correct on 2nd reference
 &UR; By SHAWN POGATCHNIK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ A business delegation led by
U.S. Commerce Secretary William Daley on Monday weighed the
opportunities for American investments in Northern Ireland versus
prospects for renewed street violence here.
	   ``The truth is the whole world is watching what's going on in
Northern Ireland,'' Daley said after introducing executives of 16
top U.S. firms _ including Boeing, Monsanto, Pfizer Pharmaceuticals
and Sara Lee _ to political and business leaders eager to build on
last month's ratification of the Belfast peace agreement.
	   ``The flip side of that is, if something negative happens,
they're still watching,'' Daley said.
	   He emphasized that the potential for street confrontations
between Protestant marchers and Catholic protesters, which have
caused widespread rioting the past two summers, could easily spoil
investors' improving perceptions of this long-unstable territory.
	   Daley envisioned the possibility that executives in coming weeks
could ``go to their boards and their investment committees and say,
`Here's a place we're looking at to locate and make a sizable
investment' _ and someone says, `Gee, I just saw last night on TV
that all hell's breaking loose there.'''
	   During the delegation's visit to Northern Ireland's largest
private employer, Short Brothers PLC, the Canadian-owned aerospace
firm announced it had secured a new parts contract with The Boeing
Co. of Seattle that would produce 350 new jobs.
	   Shorts chairman Ray McNulty said this provided ``a good
illustration of how business between North America and Northern
Ireland benefits everybody.''
	   ``We've been a good supplier to Boeing. The Boeing business in
Shorts today supports about 1,100 jobs. So we all gain. It's the
sort of thing which hopefully will be repeated over and over again
in other industries in other sectors,'' McNulty said.
	   Daley addressed Belfast City Council and met separately with two
politicians who will be crucial if Northern Ireland's new
compromise government is to work: Ulster Unionist leader David
Trimble and Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams.
	   Trimble's party represents a narrow majority of Northern
Ireland's pro-British Protestants, while Sinn Fein represents a
growing section of the north's Irish Catholic minority.
	   Trimble, predicted to become the head of the new government
after an election June 25, has refused to talk to Adams unless Sinn
Fein's military allies, the outlawed Irish Republican Army, start
disarming first.
	   ``They both shared, in their comments, a sense that a corner has
been turned,'' Daley said of Trimble and Adams. ``Both of them
almost said the same things _ that it's the people out there in the
streets that's driving this change in attitude.''
	   Daley and the business executives travel Tuesday to Northern
Ireland's second-largest city, Londonderry, which already has
several U.S. factories, including Seagate disc drives, Fruit of the
Loom textiles and DuPont chemicals.
	   (sp/eml)
</TEXT>
