<HEADLINE>
New ISP services from September, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
New ISP services from September, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   francis C. NanthaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE five new Internet service providers awarded their licences
yesterday are expected to start offering their services only from
September onwards.
	   This is due to a number of issues yet to be ironed out,
particularly that of sharing the infrastructure cost for setting up
and operating the Internet gateway.
	   To assist in this process, a Telecommunications Consultative
Committee for Internet Service Provision has been set up, said
Energy, Telecommunications and Post Minister Datuk Leo Moggie
yesterday.
	   After giving out the ISP licences at his Ministry in Kuala
Lumpur, Leo Moggie said the sharing of infrastructure costs was
essential to prevent duplication of resources amongst the
operators.
	   He said a consortium was expected to be formed among the
operators to equally own the Internet gateway - which is now
currently owned by existing operators Mimos Bhd and Telekom
Malaysia Bhd.
	   The five new operators given the ISP licences are Binariang Bhd,
Celcom (Malaysia) Sdn Bhd, Mutiara Telecommunications Sdn Bhd,
PrismaNet (M) Sdn Bhd and Time Telecommunications Sdn Bhd.
	   For its Internet gateway, Mimos currently has a T3 line capable
of transmitting 45 Megabits per second as the backbone link,
supplemented by a E1 line (1.5 Mbps) and a T1 line (2.1 Mbps) as a
back-up link.
	   Telekom Malaysia's TMNet service has a T3 line as its backbone,
with a T1 line as back-up.
	   The new ISPs would have to make adjustments to their existing
networks to accommodate the 151X numbering system to offer
discounted call rates to Internet users.
	   
</TEXT>
