<SLUG> TIGHT-MONETARY-POLICY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PM: Tight monetary policy may not be good, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
PM: Tight monetary policy may not be good, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ashraf AbdullahASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PAST experience has shown that a tight monetary policy may not
be good for the country, Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir
Mohamad said yesterday.
	   ``I do not necessarily endorse Bank Negara's tight monetary
policy. High interest rates have actually caused the economy to
contract,'' he told reporters at the Sultan Abdul Aziz Shah
International Airport on his return from a five-day working visit
to Japan.
	   Dr Mahathir was asked what he thought of the central bank's
policy to maintain high interest rates.
	   He said although some parties felt his statements on the
interest rates differed from that of his deputy, Datuk Seri Anwar
Ibrahim, this was not the case.
	   ``There is no difference between me and Anwar. What he has said
is what I have told you earlier.''
	   Anwar earlier this week said interest rates must remain firm and
their levels ought to be determined by market forces. However, he
noted that the business community felt that the existing rates were
too high.
	   Dr Mahathir said effective interest rates and lending interest
rates were different.
	   ``Interest rates went up to 24 per cent at one time, it was very
high.
	   Subsequently it came down to 15 to 16 per cent, but this was
still very high to us.
	   ``The interest rates fixed by Bank Negara is 11 per cent, which
businessmen here can survive with.
	   ``The problem now is how to reduce the cost of funds of banks.
We are trying to find a solution so that interbank rates do not
affect lending interest rates.''
	   The Prime Minister also said Malaysia would obtain loans
denominated in yen up to the equivalent of US$1 billion (RM3.9
billion) to US$2 billion.
	   He said there would be no more borrowings in US dollars because
the greenback had appreciated very fast.
	   ``If you borrow in US dollars, you are going to be in trouble.
It is better not to do business in US dollars at all if possible,''
he said.
	   Dr Mahathir said the idea of trading in the currency of trading
partners did not receive any objection, especially from Stanley
Fischer, deputy managing director of the International Monetary
Fund.
	   The Prime Minister met Fischer in Tokyo where both attended a
symposium organised by the Institute for International Monetary
Affairs.
	   ``In fact, there is no currency which can claim to be a world
currency,''
	   Dr Mahathir said, adding that Japan was willing to do business
in yen.
	   
</TEXT>
