<HEADLINE>
Bumiputera participation in strategic sectors to be raised, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Bumiputera participation in strategic sectors to be raised, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Malay Chamber of Commerce Malaysia, determined to increase
Bumiputera participation in strategic sectors of the economy, is
seeking the assistance of financial institutions to reduce costs of
borrowings for Bumiputera businessmen.
	   Its president, Tan Sri Tajudin Ramli, said financial
institutions could help by having special funds to assist ailing
Bumiputera businesses.
	   He described Bumiputera businessmen as being in a ``serious''
state of affairs with the Chamber receiving numerous complaints
daily.
	   ``With the increase in costs and tight liquidity, it is more
difficult for our businessmen to face the economic slowdown,'' he
said after chairing its exco meeting in Kuala Lumpur yesterday.
	   Tajudin said the Government must help the Bumiputera
businessmen.
	   ``We don't want the Bumiputera equity lessened. We want to
ensure our presence at the operational and technical level of
businesses.'' He said the asset management company set up recently
would play an important role in ensuring the Bumiputera strength
was not diluted.
	   ``There is an imbalance in the Bumiputera participation in
various sub sectors like banking, telecommunications, transport,
power, oil and gas as well as pharmaceuticals.
	   ``We'll appoint representatives for the various industries who
will be entrusted with the task of monitoring the situation (in
those industries) regularly.''
	   The Chamber wants to increase the Bumiputera participation in
electric, electronics, land and sea transportation, aerospace,
upstream and downstream petrochemicals, textiles and clothing,
high-technology, agriculture and food products, machines, financial
services, infrastructural, trade and hospitality, wholesale and
retail as well as construction sectors.
	   ``We don't want to only be identified with traditional sectors
like agriculture,'' he added.
	   Commenting on the RM500 million additional boost to the
Bumiputera Entrepreneurs Fund announced yesterday, Tajudin said he
was happy and that any amount rendered to the fund at the earliest
possible time would enable the economy to pick up sooner.
	   An additional RM500 million will be allocated to the fund to
enable more Bumiputera businessmen to restore their businesses
after being hit by the economic downturn, Deputy Prime Minister
Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim said yesterday.
	   The Bumiputera Entrepreneurs Fund was set up in 1989 and as at
January last year had RM750 million.
	   
</TEXT>
