<SLUG> BC-Greece-Orthodox Church </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Newly elected Greek Archbishop says his life was threatened
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Archbishop Christodoulos, leader of the
Greek Orthodox Church, on Monday revealed he had received anonymous
calls threatening his life, media reports said.
	   Following implications he made during a church service in the
port city of Piraeus that his life was in danger, the archbishop
told reporters that the archdiocese in Athens last week received
several anonymous threatening telephone calls, local media said. He
gave no further details.
	   Elected to the position on April 28 after the death of
conservative Archbishop Seraphim, Christodoulos was initially
considered a forward-looking reformer. But he quickly provoked
controversy by making statements many considered to indicate his
intention to meddle in politics.
	   ``There is no reason for anyone to worry. I am not aiming to
become a prime minister nor a statesman,'' he said during Monday's
service. ``Those governing (the country) can sleep easy.''
	   Raising his voice above the thunderous applause of his
congregation, he dismissed his critics as being ``people who don't
know the Church, who are far away from the Church.''
	   Shortly after his election, the government reacted angrily when
Christodoulos criticized its cornerstone policy of joining Europe's
Economic and Monetary Union. The archbishop warned that attempts to
make Greeks more European would lead to ``perdition and
destruction.''
	   Last week, he criticized Greek President Costis Stephanopoulos
for meeting with leaders of the Old Calender Orthodox, a Christian
religious order considered to be heretical by the Church of Greece.
	   Stephanopoulos is president of all Greeks, the government
retorted.
	   (eb) 	   
</TEXT>
