<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Abacha, 7th Ld-Writethru,0451 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nigerian leader Abacha dead of heart attack at 54
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Abacha about to mark 5th year
of army rule; ADD background on political, social turmoil in
Nigeria, color. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Nigeria-Abacha-Profile, BC-Nigeria-Glance &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos NY190-191 &QL; 
 &UR; By FRANK AIGBOGUN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Nigerian strongman Gen. Sani Abacha died
Monday of a heart attack at age 54, ending the latest in a long
string of military dictatorships in his oil-rich but impoverished
country.
	   A uniformed officer stood before the State House in the capital,
Abuja, to make the announcement. Martial music filled the
state-controlled radio airwaves to officially mark his death.
Unofficially, his myriad critics and opponents poured into the
streets of Lagos to celebrate. Top officials convened an emergency
meeting.
	   In life, Abacha offered little indication of who might take his
place, wielding absolute power in Africa's most populous nation
ever since canceling presidential er for the capital territory of Abuja.
	   Word of Abacha's death came after soldiers sealed off his home
and office in Abuja. Only the top military brass were permitted to
enter the secluded leader's compound.
	   In keeping with Muslim practice, he was buried in his hometown
of Kano, near the border with Niger, before sundown on Monday,
Radio Lagos reported.
	   The military has long justified its seizing power by saying that
strong central rule is crucial in Nigeria, where rival ethnic
groups have often turned to violence in order to assert power over
one another.
	   Abacha was a pariah abroad for his repressive policies,
including the 1995 hanging of playwright Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight
other activists despite worldwide appeals for mercy. The men were
convicted on conspiracy-murder charges that critics called
trumped-up.
	   And he was a recluse at home, rarely venturing far afield,
always wearing dark glasses and never granting news media
interviews.
	   Although he pledged to hand the government over to an elected
civilian administration, in April Abacha became the only nominated
candidate for the presidency.
	   Opposition to his rule has been mounting in recent months with
the prospect that his junta might not honor its pledge to stand
down.
</TEXT>
