<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 5th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Grim scenes visible to Kosovo visitors; shelling continues
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with new U.S. quote in 8th graf, Serbs saying soldier
killed at border in 11th graf &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By ALEKSANDAR VASOVIC &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DECANI, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Scenes of devastation reminiscent of
wartime Bosnia confronted diplomats escorted into battle-torn
western Kosovo _ target of a Serb offensive that prompted new
international sanctions Monday against Serbia.
	   Besides burned-out houses and deserted villages, whose forced
evacuation have provoked comparisons to ethnic cleansing, visitors
to the besieged zone saw evidence of fierce fighting between the
Serbs and ethnic Albanian guerrillas.
	   Along with continued clashes and shelling Monday, the first-hand
look at the devastation provides stark evidence of a fast-worsening
scenario that Western powers fear could turn into a broader Balkan
war.
	   ``What we've seen is all sorrow, all grief... all those villages
burned and destroyed, all the people had left,'' said Dutch
ambassador Jan Sizoo.
	   Sizoo was in the first group of foreign diplomats to visit the
Decani region of western Kosovo, on Sunday, since Serb police and
army forces began a punishing offensive there in late May.
	   The destruction in the southern Serb province has increased
foreign pressure on Serbia to stop using its police and army
against militants battling for independence for Kosovo's 9-to-1
ethnic Albanian majority. Tens of thousands of villagers have fled.
	   The European Union tightened sanctions against Belgrade on
Monday _ banning new investments in Serbia and freezing its assets
abroad _ and urged NATO to consider military intervention.
	   In Washington, State Department spokesman James Rubin said the
United States has not ruled out military options and is likely to
reimpose sanctions on Yugoslavia soon.
	   A prominent Kosovo Albanian, Nekibe Kelmendi, welcomed the new
sanctions but said they were only a ``small step'' compared to the
situation on the ground.
	   Serb forces on Monday pounded seven southwestern villages near
the Albanian border with artillery, helicopters and artillery,
according to the Kosovo Information Center, close to the ethnic
Albanian leadership.
	   Its Serb counterpart, meanwhile _ the pro-Serb Media Center _
said a Yugoslav army soldier was killed in an attack by militants
west of Djakovica near the Albanian border. It also said ethnic
Albanian militants attacked two Serb villages in the Drenica
region.
	    &UR; State-employed Serb, 4th Ld-11th graf
	   (ms/dc)
</TEXT>
