<SLUG> KEDAH-MAY-LIMIT-PULAU sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kedah may limit Pulau Payar visitors, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Kedah may limit Pulau Payar visitors, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   K. BalaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   LANGKAWI, Fri - The State Government will study proposals to
limit the number of visitors to the Pulau Payar marine park to
prevent destruction to its rich marine life, Menteri Besar Tan Sri
Sanusi Junid said.
	   He said if the marine ecology of the island was being affected
by the increasing number of visitors, then measures would be taken
to preserve the park.
	   The park is the only one of the 38 in the country located in the
Straits of Malacca. The others are in the South China Sea.
	   Sanusi said the Government would also look into imposing a levy
on visitors ``but the amount should not be too high''.
	   He said this after presenting Amanah Saham Kedah dividends to
104 people under the Hardcore Poor Development Programme today.
	   The authorities had also been looking to impose a levy on
visitors to another of Langkawi's attraction, Pulau Singa Besar.
	   However, the process, including privatisation of the island, has
taken quite some time to study, Sanusi said.
	   During a talk here on the Langkawi Marine Environment last week,
Universiti Sains Malaysia marine scientist Associate Prof Dr
Zulfigar Yasin proposed a limit on the number of visitors to Pulau
Payar to prevent further destruction of its aquatic life.
	   He had urged the authorities to also consider closing the island
to visitors for a short period during the spawning season of the
marine life.
	   Pulau Payar with its crystal clear waters is about an hour's
boat ride from here and is a popular attraction for tourists.
	   Last year more than 100,000 tourists, mostly foreigners visited
the island compared to a mere 13 in 1988.
	   Dr Zulfigar had said that researchers and divers who five years
ago scoured the rich marine life, including many endangered
species, had since noted the damage.
	   He had also said the short stretch of white sandy beach and
pristine waters should not be made a mere picnic destination.
	   He cautioned that the island could face competition from the
Thai islands of Taratau and Adang which also have a rich marine
life.
	   
</TEXT>
