<BODY>
<SLUG> ASBU-BAKAR-RESPECTED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Abu Bakar respected for devotion to principles, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Abu Bakar respected for devotion to principles, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE late Tan Sri Abu Bakar Samad Mohd Noor came from an era
where the civil service was much respected, and as a civil servant,
he was held in high esteem.
	   Although he went on to a career in the private sector after
retirement, many remember him for a resolute devotion to principles
and duty, traits which marked his civil service career which began
during the British era.
	   Abu Bakar died on May 26 after a short illness, surrounded by
his wife Puan Sri Salmah Idrose, son Abdul Razak and six daughters
- Zainun, Zainariah, Noreen, Maria, Nazlee and Marina.
	   Speaking on behalf of the family, Marina said, ``he managed a
smile until the end''.
	   Abu Bakar began his service as a Malay Officer, briefly under
the Japanese administration. After the war, under the British
administration, he was re-appointed a Malay Officer and was posted
in various towns.
	   He was sent to Trinity College, Cambridge for the overseas
service course, after which he returned to Malaya which had just
gained independence.
	   He joined the Federal establishment and then the Ministry of
Home Affairs. He went on to be the controller of supplies and
budget in the Treasury, rising to be the Finance Ministry's deputy
secretary-general.
	   In 1969, Abu Bakar moved on to the Defence Ministry where he
stayed until his retirement in 1977 as the secretary-general.
	   In this capacity, he had many achievements including the
founding of the Lembaga Tabung Angkatan Tentera, and a pension
scheme for retired soldiers and benefits for widows and families of
soldiers.
	   His dutybound nature is clearly remembered by a close friend,
Tan Sri Sheikh Hussein Sheikh Mohamed who was also in the civil
service.
	   ``He held very strong views that public service should remain
neutral from politics. He was strong enough to give his advice
freely to Ministers, whether an Englishman or Malaysian,'' Sheikh
Hussein said.
	   Far from fading away after retirement, Abu Bakar was invited to
join the boards of several companies, to lend his expertise and
experience.
	   At various times, he was with Boustead Holdings Berhad, Tenaga
Kimia, Malaysian Explosives, RHB Berhad, Asia Insurance, Alpha
Laval, Bestobel, Federal Auto Holdings and Ericsson group of
companies.
	   It was his close ties with the Swedish companies that won him
the Royal Order of the Northern Star, awarded by King Carl Gustaf
of Sweden in 1987.
	   He was only the second Malaysian to receive the award after
former Foreign Affairs Minister Tan Sri Ghazalie Shafie.
	   Abu Bakar was honoured for his outstanding contribution in
promoting Swedish-Malaysian relations. He was then chairman of the
Malaysian-Swedish Business Association and had worked with Swedish
authorities for 15 years.
	   Like many of the elite community at that time, Abu Bakar had his
early education at Victoria Institution and Kolej Melayu Kuala
Kangsar. He then furthered his education at Raffles College in
Singapore.
	   Despite his ``upperclass upbringing'' which gave him what some
described as an ``aristocratic bearing'', he was always
down-to-earth, said his old friend Michael Loh.
	   Loh, who insisted that they were worlds apart in social status,
said Abu Bakar never let this got in the way of friendship.
	   ``He had no airs about himself,'' said Loh, who first knew Abu
Bakar at the age of 19.
	   Marina said Abu Bakar's gregarious nature had brought people
from all walks of life, and all races, into their home.
	   He was ``cosmopolitan'', agreed Sheikh Hussein.
	   Like many of his era, Abu Bakar was broadminded about other
cultures including those now deemed as ``western''.
	   He enjoyed ballroom dancing, a love which he shared with his
wife and four of his daughters, and golf. His love for golf was
well-known and in his younger days, he was a single handicapper.
	   Marina said in golf, ``he was pedantic on the rules and
etiquette''.
	   The family remembers him most for his caring nature, which
extended to animals - 17 cats, three dogs, one monkey and one
squirrel, all strays, at one point, added Marina.
	   His philosophy in life, she said, was humility and generosity.
	   ``Two weeks before he died, he reminded us: `To err is human, to
forgive, divine'.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
