w1755 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Belarus-US 3rdLd-Writethru   06-08 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Belarus-US, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Diplomats ordered to vacate official residences in Minsk
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to ADD new quotes, photos. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo MIN101-2 &QL; 
 &UR; By MARINA BABKINA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MINSK, Belarus (AP) _ Belarus is trying to evict 22 ambassadors
from their homes in violation of international law and tried Monday
to weld shut a gate to the American residence, U.S. Ambassador
Daniel Speckhard said.
	   The Belarusian government served notice in April that it wanted
to overhaul water and sewage pipes in the diplomatic complex on the
outskirts of the capital, Minsk, where the ambassadors live with
their families, Speckhard said at a news conference.
	   Residents of the compound protested, saying they would prefer to
make arrangements to remain in the compound during the repairs,
Speckhard said.
	   Under international law, ambassadors' residences are considered
foreign territory and governments have no right to enter without
permission or insist that diplomats leave.
	   Speckhard took reporters to his home in the diplomatic complex
at Drozdy and arrived to find a team of workers and a policeman
trying to weld shut the side gate. A small American flag was lying
on the ground. The workers left when Speckhard protested.
	   Speckhard called the incident the most serious violation of the
Vienna Convention on embassy operations since the end of the Cold
War.
	   ``To lock ambassadors into their residences and weld their door
shut is not becoming to the dignity of your country,'' Speckhard
told Belarusian reporters.
	   Speckhard said that he doesn't doubt that some repairs are
needed on the pipes leading to the complex, built after World War
II to house the Communist Party elite. But he insisted that the
government must reach agreements with the foreign missions and
cannot simply evict them.
	   He said the United States has had a lease on the residence since
1992, the year after Belarus gained independence with the collapse
of the Soviet Union, and has spent dlrs 800,000 on repairs. The
lease does not expire until 2001.
	   If the government forcibly evicts the ambassadors, it would be
the first violation of the Vienna Convention since Iranian
militants seized the U.S. Embassy in Tehran in 1979, an embassy
spokeswoman said.
	   Speckhard said he and a number of other ambassadors are refusing
to vacate the compound, and appealed to President Alexander
Lukashenko to rescind the order.
	   ``I am hopeful that this press conference today will help to
inform the president of the situation in case he has not been
receiving the right information from his bureaucracy,'' Speckhard
said.
	   The Belarusian Foreign Ministry offered the ambassadors small
apartments elsewhere in the city, an offer that embassy officials
said was unacceptable.
	   (ls)	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
