<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Japan-Wenger,0394 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Arsenal's Wenger visits to root for Japanese team
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By YURI KAGEYAMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AIX-LES-BAINS, France (AP) _ Now that the Japanese have made it
to the World Cup, some of their players may soon be signing with a
European league club _ perhaps with London's Arsenal.
	   Arsenal coach Arsene Wenger said Monday the idea wasn't
far-fetched. He would like to see Japanese play on European teams,
including his own team, although he refused to say which players he
was especially interested in.
	   ``Like Japanese baseball players who have gone to the United
States and were a success. Why should not Japanese football players
come to Europe and be a success?'' Wenger said while visiting the
team as a guest of the resort town of Aix-Les-Bains, Japan's
training camp during the tournament.
	   ``The Japanese team has qualities that are superior to the South
American and European teams. They have quick reaction and tight
teamwork. But they are weak against direct contact.''
	   Wenger, who led the Gunners to their first league title since
1991 in the season just ended, has long been a friend to Japanese
soccer, having coached J-League Nagoya Grampus three seasons ago
before signing on with Arsenal in 1996.
	   But the Frenchman, now one of the most popular coaches in
England, said he didn't come to give the Japanese any advice, just
to cheer them on.
	   Still, Wenger watched the team practice and was deluged with
questions from Japanese reporters at a news conference at the town
hall. He was also scheduled to meet with Japanese coach Takeshi
Okada.
	   Wenger acknowledged he was disappointed more players from his
old J-League club weren't chosen for the national team. The only
Grampus player on the team is 23-year-old midfielder Takashi
Hirano.
	   ``I thought Ogura had a good chance, but he's injured,'' he said
of Grampus striker Takafumi Ogura.
	   Wenger had praise for Japanese players, including midfielder
Hidetoshi Nakata, whom he described as ``a world-class player,'' as
well as 18-year-old Shinji Ono and goalkeeper Yoshikatsu Kawaguchi.
	   But he also had a warning for Japanese fans: Don't expect too
much at the first World Cup.
	   ``That's dangerous,'' he said.
	   (yk/jw) 	   
</TEXT>
