<HEADLINE>
Resolve parking problems first, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Resolve parking problems first, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IT is indeed disheartening to read in the Press recently that
the Subang Jaya Municipal Council intends to launch the parking
coupon for Subang Jaya Town Centre without first solving the
parking woes for the residents, businessmen and shoppers.
	   It was reported in the News Straits Times (March 12 1997, March
21 1997 and again on June 27 1997) that MPSJ was to convert the
much neglected mall at SS15 into parking space to ease the traffic
congestion for the businessmen and shoppers.
	   After a lapse of more than one year, nothing has been done and
the pedestrian mall at SS15 remained an eyesore to the residents
and visitors.
	   We see no valid reason how the parking coupons system will solve
the parking woes if MPSJ did not first tackle the basic problem.
	   The only benefit from the system is to enrich the revenue of the
MPSJ at the expense of the motorists.
	   Even the State Assemblyman Lee Hwa Beng had promised in his last
general election manifesto to resolve the two-decade mall problem.
After more than four years, no positive action has been taken.
	   We urge that the Ministry of Housing and Local Government to
defer the implementation of the parking coupon system for Subang
Jaya until and unless the parking problem has been resolved by the
council.
	   Caring Community Subang Jaya 
</TEXT>
