<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Europe-Nigeria </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
European Union calls for swift return to democracy in Nigeria
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The European Union on Monday called for a swift
restoration of democracy in Nigeria following the death of the
country's military strongman, General Sani Abacha.
	   A statement issued by British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook,
whose country holds the rotating EU presidency, said the 15 EU
members also look forward to the ``election of an accountable
civilian government which will restore and respect human rights.''
	   Abacha's death from a heart attack at the age of 54 came in the
run-up to presidential elections in Nigeria. As the only candidate,
his victory was assured. His death creates a political vacuum.
	   The EU's brief statement said: ``We hope that following the
death of General Abacha, there will be an opening for a stable
transition to an early return to democracy, with the election of an
accountable civilian government which will restore and respect
human rights.''
	   Commonwealth Secretary-General Chief Emeka Anyaoku, himself a
Nigerian, expressed condolences to Abacha's family and hope that
his succession will be based on ``genuine national consensus.''
	   The 54-nation association of Britain and its former colonies
voted to suspend Nigeria's membership in 1995 in protest against
the execution of author and environmentalist Ken Saro-Wiwa.
	   ``I have no doubt that all Nigerians would wish to ensure that
peace prevails and that the succession arrangements are based on
genuine national consensus,'' Anyaoku said in a brief statement
issued at the Commonwealth's London headquarters.
	   Nigeria is the world's sixth largest oil exporting country, and
Royal Dutch Shell is one of its major foreign investors. In a brief
statement issued in London, the company did not mention politics.
	   ``The death of General Abacha will be a source of deep sorrow to
his family and our thoughts are with them and with the nation at
this time. Shell will continue to work with Nigeria as it has for
many years,'' the Royal Dutch Shell Group said.
	   (eml)
</TEXT>
