<BODY>
<SLUG> PARAGON-UNION-FOUNDER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Paragon Union founder fails to be re-elected, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Paragon Union founder fails to be re-elected, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PARAGON Union Bhd's founder and director Tan Siew Chin failed to
get re- elected to its board at the company's annual meeting
yesterday.
	   Managing director and chief executive director Lawrence Wong
Fook Heng said 56 per cent of the shareholders who attended the
meeting voted against Tan's re-election.
	   The shareholders also voted against three Paragon Union's
shareholders, holding not less than 10 per cent interest each in
the company, from being appointed to the board.
	   They are Tan Siew Tyan, Chua Tuan Hua and Raymond Kok Poo Him.
	   Wong, who was speaking to reporters after the meeting at its
factory in Balakong, Selangor, said another director Tang Swee Lan
had voluntarily resigned from the board.
	   Both Tan and Tang were unavailable for comment during the Press
conference.
	   Following the development, Paragon Union's current board of
directors comprise Wong, its chairman Datuk Lim Hui Boon, Tengku
Datuk Ibrahim Petra and Teoh Tek Siong.
	   Paragon Union and its subsidiaries manufacture and trade
commercial and car carpets and automotive components, machining and
production of stamped parts for the automotive electrical and
electronic industries.
	   Its current paid-up capital stands at RM14 million.
	   Tan Siew Chin is formerly the managing director of the company,
which was listed on the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange second board in
November 1994. He relinquished his position in July last year.
	   As at Dec 31 last year, Tan held 1.57 million shares in the
company while Lim, who is currently its substantial shareholder, a
total of 2.58 million shares.
	   On the company's operations, Wong said Paragon Union is
currently taking the necessary steps to improve its business.
	   For the year ended Dec 31, 1997, the company registered a
pre-tax loss of RM437,154 against a pre-tax profit of RM3.08
million previously.
	   However, its turnover increased to RM45.48 million from RM40.35
million previously.
	   ``The company's outlook will remain the same for the next two to
three years,'' said Wong.
	   In the company' annual report, Lim said Paragon Union was well
prepared to face the challenges of the coming years.
	   He said its management had decided to discontinue the metal
stamping and machining operationsfrom last March and implemented an
austerity programme to reduce expenses.
	   Asked the reasons behind the change in the date of its annual
meeting, initially scheduled for Tuesday , Wong said the earlier
date was a typographical error.
	   
</TEXT>
