JERUSALEM: SOYINKA - We have reaction to the news of General
Sani Abacha's death from the Nigerian Wole Soyinka, the winner of the
1986 Nobel prize for literature, who left his country in 1994. He is
in Jerusalem. (North America Update 1830)
-----
UK: NIGERIA  - We are are also chasing reaction in London from
Amnesty International and the son of the executed pro-democracy
activist Ken Sara-Wiwa. (North America Late 1930)
----
UK: MCCARTNEY - The memorial service from London's St
Martin-in-the-Fields for Linda McCartney begins with arrivals at
1830GMT. We hope to have a package of arrivals and fans gathered
outside for a vigil for the North America Late 1930, with a wrap to
for the Latin America Update at 2130. There will be NO pictures
inside.
---
NORTHERN IRELAND: DALEY - Coverage of the visit to Northern Ireland of U.S.
Commerce Secretary William Daley, who will spend five days in the
province to improve business links. (Europe Early 0300G  )
----
RUSSIA: MIR 2 - APTV will wrap shots of the hatch of MIR closing
(First Run 1315 f-l-a-s-h) with later coverage of a news conference
at mission control and pictures of MIR and the shuttle Discovery
unlocking. (1830 North America Update)
----
ITALY: SPICE - The girl power foursome are about to perform in Italy
--  the first time since the announcement that Ginger Spice is
leaving the group. It will include pictures of them, and other
stars, rehearsing and a news conference. (Latin America Update 2130)
----
GERMANY YELTSIN 2: Russian President Boris Yeltsin arrived in Bonn
on Monday for talks with German Chancellor Helmut Kohl. (F-l-a-s-h
after 2015)
-----
US: KIM - South Korean President Kim Dae-jung is in New York -
earlier he went to the New York Stock Exchange to ring the opening
bell.  (First Run 1325 F-L-A-S-H) - we will have an update on his
activities. (Asia Pacific Early 1945)
----
RUNNING:  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
ABACHA: FILE - The Nigerian Head of State, General Sani Abacha, has
died of a heart attack at his residence in the country's capital.
We have a profile on the Nigerian dictator and his regime, including
shots of him with the Pope.  (First Run Europe Late 1500)
----
ALBANIA: KOSOVO -  The U-S American Ambassador to Tirana and a
representative from the U-S State Department visited the town to
assess of Tropoje to view first-hand the refugee problem from
neighboring Kosovo.  The Prime Minister of Kosovo, whose government
is in exile in Brussels, also came to Albania.  Item includes
highlights from both their visits. (First Run 1500 Europe Late)
----
EU: KOSOVO 2 - European Union foreign ministers banned new
investments in Serbia on Monday in their harshest move yet against
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. We have a wrap of the day's
events at the meeting in Luxembourg. (First Run 1130 Europe Late)
----
UK: LAND MINES - The British army has blown up a thousand land mines
as part of the U.K government's commitment to destroy virtually all
its stock of the devices. APTV cameras were there. (First Run 1440
Eurovision Window)
----
UN: DRUGS - The U-N General Assembly holds a special session on the
global plague of drug use and drug trafficking in New York.  Item
includes excerpts from speeches by U-S President Bill Clinton, U-N
Secretary General Kofi Annan and Peruvian President Alberto
Fujimori. (First Run 1500 Europe Late)
----
WORLD CUP: FANS -Fans from Scotland and Brazil have led the invasion
of soccer supporters to France ahead of the start of the World Cup
on Wednesday.  But industrial action by Air France pilots could
hinder the arrival of other fans.  APTV looks at how the strike
could affect the games. (First Run 1440 APTV Eurovision)
----
FIFA: WRAP 2 - APTV has a wrap of the day's events in Paris at
FIFA's 51st Congress, where Secretary General Sepp Blatter was
elected as new president of the world football governing body.
(First Run F-L-A-S-H 1250)
----
BLATTER: PROFILE - APTV has a profile of Sepp Blatter, who won
Monday's FIFA's contest to be the new head of world soccer. (First
Run F-L-A-S-H 1250)
----
MONTENEGRO: REFUGEES - APTV has coverage showing many of the ethnic
Albanians who have fled their homes in Kosovo sheltering in
neighboring Montenegro. Shows refugees sitting by the sides of
roads, or in shelters. Includes a comment in Serbian of the
municipal commissioner for refugees and in Albanian of a refugee.
(First Run F-L-A-S-H 1025 June 8)
----
JERUSALEM: SETTLERS - Shows Palestinians and Israeli left-wing
activists scuffling with police after Jewish settlers took over
three buildings in an Arab neighborhood of east Jerusalem. Includes
comments in English of an injured Palestinian official and a settler
plus Yossi Sarid, left-wing member of Knesset. (First Run Europe
Morning 0800)
