<HEADLINE>
SC withdraws its written consent, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
SC withdraws its written consent, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Securities Commission has withdrawn its written consent to
Halim Securities Sdn Bhd to carry on its licensed business
activity.
	   In a statement yesterday, the SC said the move was taken
following default proceedings taken by the Securities Clearing
Automated Network Services Sdn Bhd (SCANS) and the SC's rejection
of Halim Securities proposed corporate restructuring plan.
	   SC's move was pursuant to Section 20A of the Securities Industry
Act, 1983 (SIA).
	   Based on a report from the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange and
SCANS, SC said Halim Securities had not only defaulted on its
payment of RM9.67 million to SCANS, but has also failed to meet the
minimum liquid funds required under rule 17A of the Exchange's
rules relating to member companies.
	   The SC's rejection of the corporate restructuring plan is due to
numerous reasons including the inadequacy of the proposed capital
injection.
	   From Monday, Halim Securities will have to stop from dealing in
securities until such time, as in context of Section 20A of the
SIA, it is able to fulfill KLSE's minimum liquid funds
requirements.
	   It will also have to settle its debt to SCANS.
	   Said SC: ``Halim Securities had been given opportunities to
regularise its financial position in compliance with the KLSE's
rules and the Securities' rules.''
	   ``SCANS had also given several notices and extension of time to
Halim Securities to settle the RM9.67 million.''
	   
</TEXT>
