<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Drift Nets, 1st Ld-Writethru,0465 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU agrees gradual ban of drift nets
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS agreement on ban, quotes; TRIMS. No pickup &QL; 
 &UR; By ANNA SATHIAH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LUXEMBOURG (AP) _ The EU governments agreed after several hours
of talks Monday to phase out high sea drift nets by Dec. 31, 2001,
to prevent the unnecessary death of thousands of species such as
seals, dolphins and whales.
	   Two countries, France and Italy, voted against the agreement
that applies to boats registered in EU countries. Ireland
abstained.
	   Britain's Agriculture Minister Jack Cunningham called the
negotiations ``on the whole amicable but tough.'' The negotiations
have been on the agenda since 1994, he said.
	   France, Italy and Ireland argued the ban would threaten the
livelihood of fishermen.
	   ``A technique of fishing has been sacrificed,'' French
Agriculture Minister Louis le Pensec told reporters. ``The
fishermen have been unjustly affected ... such a decision is
unacceptable for France.''
	   EU Fisheries Commissioner Emma Bonino, and Britain, which now
holds the EU's rotating presidency, had proposed phasing out all
drift nets as of Dec. 31, 2000.
	   Cunningham said Monday's decision was reached after the
countries agreed on a number of measures to help fishermen was
included in the deal.
	   To implement such measures by the end of this year _ including
retraining fishermen for other jobs _ the countries concerned will
have to dig into the EU funds allocated for poor regions. Ireland
has more poor regions than France and Italy.
	   ``We know that there is money at least as far as France and
Italy are concerned. In Ireland's case, the situation is more
difficult,'' said Bonino. ``We'll have to see what we can do.''
	   France had said if it came to a transitional period, it wanted a
period of at least six years. Italy is considered by EU officials
to be the worst offender.
	   In 1992, the United Nations imposed a general moratorium on
drift nets. The EU responded by limiting them to 1.5 miles (2.5
kilometers).
	   The drift nets that are kilometers (miles) long are dragged
through the water. Because they are so long, they have been
nicknamed ``walls of death.''
	   Ecological groups, including Greenpeace have denounced the use
of the nets, which they say catch animals fishermen don't want such
as sharks, dolphins, whales, turtles and diving birds.
	   The RSPCA, the British animal protection organization, published
a report last September highlighting the devastation and suffering
caused by drift nets.
	   The report revealed that in one season alone almost 83,000 blue
sharks were caught by French boats, 8,000 dolphins by Italian
fishermen. Additionally, as many as 800 leatherback turtles died in
drift nets. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-EU-Drift Nets, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
