w1811 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  NEW-AGE-JAPANESE-CUISINE     06-08 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> NEW-AGE-JAPANESE-CUISINE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New-age Japanese cuisine, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
New-age Japanese cuisine, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Eu Hooi KhawASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   JUST as fusion has crept into Chinese food, it has also made its
inroads into Japanese. It's modern Japanese cuisine, with western
flavours, one which the young people in Japan are enamoured with.
	   ``The young people will not go into a traditional Japanese
restaurants any more,'' said Eji Kamada, general manager of
Restaurant Suntory at the Kuala Lumpur Hilton Arcade West Main
Lobby. ``They go into this kind of restaurant. Now in Japan, there
is a little western culture and we want to show customers the new
Japanese-style cuisine.''
	   An example of new-age Japanese food would be the beef fillet
with foie gras that is one of the 10 courses in the kaiseki meal we
had. Foie gras is essentially French, and the goose liver is
marinated in balsamico and a little soya sauce before being sauteed
on a teppan.
	   An elderly Japanese couple seated next to our table was most
interested in the cracker served with scallop tartare sauce we had
before the kaiseki dinner. The Hotate Taru Taru Cracker was like a
large canape, with a heap of creamy chopped raw scallop with onions
and topped with flying fish roe resting on a full-size cracker. It
made a crispy, yet smooth and piquant hors d'oeuvre.
	   More finger food came in the Beef Cutlet Supaicy Sauce, which
was a piece of meat fried in a light batter, each on a lettuce leaf
and accompanied by shredded spring onion and carrot. The sauce
served with this was surprisingly hot - I detected cumin, a tinge
of curry powder and chilli.
	   If you are drinking beer or even sake, the Tomo Momo Mustard or
Grilled Chicken with Mustard Paste makes another good appetiser. I
could taste the hot, piquant mustard on top of the chicken which
has been lightly breaded and fried.
	   The kaiseki dinner shows you all the creativity of the chef.
First there was this bamboo-lined lacquer tray of hors d'oeuvres
called Sanshu Mori with boiled fresh soyabean pods in a large
hollow bamboo, grilled cold eggplant marinated in soya sauce and
sesame and topped with sesame seeds in a Chinese spoon and chilled
egg tofu in a glass bowl flavoured with ginger juice and some
shrimps.
	   These tasty, subtle appetisers put you in the right mood for
even more adventurous fare to come. The Kawai Zushi Santen Mori
offers three kinds of sushi in their nori or seaweed cases. The
small squid marinated with special soya fills the topping for one,
the intense sweetness of this burst on the palate as you bite into
the smooth squid.
	   Even more unusual was the crabmeat blended with miso paste in
yet another sushi. It was creamy, tinged with sweetness from the
miso but you would still get the inimitable flavour of crab. The
last sushi was one of salmon roe.
	   The Asari Dobin Mushi is a clear soup with short neck clam in a
special pot. I never cease to wonder at the delicacy of this soup
which is poured out of a spout in the pot on to a little teacup
which is the cover of the pot. You sip the soup from the tiny cup,
appreciating the flavour of the clams and the few drops of lemon
juice you have squeezed into it.
	   A hot soup is followed by sashimi - Kurodai Aarai Yuzomiso which
is raw black sea-bream with Yuzu miso paste. The sea-bream has a
clear taste, and I liked the springy texture of it. It's sashimi,
not dipped in the conventional soya sauce and wasabi, but a
delightful miso paste.
	   Anago Yanagawa is braised sea eel, Yanagawa style. The eel is
braised in soya sauce with onions and shredded burdock root and
finished in egg. It looks like a steamed egg dish, with the
ingredients making a striking presence. It is served in flat stone
dish.
	   Still on a traditional note in this kaiseki dinner is the
Shirauo Edamame Kakiage, which has shredded eggplant, white fish
and soya bean dipped in batter and fried into a crispy friteer.
	   Fusion food came from the teppan in the form of Foie Gras Gyu
Fillet Steak, very rich and very French, but with a touch of
Japanese.
	   Just when we were feeling full, we were presented with
Shimeiwashi Sanbaizu which is sardine with vinegar, seaweed, slices
of raw yam and cucumber and grated ginger. The tart sardine brings
everything into balance, especially with the crunchy raw yam and
the spicy, refreshing ginger.
	   I don't know why my favourite cold Japanese noodles - Inaniwa
Udon - had to come at the end of the dinner. You dip the chilled,
thin and wonderfully smooth udon in the bowl of sauce with grated
ginger, wasabe, and chopped spring onions.
	   Dessert was a small Japanese red bean tart.
	   The kaiseki could be likened to a course by course gourmet
dinner, that offers a selection from the raw appetisers to the
cooked ones, and to main courses that are deep fried, cooked on the
teppan or braised. It costs RM180 to have this feast at Suntory,
and you simply must take your time savouring the different
gastronomic ingredients brought together. A kaiseki meal should
rightly last for hours.
	   Kamada is trying to open up the world of Japanese food to
Malaysians.
	   ``For instance, there are many kinds of rolled sushi,'' he said,
``but Malaysians only want California roll. You can't find this in
Japan.'' He would also like to steer them away from staples like
tempura, to a more adventurous food..
	   The restaurant also has a Robatayaki counter, that offers the
Japanese hotpot, like a steamboat.
	   Suntory is a huge conglomerate in Japan that is involved not
only in 400 restaurants there and overseas, but also in liquor such
as whisky, wine and beer, medicine, golf clubs, health club, music
halls, museum, advertising and soft drinks, fruit juices and
ice-cream! 
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all
rights reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:NEW-AGE-JAPANESE-CUISINE sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
