<SLUG> SRII-AIMS-TO-SECURE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SRII aims to secure more world standards, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
SRII aims to secure more world standards, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Foo Eu JinASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HAVING obtained Sirim's approval in a full range of standards,
SRII Bhd will now focus on securing international standards for its
fire-fighting equipment.
	   In an interview with Business Times, SRII managing director Ong
Yow Siang said Third World export markets such as Africa and West
Asia do not emphasise much on international standards.
	   He said these markets will accept a product as long as the
company complies with the minimum standards of the countries.
	   However, given SRII's objective of increasing product
penetration into advanced countries, it has intensified efforts
towards securing more international standards.
	   According to Ong, advanced countries such as Japan and Europe
impose stringent standards, which may take up to three years for
approval and can be costly.
	   In addition to securing certification for its fire extinguishers
in Australia, SRII is trying to obtain certification in Europe.
	   Ong said the company is ensuring its fire-fighting products
comply with international standards right from the start.
	   SRII currently complies with a few international standards,
including British and Australian.
	   On its export plans, SRII hopes to capitalise on the weaker
ringgit by being export driven to boost incomes.
	   ``We have been working hard to drive up our exports to take
advantage of the lower ringgit against the greenback,'' Ong said.
	   He added that the export business is expected to be the
company's main business in five years.
	   He said total exports for this year should account for 40 per
cent of last year's revenue of RM66.29 million, up 25 per cent.
	   In the next 10 years, the group plans to achieve exports of at
least 60 per cent of its revenue.
	   Ong said profit margins for exports are more significant, given
the increase in the value of the US dollar in which its products
are traded.
	   ``Although the local market is rather small, with only a handful
of smaller competitors, we still command on the average between 40
and 50 per cent of the local market share,'' Ong said.
	   SRII's reputation for quality and reliability has made it a
trusted name throughout Malaysia and in over 30 countries worldwide
including the Asean, UK, East Asia, West Asia and Africa.
	   In UK SRII's exports account for between 15 and 20 containers
every year, while in Australia exports account for four containers
a month.
	   On the local contracts in hand, Ong said SRII has not less than
RM60 million in outstanding contracts for its fire-fighting
products, which should see the company through the next one to two
years.
	   He said SRII is also trying to get more government-backed
industrial and Multimedia Super Corridor projects.
	   These contracts include deals to supply to the Kuala Lumpur
International Airport, Kuala Lumpur City Centre and Tawau Airport.
	   Meanwhile, SRII signed a MOU with Cerberus Malaysia AG of
Switzerland last month to set up a joint venture company, Cerebus
Malaysia Sdn Bhd, to manufacture, assemble, market and distribute
Cerberus fire alarms, gas detection, security products and systems.
	   SRII's proposed stake of 10 per cent in the joint venture will
be subscribed through its 100 per cent owned subsidiary, Vital
Engineering Sdn Bhd, while the rest will be held by Cerberus.
	   Vital Engineering will have an option to buy additional shares
of up to 30 per cent at par value from Cerberus or the proposed
joint venture within the first three years of operation.
	   The joint venture will allow SRII to penetrate more effectively
into the fire and electronic security engineering markets in
Malaysia and the Asia Pacific.
	   On SRII's short-term financial performance, Ong said the group
should meet its first quarter sales and profit forecast despite the
economic slowdown.
	   Due to prudent financial management, the group has virtually no
gearing with RM19 million in the bank or 90 sen per share, he
added. SRII is an investment holding company with subsidiaries
involved in manufacturing, trading and dealing in fire-fighting
equipment.
	   The group is also involved in the business of designing and
installing fire-fighting and prevention systems as well as
servicing, buying and selling related equipment.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
