<BODY>
<SLUG> K&AMP;N-KENANGA-RECOMMENDS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
K&AMP;N Kenanga recommends Unisem a `buy up to RM10', BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
K&AMP;N Kenanga recommends Unisem a `buy up to RM10', BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Francis FernandezASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   K&AMP;N Kenanga has given a ``buy up to RM10.00'' recommendation to
Unisem (M) Bhd's shares, which will soon be listed on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange main board.
	   The stockbroking company also decribed Unisem as a ``top class
operations in an expanding market''.
	   K&AMP;N Kenanga is one of the underwriters of Unisem's initial
public offer (IPO) exercise. The company had offered its shares
under an IPO price of RM5.10 per share.
	   K&AMP;N Kenanga said the recommendation to buy Unisem's shares are
based on the company's healthy balance sheet, which puts it in a
stronger position compared with many of its peers.
	   In addition, the stockbroking firm noted that Unisem prepaid all
of its bank facilities in 1996 and it estimates that at end-1997,
Unisem was in a net cash position of some RM30.5 million.
	   Unisem, a manufacturer of semiconductor devices, has also seen
world demand for its main product, the Small Outline Integrated
Circuit (SOIC), grow.
	   The demand is estimated to rise further by a compounded annual
growth rate (CAGR) of 11.8 per cent (in number of units) up to the
year 2000.
	   With this, its revenues have also grown steadily over the years
from a mere RM37.29 million in 1993 to RM158.44 million in 1997.
	   It has forecast a pre-tax profit of RM93 million in 1998 and
RM124 million in 1999, which translates into an earnings per share
of 65.0 sen and 86.7 sen respectively.
	   Unisem, which has a market capitalisation of RM1.43 billion and
with 143 million issued shares, has forecast net tangible asset
(NTA) per share of RM2.76 as at end-1998.
	   K&AMP;N Kenanga also said that Unisem operates in a healthy
environment in a high-growth industry and gets paid in US dollars
by its customers.
	   However, the company is only allowed to keep up to US$5 million
(US$1  &QC;  RM3.99) in dollar deposits in Malaysia, while the rest of
the revenue is converted into ringgit with the surplus cash
deposited into repos and time deposits.
	   K&AMP;N Kenanga also said that Unisem, which has pioneer status that
exempts its profits from operations from income tax for five years
beginning July 1 1993, is applying for an extension of its pioneer
status, as allowed under the local tax law. There is a possibility
that the company will receive the extension.
	   In addition, K&AMP;N Kenanga pointed out that the company has at
end-1997 RM2 million in tax losses, RM17 million in unclaimed
capital allowances and RM40 million in qualifying expenditure
(reinvestment allowances) that will enable it to offset against
income tax once its pioneer status ends.
	   K&AMP;N Kenanga said Unisem presents investors with a unique entry
into one of Malaysia's most successful sectors of the economy -
that of semiconductor assembly and testing, representing about 18.5
per cent of Malaysian exports in 1997.
	   The stockbroking firm believes Unisem should achieve a 1999
price earnings ratio of at least 13 times due to its high-growth
environment and healthy balance sheet.
	   It added that the KLSE Composite Index basket is trading at 13.3
times 1999 earnings, while offering an estimated cumulative
negative earnings growth of 7.5 per cent a year.
	   Unisem, established by ex-Carsem (a subsidiary of Malaysian
Pacific Industries) employees, began operations in late 1992.
	   It was awarded MS ISO 9002 certification in early 1993, and
currently operates from its plant in Perak with a workforce of
1,480. Of this, up to 50 are engineers and over 900 operators.
	   Its major shareholders are Bandar Rasah with a 24.9 per cent
stake and the Walden Group with a 14.9 per cent stake.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
