<HEADLINE>
No new dengue cases last week, JAKARTA POST
</HEADLINE>
No new dengue cases last week, JAKARTA POST &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   JAKARTA POST
   INDONESIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   City hospitals have not received any new dengue patients
beginning last week, an official said Saturday.
	   City Health Office spokeswoman Maryani said the good news seemed
to contradict a World Health Organization prediction that the
country's dengue fever outbreak would peak in May and June.
	   ``This (no new dengue patients) happened due to uncertainty of
the seasons here this year and probably also from the tiny roles of
the recent campaign to eradicate mosquito habitats,'' she said as
quoted by Antara.
	   Aedes aegypti mosquitoes are the carriers of the dengue virus.
	   The outbreak this year, she said, had killed 114 people out of
12,549 patients treated at the 63 hospitals throughout the city.
	   Last month alone, a total of 2,999 dengue patients were admitted
to city hospitals compared to 6,900 sufferers treated in the
previous month, she said. (bsr)
	   
</TEXT>
