<HEADLINE>
No business talks during stopover: Murdoch, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
No business talks during stopover: Murdoch, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Kamarul YunusASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MR RUPERT Murdoch, the News Corp Ltd chairman and owner of Hong
Kong-based Star Television Ltd, visited the Measat Broadcast
Network Systems Sdn Bhd centre in Bukit Jalil yesterday but
insisted he was not on a shopping trip.
	   Murdoch, who was met by pressmen at the departure hall of the
Sultan Abdul Aziz Shah airport in Subang, said he was in the
country for a ``brief stopover''.
	   He said he met Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad and
his deputy and Finance Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim, but did
not discuss business.
	   ``It was a private talk. Nothing about business ... just world
affairs.''
	   Asked if he had discussed the possibility of acquiring stakes in
Malaysian companies, Murdoch said: ``No, nothing to do with my
business. I am just passing by.''
	   Murdoch had arrived in Kuala Lumpur in the morning. Mr T. Ananda
Krishnan, a major shareholder of Measat, was at the airport to send
off the world media magnate to China.
	   Ananda Krishnan said Murdoch, who confessed that Malaysia is a
``wonderful place'' to do business, briefly toured the Measat
Broadcast centre.
	   When asked if the world media magnate was planning to invest in
Measat Broadcast, Ananda Krishnan said: ``He (Murdoch) came to
visit Astro station because Astro uses Star channel ... Astro has
some form of collaboration with them (Star channel).''
	   Measat Broadcast is the operator of Malaysia's first
direct-to-user satellite broadcast services, Astro. Ananda Krishna
has stakes in Measat Broadcast through Usaha Tegas Entertainment
Systems Sdn Bhd, a company owned by trusts associated with his
family.
	   Meanwhile, Ananda Krishnan said Murdoch had expressed confidence
in Malaysia's ability to recover from the current economic
problems.
	   ``(Murdoch) is very supportive of Malaysia. He said Malaysia is
a wonderful place to do business''.
	   
</TEXT>
