<HEADLINE>
Ruling party wins most seats in elections to Parliament chamber
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ In an expected outcome, members of Egypt's
ruling National Democratic Party won a majority in mid-term
elections for the upper house of Parliament, according to results
Monday.
	   Of the 88 seats at stakes in the Shura Council, or Consultative
Council, 72 went to NDP members, including 22 that were won
unopposed, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
	   A re-vote will take place June 14 for the remaining 16 seats,
MENA quoted Interior Minister Habib El-Adly as saying. He did not
say why.
	   President Hosni Mubarak appoints one-third of the Shura
Council's 264 seats, with elections for half the others held every
three years.
	   Among the victorious NDP candidates was the council president
Mustafa Kamal Helmy.
	   Egypt's 13 opposition parties boycotted the elections, saying
they did not trust the polls to be fair. The opposition charged
widespread vote-rigging in the last elections in 1995.
	   The deputies are chosen by popular nationwide vote, but the
upper house has little power, holding only an advisory position to
the lower house, the People's Assembly. The lower house also is
dominated by the NDP.
	   MENA quoted el-Adly as saying that of the 14.3 million eligible
voters, 7.3 million, or 52.1 percent cast their votes during the
balloting Sunday.
	   Of the 628 candidates who entered the race, 19 were excluded as
unworthy by a judicial committee and 190 withdrew.
 &UR; ms/vj
</TEXT>
