<BODY>
<SLUG> POWERHOUSE-JULIA sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Powerhouse Julia, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Powerhouse Julia, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Sharon WongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PETITE Julia Peng looks more like the girl-next-door than a
`powerhouse' songstress but don't let her appearance deceive you.
She is not known as Asia-Pacific's Whitney Houston for nothing.
	   Julia's forte is her ability to hit a level of 22 octaves while
the average singer can only reach 20. However, the unassuming
26-year-old shrugs off such figures, feeling it's not exactly a
feat worth placing so much importance on.
	   ``What is more important is to be able to sing with feeling and
emotion,''
	   she says. ``After all, it is not always necessary to reach such
high notes.''
	   Julia's latest album, Seeing Through You, is a collection of no
less then five music styles - R&AMP;B, world music, skada, the usual
sentimental numbers and opera. She hopes to try all kinds of music
while still hanging on to her first love of R&AMP;B.
	   ``Although I love R&AMP;B, I can't be singing just that or the
audience is bound to get fed-up sooner or later. I need to have
variety.
	   ``A singer's vocals is like an instrument and can be used to
express different things. I want to try everything from a cappella
to Broadway.''
	   And in preparation for expanding her 'instrument', the singer
will be leaving for New York to study vocal training in July or
August.
	   Although Julie admits to having loved singing since she was
three, it was not really her first choice of career.
	   ``I'd always wanted to be a policewoman,'' she reveals. ``But
unfortunately, I failed the entry test for the police academy. Next
on my list was singing... and so here I am.''
	   She began singing in lounges after completing her high school
education and while doing the club circuit, she was discovered by
talent scouts and roped into the recording studio.
	   Although she has released three albums to date, Julia still
finds live performances more stimulating and challenging.
	   ``Singing live has more soul and energy and it doesn't matter
even if you miss a note or two,'' she recalls. ``What you need to
do is to control the audience's feelings.
	   ``As a singer, I am responsible in breaching the gap between
singer and audience.'' Cocking her head to one side and grinning,
Julia proceeds to let us in on her secret in setting the mood for
her audience.
	   ``First, I use my voice to get the audience's attention. Then, I
single out one who is not paying as much attention as the others.
To get him involved, I would ask him to sing along to a part of my
song. It usually works.''
	   In perfect control while on stage, Julia at first hit a problem
in the recording studio.
	   ``The first time I recorded a song, I felt that I sounded really
bad!''
	   she exclaims. ``I couldn't accept that I had sung so badly. This
is because in the studio, every note is amplified and one can't
afford to make the slightest mistake. ``Fortunately, it got better
as I went along and gained more experience.''
	   Well, her debut album itself sold over 150,000 copies in Taiwan
and she was named the Best New Artiste there, so she definitely
couldn't be as bad as she made her first attempt out to be.
	   Now, the lady's biggest dream is to hold a concert with a live
band in attendance. She would also like to take the band into the
recording studio with her! Her dream might soon be coming true as
her recording company has plans for her to invade the China market
as well. But not to worry, she won't forget her fans in Malaysia.
She will be back, she says.
	   Julia was in town recently to plug her latest album which was
released under BMG. With her was label-mate You Hong Ming.
	   Composer-singer You has been on the scene for five years and has
written over 200 songs, many of which became hits sung by Andy Lau,
Mindy Quah and Chiu Hai Zheng. But if you think his music is
beautiful, just wait until you hear him sing.
	   A Day; 10 Thousand Years is You's sixth album and is a
collection of the songs he wrote for other singers. However, there
are two new compositions, namely the title track and Love Me.
	   ``Love Me is a very feminine song and I had some trouble during
the recording,'' You admits. ``I had to find a way to present it
from a guy's point of view. After all, there are moments when men
too need to say `love me'.''
	   Indeed, he sings it wonderfully well too. But because most of
the songs in the album had been popularised by other singers, You
had to make sure he did not end up imitating their style.
	   As a result, he spent more time in the recording studio giving
each one a new life and a touch of himself. After listening to the
album, I am quite sure that You is as good a singer as he is a
composer and when you combine the two... well, you've got a winner.
	   You has plans to compose a number for Julia who was earlier
lamenting that she's never had the opportunity to sing one of his
compositions.
	   ``I want to get to know her better first,'' he says. ``That will
enable me to write something that is suitable for her. We want
quality and not quantity, right?''
	   You loves to travel and is away from home for a large part of
the year.
	   Travelling gives him fresh ideas for composing but laments that
writing lyrics is much more difficult.
	   ``You have to be really experienced to write moving lyrics,'' he
says. ``I think I'll stick to composing.'' Besides Julia, You is
also writing songs for other singers and he would especially like
to write for Jacky Cheung who he feels can really bring out the
essence of the song he sings.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:POWERHOUSE-JULIA sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
