<SLUG> FOREIGN-FIRMS-EYEING sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Foreign firms eyeing Janamanjung stake?, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Foreign firms eyeing Janamanjung stake?, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Wendy LimASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ABOUT 20 foreign companies are said to be eyeing for a stake in
Janamanjung Sdn Bhd, Tenaga Nasional Bhd's wholly-owned
power-producing subsidiary managing the 2,000MW plant in Manjung,
Perak.
	   And with Janamanjung expecting a sizeable cost overrun in
getting the plant ready by 2002, it may just have to turn to one or
more of the foreign suitors.
	   Tenaga executive chairman Datuk Dr Ahmad Tajuddin Ali said while
the company is still looking at ways to manage the project,
``Janamanjung is a possible candidate for foreign direct
investment''.
	   ``It is possible that the total cost of the project may increase
to close to RM7 billion. This would perhaps be too big for
Janamanjung to handle alone,'' he told Business Times.
	   Tenaga had initially expected the cost to be RM5 billion. The
coal-fired plant in Manjung is scheduled to start commercial
operations by the year 2002.
	   Sources said UK-based National Power Plc is one of the parties
interested in Janamanjung. National Power had earlier acquired a 15
per cent sake in Malakoff Bhd which have stakes in two other
independent power producers (IPP), Segari Energy Ventures Sdn Bhd
and Port Dickson Power Bhd.
	   However, the sources did not rule out the possibility of
power-related companies from Japan and Europe teaming up with
Janamanjung.
	   Alternatively, they said Janamanjung may also be absorbed into
its parent company, risking an exposure to the foreign exchange
rate if offshore financing is secured. Without Tenaga's backing,
Janamanjung may be exposed to higher financing costs.
	   Tajuddin said Janamanjung has attracted from about 20 companies,
mostly Asians and Europeans, but no decision has been made.
	   ``Many have shown their interest in Janamanjung, so this means
they see good returns in this project. There are many other factors
to be considered before we accept any offers.
	   ``The Janamanjung project is a priority project, carried out in
consultation with the Government. As such, the final decision will
not be from Tenaga alone,'' he said.
	   While the Government is interested in attracting foreign direct
investment, Tajuddin said the level and the extent of the foreign
participation has yet to be finalised.
	   Tenaga, is looking at all possibilities to ensure the project's
capital expenditure is well managed while maximising opportunities
and returns to the shareholders, the company and consumers.
	   Tenaga is expected to sign today a power purchase agrement (PPA)
with Janamanjung which will see Tenaga paying about 12 sen per KWh
in energy and capacity charges to Janamanjung.
	   Analysts said the PPA will give Janamanjung a pass-through in
fuel cost and may include a possible currency rate fluctuation
clause for the fuel purchases.
	   ``As it is a coal-fired plant, the raw materials will need to be
imported and this will expose the IPP to currency fluctuations;
otherwise it will be difficult for Janamanjung as a base-load
coal-fired plant to make profits,'' an analyst said.
	   The engineering, procurement, and construction contract, which
was believed to be awarded to an European consortium, is expected
to be finalised this month.
	   The project had also passed the Environment Impact Accessment
and construction is expected very soon.
	   
</TEXT>
