<SLUG> REGRETS-KIT-SIANG'S sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAP trio `regrets Kit Siang's further allegations', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
DAP trio `regrets Kit Siang's further allegations', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Cheah Chor SooiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sat. - The three DAP leaders who were suspended
and removed from their posts last Wednesday today expressed regret
that party secretary-general Lim Kit Siang is still making serious
allegations and remarks against them in the Press.
	   National vice-chairman Liew Ah Kim, party treasurer Fung Ket
Wing and national publicity secretary Wee Choo Keong, while
maintaining their innocence, said they would only reply to the
accusations ``at the appropriate moment''.
	   Liew, who is also Member of Parliament for Seputeh, and Fung, a
former MP for Sandakan, were suspended while former Bukit Bintang
MP Wee was removed from his post.
	   ``We are compelled to restrain ourselves at this juncture to
prevent the party's image and reputation from being damaged.
	   ``We have more than sufficient points to reply to Kit Siang's
statements last Thursday and Friday.
	   ``We sincerely hope that our top leaders will immediately stop
making irresponsible and contradictory statements such as saying
the three of us were guilty of causing members' morale to be
affected, party disharmony, confusion among members and plunging
the Malacca committee into dissension and disunity,'' they said in
a joint Press statement.
	   The trio also reiterated their request for an independent and
impartial committee to be set up to investigate the charges against
them.
	   ``We are certain that further or contradictory statements in the
Press will affect the minds of the independent and impartial
committee members who have to investigate the allegations contained
in Kit Siang's statements.
	   ``In yesterday's Press statement, there was an obvious shift
from the earlier allegations to a loss of confidence in us.
	   ``In any event, we are now plunged into confusion by such
statements,''
	   they added.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
