<SLUG> CRANES-GIVE-HUA-A-LEG sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cranes give Hua a leg to stand on, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Cranes give Hua a leg to stand on, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   R. SharminiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HUA Tim Aik is asleep in his easy chair when I stop by his
workplace to have a chat with him. Sleeping on the job? No, I don't
think anyone can ever accuse him of that.
	   Hua, 76, just happened to be taking a hard-earned rest when I
drop in.
	   The old man is a believer in being independent financially.
	   When he retired after 40 years of back-breaking toil in the
construction industry, he took a short rest before he looked around
for something to do.
	   With the help of his wife, Ng Ah Moi, 63, Hua decided to set up
a nursery. That was six years ago. Now the couple are busy, not so
much with tending to their plants, but with a more lucrative trade
- making and selling garden accessories, in particular the
long-legged crane.
	   This bird, much sought after, especially by the Chinese, as
decorative items for the garden, is apparently also a symbol of
longevity.
	   A huge crane greets visitors at the entrance to the nursery.
Another stands smack in the middle of the nursery, down the hill.
	   At any time, visitors to the Too Kuen Nursery in Section 10,
Petaling Jaya, will find Hua busy at work sculpting the cranes.
	   Hua can make between five and six birds a day. Pieces of steel
are used to make the basic framework over which is plastered cement
to shape the body.
	   When the sculpture is done, Ng takes over, waxing it to a shine
before passing it back to Hua for painting and finishing touches.
	   Hua says the two large ones at the entrance and in the nursery
took him about four days to complete.
	   The real crane, which has a red spot on its forehead, he says,
is often found in jungles and is sought after for its medicinal
properties.
	   He takes me to his workshop and shows me the tools he uses to
make the birds. A few completed cranes stand in a circle on a
table.
	   Inside the store, many birds of a similar size are neatly
stacked, waiting to be collected. Keeping them company are a few
toadstools, in white and yellow. These are Hua's best-sellers. He
sells about 20 birds a month. Apart from casual buyers, Hua sells
most of them to ``middlemen''.
	   ``The toadstool is called dong gu and the Chinese like to buy
it,''
	   explains Ng.
	   I also spot a multi-tiered cement structure, shaped somewhat
like a pagoda, waiting to be painted. It is another piece of Hua's
craftsmanship but he sadly says such items are difficult to sell.
So he hardly makes them any more.
	   Hua also makes parrots and other birds ``but it is only the
cranes that are laku''.
	   Hua also makes table-top waterfalls and there are a few examples
of various sizes at the nursery. Two are strategically placed at
the entrance, complete with running water, fish etc.
	   One shelf is filled with porcelain statues of various designs.
	   ``I don't do those,'' he admits. ``They need to be fired in a
kiln. They come from China.''
	   Otherwise, even the garden tables and chairs which visitors
often find useful for a quick rest, are made by him using a cement
mix and painted to look like wood, for a natural look.
	   ``The cement component makes it hardy for outdoor use,''
explains Hua. He laments over the increasing price of cement but
hard work and his principle of being independent and ``sendiri
kerja and jangan kacau anak- anak'' has helped him and his wife
maintain a steady income.
	   THE couple, who live in Petaling Jaya Old Town, are usually at
the nursery by 9am, leaving only at 6pm.
	   Since most of their day is spent in the nursery, it is very much
a second home to them. Modifications have been done to the wooden
shed to keep out the rain.
	   Bags of soil and fertiliser occupy shelves and floor space in
the large office cum temporary shelter. The couple store necessary
food items in the nursery, among them packets of tea and a kettle.
	   For lunch, Ng cooks a simple meal at the nursery.
	   ``My husband likes porridge, so I usually make that for lunch,''
she says.
	   ``The rice cooker comes in very handy here.''
	   She shows me the rice cooker with a mixture of rice and
vegetables inside.
	   Ng, who used to do odd jobs previously to supplement the family
income, is a very cheerful woman who usually tends to potential
customers or visitors to the nursery as Hua is often busy with his
craft.
	   Only mildly proficient in Bahasa Malaysia, she tells me they
have nine children - seven boys and two girls.
	   With some effort in explaining the finer details, she says:
``One son is a carpenter, another is in Australia. He is a chef,
specialising in western food. Another son is a wireman. We also
have a foreman (in a motor firm) in the family, a tourist bus
driver, a teacher, a car salesman, a repairman cum computer
technician and a steel worker. One of our daughters is a
housewife.''
	   On another visit to the nursery, two of their grandchildren were
there as it was the school holidays. Hua Ai Tin, 12, and her
brother Hsiao Teck, 10, were making good use of a garden table and
chairs to finish their school work.
	   ``We come here often. We like to spend time with our
grandparents and help them if necessary,'' says Ai Tin.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
