<BODY>
<SLUG> POMP-AND-ANCIENT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pomp and ancient tradition come alive at Harvard, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Pomp and ancient tradition come alive at Harvard, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Hardev KaurASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HARVARD: Bagpipe music filled the air early on Thursday morning
at the Harvard University campus and at the undergraduate and
graduate housing complexes. It was the wake-up call for 6,236
graduates of Harvard University requring them to make their way to
the Yard for the Commencement ceremony.
	   The ceremony marked their ``graduation'' from students at
Harvard to the alumni of the oldest University in the US with one
of the most recognisable ``brand names'' around the world.
	   The procession to the Yard began early with different routes
taken by advanced degree candidates, graduating classes of seniors
and alumni. The processions were accompanied by the sound of
familiar college songs played by the Harvard University Band. The
academic staff passed by the West front of the Uiversity Hall and
doffed their hats to the statue of John Harvard on his pedestal.
	   With pomp, tradition and lofty rhetoric at the 347th
Commencement Ceremony, Harvard bid its graduates ``well but not
farewell''. They will remain ``connected'' and ``linked'' to each
other from now on and with thousands who have walked Harvard's
hallowed halls and passed through its gates.
	   The open air Tercentenary Theatre, between Memorial, Church and
Widener Library, has witnessed thousands of students pass through
its gates. It was first used as an outdoor amphitheatre in 1936.
	   In keeping with the age old tradition, the University Marshal
adressed the Sheriff of the Middelsex County, ``Mr Sheriff, pray
give us order''. The Sheriff resplendent in a silk top hat, rose
and moved solemnly to the front of the platform - specially set up
for the cemermonies - struck it three times with his silver-topped
staff and proclaimed: ``The Meeting will be in Order''.
	   With a prayer for the day offered by the Chaplain, the ceremony
got underway. It is a ceremony that graduates will remember for a
long time.
	   How could they forget when the whole City of Cambridge stops to
salute them? They have worked hard for this moment. Traffic stops
and the graduates become a ``tourist attraction'' for camera
clicking visitors, locals, family and friends alike.
	   The once a year parade in full Harvard regalia is not to be
missed. The celebrations and day long activities in the City of
Cambridge revolve around the ``big'' day of new Harvard graduates.
	   The Tercentenary Theatre, in Harvard Yard, was ablaze last week
with the reds, blues, greens and golds of the flags of the
University. Three large crimson Harvard Veritas banners with the
ancient shield billowed magestically in the strong winds above the
staircase in front of the Widener Library.
	   In addition, the flags of the 13 undergraduate houses, the
Extension School and the 10 graduate schools of the University
added to the colour of the tradition steeped ceremony.
	   As a reminder of the ancient tradition, when the ceremonies were
conducted in Latin - the conferring of degrees was conducted in
Latin until 1896 - a College senior delivers a salutatory address
in Latin.
	   Harvard still uses the abbrevations for degrees in Latin rather
than in English, for example A.B. ``Artium Baccalaureus' A.M.
``Artium Magister'' and Ph.D ``Philosophiae Doctor''.
	   While much of the ancient tradition is retained, some changes
have been made over the years. In the seventeenth and eighteenth
centuries, for example, candidates for degrees were expected to be
tested academically at the Commencement itself. According to the
records, Bachelor of Arts candidates prepared theses or topics on
which they could be queried, and candidates for the Master of Arts
submitted questions that they were ready to defend.
	   Titles of the theses and questions were printed in advance to be
handed out at Commencement, and visitors are said to have taken the
opportunity to challenge candidates on their knowledge.
	   Today, ``thesis'' applies to the written results of research
submitted by candidates for the Bachelor of Arts degree with
honours in a field, or candidates for doctoral degrees. These are
examined and approved by members of the faculties.
	   Today, the University Marshal calls on the deans of the
different faculties, who then present their candidates for various
degrees to the President and governing boards. It begins with the
advanced degrees of the Faculty of Arts and Sciences while the
graduate schools are presented in the order of their date of
institution.
	   Students from Harvard Business School followed tradition and
waved dollar bills in addition to flags of various countries, those
from John F.
	   Kennedy School of Government tossed inflatable globes, those
from the Design School threw bricks, those from Law threw up hand
cuffs and those from Education had the ABC on their caps.
	   With the sea of caps and gowns of graduates that made up the
audiance at the morning ceremony, friends came family and well
wishers, who came out in their Sunday best and a fashion parade
which ranked with the best of the Derby Race, all of whom added to
the colour and sights.
	   While it was time to send off its graduates into the world,
Harvard also asked its alumni to open their wallets and checque
books to add to its coffers. A total of US$80 millon (US$1  &QC; 
RM3.99) was added to its existing US$13 billion endowment which
ranks it among the top of Fortune's 500.
	   To mark the end of the ceremonies at the Theater, several
neighbouring churches and institutions rang their bells for about
15 minutes as a salute to the graduates, in celebration of the City
of Cambridge and Harvard's 374th Commencement. This is the 10th
consecutive year that the bells have been rung. For years the bell
in the Memorial Church tower was the only bell to acknowledge the
festival rites of Commencement Day.
	   In a bow to early history, when bells of varying tones summoned
people from sleep for prayer, to work or to study, the joyful
salute began at about 11.15 am after the Sheriff of Middlesex
County declared ``The Meeting is Adjourned'' and the University
Band heralded the end of the ceremony.
	   But that was not the end. The day's events continued beyond
Harvard Yard, with each of the Harvard Schools organising their own
individual and more personal Commencement ceremonies.
	   With their degrees in hand the alumni, students and faculty move
``from the Age that is past, to the Age that is waiting before''.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
