<SLUG> NO-ONE-WILL-BE-NEGLECTED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
No one will be neglected (HL), NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
No one will be neglected (HL), NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Rashid Yusof; Alex ChoongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sat. - Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir
Mohamad assured Malaysians that no one will be neglected or their
problems glossed over by the Government during these difficult
economic times.
	   He said everyone, from unemployed workers and traders to small
and big entrepreneurs, would be helped or have their burdens eased
as the situation was not of their own making.
	   The Prime Minister said this in his loyalty speech at the
investiture in conjunction with the 76th birthday of the Yang
di-Pertuan Agong Tuanku Ja'afar at Istana Negara.
	   The King presented honours and awards to 41 recipients.
	   Dr Mahathir said the Government had taken numerous economic
measures, a testimony of which was that the country had not sought
the assistance of international agencies.
	   In this respect, the people's faith in the Government was
crucial as not all of those efforts could be disclosed.
	   He was grateful that various pressures, including bids to
undermine confidence in the Government, split the leadership,
bankrupt Malaysian companies and pit smaller businesses against
bigger ones, have not created chaos.
	   ``The attempt to put the blame on Bumiputera businessmen,
purportedly because the opportunities given to them through
privatisation was the reason for the economic difficulties, too,
has not been effective.''
	   He also warned that the economic problems could not end quickly.
	   ``We must be prepared to face this situation even if it drags on
for some time.
	   ``Our efforts must be grounded on our capabilities and
resilience.
	   ``While we do not discount the role of outsiders in economic
recovery, we cannot be totally dependent on them.
	   ``The Government believes it will be able to eventually resolve
our economic problems, God willing.
	   ``This faith is rooted on the strength of political and social
stability.''
	   Dr Mahathir alluded to the projection made at last year's
ceremony of continued strong growth with low inflation, saying this
had since changed.
	   He said even a rich country would face an economic downturn if
confronted with a 50 per cent currency depreciation, compounded by
plunging share prices.
	   ``Yet, the nation's economy has not become so bad that
international aid has to be sought. However, if we have to seek
assistance, not only would the economy worsen but its management
would be beyond the control of Malaysians as well.
	   ``If this happens, the country's independence will also be
affected.''
	   Dr Mahathir said there were those who felt it would be better to
hand over the management of the economy to international agencies.
	   However, he said, such a transfer of management would not
guarantee recovery. Most countries that received what had been
described as ``international aid'' had seen their economies
worsening, giving rise to political instability, higher
unemployment, lower purchasing power, corporate bankruptcies and
spiralling inflation.
	   
</TEXT>
