<HEADLINE>
Split in DAP widens as branches speak out, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Split in DAP widens as branches speak out, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sat. - The split in the DAP widened today as three
branches came out in support of the three senior party members who
were suspended and removed from their posts.
	   Three Federal Territory branches - Bukit Bintang Tengah, Jalan
Sungai Besi and Pudu - expressed regret that the suspension of its
``two prominent party leaders'' and removal of a third from his
post, was meted out without prior investigation into the
allegations.
	   In Penang, the State DAP said there should be room for
constructive criticism in the party. Chairman Teoh Teik Huat said
leaders and members must be able to exercise their right in
criticising the party.
	   At the same time, party chairman Dr Chen Man Hin called a Press
conference at the DAP headquarters in Petaling Jaya urging members
to remain united against destructive criticisms.
	   He told members that unity was topmost in the leadership's mind
and it was for that reason it had acted against the three.
	   At a Press conference in Malacca on Thursday, party
secretary-general Lim Kit Siang had announced the suspension of
national vice-chairman Liew Ah Kim and treasurer Fung Ket Wing, and
the removal of national publicity secretary Wee Choo Keong from his
post. This followed complaints from the Malacca and Perak DAP
committees.
	   In an open letter to Lim, the three FT branches said the action
contravened the basic rule of natural justice which the party
strongly upheld.
	   It was signed by See Keng Hock, Bowin Ng and Lim Yeong Wah, the
secretaries of the Jalan Sungai Besi, Pudu and Bukit Bintang Tengah
branches, repectively.
	   ``Since we are in the dark and there is public outcry over the
drastic action taken against our three national leaders, we demand
that Kit Siang has a dialogue with us so that we can know the
specific charges against them.
	   ``In simple terms, we want to know what they had actually said
that caused the disunity in Perak and Malacca and why no specific
charges were made against them before the drastic action.''
	   In Ipoh, it was announced that a three-member disciplinary
committee, chaired by Ahmad Nor, will meet on June 17 to conduct an
inquiry into complaints by the Perak DAP against the three.
	   Perak DAP secretary M. Kulasegaran said notices would be sent to
members who attended a party meeting at Tambun Inn on May 24 to
attend the inquiry.
	   The meeting of national party leaders, State committee members
and branch leaders was held after the ``Sympathy, Support and
Solidarity with Lim Guan Eng Round-Table Conference'' held at the
same venue.
	   The action against the three was for ``undermining party morale,
creating confusion, disharmony and disunity among members''.
	   
</TEXT>
