</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> NEED-FOR-INVESTOR sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Need for investor to keep abreast of new realities, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Need for investor to keep abreast of new realities, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Adi SatriaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   LIKE everything else, the psychology of investors is such that
after an initial surprise or shock at any new development, they
will eventually come around to accept the new reality.
	   That is why we have sudden downturns in stock prices at the
initial stages if there are shocks which unexpectedly hit the
market, followed by sharp rebounds reflecting investors' perception
that they have over- reacted to the shocks and then eventually
another pullback in prices which is less severe than the initial
fall.
	   After a while, prices will move up but will not likely be as
sharp as the initial rebound and then will probably stabilise
within a certain range.
	   What has led to the more stable prices is that the intensity of
emotions such as fear and optimism has more or less worked itself
out, and the net effect is that the emotions of those who are
fearful and those who are optimistic that things will improve are
about equally matched.
	   Hence, we find a situation of prices stabilising until such a
time when a new shock breaks out and the market starts tumbling
again and the whole cycle is repeated.
	   Apart from the big shocks which occur now and then, there are
more mundane things such as drastic changes in trading volume which
investors find hard to accept at first, but human psychology is
such that they will see the new volumes as being a fact of life -
or at least trading life.
	   Way back in late 1992, just before the start of the super bull
run in 1993, the trading volumes on the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange
suddenly shot up to over 200 million units a day in one of those
exciting rallies which we have not seen for some time.
	   A trading volume of this scale was a new record, and many
investors thought it would be wonderful if future rallies could
continue to be accompanied by this kind of high volume.
	   This was a record volume but after many months of the super bull
run in the following year, the 200 million unit trading volume
became a routine affair and it became part of the investors'
psychology that if trading was less than this level, the market
could be heading for a correction.
	   But the 200 million unit volume was later considered even low
when trading volumes rose much higher to about a billion units at
the peak of the super bull run towards the end of 1993 and spilling
over to the first week of 1994.
	   When this massive volume was reached, investors' psychology
again shifted and adjusted upwards to the new level and it was
generally assumed that if volume dropped below 500 million units,
the general feeling was that the market was due for a correction.
	   What this reminds us is that in the stock market, almost
everything is relative and what is high today can be low tommorrow,
and what is low today can be seen as high in future when
circumstances change.
	   In the dynamics of the stock market where things constantly
change, the psychology of the investor has to continuously adjust
and keep abreast of the new realities.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:NEED-FOR-INVESTOR sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
