<SLUG> TENAGA-PROPOSES-RM150M sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tenaga proposes RM150m Langkawi power projects, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Tenaga proposes RM150m Langkawi power projects, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Wendy LimASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   TENAGA Nasional Bhd is proposing three transmission and
distribution projects for Langkawi - estimated at RM150 million -
over the next seven years.
	   Tenaga's development proposal for the island says the three
projects are the 132kV and 33kV main intake station in Kuah, the
132kV line from Teluk Apau to Kuah and the 132kV line from Kuah to
Ulu Melaka.
	   TNB Engineers Sdn Bhd managing director Encik Tajudin Ariff said
when the projects are completed, the island will have a closed ring
electricity supply system.
	   This will ensure non-disruption of electricity supply if there
is a damage to the transmission line.
	   For added security, Langkawi will also be connected to the
National Grid.
	   The current maximum demand for Langkawi is 85MW to meet the
needs of 20,500 customers.
	   Maximum demand is expected to increase to 134MW by August 31
2000 and 195MW in 2005.
	   Currently, electricity is supplied to the island through a 68MW
gas turbine and three 132kV submarine cables, two with 100MVA
(megavolt amp)capacity and the other with 150MVA capacity.
	   Tenaga recently launched a 27km oil submarine cable project
across the ocean from Perlis to Langkawi costing RM130 million.
	   The project is undertaken by a consortium of companies
comprising Federal Power, Itochu and Fujikura. The consortium will
take 15 months to complete the project.
	   Tajudin said in the first three months, the consortium will
undertake a route survey in Langkawi, which will run concurrently
with the manufacturing of the cables and accessories in Japan.
	   ``The power cables are custom-made and when ready, they will be
transported using a special barge. It will take about five weeks
for the cables to reach Langkawi.
	   ``The power cables and fibre optic cables will be buried
simultaneously using a submerged hydroplow located behind the
barge,'' he said, explaining the power cable-laying work.
	   For this project, the oil-filled submarine cables will be used.
The oil will act as an electrical insulation and a cooling agent
for the cables.
	   Besides the submarine cables, the team will also attach a fiber
optic connection which will serve as a ``communications line'' for
the submarine cables.
	   These ``communications lines'' will ``inform'' Tenaga's
transmission division, through signals, if there are any problems.
	   Laying of the power cables, Tajudin explained, has to be carried
out carefully as the cables are laid nearly 2.5m below the seabed.
	   ``While the work is not difficult, the location needs to be
precise,'' he added.
	   In the same area, Tenaga has also laid two 132kV submarine
cables of 100MVA capacity. The cables are about 1km apart.
	   ``Due care is also taken to ensure that boats or ships that are
passing through the area do not damage these cables when they drop
their anchor.
	   The area is also marked by a buoy,'' Tajudin said adding that
most of the work iscarried out by Malaysians.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
