<SLUG> BC-Britain-Au Pair, 1st Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fired lawyer accuses Woodward mother of submitting phony bill
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Woodwards denying forgery

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Dan Sharp, husband of the lawyer fired by Louise
Woodward, on Monday accused the mother of the British former au
pair of submitting a forged bill for accommodation to a fund for
her defense, Sky TV reported.
	   Susan Woodward denies the allegations, her British lawyer Paul
Barrow said Monday night.
	   Sharp, an attorney whose British-born wife, Elaine Whitfield
Sharp, was fired by Woodward last week, said a dlrs 15,400
(9,131.50 pound) bill purportedly for four months accommodation for
Sue Woodward at the Sharp home was phony.
	   ``It is a forgery, and I would note a poor one at that,'' Sharp
said, shown on Sky examining the bill at his home in Marblehead,
Mass., near Boston.
	   ``I don't believe we ever charged her (Sue Woodward) a dime for
anything, but we certainly never charged her dlrs 15,400 for
anything,'' added Sharp.
	   The bill showed charges for accommodating Mrs. Woodward last
year during her daughter's trial in the death of an 8-month-old
baby in the young Briton's care.
	   ``This is not a forgery,'' said Barrow, the lawyer for Mrs.
Woodward and her husband Gary. ``That statement of account was
handed to the Woodwards by the Whitfield Sharps and any allegations
of impropriety are absolutely denied by the Woodwards.''
	   Barrow added: ``As far as my clients are concerned that is the
end of the matter. Sue is more worried about her daughter than this
nonsense that the Whitfield Sharps are bringing out for reasons
best known to themselves.''
	   A jury convicted, 6th graf pvs
	   (mj/eml)
</TEXT>
