<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Nigeria-Abacha,0436 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Nigerian players not told of Abacha death
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Nigeria's World Cup soccer players were not
immediately told of the death of the country's dictator Monday
because team officials could not get confirmation of the news from
home, a spokesman said.
	   News of Gen. Sani Abacha's death broke while the squad was
holding a closed practice at its training ground in Ressons, a
village in the countryside north of Paris.
	   After the session, the players went to their guarded, secluded
hotel for dinner.
	   ``We seem not to have any official confirmation,'' Nigerian
Football Association spokesman Austin Mgbolu said in a telephone
interview.
	   ``We tried, but could not reach Nigeria. We are waiting for word
from the Nigerian ambassador'' to France, he added. ``The team
manager is trying to get through to Abuja.''
	   There had been speculation earlier this year that Abacha might
make a rare public appearance at France '98.
	   In Nigeria, family friends said Abacha died of a heart attack.
The official News Agency of Nigeria confirmed only that he died
Monday.
	   Abacha came to power in a 1993 coup and faced worldwide
condemnation for his hard-line regime.
	   Members of the West African nation's soccer team have waged a
battle with the government over World Cup pay, meeting several
times with the country's military rulers. The players reportedly
rejected an offer of dlrs 6,000 a person per match, demanding dlrs
8,000 each.
	   The country's political situation has affected the squad
repeatedly. As recently as Friday, the national soccer federation
threatened to pull out of a World Cup warmup match in Amsterdam
because of human rights protests in the Netherlands.
	   An advertisement in the Nigeria-Netherlands match program
featured pictures of 12 prominent Nigerian activists who have been
imprisoned or harassed by the country's rulers.
	   The 12 activists made up an ``alternative Nigerian team,''
organizers of the protest said. The advertisement was placed by a
group of Dutch human rights groups, trade unions and religious
bodies.
	   In addition, Nigeria did not participate in the last two
editions of the African Cup of Nations.
	   It was barred from this year's tournament in January after
boycotting the 1996 tournament in South Africa. The reason for
Nigeria's non-participation is thought to be anger over President
Nelson Mandela's call for sanctions against the military regime for
hanging nine dissidents.
	   (hjf)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-Nigeria-Abacha; CT:s; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
