<SLUG> ENDAU-ROMPIN-HAS-FEWER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Endau-Rompin has fewer than five rhinos, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Endau-Rompin has fewer than five rhinos, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Faezah IsmailASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sat. - Fewer than five rhinoceros remain in the
Endau-Rompin area from the 20 to 25 animals five years ago,
Department of Wildlife and National Parks' surveys have revealed.
	   The loss of rhinoceros habitat, forest encroachment and poaching
have been cited as the main reasons for the sharp drop in their
numbers.
	   ``Unless urgent measures are taken, the remaining rhinoceros
would be extinct by the year 2000,'' said department veterinarian
and rhinoceros conservation officer Dr Zainal Zahari Zainuddin.
	   ``Eco-tourism activities and development within Endau-Rompin
must be done in a manner which is sensitive to the needs of the
rhinoceros.''
	   With the decline of the Endau-Rompin population, the total count
of rhinoceros in the peninsula is estimated to be between 50 and
60.
	   Besides Endau-Rompin, the three other major rhinoceros habitats
are Taman Negara (33 to 40 animals), Ulu Selama (six) and Belum
(10).
	   Stragglers (one to three) are said to move around several
States.
	   The Endau-Rompin situation will severely cripple Malaysia's plan
to conserve the Sumatran rhinoceros which the World Conservation
Union has assessed as the most critically endangered of the five
living rhinoceros species found in the world.
	   Altogether there are 250 to 400 Sumatran rhinoceros and they are
distributed in Sumatra, Peninsular Malaysia and Sabah. A few may
survive in Sarawak, Thailand, Myanmar and Laos but their existence
is unconfirmed and the viability of such populations is unlikely.
	   The first survey, undertaken in 1995, disclosed that there were
only five animals left.
	   To confirm the findings, the department took another inventory
the following year which recorded the same count.
	   The census noted rhinoceros tracks on the eastern and northern
parts of Endau-Rompin.
	   But a shift has taken place. Patrols by rhinoceros protection
units last year found no fresh rhinoceros tracks on the eastern and
northern parts of Endau-Rompin but discovered only three in the
western block of the forest.
	   ``Rapid development and ever-increasing visitor arrivals on the
eastern side of Endau-Rompin have pushed the rhinoceros to the
west. The shift is obvious,'' said Zainal.
	   Prime lowland areas in the peninsula, including parts of
Endau-Rompin, were mainly converted to oil palm plantations between
1974 and 1990.
	   ``In the case of Endau-Rompin, these sites had served as a
buffer for the core rhino habitat. But the change to agriculture
followed by infrastructure development had made the rhinoceros
areas vulnerable to disturbance and poaching,'' said department
head of wildlife management unit E. Sivananthan.
	   Between 1976 and 1977, the Pahang side of Endau-Rompin was
heavily logged, particularly the areas of Sungai Pukin and Sungai
Jemai. Towards the end of 1980 and the early 1990s, logging was
also apparent in Johor.
	   Seven years ago, 49,000ha of the core rhinoceros habitat in
Endau-Rompin was gazetted by the Johor Government as the
Endau-Rompin National Park.
	   The park is managed by Johor Parks Corporation under the Johor
Government and not the department.
	   Conservation sources said insufficient trained manpower to run
an important conservation site had resulted in ever-increasing
visitor numbers.
	   Stories of people venturing into the park in four-wheel-drive
vehicles are widely reported. In fact, four-wheel-drive expeditions
have been organised into Endau-Rompin.
	   The Pahang side of Endau Rompin has yet to be declared a
national park but some 40,000ha of the forest were gazetted as a
wildlife reserve by the State Government in 1986.
	   Still, the gazetting was done under the National Land Code and
enforcement powers were given to the district of Rompin.
	   That means the department has no control over movement of people
into the conservation area.
	   While the Sumatran rhinoceros in Endau-Rompin is protected by
the Federal Government, its habitat is looked after by two State
Governments.
	   ``For the rhino's sake and that of other wildlife, the two
approaches have to be integrated. Wildlife conservation is both
about safeguarding the animal and the ecosystem of which it is a
part,'' said Sivananthan.
	   Even though there is a national park advisory committee in Johor
to look into the co-ordination and integration of conservation
matters in Endau- Rompin, there are insufficient resources
including trained manpower on site.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
