<HEADLINE>
Big fuss over a small pill, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Big fuss over a small pill, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Shareem AmryASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   VIAGRA is at hand! Also known as THE magic bullet, this highly
successful, pharmaceutical tongkat ali has made a huge
international splash since it went on the market over a month ago.
	   Half of humanity has gone gaga over these happy pills, earning
prescribing doctors the nicknames ``Dr Love'' and ``Dr Feelgood''
like never before, and creating such a craze that these things are
selling for big money on the black market.
	   The scene has been much the same here, where men have reportedly
swamped the local branch of US-based Pfizer Inc, Viagra's maker,
with anxious inquiries about when the pill would make it to
Malaysian shores.
	   People aren't talking about the India-Pakistan nuclear arms
race, schoolyard killings or when we can expect a cure for AIDS
anymore. No, it's all about Viagra now: how to get it, where to get
it, how much is enough and how much more would be better.
	   What gives here? I guess what took me by surprise was just how
huge the demand was for this anti-impotence wonder.
	   Popular culture is largely soaked in testosterone, and with all
this clamouring assurance of virility and machismo, to have guys
suddenly go weak at the knees at Viagra's appearance was an
eye-opener.
	   I'm not trying to be insensitive here. You have to admit that
the rush for Viagra is a curious phenomenon, unchecked even by a
few scattered deaths of early users. This is serious business. But
it's also difficult to be sympathetic when you hear stories such as
the one about the lout who, once on Viagra, was able to perform in
the bedroom with his girlfriend for the first time in four years,
and then promptly left her for someone else.
	   This poor woman stood by her man for four years - four years! -
unbothered by his little problem, and for her loyalty and
generosity of heart she gets dumped?
	   Okay, so it's just one case. I'm sure that for every such story,
there are 50 more that offer glowing testimonials about how Viagra
has ushered marriages and relationships into their renaissance
period.
	   But it's still disturbing to think that there is now a handy
pill that can give men what they crave for within the hour.
	   A lot of problems can be traced to the erection, or at least the
masculinity that it symbolises. To have more men swaggering around
the streets with so much self-assurance within easy reach is
disconcerting, to say the least.
	   I hear men talk about Viagra in tones of self-congratulatory
ease nowadays. They seem comforted by the knowledge that such a
pill even exists. And what are we women doing?
	   Guys, you'd be mistaken if you thought all of womanhood have
rejoiced alongside with you at Viagra's appearance.
	   Women I know are laughing about the mad scramble for these
pills. But women have to be prepared too, so for now, everybody is
thinking up fresh permutations of the ``Sorry honey, I have a
headache,'' excuse.
	   
</TEXT>
