<HEADLINE>
UN Study Says Lack of SMEs Slows Down RP Growth, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
UN Study Says Lack of SMEs Slows Down RP Growth, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The lack of middle-sized companies in the Philippines explained
the country's sluggish march to economic development, a report by
the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (Unctad)
said.
	   The study said the ''missing middle'' may be holding the key to
sustainable economic development in the Philippines, and that
government should take steps to protect small and medium
enterprises (SME).
	   Heavy dependence on large companies, the Unctad study pointed
out, proved to be disadvantageous to Indonesia whose economy used
to be one of the most dynamic in Asia.
	   ''Indonesia and the Philippines have relied on large firms and
now have a 'missing middle' that leaves their SME sectors
relatively underdeveloped and less-internationally competitive than
might be desired.'' ''The challenge of development in Indonesia and
the Philippines is the shortage of smaller local firms with the
ability to grow and act as clients for, or subcontractors to larger
domestic or foreign firms.'' ''In Indonesia and the Philippines,
over 65% of output is produced by large firms with more than 500
employees.'' On the other hand, smaller firms with fewer than 100
employees accounted for ''less than 10% of output in Indonesia and
some 13% in the Philippines.'' In more developed Asian countries
like Singapore and Taiwan, large firms produce only 59% and 39% of
output, respectively while smaller firms account for 15% and 39%.
	   Japan and South Korea, for their part, have included SMEs in
their respective development strategies.
	   Among the developing countries, Burma and Vietnam had the least
official support for SMEs Unctad also noted in its report that
current levels of foreign direct investments (FDI) in Asia by SMEs,
represented only 10% of the total.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
