<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Heel bruise keeps South African captain out of training
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: REPEATING to add soccer to slugline &QL; 
 &UR; By TOM COHEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VICHY, France (AP) _ A bruised heel kept South African captain
Lucas Radebe out of Bafana Bafana's first World Cup practice in
France, but coach Philippe Troussier believes the Leeds United
defender will play in Friday's opening match against France.
	   Radebe, who anchors the back line and also can play in the
midfield, got hurt near the end of Saturday's 1-1 draw with Iceland
in South Africa's final World Cup tune-up.
	   After a fast-paced practice Monday evening at Vichy's Omnisports
Complex watched by about 500 people, Troussier said Radebe needed
to rest after the long English season and his South African
commitments.
	   ``He just needs 48 hours,'' Troussier said. ``He's played in
every warmup game and he needs a break.''
	   Team doctor Victor Ramathesele said Radebe's injury had
responded well to treatment so far, but he was unable to guarantee
Radebe would be ready to take on the French in Marseilles on
Friday.
	   ``I'm fairly optimistic,'' Ramathesele said. ``He's certainly
better than he was on Saturday.''
	   During a half-field attacking drill Monday, third-string
goalkeeper Andre Arendse appeared to twist or bruise his left knee
and walked off grimacing.
	   Arendse, of Fulham in England, was the starter when South Africa
won the African Nations Cup in 1996, but was dropped after former
coach Clive Barker resigned in December. He is expected to back up
Hans Vonk and Brian Baloyi at the World Cup.
	   The crowd at the training field applauded as the players
practiced attacking patterns with wide passes and crosses that led
to hard shots on goal.
	   South African players expressed surprise at the enthusiastic
reception received in the central France town, where hundreds of
people welcomed their arrival Sunday night and a crowd of about 60
waited outside the team hotel for autographs Monday afternoon.
	   ``It's like a dream,'' said defender Willem Jackson, who has
played his pro soccer in South Africa. ``I thought maybe it was
going to be quiet, we wouldn't have support or people watching
us.''
	   It is South Africa's first World Cup appearance after being
banned for 28 years from international soccer until 1992 because of
apartheid.
	   (tsc/jw)
</TEXT>
