<BODY>
<SLUG> COOL-RIDE-IN-A-HOT-SEAT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cool ride in a hot seat, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Cool ride in a hot seat, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ben D'CunhaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ANYONE who has driven a Saab before would have realised at once
that it's no ordinary car. It has an identity of its own and the
performance is second to none - whatever the class.
	   Building on these fine traditions, the Swedish car manufacturer
has produced a mid-range luxury model, the Saab 9-5.
	   Saab started out as a plane manufacturer and still does it with
great success for the European market. It is evident then that some
of the latest developments in aeronautic engineering have gone into
the development of Saab cars, giving them an edge, whether it's in
the passenger cockpit or in engine technology.
	   The 9-5 series available for the moment in Malaysia is the
2.3-litre series.
	   Saab has used its turbocharging expertise to produce the
EcoPower engine, which uses light boost only, giving smooth power
and reasonable economy. It was first introduced in the 900 series
in 1993 and further developed for the 1997 Saab 9-5 series.
	   Fuel consumption is rated at up to 9kpl (26mpg) in mixed driving
for the auto transmission. According to the manufacturers, the Saab
9-5 doesn't follow the beaten track. It forges its own way ahead -
and it does so with aplomb.
	   You have to get behind the wheel to fully appreciate the finer
points of this car. Performance is unmatched in its class. The
EcoPower engine is a lightning-quick and tough turbo-charged power
source, with extrarodinary torque at the very bottom of the rev
range; yet at the same time, it is exceptionally clean.
	   The engine's maximum torque becomes available at just 1800 rpm,
which corresponds to 80-85kph in top gear, and it can be pushed to
the limit without yielding. It drives with the precision of a much
smaller car and has a Ferrari-like urge. The speedometer reads a
maximum speed of 240kph.
	   We are inclined to think this is no exaggeration. We managed to
get it up to 200kph, where permissible, without too much effort.
	   Our test car was equipped with a four-speed electronically
controlled automatic transmission with three programmes and direct
mechanical lock up in third/fourth gear.
	   It's a car you would most certainly prefer to drive rather than
be driven around in. Like the popular 900, the Saab 9-5 is roomy,
even for an executive class, with comfortable back seat, lots of
leg and headroom and a massive boot.
	   It's reputed to be one of the safest cars on the road, with
impressive crash-protection built into the design. This Saab has
one of the most supportive and comfortable seats.
	   ``There's an old saying among aviators that one flies `by the
seat of one's pants'. That applies also to driving a car,'' a
member of the Saab design team was reported to have said.
	   That old saying has helped Saab determine the degree of firmness
of the seats in the Saab 9-5. If they are too soft, the car's
movements are difficult to interpret, and if too hard, they soon
become uncomfortable.
	   The driver's seat has different adjustment parameters, including
lumbar support. Topping the driving environment are ventilated
front seats. I suspect it comes with a heater too. So my mate ran
her fingers through the switches and in no time I was on a hot seat
despite the fact that the air- con was running at a cool 18 Degrees
Celsius. Not that it's something we would appreciate in a tropical
climate like ours.
	   In classic Saab style, the 9-5 has a wrap-around instrument
panel which tones off into a gently rounded centre console.
Everything is within reach and easy to overview.
	   True to Saab tradition, the ignition key is positioned
conveniently between the seats. The audio system developed just for
the 9-5, provides concert hall entertainment.
	   The Saab 9-5 is quiet. Background noise in naturally less
subdued at motorway speeds - the car shouldn't be fully isolated or
the driver won't benefit from any feedback. Yet you can listen to
your favourite music without touching the volume control when you
join the highway - the system automatically turns up the volume as
speed rises. To switch to another station, the steering wheel has
conveniently positioned remote-control buttons.
	   Among the vast array of advanced safety features are: ABS
(anti-lock) brakes with electronic braking force distribution and
large disc brakes all round; tuned front suspension with MacPherson
struts featuring direct-action gas-filled dampers; multi-link rear
axle with individual suspension of the rear wheel which offers
excellent comfort and road grip; exceptionally rigid bodyshell for
good on-road behaviour and high crash safety; strong door pillars,
sill beams and cross-members which dissipate impact energy in a
side collision; night panel subdues non-essential instrument
illumination for safer night driving and; high pressure windscreen
washer with three twin-spray nozzles.
	   The Saab Safeseat concept consists of: active head restraints in
the front seats to reduce the risk of whiplash injuries; airbags up
front including two on the sides; sturdy side-impact beams and
impact-absorbing material inside the doors; anti-submarining
protection for all five seats; three-point inertia-reel belts for
all five seats; load shifting protection.
	   Auto Concessionaires Sdn Bhd is the local distributor of Porsche
and Saab vehicles.
	   The Saab 9-5 2.3-litre EcoPower is priced at RM269,000 and th8e
2-litre, also a turbocharged straight-four, is at RM221,000. A
3.0-litre V6 EcoPower rounds up the 9-5 series, but is not
available in Malaysia as yet.
	   
</TEXT>
