</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BROKERAGE-FIRMS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PSE Denies Negligence in Monitoring Brokerage Firms, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
PSE Denies Negligence in Monitoring Brokerage Firms, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Rodel A. AlzonaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Philippine Stock Exchange (PSE) has denied negligence in the
monitoring of violations committed by brokerage firms. In a letter
to the Securities and Exchange commission (SEC), the local bourse
said it had been monitoring 20 complaints from investors since the
start of the year.
	   The PSE has received a lot of criticism from the SEC for not
being able to detect the trading violations allegedly committed by
EBC Securities Inc.
	   The Commission temporarily suspended the operations of the
brokerage firm until July pending its compliance with the rules of
the Revised Securities Act (RSA).
	   However, the PSE clarified that the four-man team sent by the
Commission to oversee the functions and activities of its
compliance and surveillance department (CSD) had focused on one
complaint that was never entertained.
	   ``We believe that 19 out of 20 is not a particularly bad batting
average for the CSD securities investigation division considering
it was only formally created in November 1997, plus the rules of
procedure for the entire CSD was drafted only in October 1997,''
the letter said.
	   PSE President Jose Luis Yulo Jr. said regular audits were only
conducted early this year as the Exchange embarked on an
information campaign in 1997 to get its member-brokers acquainted
with all the rules.
	   According to a reliable source, the SEC is again poised to
suspend the operation of another brokerage firm for multiple
violations of the RSA including the net capital rule, insider
trading, and the use of dummy accounts.
	   In the same letter, the PSE dismissed allegations they had not
been referring to the Commission all member-brokers that were found
to have violated the net capital rule of the RSA.
	   ``The net capital accounts of member-brokers are being submitted
simultaneously to the Commission and the Exchange, and both the
brokers and exchange department (BED) and our compliance audit
department (CAD) evaluate the monthly submissions made by
member-brokers,'' the letter said.
	   The PSE added: ``It happens sometimes that the CAD's evaluation
do not tally with SEC's evaluation of the net capital submissions
resulting in findings that are not really identical.''
	   The bourse explained that the inconsistent results were at times
``informally discussed'' between BED and CAD officers, which the
PSE considers a form of ``validation or reconciliation'' between
the findings of both parties.
	   The PSE also explained that it cannot touch brokerages violating
the net capital rule because the bourse has yet to adapt it as one
of its own rules.
	   ``The reason why the PSE could not as yet impose sanctions for
net capital deficiencies of member-brokers is that it has yet to
adopt the RSA/SEC rules as our own rules and that the PSE has not
yet come out with a table of sanctions for each violation of the
RSA/SEC rules,'' the letter explained.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BROKERAGE-FIRMS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
