<HEADLINE>
Call not to increase prices of food, drinks, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Call not to increase prices of food, drinks, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KENINGAU, Sat. - Coffeeshop and restaurant owners should refrain
from increasing prices of food and drinks to gain more profit,
Deputy Chief Minister Datuk Joseph Kurup said.
	   He said there were many reports from consumers that drink prices
at some coffee shops had increased.
	   Kurup said some coffee shop owners had increased the price of
coffee without milk to 80 sen from the original 60 sen, while the
price of iced drinks has risen from RM1 to RM1.50.
	   ``Such an increase cannot be accepted as it is a burden on
consumers,'' he said when met after attending the Parti Bersatu
Rakyat Sabah annual conference at a hotel here today.
	   Kurup, who is Resource Development and Enterprise Minister, said
people in food businesses should help the Government curb inflation
by reducing the price of food items.
	   ``They should not view the economic downturn as an opportunity
to increase the price of food and drinks. After all, items like
coffee are locally produced and not imported,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
