<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-LPGA-Sorenstam,0319 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sorenstam playing a little less, enjoying it more
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By R.B. FALLSTROM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ST. LOUIS (AP) _ Annika Sorenstam is maximizing her time on the
LPGA tour.
	   Sorenstam is third on the 1998 money list despite playing in
only 10 of a possible 17 tournaments. After winning dlrs 90,000 in
the Michelob Light Classic in a sudden-death playoff against Donna
Andrews on Sunday, the reward for her first victory of the season
was two weeks off.
	   ``I've been playing a lot of tournaments the last few years and
last year I achieved more things than I ever thought I could,''
Sorenstam said. ``I decided this year I'm just going to try to
relax a little, enjoy my weeks off and maybe even have some more
weeks off.
	   ``I have a lot of interests outside the golf course.''
	   After taking a break, Sorenstam will play two straight weeks,
then take another week off.
	   ``I just try to play when I'm ready,'' Sorenstam said. ``If I'm
not ready, I don't come out.
	   ``The last few years I've been getting slower to motivate myself
to come out, but when I do come out I love it even more.''
	   Last year, Sorenstam played in 22 events. She won six and was
LPGA Player of the Year with record earnings of dlrs 1.236 million.
	   This year, she's behind Andrews and Liselotte Neumann with dlrs
387,765. Andrews has played in 13 tournaments, Neumann 11.
	   One tournament that'll remain on Sorenstam's must list is the
Michelob Light. She's won it three of the past four years.
	   Sorenstam said it's a course for the cerebral golfer, which
suits her game. She used her driver only five times in the final
round on the tight Forest Hills Country Club layout.
	   On the 18th hole, she used a 3-wood for her tee shot on both
playoff holes.
	   ``For some reason, I always play well when I use my brain,''
Sorenstam said.
</TEXT>
