COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   From the angle that ribs make where they join the bottom of the
breast bone, just above the soft stomach area, you can determine if
you are prone to obesity or not.
	   Dr. Victor Baker calls this the ``Angle of Obesity.'' Since this
encompasses the abdominal area and touches the heart and lungs, the
angle of obesity gives us an insight to the condition of the organs
in this area. A narrow-angled (about 60 degrees) person has large
lungs and better stamina, which means that we can expect such a
person to have a large volume of efficient lung remaining even with
a pneumonia attack.
	   However, without sufficient exercise, much of the upper part of
the lungs will be unused. This poorly ventilated upper part of the
lung is the common site of tuberculosis (TB). It would, thus, seem
logical to treat TB with exercises using this part of the lung, as
well as treating the disease with the necessary medications.
	   Lung ventilation can be quite great in the narrow-angled person
because of the large range of movement possible in the lower ribs
and diaphragm. In the large-angled (around 130 degrees or more)
person, the movement of the chest is shallow.
	   Fat people are considered to be more susceptible to bronchitis
and other chest conditions; though not yet proven, the fatness is
blamed. It would seem more logical to look at the wide angle and
the small lung volume.
	   Heart disease is another problem usually related to fatness. In
the wide-angled person, the heart is likely to be relatively
smaller because of smaller chest cavity. It tends to lie
horizontally so that the main artery of the heart (the aorta) forms
a spiral, rather than the ``single plane''
	   curve of this artery in the narrow-angled. This spiral spins the
blood which has been pumped from the heart under great pressure (a
phenomenon which may affect the laying down of cholesterol and
other substances in the walls of the blood vessels), causing it to
impinge more on one area of the artery. Research may well establish
that this spiraling of the aorta plays a part in the incidence of
aortic aneurysm (ballooning on an artery), arteriosclerosis
(hardening of the arteries), and angina (reduced blood supply to
the heart itself).
	   Another organ near the angle of obesity is the liver. The liver
of a small-angled person is generally smaller because his abdominal
cavity is smaller. A smaller liver implies greater risk if
hepatitis is contracted or if cirrhosis develops.
	   Ulcers are said to be more common in the thin, anxious type of
person. The problem is how to measure worry. Facial expression and
an excess of nervous energy have traditionally given rise to people
being labeled as ``worry bugs.'' It has been found out that the
incidence of ulcers is directly related to the angle of obesity.
These people may look more worried because they have many facial
creases but there is no evidence to indicate that they worry more
than the fat person (with a wide angle of obesity) whose faces are
unlined.
	   In fact, when a fat person loses weight rapidly, skin creases
appear and the face looks less jovial even though the person may be
much happier because of the weight loss. The ``excess of nervous
energy'' may simply be an abundant supply of physical energy
possessed by the narrow-angled person who has greater stamina and
carries a lighter frame. The ulcer may develop due to: 1) a
relative excess of acid production and/or concentration in the
narrow-angled person's stomach; or 2) the valve at the bottom of
the stomach does not function efficiently since the curves of the
stomach and intestines are sharp (since the abdomen is cramped for
space).
	   These sharp curves can delay the acidified food in its passage
through the first part of the intestines (the duodenum), or cause
digestive juices from the stomach to impinge on the side wall of
the duodenum instead of being squirted along it.
	   
</TEXT>
