<SLUG> BREEDING-CATTLE-IN-OIL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Breeding cattle in oil palm plantations, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Breeding cattle in oil palm plantations, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Eirmalasare BaniASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THERE is some truth in the Malay proverb, Lebih Mudah Menjaga
Sekandang Lembu Dari Menjaga Seorang Anak Gadis, which implies that
it is much easier to handle a herd of cattle than to care for a
daughter.
	   The integrated farms of Ladang Bukit Kerisek in Pahang and
Ladang Bukit Bujang in Johor, which see cattle being bred in oil
palm plantations, have proven this.
	   No cages or additional food are needed for this effort. The
cattle are controlled with a RM3,000 electric fence system,
depending on the size of the grazing area. The electric fence will
give cattle a mild jolt if they stray out of their grazing area.
	   The cattle are divided into two groups but if the number is too
large, they may be divided into more groups.
	   These cattle are fed through a `rotational grazing' system that
takes between six and eight weeks. There is also a `holding yard'
where cattle are placed temporarily for a bi-monthly health checks.
	   And contrary to popular belief, cattle breeding and oil palm
cultivation do go hand-in-hand. Ladang Bukit Kerisek and Ladang
Bukit Bujang have successfully dispelled the notion that such an
integrated farming concept do not work.
	   ``People sais it couldn't work ... the cattle will eat the young
trees and make the ground compact as they trample on it,'' Pahang
State Farmers Organisation (Pasfa) general manager Abdul Rahman
Ismail said.
	   ``These are negative sentiments,'' he told journalists visiting
Ladang Bukit Kerisek recently.
	   Palm oil is, in fact, the best crop for integrated farming as
cattle cannot be bred in open field due to the excessive heat. The
oil palm trees provide suitable shade for these animals.
	   Pasfa, the owner of the 700 ha Ladang Bukit Kerisek, began
planting palm oil in 1990. Its integrated farming project was
initially placed under the supervision of the Malaysian
Agricultural and Research Institute (Mardi) in 1993 with 100 female
cows provided by the Pahang government.
	   Mardi also contributed three male cows which were mixed hybrids
of local cows from Kedah and Kelantan and French, Brazilian and
Indian species such as Hereford, Charoleis, Lemousine, Simentol,
Nellour and Brahman.
	   ``The idea to integrate cattle breeding and palm oil cultivation
was an old one but the potential was only clearly seen recently,''
he said.
	   Abdul Rahman said the integrated farming in Ladang Bukit Kerisek
is to maximise profit through efficient management. It is estimated
that such activity can give an additional income of between RM150
and RM200 per ha annually.
	   ``It is a good long-term investment as we could get more than 40
per cent of return every year,'' he said, adding that each cow only
needs about RM1.40 per day for food as the grass is free.
	   He said a 1.5 acre land is allocated for each cow and the farm
can save up to between RM36 and RM60 per ha on weeding cost.
	   ``We can get about RM500 for each cow that is old enough to be
sold,''
	   Abdul Rahman said, adding that only three workers are needed to
handle 1,000 heads of cattle.
	   He said Pasfa is also negotiating with the state government to
develop another 2,000 acres land to breed more cattle. Last year,
Ladang Bukit Kerisek produced 13,333 tonnes of beef (about 19
tonnes per ha). They expect to get 16,800 tonnes this year.
	   It also aims to become a catalyst to the country's meat industry
and produce about RM2 million worth of meat by the year 2000.
	   Abdul Rahman said, however, that palm oil cultivation will
continue to be its core business. The Pahang Government recently
approved a 3,600 acre land to be developed by Pasfa this year.
	   He said another 7,800 acres of palm oil plantation, which is
jointly managed with Pahang UMNO, will begin to see its profit this
year.
	   Pasfa was also awarded RM5 million by the state government as a
soft loan to develop 20,000 acres of unused land, he said.
	   Meanwhile, Ladang Bukit Bujang manager Hasbullah Karmain said
the farm made RM245,881 from the sale of cattle last December.
	   The 3,704ha palm oil plantation was awarded to the Perladangan
Peladang Johor Sdn Bhd by the state government in January 1992. The
farm also has its own factory to process the oil palm.
	   Before cattle, Ladang Bukit Bujang bred 418 sheeps. However, the
project was scrapped as there is low demand for sheepmeat.
Furthermore, the sheeps suffered from various diseases and were
attacks by wild dogs.
	   The farm lost about RM14,000 in the sheep project last year,.
	   Perladangan Peladang Johor continued with cattle breeding, aimed
at saving cost of weeding and to secure additional income for the
farm. It is also aimed at giving the farmers the working
experience.
	   
</TEXT>
