<HEADLINE>
More Contagion Effect?, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
More Contagion Effect?, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Cilette __. LiboroASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Market Maker
	   The stock market reacted to foreign concerns last week, as
reflected in the index's drop by almost 3%. The possibility of the
weakness of the Japanese yen forcing a competitive devaluation in
other Asian currencies dampened market spirits all throughout the
trading week. Political transitions in the country as well as in
Indonesia continued to make investors anxious, prodding most to
watch the market from the sidelines.
	   Moreover, economic results, such as slower export growth as well
as double-digit inflation for the month of May (using the new
index) added to the dispirited environment.
	   I expect lackluster trading to continue this week. Although
there is the possibility of a technical rally given the fact that
the market index is around support levels, any rebound will likely
be short-lived considering the lack of positive news on both the
foreign and the domestic fronts. I anticipate funds to sell into
strength. Such outlook is supported by the threatened yen and
potential effects on China's currency, as well as warnings that
interest rates may rise beginning today, in light of higher oil
prices last week. It is estimated that this would add at least 0.22
percentage points to the inflation rate for the month of June
(using the old index).
	   Another economic concern is the slowdown in export growth.
Latest data revealed export growth to be losing steam. Worries that
a potential glut in electronic products worldwide will dampen
demand has been one of the reasons why funds remained unconvinced
that the Philippines would continue to post double-digit growth in
exports, despite the peso's weakness.
	   Although investors believe that the Philippines, along with
Singapore, remains one of the stronger economies - in terms of
growth - this year, few are willing to put down new cash. Such
attitude is reinforced by fund managers' concerns about how the new
administration will finance spending this year. Joseph Estrada's
ambitious privatization plan is not exactly the answer that
international investors were hoping for. Fiscal and structural
reforms (i.e. higher tax collection and lower spending) were mostly
what was expected from the new government.
	   Adding this all up does not paint an exciting picture for the
week to come.
	   While I do not discount the possibility of a rally, the lack of
any fundamentally good news will keep investors out and speculators
in.
	   However, there are values to be found. Since I have found it
extremely difficult to call the market's trend week-on-week, I
advise investors to concentrate on value-stocks. After the market's
nine-day drop, shopping for value will not fail serious investors
who are ready to use any weakness as an opportunity to hunt for
bargains this week.
	   
</TEXT>
