<HEADLINE>
Stocks mostly easier on selling of blue chips, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Stocks mostly easier on selling of blue chips, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Foo Eu JinASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHARES on the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) extended its
downward trend last week, with the key barometer breaching its
lowest level in five months at last Friday's close, amid concerns
of local and regional contracting economies.
	   Stocks were traded mostly easier last week due to selling of
blue chips by local and foreign players despite news of a positive
trade surplus of RM12.4 billion from January to April this year,
and the central bank assurance that interest rates will be
maintained at current levels.
	   The market also failed to respond positively to the details on
the country's asset management company (AMC) which was set up to
unwind non- performing loans (NPLs) announced last Thursday.
	   Analysts said the downward trend may persist into this week,
with the possibility of the key index breaking the 500-point level
on lack of fresh leads and positive local and foreign news to spur
the market.
	   Analysts also expected the market to be volatile in the
short-term while any upside is expected to be short lived.
	   The market also took a cautious stand on worries of the
weakening yen and the possibility of the ringgit falling below the
RM4.00 level against the greenback, analysts added.
	   The local bourse began the week broadly lower in tandem with
other regional bourses and on news of the country's contracting
gross domestic product (GDP) in the first quarter of this year.
	   Shares rebounded on Tuesday after seven days of consecutive
falls to close marginally higher on limited buying interest after
Bank Negara announced it will continue to maintain interest rates
at current levels.
	   Wednesday saw the key barometer closing off its high, extending
Tuesday's technical rebound on selective buying interest on
bluechips by local and foreign funds.
	   Selling pressure continued on Thursday as players sold selected
bluechips on news of the funding details of the country's asset
management company (AMC), despite the country's RM12.4 billion
trade surplus from January to April.
	   On Friday, shares ended easier as the KLSE composite index
breached its lowest level in five months on the back of a weaker
ringgit and news that Moodys' Investors Service may cut the
country's forex ceiling for bonds and bank deposits as the
country's economy contracts.
	   Meanwhile, newly-listed second board lead products recycling
company, Metal Reclaimation Bhd ended the week at RM2.05, after
making its debut at RM2.01 on Thursday against its offer price of
RM1.80.
	   The KLCI had closed lower on Monday at 518.00 points, down 20.24
points from the previous Friday's close at 538.24.
	   The key barometer rose 2.61 points to close at 520.61 on
Tuesday, and extended its gains by another 5.75 points on Wednesday
to 526.36 points.
	   However, shares nosedived on Thursday to push the KLCI down 7.75
points to 518.61 points.
	   Shares fell again 13.56 points to 505.05 points last Friday.
	   Week-on-week, the benchmark KLCI shed 33.19 points or 6.17 per
cent to 505.05 points from the previous Friday's close of 538.24.
	   The all-main board Emas Index finished the week 5.96 points or
4.37 per cent lower at 130.55, while the second board index was
down 2.06 points or 1.85 per cent to 109.41.
	   Total turnover on the KLSE for entire last week amounted to
562.51 million shares valued at RM1.27 billion, which gave an
average daily volume of 112.50 million shares.
	   Meanwhile, index futures traded on the Kuala Lumpur Options and
Financial Futures Exchange (KLoffe), tracked the cash market and
saw it finishing easier at the end of last week on profit-taking
activities.
	   Spot June futures ended last Friday 10.3 points lower at 499.50
while nearby July futures closed 11.0 points lower to settle at
492.50.
	   
</TEXT>
