<HEADLINE>
Sukom athletes among guests at royal party, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Sukom athletes among guests at royal party, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SUKOM MEDAL HOPEFULS ... Malaysian athletes for the coming
Commonwealth Games were introduced to Yang di-Pertuan Agong Tuanku
Ja'afar yesterday.
	   The Sukom athletes, tipped as prospective gold medallists, were
at the tea party held in conjunction with the King's 76th birthday
at the Istana Negara.
	   Among them were (from left) national shooter Mohd Hidayat
Hamidon, weightlifter Hazli Irwan, badminton players Ong Ewe Hock
and Yap Kim Hock, and bowling stars, Kenny Ang and Shalin Zulkifli.
	   Others who got to meet the King yesterday were artistic gymnast
Au Li Yen, walkers Annastasia Karen Raj and Yuan Yu Fang, shooter
Noriha Abdul Rani and Thomas Cup squad members. They were led by
Badminton Association of Malaysia president, Datuk Dr Abdullah
Fadzil Che Wan.
	   Also present were the Raja Permaisuri Agong Tuanku Najihah, the
Regent of Negeri Sembilan Tuanku Naquiyuddin, Deputy Prime Minister
Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim and wife Datin Seri Dr Wan Azizah Wan
Ismail, Youth and Sports Minister Tan Sri Muhyiddin Yassin, Housing
and Local Government Minister Datuk Dr Ting Chew Peh and Chief
Secretary to the Government Tan Sri Halim Ali. Earlier, the King
signed a Royal Message, to lift the morale of Malaysian athletes
for the Games to be held from Sept 11 to 21.
	   
