<BODY>
<SLUG> ENVIRONMENTAL-JOURNALIST sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Howie Severino environmental journalist, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Howie Severino environmental journalist, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Jojo T. NonesASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Most people do not take the issue of environmental preservation
as seriously as they should. Though many may profess concern for
the environment, it is, sadly, more an effect of '90s hype than a
real personal stand.
	   But unlike an indifferent majority, a few dedicated
``crusaders'' spend extra time and effort to work for the ailing
planet. Environmental journalist Howie G. Severino believes that
his self-imposed goal of helping protect the environment does not
entail much sacrifice. ``It is something I love doing,'' he
declares.
	   Despite eight libel suits to his name for writing about the
malpractices of government officials leading to the corruption of
natural resources, he prefers not to romanticize the risks of
environmental reporting. ``It's pretty much the same as other
jobs,'' Howie says.
	   He adds that it is more of choice on his part than the result of
a grand and noble statement to the world. ``I enjoy it and I guess
this is more than enough reason for me to do it.''
	   Top Environmental Reporter Severino has long been engaged in
environmental work. He is dubbed as ``the country's leading
environmental reporter'' by The International Herald Tribune. He
has contributed several environmental articles to publications
abroad like the San Francisco Examiner and the Multinational
Monitor, and does a column for The Manila Times that focuses on
environmental issues.
	   He also regularly writes scripts for video features.
	   ``I have always been drawn to the subject of nature and
people,'' Severino muses. ``When we were still kids, my brother and
I went on trips with my dad (Rodolfo Severino, who is a diplomat
and secretary-general of the Asean). We would always have time to
camp out and sleep in tents. I think those trips have largely
influenced my work and my interests. I love to hike, dive, do
cycling. I relish the fact that I can combine my love for nature
with my work.''
	   Severino has done several internationally-distributed and
critically-acclaimed documentaries, aided by good friend and
renowned film visualizer Gerry Gerena, for the Unicef. One of these
docu-films, Hadlok, was reviewed by TIME magazine and is still
being shown in some countries since its release several years ago.
	   In 1992, Severino started formal environmental work on Mt.
Banahaw and came up with a documentary shown on local channel
ABS-CBN 2, discussing the environmental impact of pilgrimages made
to Banahaw. It was also around this time when he took his Master of
Arts degree in Environmental Policy from Sussex University in
Brighton, England where he did a thesis on Filipino migrants and
the apparent causes of their upland exodus.
	   Two years ago, Severino was awarded with the Benigno S. Aquino
Memorial Fellowship for Media by former Philippine President
Corazon Aquino and then US Ambassador to the Philippines John
Negroponte for his extensive contributions to environmental
preservation.
	   ``I can name five reasons that I think made me take that route
to environmental journalism,'' Severino declares. ``For one, I have
a genuine concern for the environment. Secondly, I believe there's
a lot to do.
	   Third, it's a life and death issue. Fourth, there aren't enough
people doing environmental journalism. And lastly, it's one good
reason to see and visit beautiful places in the country.''
	   Experienced Journalist But while engrossed in his passion for
the environment, Severino is not oblivious to social issues. His
previous jobs account for his wide understanding of politics,
society, and even indigenous Filipino lifestyles.
	   Severino has been a reporter for the now-defunct Manila
Chronicle, freelance journalist covering the Southeast Asian
region, and editor for a Sunday magazine. He has done production
work for international broadcast stations like the omnipresent CNN
and influential Turner Broadcasting Services.
	   Together with other young, ambitious journalists (including
Sheila Coronel, whose most recent book Porks and Other Perks has
made it to the current local non-fiction bestseller list along with
Ricky Lee's Trip To Quiapo and Jessica Zafra's Planet of the
Twisted), he co-founded the Philippine Center for Investigative
Journalism (PCIJ). Severino still acts as member of the board of
editors of PCIJ which has efficiently maintained a clean reputation
for intelligent and responsible reporting.
	   While he was video producer for Unicef, Severino also did
several documentaries that featured topics other than the
environment. These included films like: 1) the ethnically-colorful
Goiter in the Cordillera, which ``was finished only after six
months of non-continuous stay at one of the highly inaccessible
areas of the region;'' 2) Teachers, an interesting feature on the
mobile teacher program in Ifugao where ``teachers visit children in
remote areas to teach them;'' and 3) Tribal Teachers in Mindanao,
which showcased the intriguing and often unique lives of native
teachers in the idyllic regions of Mindanao.
	   ``In producing videos, it's fun to have what you write matched
with good pictures,'' Severino shares. ``A script needs a good
video assist to appear as clever as you thought it to be.''
	   And it is perhaps through this understanding of video production
work that he mixes well with the staff of Probe Productions Inc.,
the company behind the Philippines' most awarded television
newsmagazine show, The Probe Team, of which Severino is a reporter
and producer.
	   Newest Member of Probe ``What I like best about Probe is the 'no
star system,''' Severino says.
	   ``Team work is always practiced. We share responsibilities and
credit each other for the good outcome.''
	   Married to environmental lawyer Ipat Luna for five years now,
Severino is the newest producer and reporter for the GMA 7, 10:30
p.m., Friday night program. ``It's actually my first time to work
full-time for a broadcast media company and I'm thinking this won't
be a fleeting job. I share a mutually-beneficial relationship with
Probe, one where each party can claim success without being
detrimental to the other,'' Severino enthuses. ``I work really well
with the staff. I mean, I'm not quite used to working with an
entourage and being the center of attention whenever we arrive at a
coverage area, but I am getting more comfortable every time. As I
said, the Probe people are not into the celebrity thing. They're
into it for the high it creates, for the fulfillment it brings.''
Severino says he is ``quite lucky'' to be able to indulge in what
he enjoys and actually get paid for it in the process. ``It's
really fun. The work is tiring but it's fun,'' he smiles. ``I never
took up film in college. I had History as my major and my only
training was under Gerry (Gerena, who helped him film his
documentaries). But with Probe, it is never a bother.
	   People here help each other and it makes work so much easier.''
	   ``They asked me to join (Probe) several years ago,'' Severino
relates, ``but I was too caught up in many other concerns. I guess
that being with Probe is something really good. It helps me a lot
in being able to get more mileage. As a television mediaman,
appearing on broadcast regularly, I am able to reach more people,
get my point of view across more cultural and social barriers. In
the end, the benefits are not just for me, but for the environment
as well.''
	   photo captions: photos by Gerard Cordero 1. He has been chased
by goons of illegal loggers; caught in an earthquake disaster site
while there were still strong tremors; swamped with eight libel
suits from powerful government officials -- yet Severino prefers
not to romanticize the risks of environmental journalism. ``It's
pretty much the same as other jobs,'' he says.
	   2. Severino tells how it is to work for the Philippines' most
awarded telemagazine show: ``Fun.''
	   3. Quite slim, medium-built, and soft-spoken - ``the country's
leading environmental reporter'' according to The International
Herald Tribune.
	   
</TEXT>
