w1968 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  PARTY'S-INTERNAL-CULTURE     06-08 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> PARTY'S-INTERNAL-CULTURE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Party's internal problems a manifestation of no-dissent culture?, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Party's internal problems a manifestation of no-dissent culture?, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Carolyn HongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A NEWSPAPER had described the close juxtaposition of father and
son - Lim Kit Siang and Guan Eng - in the DAP leadership hierarchy
as a ``gunpowder situation'', and this has now more or less
exploded.
	   The party's leadership having assumed a hereditary structure,
and the apparent determination to keep it that way, was no longer
talked about in whispers but rather written in great detail by
newspapers.
	   Thanks to the removal of Wee Choo Keong as national publicity
secretary and suspension of Liew Ah Kim as vice-chairman and Fung
Ket Wing as treasurer.
	   The three were said to have undermined party morale, caused
confusion, disharmony and disunity by their remarks at the Perak
and Malacca State committee meetings.
	   DAP chairman Dr Chen Man Hin said the three had campaigned among
party members, alleging nepotism. ``They felt that deputy
secretary-general Guan Eng was being promoted by Kit Siang (his
father who is the secretary- general).''
	   The party's central executive committee removed the three as it
has lost confidence in them, said Kit Siang at a Press conference
the following day.
	   Several DAP leaders brushed off the resulting tempest as a
``storm in a teacup'' and a minor hiccup in the rough and tumble of
politics.
	   A cautious DAP national vice-chairman Dr Tan Seng Giaw remarked
that it was a small matter, no different from that of any other
organisation and will not seriously affect the party.
	   A more outspoken but nonetheless equally careful deputy chairman
Karpal Singh also quickly said ``it was not much of a crisis''
although an unfortunate circumstance.
	   They dismissed talk that it reflected serious party problems or
an internal split growing wider.
	   Karpal said if at all there was a split, it was to the ``limited
extent''
	   of the three on one side and the leadership on the other. ``Very
far from a split down the middle, if at all it can be said there is
one.''
	   Yet, the problem isn't as minor as they would like it to be; at
the very least, it is fuel for DAP critics who have long accused
the party of not practising the democracy it preaches.
	   Other than charges of nepotism, the abrupt removal of the three
isn't easy to explain away although Karpal said it was strictly
according to the DAP's constitution.
	   He said as the three were elected to their posts by the CEC,
they could also be removed by the CEC, but to lose their CEC
membership would be a little more complicated. This is because they
were elected as CEC members by delegates.
	   He also said it was not the end of the matter, as the three had
been referred to the disciplinary committee and could present their
case there.
	   They were also heard by the CEC before the decision to remove
them was taken.
	   ``It's about party discipline. They should have raised their
problems through the proper channels,'' Karpal said.
	   Legal arguments though may not be convincing to those who don't
believe this to be a problem of ``loose cannon'' blasting off for
personal reasons, but who see it as a manifestation of the
no-dissent culture and a move towards entrenching the power
structure.
	   It was a symptom of the lack of social democracy and a political
ideology within the party, said Dr Kua Kia Soong who gave this as
his reason for resigning.
	   Then the Selangor deputy chairman, Kua left the party in 1995
and later published a book, criticising the DAP for its political
structure which encourages patronage, and for failing to provide a
social democratic alternative to the Barisan Nasional.
	   He said the current crisis and that which saw his departure
shared the same roots, which he terms loosely as a lack of social
democracy and the advent of ``career-ist'' tendencies.
	   The latter refers to the bitter tussle for seats during the
general election.
	   He said the latest crisis indicated a worsening of the problems,
as two years ago, he could not imagine these stalwarts being openly
critical.
	   Whether the three were asked to give their views or did so
without prompting at the Perak and Malacca branch meetings, they
had spoken of the ``preferential treatment'' to garner support for
Guan Eng, while Wee, who also lost his seat after being fined by
the court, didn't find similar campaigns for him.
	   Guan Eng was sentenced to 18 months' jail for printing false
news and inciting the public in 1995.
	   Their comparison of the two cases implied a scenario of
intensifying nepotism, and was apparently also the straw which
broke the camel's back.
	   Kit Siang, some claim, is increasingly unhappy with those who
made oblique and direct references about the DAP's power structure.
	   But as this is by no means the first crisis in the DAP,
observers suggest that the present thunder and lightning too, will
pass without leaving permanent damage.
	   They also don't believe that there will be much of an impact on
voters, given the lack of choice in Opposition parties.
	   As Kua said, people generally voted for the DAP ``not because
they love the DAP more'' but as a protest.
	   He thinks the protest factor would continue to influence voters
more than the attractiveness or otherwise of the DAP.
	   Nevertheless, it won't do the DAP much good to be accused of the
very thing it is protesting against in its ``Support Guan Eng''
campaigns - the gagging of critics and high-handed rule.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:PARTY'S-INTERNAL-CULTURE sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
