<HEADLINE>
Australian Hospital Care Ltd, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Australian Hospital Care Ltd, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALAYSIAN-backed Australian Hospital Care Ltd (AHCL) said that
its full- year profit would be less than forecast in February
because of a continuing fall in patients with private health
insurance, Bernama reports.
	   The group also blames the slide of its share price on persistent
rumours that Peremba Group Sdn Bhd might be looking to sell its 33
per cent stake in AHCL despite vigorous denials by the Australian
group of any sellout by the Malaysian company.
	   According to the Financial Review in Melbourne, AHCL chief
executive Dr Mark Bryce had predicted in February that the
full-year profit would be more than 15 per cent higher than the
A$14.5 million for 1996-97.
	   But the newspaper reported Bryce as saying that the profit
downgrade was necessary because AHCL had been severely affected
over the past two months by the fall in number of patients with
private health cover and lower than usual patient volume in its
hospitals in various parts of Australia.
	   ``AHCL posted a 26.3 per cent jump in net profit to A$8.5
million in the first half,'' the Financial Review said.
	   
</TEXT>
