<HEADLINE>
Top 20 companies, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Top 20 companies, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ACCORDING TO KLSE MARKET CAPITALISATION LAST week's easier close
and dampened trading on the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange saw 12
companies on the Top 20 list ranked by market capitalisation
posting lower market capitalisation against the previous week,
while seven were higher and one remained unchanged.
	   The 12 companies which saw lower market capitalisation were
Telekom, Tenaga, Petronas Gas, Rothmans, Sime Darby, Genting, MISC,
Resorts, YTL Corp, Berjaya Sports Toto, Nestle and Magnum.
	   The seven companies on the list which increased their market
worth were Maybank, YTL Power, KL Kepong, Golden Hope, RHB Capital,
Kumpulan Guthrie and Oriental. PBB remained unchanged.
	   The top three companies remained in their respective positions,
while eight others on the list were also unchanged.
	   Maybank was up five places to forth, while YTL Power was up one
place to 10th.
	   Meanwhile, Rothmans, Sime Darby, Genting, MISC, Resorts and YTL
Corp were down to fifth, sixth, seventh, eighth, ninth and 11th
positions respectively. Oriental moved into the Top 20, while
Tanjong fell out of the list.
	   
</TEXT>
