<HEADER>
w1982 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  KITARO-REACHING-ROOTSske     06-08 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> KITARO-REACHING-ROOTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kitaro - reaching for his roots, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Kitaro - reaching for his roots, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Gerald MartinezASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KITARO - Gaia Onhashira THIS album from the Japanese master of
New Age music takes its inspiration from an unusual festival
originating from the Suwa Basin that is based on a Shinto ritual.
	   It's about the people of Suwa going into the mountains and
cutting down a giant fir tree which they haul back to the town to
erect.
	   Prayers are said around it, to establish a rapport with the God
of the mountain.
	   The reverence for nature and its roots in Japanese religion are
elements very close to Kitaro's heart and is reflected in the
mystical nature of the music here.
	   Yamadashi starts out with a rustic atmosphere, created by sounds
of the wind and bird calls.
	   Some brooding orchestral chords creep in before electric guitars
state the musical themes which give way to hoarse emotive
vocalisations in Japanese and the kodo drums resound, to introduce
a festive and cheerful mood.
	   Misty features plaintive flutes playing sweet and low in a
restrained neo-classical style, while Gaia starts with some runs on
nylon string guitar to ominous drums resounding in the background,
before it reaches an orchestral climax.
	   Kitaro is one of the masters at combining the sounds of
technologically advanced instruments like synthesisers, sequencers,
and electric guitars, with the folk and primitive instruments to
come up with a very natural mix. Wood Fairy has all these elements
and makes for stirring listening.
	   While the album deals with serious themes, Kitaro's ear for
melody and riveting rhythms make this album accessible even to the
casual listener.
	   GEORGE MARTIN - In My Life MARTIN is a famed pro-ducer/arranger
who worked with the Beatles on all of their albums, until they
disbanded in 1970.
	   He entered the music industry in 1950, played the oboe
professionally before being appointed head of Parlaphone in the EMI
Group in 1955.
	   In 1962, he signed the Beatles on, and helped them in recording
arranging and scoring their albums.
	   He also worked with the biggest names in the business, from jazz
singer Cleo Laine, rock guitarist Jeff Beck and Stan Getz.
	   He was knighted in 1996, and decided to retire in 1997, with
this album as his swan song.
	   It's a collection of songs from the Beatles, with singers and
musicians handpicked by him.
	   Come Together features Robin Williams and Bobby McFerrin, in a
faithful remake of the original. While McFerrin's vocal abilities
are well known, Williams also shines here.
	   A Hard Day's Night, with a cool and swinging jazz arrangement,
has the unlikely choice of actress Goldie Hawn who proves to have a
soft and seductive voice on the tune.
	   One of the highlights of the album is guitarist Jeff Beck's
moving instrumental of A Day in The Life. Beck plays with great
feel and emotion on this psychedelic ballad.
	   Celine Dion adds her inimitable touch to Martin's favourite
McCartney tune, Here There &AMP; Everywhere, while Vanessa Mae plays a
classical version of Because.
	   For the whimsical tune I Am The Walrus, Martin invited the
idiosyncratic comedian, Jim Carrey who turns in a wild over-the-top
version of this odd song.
	   There's also a classical version of Here Comes The Sun, by
guitarist John Williams, and Japanese pop star Bonnie Pink performs
a restrained version of Blackbird.
	   Phil Collins tackles Golden Slumbers, Carry That Weight and The
End, while Sean Connery intones In My Life in his suave, gravelly
tones.
	   It's an album well worth listening to. Martin has obviously a
great love for the material and while some of the songs are not
identical to the originals, they do not suffer for it.
	   TWENTIETH CENTURY BLUES: The songs of Noel Coward - Various
Artistes SONGWRITER, playwright, and actor, Coward (1899-1973)
reflected the mood and spirit of England in his well-crafted songs.
He was the decadent rebel in the 20s, the serious sophisticate in
the 30s, the stern patriot in the 40s and the hip cabaret artiste
in the 50s.
	   This album is part of the Red Hot Aids Charitable trust, which
has produced several other albums in its efforts to raise funds for
Aids research and its victims.
	   Coward himself was a homosexual, which in those days was much
less acceptable.
	   Lots of stars appear on this album, like Texas, Divine Comedy,
Pet Shop Boys, Shola Ama, Robbie Williams, Bryan Ferry, Marianne
Faithful, Space, Suede, Sting, London Pride, Vic Reeves, and Elton
John.
	   The music varies from hip hop to techno, to swing. His work may
not be familiar to the public but this is as good a time as any to
check it out.
	   JOHN ANDERSON - Super Hits COUNTRY singer Anderson has a
homespun image with a pleasant tenor voice, very mainstream
country. This is a `greatest hits' album which means the songs are
pretty good.
	   Straight Tequila Night and Seminole Wind are affecting ballads
while When It Comes To You is an engaging Mark Knopfler
composition.
	   Country fans will find this a good buy.
	   TITANIC DANCE - Various Artistes IT had to come, I guess - the
dance version of My Heart Will Go On. Well this collection features
that song as well as lots of other tracks remade with a techno
beat.
	   There's a bit of an Asian theme here, with Huang Fei Hong, Tian
Mi Mi, Kung Fu Fighting and Matsuri in the collection.
	   In addition a bonus CD comes free with alternate mixes of some
of the songs on the first album. So what you get is 140 plus
minutes of dance time. Phew! THE MOFFATS - Chapter 1: A New
Beginning THESE guys who are in their early teens, are siblings,
comprising of triplets and an elder brother. They are fresh-faced
kids, against drugs and smoking and wrote many of the songs on the
album.
	   They have been playing for several years, starting out as a
kiddie group on the country circuit in Canada and the US.
	   Now they are ready to take on the world and they already have an
international hit in the catchy I'll Be There For You, which has a
feel similar to the Hanson's hit, Dowop, and which kicks the album
off.
	   Miss You Like Crazy, a melodic pop ballad, is already scoring
good airplay.
	   The rest of the album is more or less in the same vein, although
perhaps not as inspired as the first two tracks. It's mostly
romantic pop music, easy on the ears, and should suit teenagers
real fine.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:KITARO-REACHING-ROOTS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
