<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Abacha, 9th Ld,0440 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nigerian leader Abacha dead of heart attack at 54
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: INSERTS new grafs 11-13 to ADD Shell Oil comment. PICKS UP
11th graf pvs: Word of Abacha's ... &QL; 
 &UR; With Nigeria-Abacha-Profile; Nigeria-Glance
 &UR; AP Photos NY190-191
 &UR; By FRANK AIGBOGUN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Nigerian strongman Gen. Sani Abacha died
Monday of a heart attack at age 54, ending the latest in a long
string of military dictatorships in his oil-rich but impoverished
country.
	   A uniformed officer stood before the State House in the capital,
Abuja, to make the announcement. Martial music filled the
state-controlled radio airwaves to officially mark his death.
Unofficially, his myriad critics and opponents poured into the
streets of Lagos to celebrate. Top officials convened an emergency
meeting.
	   Jubilant crowds in some Lagos neighborhoods defied the normally
heavily police presence to began cheering at the news of Abacha's
death.
	   ``This death gives us an opportunity to restart our lives,''
said opposition leader Soloman Lar. ``It is our hope that Nigeria
will not miss that chance.''
	   Despite the celebrations, uncertainty loomed as the question of
succession remained unanswered.
	   In life, Abacha offered little indication of who might take his
place, wielding absolute power in Africa's most populous nation
ever since canceling presidential elections in 1993 and seizing
power in a bloodless coup.
	   Less than two months ago, Abacha's deputy leader, Gen. Oladipyo
Diya was sentenced to death for allegedly plotting the overthrow of
the military regime.
	   Two likely successors, however, include Nigeria's chief of
defense, Staff Maj. Gen. Abdul Abubakar Salam, and Lt. Gen.
Jeremial Useni, the minister for the capital territory of Abuja.
	   Western diplomats said Salam, who presided over an emergency
meeting of junta leaders on Monday, was a leading candidate to lead
the country at least over the short term.
	   Without a clear line of succession, Nigeria's many opposition
groups could try to capitalize on a power void.
	   Oil executives in the Niger Delta city of Port Harcourt said
Abacha's death would have little impact on drilling or production
operations.
	   Nigeria's oil industry _ one of the largest in the world _ was
left to decay under Abacha's rule, but continues to be the
country's largest source of export revenue.
	   ``We try not to get involved in politics,'' said Victor Dania,
the director of community affairs for Shell Oil's Nigerian joint
venture. ``There won't be an impact on our production.''
	   Word of Abacha's, 11th graf pvs.
</TEXT>
