<SLUG> BC-Britain-Au Pair, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0406 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Woodward mother accused of submitting phony housing bill
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Precedes LONDON &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout and CHANGES byline &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBIN ESTRIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOSTON (AP) _ The husband of the lawyer fired by Louise Woodward
accused the British au pair's mother Monday of forging a housing
bill to get money from her daughter's legal defense fund.
	   Dan Sharp, whose British-born wife, Elaine Whitfield Sharp, was
fired by Ms. Woodward last week, described the dlrs 15,400 bill as
a sham. The invoice purportedly covered several months of lodging
for Sue Woodward at the Sharps' Marblehead home.
	   Sue and Gary Woodward stayed at the lawyer's house while their
daughter was on trial for the death of 8-month-old Matthew Eappen.
After her release from prison last November, Ms. Woodward stayed at
the Sharps' home until about two months ago.
	   ``We didn't charge the Woodwards one penny,'' for their
accommodations, Dan Sharp told The Associated Press. ``This is a
phony bill and it is clear they were taking money from the trust
and lying to the trust.''
	   A lawyer for the Woodward family in England, Paul Barrow, denied
the allegations.
	   ``This is not a forgery,'' he said. ``That statement of account
was handed to the Woodwards by the Whitfield Sharps and any
allegations of impropriety are absolutely denied by the
Woodwards.''
	   Barrow added: ``As far as my clients are concerned that is the
end of the matter. Sue is more worried about her daughter than this
nonsense that the Whitfield Sharps are bringing out for reasons
best known to themselves.''
	   Ms. Whitfield Sharp declined to comment. But her husband gave
The Associated Press copies of an invoice and a handwritten note
that he said purports to show that dlrs 15,400 was paid to him and
his wife from the account of Gary Woodward.
	   Sharp, who is also an attorney, said they never received any
money.
	   The bill, which Sharp described as a poor forgery, details
charges for the use of telephone, food, heat and other household
expenses, such as housekeeping.
	   The bill was distributed to the media by the Rev. Ken Davey, a
vicar who runs the Woodward appeal fund in her home village of
Elton in Cheshire, England.
	   Davey has said the Woodward legal fund stood at dlrs 400,000
(245,000 pounds) in December, but fell to about dlrs 80,000 (50,000
pounds) after paying for Ms. Woodward's appeal. 	   
</TEXT>
