<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Elections, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0433 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Beirut votes for religious harmony; Amal, Hezbollah split Shiites
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with official Beirut results, interior minister's
comments, scuffles &QL; 
 &UR; By SAM F. GHATTAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Muslims and Christians endorsed religious
harmony in Beirut and militant Shiite Muslims made major inroads in
south Lebanon in municipal elections held after a break of 35
years, partial results showed Monday.
	   Despite Beirut turning into a Sunni Muslim majority city over
the years, 12 Christians and 12 Muslims were elected to the
24-member city council, dispelling fears that Christians would be
driven out of the local politics by Muslim voters.
	   All but one of the winners are from a Christian-Muslim ticket
backed by Prime Minister Rafik Hariri, a Sunni Muslim who had
campaigned for religious unity.
	   ``To say it plainly, the number of Christians (elected) in
Beirut remained as it was before,'' Interior Minister Michel Murr
told reporters in announcing some of the official results.
	   Hariri's campaign, joined by other moderate Sunnis, was aimed at
ensuring that the delicate sectarian balance is maintained in
Beirut, as it is in senior government posts in this country of 18
religious sects.
	   But the Beirut election was marred by a low turnout among the
400,000 eligible voters _ as low as 20 percent in Christian areas
and up to 40 percent in Muslim sectors.
	   In the south, the Iranian-backed Hezbollah guerrilla group's
candidates scored major gains, chipping away at the power base of
the pro-Syrian Amal faction of Parliament Speaker Nabih Berri.
	   Preliminary results estimated Hezbollah won 18 municipalities, a
further signal that it has succeeded in transforming itself from a
guerrilla force fighting Israeli occupation forces into a populist
movement.
	   But overall victory remained with Amal. The prize win for Amal
was in the southern city of Tyre while Hezbollah took the market
town of Nabatiyeh.
	   No official results from other places in the south were
available but Berri estimated that Amal won 51 of 75 wholly Shiite
towns, tied with Hezbollah in five others and took control of 22
mixed Christian-Shiite towns.
	   Scuffles broke out in the southern provincial capital of Sidon
between supporters of rival candidates. There were no injuries but
a car was gutted, security officials said.
	   Municipal elections have not been held since 1963 because the
1975-90 sectarian civil war and the political tensions that led to
and followed the conflict.
</TEXT>
