<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Russia, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin meets Kohl in Germany ahead of Paris G-8 meeting
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with agreements signed on nuclear technology
transfers. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN MADER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin and his
ministers came to Germany, a key trading partner, on Monday seeking
counsel on their financial turmoil at home.
	   Yeltsin's talks with his good friend, Chancellor Helmut Kohl,
were expected to focus on international credit for Russia following
a collapse in Russia's financial markets last month.
	   ``New problems keep emerging which need to be solved quickly and
energetically, and the both of us, Helmut and I, will solve these
problems this way,'' Yeltsin said upon arrival at the Bonn-Cologne
military airport.
	   Germany also will try to persuade Moscow to support the European
Union's decision Monday to punish Serbia for attacks on its
separatist region of Kosovo.
	   But asked before dinner with German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel whether Russia would get behind the EU's economic sanctions,
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said: ``No, I don't think
so.''
	   The EU decided in Luxembourg to ban investment in Serbia and
freeze its assets abroad, measures Russia has been reluctant to
endorse.
	   Shortly after arriving in Bonn, Russian ministers signed two
agreements with their German counterparts covering deliveries of
uranium and nuclear technology from Germany to Russia, Kinkel said.
	   Yeltsin and Kohl then began their talks at a dinner at the
chancellor's residence. They were to hold a joint news conference
Tuesday.
	   Yeltsin also was to discuss a broad list of political,
financial, trade and social issues in the talks, which were planned
before the current fiscal crisis.
	   Yeltsin has stressed his country's need for foreign credit while
it negotiates loans from the International Monetary Fund.
	   But he and his top officials insist Russia has rebounded from
last month's financial market collapse following a drop in oil
prices. They say vigorous tax collection will ensure stability and
that they have made no ``official'' request for direct foreign aid.
	   ``The begging time for Russia is over,'' Yeltsin told Der
Spiegel, a German newsmagazine, in this week's issue. ``We're not
asking now like we once did: Give, whoever can give.''
	   Despite the disclaimers, investors have said they believe a
bailout package may be unveiled after Yeltsin departs Germany,
possibly when deputy finance ministers from the Group of Eight
economic powers meet in Paris on Tuesday.
	   German government spokesman Otto Hauser said Germany would
provide no direct aid to Russia, but would not rule out taking part
in a rescue package put together by the IMF.
	   Since the fall of communism, Germany has become Russia's most
important trade partner outside the former Soviet Union, and a key
source of aid and credit. Germany has been key to negotiating
Russia's acquiescence to the eastward expansion of the NATO
military alliance.
	   Yeltsin also is scheduled to meet Tuesday morning with
opposition chancellor candidate Gerhard Schroeder.
	   Yeltsin returns to Moscow on Tuesday.
 &UR; (im-cb-pfg)
</TEXT>
