<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bolivia-Everest,0516 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
First Bolivian to reach Everest given hero's welcome
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PETER McFARREN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) _ The first Bolivian and American Indian to
reach Mount Everest returned home Monday to a hero's welcome in La
Paz, where he was greeted by acting President Jorge Quiroga.
	   Bernardo Guarachi, 43, reached the world's highest summit on May
25 at 5:55 a.m. It was his second attempt. It took him only three
days to go from base camp to the 8,848 meter (29,028-feet) -high
summit.
	   At the La Paz airport, hundreds of students and fans greeted the
Aymara Indian who was raised on the Bolivian Highlands in an adobe
hut, 4 kilometers (2 1/2 miles) above sea level.
	   ``I have reached the summit of the Everest in the name of
Bolivia,'' Guarachi said. ``With will and dedication, all Bolivians
can aspire to a better future, and I hope my example can show that
anything is possible when one sets one mind to it.''
	   In the Bolivian capital of La Paz, Quiroga received Guarachi and
his family at the Congress building and described him as Bolivia's
greatest athlete. La Paz Mayor German Monroy gave Guarachi the
city's highest award.
	   Guarachi said growing up at a high altitude help him as a
mountain climber. It takes weeks of living at high altitudes for
many other climbers to adjust to the thin air that causes
everything from headaches and shortage of breath, to pulmonary
edema.
	   ``I think I am a privileged climber because I was born in the
Andes,'' Guarachi said. ``Living at this altitude has strengthened
my physical condition to better withstand foul weather and a lack
of oxygen.''
	   His training included a three-year mountaineering program at the
high altitude climbing school (DAV) in Germany.
	   Since his first climb up a Bolivian Andean peak in 1974, he has
reached the summit of the 6,642-meter (21,791-feet)-high Illimani
170 times and the 7,000-meter (22,965-feet)-high Aconcagua, Latin
America's highest mountain, three times.
	   Guarachi said his most dramatic climb up Illimani, which
overlooks La Paz, was in early January 1985. He was hired by
Eastern Airline to find the wreckage of a plane that crashed on New
Years day, killing all 33 people aboard. Guarachi was first to
reach the crash site.
	   He said it took him 20 years to prepare to climb Everest, where
more than 115 people have died in the attempt. Statistics show only
1 in 7 are successful. Since Edmond Hillary and Sherpa Tensing
first scaled the world's highest mountain in 1953, only 485 others
have made it.
	   Guarachi climbed with a Singapore team. He was part of a
commercially organized expedition, led by Thomas Sjogren, 39, of
Stockholm.
	   In 1994, bad weather forced Guarachi back after he reached 8,180
meters (27,000 feet).	   ``Guarachi is a sportsman and a treasure as far as mountain
climbing goes,'' said Quiroga, who is also an avid mountain
climber.
	   The Bolivian Government, private companies, the Inter-American
Development Bank and the Andean Development Corporation supported
Guarachi's efforts. 	   
</TEXT>
