<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Abacha-Reax, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0811 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mixed reaction meets death of Nigeria's dictator
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with comment from son of executed political activist.
No pickup &QL; 
 &UR; With Nigeria-Abacha; Nigeria-Glance; Israel-Abacha-Soyinka &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ The death of Gen. Sani Abacha, who ruled
Nigeria for five years, evoked mixed reaction Monday from many
Nigerians have been waiting for the military dictatorship to return
power to the people.
	   In Jerusalem, exiled playwright Wole Soyinka called Abacha's
death ``an opportunity for Nigerian civic society, an opportunity
for the Nigerian military, and an opportunity for the international
community.''
	   Soyinka, winner of the 1986 Nobel Prize in literature and an
outspoken opponent of military rule, fled Nigeria in 1994. Abacha's
military regime charged him with treason, a crime punishable by
death.
	   Reacting to news of Abacha's death, the United States and
Britain urged a quick transition to democracy in Nigeria, a former
British colony.
	   ``We hope that following the death of Gen. Abacha, there will be
an opening for a stable transition to an early return to democracy,
with the election of an accountable civilian government which will
restore and respect human rights,'' Britain's Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook said in a statement.
	   In Washington, State Department spokesman James P. Rubin called
for a ``genuine democratic process'' leading to a transfer of power
from military to civilian rule in Nigeria.
	   At the United Nations in New York, a spokesman for U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Annan praised the contribution
made by Nigeria under Abacha to ending the civil war in nearby
Liberia and to restoring the democratically elected government of
Sierra Leone.
	   ``At this crucial juncture, the Secretary-General looks forward
to a peaceful and democratic future for the Nigerian people,'' the
spokesman said.
	   Abacha also is remembered for his way of dealing with opponents.
Public condemnation followed the Nov. 10, 1995, hanging of
environmentalist and playwright Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other
political activists, convicted in a closed military tribunal of
murdering political opponents.
	   Critics said the charges were false _ Abacha's revenge for
Saro-Wiwa's constant challenges to the military government and his
criticisms of the environmental damage wrought by the oil industry.
	   In London, the son of Saro-Wiwa said that Abacha was the worst
in a long line of human rights abusers in Nigeria.
	   ``The thinking has always been that every successive dictator is
worst than the previous one,'' Ken Wiwa said. ``So one hopes that
we don't get another dictator because he will have quite a record
to better Abacha's appalling record.''
	   Even while Abacha was still in power, Nigerians were struggling
to restore democracy, Soyinka said in Jerusalem, where he was
lecturing at Hebrew University.
	   ``The people were sick of military dictatorship,'' he said. ``So
it's up to the military to recognize this _ and up to the
international community to say that we're sick and tired of the
degeneration of a potentially great society.''
	   In Nigeria's commercial hub, Lagos, many people honked car horns
and cheered in the streets.
	   ``This death gives us an opportunity to restart our lives,''
said opposition leader Soloman Lar. ``It is our hope that Nigeria
will not miss that chance.''
	   His sentiments, shared by many others, were in stark contrast to
the official reaction. The radio announcement was followed by a
broadcast of solemn martial music. Military and civilian members of
his ruling junta paid tribute to Abacha, claiming his death was a
loss.
	   ``This is a very sad development for us as a nation,'' said
Lyorcha Ayu, the president of federal senate.
	   In the western city of Owerri, streets were virtually empty
after people rushed home upon learning of the news. Although no
additional military presence was evident, some people said they
feared Abacha's death could trigger violent protests.
	   ``I know not everybody liked him, but I don't like his death,''
said taxi driver Silas Nwogu. ``He had been running the country,
and he said he would hand over power, and we were waiting for that
to happen.''
	   In the Niger Delta city of Port Harcourt, oil executives said
Abacha's death would have little impact on their work.
	   ``We try not to get involved in politics,'' said Victor Dania,
the director of community affairs for Shell Oil's Nigerian joint
venture. ``There won't be an impact on our production.''
	   The Royal Dutch-Shell Group of Cos. has come under severe fire
in recent years for its doing major oil business in Nigeria while
Abacha remained in power. Shell has always maintained that it has
been in Nigeria for years and its operations had nothing to do with
local politics.
</TEXT>
