<SLUG> BC-Commonwealth-Nigeria,0284 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Commonwealth's Nigeria contact man urges new elections
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) _ The death of Nigerian military
ruler Gen. Sani Abacha provides an opportunity for the troubled
country to return to democracy, Foreign Minister Don McKinnon said
Tuesday.
	   McKinnon, who is vice-chairman of the Commonwealth Ministerial
Action Group on Nigeria (CMAG), said the international community
should now press for ``free and democratic'' elections in Nigeria
in October.
	   CMAG was set up to monitor Nigeria after it executed nine
activists, including Nobel prize-winning writer Ken Saro-Wiwa,
while Commonwealth heads of government were meeting in New Zealand
in 1995.
	   Nigeria was suspended from the Commonwealth, and Commonwealth
leaders promised to take punitive action if free elections were not
held in Nigeria by October this year.
	   McKinnon told National Radio there had been reports for some
time that Abacha was ailing, but they had been dismissed as
exaggerated.
	   ``Well, it's happened and that will throw everything into
disarray, but I guess it does give the Nigerians a real opportunity
to move towards some kind of a democratic regime if given a
chance,'' he said.
	   ``Nigeria was one of the leaders in democracy in Africa back in
the 1960s and there's no reason why they can't return to it. But
it's very much up to (those there) to do something about it,'' he
said. ``There are a lot of pretty good-thinking people in Nigeria,
and I just hope they take this opportunity to press their claims
for a return to democracy.''
	   The international community could maintain pressure on Nigeria
to hold elections this year, he said. 	   
</TEXT>
