<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Kemper Open,0643 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Appleby enlists in golf's youth movement
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RON SIRAK &QC; 
 &UR; AP Golf Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   POTOMAC, Maryland (AP) _ Throw another name on the fire. Stuart
Appleby is yet one more young golfer clamoring for recognition as
one of the world's better players.
	   The victory in the Kemper Open by the 27-year-old Australian
means that for the eighth time in 21 PGA Tour events this year the
winner was 28 years old or younger.
	   And perhaps more significant, all eight are multiple winners in
their careers. No one-hit wonders here. These golfers are going to
be around for a while.
	   ``Hopefully, this is something I can keep on for 20 years,''
Appleby said after he closed with a 72 at TPC at Avenel for a
10-under-par 274 and a one-stroke victory over Scott Hoch.
	   Along with the Honda Classic last year, Appleby has now won
twice on the PGA Tour and finished second two other times.
	   Of the young winners this year, only Lee Westwood _ an
Englishman who does not play regularly in the United States _ won
on the PGA Tour for the first time. But if his credentials need to
be checked for membership in the Young Lions Club, keep in mind
that his victory in Europe this weekend was his second in two
weeks.
	   The credentials of the other under-30 winners are more than
impressive.
	   Phil Mickelson (27) has 12 PGA Tour victories. Tiger Woods (22)
has seven, including the 1997 Masters. Among the six victories by
Ernie Els (28) are two U.S. Opens.
	   David Duval (26) has won five times and was a very strong second
this year in the Masters. Justin Leonard (25) has four victories,
including the 1997 British Open, the 1998 Players Championship and
was second in the 1997 PGA Championship.
	   Last year when he came into Kemper, Leonard was just another
face among the rising young players. He had already won once on the
PGA Tour, but a slew of guys have done that.
	   The victory at Kemper last year, however, seemed to lift Leonard
to a new level. He has emerged as one of the world's top players.
	   ``Justin used it as a kick start,'' Appleby said. ``Hopefully,
that stuff will happen to me.''
	   Of the seven players under 28 who have won a total of eight PGA
Tour events this year (Duval has two), three already have at least
one major championship. The pressure of getting a breakthrough
major is gone for Els, Woods and Leonard.
	   Mickelson in particular since he has a dozen other victories,
Duval, Westwood and Appleby still have that hurdle to clear.
	   ``I really hope this does do something in the major
department,'' Appleby said. ``Again, to get your play at a major
level is another step higher. You only have four chances (each
year), so the odds are a lot less than in a regular tournament.''
	   Like virtually every other good young player on tour, Appleby
recognized that he is feeding off the accomplishments of the
others.
	   ``Players are going to get better as times goes on,'' he said.
``I'm learning from each tournament where I'm under pressure.''
	   On Sunday, he displayed much of what he has learned. He held off
an experienced Hoch down the stretch while playing in difficult
wind.
	   Appleby played the final two holes with Hoch already in the
clubhouse, and knew he could afford no mistakes.
	   All he did was hit a perfect 7-iron to the 17th green and an
even better 3-iron from 214 yards (195 meters) off a side hill lie
to the final green.
	   ``You can't practice competitive stress,'' Appleby said. ``You
can imagine you are holing out a putt for a tournament and that
stuff is neat. But really, in the end, the real stuff is hard to
get and that's what you have to learn from each time.''
	   Count Stuart Appleby among a very talented group of young
golfers who are learning their lessons well.
</TEXT>
