<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Basketball-NBA Finals Notebook,0677 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sloan in good mood after bashing
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RICK GANO &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CHICAGO (AP) _ He was testy following a five-point loss in Game
2, so you'd expect Utah coach Jerry Sloan to be a real bear the
morning after the most lopsided defeat in National Basketball
Association Finals history.
	   Not this time. Perhaps he was too tired to be grumpy.
	   ``I feel good. If you stayed awake and didn't go to sleep and
had to face all you people, wouldn't you feel great?'' Sloan told
reporters at a mandatory question-and-answer session Monday.
	   The Utah Jazz, 96-54 blowout losers to the Chicago Bulls in Game
3, were trying to shake it off as just another loss. No team had
scored fewer points since the introduction of the shot clock for
the 1954-55 season.
	   ``I think the players are fine. They all said hello when they
got on the bus,'' Sloan said. ``When I really have a problem is if
they don't speak to me.''
	   Forward Byron Russell was also in a playful mood.
	   Teammate Shandon Anderson was dead serious as he gave
interviews, so serious he didn't notice Russell sneak up to the
edge of the group.
	   With a grin on his face, Russell piped up.
	   ``What about last night? Did you go out, have a good time?''
Russell asked.
	   Anderson, not realizing who was talking to him, looked up as if
to answer. There was Russell, giggling at him. Anderson smiled and
couldn't help but laugh.
	   ``You know what? That's what we need,'' Anderson said. ``We need
to be loose. I think everybody plays uptight, that's why sometimes
we get put in situations where we make mistakes instead of just
going out there loose and having fun.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; EVEN IN BOSNIA: &LR;  A Bosnian TV crew is among the more than 1,300
media members covering the NBA Finals, where 43 countries are
represented.
	   Croatia native Toni Kukoc is a big star in Bosnia, but not as
big as another member of the Bulls, announcer Mizra Vilic said.
	   ``Michael Jordan is most popular. Toni is popular, too, but not
like Michael,'' he said.
	   Kukoc, a three-time European Player of the Year, is finishing
his fifth season with the Bulls. Jordan retired a few weeks after
Kukoc arrived in 1993, and Kukoc was so upset that he wasn't going
to realize his dream of playing with the world's greatest player
that he cried.
	   Now that he and Jordan have played on two championship teams
together and are going for a third, Kukoc says he's never regretted
his decision to come to the NBA and see how good he really is.
	   Instead of being the star he was in Europe, he's behind Jordan,
Scottie Pippen and Dennis Rodman as the team's top attractions.
	   ``I have no problems with that simply for the reason it's a team
sport and once your team is winning championships and playing in
the Finals, you are going to be well recognized as a player,''
Kukoc said Monday.
	   ``If you're on other teams and not winning or not getting into
the playoffs, then nobody is going to take you seriously.''
	    &UR; ---- &QC; 
	    &UR; NOT RUBBING IT IN: &LR;  Jazz guard Jeff Hornacek didn't agree with
suggestions the Bulls were piling it on in the fourth quarter of
Game 3 by shooting 3-pointers. Chicago won by 42 points.
	   Utah was down by 20 with a couple of minutes to go in the third
quarter when coach Jerry Sloan took Hornacek out along with John
Stockton and Karl Malone.
	   ``He saw if we didn't make a run in the third quarter we were
not going to make one, it was not going to be our night,'' Hornacek
said.
	   ``I don't think they were running it up at all. I'm sure if we
were up 20 our bench guys would try to score. Our bench guys would
want to get out and play, too.''
	   The Bulls regulars, most notably Michael Jordan, Ron Harper and
Scottie Pippen, were yukking it up as they sat out the final
minutes.
	   ``They had fun doing it and I'd laugh, too,'' Utah's Bryon
Russell said.
	   ``It's not a big deal whether you lose by one, 50, or 60. It's
still a loss.''
</TEXT>
