<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0821 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 1100 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Stocks rose modestly Monday, padding Friday's
big gains and positioning some measures for a new run toward record
levels. The Dow Jones industrial average rose about 31 points to
9,069, about 140 points from May 13's record close of 9,211.84. The
broad market also extended Friday's rally, although the battered
technology group fell back into a rut after a two-session rebound.
There were no major economic reports to consider in Monday's
session, which was dominated by news of a dlrs 34 billion merger
between Norwest and Wells Fargo and the government's decision to
bring an antitrust complaint against Intel. (US-CLOSING STOCKS)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian stocks drifted slightly lower in light
trading Monday, while traders waited to see whether President Boris
Yeltsin would bring home an aid package from his two-day visit to
Germany. The Russian Trading System closed down 1.1 percent, a far
cry from the wild swings caused by panic-selling late last month.
The ruble was unchanged at 6.18 to the dollar. Although the markets
have stabilized and the Russian government insists no formal aid
request has been made, traders still expect a bailout either from
Yeltsin's German trip or the meeting of Group of Seven deputy
finance ministers in Paris on Tuesday. (RUSSIA-ECONOMY)
	   PARIS (AP) _ Entering the second week of a strike with no
settlement in sight, Air France pilots moved onto a collision
course with the World Cup on Monday, two days before the soccer
championship begins. Trouble also was brewing on the ground with a
strike call by Bordeaux bus drivers for Thursday _ when droves of
tourists are likely to arrive in the southern city for the soccer
match between Italy and Chile. In the skies, only one in four Air
France planes took off Monday, the eighth day of the strike, and
the same was expected Tuesday. (AIR FRANCE-STRIKE)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The Federal Reserve Monday approved the merger
of the U.S. operations of two big Swiss banks, which are
negotiating with Holocaust survivors in an effort to settle claims
that the banks stole assets from dormant wartime accounts. The
central bank governors voted 5-0 to approve the melding of American
operations of Swiss Bank Corp. and Union Bank of Switzerland, which
are merging to create the United Bank of Switzerland. With some
dlrs 706 billion in assets, it will be the second-biggest bank
worldwide. The biggest is Japan's Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi.
(US-SWISS BANKS)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The U.S. Federal Trade Commission voted Monday
to bring an antitrust complaint against Intel Corp., alleging the
giant microprocessor chip manufacturer froze out and punished
competitors that needed help in developing new products. When three
companies tried to enforce their own patents on computer parts and
technology, Intel retaliated by withholding vital technical
information and threatening to cut off the supply of chips, the
agency charged in an 11-page complaint. Asked what remedy he had in
mind, Baer told reporters at a news conference that he wanted an
order preventing Intel from continuing the alleged practice. Intel
controls 90 percent of the world market for microprocessor chips,
which are the brains of a computer system. (US-INTEL-FTC)
	   LUXEMBOURG (AP) _ The EU governments agreed after several hours
of talks Monday to phase out high sea drift nets by Dec. 31, 2001,
to prevent the unnecessary death of thousands of species such as
seals, dolphins and whales. Two countries, France and Italy, voted
against the agreement that applies to boats registered in EU
countries. Ireland abstained. Britain's Agriculture Minister Jack
Cunningham called the negotiations ``on the whole amicable but
tough.'' The negotiations have been on the agenda since 1994, he
said. France, Italy and Ireland argued the ban would threaten the
livelihood of fishermen. (EU-DRIFT NETS)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) - Honda Motor Co. agreed Monday to pay dlrs 17.1
million and extend warranties to settle charges that it disabled
pollution monitoring equipment in 1.7 million cars and vans. The
consent agreement announced by the Justice Department is the
largest civil penalty ever for violation of the Clean Air Act. It
could cost Honda as much as dlrs 267 million if future free auto
repair work is included, officials said. In a separate action, the
Justice Department also announced that Ford Motor Co. had agreed to
a dlrs 7.8 million settlement in a case involving tampering with
emission controls on 60,000 Econoline vans in an effort to get
better gas mileage. Ford agreed to recall the vans to fix the
defect and pay a dlrs 2.5 million civil fine. (US-HONDA-POLLUTION)
</TEXT>
