<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0777 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Gen. Sani Abacha, the Nigerian dictator
who crushed dissent, defied world condemnation and repeatedly put
off handing power over to a civilian government, died Monday of a
heart attack, leaving leadership of Africa's most-populous nation
in limbo. Crowds in some areas of the capital, Lagos, broke into
cheers at news of the 54-year-old leader's death. Many saw an
opportunity for a return to democracy _ even though there was no
sign the military was prepared to yield power, nor that Nigeria's
many rival ethnic groups would cooperate in a peaceful change of
power. ``This death gives us an opportunity to restart our lives,''
opposition leader Soloman Lar said. ``It is our hope that Nigeria
will not miss that chance.'' Abacha, who came to power in a coup
after canceling presidential elections in 1993, had not indicated
who would take his place as leader of the 115 million people in
this turbulent West African nation. (NIGERIA-ABACHA)
	   DECANI, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Diplomats saw devastation reminiscent
of the wars in Bosnia as they were escorted into battle-torn
western Kosovo province _ target of a Serb offensive that prompted
the EU and the United States on Monday to impose new sanctions on
Serbia. Besides burned-out houses and deserted villages, whose
forced evacuation have provoked comparisons to ethnic cleansing,
visitors to the besieged zone saw evidence of fierce fighting
between the Serbs and ethnic Albanian guerrillas. Along with
continued clashes and shelling Monday, the first-hand look at the
devastation provided stark evidence of a fast-worsening scenario
that Western powers fear could turn into another, broader Balkan
war. The destruction in the southern Serb province has increased
foreign pressure on Serbia to stop using its police and army
against militants battling for independence for Kosovo's 9-to-1
ethnic Albanian majority. (YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO)
	   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) _ Ethiopia followed its bombing of
Eritrea's capital with a warning Monday: Ethiopia might have no
choice but to renew attack if Eritrea refuses to withdraw its
troops, Prime Minister Meles Zenawi said. The two East African
nations are locked in a border dispute, with Ethiopia resisting its
smaller, southern neighbor's attempts to assert control over
territory it says is wrongly held by Ethiopia. In Asmara, Eritrea's
capital, a spokesman for President Isaias Afwerki said Ethiopia had
effectively declared war on Eritrea and was using the threat of
renewed air strikes to blockade air and seaports.
(ETHIOPIA-ERITREA)
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Draping the site in Israeli flags, Jewish
settlers took over a pair of buildings in Arab east Jerusalem on
Monday, brawling with Palestinians who tried to stop them. At least
two people were hurt in the melee, including Faisal Husseini, the
top Palestinian official in Jerusalem. He was hit in the head by a
rock. The conflict in the Silwan neighborhood was the latest in an
escalating series of confrontations in Jerusalem's eastern sector.
Each side accuses the other of trying to grab land in the bitterly
contested city. Moving in before dawn, the settlers took over five
apartments in two buildings, plus a plot of land. They trucked in
furniture, strung barbed wire, and hung Israeli flags. ``I see
things getting worse,'' said Husseini, who has called for mass
street protests by Palestinians to block such settlement activity.
``This provocation is pushing the situation to the edge of
disaster.'' (ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS)
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ U.S. President Bill Clinton challenged
world leaders on Monday to work together attacking illegal drugs
and stop wasting time ``pointing fingers'' of blame at each other.
He also announced a dlrs 2 billion media campaign aimed at young
people. ``The debate between drug-supplying and drug-consuming
nations about whose responsibility the drug problem is has gone on
too long,'' Clinton said in the opening address at a United Nations
General Assembly special session on drugs. About 150 nations were
represented at the U.N. session. In his speech, Clinton announced a
dlrs 2 billion, five-year media campaign against drugs, targeting
young people with a message that ``drugs destroy young lives; don't
let it destroy yours.'' Similar campaigns will be launched in
Mexico, Venezuela and Brazil, Clinton said, adding that he
discussed the issue with Brazilian President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso on Sunday. (UN-DRUG SUMMIT)
</TEXT>
