r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Britiain-RedCross     06-08 0356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britiain-Red Cross </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Red Cross urges aid ombudsman to improve aid agencies
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Recipients of humanitarian aid should have an
ombudsman to whom they can complain when charitable relief efforts
go wrong, the British Red Cross said Monday.
	   Proposals for a two-year pilot project will be unveiled
Wednesday at a World Disasters Forum in London, in the hope that it
will make aid agencies more accountable to the people they serve.
	   Experiences of major international aid operations over recent
years have made agencies became more aware that the absence of
regulations governing their activities has frequently led to a lack
of coordination and duplication of effort on the ground, as well as
poor targeting of relief supplies, the organization said.
	   With up to 300 aid agencies flooding into the Great Lakes region
in the aftermath of the Rwandan genocide in 1994 and the subsequent
refugee crisis, there was confusion over what supplies were needed,
which agencies were best placed to provide them and who was
responsible for what, the Red Cross said.
	   When the major aid agencies met for last year's World Disasters
Forum, they agreed that change was needed to increase their
accountability, and the British Red Cross has coordinated the
development of the ombudsman idea in response.
	   ``As the role and responsibilities of aid agencies become more
extensive, we have a duty to become more accountable to those
people we serve,'' the project's coordinator, John Mitchell, said.
``An ombudsman is the best mechanism to achieve this.''
	   The ombudsman would be responsible for improving the delivery of
aid and would investigate complaints from beneficiaries.
	   Grievances the ombudsman might deal with could include
complaints about remote areas or nomadic tribes being missed by aid
distributors or about inappropriate aid being supplied, he said.
	   Mitchell said he would hope to prevent mix-ups which in the past
have seen slimming food supplied to starving Ethiopians and cheese
sent to people in the Far East whose bodies were unable to tolerate
lactose.
	   (er) 	   
</TEXT>
