<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Drugs-Austria </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With UN-Drug Summit
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Austria mixes treatment with ``zero tolerance'' for traffickers &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Austria's drug strategy is based on
offering addicts treatment instead of punishment while applying the
full force of the law to traffickers, the country's interior
minister said Monday.
	   ``Addiction and dependence are primarily medical problems which
require a medical as well as therapeutic approach,'' Interior
Minister Karl Schloegl told the opening session of the U.N. General
Assembly special session on drugs.
	   ``As an alternative to penalty, the concept of `therapy instead
of punishment' for drug addicts is part of the Austrian anti-drug
strategy,'' Schloegl said. ``The drug addict is provisionally given
the chance for treatment with the aim of full social integration.''
	   But the minister said when dealing with traffickers ``criminal
law is fully applied.''
	   ``The Austrian fight against transnational organized drug
trafficking is guided by the principle of `zero tolerance for
serious drug traffickers,''' he said.
	   Schloegl said Austria has relatively low level of drug-related
crime because of the country's economic prosperity and ``continuous
economic growth over the last five decades.''
	   ``A society that is marked by solidarity and prosperity provides
the best basis for a successful multisectoral policy against
drug-related crime and drug abuse,'' he said.
	   But the minister said Austria was not immune to the drug trade,
and the country was carefully watching the Balkans as an avenue for
smuggling drugs into the country and on to other markets in Western
Europe.
	   The Austrian capital Vienna is the headquarters for the U.N.
Drug Control Office which was established to intensify the U.N.
role in the campaign against narcotics.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-UN-Drugs-Austria; CT:i; 
