<SLUG> BC-Guinea-Bissau,0335 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Loyalist troops in Guinea-Bissau in stand off with renegade troops
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Government troops in the West African
nation of Guinea-Bissau remained in a tense stand off with renegade
soldiers early Tuesday after two military installations were seized
following a coup attempt.
	   Heavily armed troops were attempting to dislodge the renegade
soldiers from military installations 10 miles (15 kilometers)
outside of the capital, Bissau, on the road to the airport, the
Portuguese state-run news agency Lusa reported.
	   An unknown number of rebels were holed up at the bases _ a
military barracks and an arms depot _ in the suburb of Bra after
fighting with loyalist troops Sunday, according to Lusa.
	   Troops also set up roadblocks on routes to the presidential
palace and other government buildings and military installations.
	   President Joao Bernardo Vieira said former armed forces chief
Brig. Ansumane Mane was leading the revolt and was backed by
members of political opposition parties.
	   In a statement read on public radio Monday, Vieira vowed to
``use all possible means'' to quash the revolt.
	   Mane was fired six months ago during an investigation into arms
trafficking to the separatist rebels of Casamanca, a Senegalese
province that borders Guinea-Bissau to the north. Mane officially
gave up office only on Saturday.
	   U.S. Embassy spokesman Bryan Hunt, contacted by telephone, said
automatic weapons, rocket-propelled grenades and mortars were used
in the skirmishes near the Russian Embassy in Bissau on Monday.
Automatic weapons and small-arms fire could also be heard.
	   A reporter for Guinea-Bissau national radio, interviewed by
Lisbon radio TSF, said he counted 30 bodies scattered around the
two bases.
	   Guinea-Bissau, a former Portuguese colony, has 1 million people.
	   There are about 100 U.S. citizens in the country, including
government officials, business people, tourists and Peace Corps
workers.
</TEXT>
