<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Japan-Teen Star,0376 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Star teen Japan's World Cup hope in 1998 and 2002
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By YURI KAGEYAMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AIX-LES-BAINS, France (AP) _ At 18, Shinji Ono is the kid on
Japan's World Cup squad. But the shy, quiet midfielder happens to
be Japanese soccer's biggest hope for the future.
	   Ono is sure to be a central player at the 2000 Olympics in
Sydney as well as at the 2002 World Cup that Japan will play
co-host with South Korea.
	   Coach Takeshi Okada has repeatedly dropped hints that Ono is
bound for great things even sooner, at this World Cup, where Japan
faces Argentina, Croatia and Jamaica in the first round.
	   ``He has fantastic talent,'' Okada said.
	   In hierarchical Japanese society, it can be trying to be the
youngest member of a team.
	   ``It's not that bad, but I feel it,'' Ono said after a recent
practice at this French lakeside resort that is Japan's base camp
during the tournament. ``I am especially careful about my
language.''
	   Status distinctions in Japan are rigidly reflected in speech,
meaning different words and sentence structure must be used to show
respect to elders.
	   But the J-League's top rookie, signed with the Urawa Red
Diamonds, makes it clear all that doesn't apply on the pitch.
	   Ono's dream is to sign with a foreign league club, perhaps in
Spain, Italy or England.
	   ``I've always thought the World Cup was out of reach, so I'm
happy this is a reality,'' he said. ``If there's any opportunity,
I'm going to give it 100 percent so I become famous all over the
world. I want to show play that my opponents and even my teammates
can't imagine.''
	   Ono possesses a dancelike finesse in dribbling that makes him
delightfully fun to watch. In recent practice, he made dazzling
penalty kicks, sending the ball over players' head with artful
precision.
	   The 1.75 meter, 74 kilogram (6-foot, 160-pound) Ono has also
shown remarkable leadership, confidence and charm for someone so
young, quick to draw laughs with his unpretentious jokes.
	   But Ono showed a bit of the little boy left in him when asked to
name the most important person in his life.
	   ``My mom,'' he said.
</TEXT>
