<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-South Africa-Khumalo,0413 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: No regrets over apartheid boycott for Doctor Khumalo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TOM COHEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VICHY, France (AP) _ Doctor Khumalo looked the French
interviewer in the eye, then calmly explained why he could never
regret the apartheid boycott of South African soccer that denied
him a chance to play in previous World Cups.
	   ``I'm proud of what I am today,'' the 30-year-old midfielder
said. ``I'm proud of my country and what we've achieved in South
Africa.''
	   Pressed again, he tried to inform the questioner of a basic
South African truth.
	   ``I was part of the struggle. I don't regret that,'' said
Khumalo, who is black.
	   A gifted ballhandler, Khumalo almost missed what will likely be
his only chance to play in the global soccer showcase.
	   He had played in almost every match since the 28-year ban from
international soccer ended in 1992 and even scored the winning goal
on a penalty in the first game, against Cameroon.
	   Then his father, a former pro player in South Africa, was
murdered by robbers in the Soweto black township in 1996 and
Khumalo's game lost its spark. His insightful passes weren't as
sharp, and more importantly, he often seemed to be floating.
	   When former coach Clive Barker, a strong backer of Khumalo,
resigned in December after South Africa went winless at the
Confederation Cup tournament in Saudi Arabia, Khumalo was dropped
from the national side by interim coach Jomo Sono.
	   He missed the African Nations Cup tournament in February, then
rejoined the team after Philippe Troussier took over from Sono in
March. Now Khumalo is battling for a starting spot and just happy
to be in France.
	   ``I expect us to go to the second round,'' he said Monday night
after South Africa's first practice in France.
	   The boycott of South Africa was to protest apartheid and was one
of several international sanctions against the hated system of
white minority dominance. Khumalo was 8 years old when the Soweto
student riots erupted in 1976 and like any township youth, his life
was intertwined with the anti-apartheid struggle.
	   So when the foreign interviewer asked if the boycott hurt his
career, he felt obliged to give a history lesson.
	   ``It's because of the political issue that happened in South
Africa,'' he said. ``It kept us away from the world. Whatever
happened in past years, its gone.''
</TEXT>
