<SLUG> BC-Germany-Train Derails,0315 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German railway restoring service through scene of rail disaster
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos SESC101,103-105 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ Germany's national railway hoped to send the first
train Tuesday over a stretch of tracks closed since a high-speed
wreck killed almost 100 people last week.
	   Investigators were still sifting through loose dirt at the site
Monday in search of personal effects and additional human remains
from the June 3 crash of an InterCity Express on the
Hanover-Hamburg line.
	   Workers also have been laying new tracks, and railway officials
said they expected to send the first train through the northern
village of Eschede _ site of the disaster _ on Tuesday afternoon
unless accident investigators object.
	   Fifty-nine express trains were pulled out of service while
railway officials worked to determine what caused a wheel to break
on the ill-fated train, apparently causing the derailment and
gruesome pileup.
	   Officials on Monday doubled the number of inspectors and
ultrasound machines used for safety checks to restore full service
at the normal top speed of 280 kph (175 mph) as soon as possible.
	   German rail director Johannes Ludewig said inspectors have found
no wheel defects so far, but that the inspections would take up to
two weeks more.
	   The railway has been using slower, replacement trains and
emergency plans in the meantime, leading to considerable delays for
train passengers.
	   Officials have identified 73 of the 98 victims. Some remains
were so badly damaged that forensic experts say DNA analysis will
be necessary to identify them.
	   German President Roman Herzog will lead a memorial service for
the victims and their families on June 21 in Celle, the main town
outside of Eschede. Officials delayed the service, originally
scheduled for Friday, due to the slow job of recovering and
identifying the dead. 	   
</TEXT>
