<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Euro Bank,0174 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
European Central Bank's governing board to hold first meeting
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ The 17-member policy-making body of
the European Central Bank holds its first meeting Tuesday, but the
bank president said procedural issues would likely be the only
topics discussed.
	   ``It's too early'' to make any decisions on monetary policy,
bank president Wim Duisenberg said Monday on the sidelines of the
annual meeting of the Bank for International Settlements in Basel,
Switzerland.
	   ``Certainly there won't be any decision on monetary targeting
yet,'' Duisenberg said. ``That may not even be a discussion yet.''
	   Monetary targeting includes setting goals for money supply
growth or inflation that will guide the European Central Bank in
forming monetary policy.
	   The bank, based in Frankfurt, will set monetary policy for
European Union members adopting a planned single European currency.
Eleven countries have been selected to be among the inaugural
members when monetary union begins Jan. 1. 	   
</TEXT>
