<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,0398 </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Mexico, Paraguay and Puerto Rico. &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Mexico City's residents still have a deep,
continuing distrust of the police, according to a survey published
Monday, almost six months after the city's first opposition mayor
took office promising to clean up the notoriously corrupt force.
	   Only 9 percent of residents believe the police are doing a good
job, according to a poll conducted by the daily Reforma. A year
ago, 6 percent of residents said they thought police were doing a
good job.
	   The poll, in which 795 adults were interviewed, had a margin of
error 3 percent, making the rise statistically negligible.
	   Only 23 percent of those interviewed said they had some
confidence in police, up from 21 percent a year ago.
	   Twenty-three percent said they were crime victims _ mostly of
robberies _ this year. Seventy-five percent said they did not
bother to report it, apparently feeling it would do no good.
	   The rate of unreported crimes, according to the survey, has
risen steadily since 1991.
	   ___
	   ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) _ More than 3,000 Paraguayan farmers
marched in the capital of Asuncion on Monday, demanding the
government help with growing agricultural problems.
	   The farmers, who gathered at the Ministry of Agriculture in
downtown Asuncion, called for assistance with shortage of farming
land, lack of financial and credit support and technical help.
	   ``We're not able able to continue waiting,'' said Alberto Areco,
a march organizer. ``Our families are hungry, and the government
has not fulfilled its promises.''
	   Organized by the National Campesina Federation, the march
snarled traffic leading into the capital as well as important
routes into the interior of the country.
	   ___
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ The U.S. Coast Guard repatriated
seven Cubans rescued last week from a 15-foot (4.5-meter) boat near
the Bahamas, officials said Monday.
	   They were taken to the port at Bahia de Cabanas, Cuba, Saturday
morning. An eighth migrant was granted political asylum and sent to
the U.S. Navy Base at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, to begin applying for a
visa.
	   The eight Cubans were found adrift June 2 about 50 kilometers
(30 miles) southeast of Cay Lobos in the Bahamas. The boat's engine
had failed, the Coast Guard said.
</TEXT>
