<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar rises to 141 yen, Tokyo stocks edge higher
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Nikkei trading, adds latest economic assessment
in 4th graf &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar climbed to a new seven-year high
against the yen Tuesday morning in Tokyo ahead of a key meeting of
the group of major industrialized nations. Tokyo stocks edged
higher in light trading.
	   The dollar bought 141.04 yen in early trading, up 0.40 yen from
late Monday in Tokyo, a level not seen since June 19, 1991. In New
York overnight, it settled at 140.71 yen.
	   Japan's weak economy remained the fundamental reason for the
yen's continued weakness.
	   In its monthly report for June, Japan's Economic Planning Agency
reiterated that the economy continues to stagnate, but said that
consumer spending was showing signs of recovery.
	   Deputy finance ministers from the Group of Seven nations are to
meet in Paris later Tuesday. The Group of Seven is composed of the
United States, Canada, Britain, Germany, France, Italy and Japan.
	   Japan's Finance Minister Hikaru Matsunaga said Tuesday that he
can't rule out the possibility that the recent weakening of the yen
against the dollar will be discussed by G-7 officials.
	   ``I can't say that press reports saying that the meeting will
mainly discuss the Russia problem, and won't discuss foreign
exchange, are right,'' Matsunaga said at a regular news conference.
	   Matsunaga said that the G-7 nations are constantly discussing
trends in foreign exchange rates. He added that Japan's G-7
partners will cooperate with Japan, and Japan will take decisive
action to correct the weakening of the yen, if necessary.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
rose 56.59 points, or 0.37 percent, to 15,351.30 points in the
first 30 minutes of trading. On Monday, the average shed 28.72
points, or 0.19 percent.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 0.87 points, or 0.07 percent, to 1,198.36. The
TOPIX closed down 3.58 points, or 0.30 percent, the day before.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond stood at 1.145 percent, unchanged from Monday's
close. Its price was marginally lower at 112.45 yen, down from
Monday's 112.46 yen.
 &UR; (km-dj) 	   
