<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Crops </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Winter crops will be good as El Nino declines, forecaster says
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ The long-awaited departure of the El
Nino weather pattern will boost Australia's winter crops, including
wheat, the government's chief commodity forecaster said Tuesday.
	   But widespread rain in April and early May was too late to stop
the summer crop production forecast for the 12 months to June 1998
being cut to 3.9 million (metric) tons from about 4.1 million tons,
the Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource Economics said
in its June crop report.
	   However, Australian wheat production was forecast to increase to
19.3 million tons in the 12 months to June 30, 1999, up four
percent on the previous year and exceeding the bureau's earlier
18.4 million ton forecast.
	   ``Winter rainfall prospects are likely to improve with the
Bureau of Meteorology reporting that the recent El Nino event
declined rapidly in May and should no longer affect Australian
rainfall,'' said Stephen Beare, the bureau's acting executive
director.
	   ``As a result of the rainfall, winter crop plantings are
expected to increase in 1998-99 to just over 18 million hectares
(44 million acres).''
	   Production of winter crops, ranging from pulses to coarse
grains, should reach 29.7 million (metric) tons, a 600,000-ton
increase on the previous crop report estimate.
	   Coarse grains production forecasts are down nine percent to 6.9
million tons, as farmers move out of crops such as barley and oats
to higher-return canola, Beare said.
	   Land preparation and sowing was underway in most districts, but
follow-up rain was urgently needed in southeastern Australia.
	   Beare said nearly all early sown summer crops were now harvested
and the rest should be gathered by the end of June.
	   ``Prolonged dry conditions during the summer growing season
followed by rains during harvest adversely affected yields and
quality in some areas, particularly central Queensland (state),''
he said.
	   But the quality of New South Wales state summer crops looked
excellent, with record yields of 9.4 tons per hectare (2.47 acres)
already reported by the rice industry.
	   The bureau estimates that 2.9 million bales (666,000 tons) of
lint has been produced from the 1997-98 summer cotton crop, setting
a new record for Australian production. 	   
</TEXT>
