<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Eritrea-Ethiopia,0554 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ethiopia threatens more military action, Eritrea urges talks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS pvs &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos ASM101-104 of June 8 &QL; 
 &UR; By KARIN DAVIES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) _ With Ethiopia threatening to attack
Eritrea again unless its neighbor withdraws from disputed
territory, the U.S. government made plans to evacuate at least
another 120 of its citizens Tuesday.
	   The American planes would also carry Germans, Egyptians and some
Ethiopians.
	   The Eritrean government on Monday called for direct talks
between the two Horn of Africa countries in the presence of
high-level mediators ``so as to ensure a speedy resolution of the
crisis.''
	   President Isaias Afwerki's spokesman said Ethiopia had
effectively declared war on Eritrea and was using the threat of
renewed air strikes to blockade air and seaports.
	   ``They won't compromise,'' Yemane Gebremeskel said. ``These are
not the actions of a nation that wants peace.''
	   In Addis Ababa, Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi accused
the Eritreans of ``a pattern of prevarication, a pattern of trying
to draw out the process and consolidate their hold on our
territory.
	   ``If that's the case _ and it appears to be the case _ then the
opportunities for resolving this problem peacefully could be fastly
disappearing,'' he told The Associated Press.
	   Eritrea claims its forces are within internationally recognized
borders drawn by Italy in the late 19th century. Eritrea, an
Italian colony from 1885 to 1941, was annexed in 1962 by Ethiopia,
against whom it later fought a 30-year war for independence.
	   With per capita annual incomes of less than dlrs 300 a year,
Ethiopia and Eritrea are among the world's poorest countries.
	   African leaders deplored the Horn of Africa conflict at an
Organization of African Unity summit Monday in the western African
country of Burkina Faso.
	   An Italian envoy at the OAU meeting talked with the foreign
ministers of Ethiopia and Eritrea and asked for a halt to further
bombing raids.
	   ``There's reason to believe that this will be heeded,'' the
Italian Foreign Affairs Ministry said.
	   The envoy, undersecretary of state for foreign affairs Rino
Serri, was expected to visit Asmara and Addis Ababa imminently, it
said.
	   The United States and Rwanda have crafted a four-point peace
proposal that would require Eritrea withdraw to positions it
occupied prior to May 6, when border skirmishes broke out. Ethiopia
has accepted the plan, but Eritrea says it needs more work.
	   On Friday and Saturday, Ethiopian warplanes bombed a
military-civilian airport on the outskirts of Asmara. Anti-aircraft
artillery shot down two Ethiopian MiG-23s.
	   Ethiopia has said the bombing was in retaliation for an Eritrean
attack Friday on a school in Mekele, northeastern Ethiopia, which
killed 44 people, including 10 children.
	   But Eritrean Air Force Cmdr. Habtezion Hadgu vehemently denied
the charge, saying Ethiopia bombed the Asmara airport first. ``This
is tit for tat _ one to 100, that's the exchange rate. They hit us,
I hit them harder.''
	   Asmara-based diplomats confirmed the commander's version, saying
the airport attack occurred shortly after 2 p.m. (1100 GMT) Friday,
and 50 minutes later two Eritrean warplanes took off and headed
south.
</TEXT>
