<SLUG> BC-Puerto Rico-Statehood,0367 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Poll: Puerto Ricans split on statehood
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DAN PERRY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Puerto Ricans are deeply split on
whether to become a full member of the United States, despite a
relentless lobby by their pro-statehood governor, a poll published
Monday showed.
	   The poll in The San Juan Star daily showed support for becoming
the 51st state at 40.9 percent, while 40.2 percent favored
retaining the unusual ``commonwealth'' status worked out in 1952.
	   Under commonwealth, Puerto Rico's 3.8 million residents are U.S.
citizens but don't pay federal taxes, don't vote for president and
are represented in Congress only by a non-voting delegate.
	   Critics deride that arrangement as a relic of colonial times.
But opponents of statehood note that Puerto Ricans feel themselves
a nation with their own culture and an overwhelming preference for
Spanish over English.
	   In a non-binding 1993 referendum on the Caribbean island's
political status, continued commonwealth edged out statehood by two
percentage points.
	   Of the 1,011 people interviewed by the Precision Research firm
two weeks ago, 7.6 percent preferred independence _ almost double
the level of support independence received in the referendum.
	   The poll _ which carried a 3 percent error margin _ was sobering
news for Gov. Pedro Rossello, whose drive to persuade the U.S.
Congress to allow statehood is being hampered by his people's
ambivalence.
	   The debate over Puerto Rico's status has intensified since the
U.S. House of Representatives three months ago approved a bill for
a binding plebiscite.
	   The bill appears stalled in the Senate, where it faces
Republican opposition.
	   But Rossello has hinted that he may hold a referendum anyway. He
argues that 1998 _ being the year that marks a century of U.S.
control over the island _ is the right time for a decision.
	   The Star poll also revealed widespread dissatisfaction with
``life in Puerto Rico'' _ which was ranked as ``bad'' by some 41
percent, ``fair'' by another 41 percent, and ``good'' by only about
19 percent. The island suffers from high rates of crime,
unemployment and inflation. 	   
</TEXT>
