<HEADLINE>
Australia unchanged for Scotland test
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Australia's record-breaking rugby team
survived intact for Saturday's first test against Scotland.
	   Wallaby coach Rod Macqueen said the players who thrashed England
by a record 76-0 last Saturday night had all recovered well and
were fit and ready for the Scots.
	   Rookie fly-half Stephen Larkham was outstanding in his first
match for his country in the position as Australia posted a record
score and record winning margin in all tests and inflicted
England's worst-ever defeat.
	   Macqueen said he expected a tougher match against the Scots, who
were beaten 51-26 by Fiji in their most recent test outing.
	   ``Of course I am happy with the way we went against England but
there are many areas of our game that we can improve,'' Macqueen
said. ``We were a bit sloppy across the field and our set pieces
weren't that great so we're working on those things this week and
hopefully they will improve.''
	   The first test against Scotland will mark the 50th tests for
Queenslanders David Wilson and reserve back Jason Little. The
second test will be played in Brisbane on June 20.
	   Australia: Matthew Burke, Ben Tune, Daniel Herbert, Tim Horan,
Joe Roff, Stephen Larkham, George Gregan, Toutai Kefu, David
Wilson, Matt Cockbain, John Eales (captain), Tom Bowman, Andrew
Blades, Phil Kearns, Richard Harry. Reserves: Chris Whitaker,
Nathan Grey, Jason Little, Willie Ofahengaue, Owen Finegan, Dan
Crowley, Jeremy Paul.
