w2188 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo     06-08 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo,0628 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sealed for a week of fighting, Kosovo region reveals its
</HEADLINE>
devastation &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous. &QL; 
 &UR; With US-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, EU-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos PRI101-104 &QL; 
 &UR; By ALEKSANDAR VASOVIC &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DECANI, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Stray cattle roaming among spent
ammunition. Deserted houses riddled with grenade holes. Devastation
reminiscent of wartime Bosnia greeted diplomats allowed into
western Kosovo, target of a Serb offensive that prompted new
international sanctions.
	   The first look by outsiders since the latest Serb campaign
revealed charred ruins everywhere _ but few people, except for
armed Serb policemen. The area had been sealed for more than a week
during fighting that drove out tens of thousands of the province's
ethnic Albanian majority _ and heightened fears of a new, bigger
Balkan war.
	   ``What we've seen is all sorrow, all grief ... all those
villages burned and destroyed, all the people had left,'' Dutch
ambassador Jan Sizoo said Monday after visiting Decani on Sunday.
	   Sizoo was in the first group of foreign diplomats to see the
region since Serb police and soldiers began a punishing offensive
in late May, part of an intensifying campaign against militants
battling for independence for Kosovo's 90 percent ethnic Albanian
majority.
	   Journalists were turned back from another convoy that went in
Monday. More fighting was reported elsewhere in Kosovo.
	   In Streoce, the first village the diplomats saw, more than 20
houses were burned or shelled, and only a few policemen were
present.
	   Fresh coats of paint on shops on the outskirts of Decani could
not conceal graffiti praising the militant Kosovo Liberation Army.
A few Serb townspeople lingered about the police station.
	   Police showed the diplomats an array of weapons they said were
confiscated from militants.
	   On the road to Djakovica, the scene recalled some of the worst
damage in Bosnia and Croatia. Many houses were gutted by flames.
Cartridges of various caliber littered the area.
	   Cattle, untended, roamed the empty village of Prilep, four miles
south of Decani. Houses were peppered with bullet holes. Some had
gaping holes made by grenades.
	   There were clear signs of what the European Union assailed as
``widespread house-burning and indiscriminate artillery attacks on
whole villages'' _ as well as actions by the Kosovo Liberation
Army.
	   After seeing only ``part of what one could call a battlefield,''
Sizoo said: ``We've been told (by Serb authorities) that the blame
is on the terrorists who started first. But, this statement is very
difficult to defend _ for a conflict you always need two parties.''
	   Serb forces continued shelling the area around the Albanian
border Monday, according to the Kosovo Information Center, close to
the ethnic Albanian leadership. Its Serb counterpart, the pro-Serb
Media Center, said ethnic Albanian militants attacked two Serb
villages in the Drenica region.
	   The U.S. government, accusing Yugoslavia of wholesale violence
against the Kosovo Albanian population, decided Monday to freeze
Yugoslav assets in the United States and to ban investments in that
country.
	   The EU tightened sanctions Monday in reaction to the offensive _
banning new investments in Serbia and freezing its assets abroad _
and urged NATO to consider military intervention.
	   In Washington, State Department spokesman James Rubin said the
United States has not ruled out military options.
	   A prominent Kosovo Albanian, Nekibe Kelmendi, welcomed the new
sanctions but said they were only a ``small step'' compared to the
situation on the ground.
	   Ethnic Albanian leaders say more than 50 people have been killed
in the latest offensive and 200 men were missing and presumed
captured.
</TEXT>
