<BODY>
<SLUG> FEA-Low-Cost Airlines,0788 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Low-cost airline wars heat up in Europe
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: easyJet is cq &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo NY351 of June 2; AP Graphic EUROPE AIR FARES &QL; 
 &UR; By DIRK BEVERIDGE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Business Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Little airlines across Europe are taking off on
dozens of new routes, luring passengers with colorful sales pitches
and cheap fares.
	   One advertisement shows Greek businessman Stelios Haji-Ioannou,
the boss of easyJet, lamenting that he's ``tired of being ripped
off'' every time he flies home to Athens.
	   Haji-Ioannou's response: Two daily flights from London that take
off in July with tickets starting at 69 pounds (dlrs 112) one way _
one-third less than similar flights on British Airways or the Greek
flag carrier, Olympic Airways.
	   Low-cost rival Debonair is running ads featuring a promise by
its boss, former Continental Airlines executive Franco Mancassola,
not to squash passengers into tiny seats. In all his years of
running airlines, Mancassola boasts, he has never sold a seat to a
sardine.
	   And a low-cost Irish carrier, Ryanair, recently launched new
London-to-Dublin flights with fares as low as 30 pounds (dlrs 49)
one-way.
	   ``This fare is not a gimmick. It's here to stay,'' says
Ryanair's marketing director, Tim Jeans.
	   The big airlines are taking note, and it's not the clever ad
copy that has them worried.
	   The small, no-frills carriers are cutting into their business on
routes that for decades were run in cartel fashion. But that was
before the European Union began a deregulation of its aviation
industry that was completed a year ago.
	   With new carriers starting up services all around Europe,
analysts have been wondering if the newly deregulated skies will
run into the same problems that followed U.S. deregulation two
decades ago _ numerous airline bankruptcies.
	   An ominous shadow was cast on the low-cost sector of the
industry in May when one of Europe's biggest and most profitable
airlines, British Airways, stepped into the market. BA launched its
own low-cost carrier, called Go, based at London's uncrowded
Stansted Airport.
	   Accusing BA of illegally subsidizing Go in a bid to wreck the
competition, easyJet is fighting back in court.
	   ``The suspicion we have is that British Airways is doing this to
put the other low-cost carriers out of business,'' easyJet
spokesman James Rothnie said. ``That's historically what they do.
They either buy you out or stamp you out.''
	   Go executives did not respond to interview requests. But after a
judge stuck down easyJet's bid to stop Go from flying, chief
executive Barbara Cassani predicted that if the case went to trial,
it would show that ``Go is entirely lawful.''
	   The cheap carriers are modeled after Dallas-based Southwest
Airlines, which reshaped air travel in America. But while Southwest
turned heads in the U.S. industry by serving only complimentary
peanuts and drinks, many of the low-cost European carriers make
passengers pay for even a cup of coffee if they want one.
	   Southwest's low fares forced the big players in the domestic
U.S. market to shave costs by cutting meals on many flights and to
operate small carriers to fly passengers into their hubs from
secondary cities.
	   The trend in European aviation is likewise forcing the big
players to find different ways to respond.
	   Sabena, the Belgian flag carrier, found itself confronted with
low-cost competition at its Brussels hub from Virgin Express, run
by British entrepreneur Richard Branson.
	   Rather than get into a damaging fare war, Sabena forged a
partnership with Virgin Express. Sabena canceled a number of its
services from Brussels to three cities, London, Barcelona and Rome,
and let Virgin Express take over the routes with its own airplanes
and crew.
	   Both carriers sell tickets on the same jets, however, with
Sabena marketing all of the high-priced business class fares and
Virgin Express selling some of the cheaper seats in the back of the
airplane.
	   ``It was a win-win situation,'' said Etienne De Nil, Sabena's
general manager for the United Kingdom and Ireland. ``Instead of
fighting with each other, we said, `Let's cooperate.'''
	   The deregulation of Europe's skies came at a time when air
travel was booming and many airlines around the world were racking
up record profits.
	   Perhaps thanks to the timing, nobody has gone broke _ yet _ and
the expansion seems to be continuing with no letup in sight. But
the pressure will be on when times turn tough in what has always
been a highly cyclical business.
	   ``As long as British Airways are there, it is inevitable that
some of the low-cost carriers will go out of business,'' said
Rothnie, the easyJet spokesman.
</TEXT>
