<SLUG> BC-UN-Drugs in Paradise,0374 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Drug epidemic even reaches tiny Palau in middle of the Pacific
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT H. REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The worldwide drug epidemic has even
spread to remote Palau, the U.N.'s newest and smallest member state
located in the Western Pacific far from the world's drug centers.
	   ``In our paradise, we experience the scourge and horror of
illegal drugs, particularly among the young people,'' said
President Kuniwo Nakamura in a message read by his U.N. ambassador,
Hersey Kyota, to the U.N. General Assembly special session on
drugs.
	   ``Our problem is real and escalating and may be equally
compatible to the larger and more populated societies,'' Nakamura
said.
	   Nakamura said the major threat to Palau's 16,000 people _ who
live on a string of about 200 small islands 960 kilometers (600
miles) east of the Philippines _ comes from methamphetamine
crystals.
	   Amphetamines, abused by an estimated 30 million people
worldwide, are the ``drug of choice'' in much of East Asia, where
it is known as ``ice'' or ``shabu.''
	   ``The range of people who use `ice' has expanded to ages as low
as 13 and 14 years old,'' the president said in his message.
	   In an observation more commonly associated with inner cities of
the United States, the president said in his message that drug
abuse in high schools had led to ``higher rates of absenteeism,
dramatic lowering of grades, less concentration in the classroom''
and ``loss of interest in sports activities.''
	   Nakamura said Palau, which became the 185th U.N. member state in
December 1994, is facing a drug threat despite a growing economy,
pristine environment, cheap and abundant seafoods, low crime rates
and a tradition of strong family ties.
	   His message: if drug abuse can happen in remote Palau, it can
happen anywhere.
	   ``Drugs and the damage they cause society are not limited to
places around the world that suffer economically or do not have
high levels of education or opportunity,'' he said.
	   ``Illegal drug use around the world _ as it is in the paradise
of Palau _ a major and growing economic and human tragedy,'' he
added.
</TEXT>
