<SLUG> BC-UN-Colombia-Drugs,0371 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Samper says Colombia has done more than any country to fight drugs
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Colombian President Ernesto Samper told
world leaders at a drug summit that no country had done more to
fight the drug trade than his.
	   Colombia too is a victim, and has been unfairly criticized by
the international community, Samper told the U.N. General Assembly
special session on drugs.
	   ``Because of drugs, we have been condemned and victimized by
unilateral measures that, as with all intervention measures that
offend our sovereignty, must be buried forever,'' he said Monday.
	   He noted that he too had ``paid dearly, both morally and
personally,'' for the effects of the drug trade.
	   Washington revoked Samper's tourist visa two years ago,
convinced that his campaign received dlrs 6 million in
contributions from the Cali drug cartel for his 1994 presidential
campaign.
	   Samper travelled to New York for the U.N. session on a
diplomatic visa, as he has done in the past.
	   In his speech, Samper said Colombia spends more than dlrs 1
billion a year fighting drugs _ equal to 21 percent of what it
would cost to provide education for all Colombian children.
	   Colombia, the world's leading producer of cocaine, also
restarted extraditing Colombian nationals charged overseas with
drug crimes, which had been illegal, he said.
	   The government has approved asset forfeiture laws for assets
bought with drug money, he said.
	   ``No country has, like mine, done so much and under such lonely
circumstances to combat drug trafficking,'' he told world leaders.
	   He called for a multilateral approach to tackle the problem
``from the moment the seed of an illegal crop is planted until it
is sold and then consumed as a prepared drug anywhere in the
world.''
	   And he asked ``for international opinion to accept, once and for
all, that since drug trafficking is a market _ with supply and
demand.''
	   To help cut the market, he suggested the creation of an
international fund to pay for crop substitution programs,
interdiction and prevention.
</TEXT>
