<BODY>
<SLUG> FEA-Modernizing Syria,0865 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Times are changing in once-firmly socialist Syria
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo DAM101 of May 27 &QL; 
 &UR; By EILEEN ALT POWELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) _ Billboards with big, red English
lettering along the main streets of Damascus herald the arrival of
something new: the U.S. fast-food chain Kentucky Fried Chicken has
come to Syria.
	   The KFC restaurant, opened in mid-May, joins a growing number of
Western companies like Germany's Adidas and Italy's United Colors
of Benetton brought by franchise or license under Syria's 12-year
effort to modernize its economy.
	   Reforms have been encouraged by the West, especially Europe,
under the theory that giving Syrians and other Arabs more of an
economic stake in the Middle East would encourage peace in the
region.
	   But change comes slowly in Syria's staid socialist system, and
the economy has not been growing fast enough to improve living
standards or create jobs for thousands of young Syrians entering
the work force.
	   All this is creating rare public grumbling in Syria, where Hafez
Assad has ruled with an iron hand for nearly three decades.
	   Even state-run newspapers like Tishrin have complained that
government workers are forced to seek second jobs to supplement
salaries of 2,000 to 5,000 Syrian pounds (dlrs 40 to 100) a month.
	   And businessmen like Rateb al-Shallah, president of the Syrian
Chambers of Commerce, have become outspoken in calling for more
economic liberalization.
	   Al-Shallah told a recent chamber meeting that the government
must take ``a daring and necessary decision'' to reform the banking
system, establish a stock exchange and ease import restrictions so
the country can compete internationally.
	   Syria already has come a long way from the 1960s, when the
government nationalized all large industries, including banks and
public utilities.
	   Since 1986, it has allowed private investment in agriculture and
industry. Then, in May 1991, Parliament passed what has become
Syria's economic mantra, Law No. 10.
	   It aims at attracting investment _ from foreigners as well as
Syrians with billions of dollars squirreled abroad _ by giving tax
holidays of up to nine years, customs exemptions on machinery and
the right to repatriate profits.
	   So far, 1,292 new agricultural, industrial and transport
projects worth 312 billion Syrian pounds, or about dlrs 8 billion,
have been approved, says Mohammed Sarakbi, head of Syria's
Investment Office.
	   Sarakbi says the country is happy with its ``pluralistic
economy'' of public and private enterprises and does not envision
major new reforms soon.
	   ``Syria follows reforms in gradual steps,'' he said. ``The
government takes a step, then studies the results. It doesn't want
to do anything like what happened in Southeast Asia, where the
tigers turned into cats and rabbits.''
	   According to economic statistics, Syria can't afford to wait.
	   After oil discoveries and Law No. 10 spurred strong growth in
the early 1990s, expansion of Syria's dlrs 16 billion economy
slowed to 3.5 percent or less in recent years.
	   That's barely enough to keep up with the 3.3 percent population
growth, among the world's highest. More than half of Syria's 16
million people are under age 16, and some 200,000 young people
enter the work force each year.
	   Faced with low pay and an unemployment rate of some 15 percent,
an estimated one million Syrians have gone to neighboring Lebanon
for work. Thousands more are in the Gulf.
	   Foreign investment has fallen after the initial burst. The
economy didn't get the expected boost from the Middle East peace
process, which all but collapsed in 1996 after the election of a
hard-line Israeli government.
	   Western diplomats say foreign investors are discouraged by
widespread corruption, and young entrepreneurs complain they can't
get financing because state-run banks still give preference to
state-run companies.
	   Even successful businessmen say inadequate financing is
hindering development.
	   ``Law No. 10 was the first step in the direction of a market
economy. What we need is to complete it,'' said industrialist Saeb
Nahas, who urges that private banks replace government institutions
with their ``civil service mentality.''
	   Nahas' companies show how liberalizing the economy can benefit
Syria. One is a dlrs 17 million pharmaceutical plant that has some
300 workers producing medicine under license from Glaxo Wellcome of
Britain, Organon of Holland and Upjohn of the United States.
	   Another company has turned Syria from an importer to an exporter
of industrial chemicals, and a third makes ice cream bars.
	   Business consultant Nabil Sukkar says growing regional pressures
mean ``the time is right for another push on economic reform'' in
Syria.
	   Entrepreneurial Lebanon is seeking more open trade with its
neighbor, the Arab League has a 10-year plan for a free-trade zone,
and the European Union is negotiating a partnership agreement with
Syria to be phased in by 2010.
	   ``All of these will require a restructuring of the economy if we
want to take advantage of these alliances,'' Sukkar said.
</TEXT>
