<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Briefs,0592 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Includes items on Germany's silence over train crash; red card
</HEADLINE>
odds: new FIFA members; Beirut celebrates World Cup; customs vs.
Scots; Premier League dominates &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   NICE, France (AP) _ Germany's World Cup players observed a
minute's silence before a warmup game Monday for the victims of
last week's train disaster at Eschede.
	   Playing a professional but mostly junior selection of players
from second-division clubs Nice and Cannes, Germany used a starting
lineup that is not likely to take the field against the United
States in Paris June 15 and only managed a 2-1 victory.
	   Olaf Marschall and Oliver Bierhoff fired the Germans into a 2-0
lead before the defense was caught embarrassingly flat-footed a few
times and David Andreani replied for the home team.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   LONDON (AP) _ Bookmakers are offering odds of only 10-1 that
four or more players might be sent off in one World Cup game.
	   The new tough rules on the tackle from behind have made it
almost certain that there will be far more red cards at this World
Cup than before.
	   Bookmakers Corals have cut the odds on four or more expulsions
in one game from 25-1 to 10-1.
	   The British-based bookmakers rate an England vs. Scotland final
a 750-1 shot and are offering 250-1 that Denmark's goalkeeper,
Peter Schmeichel, will score with a header.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   PARIS (AP) _ Palestine was among six soccer authorities added to
the FIFA rolls Monday, bringing total membership to 206.
	   Others approved were Eritrea, Turks and Caicos Islands, U.S.
Virgin Islands, American Samoa and Mongolia.
	   The Palestine Football Association has been a provisional member
of FIFA since 1995 but now has added powers, including voting in
federation elections.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Flags from Italy, Brazil and Germany
cover campaign posters for municipal elections. Restaurants are
scrambling to buy TVs. Street peddlers are hawking a range of
France '98 accessories.
	   No, this isn't Paris. This is Beirut.
	   Although Lebanon is not participating, World Cup fever is in
full force here.
	   The tournament has always been a hit in this soccer-mad nation.
During the civil war from 1975 to 1990, militiamen were known to
stop shooting and residents would crank up electrical generators to
watch matches.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   PARIS (AP) _ Beware the tartan terror.
	   French customs officials didn't like the look of the Scottish
fans who arrived at Charles de Gaulle airport before Wednesday's
World Cup opener against Brazil.
	   They told the Scots to remove their ginger wigs and tartan caps
and wash off the face-paint before they would let the fans through
customs.
	   ``It is absolutely ridiculous,'' said 36-year-old Andy Finley,
who was wearing a tailor-made Black Watch tartan suit complete with
waistcoat and top hat.
	   ``It took me hours to paint this flag on my face and the next
thing I'm told to wash it off or they won't let me in the country
because I don't look like my picture in my passport.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	   PARIS (AP) _ Even if England don't win the World Cup, the
English league likely will have a big say in who takes home the
trophy.
	   Of the 704 players at the World Cup, 75 play in England, more
than anywhere else. Spain and Italy have 70, Germany has 54 and
France and Japan have 30.
	   Half of the 32 qualifiers have players who compete in the
English Premier League although that doesn't include hot favorite
Brazil.
</TEXT>
