<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar rises to 141 yen, Tokyo stocks higher
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with midday currency, stock and bond prices

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar touched a new seven-year high
against the yen Tuesday morning in Tokyo ahead of a key meeting of
the G-7 major industrialized nations. Tokyo stocks edged higher in
light trading.
	   The dollar bought 140.63 yen at midday, down 0.01 yen from late
Monday in Tokyo and just below its New York level overnight of
140.71 yen. During Tokyo trading, the dollar rose as high as 141.11
yen, a level not seen since June 1991.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
rose 164.13 points, or 1.06 percent, to 15,458.84 at the close of
morning trading. On Monday, the average shed 28.72 points, or 0.19
percent.
	   The U.S. currency topped 141 yen amid widening sentiment that
Tuesday's meeting in Paris of deputy finance ministers of the Group
of Seven largest economies won't announce joint intervention to
stem the yen's decline.
	   Meanwhile, the main cause of the yen's fall _ Japan's ailing
domestic economy _ remains unchanged. On Tuesday, a Japanese
government report warned that key sectors of the economy such as
employment and production would likely worsen in June.
	   With no economic turnaround in sight, Japan's central bank has
had to leave interest rates at historic lows in an attempt to
reinflate growth.
	   But lower interest rates mean lower returns for Japanese bonds
and other investments, increasing selling pressure on the yen as
investors shift money overseas in search of better returns.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, stock prices rose amid optimism the
strengthening dollar will boost profits at the country's vaunted
exporters.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 4.13 points, or 0.34 percent, to 1,202.49. The
TOPIX closed down 3.58 points, or 0.30 percent, the day before.
	   For every yen the dollar gains in value, Toyota Motor Corp. sees
its earnings jump 10 billion yen (dlrs 71 million) and Sony Corp.
earns another 6 billion yen (dlrs 43 million), Japan's NHK
television said.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond rose to 1.180 percent from Monday's close of 1.145
percent, driving its price down to 112.19 yen from Monday's 112.46
yen.
 &UR; (mef-km-dj) 	   
</TEXT>
