<HEADLINE>
Nigerian military names Abacha's successor
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS quote from Abubakar, declaration of period of mourning;
RESTORES byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By FRANK AIGBOGUN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Nigeria's military early Tuesday named a
general as the new head of state after the unexpected death of Gen.
Sani Abacha, the dictator who crushed dissent, defied world
condemnation and repeatedly put off ceding power to civilians in
Africa's most populous nation.
	   Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar, a major general in the army and
defense chief of staff, was promoted to the full rank of general
during a pre-dawn ceremony in the capital, Abuja. He was sworn into
office by Nigeria's chief justice Mohammed Uwais.
	   ``I appeal to all Nigerians to put all hands on deck to move our
nation forward,'' Abubakar said in a statement issued shortly after
his appointment.
	   As one of his first official acts in power, Abubakar declared
seven days of mourning for Abacha.
