<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyL-Australian-Origin </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Three changes in Queensland starting side
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRISBANE, Australia (AP) _ Newcastle utility Robbie O'Davis,
North Sydney's Ben Ikin and Gold Coast hooker Jamie Goddard were
promoted to Queensland's starting side Tuesday for the June 19
State of Origin rugby league decider in Sydney.
	   The tip that Sydney City's Adrian Lam would play hooker failed
to eventuate when the Queenslander selectors announced their 17-man
squad.
	   Ikin, who has been impressive off the bench in the first two
games of the series, which is locked at 1-1, has grabbed a starting
center spot.
	   Darren Smith shifts to lock while O'Davis has bumped Sydney
City's Matt Sing to the bench.
	   Goddard, whose National Rugby League club is struggling, has
ousted Canterbury hooker Jason Hetherington for the No.9 job for
which selectors also considered brothers Kerrod and Steve Walters
along with Lam.
	   Queensland chairman of selectors Les Geeves said Goddard offered
a slightly different package of options to Hetherington who had
played both games with an injured knee.
	   The selectors dropped Lang from the bench while Brisbane utility
reserve Tonie Carroll, who scored the matchwinning try in game one
in Sydney, was not considered after suffering a hamstring injury.
	   Queensland:
	   Darren Lockyer, Robbie O'Davis, Steve Renouf, Ben Ikin, Wendell
Sailor, Kevin Walters, Allan Langer (captain), Darren Smith, Jason
Smith, Gorden Tallis, Gary Larson, Jamie Goddard, Shane Webcke.
Reserves: Matt Sing, Steve Price, Peter Ryan, Brad Thorn.
