<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Quake </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Earthquake rattles northern South Australia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ An earthquake with a magnitude of 4.3
shook the sparsely populated northern part of South Australia state
on Tuesday. There were no reports of injuries or damage.
	   The quake was at a remote location 37 miles (60 km) southeast of
Oodnadatta in the state's north, Australian Geological Survey
Organization scientist Kevin McCue said.
	   That would be about 530 miles (850 km) northwest of Adelaide.
	   ``There are some mining communities there and although we've
received no reports anyone felt it, there's bound to be someone who
did,'' McCue said.
	   McCue said an earthquake measuring 4.3 would have caused serious
damage had it occurred under a major city or town. 	   
</TEXT>
