w2268 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-NorthKorea     06-08 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-North Korea </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
North Korea says Japanese wives give up plans to visit Japan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A group of Japanese wives married to North Koreans
has canceled plans for a visit home because of ``obstacles'' on the
Japanese side, North Korean radio said Tuesday.
	   ``Japanese women in North Korea retracted their applications to
visit Japan on their own,'' official Korean Central Radio quoted a
North Korean Red Cross spokesman as saying. The broadcast was
monitored in Tokyo by the Radiopress agency.
	   Among the obstacles cited, the broadcast quoted the spokesman as
criticizing the Japanese side for suggesting that women who have
given up Japanese nationality be excluded from the visits.
	   Also, Japanese media handled the previous visits by the women
with ``impolite'' news coverage, the Red Cross spokesman said.
	   ``Japan has constructively tried to discuss the issue'' of those
who have given up Japanese nationality, a Foreign Ministry
official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said without
elaboration.
	   About 1,800 Japanese women, many of them married to North Korean
men, left Japan around 1960 and had not been allowed by North Korea
to go abroad until last year.
	   North Korea and Japan held years of tough negotiations before
the North in November finally allowed 15 Japanese wives to visit
their homeland.
	   A second group of 12 women also made a brief visit to Japan in
February for reunions with family members. The visits were
coordinated between the two countries Red Cross organizations.
	   Plans were reportedly under way for a visit by a third group.
	   Kanezo Muraoka, Japan's top government spokesman, told a news
conference Tuesday that the North's announcement was
``regrettable'' as the program had been conducted from a
humanitarian standpoint.
	   The visits had been seen a step forward in normalizing relations
between North Korea and Japan, which have no diplomatic ties.
	   Prospects for normalization talks have also suffered on Japanese
suspicions that Pyongyang has withheld information about alleged
kidnappings of Japanese nationals by the reclusive, Stalinist
state.
	   On Friday, North Korea said an investigation had found no
evidence that 10 Japanese believed missing there are in its
territory.
	   Japan believes that North Korean agents abducted the Japanese,
including a 13-year-old girl, over the past two decades to use them
as language teachers for their spies.
	   North Korea has dismissed the alleged abductions as ``faked-up
cases.''
	   Their status is a key pending issue between Japan and North
Korea.
	   Japan, which ruled the entire Korean Peninsula as a colony from
1910 until 1945, never established diplomatic relations with North
Korea after the peninsula was split into the communist North and
capitalist South after World War II.
 &UR; (km)
</TEXT>
